<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY LEADS NOTRE DAME TO VICTORY OVER RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE DRAPE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When you have won Big East player of the year honors,
your name should be spelled in lights outside Madison Square
Garden, not smeared with blood on the back of your jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But Troy Murphy saw his stained jersey as a proper tribute after
he led Notre Dame to its first ever victory in the Big East
tournament _ a 74-62 brawl over Rutgers on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``MU'' on his jersey highlighted in red, the willowy
left-hander got in the spirit of abuse he was subjected to by the
Scarlet Knights' big men. With Notre Dame leading by 11 points late
in the game, Murphy soared above the rim for a rebound, hooked the
ball down with one hand and let out a guttural yell that drew a
double take from Rashod Kent of Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time Murphy moved the 6-foot-6-inch 265-pound
bruising Kent. Instead, he went over and around the Scarlet Knights
to finish with a game-high 25 points, largely because the Scarlet
Knights sent him to the free throw line 14 times. He hit 12 of them
to go along with 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not sure whose blood it was,'' said Murphy, the
sophomore from Morristown, N.J., whom the conference coaches named
player of the year. ``You just have to go, make cuts and expect to
get hit. That's how the Big East is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish will face No. 2 seeded Miami on Thursday in
another physical matchup that Notre Dame needs to win to help their
cause for an NCAA tournament bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might be the best defensive team we face this year,''
said Notre Dame coach Matt Doherty. ``I mean they're co-champs of
the league. So we don't have nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite _ with a record of 18-13, Notre Dame needs a stirring
run to the Big East tournament finals to coax an invitation out of
the selection committee for the National Collegiate Athletic
Association Basketball tournament. Syracuse, St. John's,
Connecticut, Miami already have earned invitations, as well as
Seton Hall after Wednesday's 85-65 rout of Providence.
</P>
<P>
   The conference tournament championship insures Notre Dame an
automatic bid; a defeat in the finals, however, leaves them at the
mercy of the selection committee. The Irish boast quality victories
- two over Connecticut, as well as St. John's and Ohio State _ but
were only .500 in league play. A loss in Saturday's final means
that the Fighting Irish would have 14 losses and, since 1994, no
college team in the nation has been invited with that many defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Murphy and his teammate's knowledge of the Big
East tournament play was extremely limited - in Notre Dame's four
previous appearances as conference members they were bounced in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   In Notre Dame's only game with Rutgers in Piscataway, Murphy,
was booed, heckled and harassed into one of his only poor
performances of the year. Kent banged on Murphy so persistently he
drew a technical, fouled out and scored 18 points on five of 16
shooting as the Scarlet Knights pasted the Irish, 76-51. The
Fighting Irish vowed not to repeat what Doherty considered their
worst game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good motivator that we got Rutgers as a draw. We got
embarrassed down there and gave us a sense of payback,'' said
senior guard Jimmy Dillon, who had 7 points and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, his backcourt mate Matt Carroll, and David Graves
dropped in long-range jumpers and helped open a 15 point first-half
lead that Rutgers (15-15) only was able to carve nine points with
1:38 left in the game. The Irish were seven of 13 from the 3-point
line and shot 51 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're making shots that gives Troy much more room to
operate,'' said Rutgers Coach Kevin Bannon. ``When you have to
worry about both that's when this is a team that could play with
anybody in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   For Murphy, the focus was on acquitting himself better before
his home folks. He admitted to being to emotional about returning
to New Jersey during the regular season and to the school that was
his second choice behind Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I made too much of playing against Rutgers,
going out there and playing against the whole team and trying to do
everything. They really got to me,'' he conceded. ``I just tried to
focus on the game plan today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
