<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR UCONN'S EL-AMIN, IT'S JUST NOT THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With two minutes left to play Wednesday in what would be a 70-55
rout of Boston College on the first day of the Big East tournament,
Khalid El-Amin, the University of Connecticut's effervescent junior
point guard, sat on the bench celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin was animated as he laughed and smiled with teammates.
The smile used to be his signature, but for El-Amin and
Connecticut, the carefree smiles have been a lot tougher to come by
this season.
</P>
<P>
   After a dream-come-true campaign last season when the Huskies
won the national championship, defense of the crown has been so
precarious that coach Jim Calhoun has jokingly wondered whether the
subsequent grief has been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   UConn came into the tournament at 21-8, yet Calhoun found
himself apologizing for the record. The season has been uneven and
El-Amin has been a large part of the unevenness.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he was good. After the game, El-Amin was businesslike
and resigned about the team's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for it to be another storybook season,'' he said,
``but you're not going to have that every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from being a storybook season, this one has teetered between
a bad dream and a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin led UConn to the national championship last March 29.
But 15 days later _ and one day after he was honored in his
hometown of Minneapolis _ El-Amin, then a 19-year-old sophomore,
was stopped for a traffic violation in Hartford, Conn. A small
amount of marijuana was discovered during a pat-down search.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin pleaded guilty in Hartford Community Court and agreed to
perform six hours of community service, including picking up trash
for the City of Hartford. In exchange, his record was wiped clean.
The following months were filled with apologies and what, to El-
Amin, must seem like suffocating scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, as Connecticut began its title defense, a
Connecticut newspaper ran an article about possible NCAA violations
involving El-Amin. The story alleged that the UConn point guard
traded game tickets for use of a vehicle registered to a Hartford
man with a record of drug arrests. A UConn investigation into the
allegations produced no evidence of NCAA violations.
</P>
<P>
   In another episode, Jake Voskuhl was investigated in connection
with his use of a car and was cleared of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent incident involved the UConn players Tony
Robertson and Doug Wrenn, who allegedly tried to swap tickets to
games for merchandise at a mall. They were suspended from the team.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's victory, El-Amin admitted that the off-court
episodes drained his enthusiasm for the student athlete experience.
He was not as enthusiastic about being a college player as he had
been the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not,'' he said. ``I'm sorry to say I'm not.'' You
could tell he was bursting to say more. Wisely, he pulled back.
With the testy mood of the NCAA enforcement staff, its narrow
interpretations of arcane regulations and mounting tension
involving coaches, school administrators and players, the less
said, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going into depth about that,'' El-Amin said. ``That
would take days and weeks and I'm not going to do that. But I'm not
really happy about being a college student athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   How had the joy gone out of the game? Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young men's dreams have been shattered or could have
been ended by all the nit-picking that the NCAA has been doing,''
El-Amin said. ``That speaks for itself. Some violations are indeed
violations: A guy knows that he committed a violation. But others,
like I said _ the nit-picking things _ are like cat and mouse. All
this nit-picking, it shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun wondered how El-Amin could come back next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how he can stay next year _ children, a wife,''
the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are bright and they're talking more and more with
each other,'' Calhoun added. ``They've played against each other
since they were 12 and 13 years old. Yes, we're giving them a
$70,000 education and we're giving them a stage. They see the NCAA
sign a billion dollar television contract and they can't get a
loan, or work a job.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's game, Calhoun said that so much will depend on
El-Amin's energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about my energy,'' El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My energy,'' he said. ``If that's the case, we might as well
go to the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
