<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLING TIME FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Better teams have lost to the Detroit Red Wings.
How the Kings play in their next four games could be a better
indicator of how good they really are.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there were issues in the Kings' 3-1 loss Tuesday night
at Staples Center. The power play went 0 for 5 and even let in a
short-handed goal. The top two lines did not respond to the
clamp-down style they will be seeing the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Kings defeated the Red Wings in their previous
two meetings, players acknowledge there is a greater sense of
urgency now with just 16 games remaining. And Detroit has won the
Stanley Cup two of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're looking at a point in the schedule that should tell
us a lot,'' captain Rob Blake said. ``New York, Calgary, Vancouver
and Anaheim. We don't have to win them all - even though it would
be nice - but we have to regain some of the momentum we had on the
last road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are 1-3-1 since winning four of the first six games on
the road. Blake said last Thursday's 5-2 loss to struggling
Carolina, ``still seems to be haunting us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings know that only tonight's opponent, the Rangers,
ranks are among the top eight teams in either division. And just
barely. They also know New York faced the Mighty Ducks on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we did not have a full workout today,'' coach Andy
Murray said. ``They are playing back-to-back games and we thought
it was better not to use up the extra energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Murray met with Blake and several members of his top
two lines. Except for Jozef Stumpel's game-winning goal Saturday in
the 3-2 overtime victory over Nashville, both lines were shut out
the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Smolinski returned from a corneal abrasion on his left eye
to record his 35th assist vs. Detroit, but he does not have a goal
in the past 10 games. After scoring in a career-high 15 consecutive
games, Luc Robitaille has one shot in the past two.
</P>
<P>
   And Blake, who runs the power play from the blue line, was on
the ice when the Red Wings' Sergei Fedorov scored short-handed in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no excuse for that, we just need to work harder,''
he said. ``If we do what we're supposed to do, it's a 1-0 game and
anything can happen. Those are things we can't allow during these
upcoming games.''
</P>
<P>
   KINGS vs. N.Y. RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:30 p.m. at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net; KRLA-AM (1110)
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: The Rangers were 0-5 lifetime at the Pond entering
Wednesday's game with the Ducks. They came in just a point ahead of
Montreal for the eighth and final playoff spot in the East. There
is great disappointment in New York that the team with the $60
million payroll isn't better. Free-agent signings Theo Fleury (14
goals, 56 points) and Valeri Kamensky (8 goals, 26 points, minus 9)
have not panned out. Monday, the Rangers had a chance to pick up a
point in San Jose but gave up a goal in the final minute in a 2-1
loss. The Rangers are 20-0-0 when scoring four or more goals,
1-25-7 when getting two or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Matt McHale
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
