r d BC-SCHOOL-COMPARISON-KAN     03-09 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COMPARISON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICT COMPARISON GETS UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Although the state of Missouri has long
resisted ranking its public schools, an education reform group
today will issue its first report card aimed at comparing student
achievement in economically similar districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Education Evaluation Report is designed to show what
comparable districts can achieve with similar resources, said Peter
Herschend, president of the Missouri Partnership for Outstanding
Schools, which commissioned the study.
</P>
<P>
   Herschend said the report would provide valuable information to
Missourians, many of whom seem better informed about their public
schools' athletic performance than about academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appropriate that patrons know how their schools are
doing in the most important aspect for which they exist,'' said
Herschend, co-owner and vice chairman of Silver Dollar City in
Branson and a member of the state Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The report clusters the state's 524 school districts into 20
groups, based largely on the number of low-income students and the
amount spent per pupil.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the groups provide a benchmark for
district-to-district comparisons on indicators such as dropout and
graduation rates, student performance on state standardized tests,
and transition to jobs or higher education. The report also
includes percentages of minority students, student movement in and
out of the districts, attendance rates, student-teacher ratios and
tax-rate information for each district.
</P>
<P>
   But critics questioned some of the groupings and warned about
drawing too many conclusions from the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``No two school districts in Missouri are identical, and it's
really difficult to develop some comparison, because so many
factors come into play _ socioeconomic, size, location,'' said
Brent Ghan, spokesman for the Missouri School Boards Association.
``I know they tried to take that into account. I just don't know if
they've developed meaningful comparisons here. When you look at
some of the cluster groups they've come up with, some don't make a
great deal of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ghan questioned grouping the 5,646-student Normandy
district in suburban St. Louis with the 103-student Wyaconda
district in the state's most northeastern county.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to Wyaconda. It's nothing like Normandy,'' Ghan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report's supporters acknowledge some seemingly unusual
groupings.
</P>
<P>
   ``By grouping economically, they may not look and feel
intuitively the same, but according to their economic data they
are,'' said Angie Hull, communication coordinator for the
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City district is grouped with the St. Louis district
in the smallest of the 20 clusters. ``They were subdivided out
because they were so, so different,'' Hull said. Other clusters
have from five to 17 districts.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows, for example, that Kansas City has a better
high school graduation rate than St. Louis, but that a higher
percentage of students in St. Louis go to college. Students in both
districts generally perform far below the state average on state
standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   Many other states have adopted report cards that make it easier
to compare public schools or districts.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, the state mandates that all schools report uniform
information, such as test scores, student demographics, dropout and
graduation rates. The state posts the information in an
easy-to-read format on a Web site and makes hard copies available.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas also discourages using the information in the reports to
rank schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``That clearly wasn't our intention, but much to our
consternation, that's been the result,'' said Sharon Freden,
assistant commissioner for the Kansas Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, what it does is let the public in that school
district see if that individual school is making progress, not how
it compares with the school down the road or across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Using similar arguments, Missouri has long balked at ranking
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Outstanding Schools Act of 1993 requires local districts to
publish an annual report card on their performance. The law also
requires the state Department of Elementary and Secondary Education
to publish an annual comprehensive report on all districts.
</P>
<P>
   But the law specifically prohibits the state from using the
information to compare school districts, resulting in a complex
compilation of information that is difficult for the public to
analyze. The law also gives districts wide discretion on how they
assemble and present the reports, making comparison difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman said the law was
designed to provide the public with information to foster a richer
understanding of individual school performance without creating a
competitive or punitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The education community was fearful that the evaluation of
school districts would come down to one number, which would be
unfair because school districts are not and should not be reduced
to just a number,'' Bartman said. ``They're complex institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said he considered the partnership's evaluation report a
useful tool to identify schools that could then serve as models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure it's a useful tool for all other districts to
know which districts or school sites are doing poorly,'' Bartman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the report are quick to note that schools are not
ranked, but are instead listed by enrollment size.
</P>
<P>
   Still, readers can scan the groupings and quickly draw
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Herschend said he hoped the report would help districts identify
their strengths and shortcomings, create conversation among
teachers, parents and business and political leaders, and prompt
more local involvement in school improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The study is by far the largest undertaking for the 6-year-old
partnership, a nonprofit, nonpartisan group formed after passage of
the Outstanding Schools Act to serve as an advocate for school
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia-based partnership is funded by grants and donations
from businesses and foundations across the state and is governed by
an unpaid board of directors. In the past, the partnership has
produced public-opinion reports and newsletters highlighting
educational successes.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership used $120,000 in grants from the Kauffman
Foundation, the Hall Family Foundation and the Herschend Foundation
to commission the Center for Educational Policy Analysis at the
University of Missouri's College of Education to generate the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership hopes to produce the report annually and
eventually move to school-by-school comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of the complete report will be made available at public
libraries and through local school districts or can be purchased
for $20 from the partnership by calling (800) 659-4044.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
