<HEADLINE>
INDICTMENT SAYS VANOVER ASSISTANT AMONG PART OF CAR-THEFT RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 &HT;    c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City Chiefs kick returner Tamarick
Vanover's personal assistant was among seven persons charged as
part of a nationwide car-theft ring that specialized in BMWs,
Lexuses and other luxury vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A federal indictment, unsealed Wednesday, alleged the seven
stole up to 50 luxury vehicles from North Carolina, retitled them
in Missouri and then sold them across the country. The development
is part of a related investigation of drug dealers who shipped
cocaine and marijuana to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, which a grand jury returned in late February,
does not mention Vanover.
</P>
<P>
   However, Vanover's personal assistant, Gregory E. Burns, was
accused in the indictment. Burns already is facing federal
drug-trafficking and weapons charges in a related case.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Vanover pleaded guilty to aiding and abetting the
sale of a stolen vehicle that crossed state lines. The stolen
vehicle that he sold to a friend in Florida _ a 1999 Ford
Expedition _ was not mentioned in the indictment. Vanover has
agreed to cooperate with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The recent auto theft indictment alleges that since January 1996
the ring stole more than $1 million worth of luxury sport-utility
vehicles and high-end makes such as Lexus, Mercedes, Infiniti and
BMW.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest auto vehicle theft case the FBI has been
involved in, in this area, in at least a dozen years, in terms of
the numbers of vehicles and people involved,'' FBI spokesman Jeff
Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, a Justice Department spokesman, added: ``It's a
substantial theft ring. As we allege, they operated this ring in an
almost machinelike fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns appeared Wednesday at two federal court hearings to answer
charges in the stolen car and drug cases. Accompanied by his
lawyer, Jacqueline A. Cook, Burns pleaded not guilty to all counts.
Afterward, Cook declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Court records filed in Burns' drug case show that in March 1998
he sold a 1994 white Lexus SC400 that had been stolen in North
Carolina to a cocaine customer in Vanover's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's indictment listed a 1994 white Lexus SC400 as among
the vehicles stolen in North Carolina. The indictment, however,
does not say the Lexus is the same car Burns sold.
</P>
<P>
   Another defendant in the car theft indictment was named in the
drug case. Marcus Hammond of Roswell, Ga., remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also charged Angela R. Harper of Kansas City, who
was charged in the case earlier this month in a criminal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers filed in support of those charges note that Kansas
City police stopped Harper in January 1998 while she was driving a
1997 Toyota 4Runner that had been reported stolen the month before
during an armed carjacking in Raleigh, N.C. She remains free on
bond, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Two other defendants, Mark N. Hutton of West Palm Beach, Fla.,
and Desmond A.E. Jackson of Durham, N.C., are in custody in Florida
and Georgia, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Gyasi Ralemecca Edwards and Josephine S. Williams, both of
Durham, N.C., remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the defendants conspired to steal
vehicles from North Carolina, sometimes from car dealerships, and
transported them to Washington, D.C., where their vehicle
identification numbers were altered. The vehicles then were
retitled in Missouri under the false numbers and sold.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have recovered 20 of the stolen vehicles from
Arizona, California, Florida, Missouri, North Carolina, Ohio,
Virginia and Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a large and continuing operation with tentacles in many
parts of the country,'' Lanza said. ``It was brought to a halt
after a two-year investigation and the cooperation of eight
agencies, most notably the Missouri//Kansas Auto Crimes Task Force
and the Missouri Highway Patrol.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest indictment stems from a 28-month investigation of a
large-scale cocaine and marijuana smuggling operation based in
Fresno, Calif. Court records show the ring smuggled more than 200
pounds of cocaine into Kansas City each month.
</P>
<P>
   At least 23 persons have been charged in the probe, while nine
have been convicted, including Vanover, and are now cooperating
with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Pollard of Kansas City, Kan., is expected to plead guilty
to drug-trafficking charges, his lawyer said recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
