<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TISSUE-MARKETING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY WITNESSES EXPECTED AT FETAL TISSUE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 &HT;    c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional hearing on the marketing of tissue
taken from fetuses at abortion clinics in Kansas and elsewhere will
be open to the public today, following assurances it won't
``degrade or incriminate innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Kansas City area witnesses who worked at the Overland
Park, Kan., clinic of Planned Parenthood of Mid-Missouri and
Eastern Kansas are expected to testify at a U.S. House subcommittee
hearing on extraction and sale of fetal tissue for research.
</P>
<P>
   Four other witnesses also are to testify about possible
violation of federal fetal tissue laws. Such organs can be donated
for research, but fees for removal and transportation are not
supposed to exceed actual cost.
</P>
<P>
   The House Commerce Committee's Health and Environment
Subcommittee will conduct the hearing, which some members sought to
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern was that the testimony might defame, degrade or
incriminate innocent people, with consequences that might range
from harassment to physical violence,'' said Dennis Fitzgibbons,
spokesman for subcommittee Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgibbons said that concern has been eased, and that the
dispute over opening the meeting was never a Democrat vs.
Republican issue. Republicans disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely was a partisan dispute,'' said Steve Schmidt,
spokesman for subcommittee Republicans. ``They tried every tactic
at their disposal to close the meeting and keep the American people
uninformed. Under intense media pressure, they caved.''
</P>
<P>
   The key witness at the hearing is expected to be Miles Jones, a
Lee's Summit, Mo., pathologist who has operated a company that
removed and marketed fetal tissue at Planned Parenthood and other
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was subpoenaed but has given no indication he will appear,
Schmidt said. Failure to appear would subject him to being held in
contempt. Jones has not returned repeated phones calls from The
Kansas City Star for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee plans to show a replay Thursday of a hidden
camera interview Jones did with the ABC News show ``20//20''
broadcast Wednesday in which he discussed the profitability of
selling brains, livers, hearts and other organs from aborted
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a market force,'' Jones tells a ``20//20'' producer who
posed as a potential investor in Jones' company. ``It's what you
sell it for.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee also subpoenaed Dean Alberty of Lee's Summit, a
medical technician who worked for Jones and another company that
did fetal tissue marketing. Alberty told ``20//20'' he became upset
about the procedure and agreed to accept money from an
anti-abortion group to report back on possible illegal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying voluntarily to the committee will be Lynn Fredericks
of Lake Waukomis in Platte County. Fredericks said she was vice
president of surgical services at Planned Parenthood two years ago.
She declined to discuss her intended testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is to hear from James Bardsley, president of the
Anatomic Gift Foundation, which did fetal tissue extraction at the
Planned Parenthood clinic several years ago. Three medical experts
from Nebraska, Massachusetts and California are also on the witness
list.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is getting substantial attention from anti-abortion
and pro-choice groups. The National Right to Life Committee Inc.
issued a news release Wednesday demanding the hearing be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a right to know whether abortion methods are
being altered to obtain organs, whether live births sometimes occur
during such procedures and whether baby body parts are being sold
for profit,'' said Douglas Johnson, legislative director of Right
to Life.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman for the New York office of Planned Parenthood
said the group was neutral on whether the hearing should be open
and is not opposed to rigorous investigation of any wrongdoing in
fetal tissue research.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are bad actors out there in the private sector who
are in fact profiteering, those individuals have to be identified
for the benefit of the true, legitimate value of fetal and organ
tissue research,'' said Adina Wingate Quijada, senior press officer
for Planned Parenthood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
