<HEADLINE>
A REPEAT EFFORT FROM SHAQ?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Now that he's flexed all those muscles, now that
he's shown what he can really do when he sets his birthday mind to
it, should the NBA be put on alert for an even more explosive
Shaquille O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal partied on his 28th birthday by scoring a career-high 61
points Monday night, an eye-opening performance even if it was
against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers center is already being championed as the league MVP
this season, but he was a man who acted like he could raise his
game another notch on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Now the schedule brings another weak opponent - without a
legitimate big man - in tonight's game at Golden State. The
Warriors start 6-10, 250-pound Adonal Foyle at center. Is a repeat
performance possible? Opponents know one thing: O'Neal will always
be the focus of the Lakers offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go inside every night,'' said Lakers coach Phil
Jackson. ``That has to be the thrust of our offense. But it depends
how much a team collapses on him. If they send everybody in the
lane, then we have to use our outside game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal maintains he's not planning anything special for the
Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worry about scoring points before the game,'' O'Neal
said. ``If I get in a game and am feeling it - just like anybody
else on the team - you just keep on going to him. I'm not even
thinking about it. If it happens, it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so primary: Jackson, a former Knicks teammate of Bill
Bradley, was disappointed but philosophical about his old friend
being swept out of the Democratic presidential race by Al Gore in
the Super Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke to Bradley on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill had an impact on this election,'' Jackson said. ``I think
Gore became a viable candidate through the competition he had to
face with Bradley - pulling out of Washington, going to Tennessee,
firing a lot of people on his staff and reorganizing his campaign.
He became quite a contender, and the machine overran Bradley and
his ability to be a populist candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the press' infatuation with (John) McCain as a populist
candidate sucked all the wind out of Bill's publicity or any kind
of press he might have been able to generate in the last three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not going to work, either, so we're going to be
stuck with two guys that have been bred and born to this position
in the world. People who really haven't had to go out and haven't
had a real job in their life. They haven't been part of the real
population of America, so that they've had to function like normal
citizens, with their normal cares and concerns. It's quite a
statement of where we are as a country.''
</P>
<P>
   Tidbits:: Jackson was surprised to learn the Lakers became the
NBA's first team to clinch a playoff spot on Tuesday's off-day:
``No, really? That's nice to know.''... The Lakers completed what
Jackson termed only their second full practice at their new
facility in El Segundo. O'Neal said he likes the place but is
missing one thing: ``I still need my own key so I can come shoot
when I want to.''.. Despite his scoring outburst against the
Clippers, O'Neal trails Sixer Allen Iverson in the league scoring
race by 1 points (29.7-28.2).
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. GOLDEN STATE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:30 p.m. at Oakland
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Channel 9; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (50-11) update: The Lakers have won 16 in a row,
stretched their lead over Portland to 3 games and became the first
team to reach 50 victories after their win over the Clippers on
Monday. Said coach Phil Jackson: ``That's always a significant
thing at this level. You hope to be the first to 50 and then get
those last 10 or 12 wins that will give you the homecourt
advantage.'' Guard Ron Harper said it doesn't matter much to him if
the Lakers end up with the homecourt edge should they meet the
Blazers in the playoffs: ``I don't care. I'll take my chances with
this basketball team anywhere. I think we have a good enough
basketball team that we can win in any hostile place.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden State (16-43) update: After meeting the worst team in the
West, the Lakers now draw the owners of the second-worst conference
record. The Lakers won the only previous meeting this year, 93-75.
It's L.A.'s first look at Golden State with guard Larry Hughes,
averaging 11.2 points since being acquired from Philadelphia in a
three-player deal Feb. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
