<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-GROWTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LEADS NATION IN POPULATION GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILBURG  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Despite more than 2 million defections,
California continued to lead the nation in population growth during
the '90s, the Census Bureau is expected to report. A wave of
immigrants and a baby boom fueled a statewide gain of 3,333,694
residents in the 1990s. During the same period, the Census Bureau
reported, 2,170,790 Californians left the state for Las Vegas,
Phoenix and other U.S. destinations.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of those defectors were from Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau report, the last to be issued by the agency
before it officially begins its 2000 count April 1, covered the
period between April 1, 1990, and July 1, 1999. It was based on
bureau estimates and data supplied by other federal, state and
local agencies. The report is due Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, California gained a net 2,280,354 immigrants
from outside the United States, recorded 5,227,258 births and
logged 2,039,044 deaths. The state's 1999 population total of
33,145,121 was up 11.2 percent from the 1990 level.
</P>
<P>
   California has led the nation in population growth since the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   A boom in babies was a major growth factor in the Southland,
where recorded births in the six-county region outpaced recorded
deaths from 1990 to 1997 by an average of nearly three to one. For
example, Los Angeles County recorded 1,676,786 births during the
decade and 563,934 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County, which added 466,937 residents during the
period to hit a total of 9,329,989, posted a net loss of 1,560,687
domestic migrants. They are defined by the Census Bureau as people
who moved from the county, either to other areas of California or
other states. The net census figure is the difference between the
number of migrants who moved to the county and the total of those
who moved out.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Los Angeles County saw a net influx of 902,097
international migrants, people who relocated from outside the
United States. The total included both legal and undocumented
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``These figures are extraordinarily significant,'' said Marc
Perry, a Census Bureau demographer who prepared today's report.
``We've rarely recorded migrations and shifts of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said several factors contributed to the Southland's
demographic shifts, including increased legal and illegal
immigration, the passing of the World War II generation and the
post-Cold War recession that gripped the region in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Los Angeles County ranked third in the nation among
counties in terms of total population growth. Maricopa County,
Ariz., which includes Phoenix, ranked No. 1 with a gain of 475,787
residents and a 1999 total of 2,861,395, up 34.8 percent over 1990.
Clark County, Nev., which includes Las Vegas, ranked second with an
increase of 475,787 and a total of 1,217,155, up 64.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to Perry, Maricopa and Clark counties made most of
their population gains at the expense of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was among five Southland counties that posted net
losses of domestic migrants and sizable increases of new residents
from outside the United States. Only Riverside County bucked the
regional trend, adding 175,275 domestic migrants, most of them from
other areas of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside, in fact, ranked second in the state in county
population growth and fifth in the nation. According to Perry,
Riverside's growth mirrored that of the Las Vegas and Phoenix
regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have areas that are newly developed, and where housing and
living costs are relatively lower,'' he said. ``Growth by itself
can become an industry. In places like Las Vegas, much of the job
growth has come in construction and related trades.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the outflow of Southland residents began in the early
1990s, when World War II veterans, many of whom were original GI
Bill homeowners in regions like the San Fernando and San Gabriel
valleys and the Long Beach area, began moving en masse to
retirement communities in rural California as well as the Southwest
and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The trend accelerated with the post-Cold War downturn in
Southern California's aerospace and defense industries, which
forced thousands of working-age adults and their families to
relocate in search of employment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Census Bureau data, the exodus of Californians
peaked in 1993, when an estimated net 430,000 domestic migrants
left the state. Perry credited an improving economy with cutting
the annual net loss of residents to 80,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
