<SLUG> BC-SAMESEX-MARRIAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HEAD OF MORMON CHURCH PRAISES CALIFORNIA ON PROP. 22, STATE'S 
 GAY ADVOCATES SAY PASSAGE WON'T STOP MOVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ELAINE HERSCHER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worldwide leader of the Mormon Church said Wednesday he is
grateful to California's voters for approving a measure banning
same-sex marriage, as gay rights advocates gamely found a silver
lining in their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Tuesday's election approved Proposition 22 by 61 to 39
percent, a lopsided victory for those seeking to reinforce the law
that makes civil marriage legal only between a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to do with core prejudice and not rationality, and
those of us who are gay know what a difficult thing that is to
surmount,'' said state Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San
Francisco. ``But four out of 10 voters think gay marriage is OK. I
think there's great nobility in that outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure was sponsored by state Sen. William ``Pete'' Knight,
a Republican from Palmdale. Knight's supporters enlisted the help
of the Mormon and Roman Catholic churches early on and raised $10
million, compared with $6.6 million for the No on Knight campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Hinckley, president of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints, said Wednesday that voters had upheld a ``moral
issue of great importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not anti-gay,'' Hinckley said at the National Press
Club in Washington, D.C. ``We are pro-family. We want to emphasize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Glazier, communications director for the Protection of
Marriage Committee, said Californians should be proud of ``our
diversity and tolerance, but there are societal boundaries that
should be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   No same-sex couple in the United States can legally marry now,
and Proposition 22 does not change that. It pre-empts California's
acceptance of gay or lesbian marriages should they ever become
legal in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The No on Knight campaign argued that the measure was divisive,
intruded on gays' rights to equal protection and carried a hidden
agenda of overturning gains gays have made in domestic partner
benefits, adoptions and other rights and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But as it became clear Tuesday night that they had lost, many in
the campaign were saying the initiative started a conversation with
heterosexuals from which there is no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Proposition 22 tried to make their case with images
of lesbian and gay families who, they said, would suffer increased
discrimination if the measure passed. The campaign, which went to
the heart of people's deepest emotions about marriage and family,
was well under way in December when the Vermont Supreme Court ruled
that same-sex couples should have the same protections marriage
offers to heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about whether gays and lesbians should have
rights. We're talking about  &UR; how  &LR; they should,'' said Tracey
Conaty, press secretary for No on Knight. ``The voters aren't ready
to grant gay and lesbian couples civil marriage, but they are more
ready than ever before to recognize our families and to grant us
the same rights and responsibilities they enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a vision there that wasn't there before,'' Conaty
said. ``I didn't think I'd ever have anything to say `thank you' to
Pete Knight for.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kennedy, vice president of the Claremont Institute, a
think tank that says it works to preserve traditional heterosexual
families, said the majority of voters ``live and let live'' but
draw a line at conferring anything to same-sex couples that seems
like marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``California voters in the end seemed to have a good deal of
common sense about this,'' Kennedy said. ``Whether you're for or
against gay marriage, a `no' vote meant a possible redefinition of
marriage. In the end, I think people were not willing to redefine
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kennedy said, ``Voters never bought into the idea that
this was an anti-homosexual measure.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative's critics said the measure would codify gays'
second-class status and could encourage further discrimination,
even violence against them.
</P>
<P>
   But Migden said she believes the state's domestic partner laws
are secure, as well as California's laws banning discrimination in
workplaces and schools based on sexual orientation. Migden
sponsored creation of the state's domestic partner registry, which
took effect January 1.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Community Churches throughout California will begin
a campaign Sunday to register 50,000 domestic partnerships by
year's end, said the Rev. Troy Perry, founder of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Gay groups vowed to hold proponents of Proposition 22 to their
word that they would not use the measure to undo benefits gays now
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they thought they could roll back human rights,''
Kennedy said, ``they'd be up against a Democratic Legislature, a
Democratic governor and many Republicans who are in favor of
domestic partner protections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
