A1372 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     03-09 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HAS TOUGH FIGHT TO WIN STATE IN NOVEMBER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
California showed its political stuff in the Super Tuesday contest
this week _ and it wasn't necessarily what George W. Bush wanted to
see.
<P>
   Although Bush solidly defeated GOP rival John McCain, the Texas
governor finished a full six points behind Vice President Al Gore
in the state's so-called ``beauty contest,'' which ranked all of
the candidates regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   And exit polls and political observers say Bush has a lot of
work to do if he has any hope of winning the state in the November
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls show Gore running well ahead of Bush among the
moderate, centrist voters who will be crucial in November, as well
as receiving a strong mandate from his own Democratic base _
including women, union members, Latinos and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Those polls also show that three-fifths of California voters
approve of President Clinton's job performance and policies,
two-thirds believe the country is on the right track and 90 percent
are positively beaming about the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, the Voter News Service exit poll showed Gore
beating Bush in a head-to-head matchup, 51 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait, personally. I haven't even gotten started on
Bush,'' said Garry South, the Democratic campaign consultant who
helped shape Gov. Gray Davis' landslide victory over Republican Dan
Lungren in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats are sounding a little giddy, it's because
California is considered essential to maintaining their grip on the
White House in the fall. The GOP nominee, presumably Bush, doesn't
need the Golden State to win the election, but he'll have to spend
both time and money here as a strategic move, to keep Gore from
spending it elsewhere in crucial states the GOP does need, like
Illinois, Ohio and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans insist they are conceding nothing in November _
certainly not California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed this week to do battle in California all the way to
November. But state Republicans have reason to be nervous about
that promise: His father, George Herbert Walker Bush, may have cost
the party crucial state legislative races in 1992 when he stopped
campaigning here early in the presidential contest and virtually
surrendered California to Democrat Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``(George W.) has to start, right away, defining the issues
toward the fall. He can't let Gore do it,'' said Matt Cunningham, a
GOP political consultant. ``He has got to make a case against
sleaze in Washington, and he has got to tie it into the campaign
finance scandals and the dishonor at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor appeared to do just that Tuesday night with a
speech that proclaimed ``the American people don't want a White
House where there's `no controlling legal authority,''' a reference
to Gore's explanation of his connection with a 1996 fund-raising
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The lively presidential contests brought voters out to the polls
in record numbers Tuesday. About 7.1 million votes have been
tallied so far, with another 700,000 to 800,000 absentee votes
still to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic about the way the election went,'' said
Secretary of State Bill Jones. ``The turnout will be about 55
percent, higher than I predicted. It's the highest percentage for a
primary election in 16 years and the largest number of votes ever
cast in a California presidential primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outpolled Democrats, collecting 54 percent of the
popular vote, compared to 43 percent for Gore, Bradley and fringe
candidate Lyndon LaRouche.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; McCain Voters
</P>
<P>
   Many of those GOP votes were from Democrats and independents who
backed Arizona Sen. John McCain, who collected 38 percent of his
support from outside the Republican party. Keeping those voters in
the GOP ledger is going to be tough for Bush to do.
</P>
<P>
   Those party-switchers ``were voting for McCain, not the
Republicans,'' said Paul Maslin, a Democratic pollster. ``Besides,
the very Democratic and independent voters who gave the Republicans
their advantage (Tuesday) are the very people that Bush has been
denigrating for months. How is he going to convince them that all
is forgiven?''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's father held those voters in 1988 and his son can do
it this time around, said Steve Merksamer, a veteran GOP adviser in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to campaign the way he did initially _ as a
compassionate conservative whose message manifests tolerance and
inclusion,'' he said. ``If he does, he absolutely can beat Gore
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history is on the Democrat's side, however. Gov. Davis,
interviewed on television Tuesday night, said that Gore simply
needs to rewind the tape on the governor's own stunning win two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush deserves credit for making education a priority
... but the fact that he's not for a woman's right to choose will
affect a lot of voters,'' Davis said. On abortion, guns and the
environment, the Texas governor ``is on the wrong side of the
issues ... and California is an uphill battle for George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   With eight years of Democratic success to build on in
California, Gore is positioned for a winning effort in the state,
Maslin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is in strong shape in California,'' he said. ``To some
extent, Democrats have to make sure that we don't screw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's also the matter of ``face time.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been to California 65 times as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has made 11 trips here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are playing catch-up,'' said David Chai,
California spokesman for Gore. ``Al Gore, being here as much as he
has, has a very solid understanding of the issues Californians care
about, and he knows the state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
