r a BC-PARENT-ACTIVISTS-2TAK     03-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENT-ACTIVISTS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS BECOME RELUCTANT ACTIVISTS AFTER SON'S BEATING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 &HT;    c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The mother and father of Pfc. Barry Winchell
often silently sit at their kitchen table, paperwork about their
son's murder piled between them.
</P>
<P>
   There are countless newspaper and magazine articles. Each tells
how their son's head was pounded by a baseball bat because other
soldiers thought he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   There are inch-thick printouts of military policy, which they
think should have prevented the death last July.
</P>
<P>
   There are legal papers, part of an effort to hold the Army
accountable for the murder.
</P>
<P>
   There are condolence letters, many from soldiers, many from
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a growing stack of requests from media and
activists, all wanting this south Kansas City couple to go public
with their grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all so overwhelming,'' Barry's mother said. ``Sometimes
Wally and I just sit here and stare at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of a son would have been devastating enough for Pat
and Wally Kutteles. But Barry was murdered. He was murdered on an
Army base, a place this military family viewed as a safe haven. And
because this high-profile homicide involved issues of
homosexuality, it challenges not only the military's, but also
society's homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not like you have someone die and you bury them and you
mourn,'' Pat Kutteles said. ``It becomes more complicated, and more
complicated and more complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is forcing the couple into the role of reluctant
activists, pushing the military to rescind its ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy, which allows homosexuals to serve as long as they
stay closeted.
</P>
<P>
   Today their Washington lawyers are expected to announce the
couple's intent to file a claim under an Army administrative
process, not unlike a civil lawsuit. It is an effort, they admit,
that may be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   In angrier moments, the action is about vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want somebody to pay for this,'' Wally Kutteles said.
``Somebody has to be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the idea of another family enduring the same
pain is central.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure that nothing happens to anyone else's
son,'' Pat Kutteles said.
</P>
<P>
   And while the military is taking steps to prevent harassment, it
is the lesser of the couple's targets.
</P>
<P>
   They are also taking on society itself.
</P>
<P>
   Inside their ranch house near Bannister Mall, one parent's words
often tumble over the other's as they form thoughts into a family
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try and change the attitudes, the environment on
the bases,'' Pat Kutteles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stop the bigotry,'' Wally Kutteles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, so that the bigotry is not allowed to exist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many days, the Kutteleses are exhausted _ from grief, from
wrenching gravesite photo sessions, from a schedule that has them
flying from Kansas City to Fort Campbell, Ky., where the trial was
held, to Washington to meet with attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has worked since the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep still comes hard, complicating everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very reluctantly doing all of this,'' she said. ``But, I
guess I have to keep at it to keep the issue in the forefront. I'm
doing it for Barry.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, on what should have been their son's 22nd birthday,
Wally and Pat Kutteles attended a court-martial, seated a few feet
from the men accused of their son's murder.
</P>
<P>
   The small courtroom is part of Fort Campbell, a sprawling Army
base of more than 23,000 soldiers on the Kentucky//Tennessee
border. There, over several months, the parents learned the story
of their son's death.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers testified that the weekend Barry Winchell died was
a raucous one, fueled by daylong keg parties to celebrate the
Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   Drunk from the revelry, Pvt. Calvin Glover attacked Winchell as
he slept on a cot in the barracks. Another soldier, Spc. Justin
Fisher, provided the bat, prodded Glover to strike and then washed
the blood from the weapon, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Fisher are in prison at Fort Leavenworth. Glover was
sentenced to life in prison, and Fisher was sentenced to 12 1/2
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial, the Kutteleses knew their son had been
harassed for months. But they had only suspected commanders did not
stop or discourage the harassment _ a violation of the ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony, combined with stories from other soldiers on the
base, provokes the family to spin the mourner's tale of ``what
if'':
</P>
<P>
   What if officers hadn't led chants with gay epithets; what if
other soldiers had spoken out; what if Barry hadn't been afraid of
being expelled from his beloved Army by telling of the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   And what if Pat Kutteles hadn't urged Barry to join the Army.
Her father served during World War II in the Navy, two brothers
were in the Marine Corps, her husband and a surviving son were in
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled when Barry wanted to go into the military,''
she said. ``I still have a hard time with that, that what I wanted
for him is what killed him.'' MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
