</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FIGHTS FOR CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With congressional support for China's entry into
the World Trade Organization eroding day by day, President Clinton
warned Wednesday that rejecting Beijing now ``would be a mistake of
truly historic proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sent legislation to Congress to grant China permanent
normal trade relations with the United States, Clinton made it
clear that he considers China's admission to the world trade body a
top priority of his last year in office and vital to U.S. economic
and foreign policy interests.
</P>
<P>
   Calling China's WTO entry the best opportunity since President
Nixon's groundbreaking trip to Beijing nearly three decades ago to
force further political liberalization in China, Clinton said, ``We
can work to pull China in the right direction, or we can turn our
backs and almost certainly push it in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade legislation would end the contentious annual fight
over China's trade status, but it also lifts the curtain on what is
sure to be one of the most hard-fought battles this year in
Congress, pitting business supporters against labor and
environmental critics.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress will not vote on China's WTO entry, which is
expected later this year, rejection of the trade measure would be a
humiliation for Clinton on his last major foreign policy effort. It
would prevent U.S. companies from benefiting from trade concessions
_ like tariff cuts and the opportunity to buy large chunks of
Chinese firms _ that U.S. negotiators obtained last November in
exchange for U.S. approval of China's entry to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Leading business organizations, especially in the high-tech
industry, are waging an all-out effort to gain passage, while labor
unions, led by the Teamsters and United Auto Workers, are fighting
just as hard against it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aimed to rebut a growing chorus of critics from both the
left and the right who warn that China should not be rewarded with
freer trade even as it threatens to invade Taiwan, clamps down on
Internet speech and moves backward on labor and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing normal trade status with China ``won't free a single
prisoner or create a single job in America or reassure a single
American ally in Asia,'' Clinton said. ``It will simply empower the
most rigid anti-democratic elements in the Chinese government ...
Our friends and allies would wonder why, after 30 years of pushing
China in the right direction, we turned our backs now that they
finally appear to be willing to take us up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated his insistence that the trade pact his
administration negotiated presents ``a one-way street'' for the
United States into potentially the world's biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   The pact would open key Chinese industrial sectors, including
telecommunications, automobiles and agriculture, granting enormous
access to a wide range of U.S. businesses. Clinton warned that if
Congress rejects the measure, foreign competitors will gain those
advantages instead and lock out U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton emphasized the foreign policy implications at stake
were even greater.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging China's recent backsliding, Clinton argued
that economic liberalization has already forced the government into
the ``dilemma'' of choosing either further economic and political
freedom, which `'risk unleashing forces beyond their control,'' or
greater isolation, which he said could push China's leaders toward
more internal crackdowns and outward belligerence.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this agreement, China has chosen reform, despite the
risks,'' Clinton said. ``It has chosen to overcome a great wall of
suspicion and insecurity to engage the rest of the world. The
question for the United States, therefore, is do we want to support
that choice or reject it, becoming bystanders as the rest of the
world rushes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, even opponents viewed the trade measure
as a pretty sure bet to pass the House and certain to clear the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks, the Chinese government's threats to
invade Taiwan, its attempts to control use of the Internet and its
failure to reach agreement with the European Union on entering the
WTO have undermined congressional support and emboldened opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we may have lost a few Democratic members just on the
basis of the recent comments on Taiwan,'' said Sacramento Democrat
Robert Matsui, who is leading efforts to round up Democratic
support in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable, when you think about it, for them to make
that provocative statement about their willingness to attack Taiwan
in the middle of all our discussions on WTO,'' Matsui said. ``It's
kind of foolhardy and maybe worse than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui said labor unions are ``working this thing hard,'' posing
problems for members as the November elections approach. ``We need
an early vote, that's key,'' Matsui said. ``The longer it drags
out, the more problems occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also rattled China supporters, including
those within his own administration, by sending mixed signals about
the China trade measure. Labor leaders meeting with Gore in New
Orleans last month said Gore told them that he would negotiate a
tougher agreement with China if he became president.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Gore clarified his position, writing a letter of
reassurance to the National Association of Manufacturers that he in
fact supports the administration's policy.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is now pushing for a vote as early as April
in the Senate, which normally would vote after the House in an
effort to gain some momentum for a House vote by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a vote as early as we possibly can,'' said
Covina Republican David Dreier, who is leading the drive for the
pact among House Republicans. Asked when that was, he said, ``When
we have the votes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
