r a BC-BELMONT-SITE-LADN     03-09 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-SITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES UNIFIED SCHOOL DISTRICT MAKES PITCH TO USE DODGERS LOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Desperate to replace the now-abandoned Belmont
Learning Center, Los Angeles education officials have found a nice,
open, empty spot downtown to build a new school - Dodger Stadium's
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   A corner of it, actually, is all they want for Dodger High.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Los Angeles Unified School District said
Wednesday that Dodgers Lot 23, part of the stadium's outer ring of
parking, could easily hold a school for 2,000 students on 16 acres.
</P>
<P>
   That would go a long way toward replacing the more than 4,000
student seats lost when the school board voted earlier this year to
abandon the Belmont Learning Center, a $175 million high school
built atop a dangerous oil field. Together with several other
downtown sites, including the Ambassador Hotel and the school
district's own headquarters, the Dodgers lot could provide the
space needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sites will provide smaller and better schools, faster
than Belmont ever could have been completed,'' said Howard Miller,
the district's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming the Dodgers can be persuaded to part with the
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers spokesman Derrick Hall said it was too soon to comment
on the proposal. The organization just received a letter from
Miller on Tuesday expressing the district's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still new to us,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he had a brief phone conversation with Dodgers chief
executive officer Bob Daly to begin discussions about the site.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Unified already has run into stiff opposition over
its efforts to find land for building badly needed schools. North
Hollywood residents still are protesting the district's proposal to
build a high school on the site of the Robinsons-May department
store chain headquarters on Laurel Canyon Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Miller emphasized that the district only was interested in a
16-acre piece of the 300-acre parking lot, not the entire stadium.
Since many of the students who would have attended Belmont live
close by, the site makes too much sense not to consider, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site is so perfect for us, from everything we know, we
have to look at it,'' said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   He will present the idea to school board members today at a
meeting of the board's facilities committee. Even before the
meeting, however, several board members praised the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids could leave their densely crowded neighborhoods and have
a more peaceful place to study in the hills,'' said board member
David Tokofsky, chairman of the facilities committee. ``There's
room for the city, the board, the parks and the Dodgers owners to
come together around some of the extra space up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on sales of other large parcels in the area, the Dodger
Stadium site might be worth about $9 million, said Ed Palmer,
associate vice president in the downtown Los Angeles office of
Grubb &AMP; Ellis, a commercial and industrial real estate firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat of a unique situation, considering it sits
within the Dodger Stadium confines,'' said Palmer. ``There is not a
lot to compare that with.''
</P>
<P>
   But the site would pose several problems. Most notably, it would
eliminate some parking at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But several board members said the district might be able to
compensate by building a parking garage. And unlike other potential
school sites located near industrial properties, they said the lot
would rest between relatively benign neighbors - parkland and a
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is dealing with traffic, but that can be
managed,'' board member Caprice Young said. ``And there's nothing
that goes on at a ballpark that goes against family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Los Angeles City Council belatedly entered the
Belmont debate. At the urging of Councilman Mike Hernandez, the
council passed a motion that calls for the city to withhold key
funding and building permits for new school construction in the
Belmont attendance area if the council is dissatisfied with the
district's plans to replace Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   The motion also calls for the school board to reconsider the
fate of Belmont, the nation's costliest school. Despite the
threatened sanctions, the school board has vowed to reject any
attempt to resuscitate Belmont. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writers Greg Gittrich, Gregory J. Wilcox and Jason
Takenouchi contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
