<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; kan-z
r d BC-PARENT-ACTIVISTS-2NDT     03-09 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENT-ACTIVISTS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 &HT;    c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ is what killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Barry's death, his parents had only a shadowy familiarity
with the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. It represented more of a
media catch phrase than anything.
</P>
<P>
   Now they understand it is only a policy and that the military
stands firmly behind its court-upheld right to reject anyone for
military service.
</P>
<P>
   The military has reissued and clarified regulations stating
harassment of gays is not allowed, and other rules governing who
and what can initiate an investigation to decide if someone is gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the American public to think that we just created
all of these policies because of his death,'' said Maj. Pamela
Hart, spokeswoman for Fort Campbell. ``It is preposterous for
someone to think that we had no structure in place, but we have
clarified it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense's inspector general is examining the
level of harassment at 38 military installations, both in the
United States and abroad. The inquiry includes all military
branches, military officials say, with a report due to Secretary of
Defense William Cohen on Monday. And anti-harassment training has
begun on many bases, including Fort Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the murder itself, but the Kutteleses' willingness to
speak about it that pushed the military response, said Michelle M.
Benecke of the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a Washington
group that monitors the military's policies about homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have already made a big difference,'' Benecke said. ``For
six years, SLDN asked the military service leaders to send a strong
message against harassment, but no steps were taken until after the
Kutteleses began to speak publicly about their family's
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Korean War veteran, Wally Kutteles speaks especially well
to other veterans, Benecke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is supposed to be an Army of the people,'' Wally Kutteles
said. ``And if it is, then all Americans should be able to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaining the ability to speak about the murder has been a painful
journey for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   For four months they refused to speak to the media.
</P>
<P>
   That stance changed after coverage focused on the murder as a
hate crime, but not on Barry, their son.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they allowed The New York Times to visit their home.
</P>
<P>
   They appeared on ``60 Minutes'' and national morning television
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair photographers came to the house on Monday, preparing
for a large article in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kutteles spent hours taping media interviews at Fort
Campbell to be aired with the announcement of their intent to
challenge the Army.
</P>
<P>
   At some levels, each interview reignites the pain as they
retouch their grief, their growing distrust of military justice and
their current activism.
</P>
<P>
   More unsettling have been the articles and news reports they do
not agree to give.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kutteles went to her son's grave one day, hoping for some
quiet time. She found a photographer hired by Time magazine,
clicking shots of the tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the instances when they are ``blindsided,'' as
Pat Kutteles says.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she stopped for gas at a convenience store. She
filled her car, stepped inside and asked for a pack of cigarettes
to fuel the chain-smoking that returned when her son was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching into her purse, she spotted a Rolling Stone magazine
propped in a rack near the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   And with that one glance, the anguish slipped into her day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a reality check that just jerks you right back,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She knew the magazine had an article about Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, there are new revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of photographs recently arrived in the mail. One shows
graffiti on a wall at Fort Campbell after the murder, a sketch of a
baseball bat with the inscription, ``Gay Whacker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just cried when I saw it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kutteleses know Barry can be a sympathetic victim, even to
people adamantly opposed to homosexuals, because it is unclear
whether he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   That is another very private issue that still goads the family.
</P>
<P>
   They insist that it really doesn't matter, that it is enough
that Barry was killed because people thought he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Some question whether Barry's murderer was gay. During the
trial, a psychiatrist testified that Fisher secretly dressed in
women's clothing for years, prompting speculation that his hatred
originated from unresolved feelings about his own sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing stops the speculation about Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Their son's self-described lover is doing interviews in national
magazines. Calpernia Sarah Addams is a man but lives and dresses as
a woman. In pictures, Addams appears voluptuous, with heavy makeup.
He refers to himself as a ``female impersonator.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry had a girlfriend for years, until a breakup several months
before the murder. His parents searched their love letters, some of
the personal belongings the Army returned after Barry's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no indications that he was gay,'' Wally Kutteles
said. ``They were love letters, just love letters.''
</P>
<P>
   To them, their son was Barry, who they still sometimes called
``Bear Bear,'' a childhood nickname.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Bear,'' a Jack Russell terrier, runs through their
home as they sort the piles of paperwork that stream through their
new fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kutteles flips through her schedule for the coming months.
There will be more meetings with lawyers, a speech at a gay rights
rally in Washington, another in Chicago, a panel discussion in
Philadelphia and, always, more media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Tallying each event, she begins to mentally commit to the
activist role that is now hers.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is involved in all of the decisions. But it is she
who carefully clips all the news articles. It is she who usually
answers the telephone when reporters call and she whom the cameras
tend to dote on, seeking to capture a mother's grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it is harder now,'' she said. ``When it first
happened, you are in such a state of shock. But now, well, I still
have times when I feel like he should be walking through the
door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
