<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CANUCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKESHIFT STARS HAPPY TO FORGE TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock glanced at his depleted
lineup, and a single thought came to mind. ``I'm looking at a crowd
of about 4,000 back in Kalamazoo,'' Hitchcock said. ``I wouldn't
want to be going into the playoffs with this lineup. Right now, I
see early golf times.'' Maybe the Brad Lukowich-Roman Lyashenko-Jon
Sim line convinced him. Maybe it was his goalie tandem of Manny
Fernandez and Marty Turco. Or maybe the simple math of subtracting
nine regulars from his lineup because of the early-morning arrest
of usual goalie Ed Belfour, injury and flu finally sunk in.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account that nine, one looked pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars said they were more than happy to take the point that
came with their 3-3 tie with a surging Vancouver bunch last night
at Reunion Arena. The Canucks are 6-3-3 with 16 points in theirpast
12 games. ``To get a point with everything that happened
\Ryesterday\S, with the flu and everything, losing guys, it's
good,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``We'll take it and move
on.'' Even coughing up two third-period goals didn't seem to bother
the Stars too much. Considering the day they had and the lineup
they skated, who could blame them? The day began with news that
Belfour had been arrested and wouldn't play. He wasn't scheduled to
start. Backup Manny Fernandez was. But they didn't have a backup,
so Turco was called up from Kalamazoo, Mich. Stars players and
coaches talked about it yesterday morning then tried to put it
behind them for the game. ``We faced so much adversity this year
that what can you do,'' said Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor, who
started the game playing wing on the third line and finished the
game playing defense alongside Sylvain Cote. ``Guys that were in
this room still had to go out and play the game.'' The list of
players who weren't was long and impressive. The injury list grew
to include winger Mike Keane (back) and center Guy Carbonneau
(wrist) along with the regulars: winger Blake Sloan (ankle), winger
Jere Lehtinen (ankle), center Joe Nieuwendyk (shoulder), center
Brian Skrudland (chest) and defenseman Shawn Chambers (knee). The
flu prompted the Stars to send captain Derian Hatcher and winger
Scott Thornton back from morning skate in hopes they'd be ready for
the game. Only Hatcher could go, and he didn't last the entire
game. He left in the third period with a strained right Achilles'
tendon and plenty of flu symptoms. He's listed as day to day. Only
the Stars could dress eight defensemen and be left rotating two
defensive pairs by the end. ``It seemed like everybody they played
was on defense,'' Canucks winger Alexander Mogilny said. ``So you
had to play against five defensemen pretty much.'' Which seemed to
be working for the Stars until the third period. Well, that and
Fernandez kept bailing them out. But the 3-1 lead the Stars took
into the period didn't last long. Vancouver got goals by Harold
Druken 79 seconds in and Mogilny at 9:41 of the period to wipe out
the Stars' lead that had taken two periods, two power plays to
create. The Druken goal was especially hard to swallow as Fernandez
had come out to play the puck. He lost. Druken scored into what
amounted to an empty net. Fernandez said he felt a little naked
without Belfour on the end of the bench. ``I didn't think I was
going to say this, but it's like an extra confidence when he's on
the bench,'' Fernandez said. ``It feels a lot better. It felt weird
today, all in all. I think I put a little too much pressure.'' He
finished with 23 saves, and Vancouver goalie Garth Snow had 33.
Snow didn't look good early, but he got better, including stopping
seven shots in overtime. The Stars were all over him early. Brett
Hull opened scoring at 9:30 of the first period. It was Hull's
first goal since Feb. 25, his 20th of the season and the 606th of
his career. He's four goals away from tying his father, Bobby, for
eighth most goals. Stars winger Grant Marshall flipped the puck in
off Canucks defenseman Chris Joseph's stick and past Snow at 18:16
of the first period. The referees sent the play upstairs to be
reviewed, and it was called a goal. Jon Sim then scored on the
power play. The shot came from Sergei Zubov from the point. Sim
tried popping it in. The puck went into the air so Sim took a
baseball swing and scored that way at 17:30. They weren't happy to
cough up the lead. But considering Hitchcock called it the
``worst'' of the makeshift lineups he's had to use this season, he
wasn't complaining too much. ``That was one of those times you get
a point and you're happier than hell,'' Hitchcock said. ``All in
all, missing that many hockey players and to play that hard and
quite frankly that well against a team on a roll is a happy point
for us.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
