<HEADER>
A1382 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     03-09 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MARRIAGE NEEDS VIGOROUS DEFENSE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The fear here is that government is getting too
complicated, especially after Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Proposition 22 passing, it now becomes vital for the
government to prevent fraudulent marriages by determining that each
prospective married couple contains one bona fide representative of
each of the two major genders. As anyone who spends much time in
San Francisco knows, a cursory visual inspection won't do the
trick.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the Department of Motor Vehicles will be assigned
to handle the job, creating a subdivision of the smog-check
program. Certified walk-in inspection stations will advertise,
``Sex Chex _ You pass or you don't pay.''
</P>
<P>
   And because sex-change operations do occur, married couples will
be required to get a sex check every five years to make sure
they're not polluting the marriage pool.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER PROBLEM could arise from the voters' passage of
Proposition 12, a $2.1 billion bond for water quality,
environmental and park projects.
</P>
<P>
   Niccole Bilotti was reading her state voter information booklet
and noticed that the argument against the bond was: ``The truth is
the govt. will use the vast majority of this money ... to buy more
land for insects, rats and weeds that your family will never get to
see or use.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilotti voted yes on 12, taking the leap of faith that our
government will allow us at least some visitation rights to the
insects, rats and weeds that will be purchased with our hard-earned
tax moneys.
</P>
<P>
   THE CENSUS can be confusing, too.
</P>
<P>
   First the bureau mailed out the census forms with an extra digit
in each address. Which means that many people won't receive their
form until their next life.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Sheehan received his letter. ``It said I was going to
receive a form in about a week, and it will be important to
complete and return the form. Enclosed was an envelop addressed to
Census 2000. No clue as to what I was to put in the envelop. Am I
to save the envelope for `about a week'? Hope you have an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin, I think you're supposed to take your scissors and
carefully cut the extra digit off the address on that envelope and
mail it back, so it can be recycled. But that's just a guess.
</P>
<P>
   THE ELECTIONS did help simplify the political situation in one
respect. Now Gore and Bush can finally stop the senseless and
monotonous trashing of their party rivals and start the senseless
and monotonous trashing of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Elections are a party in S.F., and Ed Moose threw an FDR party
on election day at his North Beach restaurant. Revelers included
Jean Stapleton, who is playing Eleanor Roosevelt in a one-woman
show here in S.F., and Jan Katten, one of FDR's two surviving
nieces.
</P>
<P>
   Guests ate Hooverville Stew and passed the hat, chucking in
nearly $2,000 for St. Anthony's Dining Room, and everyone gathered
'round the bar to talk politics.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown mentioned to a group of his admirers, ``George W.
Bush is the only national candidate in my experience who probably
reads the sports section first.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE W IS searching the sports pages for a running mate. With
Jesse Ventura's popularity, it makes sense for Bush to look to the
world of sports to fill out the old ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan would make a good VP. Even though he endorsed
Bill Bradley, Jordan is now a political free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about Mark McGwire, a good guy who enjoys enormous public
popularity? McGwire plays baseball seven months out of the year,
but as Al Gore has demonstrated, VP is only a part-time gig.
</P>
<P>
   What a ticket: W and Big Mac. A hot dog and a hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, McGwire is too nice a guy for the job. And not
terribly sophisticated politically; at least he wasn't years ago
when he played for the Oakland A's. He went to vote one election
day and got turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know you had to sign up first,'' Mac said.
</P>
<P>
   INTERESTING theory put forth by one of the revelers at Moose's:
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ran for the nomination at the urging of Demo insiders,
who knew Bradley couldn't win but knew that Gore needed a worthy
foe, much as a boxer in training for a big fight needs a good
sparring partner.
</P>
<P>
   The insiders knew it would be dangerous for the GOP to get all
the ink during the primaries as Bush and McCain battled it out
while Gore was on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's primary attribute, polls show, is that people recognize
him, and it was vital to keep him in the public eye. Thus the bid
by Bradley, who kept Gore sharp without injuring him.
</P>
<P>
   As a theory, this one is either half-baked, or poached in a
creamy dill sauce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
