<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to delete last graf. Gore will not be appearing in
Minneapolis) 
(bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WEST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VETERAN LAWMAKER ROUTED
</P>
<P>
   After 17 years in Congress representing eastern Los Angeles
suburbs, Rep. Matthew G. Martinez was soundly defeated Tuesday in a
primary challenge from a fellow Democrat, state Sen. Hilda L.
Solis. In unofficial returns, Solis had 63 percent of the vote, to
28 percent for Martinez, a result whose lopsided nature surprised
even supporters of the 42-year-old challenger and reflected the
continuing emergence of a new generation of Hispanic politicians in
California. Martinez, 71, known as Marty, was the only member of
Congress who lost in Tuesday's primaries around the country. He had
faced primary challenges in the past in a district that includes
towns like El Monte, Baldwin Park and Alhambra and remains safely
Democratic in November, but this contest was especially bitter,
dividing the local Hispanic elected establishment. Solis, with
backing of local unions, maintained that Martinez had grown out of
touch, and just hours before conceding, he called her obnoxious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES D.A. STUMBLES
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Gil Garcetti, as district attorney of Los Angeles
County the head of the largest local prosecutor's office in the
nation, fall short of a majority in his re-election effort, he came
in second. Garcetti got a little more than 37 percent, to 38
percent for Steve Cooley, one of his deputies. That means they will
face off in November, with Garcetti struggling because of criticism
that he has been slow in handling a police corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   THIS BIRD WON'T FLY
</P>
<P>
   The people of Orange County, just south of Los Angeles, voted in
surprisingly strong numbers for a ballot measure that appears
likely to kill the prospect of building what would have been one of
the largest airports in the region. By 67 percent to 33 percent,
they backed Measure F, which requires that the county government
obtain two-thirds voter approval for a plan to transform the El
Toro military base into the huge airport. Few expect that the
county can muster such a majority for the project, strongly opposed
by residents in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE AND ON TRACK
</P>
<P>
   More than 17,000 Democrats in Arizona cast ballots through the
Internet in the first two days of a primary billed as the first
binding online election. An hourlong failure caused by online
traffic congestion prevented voters from casting ballots early
Tuesday afternoon, and at least 100 voters required technical
assistance because outdated Web browsing software would not allow
them to vote. But by the end of Tuesday, more than 13,000 Democrats
had voted online, officials said. The rate fell Wednesday, after
news that Bill Bradley would drop out of the race. Arizona
Democrats with Internet access can cast ballots through Friday, at
any time of day, and those without access can vote at polling
places Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   OHIO COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   Back from political oblivion, Mary Rose Oakar, an Ohio Democrat
who in the 1992 elections lost her seat in the U.S. House after
eight terms and later pleaded guilty to election law abuses, was
effectively elected by Democrats to a seat in the Ohio House on
Super Tuesday. Oakar defeated three primary rivals for the
nomination in a legislative district that includes part of her old
working-class congressional district. Oakar, who will be unopposed
by Republicans in November, lost her congressional seat after the
House banking and post office scandals broke in 1992. She wrote
more than 200 House bank overdrafts and circumvented election law
by funneling contributions through the House post office.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Denver
</P>
</TEXT>
