<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MEMPHIS _ This was no Elvis sighting. This was the real deal, start
to finish. His Cougars, Clyde Drexler bragged, finally kept the eye
of the tiger right through the final horn. As a result, The Streak
is as dead as The King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Clyde said, looking relieved, ``I might get my hug.''
</P>
<P>
   After the University of Houston succumbed to Louisville on
Saturday, having started horribly and concluded listlessly to
complete Drexler's second regular season with a humbling 11-game
skid, athletic director Chet Gladchuk suggested to Clyde's mother,
Eunice Scott, that her famous son needed a warm embrace to help
keep his dauber up.
</P>
<P>
   Mom, however, is an advocate for tough love. She replied that
none would be forthcoming until the Cougars found a way to beat
somebody. Absolutely not.
</P>
<P>
   We must assume she was kidding. Wasn't she?
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The Cougars got Drexler off the hook Wednesday.
Pyramid power paid off for them _ again _ in the form of a 77-75
victory over Marquette in the first round of the Conference USA
tournament. Since Jan. 8, a span of 60 days that probably felt like
60 years to everybody who cares about the battered Houston program
Drexler is so selflessly attempting to restore to a modicum of
prominence, UH is 2-0 in Memphis' arena and a very unlucky 0-13
everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only other game the Cougars have claimed since the
millennium was by a single point at home against Tulane, which
happens to be their Round 2 opponent today. Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won much lately,'' Gee Gervin said in response to a
question about how he and his teammates would respond to their
newfound, uh, momentum. ``We're hungry for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once all season have the Cougars put together back-to-back
victories _ they beat TSU, Rice and Valparaiso successively in
Houston in early December _ but they've come tantalizingly close
too many times to count.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler's frustration with their inability to stay strong down
the stretch boiled over last week when a 15-point halftime lead
over Southern Mississippi was blown in a 67-65 loss. Afterward,
Clyde questioned the Cougars' heart for making good things happen
with the outcome hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams with no heart find ways to lose, and we have no heart to
step up and win games in the last three minutes,'' were his exact
words that night. Three days later, another flat tire near the
checkered flag doomed UH against Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Against Marquette, however, the Cougars unflinchingly withstood
every threat and never coughed up the lead that Gervin's
three-point play gave them with just under eight minutes gone in
the first half. The Golden Eagles kept the heat on, but in a
startling script rewrite, the Cougars played for the ``W'' instead
of playing to avoid the ``L'' at the end. Shots dropped on a series
of crucial possessions, each of which could have proved fatal with
a misstep.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in shades of UH disasters past, Gervin and Bernard Smith
chased made free throws with misses to keep Marquette in striking
distance, ensuring the dark clouds of doubt over the UH bench would
keep roiling until a successfully completed inbounds pass with 1.8
seconds left permitted the clock to expire.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations, based on empirical evidence, had to have been low,
for both Drexler and the Cougars. Yet somehow the terrible weight
of the past wouldn't be allowed to drag them down. UH hadn't won a
postseason game of any kind since defeating TCU in the Southwest
Conference tournament in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when everybody thought Pat Foster was a bum because he
couldn't get the Cougars out of the first round of the NCAAs? Or
when Guy Lewis got beat up for failing to win a national
championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``This team had a lot to overcome mentally,'' Drexler conceded.
``I'm really proud of the way they were able to hang in. We finally
made a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   If not exactly a statement. Marquette, at 15-13, isn't anything
special. That the Golden Eagles were unable to erase one-point
deficits on nine occasions was at least as much an indictment of
their own deficient wherewithal as it was evidence the Cougars have
truly turned a meaningful corner. But as desperate as Houston's
plight had become, with a school-record 21 losses already indelibly
attached to Drexler's legacy, any sign of life is to be construed
as a major step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of how next year should be the year for UH to
blossom, given its promising incoming recruiting class.
Nonetheless, to go into the season beaten down by the weight of a
dozen defeats in a row wasn't going to be a healthy situation for
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   A mother and her son included.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
