<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-09 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
RUDY Tomjanovich was flipping channels on the TV recently when
suddenly the pictures and the faces became so familiar that he put
down the remote control and became caught up in the old moment.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charles Barkley wearing the uniform of the Phoenix
Suns, and there were Hakeem Olajuwon, Clyde Drexler, Sam Cassell
and Mario Elie doing amazing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those classic sports channels, and they were
showing Game 7 of the Phoenix series in the second championship
season,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I got caught up in it and started to
watch it, to appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, we all remember Mario's shot that won the game. But
I was sitting there, and I started to see all the other little
things that made it possible. Loose balls, an extra pass on
offense, a hand on a ball on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching, and I'm thinking, `One free throw in the right
place by them, and all this could have not taken place.' It's
amazing how fast it's all happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What is equally amazing is that Rudy T, the reluctant head coach
at the time he succeeded Don Chaney in February 1992, has now
signed a contract extension that will keep him on the job through
2005. Which speaks to the respect he has earned from within the
Rockets organization and the stature he has achieved outside it,
all while attracting little notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Any time somebody starts listing the coaching geniuses on their
blackboard or telestrator, the familiar names are offered.
</P>
<P>
   There is Ayatollah Pat Riley and an approach that has grown
increasingly iron-fisted in his three incarnations in LA, New York
and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Brown is usually regarded as a basketball gypsy, roaming
from town to town spreading locker-room wisdom like Johnny
Appleseed.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, the guru, has six championship rings in his trophy
case, not a single one of them without Michael Jordan, and now he
may be moving toward another, with Godzilla _ in the form of
Shaquille O'Neal _ trampling a path.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson still gets acclaim in some corners as a nutty
professor with all of his wild lineups and tactics, but he has
never taken a team to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, managing to stay just out of the spotlight are a couple
of guys named Rudy T and Jerry Sloan, who just happen to have more
tenure with their current teams than any other pair of coaches in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're similar in that we don't necessarily like the
notoriety,'' Tomjanovich said. ``All the other stuff that goes
along with having this job, I do because it's part of it. But if it
were just about basketball, I'd be in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the shoemaker's son from Hamtramck, Mich., has changed
somewhat as a result of his success, because success does that. But
what has not changed are his core beliefs about playing the game,
about starting it all with defense, about teammates making
sacrifices and yet allowing the disparate personalities on a club
to keep their individual identities while committing to the common
goal. It's how he won two championships in his first three full
seasons on the job and how he has quietly carved out a reputation
as one of the coaches everybody wants to play for and have
represent them.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Tomjanovich led a group of CBA wannabes and
European castoffs to the bronze medal at the World Basketball
Championships in Greece, it was not just the X's and O's and
results that overwhelmed the hierarchy of USA Basketball, but his
demeanor and the way his team played for him.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he'll lead the Olympic Dream Team this summer. And
why it was the right move for owner Leslie Alexander to keep this
team in his hands as the Rockets try to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich is so familiar, so comfortable here that we
sometimes fail to put his accomplishments into proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens is the career leader in coaching victories, won
one title in Seattle, coached the U.S. to Olympic gold in 1996 and
is in the Hall of Fame. Chuck Daly won two NBA titles in Detroit,
coached the 1992 Olympic team to gold and is in the Hall of Fame.
Rudy T has two titles and will be on the sidelines in Sydney. He is
compiling a Hall of Fame resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about those things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he has other problems. Like teaching these young
Rockets what it means to give it up for each other, to buy into his
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, it's an awesome task to try to do it all again from the
ground up,'' he said. ``But I watched that game on TV from '95, and
I remember the feeling. I want to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   So he stays and believes. In the past and the future.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
