<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SEEKING NEW HOME?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the start of the 2000 Major League Soccer
season just nine days away, the Galaxy's long-term future at the
Rose Bowl appears to be shakier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy and Cal State Dominguez Hills officials confirmed
Wednesday they have talked about the team building a stadium on the
Carson campus. The 30,000- to 35,000-seat soccer-specific stadium
would be constructed on the site of the 1984 Olympic Velodrome.
</P>
<P>
   The $50-60 million facility also could house a training center,
perhaps featuring six or more fields that also could be used by
U.S. Soccer's National Teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy opens the 2000 MLS season March 18 against Colorado
at the Rose Bowl, where it has played for four years. The team's
Rose Bowl lease expires after this season, but it holds an option
for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't solidified anything yet, but we are fortunate that
we have the kind of land available for this to happen,'' said
George Pardon, Cal State Dominguez Hills vice president of business
and administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next month is really going to determine what happens,''
Galaxy General Manager Sergio Del Prado said. ``The support we get
at the start of the season will determine it, and also what we're
able to work out with the Rose Bowl in terms of making it more
attractive for our fans. But obviously, we would love to have a
soccer-specific stadium. But the economics have to make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl General Manager Darryl Dunn said he isn't resigned to
losing the team yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to do what's best for their franchise,'' he said.
``You have to respect that. But hopefully, they would look at our
positive attributes before they make a decision (to leave).''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy owner Philip F. Anschutz took a helicopter ride over the
campus a month ago. It is located near the junction of the Harbor
(110), San Diego (405) and 91 freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Just Tuesday, U.S. soccer officials unveiled their plans for a
National Training Center. They are accepting bids to construct and
service a permanent training facility for all of U.S. Soccer's
National teams.
</P>
<P>
   If the Galaxy and Cal State Dominguez Hills can reach agreement,
officials said Anschutz would build a stadium and also make a bid
for the U.S. Soccer training center.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon said architects hired by the Galaxy have surveyed 40 to
50 acres of the university's campus that would be needed for the
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we met, about three weeks ago, they brought a
master plan architect and we talked about availability, how much
land we had to offer and how this could work for them,'' said
Pardon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know whether it works from their perspective, but
we're hopeful. People here are embracing the idea. The only people
objecting are those who use the velodrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon says the velodrome doesn't generate any revenue for the
university. He said the university spends roughly $10,000 a year to
help maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon said Cal State Dominguez Hills would make money on a
soccer stadium, because the Galaxy would lease the land from the
university.
</P>
<P>
   If the parties can reach an agreement, Pardon said he expects
the Galaxy would begin construction quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read an article that said Anschutz would like a stadium
built in 18 months,'' said Pardon. ``I would speculate once they
have a design, it's costed out and the framework is put forward, we
could go through this in a timely manner once environmental studies
and other necessary studies are completed. It also has to be
something the community wants, and we think it does.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rose Bowl also would love to keep the Galaxy, Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the history of soccer here, we would love to be the
permanent home of the Galaxy,'' he said. ``We know they have
concerns about the size of the Rose Bowl, but there are sports
architects these days that can do incredible things to develop an
intimate atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rose Bowl can't offer the new training facility the
Galaxy desperately needs and wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the space for soccer in the city of Pasadena is
lacking,'' said Dunn. ``If there was space in Pasadena for us to
use both our resources we would love to work something out with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said there is no animosity between the Rose Bowl and the
Galaxy, nor has there been since Anschutz purchased the franchise
in the fall of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 0117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
