<HEADLINE>
CARTER'S LEGEND GROWS WITH ANOTHER GAME-WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a cushion of 324 days before Vince Carter's
next birthday, the Clippers appeared to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   So, like graffiti on a masterpiece, the NBA's biggest joke
thought it had rallied from Shaquille O'Neal's 61-point birthday
party by defacing Carter's critically acclaimed road show.
</P>
<P>
   Hah, these are the Clippers and this is March Badness.
</P>
<P>
   All Carter did was pen another chapter in his growing legend by
dropping a 3-pointer at the buzzer Wednesday to give Toronto a
95-94 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This foiled art depreciation happened before 18,176
rubberneckers at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   After Toronto erased a 14-point, fourth-quarter hole, rookie
Lamar Odom dropped a pair of free throws with 1.5 before extinction
to give the Clippers' a 94-92 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors' now have a franchise-high, seven-game winning
streak. Carter, the NBA's newly anointed acrobat out of hell,
answered his 35-point effort vs. the Trail Blazers by scoring 23
points (12 in the fourth quarter) on 9-of-21 shooting. He had 51
points vs. Phoenix in the first game of the streak.
</P>
<P>
   Clipper Tyrone Nesby, Carter's date for the evening, showed up
prepared and produced 21 points. He also left Carter wide open on
the final play.
</P>
<P>
   Odom bagged 16 points, 11 rebounds and 8 assists while running
the point. Maurice Taylor had 20 points on 8-of-14 shooting, while
Michael Olowokandi checked in with 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a 6-point, 5-rebound deliverance by Olowokandi - and a
1-for-6 shooting effort from Carter - the Clippers led, 21-18,
after the first quarter. Nesby (9 points) and Taylor (8) took over
in round two, and the Clips led, 51-43, at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto went up, 65-64, with three minutes left in the third,
but consecutive steal-and-dunk plays by Nesby and Derek Anderson
gave the Clippers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Their greatest advantage (86-72) happened when Anderson nailed a
3-point jumper with 9:01 to play.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Clippers sprayed a little graffiti on what had
been their own masterpiece. Charles Oakley finally brought the
Raptors even at 90 by making a 20-footer with 1:16 left.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Former Long Beach State head coach Joe Harrington
(1987-'90) is in his second season as an assistant with the
Raptors. Toronto's head coach, Butch Carter, was an assistant for
the 49ers under Harrington, who won 53 of the 89 games at LBSU. ``I
love it and I've learned so much about basketball,'' Harrington
said of coaching in the NBA. ``To be around guys like Vince
(Carter) and Tracy (McGrady) is a privilege.'' ....Clippers point
guard Troy Hudson (gastritis) extended his streak for not suiting
up to t hree. ... Aside from having only a dozen victories, the
Clippers had added incentive in their attempt at defeating Toronto.
The Raptors' lottery-protected pick in the 2000 NBA Draft - which
would be the 18th selection as the standings fall right now - had
belonged to the Atlanta Hawks, who traded it (along with their own
No. 1 pick) to the Clippers in last summer's Lorenzen Wright
sign-and-trade deal. More Raptors' losses mean a higher selection
for the Clips. ... Veteran point guard Haywoode Workman turned down
an offer to sign with the Clippers last off-season, then had his
agent tell the Clips to pass when the Milwaukee Bucks put him on
waivers last month. The Clippers did, choosing to avoid bringing in
a player who didn't want to be here. Workman was claimed by the
Raptors, who've played him 42 minutes in the six games he
participated in prior to Wednesday night. He might be starting for
the Clips, but the Raptors entered the game as the fourth playoff
seed in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
