<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, March 9.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-GIRLS-SCHOOLS (Kabul, Afghanistan) _ Her name is Fatima,
and she was risking a beating. Defiantly, she stood outside,
talking to a man. Her face was uncovered. Under Taliban rule, such
openness by a woman is forbidden. But Fatima said she did not care.
She was growing used to a life with some risk. Three months ago,
she and a few other women decided to break the law. They opened a
school for girls. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Dateline to kum) _ Interview with the presidential
candidate excoriated by China for independence views. He says the
attacks will help him, but they seem to be scaring voters. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-MUSEUM-EXHIBIT (New York) _ Every couple of years the Whitney
Museum of American Art mounts its Biennial, an exhibition of new
and often cutting-edge American art. This year, one work may be a
little too cutting. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXTINCT-RECOVER () _ The history of the Earth is pocked with
episodes of mass extinction _ including the present, apparently _
in which large numbers of species have died out. New research
suggests that, contrary to what you might think, it takes about 10
million years for the ecosystem to repopulate itself, regardless of
the magnitude of the extinction. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-GENOME (Undated) _ An inside look at how and why a
proposed collaboration between Craig Venter and the NIH _ the two
players in the race to sequence the human genome _ fell apart last
week. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Strategists for Vice President Al
Gore and Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that there would be no
let up from the primary season as they move quickly to define each
other on the stump and on the air in an unusually frenetic
five-month run up to their parties' nominating conventions. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT1,2) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Even as Vice President Al Gore
challenges Gov. George W. Bush to stop raising the unlimited
campaign donations known as soft money, Gore aides are launching a
program to help the Democrats raise $35 million in such funds over
the next few months. By Don Van Natta and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ Magic was in the air as Bill
Bradley returned to his hometown last September. Pundits and
pollsters swooned, Vice President Al Gore's campaign seemed to be
disintegrating, and Bradley launched his own presidential race with
a brilliant speech that sent him soaring the way he first had as a
high school basketball star in that very same gymnasium. And then,
of course, Bradley crashed back to earth. A look back at what went
wrong. By James Dao and Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-COLO (Denver) _ Sen. John McCain is still in the running
in Colorado's primary, which is Friday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-JOBS (Chicago) _ With unemployment low and companies
scrambling to find workers for the jobs they are creating, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service is looking the other way
when it finds illegal immigrants on the job. Border patrols are
working harder than ever, and the INS still comes down hard on
companies that smuggle aliens into the country. But once inside the
U.S., illegal immigrants are largely left alone. Unions are even
negotiating contracts that shield these workers from INS scrutiny.
By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Is it still a bull market if it
is running on only one leg? That is the question investors are
asking as they ponder a badly bifurcated stock market, where a
handful of strong stocks is surrounded by a mass of the weak. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-PHONES (Richmond, Mass.) _ Richmond Telephone Co. is
not your typical phone company. Its headquarters is a
green-shuttered, white clapboard house on Route 41, in far-western
Massachusetts just shy of the New York border. It has 13 employees,
including a one-man repair crew named Maurice. Its phone book
listings are 12 pages long, representing 1,168 residents and
businesses. And it has handled the calls here for 97 years. By
Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to to NYT graphic clients.)
