<SLUG> BC-CONG27-FOLLOW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
27TH DISTRICT BATTLE UNDER WAY
</HEADLINE>
 - LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER HAMM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Los Angeles _ The November congressional campaign is already in
high gear between incumbent Rep. James Rogan, R-Pasadena, and
challenger state Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena, even before the last
ballots in Tuesday's primary have been tallied.
</P>
<P>
   The rivals, who will meet in the Nov. 7 general election, had a
free ride in this week's primary because neither faced opposition
from within his own party.
</P>
<P>
   But both were pointing to Tuesday's results as a sign of failure
by the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff called it a ``stunning defeat'' for Rogan, who received
47percent of the votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally shocked,'' said Schiff, who received 49percent
of the votes. ``I figured (Rogan) would have to have a substantial
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rogan, who represents a district in which registered voters
are 44 percent Democratic and only 37 percent Republican, said he
was also surprised, pleasantly so, because his support Tuesday
extended beyond the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   He said the results prove voters are solidly behind what he
calls his ``issue-based campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This election shows that voters stand behind honest
representation in Washington, not partisan politics,'' Rogan said
Wednesday. ``Adam Schiff's dreams of being this great savior of the
district who was just going to ride in to a victory is obviously
not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted he might have the most votes in the primary after
late absentee ballots are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, a two-term congressman and former Municipal Court judge,
drew national attention when he served as a House impeachment
manager during the Senate trial of President Clinton last year.
Critics of the impeachment process vowed to raise campaign
contributions and drive Rogan from office in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be one of the most closely watched congressional races
in the country,'' said H. Eric Schockman, a professor of political
science at the University of Southern California. ``If Schiff does
win, it really does start chipping away at the Republican
scorecard.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a Republican stronghold, the 27th District has seen its
registered voters becoming increasingly Democratic in recent years.
The district includes Burbank, Glendale, Sunland, Tujunga, Pasadena
and nearby areas.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff has raised nearly $1.4 million in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan has collected $2.5 million and spent much of it on
fund-raising, establishing a list of contributors he can call on in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   A large Democratic voter turnout for the presidential election
in November could be a factor in the Schiff-Rogan contest, said
Stanley W. Moore, a political science professor at Pepperdine
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a powerful election tide for Gore, I think Rogan
will leave,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
