<HEADER>
A1432 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHR     03-09 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER'S LEGEND GROWS WITH ANOTHER GAME-WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a cushion of 324 days before Vince Carter's
next birthday, the Clippers appeared to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   So, like graffiti on a masterpiece, the NBA's foremost punch
line attempted to rally from Shaquille O'Neal's 61-point birthday
party by defacing Carter's critically acclaimed road show.
</P>
<P>
   But these are the Clippers and this is March Badness. They don't
seem eager to study their play book, but they certainly can read a
script.
</P>
<P>
   And all Carter did was create another Michael Jordan
impressionist painting by dropping a deep 3-pointer at the buzzer
Wednesday to give Toronto a 95-94 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This foiled art depreciation happened before 18,176
rubberneckers at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we could go for a 2 or a 3, but I was going for a 3,''
Carter said of his battle plan when the Raptors broke their huddle
trailing, 94-92, with 1.5 to play. ``If I miss it, everybody will
be mad. If I make it, we celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   And, once again, the Clipper bannedwagon (31 defeats in their
last 34 games) careened into the nearest ditch.
</P>
<P>
   After Toronto (35-25) erased a 14-point, fourth-quarter hole,
rookie Lamar Odom dropped a pair of free throws with 1.5 before
extinction to give the Clippers that 94-92 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after a pair of strategy-shuffling timeouts, an unguarded
Carter received the inbound pass from Tracy McGrady and promptly
extended the Raptors' winning streak to a franchise-high seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to switch everything so we could stop the lob
inside,'' said Clippers interim coach Jim Todd, attempting to
explain why Carter was so lonely above the 3-point arc. ``We were
going to switch any screens and any cross screens.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Raptors didn't screen. The Clippers switched anyway,
with Tyrone Nesby - who guarded and outplayed Carter for three
quarters - running at McGrady, who wouldn't have had time to
receive a return pass and fire before the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured he (Nesby) was going there for reason, because there
must have been someone behind me,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Your witness, Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just got all messed up,'' said Nesby, who shared team-high
scoring honors with Derek Anderson at 21.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the NBA's newly anointed acrobat out of hell, scored 23
points (12 in the fourth quarter) on 9-of-21 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Odom bagged 16 points, 11 rebounds and 8 assists while running
the point. Maurice Taylor had 20 points on 8-of-14 shooting, while
Michael Olowokandi checked in with 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (12-49) led after each of the first three quarters,
and took their biggest lead (84-72), when Anderson nailed a 3 with
only 9 minutes between his team and victory.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Clippers sprayed a little graffiti on what had
been their own masterpiece. Charles Oakley finally brought the
Raptors even at 90 by making a 20-footer with 1:16 left.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Former Long Beach State head coach Joe Harrington
(1987-'90) is in his second season as an assistant with the
Raptors. Toronto's head coach, Butch Carter, was an assistant for
the 49ers under Harrington, who won 53 of the 89 games at LBSU. ``I
love it and I've learned so much about basketball,'' Harrington
said of coaching in the NBA. ``To be around guys like Vince
(Carter) and Tracy (McGrady) is a privilege.'' ....Clippers point
guard Troy Hudson (gastritis) extended his streak for not suiting
up to three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
