<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 03:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     03-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS LET ANOTHER GET AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks seem intent on making it Christmas
all season long -- they certainly have caught the spirit of giving.
In their lastest third-period disaster it was Guy Hebert in the
role of Santa Claus as he gave up two soft goals and the New York
Rangers went on to defeat the Ducks 4-3 in overtime before 13,565
at The Pond on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim dominated the game, outshooting New York 39-22, but they
couldn't overcome yet another shakey performance by Hebert, who
like the Ducks is making inconsistency an artform.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert had already allowed a floater by Radek Dvorak to beat him
on the stick side in the first period, but Ducks responded to take
a 3-2 lead into the final 1 1/2 minutes of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   It look as if it would be a mere formality for Anaheim to wrap
up its sixth win in six games against the Rangers at The Pond. But
then Jan Hlavac's sharp angle shot from the bottom of the left
circle somehow went under Hebert's arm to tie the game at 18:40.
</P>
<P>
   With one point already given away, the Ducks then allowed Brian
Leetch to walk down the slot and beat Hebert on glove 29 seconds
into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a helluva game, I can't say anything bad about the
way we played,'' said Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg. ``It's
certainly a heartbreaking loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg seemed leery to say much about Hebert's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other goalie (Mike Richter) stood on his head,'' he said.
``We have to come up with bigger saves.''
</P>
<P>
   By squandering the lead and the game, the Ducks lost a chance to
pick up a point on eighth-place San Jose, which remains four points
ahead of the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give up points like that,'' said Ducks center Tony
Hrkac, who gave the Ducks a 1-0 lead in the first period. ``One
minute left, you have to keep them down. Maybe in a year or so we
won't make these mistakes, but we need the points now.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly bent on self-destruction the Ducks fell behind 2-1
early in the second period. But Anaheim responded with two goals to
take a 3-2 lead after 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Richter on the top of his game, Anaheim needed to crash the
net and that is just what it did. On the Ducks' second power chance
of the night Paul Kariya, returning from a seven-game absence due
to a foot injury, made a nice backhand pass to Fredrik Olausson at
the right point and his shot was deflected in the slot by Steve
Rucchin for the center's 15th goal of the season at 6:45.
</P>
<P>
   Richter denied Jeff Nielsen, Mike Leclerc and Hrkac on one
flurry in front of the New York net midway through the period, but
there was little he could do to stop Teemu Selanne from scoring his
26th goal of the year at 12:08. Rucchin put a shot on net after
Pavel Trnka aggressively held the puck in at the left point and
Selanne outbattled Brian Leetch for his own rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot New York 10-6 and controlled play most of the
first period, but they left the ice with little to show for their
efforts as the Rangers tied the game 1-1 with 35.2 seconds left in
the period on a suspect goal by Radek Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who shutout Nashville on Sunday, was beat stick side
from the top of the right circle on a shot -- yet another in series
of soft goals that have plagued the Anaheim goalie this year.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes earlier, Richter made a huge save on
Rucchin to keep the Rangers within a goal. After taking a cross-ice
pass from Selanne, Rucchin appeared to have the New York goalie
beat with his one-timer from the right circle, but Richter slid
across the crease and just got his pads on the shot.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied, 1-1, another Anaheim weakness reared its
ugly head. The league's worst penalty killing unit gave up its 55th
goal of the season at 4:43. The Ducks failed on a chance to clear
the puck and it soon wound up behind Hebert when Michael York found
Adam Graves alone in front of the net. The verteran winger took his
time and beat Hebert with a perfect shot on the stick side.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame attention was rightfully centered around the return of
Kariya, but it was Anaheim's fourth line that gave the Ducks a 1-0
lead at 7:11. Taking advantage of a turnover at the New York blue
line and some good corner work by Nielsen, Tony Hrkac scored from
the edge of the crease when his shot bounced off Mike Knuble and
into the New York net. It was just the fourth goal of the year for
the veteran Ducks center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
