A1436 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     03-09 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INS AND OUTS OF NCAA TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who's in, who's out, winners and losers, picks and
pans - it's the season (and postseason) in 1,000 words, starting
with predicted NCAA Tournament bids.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10: Stanford's the No. 1 seed in the West if it beats
Arizona tonight. (If not, the Cardinal could lose its top spot.)
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the No. 2 seed in the West if it beats Stanford
tonight. (If not, the Wildcats will get shipped out as a No. 3.)
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's in for the first time since 1995, probably as a seventh
seed.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA needs one victory to clinch - presumably, it comes tonight
against Washington State - and probably is headed for a No. 7 or 8
seed.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State has just 16 Division I wins and ziltch on its
nonconference resume, so the Sun Devils must sweep Cal and Stanford
this weekend to get a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Coast Conference: Duke is the top seed in the East and
will play in Winston-Salem, N.C. Maryland's in, North Carolina's
in, and Virginia clinches a bid if it beats N.C. State in the first
round of the ACC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic-10: Temple's a No. 2 seed if it wins the A-10 tourney,
a No. 3 seed if it doesn't. Either way, the Owls are the one team
!ital!no one wants to play. Just ask Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's also in. St. Bonaventure and Xavier probably aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten: The winner of the league tournament (assuming it's
Michigan State or Ohio State) is the top seed in the South and
probably plays in Nashville, Tenn. The loser's a No. 2, perhaps in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, Purdue and Illinois are locks. Wisconsin's deserves a
bid based on nonconference victories over Texas, Temple, Marquette
and Missouri. The Badgers could be a No. 9 or 10 seed, which makes
them a possible first-round foe for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   SEC: The nation's best conference should send six to the
tournament. Florida, Tennessee, Kentucky and Louisiana State
(another team to avoid) will be high seeds. Vanderbilt's probably
in that No. 8-10 range and also could draw UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's fate depends on suspended star Chris Porter; if the
Selection committee doesn't expect him to return, it could drop the
Tigers to a No. 7 or 8 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12: Texas, Oklahoma, Oklahoma State, Kansas and surprising
Iowa State are locks. Missouri, which lacks good wins, probably
needs a victory in the conference tourney. Yes, the bland Big 12
could get six bids.
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA: Cincinnati is the No. 1 seed in the Midwest and
probably will play in Cleveland. Louisville has 18 wins and tough
schedule to boost its seed. DePaul needs a win in the C-USA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Big East: Syracuse, Connecticut, Miami, Seton Hall and St.
John's, the hottest of the bunch, are in. Notre Dame (17-13) and
Villanova are out, hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain West: Utah's the only lock from this rookie conference,
which does not have an automatic bid this season. UNLV probably
needs a few wins in the conference tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Western Athletic: Tulsa is the trendy pick for a few upsets -
this year's Gonzaga. Jerry Tarkanian's trying for his first
tournament appearance with Fresno State. Southern Methodist also
has a case. Odds are, one of the two will get in.
</P>
<P>
   West Coast: Gonzaga's in, of course, and Pepperdine should have
nothing to worry about. The Waves' schedule will score major points
with Selection committee members, who saw the botched call against
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   All-American team: Iowa State's Marcus Fizer, Cincinnati's
Kenyon Martin, Notre Dame's Troy Murphy, Louisiana State's Stromile
Swift and Indiana's A.J. Guyton.
</P>
<P>
   Second-team: Ohio State's Scoonie Penn, Michigan State's Mo
Peterson, Duke's Shane Battier, Texas' Chris Mihm and Fresno
State's Courtney Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Player of the Year: Martin is the best player on the No. 1 team,
and his numbers are superb: 19.5 points, 10 rebounds and 3.57
blocks per game. But the Bearcats would be a top-25 team without
him.
</P>
<P>
   No one combines production and value like Fizer, a 6-8 junior
who's averaging 24.8 points in Big 12 play. The Cyclones were
picked seventh in the Big 12 in the preseason. Thanks to Fizer, who
has scored at least 30 points in five consecutive games, they won
the regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Iowa State's Larry Eustachy has been
brilliant, guiding the Cyclones to their first league title since
1945. But the pick here is LSU's John Brady, who guided the upstart
Tigers (25-4, 12-4) to the SEC West title.
</P>
<P>
   All-Pac-10 team: Arizona's Loren Woods, Michael Wright and Jason
Gardner, Arizona State's Eddie House, USC's Brian Scalabrine,
UCLA's Jason Kapono, Stanford's Mark Madsen and Casey Jacobsen,
Oregon's Alex Scales and A.D. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Just missed the cut: UCLA's Earl Watson, Arizona's Gilbert
Arenas, USC's David Bluthenthal, UCLA's Jerome Moiso, Cal's Sean
Lampley and Stanford's David Moseley.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 freshman of the Year: It's a fabulous group, no doubt.
Jacobsen, Kapono and Arenas were consistently good. But for
excellence and impact, they can't top Gardner, who averaged 12.9
points, 4.9 assists and 37 minutes at the toughest position, point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 Coach of the Year: Arizona's Lute Olson or Stanford's
Mike Montgomery? Give it to tonight's winner.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 Player of the Year: It was Woods until he got hurt. House
has the best numbers (22.9 ppg) and the best game (61 points) of
the contenders, and he's pushed his team beyond expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one problem: He's the mouthiest, dirtiest player in
the league. House went so far as to grab Arizona guard Gilbert
Arenas' groin several times in a recent matchup - for the purpose
of inhibiting Arenas' off-ball movement.
</P>
<P>
   One courtside observer saw House do it, while another heard
Arenas complain to the officials. After the game, Arenas confirmed
it. Naturally, House denied it.
</P>
<P>
   So let's give the Pac-10's top prize to one of its best
citizens, Stanford senior Mark Madsen, who plays hard, not dirty.
Madsen might be the nicest guy in the league. When UCLA's JaRon
Rush took the court for warmups Saturday - his first game in three
months - Madsen immediately extended a hand and welcomed Rush back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 0322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 03:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-09 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING IS THE HARD PART FOR PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pepperdine basketball players surely know how John McCain
felt as he waited for the votes from Tuesday's primaries to be
tabulated.
</P>
<P>
   Or what it was like to be Michael Clarke Duncan in the days
before the Academy announced its Oscar nominees.
</P>
<P>
   For Jan van Breda Kolff, Pepperdine's first-year coach, this
week must feel kind of like that moment 26 years ago between his
proposal of marriage and wife Betty's reply.
</P>
<P>
   For four days more, the Waves are doomed to college basketball's
purgatory, suspended between grace and everlasting regret.
</P>
<P>
   They earned the benevolence of the 10-member NCAA Tournament
selection committee by winning the West Coast Conference
regular-season title outright but are being made to suffer for
having narrowly failed to beat Gonzaga in Monday's WCC tournament
final.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' 69-65 overtime victory against Pepperdine earned
them automatic entry into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves ought to crash the postseason gala as one of the 35
at-large teams by virtue of their 24-8 record, which includes
regular-season victories over tournament-bound Louisiana-Lafayette
and Gonzaga, an Elite Eight team in 1999, and RPI-boosting losses
against Auburn, UCLA and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all worried today,'' van Breda Kolff said Wednesday
about securing an at-large berth. He allowed himself a small
chuckle. ``You can ask me again in a few days. But right now I'm 99
percent certain we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff gave his players Tuesday and Wednesday off, so
naturally they've been doing a lot of surfing. Not in the swelling
waves of the Pacific below campus, mind you, but on the Internet
where various so-called experts have seeded Pepperdine anywhere
from No. 9 in the South to No. 11 in the East to a No. 12,
destination unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the result of too many hours holed up in a hotel
meeting room, but the NCAA Tournament Selection Committee has shown
a puckish streak in the past. A wink-wink-nudge-nudge scenario this
year would have the Waves being shipped out to Nashville, one of
the South sub-regional sites and van Breda Kolff's address until
last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny ... for the past month my assistant coaches have
pulled up (mock) Tournament seedings on the Internet and lately it
seems that our seeding keeps changing, but we always end up in
Nashville,'' said van Breda Kolff, who coached at Vanderbilt for
six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He was unceremoniously let go from the university - his alma
mater, no less - at the end of the 1999 season after averaging 17.3
wins a year. Van Breda Kolff's son, Jan-Michael, is a senior at
Vanderbilt and he keeps hearing the Waves are Nashville-bound.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls me, laughing, and says, `Wouldn't that be
unbelievable?''' said the elder van Breda Kolff, who would prefer
not to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather the focus be on who we're playing, not where we're
playing,'' said van Breda Kolff, who landed the Pepperdine job in
April.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to Malibu, he promptly installed a high-octane
brand of basketball, complete with a full-court press that
perfectly complemented the nine returning lettermen he inherited
from Lorenzo Romar, who left to become the head coach at St. Louis
University.
</P>
<P>
   The lapping Waves opened with a two-point win over Long Beach
State, a probable NCAA Tournament participant, and finished with 16
victories in their final 19 games. Their Ratings Percentage Index -
the tournament admission equivalent of the SAT - is in the high 30s
or low 40s, depending on whose calculations you endorse.
</P>
<P>
   (Pepperdine has reason to be suspicious of the RPI after winning
two games against conference caboose Loyola Marymount in
mid-February and watching its RPI drop while Cal saw its RPI rise
after suffering a 51-point defeat at Stanford the same week.)
</P>
<P>
   The Waves did everything to get into the NCAA Tournament but
crisply execute their offense in their final few possessions
against Gonzaga Monday night. They deserve an at-large bid, if for
no other reason than to keep the two-month conference schedule from
appearing as expendable as tonsils.
</P>
<P>
   A snip here, a cut there and college basketball loses much of
its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, to presume the curtain will rise on Pepperdine's NCAA
Tournament scenario is to set the stage for yet another Vitalean
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Cal was bloodied by the dagger last year, failing to make the
64-team cut despite posting regular-season victories over Arizona,
North Carolina and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   How deep was the wound? More people probably remember the
Bruins' first-round loss to Detroit-Mercy in the NCAA Tournament
than the Golden Bears' victory over Clemson in the final of the
National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Gonzaga beat Clemson during the regular season but
San Francisco, with nary a quality win on its regular-season
ledger, won the WCC Tournament and advanced to a first-round NCAA
Tournament date while the Bulldogs stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   Those Bulldogs were as worthy of an NCAA bid as these Waves,
which is why there is no joy in Malibu just yet.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, until dusk on Sunday it'd probably be better for
Pepperdine fans to err on the side of gloom, especially given that
only six times in the 45-year history of the WCC has two of its
teams marched in the NCAA postseason parade.
</P>
<P>
   If the Waves don't expect too much from the NCAA Tournament
Selection Committee, they're liable not to be let down. That said,
we'll be chagrined if Pepperdine isn't in.
</P>
<P>
   Why, it'd be the biggest crime committed against the program
since referee Ruben Ramos waved off Craig Lewis' putback of a David
Lalazarian three-point miss that would have sent Pepperdine's game
at UCLA into overtime back in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves deserved the chance to play on then, just as they do
now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 0326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
