<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     03-09 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SURPRISES WEBER STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. - This is a knockout tournament, and the Cal
State Northridge men's basketball team had the heavy punches, the
speed and the stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Bye-bye, Weber State. So long, defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who had never played the Wildcats in the Big Sky
tournament, made their mark Wednesday night in a 73-68 win in front
of 3,522 surprised fans at Dahlberg Arena.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (19-9) advanced to Friday night's semifinal against
top-seeded Montana, the tournament host. The Wildcats (18-10) limp
back to Utah after losing in the first round for the first time in
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Matadors) are just a good team,'' said Weber State's
Harold Arceneaux, the two-time Big Sky Player of the Year who had
26 points. ``I can't beat around the bush; they've probably got the
best talent in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN, which made it to the tournament semifinals for the third
time in four seasons, simply ran WSU into the ground in the second
half for its fourth consecutive win. Northridge used an 18-5 run
out of halftime to take a 52-40 lead and control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Andre Larry had eight of his 20 points in the
flurry. Larry made 8 of 11 shots, including 4 of 6 on 3-point
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to go home early like we did last year,'' Larry
said, referring to CSUN's 91-90 first-round loss to Montana State.
``This year we've got a lot of fire in us.''
</P>
<P>
   That fortitude was strong in the first half, when Arceneaux
appeared to be on his way to a 40-point night. The 6-foot-6 forward
outscored CSUN himself 8-6 in the first four minutes, and Weber
State took a 13-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But CSUN held and rallied to tie the game at 17 at the 12-minute
mark. A dunk by Larry made it 19-17 and WSU realized this wasn't
the same Northridge team that disintegrated in the second half of
the teams' first game, a 113-92 Wildcats win in Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   Arceneaux and Eddie Gill combined for 70 points that night, and
afterward CSUN coach Bobby Braswell vowed the Wildcats hadn't seen
``the real Northridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Braswell was right. Despite the early Arceneaux
explosion _ Braswell said the Matadors were failing in their
``Arceneaux awareness'' _ he and Gill ended up making a combined 10
of 29 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Gill had a miserable game to possibly end his career
</P>
<P>
   1 for 13 from the field, five points, eight turnovers, five
fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know (Weber State) doesn't sub Harold and Eddie much,''
Braswell said. ``Part of Eddie's poor shooting has to do with the
fact he played 39 minutes. He didn't get a break until he fouled
out. We wanted to keep defensive pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was done in part by CSUN point guard Markus Carr, who
destroyed Gill on the offensive end with a career-high 23 points,
and reserve Craig Calloway, a freshman who had seven quality
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gill wasn't the only first-team all-conference player in the
tank. CSUN center Brian Heinle missed all seven of his shots in the
first half. But Heinle's fortunes changed a bit in the opening
seconds of the second half; he rattled in a 12-footer that gave
Northridge a 35-34 lead. Weber State never led after that.
</P>
<P>
   Heinle made up for his 2-for-13 night with six rebounds and four
assists. Also strong on the boards was senior forward Hewitt Rolle,
who had seven rebounds in 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northridge played a great game,'' said WSU forward Shawn
Moore, who missed both his shots and was scoreless. ``Northridge is
a great team. No excuses. We just couldn't hang with them in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first men's quarterfinal, third-seeded Northern Arizona
held off No.6 Portland State 77-75. The Vikings (15-14) had a
chance to tie the game at the buzzer, but guard Ivan Garner's
10-foot shot bounced off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   NAU (18-10) plays No.2 Eastern Washington (15-11) in the other
semifinal Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
