<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX     03-09 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Public that favors gun control held hostage by NRA
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After just about every notorious new, senseless shooting spree _
most recently the death of that six-year-old girl, those five shot
by a Pennsylvania man in anti-white rage _ my wife asks how many
more must die before we get sensible gun control. The question is
only rhetorical, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be because the answer is already in: the numbers do
not matter because the powers resisting gun control simply don't
care about them. There is no elusive, magical body count out there
that will trip legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   If there were, we would have comprehensive control now, instead
of our current mishmash of laws. After all, year in and year out,
we lose more of our folks to gunfire than most other comparable
democracies combined.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton keeps pointing out, last year we lost some
4,700 children in gun deaths _ more than the child gun deaths in
the next 25 countries altogether. Even that can't unstick beholden
members of Congress from gun-lobby money and the votes promised
with it. (Or stiffen the craven against the threat implied to those
who disdain it.)
</P>
<P>
   So, although the public overwhelmingly, though inchoately,
supports gun control and has for decades, the nation remains
hostage to the National Rifle Association's permanent hysteria _
any control is a step toward federal storm troopers kicking in your
door and snatching your guns! _ and hostage to the big money and
the power politics that support the hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the current stand-off. The House and Senate passed
mild-to-meaningless controls last year, but there were signal
differences over one feature that could really matter: provisions
to close a loophole that allows sales at gun shows without
background checks. The Senate version plugs the loophole. The House
version pretends to.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference is necessary to resolve the
differences, and the president recently called in leaders of both
chambers and urged action. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the key
player, said no.
</P>
<P>
   (The NRA remains bee-busy in the state legislatures, too. It was
instrumental just days ago in killing a bill in Georgia that would
have held adults liable for negligently leaving firearms where kids
could get to them easily.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, just like my wife, recently asked, ``How many more
people have to get killed before we do something?''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, when it is expected to, dutifully tsk-tsks over gun
victims, but in truth it doesn't really give a hoot about them. If
it did, it would be trying to prevent gun crime. Instead, its
response to every new gun outrage is only to call for putting
someone in prison, though that is self-evidently not a deterrent
and is cold comfort to the dead.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of fussing in the political atmosphere about
victims' rights. The most important right is the right to be given
a fair crack at not becoming a victim in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   On average, we're sacrificing 13 kids a day to keep the NRA
happy. It's political paganism.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 0934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV12-C     03-09 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: NOW YOU SEE HIM, NOW YOU CAN'T
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``A lot of people turned back,'' recalls trail
guide Jim Frush, who last August led Al Gore and his son, Albert
III, on a 16-mile trek to the snow-encrusted peak of Washington's
Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Frush shared his recollections in a 30-second TV spot that was
aired to promote Gore's bid for the White House. It featured
personal photos of Gore and his then 16-year-old son, loaded down
with heavy backpacks, as they scaled the 14,410-foot mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it _ safely,'' Frush says in the campaign ad.
``Strength of character, perseverance, grace under pressure. These
are qualities you look for in a mountaineer, or even better, in a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the climb, Gore had left town without, as is usual,
informing the press of his travel plans. Subsequently, the vice
president said he had sought privacy because this was a strictly
personal family trip aimed at bonding with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Some seven years before the Mount Rainier trip, Albert III also
served as a Gore campaign prop. That was at the 1992 Democratic
National Convention when, in an emotional speech, Gore listed the
life-threatening injuries that his 6-year-old son had suffered on
April 3, 1989, when he let go of his father's hand and darted in
front of a speeding car as they left the Baltimore Orioles' season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to his family life, Gore claims the right to pick
and choose what should be made public and what should stay private.
</P>
<P>
   Some seven years after his accident, young Gore, by then a
student at St. Albans School, was caught smoking an illicit
substance in a secluded part of the campus known as the Bishop's
Garden. As their punishment for breaking the school's honor code,
Gore and two of his 13-year-old classmates each were given two-week
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the school officials' response, Gore and his wife,
Tipper, abruptly cut their ties to St. Albans, from which Gore had
graduated and where he continued to work out after moving into the
nearby vice-presidential residence. Sidwell Friends, another
prestigious Washington prep school, where at the time President
Clinton's daughter, Chelsea, was enrolled as a senior, promptly
agreed to admit Albert III to the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Before that transfer took place, the vice president had called
several editors, urging them to respect his son's privacy. (A brief
account of the incident had run in a school newspaper, without
citing names. Another rule-breaker was the son of a prominent
journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   No other press accounts appeared, although the incident was
later raised obliquely in some stories as a counterpoint to the
widespread charge that the press had gone over the top in reporting
about Clinton's escapades with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the Gore privacy pendulum swung back again from
his publicized family outing on Mt. Rainier. In his Harlem debate
with Bill Bradley, Gore was asked why, while sending his children
to elite private schools, he opposed vouchers that would allow some
poor families do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the question, Gore replied: ``You know, you can leave
them out of this if you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 0943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
