<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Always having to say you're sorry
 &HT;    For release March 12, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're old enough, you likely will remember Billy Eckstine's
soulful rendition of ``I Apologize'' which begins, to paraphrase:
``If I told a lie, if I made you cry, from the bottom of my heart,
I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that song ought to be brought back as this appears to be
the Year of the Apology. Seemingly, everyone is apologizing for
something or being asked to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is expected to deliver a cluster of apologies today on
behalf of what are called sins of the Catholic Church over the
centuries. Expected among them are apologies regarding the
Holocaust, Crusades, Inquisition and religious wars against other
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of apologizing and I wonder who is around to feel
soothed about it _ other than the pope. Certainly not the Jews who
still lay great blame for the Holocaust at the indifferent feet of
Pope Pius XII. And certainly not Italy's gay community, which is
quite upset that gays are not included in the pope's index of
apologies and is demanding that he add it.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, legislators are calling for Gov. Parris Glendening
to apologize for the state's history of slavery. In North Carolina,
Duke University students want an apology from CBS basketball
analyst Billy Packer for sexist remarks. And in Florida, a
legislator has agreed to apologize to the full House of
Representatives for failing to show a child support debt on his
financial disclosure report.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the really big-time apologies:
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker, the baseball pitcher, apologized to practically
every one in the world who was not white Anglo-Saxon. Darryl
Strawberry apologized for snorting more cocaine. John McCain
apologized for terming his North Vietnamese captors and torturers
``gooks.'' (I wouldn't have but I wasn't running for president.)
George W. Bush somewhat apologized for speaking at Bob Jones
University. He really didn't apologize for being there, instead
said he was sorry for not speaking out while there about racial and
religious injustice at the racially and religiously unjust
university.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida tried to defend his brother's
appearance there, he likened speaking at Bob Jones University to
speaking at a synagogue. Sixteen legislators expressed rage and
demanded an apology from the governor. As of this writing, none is
forthcoming; perhaps the pope can include it in his congregate
apologies.
</P>
<P>
   There are more apologies floating around than there are dragon
flies.
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the New York Knicks basketball team last month
apologized to a Miami Heat player for tackling him in a playoff
brawl in 1998. And the lieutenant governor of Massachusetts has
apologized for using paid aides to babysit her newborn child.
</P>
<P>
   How far do we take these apologies, and does it really change
anything?
</P>
<P>
   Shall the Egyptians be made to apologize for enslaving the
Hebrews? Shall the descendants of David be made to apologize to
Goliath's kin; the oaf had kids, didn't he? Then there's that Jews,
Judas and Jesus thing.
</P>
<P>
   And something else that needs apologizing for: In two
dictionaries I researched (Oxford English and Webster's New World),
first definition for ``apology'' is to DEFEND an idea, religion,
philosophy; a vindication from accusation or aspersion. Second
meaning is reference to an acknowledgement of fault.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't enough to confuse people I don't know what is.
Therefore, even the lexicographers owe us an apology.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
