<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did you hear the one about the kid with the shaved head?
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ A friend of mine told me this story the
other day. An employee told him, and she heard it at the bank. All
three people believed it to be true, because that's how it was
related to them:
</P>
<P>
   A mother and her 5-year-old daughter were in a Lufkin store. I
won't say which one. The mother turned around, and the child had
disappeared. The mother wisely went to the front of the store and
told the manager, who promptly locked the doors. They began to
frantically search for the little girl. Finally they searched the
bathroom. They found the girl with her head shaved, wearing a
completely different set of clothes than she had originally worn.
Luckily, she was unharmed, except for the shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption was that someone was attempting to kidnap the
girl by changing her appearance and then planned to spirit her out
of the store.
</P>
<P>
   My friend wanted to know if we had reported this in the
newspaper. I said we would check into it, though I had a strong
suspicion about what had happened. Turned out I was right.
</P>
<P>
   The story is an urban legend. There is not a shred of truth to
it. A police department spokesman said this particular legend has
been floating around Lufkin for several months, with slight
variations. A colleague wisecracked that all that was missing from
this version was that besides a shaved head, the kid's kidney
should have been missing.
</P>
<P>
   This urban legend is especially gripping because it plays off
every parent's worst nightmare: losing a child. It does happen, of
course, though more often than not a angry ex-spouse is to blame.
And the fact that children, sadly, do disappear lends a slight
amount of credence to this story. Happily, this version is
completely bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Out of curiosity, I found a Web site (there are many) that
collects urban legends. It took me just a few seconds to find a
legend on that site that bears strong resemblance to the story
above:
</P>
<P>
   ``A small girl was abducted away from her parents at Disney
World. The distraught parents were taken to a surveillance room
filled with monitors to look for the child. Almost at the point of
giving up, the mother recognized the child's shoes when a strange
woman attempted to leave the park, child in hand. The reason the
shoes were all that were recognized is the child's hair had been
cut and dyed, and she'd been dressed as a little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The footnote below reads, ``No child has ever been abducted at
Disney World or Disneyland. Sometimes this one takes place in other
amusement parks, or even supermarkets.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another urban legend that passed our way a few weeks ago.
It's one I've encountered several times over the years. I received
a fax from a reader who said he had heard the Federal
Communications Commission was about to ban all religious
programming on television and radio. He was understandably upset
and wanted to alert the public so letters of protest could be sent
to the appropriate agencies and elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Versions of this also have made the rounds for years; this urban
legend seems to have come to life during the heyday of obnoxious
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair, who brought the lawsuit that
restricted organized prayer in schools.
</P>
<P>
   There is no truth to the story that the FCC wants to ban
religious programming: not then, not now. You can go to the FCC's
Web site and read statements from FCC officials assuring the public
that nothing of the sort is being contemplated. For one thing, it
would unquestionably be a violation of the Constitution to have
such a ban. Again, there's not a shred of truth to this legend, but
that doesn't stop it from popping up every few years. And it
doesn't stop the FCC from periodically being swamped with angry
letters from outraged citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, I went to the Web site, downloaded a stack of
material and sent it to the reader with a note explaining that this
is an urban legend and asking him to reconsider publishing the
letter. He thanked me and, one hopes, is no longer concerned with
this bogus issue.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that strange things don't happen. But when you
hear a bizarre story from someone who heard it from someone else,
whose third cousin swears her best friend's brother-in-law was an
eyewitness to this horrific or amazing event, be skeptical. And if
you have Internet access, you can search for ``urban legends'' and
often as not discover yet another version of the same grisly or
strange story that's making the rounds in your town.
</P>
<P>
   (To read more urban legends, go to
www.redrival.com/urbanlegends/)
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
