<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Past can be deceptive when gauging candidates
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The best indicator of future performance is past
performance, or so the human-resources gurus tell us. While that
may be true in most hiring situations, it ain't _ to quote Gershwin
_ necessarily so when it comes to picking a president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   For Exhibit A, I submit a fellow who was derisively called ``the
senator from Pendergast.'' In his day, Harry S. Truman was
dismissed as a bourbon-swilling, poker-playing lightweight bought
and paid for by the Pendergast machine in his native Missouri. He
was picked as a running mate to the ailing Franklin D. Roosevelt in
1944 and, of course, became president the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys,'' he told reporters immediately after FDR's death, ``if
you ever pray, pray for me now. I don't know whether you fellows
ever had a load of hay fall on you, but when they told me yesterday
what had happened, I felt like the moon, the stars and all the
planets had fallen on me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was thought to be easy pickings in the 1948 elections. Most
professional pols and the newspapers gave up the plain-spoken
Truman for dead in the face of Republican challenger Thomas E.
Dewey, who had built a name for himself busting organized crime in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that the professional pols and the newspapers were
just wrong, and Truman claimed four years in his own right.
Somewhere in there, the senator from Pendergast disappeared,
replaced by a president who tackled tough decisions and damned the
political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   There would be hell to pay, he was advised, for firing Gen.
Douglas MacArthur. The dismissal of the popular _ but insubordinate
_ general touched off calls for impeachment. There could be only
one commander in chief, and it was the elected head of government.
Truman knew what he had to do and did it.
</P>
<P>
   When Truman decided to integrate the armed forces, the joint
chiefs _ and most of the country _ winced. That decision was among
the first to crack the segregationist wall that had long divided
us.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B, I submit, is Lyndon B. Johnson. As the senior senator
from Texas and as Senate majority leader, LBJ was a conservative's
conservative who never met a special interest he didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have expected that a conservative senator from a
Southern state would have been at the forefront of transforming
American society? The War on Poverty, the Civil Rights bill and the
Voting Rights Act were willed into being by a president who used
his considerable powers of persuasion and mastery of the
legislative process to make things happen. And he knew all the
while that doing these things would cost Democrats their dominance
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   This master politician did it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like Truman, LBJ was not fully appreciated in his day. Like
Truman, he became president at a time of profound national grief,
following a more glamorous figure whose popularity was magnified by
his death.
</P>
<P>
   A re-examination of the Johnson presidency, spattered by
bloodshed in Vietnam, is now under way, and LBJ's stature should
rise by any objective measure.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit C is Richard M. Nixon. Who would have expected a
politician who built a career on Red-baiting would open the
diplomatic door to China? This is the same Red baiter who
negotiated detente with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have expected a conservative Republican to foster the
concept of affirmative action? Indeed, who would have expected a
conservative Republican to impose wage and price controls to cool
an inflationary economy? His was the first administration to
recognize the importance of ecological protection to create an
agency devoted to it. The Environmental Protection Agency was a
product of the Nixon presidency.
</P>
<P>
   During the Nixon presidency, the voting age was lowered to 18,
and the first steps to eliminating the draft were taken.
</P>
<P>
   No one could or should have expected those accomplishments to
issue from a Nixon presidency. The Watergate scandal will forever
stain Nixon's memory, but his behavior as president was at times
counterintuitive.
</P>
<P>
   We are nearing the end of the first round of choosing the next
president. Naturally, there is a lot of comparison of records and
the eternal search for their portent.
</P>
<P>
   While those are worthwhile examinations, they don't deliver the
whole story nor are they accurate predictions of what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Just witness the senator from Pendergast.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
