<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN10-COX     03-09 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party politics at the precincts
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In 1996, the delegates to the Republican State
Convention snubbed Texas Gov. George W. Bush and chose instead to
have State Republican Chairman Tom Pauken lead their delegation to
the Republican National Convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Only a quick gavel on Pauken's part prevented their excluding
U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison from the delegation because she's
against outlawing abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was Christian conservatives months earlier had packed
the precinct conventions that are the beginning step in delegate
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Many Texans may not know it, but most of the people who actually
run the Republican and Democratic parties are chosen through that
process, which begins this year after the polls close March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's troops have made no organized effort to re-take the party
levers from the religious conservatives. It's too big a task.
Besides, says party spokesman Robert Black, it's unnecessary. At
least since Susan Weddington replaced Pauken as chairman, the party
``is completely in Bush's corner,'' Black said. And Bush has cozied
up to religious conservatives in other states in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a brief primer on how the parties choose their officials
and delegates to the presidential nominating conventions:
</P>
<P>
   First, you choose which party's process to participate in by
voting in that party's primary. You can't participate unless you've
voted.
</P>
<P>
   After the polls close at 7 p.m., the precinct conventions begin,
usually at the polling place. Delegates are selected to the next
level convention _ county conventions for counties wholly within
one state senatorial district, and senatorial district conventions
for those that are not.
</P>
<P>
   The county and senatorial district conventions, on April 1, will
select delegates to the state conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The parties' state conventions are in June _ the Democrats on
June 9-10 in Fort Worth, and the Republicans on June 15-17 in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   At the state conventions, the parties select state chairs and
other officers, representatives to their national committees and a
male and female state committee member from each senatorial
district.
</P>
<P>
   They also write party platforms and pass resolutions on a
variety of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the presidential selection process that the parties
differ.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   Texas has 124 delegates and 124 alternates to the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia beginning in late July. Ninety
of each are divided equally among the state's 30 congressional
districts. They are allocated according to the results in the
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Within the congressional districts, if a candidate wins a
majority, he gets three delegates and alternates. If no one gets a
majority, and two candidates receive more than 20 percent, the
leader gets two of each, and the second-place finisher gets one.
The delegates are selected in state convention caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   There are 34 at-large delegates and alternates. If a candidate
wins a majority statewide March 14, he gets them all. If no one
gets a majority but two get more than 20 percent, the leader gets
two-thirds of the delegates and alternates, and the second-place
finisher gets one-third. In this case, the leader gets 23 and the
runner-up 11.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Texas has 231 delegates and 32 alternates to the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles in mid-August. The Democrats'
system is a complicated hybrid aimed at reflecting the popular vote
but also encouraging precinct participation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sign in at their precinct conventions according to
their presidential preference or as uncommitted. Delegates selected
there also sign in by presidential preference at the county or
senatorial district conventions, and again at the state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Of the total, 127 delegates and 21 alternates are allocated
among the state senatorial districts based on Democratic turnout
for president and governor in the last two elections. The actual
delegates are awarded based on the March 14 vote. They will be
chosen in senatorial district caucuses at the state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Of the remainder, the state convention will select 42 at-large
delegates and six alternates pledged to particular presidential
candidates. There also are 37 unpledged delegates, including the 15
Democratic National Committee members and Texas' 17 Democratic
congressmen, plus 25 pledged delegates and five alternates, who
will probably include some mayors and other Democratic bigwigs.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
