<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-COSMO-BOY10-COX     03-09 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMO-BOY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida teen confidently counsels 'CosmoGirls'
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Michael, we need to talk.
</P>
<P>
   About your stint as an advice columnist in this month's
CosmoGirl! magazine.
</P>
<P>
   About the pitfalls of writing for teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   About why guys would rather go on a date with Helen Gurley Brown
than talk about their relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may find this hard to believe,'' Michael Rodan, a Jupiter
18-year-old, writes on page 36 of CosmoGirl!, which calls itself
``the cool new magazine for teens,'' ``but most guys are pretty
straightforward _ so there's no need to look for hidden meaning
behind everything we say or do.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't stopped readers from logging onto www.cosmogirl.com
to tell Michael what for. ``You sucky suck suck,'' wrote one
teed-off teen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I got negative responses because I said, `You need
to leave guys alone.' They did a little male-bashing,'' he says.
``But about a third agreed that you need to have fun while you're
young and enjoy relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The Benjamin School senior also fielded some online offers of
dates, or at least gushy e-mails, ``but everyone at school knows
that I'm taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael met Alyssa, his girlfriend of eight months, last summer
at Northwestern University's National High School Institute, where
he was studying journalism. That's also where he made the contacts
that led to the CosmoGirl! gig. A magazine editor who talked to the
students in class later e-mailed all the guys asking if they'd like
to write for CosmoGirl!.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I'd never heard of CosmoGirl!,'' Michael says. (The
magazine has just begun its second year of publication.)
</P>
<P>
   But he was familiar with CosmoGirl!'s older, sassier sister,
Cosmopolitan. ``The name `Cosmo' is overwhelming. I thought, `Oh my
God, they want me to write for them?'''
</P>
<P>
   He submitted a few story ideas and some embarrassing moments for
the monthly ``Ouch!'' column (''humiliating stories that will make
your hair curl!'') that weren't mortifying enough for publication.
But the editors agreed that his ``We need to talk'' topic had legs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael writes: ``A guy who really cares will want to know if
there's anything he can do to make things better. Just pick things
that are truly important to you. And if there are so many problems
between you and your guy that you feel the need to keep having
these `discussions,' then maybe you should stop talking to him
altogether and find someone new.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was actually a tough one to tackle,'' says Michael. ``I
feel that I have beyond-novice experience with women. ... And it's
a teeny-bopper magazine, so I can write about this without getting
too deep.''
</P>
<P>
   He's learned one lesson about communicating with women, or at
least teen-age girls: Don't be so brutally honest.
</P>
<P>
   If he had the article to write again, ``I would definitely play
to what they want to hear a little bit more, instead of saying what
I truly felt,'' says Michael, who will attend Vanderbilt
University. ``Guys do want to talk about the relationship, not
every single day, but just to make sure everything's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   HE'S GOT LOWDOWN ON HANDLING 'HOTS'
</P>
<P>
   Now that 18-year-old Michael Rodan is a published advice
columnist, we thought we'd ask the CosmoGirl! writer for his
thoughts on these time-tested riddles of the teen-age heart.
</P>
<P>
   I have the hots for this guy in my math class. How can I tell if
he likes me?
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll hang around you more often. He'll start looking at you
in class. He'll definitely start cracking jokes with you.''
</P>
<P>
   And watch for the tell-tale emissary. ``He'll send a friend to
talk with you to see if you like him. He'll do one of those
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do I get the feeling that all my boyfriend ever thinks about
is sex?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because that's all he's thinking about. Just kidding!''
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to this: Many teen-age guys are more comfortable
with their bodies than their emotions, and would rather take action
than sit around talking about feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood hits him, and he has to do something,'' Michael says.
``Instead of playing out a romantic scene, it turns to sex.''
</P>
<P>
   I just got dumped by my guy. He says he wants to ``just be
friends.'' What would you advise?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooooohhf. All guys do that as a safety, even girls do it too,
to keep the waters clear so when you see each other in the hallway
or at the mall, you don't have that animosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three weeks to a month and a half, things will fade away.
It's kind of a buffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you truly want a friendship with your ex, you might as
well give it a try, Michael says. ``Some can do that, and some
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   I met this guy at a party last week. He took my number and said
he'd call, but I still haven't heard from him. Why do guys say
they'll call and then they don't?
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys typically say that because girls want to hear that type
of commitment. But guys can become easily sidetracked. We'll
finally find (the number) under a pile of clothes two weeks later,
and we'll be too embarrassed to call back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
