<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-NEWYORKER10-COX     03-09 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEWYORKER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former employee turns out agreeable book about his New Yorker
days
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Tina Brown became editor of the New
Yorker in the summer of 1992, one of her first hires was Alexander
Chancellor. His stated mission was to edit the Talk of the Town
section, the short ``casuals'' in the front of the book whose
desired effect Brendan Gill once likened to a cloud of blue
butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor was an old Fleet Street cohort of Brown's. He agreed
to a one-year contract and told Brown he wanted to write a book
about his experiences in America. She was agreeable, as is the
resulting book.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, in common with many of his countrymen, likes America
but seems rather frightened of it, as if at any moment the Indians
will sweep over the settlement walls and start scalping.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of those urbane, vaguely Tory, seen-it-all Brits who
doesn't get riled about anything; a raised eyebrow constitutes a
shattering comment.
</P>
<P>
   The eyebrow gets a workout, because Chancellor had a rocky
trial. Part of the problem was that he had rarely read the New
Yorker, so didn't have a real sense of its peculiar rhythms. He
gives the distinct impression that Brown was as glad as he that he
chose to go back home after his year.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor doesn't come right out and say that so-and-so is a
dreadfully overrated hack. Instead, he lists their vitae in a way
calculated to render them absurd, as in, ``Ms. Angelou was black.
She had been raped by her mother's boyfriend when she was eight
years old and struck dumb for five years as a result. After giving
birth to a son at sixteen, she had started out on a varied career
as a nightclub singer, dancer, actress and writer. She had
published several volumes of autobiography and several of verse ...
If these were not qualifications enough to be chosen as the
presidential troubador, there was the clinching fact that Maya
Angelou had spent much of her childhood in the care of her
grandmother in the town of Stamps in Arkansas, Bill Clinton's home
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Condescension has its limited uses, but it bespeaks an
unwillingness to really engage with the people or literary material
at hand. Still, Chancellor has a knack for the journalistic quick
cut: William F. Buckley's house in the East 70s ``was furnished
with all the heavy opulence of an Edwardian brothel.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has a very interesting take on Brendan Gill, the longtime
New Yorker writer who, despite his personal joie de vivre, tended
to subtly cut everybody down to his own size when writing about
them, even if they were actually much bigger than he.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor's take on Tina Brown is not at all condemnatory and
rather affectionate. A bit of a diva, but also vulnerable, Brown
never felt secure in her job, always worried that Si Newhouse would
bounce her.
</P>
<P>
   Compulsive, forever in search of the hot, new thing _ a trait
that deformed the magazine _ abhorring anything she termed ``wet,''
Brown regularly tore up the Talk of the Town just before presstime,
leaving a desperate Chancellor scrambling for substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor hated this weekly emotional hazing but didn't say
anything about it. That was left to Hendrik Hertzberg, who told
Chancellor that Brown had given him responsibility without
authority and that he was going to speak to her about it.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Brown announced that she had given him
responsibility without authority and would stop it forthwith. ``She
was, in other words, insensitive, but not at all uncaring.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor noticed that Brown didn't really seem to like America
at all, leading a friend to say, of course not, she'd never been
there, i.e. anyplace outside a limousine in New York or Los Angeles
_ a point well taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Times in America'' is entertaining, and, I think,
accurate, especially about the sundry differences between American
and English journalists: ``She liked to turn them into celebrities
and feed their vanities with extravagant compliments and bouquets
of flowers. At the same time she would grumble privately about
their big-headedness and dwell upon the virtues of the flexible
British journalist who would quickly and competently turn his hand
to anything in return for no more than a modest fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``British journalists are not permitted to give themselves airs.
They are too numerous, too dispensable, and too despised ...
American journalists, are, on the whole more diligent,
conscientious and high-minded, as befits their exalted concept of
their constitutional role, but they consequently lack the cheerful
solidarity and subversive urges of their colleagues across the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book is in the self-deprecating manner of one of
Alistair Cooke's ``Letters from America,'' but Chancellor's voice
lacks Cooke's urbanity; he's unpretentious and ``matey'' but
doesn't have the authoritative tone that might have made for a
stronger book.
</P>
<P>
   Odd that Chancellor finally got the proper tone for that cloud
of blue butterflies, not in Talk of the Town but in a book that
amounts to a confession of his failure in putting out Talk of the
Town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some times in America: And a Life in a Year at the New
Yorker,'' by Alexander Chancellor; Carroll &AMP; Graf; 309 pages; $25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
