<HEADER>
A1570 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-REFLECTIONS10-C     03-09 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REFLECTIONS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rich prose style, good intentions, but a drab memoir
 &HT;    By Noah Bierman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mary Gordon has created the print
version of a well-crafted still-life painting _ rich in detail,
clever in structure, keen in some of its insights.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it's still like staring at a bowl of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed author and professor's life is too boring to
justify a memoir. Even she was bored through much of her childhood,
and observations to that effect take up much of the book.
</P>
<P>
   To tie something as random as the human experience into a
narrative, Gordon uses geography and sense of place as her central
theme. Hence the title, ``Seeing Through Places: Reflections on
Geography and Identity.''
</P>
<P>
   The device is especially relevant here; she lived many years in
her grandmother's unwelcoming home, rarely feeling like more than a
guest. Self-doubt, fused with a strong sense of Catholic guilt,
seems impossible to overcome. And becoming a woman, creating an
authorial voice, becomes Gordon's eventual triumph, though she
retains the guilt and self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   That voice is the book's strongest quality. Gordon's declarative
sentences flow candidly as she describes her mother's alcoholism,
her father's lack of career and her extended family's tendency to
squabble. Few adults show her any warmth or acknowledge her
emotional needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My weekends were devoted to helping clean the house. There was
no joy in it; it was a grim battle against dirt and disorder,'' she
writes. ``No modern products were employed. Ammonia burnt my eyes
and hands, Bon Ami cleanser, shaken from the gold can with the
chicken only half out of its egg, got under my nails.''
</P>
<P>
   The detail helps re-create the scene in full sensual stereo,
even if it's only elevator music.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon takes these detailed youthful observations, then dissects
them with adult wisdom. When her grandmother collapses, it's the
neighbor who brings her to the hospital. ``Everyone pretended to be
grateful to her, but it was a family that made no real place _
though they were capable of simulating a false one, or perhaps an
anteroom, a vestibule _ for strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Honest moments such as these show Gordon's best and worst. In
concept, the idea of a memoir by a thoughtful, relatively ordinary
person makes sense _ consider all the lame material from jurors and
dietitians to the stars or the self-important, uncritical histories
of famous men.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the good intentions just do not command enough
interest. The mother-daughter relationships, the observations of
the priests who would often visit Gordon and the worry over whether
she deserves a house in Cape Cod don't stimulate. And they aren't
particularly revealing of anything global.
</P>
<P>
   I'm leaving the door open to the possibility that Gordon's
fellow middle-aged, Catholic, New York intellectuals identify with
her and will find this book particularly revealing or interesting.
</P>
<P>
   I'm holding out that possibility, but I'm not rereading the
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing through places: Reflections on Geography and
Identity,'' by Mary Gordon; Scribner; 254 pages; $23.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
