<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1571 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-MARTIN-OLINGER10-     03-09 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MARTIN-OLINGER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cart Wars still at the forefront on PGA Tour
 &HT;    By Alan Tays
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL SPRINGS, Fla. _ Two golfers. Two disabilities. Two courts.
Two rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all together, and it comes out to one puzzling scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin walked into the interview room at the Tournament
Players Club at Heron Bay on Wednesday and said he was ``looking
forward to now just playing golf and hopefully letting this
gradually die down.'' It was his first public comment since the 9th
U.S. Circuit Court in San Francisco on Monday refused to overturn a
lower court's decision allowing him to use a golf cart on the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, meanwhile, club pro Ford Olinger lost his appeal to
use a cart in local qualifying for the U.S. Open. The 7th U.S.
Circuit Court upheld a lower court's ruling that allowing Olinger
to use a cart would change the nature of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a circulatory disorder in his right leg. Olinger has
a degenerative hip disorder. Both sued in 1998 for the right to use
a golf cart in competition, a practice ordinarily banned by both
the PGA Tour and the United States Golf Association, which runs the
U.S. Open. Each cited the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) in
support of his case.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Martin can continue to play the PGA Tour, including
this week's Honda Classic. But if Olinger wants to try to qualify
for this year's Open, he'll have to walk, as he did in 1999, when
he shot an 88 and failed to advance to sectional qualifying. He
rode a cart in 1998 Open qualifying after obtaining a temporary
restraining order against the USGA, but shot an 83 and failed to
advance. After Martin won his initial court victory in 1998, the
USGA allowed him to ride a cart in Open qualifying that year and
the next, saying it would honor the court ruling even though it
applied specifically only to the PGA Tour. Martin says he will try
to qualify for the Open again this year and hopes to be able to
ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they won't challenge it,'' Martin said. ``(But) I bet
they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the USGA fight Olinger in court, yet allow Martin to
ride?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a great question,'' Martin said. Olinger could not be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   In Far Hills, N.J., the USGA declined comment until it has had
time to review the Olinger ruling. The PGA Tour similarly declined
to comment on the Martin case until after next week's meeting of
its Policy Board in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he was driving to a speaking engagement Monday
afternoon when he heard the news. He had just completed his flight
from Eugene, Ore., to Orlando. Few people had the number of his
tour-issued cell phone, so he was surprised when he had several
messages. One was from his father, telling him he had won the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said fellow players have been mostly supportive, as have
fans. ``I haven't heard one thing negative from the gallery,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has played in five events this year, making three cuts
and earning $51,015, almost $38,000 of it from his best finish, a
tie for 17th at Tucson. His year has been an adventure so far. In
the Bob Hope tournament, he was paired with Tour Policy Board
chairman Dick Ferris, who while testifying against Martin in 1998
made the infamous declaration that carts are allowed on the Senior
Tour because it is more about nostalgia than competition. In Los
Angeles, he accidentally stepped in a sprinkler hole. ``It was
absolutely the worst day of my life physically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to play about 25 events this year, a number he should
have no trouble achieving because as an exempt tour member, he is
eligible to accept an unlimited number of sponsor's exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take exemptions two years ago when I first got this
(court victory) because I hadn't made it out here yet,'' he said.
``I didn't want to take advantage of the situation. Now that I have
made it, I've felt free to take exemptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin typically drives his cart from tee to green. ``A lot of
times there will be a guy going around with me and I will park it
somewhere near the green and then he takes it around the back to
the next tee box or wherever is appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the deterioration in his right tibia has slowed
since he has been allowed to ride. ``I got some X-rays a couple of
months ago and it hasn't deteriorated any more than it was a couple
of years ago,'' he said. ``Probably because I am riding.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the PGA Tour declined comment, its former general
counsel characterized the Olinger and Martin rulings this way:
``One (Olinger) is well reasoned, the other (Martin) is not,'' said
attorney Gary Crist of Jupiter. ``On the one hand, you have
activist judges interpreting the statute as saying there should be
some form of social engineering. On the other, you have
conservative judges, strict constructionists, if you will,
believing that the governance of golf should be left to the
governing bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step _ if there is one _ in both cases is for the
losing side to appeal to the Supreme Court. There is no guarantee
the court would agree to hear such an appeal, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Olinger appeals his case,'' Crist said, ``that could remove
from the PGA Tour the obligation to appeal the Martin case.'' A
Supreme Court ruling in one case, however, would not be binding in
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Martin believes the tour will appeal to the Supreme Court.
Understandably, he hopes the court refuses to hear an appeal.
``Honestly,'' he said, ``driving a cart in golf _ surely there are
more important things that they would hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
