<SLUG> BC-ANNEFRANK-FRIEND10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Childhood friend of Anne Frank shares memories
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Writing in her diary as she hid in the
attic of her Amsterdam home, Anne Frank lamented that Hannah Pick,
her good friend and neighbor, was no doubt already dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna always wanted to be very, very famous,'' Hannah
Pick-Goslar recalled Wednesday night for about 100 students and
parents at the Meyer Jewish Academy in suburban West Palm Beach.
She lives in Israel and is visiting the area as a guest of the
Anti-Defamation League of the Palm Beach region.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a folding chair, sipping from a cup of water and
speaking in a gentle, matter-of-fact voice, Pick-Goslar, 73,
recalled Anne Frank and her own Holocaust experience.
</P>
<P>
   She told of how they met in a grocery store, shortly after the
Pick family arrived in Holland from England, and of how they did
their homework together on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   After the Nazis invaded Holland, Anne and her family
disappeared, and Pick-Goslar was told they had fled to Switzerland.
Only when she herself was a prisoner in the Bergen-Belsen camp did
Pick-Goslar learn the Franks had been in hiding, the Swiss story
only a lie to divert the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   She and Anne called to each other across a camp fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am nobody anymore,'' she remembered Anne saying to her in
the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was not the same Anne I had known,'' she said. ``It was
a broken little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, 1945, Pick-Goslar was freed. By then, her friend
had died of typhus, but the diary survived to make Anne Frank the
most famous of the Holocaust's millions of victims.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
