   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EXILE _ Review of James Alan McPherson's essays ``A Region
Not Home: Reflections From Exile.'' (Boyd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, March 12.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Serious novelists like to say that fiction is a
moral concern, and perhaps it is. But right and wrong exist on one
plane, and good and evil on another. It is easier to take measure
of the forgivable than of the ineradicable. Evil, if you believe it
exists, is somehow beyond human reach and yet it is all around us,
resistant to all purgatives. For Graham Greene, it was in the
nature of things that there be no grace without evil, the renewal
of the one reinforcing the presence of the other. Try as we might,
we can never rid ourselves of ourselves. Those who have seen the
artistically exquisite movie version of Greene's novel ``The End of
the Affair'' understand this better than they could have before _
understand, in particular, how deeply he penetrated the psychology
of desire and obligation, betrayal and guilt. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, March 12.
</P>
