<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PEN-AWARDS10-COX     03-09 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEN-AWARDS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEN awards are mightier (and more numerous)
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The PEN American Awards have announced
two new major literary awards. The PEN/Nabokov Award for $20,000
will honor writers of ``enduring originality and consummate
craftsmanship.'' In other words, James Patterson need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   The PEN/Architectural Digest Award for $10,000 will be for
Literary Writing on the Visual Arts. Both awards will be announced
in April and will join the 16 awards administered by the PEN
American Center for excellence in writing and letters.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR SCORE AND SEVEN YEARS AGO ...
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln is undoubtedly the most venerated American
president, and Frank Thompson adds yet another volume to the
lengthy bibliography. ``Abraham Lincoln: Twentieth Century Popular
Portrayals'' (Taylor, $26.95) surveys Lincoln as reflected through
the acting prism of Henry Fonda, Raymond Massey, Walter Huston and
Sam Waterston, among others. Thompson covers not only film and
television but also theater. All in all, bountifully researched and
well-written, with a filmography that extends to 100 pages and many
fascinating stills.
</P>
<P>
   REST IN PEACE ...
</P>
<P>
   Norton has published ``Saving Grace,'' a collection of
photographs of female sculptures found in cemeteries (and people
think modern publishing is too monolithic ...).
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson's black-and-white photos are nice, but the forms
depicted are often truly beautiful, if bereft grieving is your
thing. All the sculptures are to be found in European cemeteries
such as Pere Lachaise in Paris, Highgate in London and Monumentale
in Milan. Joyce Carol Oates contributes a typically lofty
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS CREEK ...
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida Press has had a tidy little success
with its excellent ``Max &AMP; Marjorie,'' a collection of the letters
between Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings and Max Perkins, her editor at
Scribner's.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher solicited blurbs from people such as Michael Korda
and had the book chosen for special attention by Barnes &AMP; Noble.
Its 4,000-copy first printing was quickly exhausted and the second
printing is now in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting statistic: University presses publish 17 percent
of all books printed in the U.S. but account for under 2 percent of
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of brilliant segues, Barnesandnoble.com has announced
it will no longer sell ``Mein Kampf'' to customers in Germany,
where Nazi literature is against the law. Amazon has also stopped
selling the book to German customers.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of Barnes &AMP; Noble is owned by the German firm
Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle of procrastinated rape is said to be the ruling
one in all the great bestsellers.'' _V.S. Pritchett
</P>
