   MOVIES-MARS _ Review of Mission to Mars. (Erstein, Palm Beach
Post). 14. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-MARS _ Give it up, Hollywood: Mars is dead. No canals.
No mysterious face. No life of any kind. Nope, not even one
</P>
<P>
   stinking bacterium. Nothing but red, dead, rusty dust. But when
did the facts ever get in a movie's way? Mission to Mars, which
opens today, features not just Martian life, but super-intelligent
Martian life that supposedly started life on Earth. The movie is
set in 2020. Humanity has launched its first manned mission to the
Red Planet. But yikes! When they get there, three of four crew
members are wiped out by a huge whirlwind worm. In comes the rescue
team, who wastes no time getting itself in big trouble. Good thing,
for while saving themselves they uncork the secret of life, and
then, of course, live happily ever after. (Alicea, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EXILE _ Review of James Alan McPherson's essays ``A Region
Not Home: Reflections From Exile.'' (Boyd, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, March 12.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Serious novelists like to say that fiction is a
moral concern, and perhaps it is. But right and wrong exist on one
plane, and good and evil on another. It is easier to take measure
of the forgivable than of the ineradicable. Evil, if you believe it
exists, is somehow beyond human reach and yet it is all around us,
resistant to all purgatives. For Graham Greene, it was in the
nature of things that there be no grace without evil, the renewal
of the one reinforcing the presence of the other. Try as we might,
we can never rid ourselves of ourselves. Those who have seen the
artistically exquisite movie version of Greene's novel ``The End of
the Affair'' understand this better than they could have before _
understand, in particular, how deeply he penetrated the psychology
of desire and obligation, betrayal and guilt. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, March 12.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundup of the latest children's books. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Four American writers have made the shortlist of 7
finalists for the $130,000 IMPAC Dublin Award, the richest literary
prize in the world. U.S. finalists are Toni Morrison, Philip Roth,
Michael Cunningham and Alice McDermott. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NEWYORKER _ Review of the book ``Some Times in America:
And a Life in Year at the New Yorker,'' by Alexander Chancellor. He
was one of those urbane, seen-it-all Brits hired by the new kid at
the New Yorker, a compulsive, insecure diva. The year they spent
together wasn't pretty. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post). 25. WITH PHOTOS
(mugs and book jacket) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PEN-AWARDS _ The PEN American Awards have announced two new
major literary awards. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post). 14. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is the weekly books column by Scott Eyman.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REFLECTIONS _ Review of ``Seeing Through Places:
Reflections on Geography and Identity,'' by Mary Gordon. Mary
Gordon has created the print version of a well-crafted still-life
painting _ rich in detail, clever in structure, keen in some of its
insights. But in the end, it's still lilke staring at a bowl of
fruit. (Bierman, Palm Beach Post). 16. MOVED
</P>
