<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-RE     03-09 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CREDIBILITY GAP IN THE DIGITAL DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest buzzphrase circulating among politicians and computer
industry executives these days is the digital divide, the gulf
between those who have access to computers and the Internet and
those who do not. Poor people and minorities, or so the thinking
goes, are in danger of being shut out of what promises to be the
most important mode of gathering and exchanging information, and
what is emerging as a common way of making and spending lots of
money.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, there is a growing recognition among those
dealing most closely with the issue that the term digital divide,
while clever and provocative, has become a catchall phrase for
politicians with conspicuous agendas and that the divide is a
complex phenomenon that no amount of measurement can fully explain.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, it seems that the nation is actually facing a
multitude of digital divides, not one limited to race or income or
education. While it is true that millions of people are still
without access to computers or the Internet, those who are counted
as connected fall along a spectrum: Some are dialing into the
Internet through antiquated rural phone lines that cannot handle
high data speeds, while others use ultra high-speed connections
from both work and home. Millions of others are getting their
connection only occasionally from public libraries, classrooms or
community centers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was a busy time for those in the digital
bridge-building business. First, Vice President Al Gore visited a
San Francisco nonprofit group to deliver a speech on the divide.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, the Rev. Jesse Jackson opened a branch of his
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition in Silicon Valley, with the goal of closing
the divide among the poor. The same day, Jackson delivered a speech
at the University of California at Berkeley in which he pronounced
access to technology ``the newest stage of the civil rights
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, results of a survey conducted by National Public
Radio, the Kaiser Family Foundation and Harvard University's
Kennedy School of Government corroborated earlier studies that
found that at higher income levels there is virtually no racial
gap. More good news: Of those who bought computers in the last two
years, about one-third are from low-income or minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the survey found a persistent racial divide among
low-income households when it comes to computer ownership and
Internet access at home.
</P>
<P>
   Such findings may not spell out the problem as much as help
reveal its thorniness. It helps to start by looking at the ways in
which people connect to the Internet. Plenty of people have
connections at work, but some of them are not wired at home. In
addition, connecting to the Internet from work, a library or school
is quite different from connecting from the privacy of one's living
room. Experts say that the only way to fully appreciate the Web is
to experience it and that the most useful experience, unfettered by
the constraints of an institutional setting, comes with using the
Internet from home.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a high-speed cable modem connection gives a
Web surfer a far different view of cyberspace _ one that's
lightning quick and rich with sound and motion _ than that seen via
a slower link from a traditional modem.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, much of the digital bridge-building has focused on
schools. At first blush, the gap there doesn't seem especially
alarming. According to Market Data Retrieval, a company that has
surveyed the nation's public schools, 94 percent of schools in
wealthy districts have access to the Internet, compared with 84
percent of schools that serve poor populations.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures are deceptive. ``Those numbers fail to address
the nature of those connections,'' David Gollaher, chief executive
of the California Healthcare Institute, a nonprofit group in La
Jolla, Calif., told a group of health care experts who gathered
last week at Berkeley to discuss the digital divide and e-health
(industry shorthand for the delivery of health information and
services on the Internet).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the poorer schools, Gollaher said, connect to the
Internet using a relatively slow 56 kilobit-per-second connection,
which may be fine for sending e-mail but prevents a large
population of potential users from experiencing the full scope and
power of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gollaher later said it was not until he got a high-speed
connection at his home that his own children grew interested in the
Web. ``They download a lot of music, and they listen to radio
stations online,'' he said. ``Many of the uses they prefer are uses
that depend on high-speed connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts have claimed in recent weeks that the digital
divide is actually a myth, that income at all levels might play a
greater role than race in disparities between the digital haves and
have-nots, though the two are often connected.
</P>
<P>
   The NPR survey disproved that claim with a finding that among
households of all income levels, 57 percent of whites under the age
of 60 have Internet or e-mail access from home, compared with 38
percent of blacks. In households where income is less than $30,000
a year, the study found, 34 percent of whites have access from
home, compared with 19 percent of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   That divide narrows drastically when online access takes place
outside the home, especially in the workplace. ``The gap largely
disappears everywhere except at home,'' said Molly Brodie, a vice
president at the Kaiser Family Foundation, who oversaw the NPR
survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you start to look a little deeper, you see that the
biggest problem is at home,'' said Donna L. Hoffman, a professor of
management at Vanderbilt University and the co-author of a 1998
study with results similar to those in the NPR survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can understand what it can do for you
unless you use it,'' she said of the Internet. ``You have to try
it, then you can see the meaning it can have in your own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecting to the Internet from outside the home makes having
such an experience more difficult, she said. ``I just think it's
very hard to do that when you have a 30-minute limit, or when you
have to wait in line, or with others around.''
</P>
<P>
   David Greenbaum, a researcher at Berkeley who works with
community groups in Oakland to address the digital divide, suspects
that the problem of access from home might be one of cause and
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``One premise that underlies all of this is that if someone had
the right kind of access at home, they'd be much more involved in
the whole wired and online world,'' Greenbaum said. ``But if they
already had the impulse and interest to be part of that world, then
they'd have the kind of motivation to have a machine at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the NPR survey found no significant difference
between whites and blacks at low-income levels when it came to
owning other home electronics, like cable television and VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum said that at a recent digital divide conference in
Oakland, a number of people asked: ``Why is it people are willing
to spend $500 on a big wide-screen TV? How can we instill that same
kind of economic pull to a desire to being online?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-06-00 0958EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
