<HEADLINE>
CMGI'S LATEST CATCH: A WEB SITE TO LAND FISH BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BETH HEALY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Check out the latest catch in CMGI Inc.'s net: GoFish.com, an
online seafood marketplace, where a fisherman in Thailand can sell
shrimp to an American grocer.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI is making a $12 million venture capital investment in the
year-old company, which is Maine's leading Web business and a
frontrunner in the move toward Web-based seafood sales. CMGI is
based in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The deal wraps up GoFish's second round of financing and gives
it a big headstart over rivals, with a total of $41 million in
venture backing since August.
</P>
<P>
   For CMGI (at)Ventures, this is a pure B2B play, and the money's
coming from the firm's new $1 billion business-to-business fund.
CMGI partner Marc Poirier points out that the wholesale seafood
market is $80 billion strong in the United States and Europe alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an industry that's well-suited to the Internet,'' Poirier
says. ``It's information-sensitive and it's time-sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI expects no less than for GoFish to be the number one online
seafood market for wholesalers. Their advantage, he says, is their
management and history as a credit-rating service to the seafood
business. Chief executive Neal Workman has been in that arena since
1985, when he founded a collection agency for New England
lobstermen. Last year, he decided to turn his SeaFax Inc. into a
Web business, and to expand from credit checks to handling the
actual buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   The company's focus is at the high-price end of the seafood
business. That means crab, shrimp, live lobsters, salmon, and
scallops. The site brings fisherman from Thailand to Equador to the
table with importers and exporters, supermarket chains like
Hannaford Brothers and Stop &AMP; Shop, and large restaurant groups.
</P>
<P>
   GoFish provides real-time prices on seafood. It also offers
credit checks and a collection service to guarantee that sellers
get paid. Since going live in November, $2 million worth of sales
have been conducted on the site. Daily visits to the site exceed
1,300.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to grow those numbers quickly, as it adds
auctions and receivables financing (courtesy of investor GE
Capital) by summer. The draw for users, GoFish says, is to save
money and time.
</P>
<P>
   Explains David Weatherbie, chief operating officer at GoFish:
``Seafood is sourced all over the world, and it can change hands
four to six times before reaching the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``On our site, you can have access to key market
information on pricing and supplies _ information you need to make
important business decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   As with all good ideas on the Web, one is never alone. Nipping
at GoFish's heels are sites like fishmonger.com and
GlobalFoodExchange.com. The latter just hooked $12.2 million in
seed financing, led by Charles River Ventures in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Every VC figures he or she has found the best of the players in
a given field. Charles River partner Jonathan Guerster says they
liked GlobalFood Exchange because ``we'd rather back the bigger
category.'' He thinks GoFish may be too narrow a business model.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's Poirier stands behind the GoFish pick: ``I think they're
far ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   They and hundreds of other seafood-related companies will get to
strut their stuff this week at the International Boston Seafood
Show. The world's biggest gathering of fish industry folks will be
at the Hynes Veterans Memorial Convention Center from Tuesday
through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   IPO watch
</P>
<P>
   Here are some initial public offerings scheduled for this week:
</P>
<P>
   Crayfish Co. Ltd., Tokyo, 4.35m American depositary shares,
priced $22-$24, business services and software; FirstWorld
Communications Inc., Greenwood Village, Colo., 10m shares, priced
$11-$13, communications; GT Group Telecom Inc., Toronto, 16m
shares, priced $10-$12, communications; HomeGrocer.com Inc.,
Kirkland, Wash., 22m shares, priced $10-$12, retail trade.
</P>
<P>
   ImageWare Systems Inc., San Diego, 1.5m units, priced $8-$10,
business services and software; IPrint.com Inc., Redwood City,
Calif., 4.5m shares, priced $8-$10, printing and publishing;
Net2000 Communications Inc., Herndon, Va., 10m shares, priced
$13-$15, communications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
