<HEADLINE>
REVENGE OF THE RETAIL GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upstarts at Amazon.com, the Web's biggest retailer, still
can't resist taking jabs at the online efforts of the nation's
biggest retail chains.
</P>
<P>
   And who can blame them? During the past two Christmas shopping
seasons, traditional merchants have bumbled online, irritating
consumers with frequent site crashes, delivery problems, and Web
stores as cluttered as suburban yard sales.
</P>
<P>
   But this may be the year the laughs end. There are signs the
brick-and-mortar retailing giants have begun to figure out the Web
and are ready to give their online-only rivals a cyberspace
spanking.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional retailers have ``smelled the coffee,'' said Seema
Williams, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The recent online successes of Gap Inc., outdoors-goods retailer
REI, and even Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. are starting to get noticed in
the electronic marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Although virtual businesses still top the charts in many
categories, old-line merchants such as Victoria's Secret, Office
Depot Inc., and Best Buy Co. Inc. posted large visitor growth rates
at their Internet stores in December, according to a survey by
Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Even some traditional retailers that have had online problems in
the past can no longer be ignored. With powerful brands, they drew
large crowds of online shoppers last year. And they didn't have to
spend millions on advertising to get consumers to recognize their
names.
</P>
<P>
   It may be mammoth Wal-Mart Stores Inc., until recently a
sleeping presence online, that poses the biggest threat to
Internet-only retailers, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see the big discounters and mass
merchandisers come online,'' said Todd Canfield, an analyst with
Gomez Advisors. ``I would be concerned if someone like Amazon was
not worried. And the smaller players and those behind the curve
should be more worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some stumbles, many old-line retailers showed surprising
strength during the 1999 holiday season, said Mike May, an analyst
with the Internet research firm Jupiter Communications. ``They
emerged online, and in some cases, surpassed industry watchers'
expectations,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is not yet stiff enough to still the sniping of
the online leaders, however. In a video appearance at a Harvard
Business School conference last month, Jeff Bezos, the cherubic
founder of Web giant Amazon.com Inc., said rival Barnes &AMP; Noble had
a better chance of building a chain of hardware stores in the past
than a thriving Internet bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that ``both sell books, so they must be similar''
does not fly in the new economy, Bezos maintained.
</P>
<P>
   For years, executives at many of the nation's largest retail
chains have boasted that they could easily make the transition to
the Web. They argued that strong brands, large customer bases,
marketing experience, and existing supplier relationships gave them
an edge over Internet-only firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can catch up very quickly,'' said Terry Burman,
chief executive of Sterling Jewelers Inc., which plans to create an
e-commerce site some time in the future. ``I don't think the
learning curve is very steep.''
</P>
<P>
   The virtual retailers don't buy it. They contend the lumbering
old-line merchants failed to grasp electronic commerce from the
start. As recently as two years ago, some big retailers were still
pooh-poohing the idea of selling on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce evolved much quicker than anticipated. And in
categories like computers, books, and music, online sales picked up
so fast that traditional retailers were forced to speed up their
e-commerce efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even migrating to the Web have been items that were never
thought to be easy sells online because of their bulkiness,
expense, and touch-and-feel requirements. Shoppers can now purchase
refrigerators from Sears.com, Anne Klein dresses from
Neimanmarcus.com, and sleigh beds from furniture.com.
</P>
<P>
   By 2004, Forrester predicts that online retail sales will
skyrocket to $184 billion, or 7 percent of all US retail sales,
from only $20 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional retailers want a big chunk of those online sales.
And some have already become the leaders in their categories.
</P>
<P>
   Superstore operator PetSmart Inc., for one, had online revenue
of $7.8 million the fourth quarter of last year. Rival pets.com, a
virtual retailer backed by Amazon.com, had sales of $5.2 million in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales figures are incomplete or unavailable, some
analysts rate traditional retailers Best Buy Co. Inc. and Circuit
City Stores Inc. as the top consumer electronics sellers on the
Web. Amazon.com probably ranks third in the category.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap and a host of catalog companies lead the apparel market
online. Although the Gap does not release its online sales figures,
Canfield, the Gomez Advisors analyst, believes its aggressive
tactics will soon make it the dominant Internet clothing retailer.
Competitors include Lands' End Inc., Spiegel Inc., L.L. Bean Inc.,
and J. Crew Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As latecomers to the Web, most traditional retailers still lag
behind their Internet-only rivals in performance. Their online
stores are clunkier _ and many don't offer features such as Web
pages personalized to an individual consumer's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual retailers continue to make advances. For example,
parents who shop at SmarterKids.com Inc., a Needham, Mass. online
education store, can type in information about their children _ and
out pops a list of games or toys tailored to their kids' needs and
learning styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not worried'' about traditional toy retailers, said
Albert Noyes, executive vice president of SmarterKids.com. ``Let's
assume they do catch up, and I'm confident they will. But it will
be 2001 or so before they get around to the educational (market).''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the most basic level, old-line merchants have discovered
the transition to cyberspace can be wrenching. Some manufacturers
have fought to keep their products offline or have tried to claim
the Web as their own selling space. Store employees finger the
Internet as an enemy that will siphon away their sales commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they can just quickly become an Internet
presence,'' said Scott Segal, chief executive of ijewelry.com, an
Internet-only jewelry retailer. ``It's really a sense of arrogance.
It's because they don't know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual retailers acknowledge their old-line rivals may have
more experience in distributing merchandise to their stores. But
that does not necessarily translate into the know-how to pack and
ship orders, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions are catalog retailers such as Eddie Bauer and
L.L. Bean. Because they have the fulfillment side of the business
down to a science, they are adapting quickly to the Web and have
scored high ratings from online shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge for traditional merchants has been the high
market values placed on Internet-only retailers, which keeps them
flush with cash. Investors recently have cast more critical looks
at unprofitable virtual merchants _ but not Amazon.com, which still
has nearly 10 times the market value of Barnes &AMP; Noble's bn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bn.com executives say they plan to be profitable in the last
quarter of 2001, while some analysts estimate that Amazon.com will
make a profit in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that they (Amazon.com) have actually given a
date,'' sniffed Steve Riggio, vice chairman and acting chief
executive of bn.com, a joint venture between the nation's biggest
bookseller and publisher Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike bn.com, Amazon.com has expanded beyond books and compact
discs into a hybrid Wal-Mart of the Web. In three years, it has
become an auction site, a toy seller, an electronics retailer, and
a landlord for other online businesses. Eventually, Amazon.com's
Bezos _ who started with books _ says he wants to sell everything
online, except live animals and guns.
</P>
<P>
   But the traditional retailers are not going to cede their
business to the likes of Amazon.com without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart and other big chains are getting more serious about
strengthening their Web sites. Last week, Wal-Mart announced it was
hiring Jeanne Jackson, former chief executive of the Gap's
successful Banana Republic, to head its e-commerce division. The
world's largest retailer also is moving its Internet unit to
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think we're the Wal-Mart of the Web,'' said Wal-Mart
spokeswoman Melissa Berryhill.
</P>
<P>
   Other old-line merchants are starting to ``get it'' by
experimenting with different business models and cleaning up their
sites, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, Bloomingdales.com confounded online shoppers
with blinking lights and a busy Web design. Today, the flickering
lights are gone _ and the department store's online aisles are now
clear of clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co., which has struggled in the old world, has
decided to bring what it does best to cyberspace. At its Internet
store, consumers will find stoves, sewing machines, and cordless
drills.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking another way to tap into the Web, Sears recently
announced that it would team up with Carrefour SA, the world's
second-largest retailer, to create the industry's largest supply
exchange on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap is one of the few traditional retailers that managed to
knit its offline and online operations early in the game. Internet
shoppers, for example, can return purchases to regular stores. In
eight of its stores, customers can now use interactive kiosks to
check out the Internet clothing assortments.
</P>
<P>
   Online shoppers can locate any Gap store on the ground with a
few mouse clicks, while offline customers will find the Gap's Web
address on shopping bags and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco retailer has added several goodies to its Web
store, including a customer wish list and a clearance section. It
is now developing a feature that will allow customers to pick out
the perfect pair of pants.
</P>
<P>
   Bn.com, in the meantime, has begun testing a 24-hour delivery
service in New York. If expanded nationwide, the company could gain
ground in its race against Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kratz, a 29-year-old public relations employee from New
York, has been won over by the service. Last week, bn.com delivered
her order for the novel ``Disgrace'' in 24 hours, giving her enough
time to read it for her book club meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When she bought her first book online, Kratz bypassed Amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   ``Barnes &AMP; Noble is a name I'm more familiar with,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-07-00 1345EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
