</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BATTLEGROUND (San Francisco) _ In the huge California
battleground this fall, George W. Bush and Al Gore will be hoping
to sharply boost their primary vote numbers. The vice president
captured 2.37 million votes in California Tuesday while the
Republican Texas governor, with a much stronger opponent, received
1.9 million. Both candidates will be wooing independents who went
for John McCain or Bill Bradley and who accounted for another 2.2
million voters statewide. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DIVERSITY (San Francisco) _ Exit polls show that
California voters are becoming more ethnically diverse, thanks to
increasing numbers of Latinos and Asians exercising their political
right. And the state's electorate is notably more affluent than it
was in 1992. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR-PAYBACK (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown, fresh from winning one of the toughest reelection campaigns
of his long career, is paying back his political allies and passing
perks to his friends - including his estranged wife - with
appointments to city commissions. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   FALUN-GONG (San Francisco) _ Jein Shyue says that as soon as he
boarded an airplane headed for California, he wanted to return to
Beijing _ despite just having been jailed for three days over his
spiritual beliefs. Shyue of San Jose and Loretta Sukmei Lam of San
Leandro talk about their experiences in detention after Beijing. By
VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPSNAKE (San Francisco) _ A shy black snake with yellow-orange
stripes called the Alameda whipsnake may stop or delay major
construction projects in California because the U.S. government
plans to designate 406,708 acres as habitat for the rare critter.
By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RARE-RADIOS (Baytown, Texas) _ Bob Botto shows off a remarkable
piece of technology in his dining room. This item is so
revolutionary it reproduces sound without electricity. It is an
1892 Edison Class M business phonograph. Botto, an analytical
chemist for ExxonMobil, and his wife, Kathy, who runs the couple's
antique radio and record player shop, own more than quaint,
fanciful machines. These are artifacts. By MARTY RACINE. (Photos
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-SMOKING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Dr. Michael Schrom's waiting
room does not offer magazines that advertise tobacco products. And
he goes further than that in telling people to quit smoking. ``I
read the riot act to smokers,'' he says. Experts are urging more
doctors to do just that to reducing smoking, which kills 400,000
Americans each year. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SINISE (New York) _ After playing unpleasant types in three
films over the last few years, actor Gary Sinise is glad for a
change. His latest film _ ``Mission to Mars,'' which is being
released this weekend _ ``is just a straight-up heroic, courageous
astronaut,'' he says. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A review of the films ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' and ``Random Hearts,'' which are being released on
videotape. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MP3-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Joining 100 other campuses, the
University
</P>
<P>
   of Texas is discouraging the use of its computers to download
playable music_ not because of the music itself but because of the
burden the
</P>
<P>
   downloads place on the campus' overwhelmed computer network,
with 75,000 users. Texas A&AMP;M, alarmed about students' increasing
use of campus computers for music file downloads, is contemplating
a similar
</P>
<P>
   crackdown. At colleges nationwide, the high-tech phenomenon of
MP3 music files, making popular songs available free of charge via
computer, mingles issues of free enterprise, freedom of expression
and copyright infringement. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Career coaching is like a
prescription drug: If you use it properly, it can be wonderful; if
you take it for the wrong reason, it can be useless. And if anyone
promises you a miracle cure, hold on to your wallet. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The most important number the
morning after the primary was on the sign of a gas station where I
sometimes fill my tank. It said $2.06.9. I could swear the sign
said $2.01.9 just two days before. By the time you read this,
low-octane car juice should be over two bucks, too. These are the
numbers Al Gore should watch, not polls. That is, if he wants to be
president instead of a guy pounding nails into homes for the poor
with Jimmy Carter. Remember Jimmy Carter? Remember gas lines? By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
