<HEADLINE>
TELL KIDS HOW MUCH YOU THINK OF THEM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By NANCY HEWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents and other caring adults, here's your opportunity to tell
that special youngster what he or she means to you on this special
day dedicated to kids.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp Fire Boys and Girls organization is asking all adults
to celebrate its fourth annual ``Absolutely Incredible Kid Day'' on
Thursday by writing a letter to those special children in their
lives. It only takes a few minutes but it could leave a lasting
impact on the life you touch.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few hints for getting started. You could open the
letter with a question: Do you know what I like about you? I like
it when ... Or you can begin with a favorite poem or a famous quote
that has meaning for you.
</P>
<P>
   Write from your heart and be sincere. And don't forget to write
a letter occasionally to this person; it will open the lines of
communication and promote better self-image for the child.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp Fire Boys and Girls group has also had a book published
called ``Letters From the Heart.'' The book features letters from
previous years written by adults to the children most important to
them. The book retails for $11.95 and is available in local
outlets. It can also be ordered by phone: (888) 254-3329. For
additional information, be sure to visit the Camp Fire Boys and
Girls' Web site: www.campfire.org. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
