<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-BABY-VIDEO-LEARNING-L     03-09 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-VIDEO-LEARNING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABIES SOAK UP KNOWLEDGE FROM VIDEOS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NANCY HEWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young children are like sponges; they absorb just about
everything, including language.
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers are especially absorbant because they are just learning
how to express themselves verbally. For parents wanting their child
to learn another language, this is an opportune time. And now there
are videos available for just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babyscapes'' Educational Video Series will be releasing its
third and fourth videos Tuesday. The titles include ``Miracle of
Mozart, Teaching Your Child Numbers &AMP; Shapes in Spanish'' for
youngsters 8 months to 5 years old and ``Miracle of Mozart,
Teaching Your Child ABCs in Spanish!'' for children 18 months to 5
years old.
</P>
<P>
   This series, the brainchild of Keri and Steven Mann of Las
Vegas, came about after the birth of the couple's second son.
``When my second son was 6 months old,'' Keri recalls, ``I was
looking for a subject that would visually stimulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most child development experts agree that the first year of life
is the most crucial for developing the brain and that's why infants
need a lot of different stimulation, Keri adds.
</P>
<P>
   So, not finding what they wanted, she and Steve decided to
create their own videos. The first video, ``Baby's Smart Start,''
for kids 3 months to 5 years, was released in 1996. This video
emphasizes black, white and red images set to classical music.
Video two _ ``Celebration of Color'' for ages 8 months to 5 years _
followed in 1998. Its focus is on primary colors, also set to
classical music.
</P>
<P>
   By the third video, the Manns decided to use the music of Mozart
exclusively, having experimented with Brahms, Beethoven, Grieg,
Bach and others on their first two tapes. ``(We discovered) Mozart
aids in receptivity and retention,'' Keri says.
</P>
<P>
   The couple also discovered that there is a demand for Spanish
language tapes. ``There is a tremendous demand for Spanish,'' Steve
says. ``Not only for English speakers but for Spanish speakers,
too.'' But right now the emphasis is on the young ones. ``A baby
can learn two or three languages by the time it's 3,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Miracle of Mozart, Teaching Your Child ABCs in Spanish''
video features colorful graphics that are easy for a toddler to
track. Little eyes will follow a train that carries all the letters
of the alphabet and view a factory where little wooden people build
and paint the letters. And they will learn how to say each letter
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Miracle of Mozart, Teaching Your Child Numbers &AMP; Shapes in
Spanish'' focuses on the six basic shapes: diamonte (diamond),
circula (circle), triangulo (triangle), estrella (star), quadrado
(square) and rectangula (rectangle).
</P>
<P>
   Little ones will see colorful shapes coming out of the water or
being made in a factory. And not only will they enjoy the gentle
music of Mozart, but they will also listen to a soothing voice
narrating on each tape. According to Steve, ``The graphics keep
your attention when they keep repeating.''
</P>
<P>
   Next in the works is a tape on phonics. ``Videos will age as
kids age,'' Keri says. ``It's not just entertaining, it's
educational too.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggested retail price for each video is $14.95. All four videos
are available by phone (888) 441-5437 or by visiting the Babyscapes
Web site at www.babyscapes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1233EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-SCOFIELD-FEATUR     03-09 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SCOFIELD-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ GUITARIST JOHN SCOFIELD GETTING A `BUMP'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inventive jazz-funk guitarist John Scofield admits it: ``I love
organ too much.''
</P>
<P>
   For his latest disc, the aptly titled ``Bump,'' Scofield expands
the syncopated grooves he developed on 1998's ``A Go Go,'' an
adventurous collaboration with acid-jazz organ trio Medeski, Martin
and Wood. Previously, he worked with organist Larry Goldings on
several albums.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, don't expect the gospel-tinged feel of a
Hammond B-3 or funky clavinet bubbling away in the background.
Scofield says the rhythm instrument simply works ``too well'' in
his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to change the whole sonic thing this time,'' he
explained. ``It made a big difference. I'm glad I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scofield is certainly no stranger to funk. In the early '80s, he
recorded and toured with the pioneer of jazz-funk fusion, Miles
Davis, appearing on ``Star People,'' ``Decoy'' and ``You're Under
Arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's happy to see deep, churning grooves come back into
style at the start of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been into funk, and right now, the James Brown,
Sly Stone, Miles Davis `Bitches Brew' tradition of the late '60s
and early '70s is so alive in young bands,'' Scofield, 48, said.
``At this particular time in history, there's no generation gap _
for me anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Scofield is considered one of the ``big three'' influences in
contemporary jazz guitar, along with Pat Metheny and Bill Frisell.
But the Dayton, Ohio, native is perhaps the most directly
rock-oriented of the trio and his distinctive, jagged tone stems
partly from the use of effect pedals. On the new album's ``Beep
Beep,'' for example, he experiments with various effects, tweaking
out playful squeals and snarls over percolating beats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities are endless,'' Scofield said.
</P>
<P>
   A masterful soloist, the guitarist studied at the Berklee School
of Music in the early '70s, playing around Boston before signing on
with the Billy Cobham-George Duke band and cutting a live album
with Gerry Mulligan and Chet Baker at Carnegie Hall. He later
recorded with Charles Mingus and joined the Gary Burton quartet and
Dave Liebman's quintet.
</P>
<P>
   His nearly two dozen solo albums include projects with such
well-known players as Charlie Haden, Jack DeJohnette, Joe Lovano
and Eddie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   To vary the feel of the dozen original compositions on ``Bump''
(in stores Tuesday), Scofield called upon a number of young
musicians to bring beats and bass lines in various rhythm-section
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Eric Kalb and percussionist Johnny Durkin come from the
New England funk outfit Deep Banana Blackout, bassist Tony Scherr
and drummer Kenny Wollesen play with the postmodern jazz quartet
Sex Mob, and sample maven Mark De Gli Antoni plies his trade with
Soul Coughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bump'' (Verve) was produced by Lee Townsend, with whom
Scofield has worked on his last half-dozen records, as well as his
joint album with Metheny, ``I Can See Your House From Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Scofield's flexibility allows him to move from a project like
``Bump'' to another with drummer Billy Higgins, saxophonist Kenny
Garrett, bassist Christian McBride and pianist Brad Mehldau; to jam
with bands like Govt. Mule and Moe; to pursue an unusual side group
with Steve Swallow and Bill Stewart; and to join a New Orleans jam
session with members of the Meters and the Dirty Dozen Brass Band
horns.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he was in Britain appearing with the Birmingham
Symphony Orchestra to perform contemporary composer Mark Anthony
Turnadge's ``Blood on the Floor,'' conducted by Sir Simon Rattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The composer knew about me and asked me to play,'' Scofield
said from Birmingham. ``It was influenced by jazz and Stravinsky
with a little room for improvisation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Philharmonic will perform the Turnadge piece
this year, but without Scofield, who will be on the road with his
new band, the guitarist said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Scofield will be touring with a rhythm
guitarist, Avi Bortnick, who was recommended by Bay Area guitarist
Charlie Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a master at rhythm,'' Scofield said. ``He switches off on
electric and acoustic and uses a lot of pedals like I do. We're
just working out all the things we can do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
