<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NOT ALL CAREER COUNSELORS ARE CREATED EQUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Career coaching is like a prescription drug: If
you use it properly, it can be wonderful; if you take it for the
wrong reason, it can be useless. And if anyone promises you a
miracle cure, hold on to your wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they call themselves coaches, counselors, advisers or
gurus, people who get paid to offer career advice can help you help
yourself. But first, you have to pay attention to the cardinal rule
of business: Hire the right people.
</P>
<P>
   Many well-intentioned counselors will talk about how you should
find your passion, then figure out how you could make money
following that passion. As any soap opera fan will tell you,
though, passion has its pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   You need some passion in your life, whether it's for
relationships or travel or food or money or whatever else. If your
career saps so much energy that you have a passion for absolutely
nothing, including work, get help or get out.
</P>
<P>
   Your career should certainly be something you enjoy _ something
that gets your adrenaline pumping, at least once in a while. Make
sure you're good at it, or have the potential to be. The greatest
job in the world will quickly turn ugly if you don't have the
talent.
</P>
<P>
   But should it be your passion? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're doing something because you have to instead of
because you want to, your passion for it is almost certainly going
to diminish. You might make your career more satisfying, but you'll
sacrifice one of life's pleasures in the process. That's a heavy
price.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for outsiders to underestimate how much grunt work is
involved in any job. Actors spend hours getting made up and waiting
for others to finish their scenes. Doctors have to conquer the
insurance industry as well as diseases. Entrepreneurs must put a
lot of energy into ordering supplies, figuring out finances and
drumming up business.
</P>
<P>
   Before you see a career counselor, think about what jobs out
there might suit your passions and interests. Then talk to people
who have those jobs so you can discover the drawbacks as well as
the pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Realize, too, that all this talk about passion can be part of a
sales pitch. After all, if counselors make you feel that you ought
to be passionate, but you aren't, that's an awfully compelling
argument for hiring them, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Define success on your terms, not a counselor's. Some people
would rather put in their eight hours and go home to a life without
pagers or cell phones or thoughts about work. There is nothing
wrong with that. Your No. 1 goal should always be to have a good
life, and only you can decide the importance of work in that
picture.
</P>
<P>
   What do you hope to gain from career counseling? Obviously you
want something to change, but try to focus on specific items rather
than a general malaise. If all you really want to do is complain, a
career counselor won't be much help.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have trouble getting along with your boss or co-workers?
Are you unhappy, but you really don't know why? Counselors with
strong backgrounds in psychology might offer the most help.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to change careers, but have no idea what else to go
into? Some counselors specialize in aptitude tests and in knowing
what kinds of jobs are out there besides the obvious ones.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of becoming an entrepreneur, find a counselor
with experience in starting a business _ and not just a career
counseling business. Warning: Starting your own business to escape
a lackluster career is a path to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Do you just want help job hunting or getting promoted? Many
counselors offer the basics, but try to find someone with expertise
or connections within your industry. Avoid anyone who demands large
upfront fees.
</P>
<P>
   How important is money to you? If your main source of
unhappiness is that your job just won't pay the bills, find a
counselor with financial expertise. Maybe better budgeting and
investing will make your current job more acceptable. Maybe you
need help negotiating with your current employer.
</P>
<P>
   Are you uninspired? Maybe you do need someone who talks of
passion and loves exclamation points. Just because they turn my
stomach doesn't mean they'll turn yours.
</P>
<P>
   In all these cases, make sure you have looked within your
industry and checked the library and the Internet before seeing a
counselor. If you are having trouble with someone, maybe you can
get advice from someone else who gets along with that person. If
you are having trouble finding a job or getting promoted, maybe you
need a mentor or a better network and not a counselor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
