<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     SUV CULTURE GETS A TASTE OF THE 70s  
 &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The most important number the morning after the
primary was on the sign of a gas station where I sometimes fill my
tank. It said $2.06.9.
</P>
<P>
   I could swear the sign said $2.01.9 just two days before. High
test was going up faster than Amazon.com stock did, and regular was
following close behind at $1.86.9.
</P>
<P>
   These are the numbers Al Gore should watch, not polls. That is,
if he wants to be president instead of a guy pounding nails into
homes for the poor with Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Jimmy Carter? Remember gas lines?
</P>
<P>
   Green and red flags, odd and even days, lines of dozens of cars
waiting at the pumps. These are the things that can break a
president, not Social Security or education policy.
</P>
<P>
   The hell with old age and kids. We're Americans, and we've got
to get in our cars and drive _ now. Heaven help any politician who
gets in the way, or is linked with $100 fill-ups for our precious
SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bright young kids in the San Francisco Bay Area who
work on the information superhighway don't even remember 1973 or
1979 when real superhighways were cleared of cars for lack of gas.
Heck, they don't even remember the recession of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   These dot.com kids think stocks always go up, and plenty of
gasoline is always available to pour into their Saabs and Land
Cruisers so they can head for Tahoe to spend their stock options.
Or whatever they do.
</P>
<P>
   With a gas shortage in the offing for California and perhaps the
nation, the kids should know how gas lines work. OK, kids, think of
gas stations as Web sites with too many visitors _ sites to be
accessed only after hours on line.
</P>
<P>
   Disco wasn't the only thing that was invented in the '70s. The
powers that be also came up with a system for dealing with gas
shortages, and believe me, it sucked worse than disco.
</P>
<P>
   I use that objectionable verb ``sucked'' not just because of the
disco reference, but because of siphoning, a form of orality all
too many of us became familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, gas shortages. One company started selling siphons that
didn't require mouth-to-hose contact. Locking gas caps were
invented. Gas was so precious no one robbed cars for the stereos,
and not just because they were eight-track.
</P>
<P>
   On odd and even days gas stations flew red or green flags
indicating that gas could be sold only to those with license plates
ending in odd or even numbers. I seem to remember that personalized
plates were categorized as odd, which they usually were.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, abuses occurred. People would switch plates, or steal
plates, just to get gas. Whatever they did, though, they had to
wait in long lines, pay high prices and not take trips farther than
the nearest grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The only people who had Land Rovers in those days lived in
Kenya, but we had other cars that guzzled gas and constantly
required fill-ups. We didn't call them SUVs. We called them
American cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973 I lived in Boston, which has a decent public transit
system, so when the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
decided to punish nations that backed Israel in the Mideast War
they didn't punish me.
</P>
<P>
   Those who needed cars were hurt, though. Boston used to have the
highest rate of car theft in the nation, but that year thieves were
giving cars back.
</P>
<P>
   By the gas shortage of 1979, I was living in California, and
this is where a gas shortage really hurts. I had an old pickup that
got 11 miles to the gallon and I worked as a dispatch messenger for
a newspaper, which meant I had to drive hundreds of miles a week.
</P>
<P>
   Solution: I just used the pickup to go to the pump on odd days
and siphoned the gas into my 70 mpg motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   I recommend car-to-motorcycle refueling for anyone with a gas
guzzler who doesn't like waiting in lines, as well as motorcyclists
with pathetic four-gallon tanks.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the schizophrenia. We're Californians, so we're angry
at anything that interferes with our right to fill up our monster
SUVs and drive. But we're also Northern Californians, so our social
consciences tell us that Americans have been spoiled by low gas
prices and the delusion that they'll never have to economize on
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two halves of us can get together and hate the
oil companies, which seem to have rigged the system, especially
against California.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, there's another thing about the summer of '79 that
young SUVers will find incredible. It was the summer of the Honda.
Everyone wanted a Honda Civic, and there was a waiting list of
months before you could trade in your American car for one of those
gas-sipping babies.
</P>
<P>
   I still drive a Honda and until recently I felt pretty small
next to Ford Explorers and Lincoln Navigators. In fact, the car is
so small I'd be looking somewhere below their gas caps.
</P>
<P>
   Now I look at their gas caps and laugh. But I'm not sure 35 mpg
is enough.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
