<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-SMOKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOCTORS GETTING MORE AGGRESSIVE ABOUT PATIENTS WHO SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dr. Michael Schrom does not keep the usual staple
of magazines in his waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Schrom, who is passionate about getting people to stop smoking,
refuses to subscribe to any publication that accepts cigarette
advertising, ruling out most of the popular reads like People, Time
and Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   At his Manning Boulevard office in Albany, there is a collection
of Smithsonian, Architectural Digest and New York State
Conservationist magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's appropriate to read the riot act to smokers
and then have the Marlboro man staring them in the face in my
waiting room,'' said Schrom, an otolaryngologist at the Capital
District Ear, Nose and Throat Service.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against smoking has always been helped by
individual physicians like Schrom, who have worked to educate
patients about the dangers of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   More physicians are growing increasingly militant about their
stance against tobacco, which kills 400,000 Americans each year.
Some heart surgeons have been known to give their patients three
months to quit _ or seek treatment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors aren't yet willing to go that far, and some studies
have shown that many physicians are unwilling to discuss smoking
with their patients at all, citing time constraints from managed
care and the fear of alienating people.
</P>
<P>
   One recent study revealed that while 70 percent of smokers see a
physician each year, only half are urged to quit, and less than 20
percent are given advice on how to quit or information on effective
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think physicians are necessarily among the worst
offenders about not encouraging smoking cessation but we don't go
far enough,'' Schrom said.
</P>
<P>
   But as few as three minutes of a physician's time can almost
double the rate of quitting among his or her patients, and the more
time spent with smokers, the higher the rates of quitting,
according to Dr. Michael Fiore, director of the Center for Tobacco
Research and Intervention at the University of Wisconsin Medical
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are still afraid to bother their patients about
it,'' said Dr. John A. Van Deloo, a family practitioner in
Schenectady, N.Y.. ``Some patients are antagonistic.''
</P>
<P>
   David Mulligan, the former Massachusetts Department of Public
Health Commissioner, believes physician involvement is vital in
getting people to give up smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are community leaders,'' said Mulligan, who worked with
doctors in Boston to implement a smoking ban in restaurants.
``Having them at the forefront of this issue is the key to
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet physicians acknowledge they can only do so much.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Wilson, acting chairman of the medicine at Ellis
Hospital in Schenectady and a longtime opponent of smoking, has
been unable to convince his own mother to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally gave up because it wasn't worth the arguments,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said doctors have to weigh how much to push the cigarette
issue with their patients, especially if it means losing their
attention on other important health matters, such as taking
medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some physicians don't want to introduce that tension into the
relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrom, who deals with head and neck cancers, has no plans to
tone down his position on smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the riot act to smokers,'' he said. ``I've never had to
take out the voice box of a someone who doesn't smoke, I never had
to remove the tongue of someone who doesn't smoke, I've never had
to remove the jaw of someone who doesn't smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be just as happy if they'd ban that weed from the face of
the Earth,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
