<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV17 
 IF YOUR SON IS SUICIDAL, GET ON A PLANE AND GO HELP HIM  
 FOR USE FRIDAY, MARCH 17, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRJOY-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call (888)-269-8796. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 c.2000 Dr. Joy Browne. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: We have a 23-year-old son who lives in another
state. For the first 20 years of his life he was the ``perfect
child.'' The last three years show a complete reversal _ he dropped
out of school, drank to excess, got speeding tickets, stopped
attending church, pushed his girlfriend up against a wall and even
made an ``attempt at suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time he gets his life on track, he seems to exhibit
self-destructive behavior. My wife wants to fly back to Denver to
``help him,'' and I am saying that at 23, he has to help himself. I
have told him repeatedly that he needs help _ Alcoholics Anonymous,
a shrink and/or treatment for what sounds to be numerous ongoing
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Please tell me if we should go to Denver to help our son through
this health crisis or just continue to make the suggestions that we
know he should be following and hope that he starts listening. I
have a potentially suicidal son, a wife who is crazy with worry and
me who knows he needs immediate help but doesn't know what to do!
F.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I'd follow your heart on this _ not your head. It
sounds as if your son is in acute distress so get on a plane to go
and show your moral support, if nothing else. You'll have some
face-to-face information, and you may be able to get him into some
kind of treatment program in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   If he is suicidal, Alcoholics Anonymous is a good, long-term
solution, but not a short-term solution. He likely needs to be
hospitalized and put on medication. Certainly he needs to be seen
by a professional. You'll be able to assess the situation and
accomplish these goals much better in person, rather than over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like your son experienced some kind of traumatic event
that triggered this situation. I always worry when someone says
they have the perfect son or daughter because that's simply not
true. There are no perfect children and there are no perfect
situations, which means something knocked him off course. Whether
he's having a delayed teen-age rebellion or something more
specific, your son seems to have been derailed a couple of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a short-term solution, I'd get on that plane and see what you
can do to help your son.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: My mate never leveled with me until 10 years into
the relationship and subsequent marriage about his secret urges. I
was shocked, confused and hurt when I walked in on him wearing my
silk negligee, a wig, full makeup, heels and a great big smile on
his face.
</P>
<P>
   There had been times when I had wondered about his
deceitfulness, but I was quite naive about the whole thing. Coming
home and finding a man in full drag is not my idea of being turned
on. Could you gather some input from other spouses suffering with
this problem?
</P>
<P>
   Please try to explain why these men feel compelled to wear
women's clothes. I believe it is their duty to explore where they
are ``coming'' from if they expect their mate to understand. C.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: You may be asking the wrong questions. Finding out how
other people deal with the situation may be helpful. You could go
online _ the Third Sex Society deals specifically with tranvestism
_ to find out how other people cope. But what you really want to do
is figure out what YOU want to do about it. We don't run our lives
by consensus. We figure out what's important to us and make our
choices accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear when this occurred. However long ago, you're
obviously committed enough to your spouse _ even with this
uncomfortable revelation _ to stick by him, if only for this
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The person who can tell you the most about why he does this is
your spouse. Whether or not he's willing to do this is unclear. As
for cross-dressing, it's not all that uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   In our society we allow women a huge latitude to cross-dress. At
this moment, you may be wearing blue jeans, a baseball cap and
sneakers. Not so long ago these were considered strictly male garb.
Now it is not only OK, but perfectly stylish for women to wear
clothes once worn exclusively by men.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that we don't allow men a whole lot of latitude in
this area. I am not saying, however, that it's fine to cross-dress
because this behavior is clearly upsetting to you. So start with
your feelings: Is there anything specific about his behavior that
you consider acceptable? For example, if he did this when you
weren't around, would that make you feel comfortable? Does he do
this in public and is that part of the issue _ that you feel other
people will find out and you'll be embarrassed? If you could figure
out a little bit more about what your concerns are, you may be able
to address them with your husband.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of him understanding why he does this, he will most
likely tell you that he doesn't know. Whether it stems from his
childhood is unclear. For better or worse, this is where he is
right now. The likelihood is that he is not going to change his
behavior unless he really wants to. You need to decide where your
perimeters are and what you're willing _ and not willing _ to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168, or
to drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered
in this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
