<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SINISE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES OF GARY SINISE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gary Sinise is making tea.
</P>
<P>
   Room service has just delivered a large tray with several
containers and cups, and Sinise makes a loud rattle of finding the
hot water and the bags and getting the tea brewing. The process
goes on for several minutes, but once the liquid and leaves are
finally together in the delicate pot, Sinise is ready to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, buddy,'' he says, leaning back on the sofa. ``Go ahead,
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sinise is clean-shaven, short-haired and dressed neatly
in new jeans and a casual blue shirt. He looks much more like the
heroic good-guy astronaut he plays in ``Mission to Mars,'' the
big-budget science-fiction adventure opening Friday, than the
scuzzy, gun-running nasty he created for the action thriller
``Reindeer Games,'' already in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   And thank goodness, because the muscular Gabriel from ``Reindeer
Games'' would be scary, even if he were having tea in an elegant
suite high up in the Essex House on Central Park South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I scared myself,'' Sinise says of Gabriel. He has that slight
one-sided smile he uses in movies, and his expression suggests
amused amazement that he could seem so creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Sinise is much easier to like and trust in ``Mission to Mars.''
He plays the leader of a rescue mission sent to the Red Planet
after an earlier crew meets with ... well, serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   After playing unpleasant types in three films over the last few
years _ a kidnapper of Mel Gibson's son in ``Ransom,'' and a
double-dealing military man in ``Snake Eyes'' _ Sinise was glad for
a change.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mission to Mars' is just a straight-up heroic, courageous
astronaut,'' he says of his role.
</P>
<P>
   The space movie reunites Sinise with Brian DePalma, his ``Snake
Eyes'' director, in a film that has plentiful special effects, many
involving the actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough shoot,'' Sinise says. ``Tough physically,
because we had to do a lot of physical stuff _ hanging on wires,
and wearing these space suits, all that kind of stuff. We're in the
space suits 50 percent of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinise had some of his preparation for the role of an astronaut
out of the way, however, thanks to his previous role in ``Apollo
13.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Houston and doing all that stuff for `Apollo 13,'''
he says, ``all that was real helpful on `Mission to Mars.' Going up
in the zero-gravity jet _ all that was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinise hopes the big visuals won't overshadow the script and
characters in ``Mission to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good story,'' he says. ``I think you really grow to
care about these people and what they're trying to do _ and what
ends up happening to them at the end of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' combines elements of three of the most
famous space films ever: ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' for its
authentic scientific feel; ``Apollo 13'' for its emotional
involvement; and ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' for the
fantastical elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hopeful, positive, life-affirming kind of story,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie is also mildly frightening in places, and Sinise
still has not decided whether to let his three children, two girls
and a boy ages 11, 9 and 7, see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm debating whether I should bring them to the premiere or
not,'' he says. ``It's PG-13, but there's some scary stuff in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll never see `Reindeer Games,''' he says of that R-rated
movie, which offers violence, nudity and harsh language, much of it
involving Sinise. ``They'll have to be a lot older.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinise, who turns 45 this month, has been married to theater
actress Moira Harris for 19 years. His family is one reason he does
not make more movies. Being at home is too important to him right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've maneuvered things in such a way that I have enough money
that I can support the lifestyle I have, which isn't too eccentric
_ so that I don't have to go to work constantly to support a whole
big bunch of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to work, I want to be sure it's stuff that I like
and I'm going to get something from it as an actor _ or with people
that I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Being picky may have kept Sinise from reaching major-star status
_ something he would like _ but it has not hurt his considerable
acting reputation, which followed him from the stage when he
finally started doing movies at age 36, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest advice to any director is, `Cast Gary Sinise,'''
said ``Reindeer Games'' director John Frankenheimer. ``He makes you
look good. I mean, the guy _ with Frederic March, Raul Julia and
Angela Lansbury _ is one of the four finest actors I've ever worked
with.''
</P>
<P>
   After having made the Emmy Award-winning cable movie ``George
Wallace'' starring Sinise, Frankenheimer wanted the actor to star
in his big-screen film ``Ronin.''
</P>
<P>
   The studios said no, Sinise wasn't a big name. The film
eventually starred Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   Long before he got an Oscar nomination as Lt. Dan, the
embittered legless Vietnam veteran in ``Forrest Gump,'' Sinise had
made his mark in theater.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after graduating from high school, the then-18-year-old
Sinise and some friends began Chicago's Steppenwolf Theater in the
basement of a church. A quarter-century later, the now-famous
theater is housed in an $8 million building. Alumni of the company
include John Malkovich and Joan Allen, both twice Oscar-nominated,
and John Mahoney (``Frasier'').
</P>
<P>
   Sinise was the theater's artistic director for seven years. Two
years after staging an award-winning production of John Steinbeck's
``The Grapes of Wrath'' (which he still hopes to film one day), he
directed and co-starred with Malkovich in a well-received film
version of ``Of Mice and Men.'' Two years later came ``Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six years since, Sinise has played mostly character parts
in supporting roles. Even his leads in two TV movies, ``Truman''
and ``George Wallace,'' are what he calls character roles.
``Truman'' brought him an Emmy nomination, and ``George Wallace''
won him an Emmy and a Golden Globe.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Mission to Mars,'' Sinise may be seen this year in two
films that he shot in 1998, if they ever open. He did his work in
both in just six days each. One is a science-fiction film called
``Impostor.'' The other, ``Bruno,'' was directed by Shirley
MacLaine.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, this spring Sinise returns to Chicago and the
Steppenwolf stage to star in a new production of ``One Flew Over
the Cuckoo's Nest,'' a play he has wanted to do for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since there was a major production of
it,'' he says, adding with a laugh, ``probably because the movie
was so good. The theatrical experience is very different.''
</P>
<P>
   When tickets went on sale early last month for ``Cuckoo,'' which
opens April 16, patrons lined up around the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ``Mission to Mars'' does for his career, it may be a
while before we see Sinise playing another major villain. He didn't
want to do Gabriel in ``Reindeer Games,'' but when he read the
script, wheels began turning.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, what can I do with it that's going to be different from
the last one I played?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every character has his point of view, and you have to see the
world from that perspective.'' he says. ``If you're playing Adolf
Hitler or whatever. Otherwise you can't do it with any honesty or
reality. You play George Wallace, you have to try to understand,
`OK, what's drivin' this guy? Why is he doing the stuff he's
doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when he played Stanley Kowalski in ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' at Steppenwolf, Sinise says, he was
attracted by Kowalski's animal qualities, something he figured he'd
never be able to do onscreen. Gabriel offered him that chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more of an animal than (the bad guys in) `Snake Eyes' or
`Ransom,''' the actor says. ``Those guys are a little slicker. I
saw Gabriel as kind of a rocker. I decided to give him a stringy,
long-hair look. Put a tattoo up here.''
</P>
<P>
   He also gave him some pretty good biceps, something that has
brought a lot of comment. Sinise was surprised and a little
embarrassed by the attention his arms got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time when you see me acting, you don't see me in a
tank top or with my shirt off. You don't really know what's going
on,'' he says, grinning again. ``It doesn't take me that long to
pump up like that. I stay in pretty good shape. I've always had
arms that ... '' He stops abruptly, looking sheepish. ``Why are we
talking about this?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
