</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK CLOSES WITH DROOPY `EYES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `EYES WIDE SHUT'
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick was one of film's great directors. From ``Paths
of Glory,'' ``Dr. Strangelove'' and ``2001'' to ``A Clockwork
Orange,'' ``Barry Lyndon'' and ``Full Metal Jacket,'' his
immaculate movies were as artful as they come.
</P>
<P>
   But his final film, while artful, is a long, listless swan song
that assumes a profundity it doesn't merit.
</P>
<P>
   Like a great painting, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is remarkable to
behold. It's another of Kubrick's amazing inventions on a British
soundstage, where the expatriate American could tinker to his
heart's content. (``Eyes Wide Shut'' was in production for more
than two years.)
</P>
<P>
   But you don't stare at a great painting for 159 minutes nonstop,
and at that length, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' seems almost as inanimate.
</P>
<P>
   Edited with glacial slowness, scenes drone on beyond any
reasonable narrative function. Such bloating poorly serves a
sexually charged plot in need of purposefulness, not inertia.
</P>
<P>
   Married actors Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman play a loving,
upscale married couple in Manhattan who are troubled by carnal
temptations.
</P>
<P>
   A suave, older European tries to seduce her at a party. She
confesses a sexual fantasy to her husband. Curious, he questions a
prostitute and invades a costumed sex party in a mansion.
</P>
<P>
   These events prove almost shattering to the couple. And it's the
``almost'' that almost redeems the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' was marketed as a bold sex film, but its sex
is largely limited to dialogue and the brandishment of female
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the film is a tease _ and it's no less sexist
than today's men's magazines (Maxim and GQ, to name two), with
their boyish leaning toward leering.
</P>
<P>
   The film's greatest power lies in its craft. Music, production
design, lighting and cinematography are exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   The editing may falter (including continuity glitches _ watch
that moving stack of CDs), but the performances also are strong,
from the leads to the smallest bit parts.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make this alleged erotic odyssey any more
satisfying _ just admirable for its final evocation of Kubrick's
fierce devotion to detail.
</P>
<P>
   His death before the film's release led to a compromise of that
devotion, especially in terms of shot composition.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid an NC-17 rating, the studio changed the orgy scenes,
with nameless characters digitally added. In shot after shot, they
stand in the way as Cruise roams the mansion, obscuring sexual
activity.
</P>
<P>
   These clumsy clusters become a running joke. If you didn't know
better, you'd swear this was the worst-blocked movie ever _ or
perhaps a ripoff of the peek-a-boo scenes of the ``Austin Powers''
flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, neither is the case. Kubrick was an artist to the end.
But most of his films were also grandly entertaining, and ``Eyes
Wide Shut`` is not.
</P>
<P>
   _ DVD extras: ``Eyes Wide Shut'' on DVD offers two TV spots, the
theatrical trailer and three interviews: with Cruise, Kidman and
colleague Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   In her 18 1/2-minute talk to an unseen interviewer (who
complains about the session's brevity), Kidman seems the most
candid.
</P>
<P>
   Like her husband, she was awed by Kubrick, then fell under his
spell as a craftsman and under his wing as a father figure.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman fights back tears when she is asked about Kubrick's
death. Cruise is more successful, though he is also tormented. Both
feel the director's sudden demise at age 70 was ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   They sound as if they'd be happy to be still working on the
movie. Cruise says he ``didn't want the experience to end,'' and
Kidman equates it with ``getting lost'' in another world.
</P>
<P>
   Review: C
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`RANDOM HEARTS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a costly, glossy film with big stars _ and familiar faces
even in bit parts _ ``Random Hearts'' is one lousy clunker.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing random about this botched job. It's bad on every
front, from the morose, meandering screenplay to the leaden
direction of Sidney Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford plays a tough cop _ call him Dirty Harrison. When
he's not being grimly stoic, he tries mightily to be mean, via an
explosive, violent temper.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow this makes him a hunky magnet for a conservative
congresswoman (Kristin Scott Thomas).
</P>
<P>
   They don't exactly cute-meet. Their respective spouses were
flying off for an affair when their plane crashed, killing both of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ford laboriously learns o4U%M
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
