<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-JACOBS-BOS     03-09 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-JACOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOBS SEES FUTURE IN SINDEN, O'CONNELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Jeremy Jacobs will leave the specifics to his
top two administrators, Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell, but the
Bruins owner made it clear Wednesday there must be some fundamental
changes in the way his sagging hockey franchise does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't come off a year like this and not change,'' said
Jacobs in his Delaware North Companies office in downtown Buffalo.
``You can't. If you come back with the same attitude and the same
approach, then you'll have the same results.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in four seasons, business as usual on
Causeway Street will be done without the Bruins in the playoffs.
Jacobs said he isn't sure where or how deep the changes will be,
but did suggest there will be some ``prudent'' spending aimed at
adding to the player roster and possibly adding to the
decision-making personnel in the front office.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was emphatic, however, that both Sinden and O'Connell
will continue to run the show, with O'Connell moving into the
general manager's job full-time whenever Sinden finally takes on
the club presidency as his sole responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is up to (Sinden),'' Jacobs said shortly before
departing for a trip to Florida, hours before his club faced the
Sabres at Marine Midland Arena. ``I don't know if right now is the
easiest time do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden hinted at Monday night's news conference, the farewell to
longtime team captain Ray Bourque, that he soon may relinquish the
GM job. If that decision is imminent, Jacobs said he will endorse
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' Jacobs said. ``I am confident that Mike
O'Connell has the brain power to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that some 450 miles to the east, Bruins fans are
villifying him, Jacobs acknowledged what he called ``the rhetoric''
among the disgruntled legions. He knows that Bruins Country is
unhappy, incensed most of late by Bourque's departure. He
acknowledges his club could be in for a sizeable hit at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as things look, said Jacobs, he has seen worse in his
25-year tenure as club owner. He bristled at the suggestion that
now might be the time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean get out of it?'' Jacobs said. ``Ain't gonna happen.
I'm in this sport for a long time. I think it's a terrific
franchise, I really do. We are stayers. This is not bleak. It's not
good, what's happened this year. But this is bright on the all-time
list of bleakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Much worse, said Jacobs, were the late 1980s and early '90s when
Boston politics threatened to prevent him from building his $160
million arena on Causeway Street. Worse was Bobby Orr's departure
as a free agent to Chicago in the summer of '76. If Orr's departure
registered a 10 on the scale of bleakness, he said, then today's
travails max out around a 7 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bad right now, too, don't get me wrong,'' Jacobs said.
``But not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jacobs, business dipped considerably in the wake of
the 1996-97 bottoming out that resulted in the Bruins missing the
playoffs for the first time since 1966-67. He said business fell
off by as much as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's a lot in this business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If pundits are to be believed, the fallout from this season's
``freefall,'' as Jacobs terms it, could rival the apathy that came
in light of Orr's departure. At the moment, said Jacobs, he has no
hard evidence that the rhetoric among the vox populi will translate
into empty seats. Despite how it translates, he doesn't sound like
a man about to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people would love to hear me say, `Blow it up and
rebuild it.' That's not going to be the case,'' he said. ``But we
do have to make changes. We have a tremendous fan base, and they
have not gotten what they bargained for in the Boston Bruins. And
they have stuck with us. And, frankly, I've never seen Bruins fans
stick with the Bruins like they have this year. I know to some that
sounds like so much (expletive), but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to be more specific, Jacobs would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking me, `Where's the beef?' '' he said. ``And I have
to say I have (Sinden and O'Connell) to make those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the points that most angers fans is the perception,
supported by financial publications, that the Bruins are a cash
cow. Why, fans ask, doesn't Jacobs plow some of the profit back
into the product? He acknowledged that the Bruins rank in the top
third of NHL clubs for profits and the bottom third for payroll.
That profit now, he said, offers the opportunity to repair some of
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not hammerlocked here by financial restrictions,'' he
said. ``We don't have the issues some teams, like Ottawa and
Pittsburgh, have encountered. We have some (financial) latitude,
and in a prudent way, these things (changes in the way the club is
managed and spends money) will take place.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of Bourque, Jacobs said he was sorry to see the
club icon depart town. He said he was surprised by Bourque's
request to be traded, and he interpreted it as a measure of
Bourque's frustration with his own game and the lack of team
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bourque was a wonderful player for us for 20-21 years _ just
an unbelieveable, remarkable player,'' he said. ``He's almost 40
years old, and I think he's had his playing career. I had no idea
he wanted to leave Boston. Until he asked to leave, I thought he
would never leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he is frustrated . . . I think with himself and
with the team around him. I'm not sure how much of that is the team
around him. We wound up with some skilled players in return, and I
am happy we were able to harvest something in his departure.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bourque, who will become a free agent July 1, wants to return
to Boston, Jacobs says the opportunity will be there. ``As far as I
am concerned, he will always be welcomed as a Boston Bruin,'' he
said. ``I'd like to see him back in uniform. But at the same time,
I think that's highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   And what if Bourque wants to return next season at his current
wage of $6 million a year? ``I think that's up to Harry,'' he said,
``and then the question is, is he a $6 million-a-year player?''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque for years has worked with the belief that a job would
await him in Boston after his playing days. His departure Monday to
the Avalanche shouldn't change that assumption, said Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still would be welcomed back,'' he said. ``We would like to
see him come back to Boston and have a future in our organization.
What capacity that would be, other than skating, I'm not sure. But
we know he is a special person.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was unfazed by suggestions that Bourque was let down by
being dealt to Colorado, considering his stated first choice was
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like him to be where he'd like to be, but we also have a
bigger responsibility to the Boston Bruins,'' Jacobs said. ``In
that situation, he's an asset to the Bruins. At his age, he's doing
well. He's made a fortune, and he should be happy. The worst thing
we could have done was to look back and feel we shorted the team.
Then next year, you'd have to deal with the fact that you're short
skilled players _ and we aren't now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs criticized the coaching staff weeks ago, expressing to
Globe columnist Will McDonough his displeasure with the club's
penalty-killing woes _ remarks that seemed to trigger the season's
unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am suspect as hell about everything,'' said Jacobs. ``You
look at someone like Pat Burns _ a very competent guy _ with
wonderful credentials and all . . . and you look at this this from
so many directions . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs then changed the course of the conversation to O'Connell.
``I think he is showing he's more reactionary (than Sinden) at this
point . . . and Harry's been the one who's more moderate, saying,
`Let's ride this a little longer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this could be construed as O'Connell being more
interested in canning the coach than Sinden, Jacobs said, ``I think
(O'Connell) wants to make more changes, but . . . I don't know if
changing Burns is the right thing, I really don't. I mean, we've
had bad coaches before.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad coaches, according to Jacobs, were Don Cherry and Steve
Kasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't fond of Kasper,'' said the owner. ``I know Harry
thinks he's a bright guy. I didn't think his players believed in
him. And Cherry did foolish things. At the end, his `I'm out of
here' thing . . . his nutty. I didn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Revisting his comments weeks ago about the lapsed penalty
killing, Jacobns said he was not being directly critical of Burns'
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was critical, but it wasn't of Burns, really,'' he said.
``What I said, and I still feel, is that I don't think you go from
first to last (in penalty killing) with the same group of people.
With the exception of Tim Taylor, things were the same _ and I just
don't see how you go from first to last. Now, I don't know if
that's the coach, or what it is. But by process of elimination, I
guess you end up criticizing the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly during the interview, Jacobs said he felt this club
has underperformed. Time and again he referred to the club's young,
core talent and how he believes it should perform better. On a
positive note, he said he thought Joe Thornton's play improved
considerably, something, he conjectured, that might not have
happened if Taylor played those minutes. On a negative note, he
said Sergei Samsonov's play has tailed off considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very discouraging, isn't it?'' said Jacobs. ``But I
think there's a better player in there. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Right from the start this season, said Jacobs, he wasn't pleased
with his club's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from Day 1 this season, this team has
underperformed,'' he said. ``From the start, we looked like we we
weren't fit, like we couldn't skate _ things you just couldn't
expect after what we saw last year.''
</P>
<P>
   If the problem isn't coaching, as so many of the owners'
comments seem to suggest, what will that say about this season and
the future of the club?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we've got to dig deeper, don't we?'' he said. ``Then we
really have to start over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
