<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-09 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SKIPPER IS FEELING RENEWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ An honest-to-God, Standing-Room-Only,
record-setting crowd of 7,132 jammed City Of Palms Park Wednesday.
Who was in town? Well, as my mother used to say, ``You get three
guesses, and the first two don't count.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was the Yankees. Some of 'em, anyway. There was no
Derek Jeter, no Bernie Williams, no Paul O'Neill, no Chuck
Knoblauch, and no need to duck if you were sitting behind first
base. (Hey, he's a Yankee, so there's no such thing as a cheap
shot.) It was just March 8, and it was just spring training, so it
wasn't going to be the full Yankee lineup the Red Sox will be
looking at when the teams play their first serious game of the 2000
season May 26 in New York. In spring training, the guiding
principle when it comes to ticket buying is caveat emptor, and
don't you forget it. The Yankees had played in Tampa Tuesday night,
so they almost went into a split-squad mode for this one. Even Don
Zimmer didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Joe Torre did, and that meant that the New York
organization was going to be represented with the maximum amount of
class and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The genial skipper had to make sure he had packed his sense of
humor, too, because the team he brought was 0-6, as in winless.
Rumor had it that The Boss was not amused, and never mind that last
year's world champions were 14-19 down here, or that the 125-win
juggernaut of two seasons ago was a modest 15-12 in the Grapefruit
League. George Steinbrenner is not noted for his clear perspective
in these matters.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that WBZ's John Miller cracked a little wise with the
opening query for Torre. ``If you lose today, will you have to walk
back to Tampa?'' Miller inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask George about that,'' Torre said with a
smile. ``But I brought some money so I can take a cab.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that when Roberto Kelly's ground out brought
home Rafael Bournigal (double, stolen base) from third in the third
inning, it represented the Yankees' first lead of the spring. (As
the late Mel Allen would say, ``How about that!'') And further let
the record show the manager was able to occupy his regular seat on
the bus back to Tampa after his team put a 10-4 whuppin' on the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   No Yankee follower with half a baseball brain should have been
unduly concerned about the results of a few exhibition games. But
as Torre explained when asked about the basic daily difference
between managing the Yankees and the other big league clubs he's
been in charge of (Mets, Braves, and Cardinals), the Yankees are
not your normal baseball anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're working for George,'' Torre pointed out. ``You have to
be aware that anything can break out at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that working for the George Steinbrenner
Yankees means you have, shall we say, resources. ``I am very
grateful to be working for George,'' Torre insisted. ``If I
weren't, I wouldn't have three (World Series) rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's Yankees have had their depth weakened in the offseason,
and there is always a question about the health of pitching ace
David Cone, but they remain the favorites to win the American
League East. The difference, Torre says, is the identity of his
chief threat. He thinks he was looking at them Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at this time I didn't consider the Red Sox to be the
chief competition,'' said Torre. ``I was totally wrong. Jimy
(Williams) had that team playing all-out, every day. There is no
question that I am looking at Boston as the team we are going to
have to beat this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre then began to wax eloquent on the Yankees-Red Sox rivalry.
``It's a healthy thing for sports,'' he said. ``You ask the people
at Fenway, and they'll say it's always been there. They talk about
our rivalry with the Mets, but I don't feel it. I hate that
interleague play for that. They make more of it than it is. But
there's no question, with the Red Sox versus the Yankees. It's city
against city. You've got the connection of Babe Ruth. That's a
pretty good connection, considering that Babe Ruth saved baseball,
and he was a pretty important part of both organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forwarding a bit to recent past, as well as the present,
Torre lavished more praise on the Red Sox, saying he and his staff
had their eye on the Sox even before the famous Boston three-game
sweep in Yankee Stadium in September. ``I'm not saying they were
the most talented team,'' Torre said. ``I'm talking about how they
went about their business. The two teams that played the hardest,
all the time, were the Mets and the Red Sox. They battled for every
at-bat. They were tough outs. There was never a time where you sat
there and said, `We'll get through this inning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing in particular that Torre likes about the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Mary Ryan hint: three guesses, and the first two
don't count.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, OK?
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes everybody else on that staff better,'' Torre said.
``The rest of them know they only have to win 10 or 12 (games). It
was very nice that we didn't have to face him in Game 1 of our
(American League Championship) series. I realize that without his
pitching in the fifth game of the other series the Red Sox wouldn't
even have been there. We were 11-1 in the postseason, but I say we
should be thought of as 11-0. The game we lost to him shouldn't
count. The old aximom is always true: Good pitching will always
stop good hitting. I was fortunate enough to manage him in the
All-Star Game. It was no contest.''
</P>
<P>
   This week is the first anniversary of his prostate cancer
diagnosis. ``You definitely have a different outlook on life,'' he
acknowledged. ``When I get stressed now, I start thinking about how
it's just a game. But then it gets to be the bottom of the seventh,
and you would definitely sell your soul to get another win.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, be happy for Joe Torre that the Yankees pulled this game
out. It's 125 miles to Tampa, and even a big league manager might
not have had a wad on him large enough to cover that cab ride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
