<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LEBANON-WITHDRAWAL-BO     03-09 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-WITHDRAWAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LEBANON, UNEASE OVER VOID ISRAELI EXIT WILL LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIBIL, Lebanon _ A journey into Israeli-occupied southern
Lebanon, the last active front in the Arab-Israeli wars, begins on
a road so perilous that only one taxi driver will brave it.
</P>
<P>
   The potholed pavement winds into the craggy folds of the
nine-mile-wide zone occupied by Israel and its proxy militia, the
South Lebanon Army. Then it rises through exposed terrain where
Islamic guerrillas have repeatedly planted their weapon of choice:
roadside bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, especially in the south where the military and
diplomatic conflicts play out among Israel, Syria, and the
Hezbollah, people fear where they are headed at this crossroads of
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very afraid of the future here,'' said Boutros
Habib, 72, the lone taxi driver on the route he calls ``sure
death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what will happen down the road,'' Habib said.
``But right now people are fearing the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government made it clear
Sunday that with or without a peace agreement with Syria, Israel
will pull its forces out of Lebanon unilaterally in July. The
Cabinet vote was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, this looks like a victory for the Shiite
Hezbollah fighters who have long fought the Israeli occupation, and
it would seem to offer relief to an Israeli public weary of the
18-year military presence in Lebanon. But this is Lebanon, and
things are almost never what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a unilateral withdrawal has sharply increased
apprehension on all sides, creating a volatile situation that
analysts and diplomats warn could ignite into a wider conflict
between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Apprehension is most acute among the 2,000 soldiers of the South
Lebanon Army. The Israeli-paid Lebanese militia and their families
are seen as collaborators by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
``Party of God.'' The South Lebanon Army soldiers fear a bloodbath
of revenge once the Israelis are gone. A week ago, Hezbollah
sharply tightened the noose on the militia when it killed five
soldiers in one ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the zone, Lebanese and Israeli analysts alike are also
fearful. They worry that a unilateral pullout by Israel will be a
dangerous gambit in the diplomatic exchanges between Israel and
Syria, which has 35,000 troops in Lebanon and effectively runs the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Even Israel's deputy defense minister, Ephraim Sneh, warned last
week that if Israel withdraws without a peace agreement with Syria,
it is likely to be a bloody and incomplete solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chance of deterioration and broad confrontation,''
Sneh told reporters in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, Mohammad Raad, the head of Hezbollah's political
bureau, said: ``An Israeli withdrawal without an agreement with
Syria is not a serious proposal. This is not possible from our
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, a group of 500 active Shiite Muslim soldiers, took on
the vaunted Israeli military machine and dragged it into a
guerrilla war of attrition, and now the guerrillas appear to be on
the verge of winning.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that while some in Hezbollah trumpeted victory this
week following the Israeli Cabinet's pullout vote, the cheering was
muted _ the lack of enthusiasm a sign of how much Hezollah is
beholden to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   And in the strongest comments from either Beirut or Damascus
since the Israeli Cabinet vote, the Lebanese information minister,
Anwar Khalil, said this week, ``Either it is a comprehensive, just
and lasting peace, or it will not be peace at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Lebanon would give no guarantee of peace to Israel until
Syrian demands for the return of the Golan are satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say a wider crisis in the peace process is looming if
the interlocking triangle of negotiations among Israel, Syria, and
Lebanon comes undone.
</P>
<P>
   Without a peace deal, said a senior diplomat in the region, a
unilateral Israeli pullout could lead to an ``apocalyptic''
scenario in which Syria, deprived of the negotiating lever that the
occupation of south Lebanon provides, becomes desperate to find
another way to pressure Israel.
</P>
<P>
   One line of thinking holds that Syria, which is trying to secure
the return of the Golan Heights captured by Israel in 1967, could
turn to other militants, perhaps Palestinian groups based in
refugee camps, to reopen hostilities along Israel's northern
border. Hezbollah, the diplomat said, is likely to become
preoccupied with securing a political future in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, the diplomat said, Israel could be drawn back
into a wider conflict in Lebanon more directly involving Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very real fear here,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   While diplomats struggle for a solution to what some have called
Israel's Vietnam, those living in south Lebanon must deal with the
realities of a war zone.
</P>
<P>
   On the road in south Lebanon, Habib, the taxi driver, peered
through a splintered windshield as he navigated a three-mile
stretch of road where 70 roadside bombs have been planted in recent
years, killing more than 60 members of the South Lebanon Army or
civilians connected to them.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs are frequently planted in simulated rocks made of
plastic, then detonated by remote control. The sides of the road
are combed and cleared daily by specially equipped tractors. But
they can't check every rock.
</P>
<P>
   Habib pointed to an overturned South Lebanon Army personnel
carrier hit by a Hezbollah bomb last June, just as the militia
pulled out of the town of Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
   That episode is cited as a model of Hezbollah restraint
following Israeli and South Lebanon Army troop withdrawals. Islamic
fighters stayed out of the largely Christian town. There have been
no reports of reprisal killings. Many of the about 200
rank-and-file militia soldiers in Jezzine turned themselves in to
Lebanese authorities to face charges of treason. Most served six
months in prison, although some have been sentenced to several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Saad was a sergeant in the South Lebanon Army for 11 years
before he turned himself in last June. He served six months and
says he feels no shame about being viewed as a collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ashamed of trying to feed my kids,'' said Saad.
</P>
<P>
   Israel paid him $400 a month in cash for his services as a cook
in the barracks. Now he makes $200 a month serving tea in a
restaurant. The Lebanese government is doing very little to offer
economic opportunity in south Lebanon, he says. If Jezzine is a
model for the future, he adds, the future looks bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Jezzine, the road continues south into the center of the
occupied zone, which echoes daily with the thud of Israeli missiles
slamming into hillsides in the hit-and-run conflict with Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the mists of an early-morning fog rises the Crusader-era
fortress known as Beaufort Castle. The 12th-century fort, atop the
most strategic plateau in southern Lebanon, was once held by
Europeans fighting to reclaim the Holy Land from Islamic conquest.
Today the crumbling remains are a central command post for the
Israeli army and the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   The vulnerabilities Israel would face if it pulled out of
Lebanon without a solid peace agreement with Syria are evident as
the road turns close along the border. From there, the orange tile
roofs of the neat white-stucco neighborhoods of the northern
Israeli town of Tel Hi are plainly visible. An Israeli farmer can
be seen working the fields of a nearby kibbutz.
</P>
<P>
   The road then turns west into the little town called Dibil in
the rocky hills. It is the heart of South Lebanon Army territory
and the hometown of the militia's recently assassinated field
commander, Akel Hashem.
</P>
<P>
   The current escalation in the zone began with the killing of
Hashem, who was blown up while tending to a garden near his home.
While he was being buried, Hezbollah killed three Israeli soldiers,
then picked off three more in the following days. The deaths left
Israel mourning its fallen soldiers and watching television news
footage that looked hauntingly like Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bravado of some South Lebanon Army soldiers, there
are signs of growing panic even in a stronghold like Dibil. There
is an active black market in forged passport documents. South
Lebanon Army commanders are not expecting the sympathetic treatment
the Lebanese government allowed the rank-and-file soldiers of
Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Hashem, the slain commander, widow, Layya, was
dressed in black.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband always told us that Israel would not leave without
establishing security. I have to believe that now,'' she said,
surrounded by her two sons and Hashem's six brothers, all of them
prominent fighters in the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the brothers drove to to Hashem's grave on the edge of
town. They had to weld his crypt shut, they said, because Hezbollah
leaders have said that a collaborator like Hashem should not be
allowed to be buried in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As the taxi driver pulled away from the grave, he said: ``They
are afraid that in the end there will be no law here, just revenge
killing by one family against another. I can see that happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to really end the fighting is for both Israel and
Syria to leave us alone and let Lebanon rule Lebanon.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
