u e BC-BOOK-BRETHREN-BOS &LR;      03-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BRETHREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRISHAM'S ``BRETHREN'' DISAPPOINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BRETHREN 
By John Grisham 
Doubleday, 366 pp., $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Grisham's readers love him because he understands the
criminal mind _ and understands that some ``respectable'' people
like lawyers have criminal minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brethren,'' Grisham's 11th novel (not counting his
serial-in-progress), is unusual among his books because just about
everyone in it has a criminal mind. There are virtually no
sympathetic characters _ there's not a cute kid in sight, nor a
feisty woman, nor an innocent who has wandered into some
elaborately nefarious plot. Just about everybody is creepy, and the
suspense of the story lies in discovering whether the small-time
crooks are smarter than the big players.
</P>
<P>
   There are two plots that collide at an intersection no one saw
coming up. Three former judges, ``the brethren,'' are doing time in
a soft federal prison in Florida. They are providing for their
sunset years by running an extortion scheme. They have placed a
classified ad in a gay magazine, Out &AMP; About, and maneuver wealthy
closeted men into compromising correspondence with two nonexistent
troubled young men, Ricky and Percy, who are trying to get
straight. Then the brethren spring the trap _ pay up, or the
correspondence becomes public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the wheelchair-bound head of the CIA has determined
to buy a presidential election, and he has identified a pliable and
apparently spotless candidate in the House of Representatives. But
once the wheels have been set whirring, the CIA learns that its
candidate has been maintaining a private mailbox and an even more
private correspondence with ``Ricky.'' The interests of the CIA and
the brethren do not coincide, and what happens next is for Grisham
to know and his readers to find out.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of his readers are going to be disappointed. Not
because anyone reads Grisham for distinction of style. ``For an
early dinner he was whisked away to Mortimer's, the current power
place to be seen, just down Pennsylvania, where he met Elaine
Tyner, the lawyer running D-PAC. Over fruit and cottage cheese she
laid out the current financials of the newest PAC on the block.
Cash in hand of $29 million, no significant debt, money being
churned around the clock, coming in from all directions, from
everywhere in the world . . .'' _ Grisham is capable of going on
like that for pages.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the disappointment a matter of verisimilitude: It's been
a long time since plausibility was one of Grisham's strong points.
``The Brethren'' does push the envelope, though _ quite literally,
because one turning point of the story comes when someone stuffs a
card into the wrong envelope and mails it, just as a character
might have done in a creaky Gothic romance written by Mrs.
Radcliffe back in the 18th century. One would like to think that
blackmailing prominent gay men today wouldn't be quite as easy as
it would have been 50 years ago _ but then, one would like to
believe presidential elections can't be bought as blatantly as they
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   What one does expect from Grisham is a measure of excitement.
But who can get excited by characters this shallowly drawn and this
transparently wicked? They don't even seem to have fun being bad.
The moral lines are crazed, and there's not even an elementary
sense of rough justice in play. The book isn't exactly homophobic,
but it makes it seem that the victims of the extortion scheme are
getting what's coming to them, if only because they're closeted.
The mechanics of Grisham's plot are creaky and awkward; he writes
himself into corners, then tricks his way out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Grisham has a little wit and he lets it flash out occasionally.
``A liberal is a conservative who's been arrested,'' the writer
observes. His attempts at more sustained satire are pretty feeble.
The presidential hopefuls show up for a debate. ``Tarry wore a navy
suit his wife had selected, with the standard blue shirt and the
standard red and blue tie. Lake wore a dashing light brown suit, a
white shirt with a spread collar, and a tie of red and maroon and a
half-dozen other colors. The entire ensemble had been put together
by a fashion consultant, and was designed to complement the colors
of the set. Lake's hair had received a tinting. His teeth had been
bleached. He'd spent four hours in a tanning bed.''
</P>
<P>
   But basically it's hard for the reader to feel that Grisham
really cares about this book or anyone in it. Grisham's audience
wants to see hypocrites get what's coming to them, but there are
few hypocrites in this book; everyone is openly trying to
manipulate everyone else, and Grisham has forgotten who his
audience is. Until now, he has always delivered sympathy for the
little guy who is being screwed by the system, and that is what has
won him legions of readers who feel that way about themselves,
readers who mistrust the system and its official representatives _
the millions of us who repeat lawyer jokes. It's tricky to write a
book about people we love to hate if you don't also give us someone
we really like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
