<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WHIPSNAKE-HNS &LR;      03-09 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHIPSNAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT MOVES TO GUARD SNAKE HABITAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A shy black snake with yellow-orange racing
stripes known only in the valleys and foothills of Alameda and
Contra Costa counties just may stop or delay major construction
projects.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service plan to designate 406,708 acres
of Northern California as habitat for the rare Alameda whipsnake
may present roadblocks for big developments, environmentalists and
home builders said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for developers is that the remaining populations of
the fast-moving whipsnake live in places like the Hayward Hills and
Orinda, all hotly pursued for upscale housing subdivisions and golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary threat to the whipsnake is the proposed
development on private land,'' said Jeff Miller, a spokesman for
the Center for Biological Diversity in Berkeley. ``If you look at a
map of the East Bay, and you look at the large chunks of open
space, it almost completely corresponds with remaining whipsnake
populations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Biological Diversity and another nonprofit
organization, Christians Caring for Creation, sued the Fish and
Wildlife Service last year, winning protection for the snake's
habitat in an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for the new habitat, released Wednesday, would not
mandate preserves. However, it would make some land harder to
develop since builders typically need federal permits to change
streams or wetlands. And those permits could not be issued without
Fish and Wildlife Service approval.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is taking comments on the proposal and intends to
decide in September.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-foot snake that feeds on lizards, rattlesnakes, mice and
birds was listed as threatened under the Endangered Species Act in
December 1997. The snake isn't poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists know that its habitat has diminished but not how many
of the reptiles are left in the world. Clearing grassland,
chaparral and oak savanna with mechanical equipment for houses,
roads, grazing and fire control is a main killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the activities that are harmful to the whipsnake are
already being regulated just because of the fact that it's on the
threatened species list,'' said Patricia Foulk, a spokeswoman for
the Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   The snake's important habitats are in Alameda, Contra Costa,
Santa Clara and San Joaquin counties.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Bjerke, a spokesman for the Home Builders Association of
Northern California, said members were reviewing the documents and
would submit comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're concerned any time additional designations
are made,'' Bjerke said. ``Our builders do everything they can to
comply with the Endangered Species Act. However, it's not easy. The
amount of additional paperwork, in many cases, stops or delays a
project. Often times, when a particular animal or plant gains
endangered status, it becomes an expensive game to figure out
whether it exists on a particular piece of property or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that it was more than a game. ``When our native
species start to disappear, we have to start worrying about what
we're doing to the air, to the land, to the water,'' he said.
``Ultimately, if we can't keep intact healthy habitat for other
species, we're probably not keeping healthy habitat for
ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
