<HEADLINE>
STILL NOT USING USENET? TRY IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes I assume too much. Now that Internet use is routine, I
occasionally suppose that all of you know the basics, such as how
to find valuable information via Usenet.
</P>
<P>
   In January, I bemoaned the fact that few Internet newcomers get
onto the Usenet system. In came a host of e-mails from people who'd
love to sign on, if they only knew how.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday, I wrote a piece for The Boston Globe's tech Web
site at www.digitalmass.com, on Microsoft Corp.'s excellent Usenet
tech support system. Sure enough, more readers were bemused. What
is this Usenet thing, and how do I sign up?
</P>
<P>
   Very well, then. Back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   The Usenet is a worldwide computer network that was founded in
1979. Originally, it had nothing to do with the Internet; it was
just a way for graduate students at the University of North
Carolina and Duke University to send messages to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Usenet is made up of hundreds of thousands of
interconnected machines called news servers. Millions of messages
are published on these servers every day, and they can be read by
anyone with access to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Messages are divided into tens of thousands of categories,
called newsgroups. People find the newsgroup topics that interest
them, and then hang around to swap comments and complaints with
like-minded folk worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Newsgroups have odd-sounding names that tell you what kinds of
messages you'll find there. The names generally begin with an
abbreviation that hints at what the group is about; ``rec'' for
recreation, ``comp'' for computer-related issues, and so on. If
you're a trucker outraged by the high price of diesel fuel, you'd
post your gripes at misc.transport.truckers. If you're sick of
Windows 98 crashing all the time, go to
microsoft.public.win98.performance.
</P>
<P>
   Internet providers run their own news servers, where subscribers
post messages. Each server ``propagates'' copies of the messages it
collects, sending them to other servers, which pass them on to
still others. In the end, copies of one message will pop up on
Usenet computers all over the planet. It's a sloppy system, but it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Signing on to Usenet can take a little effort. First, you must
ask your Internet provider for the name of its news server. Mine,
for instance, is called news.monitortan.com. Then, you plug this
information into a newsreader _ the software that allows you to
read Usenet messages.
</P>
<P>
   Newsreaders are included with the two leading Web browsers,
America Online Inc.'s Netscape Communicator and Microsoft's
Internet Explorer. Both programs can be set up in about a minute,
even by a newbie. Plug in the news server information and a few
other details, like your e-mail address, then connect to the
Internet. There will be a delay of several minutes, while your
computer downloads a list of all available newsgroups. But after
that, you'll be ready to hit the Usenet.
</P>
<P>
   There are simpler alternatives. AOL subscribers can use that
service's built-in Usenet system. It's crude compared to a decent
newsreader, but it gets the job done.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are companies that offer Usenet service directly
through the Web. I wrote about one of them, Talkway, in January.
Talkway.com has found so little interest in their Usenet services
that they're branching out into other fields. The same has happened
at the granddaddy of Web-based Usenet services, Deja.com. Visit its
home pages and you'll see hardly a sign of anything Usenet-related.
Too bad, because they're excellent gateways for the Usenet
beginner.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Web-based Usenet access is limited. For instance, some
Usenet groups feature pictures and music clips embedded into
messages. There's a lot of porn here, but some decent stuff as
well. But you need a good newsreader program to decode these
messages; the Web-based Usenet services can't handle them.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a newsreader program won't notify you when someone
responds to one of your messages. The Web-based Usenet services
will fire off an e-mail to let you know. By the by, Deja.com
maintains an index of virtually all Usenet messages. So watch what
you write; it could come back to haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   Usenet isn't that difficult to use, but it still takes a bit
more effort than other Web-based discussion forums. That's one
reason it's languishing. But on the upside, Usenet's quality hasn't
been spoiled by a horde of ignorant newbies, as Internet pioneers
once feared. My favorite technology-oriented newsgroups are as good
as ever, largely because all you amateurs have stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, maybe this column wasn't such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
