<SLUG> BC-HUNGER-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADCASTERS' HUNGER STRIKE POINTS UP LOW-PAY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ In a rented camper parked outside the area's
top-rated television station, the face of KFTV Channel 21 is
growing gaunt.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Fermin Chavez, who reads the news on two daily broadcasts
and prerecords a third, is down 13 pounds or more. He's dizzy,
weak, and weary. With his camera-friendly cheekbones even more
angular than usual, viewers of the Spanish-language station have
started calling in their concern.
</P>
<P>
   Tugging at his now-loose waistband, Chavez says he would like to
gain back the weight. But even more, he would like to earn what he
considers a decent wage. He says he won't eat until his employer,
the local affiliate of Univision, stops paying starvation wages.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, along with a handful of other unionized on-air
personalities and station engineers, has been on a hunger strike
since Feb. 18. Taking a cue from Central Valley farmworkers who
have fasted to draw attention to their own issues over the years,
the newsroom employees decided to forgo solids in protest of
salaries low enough to qualify some of their families for food
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using us, exploiting us, and we knew we needed to do
something to get everyone's attention,'' said Chavez, 37, the
highest-paid protester at $32,500 a year, but the lowest-paid
anchorman in the Fresno market. ``I don't earn a quarter of what an
anchor for an English-language station earns for one hour of air
time a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The union representing fewer than two dozen anchors, reporters,
news writers, camera operators, and master controllers, has been
trying to hammer out a contract with KFTV since July. The contract
would be the local's first with the station, where employees voted
to join the union by a narrow margin in May 1999. But negotiations
have gone next to nowhere during more than 25 bargaining sessions,
said chief negotiator Carrie Biggs-Adams, who is subsisting on
fruit and vegetable juices and water. She has lost 10 pounds so
far.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the key issue has been wages, which station
employees say are out of line with the market share enjoyed by KFTV
and the earnings power exhibited by Univision, which is the
nation's leading Spanish-language network and is run by Henry
Cisneros. The journalists who compete against them, according to
union officials, earn double or more the salaries paid by KFTV,
which dominates Fresno's Spanish-language market and often tops the
overall ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's offering percentages that look like decent
increases, but they're making next to nothing, so it's a big
percentage of nothing,'' said Biggs-Adams. ``The money being
offered is appallingly low. It's not enough to live on.''
</P>
<P>
   KFTV, for instance, has offered to raise Martin Castellano's pay
to $23,000 a year, from $21,481, she said. Castellano, a master
control operator with 10 years on the job, supports his wife and
three young daughters on that salary _ an amount low enough to
qualify them for public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   As he put it, ``The only way I'll start eating again is for them
to pay me enough to eat.'' The union is also upset over what it
considers an overreliance on freelance reporters and other workers.
</P>
<P>
   As it has throughout the hunger strike, now in its 21st day, Los
Angeles-based Univision declined to comment on the protest,
referring calls to KFTV management in Fresno. KFTV, in turn,
reissued a two-paragraph statement saying the station is committed
to good-faith negotiations and is hopeful that a fair settlement
will be reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, newsroom employees are trying to pressure
management any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   They spent $385 for a table at a business luncheon where
Cisneros, a former US housing secretary, spoke Feb. 24. If he
agreed to meet with them, their plan was to eat. When he ignored
them, they sent their lunches back to the kitchen. Last weekend,
they picketed outside his Bel Air home. Cisneros was not there, so
they spoke with his neighbors instead.
</P>
<P>
   Daily, the employees take turns picketing in front of KFTV,
where their placards rest against the rented Phoenix Flyer camper
when not in use. Chavez, who has been instructed not to mention the
strike on the air, puts on a suitcoat and tie to go to work, then
puts in time on the picket line. People in the area are starting to
notice, the protesters say, honking when they drive past and
shouting encouragement at camera operators on assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Even before a doctor monitoring the hunger strikers began urging
them to eat, they had won wide support among other union members in
the heavily agricultural Central Valley, where about 40 percent of
the residents are of Hispanic descent. Three of the original eight
participants have dropped out of the hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the protesters, such as KFTV reporter Reina Cardenas,
grew up working in the surrounding grape fields, aware of the
struggles of their farmworker parents and the fasts that
now-deceased labor leader Cesar Chavez sometimes staged to draw
attention to their plight.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the current hunger strike came from Fermin Chavez,
the anchorman. But the inspiration came from KFTV management, which
sent pizzas to the pickets one day in December. Chavez says he was
so insulted by the gesture _ fast food rather than fair wages _
that he decided he would rather starve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is not to stop working, even if it's getting hard
to work,'' said Cardenas, 27, a $25,000-a-year reporter who has
dropped 8 pounds from her small frame and now worries about low
blood pressure and heart palpitations. ``What do we need to do to
get them to take us seriously? Do we have to die?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
