<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED HERO MAY TURN INTO GREENSPAN THE GOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan isn't winning any popularity contests on the
message boards at Raging Bull, an online financial site.
</P>
<P>
   One unhappy investor this week called him a ``scary old
codger.'' Another called him a ``wet noodle.'' Still another,
blaming the Fed chairman for this week's steep decline in the stock
market, said, ``The old fart ought to be doing audits for the
IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raging Bull crowd may not represent mainstream opinion, but
a few months from now, who knows? With his frontal assault on the
economy and the market, Greenspan the hero could yet turn into
Greenspan the goat.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman has said in no uncertain terms that the economy
is growing too fast and that it has to slow down. He has complained
on more than one occasion about the rising stock market and its
impact on consumer spending. He has even worried aloud that too
much productivity growth is contributing to an overheated economy.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he warned bankers about making loans on the
expectation that the strong economy will stay strong forever.
``Lending granted on that basis could have grave consequences,''
the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   This is standard stuff. When everyone is smiling and feeling
great, we expect the chairman of the Fed to act like Oscar the
Grouch. We also expect him to raise interest rates, which is just
what Greenspan has been doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tightening monetary policy is never a fun job, because to one
degree or another everyone gets hurt,'' said Mark Zandi, chief
economist at RFA Dismal Sciences. But this time around, in addition
to the home builders, home buyers, factory owners, and factory
workers who typically feel the weight of higher interest rates,
Greenspan could face attack from a new set of critics. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   --Investors. Higher interest rates have always been bad for
stocks. But with so many people invested in stocks, and with so
much attention focused on stock prices, the pain is likely to be
felt more intensely than in years past. Also different today is the
Fed's attitude toward stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has said that he is not targeting stocks, but it is
clear that a market correction would help him slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way he can conduct monetary policy without
factoring in the value of stocks,'' said Fred Breimyer, chief
economist at State Street Bank and Trust Co. in Boston If the
correction gets ugly, and the average American sees the decline
show up in his quarterly 401(k) statment, the investors at Raging
Bull won't be the only ones fuming.
</P>
<P>
   --Defenders of the new economy. Greenspan himself has been one
of the great champions of the new economy. He has given technology
the lion's share of credit for the strong growth and low inflation
of the past five years. But Greenspan has decided that even a new
economy cannot run this fast _ a view that may not sit well with
others.
</P>
<P>
   In a piece he wrote last fall for the Harvard Business Review,
William Sahlman, a Harvard Business School professor, likened
Greenspan to Chicken Little. Both, he said, ``fret for no good
reason.'' Sahlman argued that the new economy was stronger than
people realized and that it would do fine ``if the government just
manages to stay out of its way.''
</P>
<P>
   New economy advocates can point out accurately that inflation
remains hard to spot. In its own survey of economic conditions
released Wednesday, the Fed found only ``limited'' evidence of
rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   --Politicians. When Greenspan was confirmed for a fourth term in
February, only four senators voted against him. All were Democrats
who come out of the William Jennings Bryan populist tradition:
Tight money is bad for the little guy.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign season heats up, however, it would not be
surprising to see more politicians jump on the anti-Greenspan
bandwagon. Democrats and Republicans could join in the attacks,
especially if the economy looks as if it is headed south.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore can be counted on to support Greenspan.
As a mainstream Republican, George W. Bush probably will avoid
criticizing Greenspan, too.
</P>
<P>
   But should Bush begin to fall behind, his position could change.
``A politician who gets desperate might have more incentive to
attack the Fed,'' Zandi said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Greenspan remains quite popular. Many Americans
would agree with President Clinton, who recently praised the Fed
chairman's ``wise and steady leadership.'' And should Greenspan
manage to pull off a soft landing for the economy and the stock
market, he might even enhance his already legendary status.
</P>
<P>
   But if the landing turns out to be a rough one, all bets are
off. Under those circumstances, most people may feel like the
Raging Bull investor who, after watching Greenspan on CNBC
Wednesday, asked: ``Will someone get Greenspan off the screen?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
