<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IS HIS NEW SIDEWALK CRUMBLING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Just 18 months ago I installed a concrete sidewalk. Now the
tops are powdering and breaking up. I used a little salt the first
winter, but this winter I used salt substitute. What happened, and
how can I fix it so it won't happen again? Another walk that takes
a lot of salt treatment is 10 years old and in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   FARKIS TOOMAJIAN, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is amazing what salt will do. I used some concrete patio
blocks as raisers for a new step I built just last summer. These
blocks were old, but still in good shape. Or so I thought. We used
a little salt (maybe too much) in that area this winter, and two of
the blocks disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been a bad batch of concrete, both in your case
and mine. That is indicated by the fact that one of your walks is
in good shape despite salt treatment. The concrete might have had
too much cement, or too much water when it was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   To fix yours, you could try this: Sweep off all the loose
concrete and apply a bonding agent to the concrete, then appy a
thin layer of hydraulic cement or ordinary mortar, or a sand-mix
concrete. The powdering concrete may cause failure with this, too,
but the bonding agent may help keep things together. If it does
fail, then replace the misbehaving walkway areas.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman is fixing his problem by putting in new blocks,
before someone takes a tumble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I had a new roof installed last year, a ridge vent was
installed. There was no room for soffit vents, so they were not
installed. This winter, during the rather windy snowfalls, big
piles of snow appeared on the floor of the attic, right under the
ridge vent. There was enough to cause water stains on the ceilings
of the rooms below. How can I prevent that?
</P>
<P>
   MARY LASSEN, Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Any vent will leak water or snow, depending on the wind and
its direction. Most ridge vents have deep baffles, deep enough to
prevent the infiltration of rain or snow. Your type (Cobra) is a
quality vent, but may be too short to prevent such infiltration.
</P>
<P>
   Short of putting in a deeper-baffled vent, there are two things
you can try. Hang a long, shallow tray under the full length of the
ridge vent. Any invading snow and water will go onto the tray and
evaporate before the next storm. An alternative is to fasten a 1 x
4 or 1 x 3 board 3 or 4 inches downroof from the vent. This will
allow air to move, but will keep out blown rain and snow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. At a recent antique home show, a man was selling a central
air conditioning system designed to be noninvasive for antique
houses. It uses small vents in the ceiling and costs $18,000, which
includes two cooling coils, the usual outdoor compressor, and
enough vents to serve a 3,000-square-foot house. Is this feasible,
or is it overpriced? Also, there is a lot of dust in my house; the
man said that his system would reduce the dust by 85 percent. Is
that so?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY YOUNG, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is certainly feasible, and the high-speed system using
small ducts is a good one, but from your description I find that
price somewhat high. I had one coil and a compressor installed last
year for $2,700 (the ducts were already in position). An extra coil
might cost $1,000, and for you that will leave $14,300 for the
ductwork. That seems excessive. Even if you double the cost of the
units to $7,400, that would leave $10,600 for ductwork, still
excessive, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I don't subscribe to the view that an antique house
should have a special air conditioning system or none at all. If
the old house is tight enough, any system will work nicely _
without resulting in excessive moisture, because an air
conditioning unit also is a dehumidifier. Whatever the system, I
don't think the dust will be reduced much at all, although it will
be moved around faster. If there is a main filter on the unit, that
might help some, but not, I think, by 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
