<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; `SUPER TUESDAY' POST-MORTEMS &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND NOW THE SCORCHED-EARTH CAMPAIGN BEGINS... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates left standing in America's ``Super Tuesday''
primary showdown turned their guns on each other Wednesday, the
first shots in what is likely to be a scorched-earth election
campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ALAS-`BOREGUSH'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH VS. GORE: WHAT A CRASHING BORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So at least we now know where we stand. Following the electoral
fireworks of ``Super Tuesday,'' Bill Bradley, who put the liberal
cat among the cautious pigeons, and John McCain, the Vietnam
veteran who was unafraid to call a spade a spade, are both out for
the count. The disappearance of the two outsiders is a loss for
American politics. Both provided alternatives voices that needed _
and need _ to be heard. We are now left with the old Establishment,
scarcely shaken or stirred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORIAL) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By The Editorial Board of the Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ADIEU-MCCAINBRADLEY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCCAIN STOIC AS BLOWS RAIN DOWN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If everything had gone according to the script, it would have
been a truly arresting venue for a Republican victory bash: a funky
design center in the hottest area for gay nightlife in Los Angeles.
But, as became increasingly clear in the closing stages of John
McCain's presidential campaign, this script did not have a happy
ending. Not only did McCain fall far short of his rival, George W.
Bush, he stumbled particularly badly in the state in which he had
hoped for his greatest popular triumph, California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-STOIC-MCCAIN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSURGENTS LIT A PRAIRIE FIRE. WHY DID IT GO OUT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two rebel presidential candidates were set to bow to the
inevitable and exit the race after suffering crushing defeats in
Tuesday's primaries. The effective end to the campaigns of
Republican John McCain and Democrat Bill Bradley _ insurgencies
that had breathed new life into a flagging primary process and
galvanized hundreds of thousands of new voters _ was mourned by
supporters of both men Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Rupert Cornwell, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
