<P>
   JERUSALEM _ First corruption allegations, then a stunning defeat
in the Knesset, and now a sex scandal. The ground under beleaguered
Ehud Barak, Israel's prime minister, seems to be slipping a bit
more each day. Amidst all this, fears abound in Israel over what
will happen when Barak carries out his pledge to withdraw forces
from south Lebanon by July. Whether Barak will still be around to
see it is now becoming a matter of genuine debate. &QL;
