<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPEN LETTER TO A MOTHER OF YOUNG CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Carol or Sarah, Fran or Chloe,
</P>
<P>
   I can see you've had a bad day. No? A bad week, then. The baby
isn't sleeping through the night, your son chipped a bone in his
ankle, your daughter lost her glasses, and the car battery went
dead at the mall. Sounds awful. The teacher wants to talk to you
about your child's dyslexia, the two older ones fight all the time,
and the daily struggle over how much TV your kids can watch is
wearing you down to a nubbin.
</P>
<P>
   It's terrible. I know. It's unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   All you want is a night's sleep, an afternoon to yourself, 15
minutes alone in the bathroom. You'd be satisfied if the kids would
just throw their dirty clothes in the laundry basket, stop being so
fussy about what they eat, or quit nagging you to let them play
video games. You'd like just one day when everything went the way
you expected, when the baby sitter didn't let you down at the last
minute, when illness didn't fracture the plans you had so carefully
made and passionately anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   It's frustrating. I know. Motherhood is driving you crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Why did all the other parents get well-behaved, predictable,
happy-go-lucky kids while you were saddled with willful, moody,
opinionated offspring? They didn't. It only seems that way. You're
doing the best you can, and yet your daughter's friends are
tormenting her at school and your son is in a funk because the
coach plays favorites and never lets him into the game. All you'd
like is a little peace of mind and the feeling _ for just one hour
_ that things aren't always spinning out of your control.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to me. Let that fantasy go!
</P>
<P>
   This is your life, Mom, and the life of millions of parents just
like you. You can't count on anything going right ever. I can
gurantee that the minute you allow yourself to have an expectation,
it will be thwarted. Everything will conspire against the family
outing you've been looking forward to. Inanimate objects _ lost
shoes, a broken dishwasher, a missing sled _ will mock your
best-laid plans. While everything is in constant flux, holding on
to the idea of a family that operates without glitches is a move
that will leave you tense and disappointed every day of your life.
</P>
<P>
   You have to accept that what's happening is fine, as unlikely as
that may seem. Did you miss your plane and spend seven hours in the
airport in Phoenix with three children under 6? Breathe deeply.
It's perfect. Were you planning to have lunch with a friend you
haven't seen for months only to wake up to a snow day? It was meant
to be. You have to stop resisting life as it unfolds, no matter how
far afield it wanders from your desires.
</P>
<P>
   You have to learn to enjoy chaos.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend a lifetime unsuccessfully trying to change the
external world or you can alter your attitude. That's your only
choice. It may not be what you want, but it's the only chance for
happiness you have. Your response to events is the only thing that
is actually under your control.
</P>
<P>
   I can see how tired you are, but what's really wearing you out
is your own resistance to reality. Give up dreaming of some other
life. If at this very moment you could be in the Bahamas with a
nanny and a cook, your child would slip and cut his chin on the rim
of the pool, need stitches, and keep you up all night with his fear
and discomfort. There's no place to run, no paradise for mothers.
It's awful. I don't blame you for getting emotional. Go in the
shower and cry. Sit in a car in the driveway, roll up the windows,
and yell every curse you've ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Then choose to be happy. Invent a game called ``Making Hay While
the Rain Falls.'' Use your imagination, your cunning, your sense of
invention. Don't hesitate to ask for help. Think about what you
have to do to make the worst moments an adventure. Figure out ways
to soothe yourself, amuse yourself, center yourself in any
circumstance. Don't try harder. Choose peacefulness. Be good to
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Motherhood is nature's basic training, which will stand you in
good stead in years to come. It's a cram course in patience and
wisdom, and the tests keep coming until you get it right. Then they
keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   It gets easier, but I have to warn you _ it never ends.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just the way it should be. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
