<SLUG> BC-FALUN-GONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FALUN GONG MEMBERS TELL OF ARREST IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The moment Jein Shyue boarded the airplane
headed for California, he wanted to return to Beijing, even though
he had been jailed for three days because of his spiritual beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go back right now,'' said Shyue, a 44-year-old San
Jose materials engineer and follower of Falun Gong, the mystical
movement that is banned in China. ``Seeing practitioners with your
same mind-set is like looking at yourself in a mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Shyue, and Loretta Sukmei Lam, 42, of San Leandro, talked about
their experiences in detention after the Beijing police raided a
rented house Saturday night, arresting 18 followers, including
several people from Northern California and Australia. The
authorities arrested another Californian, Zhizhen ``Mary'' Qian, on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests followed months of police crackdowns in China
against Falun Gong, an outlawed mystical movement that has an
estimated 60 to 70 million practitioners worldwide. The police are
trying to stem protests during the national legislature's annual
session.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist regime reviles the Falun Gong movement as
subversive and cult-like.
</P>
<P>
   Shyue, a Taiwanese citizen in the process of attaining U.S.
citizenship, arrived in Beijing on March 1, intent on learning
first-hand about the recent tribulations of Falun Gong followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a different world over there,'' said Shyue, who began
practicing Falun Gong in 1995 in Boston. ``It's a life-or-death
choice for them.''
</P>
<P>
   With information gleaned by e-mail, Shyue met up with the
others. They had gone to China separately with plans to protest in
Tiananmen Square and to try to address the Chinese People's
Congress on Sunday. Though they never met before, the followers
felt a deep connection by sharing their experiences, meditating and
practicing their Falun Gong exercises, Shyue said.
</P>
<P>
   The police, pounding on their door around 8 p.m. Saturday,
shattered that peace. During the raid, Lam said, she saw police
officers use a stun gun on a San Jose resident, Yili ``Vennessa''
Wang, 28, for trying to keep them from taking the group's book on
Falun Gong meditations and exercises. They ransacked the house, she
said, and ordered everyone to gather their belongings before
shipping them off to a police detention center, where they were
interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   Lam speculated that the police had tracked them down through
their cellular phones, or else had noticed the large number of
people coming to and leaving the house.
</P>
<P>
   The followers continued to meditate afterward as they waited in
the dark cement cellblock, Shyue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them showed fear,'' Shyue said. ``We didn't do
anything wrong. We have no bad intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   The police separated Shyue and Lam, as well as David Sun, an
11-year-old Fremont boy, from the others, and sent them to their
department's foreign affairs division. They joined Falun Gong
followers from Washington, D.C., and Australia who had also been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very brave and independent,'' said Shyue, praising
David, who kept up the detainees' spirits with his lively,
talkative nature. ``He loves to talk to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the police escorted the group to the airport in
Beijing, forcing them to leave the country. Lam left first,
boarding a plane headed for Hong Kong. Shyue waited with Sun until
his mother, Zhizhen Qian, arrived at the airport in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, relatives and friends of the mother and son still had
no word of their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Lam and other the followers vowed to continue trying to raise
awareness with human rights groups and government officials of the
persecution of Falun Gong followers in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has no human rights,'' Lam said. ``It's very, very
bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
