<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1746 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-09 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERACTIVE SYSTEM IS THE NEXT WORD IN COMMUNICATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The television pictures were riveting: a wrecked car beside a
river far down a hillside from the highway. A Texas woman and her
baby were trapped inside.
</P>
<P>
   Using her cell phone, the mother managed to call for help and
then, because she did not know exactly where she had gone off the
highway she was traveling, stayed in contact with the police until
she heard their sirens wailing high above her.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long it would have been before the wreck was found had
she not had a cell phone, one police officer replied it would have
been found by hunters, weeks later. A second question, unasked but
with an obvious answer, is what would have happened had she been so
injured she could not use her cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this, and then say this word: telematics.
</P>
<P>
   Say the word, because it will be coming soon to a vehicle near
you.
</P>
<P>
   Telematics in-vehicle communications systems use satellites and
wireless networks to keep your vehicle in constant link with the
world outside your windshield.
</P>
<P>
   A telematics system in your car will notify monitoring centers
if your airbags deploy and where your car is at the time of the
wreck; you can use it to summon help in an emergency or for basic
roadside assistance; it will track your vehicle if it is stolen; if
you lock your keys in your car, you simply provide a code to the
monitoring center, and the center will unlock the car from afar;
even your doctor's name and your medical records can be kept on
file for use by emergency crews that come to your aid.
</P>
<P>
   And these are just some of the basics.
</P>
<P>
   Already offered or in the works are systems that let mechanical
problems in your car be diagnosed from the center; navigation
systems that can be downloaded, eliminating the need for discs;
systems that download MP3 music from your home computer; systems
that link you to radio stations nationwide, wherever you are, via
satellite; links to thousands of services from restaurants and
hotels to sports venues; and concierge services.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable amid the wonder of this blossoming electronic
benefit is that consumer awareness of these systems is relatively
low right now. General Motors, probably the leader in the field in
getting telematics into its vehicles, has installed about 100,000
units so far. They hope to top a million by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   A look at GM's system, called OnStar, is a vivid glimpse into a
future rapidly becoming the present. GM offers OnStar in models of
the Buick, Cadillac, Chevrolet, GMC, Oldsmobile, Pontiac, and Saab.
</P>
<P>
   You pay $695 for the system, then $199 per year for a safety and
security package, or $399 per year for more esoteric premium
service.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the 24/7 link with an OnStar center offers you:
</P>
<P>
   With the safety and security package you get MED-NET, which
stores your medical information and can provide it to emergency
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Accident assist links you to an adviser who helps with insurance
issues and police reports.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency, the driver hits a button, a monitor plots the
vehicle's position and sends help from the closest emergency
services provider, such as police or fire and rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Remote diagnostics are available if you see a warning light on
your instrument panel. You contact the center, and an operator
there signals the vehicle's computer. It transmits problem codes
and from this determines whether you need immediate roadside
assistance, if it is safe to keep driving until you can find a
garage, or if you can wait until your next regular maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   If your airbags deploy, an emergency signal is sent to the
OnStar center. An operator there will try to communicate with
occupants of the vehicle. If there is no response, or if you report
an emergency, the operator finds you via satellite and sends help.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle is stolen, you call OnStar and an operator
signals the vehicle, finds it, and tracks it. (I have read of other
systems that remotely set off the horn and make the lights flash _
certainly disconcerting to a thief who can't stop these attention
grabbers once they are activated.)
</P>
<P>
   If you get a flat or run out of gas, but don't feel safe leaving
your vehicle, OnStar will send the nearest GM service provider to
your aid.
</P>
<P>
   And if you lock your keys in the car, you call a toll-free
number, give them your code, and a cellular data call from the
operator to your vehicle unlocks the doors.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get a bit more esoteric, opt for Premium
Services. They include:
</P>
<P>
   --Information/Convenience Services in which OnStar advisers tell
you about local hotels, restaurants, and hundreds of other types of
services as you travel.
</P>
<P>
   --A navigation system that pinpoints your location and uses
voice direction to guide you on your way. It will even help you
find your way out of a traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   --And concierge service that will send flowers, book you into
hotels and restaurants, get tickets to sporting events and
entertainment venues, and help you plan a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It won't stop here, and GM certainly will not stand alone.
Already, Ford and Daimler-Chrysler are heavily into telematics.
</P>
<P>
   And once this is added to a voice-activated system that not only
makes phone calls for you, but also connects you to the Internet
for e-mail, sports scores, and stock, news, and weather reports,
the time you spend in your car will be not only safer, but also
time you can spend doing far more than waiting out the ride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
