<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      03-09 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NEW SUBURBAN, CHEVROLET TRADES BIGGEST FOR BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am rolling up Interstate 93 in New Hampshire, headed for a
week of skiing, watching from the high seat of the new Chevrolet
Suburban LT 1500 as traffic passes me.
</P>
<P>
   Two Honda Accords, one Toyota Camry, and a BMW328i, all with ski
racks atop, pass me in sequence. Seven people are rolling north in
those four cars. There are seven in my Suburban, plus ski gear and
vacation supplies. The Suburban is averaging just over 13 miles per
gallon. I don't know what the other four cars are getting for
combined gas mileage, but I am certain I hold the environmental
high ground.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Suburban is not the biggest SUV on the block anymore.
That title goes to the Ford Excursion, built in what may have been
the final leapfrog of automakers trying to outsize each other.
</P>
<P>
   Ford got bigger last year. Chevrolet did not respond in kind.
Instead, it took what was already a very large SUV and refined it.
Shortened it slightly, cut the wheelbase slightly, gave it a
tighter turning radius _ and somehow made it feel roomier inside
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   And in a week in which the furies of the weather subjected us to
snow, ice, freezing rain, warm rain, and mud, I learned that
Chevrolet's Suburban has also given us enhanced handling and ride
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, they've taken the angular lines of the last generation
of Suburbans and made the SUV a rounder beast: rounded at the
fenders, along the roof line, at headlights and tailights. Round
like the Chevy trucks on which it is based.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it continues to feature seats as comfortable as any
you'll find: leather buckets up front, twin leather buckets in the
middle, a wide leather bench at the back. They all are firm and
supportive, yet feel as soft to sit in as fine living room
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Headroom and legroom abound, and behind it all is a massive
cargo bin, accessed by a horizontally split rear hatch. You can
open just the window or the whole thing as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, there are noticeable improvements. The controls
for four wheel drive have been moved from the dash on the right
side of the steering wheel _ where they were often blocked by the
gearshift _ to left of the wheel, where they are more accessible.
Controls for the heated seats have been placed high on the doors,
where you can see them, from down on the sides of the seats, where
you couldn't. And the interior door handles are big, full-hand-size
grips that ought to become standard in trucks and big SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Because large rigs like the Suburban ought to be hauling big
groups on trips, Chevrolet has liberally sprinkled bins, cup
holders, door slots, and pouches throughout. There are plenty of
places for plenty of stuff, from Gameboys to road maps.
</P>
<P>
   So it's comforable, it's full of people and gear, but how are
you going to move it on down the road?
</P>
<P>
   No problem when you plunk in the 5.8-liter V8 engine that seems
to have endless power and bottomless torque.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.8 in the test model had 285 horsepower; an available 6.0
boosts that to 300.
</P>
<P>
   Handling all that power with quiet, seamless transitions is a
four-speed electronic automatic transmission. It is coupled with an
Autotrac transfer case, a computer operated setup that, when in
part-time four wheel drive or low-range four wheel drive, monitors
slippage and transfers torque front to rear as needed.
</P>
<P>
   The drivetrain is settled into a new three-piece modular frame
based on the Silverado truck platform. It's rigid center and rear
for truck-like strength (you do carry big loads in an SUV) while
the front section has crash caps, which absorb the energy of
frontal crashes.
</P>
<P>
   So now you've got big, heavy, and stiff. How's it ride? Better
than any large SUV out there.
</P>
<P>
   On frost heaves, through snow, over ice, down the highway, it
was smooth and chatter free. You could feel it resisting sway on
sharp backroads corners and it moved crisply from lane to lane with
the flow of traffic. This is where big SUVs ought to be headed.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet accomplished this by doing away with rear leaf springs
and setting up a rear suspension that uses upper and lower control
arms, a track bar for lateral axle control, a rear stabilizer bar
to reduce body roll, coil springs, and self-leveling shocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2500 model, you still get leaf springs, but that's more a
rig for heavy towing, so the 1500 setup is perfect for hauling
families, gear, and lighter towing.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet has also gone to disc brakes all around and stopping
is far smoother than it was with the former disc/drum setup.
</P>
<P>
   With SUVs, of course, manufacturers rack up their big profits on
options, and the Suburban tested was a perfect example of this. We
started with a base price of just under $29,000. Then we added,
among other options, a Preferred Option Group, which included a
9-speaker sound system, cruise, front and rear air conditioning,
power bucket seats, power windows, running boards, an OnStar
communications system and rear seat audio. Then came a trailer
package, bucket seats for the second row, a locking differential
rear axle, and offroad skid plates. That got us up to more than
$42,000.
</P>
<P>
   This is why manufacturers just love to sell big SUVs. After all,
what's a rolling home-away-from-home without all the amenities?
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches
</P>
<P>
   --The push-tab sliding horizontal rails on the roof racks. Makes
installing add-on gear very easy.
</P>
<P>
   --The lights built into the bottom of the rearview mirrors. They
come on when you use the remote entry button and illuminate the
doors and running board.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --In the last generation of the Suburban, passengers had little
round lights much like those above airplane seats. They were great;
kids could read in the back without disturbing the driver at night.
They've been replaced with standard rectangles that cast a broader,
more annoying beam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $28,627 &QL; 
Price as tested: $42,450 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 285/325 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 130.0 inches/219.3 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 78.8 inches/74.2 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 5,600 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 7/8 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
