<SLUG> BC-ALAS-`BOREGUSH'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW THE SCORCHED-EARTH CAMPAIGN BEGINS...  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This post-`Super Tuesday' 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is
from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two candidates in America's presidential
contest turned their guns on each other Wednesday, the first shots
in what is likely to be a scorched-earth election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While the votes in the party primaries were still being counted
on Tuesday night, Al Gore for the Democrats and George W. Bush for
the Republicans both presented themselves as the only figures who
could unify the country, while vilifying each other.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore beat Bill Bradley, his opponent for the
Democratic nomination, in every state which was at stake in
Tuesday's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Governor of Texas, emerged the clear victor on the
Republican side against Senator John McCain of Arizona. Though only
half the country has voted in primary contests, it is clear who
will represent each party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fight has just begun,'' said Gore, celebrating his victory
on Tuesday night. ``We need to build on our record of prosperity.
We don't need to go back to where we were before,'' he said, a
reference to the Republican era in the White House which preceded
Bill Clinton's election.
</P>
<P>
   The last Republican president was George Bush, father of the
current candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were challenged and we met the challenge,'' said Bush. ``We
are ready, and I believe our country is ready, to return exiled
honor to the White House,'' a reference to the many ethical
scandals surrounding the administration of Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that both won so strongly suggests a close and
hard-fought campaign. The latest opinion poll, in the Wall Street
Journal on Tuesday, shows them neck and neck in a contest against
each other; other polls show Bush's once substantial lead cut to
single figures. But the general election in November is still
months away.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leaned heavily on the support of the party's right in his
campaigns, especially in South Carolina, a bitter and controversial
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion groups spent $340,000 attacking McCain on Tuesday
alone. While it helped Bush to cement the party hard core, this may
cause problems as he seeks more moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faced a less serious fight against Bill Bradley, and has
less ground to cover as he shifts to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that both candidates are in the political
center, in a time-honored tradition they will now seek to paint
each other as ideologically-crazed zealots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is way to the left. Bush is right in the center of the
Republican Party and right in the political mainstream of the
American people,'' said Haley Barbour, a Bush advisor and prominent
Republican money man.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attacked Bush for ``smear telephone calls from the
extremist right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates desperately need some of the support which went
to John McCain, who pulled in voters from Republican and Democrat
parties as well as independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those Republicans and independents out there whose heroes
are Theodore Roosevelt and Abraham Lincoln, to all of you I say as
well, join with us. Our campaign is now your cause,'' Gore said, a
direct appeal to McCainites.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president immediately took up the cudgels on behalf of
campaign finance reform, McCain's signature issue, calling on the
Republicans to ban ``soft money'' _ cash from interest groups and
companies that can be used to fund national campaigns. The
television ads which make American elections so prohibitively
expensive should also be forsworn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to ``make this a campaign of ideas and not
insults and conduct it in broad daylight instead of with these
secretly funded special interest attack ads that distort and
dishonor the process of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a clear assault on Bush, whose friends attacked McCain
using privately-funded ads. McCain lashed out at Bush's ``sleazy
Texas buddies,'' and Gore clearly wants voters to remember that.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also moved swiftly to heal differences with Bradley. ``I
have been moved and touched by the strength of his commitment to
healing divisions in this country,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has fought a bitter battle against McCain and will find it
harder to reach out to his opponent. ``I congratulate John,'' he
said on Tuesday night. ``We have our disagreements, but I respect
him and his commitment to reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Respect, however, has not been the most notable quality of the
Republican battle. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
