<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURGENTS-LOSS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURGENTS LIT A PRAIRIE FIRE. WHY DID IT GO OUT?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This timely 1,050-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two rebel candidates for the U.S. presidency
were set to bow to the inevitable and leave the race after
suffering crushing defeats in Tuesday's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Closeted with their families and advisers at opposite ends of
the country for much of Wednesday, they were expected to make
formal announcements Thursday that their insurgencies, which had
generated so much excitement and inspired record turnouts from New
England to California, were at an end.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former New Jersey senator, who won not a
single state, let it be known that he would throw in his lot with
Vice President Al Gore when he announced his formal withdrawal
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain of Arizona, whose duel with George W. Bush
had become particularly bitter and personal in its latter stages,
was still considering his position, despite this chummy invitation
from Bush in a breakfast television interview Wednesday: ``I would
say, John, let's team up and let's win. Let's beat Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not, as Bush then clarified, an offer of the vice
presidential slot to McCain, just a call to unity.
</P>
<P>
   His team had hoped that McCain would be able to come close
enough to Bush in a sufficient number of states to justify
continuing his challenge, but all the big prizes _ California, New
York and Ohio _ eluded him on Tuesday, leaving him with victories
only in four of the five small New England states and decisively
defeated elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The effective end to the insurgencies that had breathed new life
into a flagging primary process and galvanized hundreds of
thousands of new voters was mourned by supporters of both men.
</P>
<P>
   Radio talk shows and the Internet buzzed with the protests of
disconsolate voters, pledging to vote for no one in November rather
than betray their heroes.
</P>
<P>
   America's vast army of media pundits, however, was downbeat,
dismissing the end of the rebellions as only to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   No insurgent, they pointed out, has won the Republican
presidential nomination since 1964, and Barry Goldwater's win then
was possible only because the party establishment was in chaos.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, it was noted, even so popular and well
supported a figure as Edward Kennedy was unable to buck the system.
</P>
<P>
   The organizational advantage enjoyed by Gore as vice president
and Bush as the early anointee of his party hierarchy was
formidable. The youth and enthusiasm of the insurgents' campaign
staff could not compensate for the presence on the ground of Bush
and Gore campaign workers in practically every constituency for
weeks and even months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and McCain had sharp professionals masterminding
their campaign strategies; when the pace of primaries accelerated
and campaigns had to be waged simultaneously in far distant parts
of the country, however, there was nothing to having the support of
the local trade union or Republican machine.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had made a failed bid for the union machine; but both he
and McCain were treated as pariahs by their respective parties.
</P>
<P>
   They could count the number of Congressional and state
government supporters only in low single digits, and while this
proved a perverse advantage to McCain in Michigan, where he
benefited from a protest vote against the state governor, the
opposite was more often true.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the times, perhaps, money was less of an advantage
to the front-runners than establishment clout. Bush's record 70
million dollar war chest was down to its last 10 million before
Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley tapped into new sources of money via the
Internet. Bradley also attracted wealthy sponsors from Wall Street
and Silicon Valley, and if money were the only consideration they
could both plausibly continue their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns, however, made mistakes, and Bradley's in
particular suffered an eerie sequence of sheer bad luck. Bradley's
first and biggest mistake, with hindsight, was not to rebuff and
keep rebuffing the malevolent misrepresentation of his health
proposals that was put about by the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Once pensioners, the poor and ethnic minorities were given the
idea that Bradley's plans would make them worse off, Bradley lost
some of his key constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain learned from Bradley's early mistake, and responded to
each and every underhand attack from the Bush campaign. There were
drawbacks to that tactic, too, however, as McCain risked being seen
as excessively combative.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the ethical high road, as both insurgents tried to do,
was the key to much of their initial support. But it left them
damned if they retaliated in kind to their opponents' so-called
``negative advertising,'' and damned if they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Bradley was starting to get his campaign back on track,
he was forced to cancel two days of a West Coast tour because of a
heart problem.
</P>
<P>
   However he might insist that an irregular heartbeat was no
impediment to being president, it dented his image as a super-fit
former athlete and his failure to disclose it before damaged his
reputation for straight talk.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, his luck just seemed to run out: the heating on a
chartered plane failed, another developed engine trouble; and at
his final rally the lights fused.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest piece of bad luck, however, was John McCain. In the
early primaries, the two were essentially competing for many of the
same voters: independent-minded and nonaffiliated voters with an
interest in changing the political system.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's heroic life history and his talent for ``connecting''
with voters gave him an immediate advantage over Bradley. Bradley
lost New Hampshire to Gore by only 4 percent; McCain beat Bush by
19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If even a few of those votes had gone to Bradley, the whole
course of the race might have been different.
</P>
<P>
   In winning over Bradley's voters, however, McCain arguably lost
his own. His appeal to independents and Democrats came at the
expense of his appeal to mainstream Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Among McCain's devoted supporters, many are already pressing him
to leave the Republican Party and run for the presidency as an
independent. Even as he conceded defeat on Tuesday night, however,
McCain repeated his insistence that he was a loyal Republican and
would stick with his party. That is unlikely to change overnight. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 1,050-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
