<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-JUDGES (Washington) _ After a bitter debate, the Senate
is expected to approve the controversial nominations of two
Californians, U.S. District Judge Richard Paez of Los Angeles and
civil rights advocate Marsha Berzon of San Francisco _ to the U.S.
9th Circuit Court of Appeals. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Tackling the issue of youth
violence in the wake of several fatal school shootings across the
country, a bipartisan group of lawmakers issues a report calling
for more programs aimed at identifying troubled children early and
addressing their mental health needs. BY ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In any war, political or military, a
good general has an exit strategy. For Bill Bradley, that was easy.
With no primary victories, he had to pull out of the presidential
race. But for Sen. John McCain, there are more options. He
suspended his campaign, but he can still be a force in the
Republican Party. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-RETURN (Washington) _ When John McCain returns to the
Senate after a presidential campaign in which he accused his
colleagues of being corrupted by special interest money, he is
likely to face plastic smiles and cold shoulders but enjoy greater
clout because he whipped up crucial support from independent
voters. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore could learn a lesson from
the example of John F. Kennedy, who selected his chief opponent for
the presidential nomination, Lyndon Johnson, to be his vice
presidential running mate. Johnson's knowledge of the ways of
Washington and his ideas on helping the people were valuable to
Kennedy. Similarly, Bill Bradley could help Gore. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON.
