<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Sedona, Ariz.) _ Sen. John McCain ``suspended'' his
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination on Thursday and
wished his rival, Gov. George W. Bush, well, but stopped short of
endorsing him. And in an effort to make sure that his reform
message would continue to have resonance in the party, McCain said
he would hold on to his delegates until this summer's convention.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Denver) _ Gov. George W. Bush continues campaigning in the
mountain states ahead of Fridays primaries. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY (West Orange, N.J.) _ Bill Bradley withdrew from the
race for the Democratic presidential nomination on Thursday,
leaving the field to Vice President Al Gore. ``Following the
results of Tuesday's primaries, I have decided to withdraw from the
Democratic race for president,'' Bradley said. Bradley pledged his
support for Gore, saying, ``Now is the time for unity.'' But he
said he would not yet release the delegates that he had won. By
James Dao and Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bradley and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   More to kum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (Washington) _ House votes on raising the federal
minimum wage to $6.15 an hour from $5.15 an hour, and on a
Republican $122-billion tax break bill for businesses and the
wealthy, which President Clinton has said would force him to veto
the entire package. The vote expected at 7 p.m. By Eric Schmitt.
(900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-JUDGES (Washington) _ The Senate approves two more
federal judges as Vice President Al Gore cancels a campaign trip to
be in Washington in case his vote is needed to break a tie. By Neil
A. Lewis. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FRAUD () _ Federal officials issue an annual report on
improper Medicare payments to doctors, hospitals and nursing homes.
The report says that fraud, waste and abuse have leveled off, after
declining sharply for two years in a row. By Robert Pear. (900
words)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-MILITARY (Washington) _ The murder of an Army private was
the most severe example of a record 968 incidents of anti-gay
harassment in the military last year, according to a legal group
representing gay men and lesbians. By Elizabeth Becker. (650 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KY-POLICE-SHOOTING (Louisville, Ky.) _ A police shooting
incident with eerie echoes of New York City plunges Louisville into
open doubts about the loyalty of its police force after the mayor
fires the police chief and his nine field commanders throw down
their badges in protest. Open standoff with rank and file's police
union follows the chief's giving departmental awards to two cops
who shot an unarmed suspect 22 times. By Francis X. Clines. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ A hearing began Thursday today to determine
whether a federal court has jurisdiction over the custody of Elian
Gonzalez. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-LABOR (Undated) _ The AFL-CIO releases a survey on issues
most important to women. By Steven Greenhouse. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRADE (Washington) _ What are the chances of the China
trade bill getting through Congress? Secretary of Commerce Daley,
President Clinton's point man to get the deal approved, said
Thursday that right now the administration does not have the votes.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ Former Chancellor Kohl surfaces. At a
news conference, he tells of the money he is raising to pay the
fine levied on his Christian Democratic Party for the illegal
campaign gifts he accepted. He says he has mortgaged his house, but
still refuses to name the secret donors to the fund. By Roger
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Sharm el-Sheikh) _ The Palestinians' Arafat,
Israel's Barak and Egypt's Mubarak meet. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CRASH (Moscow) _ A private passenger jet crashed Thursday
while taking off from Moscow's main airport, killing all nine
people aboard, including Artyom Borovik, a well-known Moscow
journalist, and Ziya Bazhayev, president of the Oil Alliance
company. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRANSPLANT-FRAUD (Undated) _ Talking to the doctors who
uncovered the fraud of the South African researcher who claimed to
have the only data that showed bone marrow transplants worked for
women with breast cancer. The researcher will go on trial Friday.
By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMF-KOHLER (London) _ More developments on Horst Kohler,
president of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
who is Germany's new candidate to head the International Monetary
Fund. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ the weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were little changed by mid-afternoon.
At 1:55 p.m., EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 2
points, while the Nasdaq composite index was up 87 percent.
Treasury prices were slightly higher. Crude oil was at $31.87 a
barrel. European markets were mixed: London was up 1.92 percent and
Frankfurt was down 0.64 percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed down
0.53 percent and the Hang Seng ended down 1.75 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER (Munich, Germany) _ Deutsche Bank announces
that it has agreed to buy Dresdner Bank for $29 billion in stock in
Germany's biggest banking takeover, creating a company focused on
investment banking and wealthy private clients. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
