<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WOUNDED-EAGLE-HNS &LR;      03-09 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOUNDED-EAGLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WOUNDED EAGLE RETURNS TO SAN FRANCISCO ZOO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Bobbie flew away in 1994, little did the
people at the San Francisco Zoo realize that they would someday be
reunited with the beautiful bald eagle they had watched being born.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years later, Bobbie is back. But he will no longer be
able to fly because in January someone shot him, piercing one of
his wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saddens everyone,'' said Kathy Hobson, an aviculturist at
the San Francisco Zoo. ``It took a thoughtless person to put an end
to this bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bobbie survived the bullet wound from a .22 caliber
rifle, part of his wing was removed, and he will no longer be able
to fly or breed as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The bald eagle is a powerful bird distinguished by its white
head and tail contrasted by its dark brown body. Though once
endangered, the bald eagle population in the lower 48 states has
increased considerably in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The bird is also found in greater numbers in North America,
nesting on both coasts from Florida to Baja California.
</P>
<P>
   Hatched at the San Francisco Zoo, Bobbie was a week old in April
1994 when he was placed in a nest in Catalina Island as part of a
recovery project. He was soon adopted by a pair of bald eagles.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Zoo's Avian Conservation Center, home of the
Bald Eagle Recovery Project, is the only large-scale captive
breeding program for bald eagles in the Western United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, 36 chicks have been successfully hatched from eggs
brought from nests in Catalina or breeding pairs at the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie was one of them. He was released on Catalina Island at
the same time as another bald eagle chick from the program.
</P>
<P>
   When he was found wounded in January near Bakersfield, he ended
up in the care of veterinarian Thomas Banks, who found
identification bands on the eagle's right and left legs linking him
to the zoo's monitoring program. The bird was returned to the zoo
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie will be quarantined as a precaution for the next 30 days
before visitors will be able to get a glimpse of him, zoo officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo veterinarian Freeland Dunker has performed general tests on
Bobbie and said the quarantine would help him adjust to his new
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're feeding him a variety of things, including fish,'' zoo
spokeswoman Nancy Chan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbie's permanent home at the zoo, once he's taken out of
quarantine, will be on Eagle Island, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bald eagles live a relatively long time. The longest known life
span for a bald eagle living in the wild was reported near Haines,
Alaska, as 28 years old. Bald eagles from Arizona are known to have
exceeded 12 years of age. In captivity, bald eagles may live 40 or
more years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
