<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX     03-09 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Public that favors gun control held hostage by NRA
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After just about every notorious new, senseless shooting spree _
most recently the death of that six-year-old girl, those five shot
by a Pennsylvania man in anti-white rage _ my wife asks how many
more must die before we get sensible gun control. The question is
only rhetorical, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be because the answer is already in: the numbers do
not matter because the powers resisting gun control simply don't
care about them. There is no elusive, magical body count out there
that will trip legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   If there were, we would have comprehensive control now, instead
of our current mishmash of laws. After all, year in and year out,
we lose more of our folks to gunfire than most other comparable
democracies combined.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton keeps pointing out, last year we lost some
4,700 children in gun deaths _ more than the child gun deaths in
the next 25 countries altogether. Even that can't unstick beholden
members of Congress from gun-lobby money and the votes promised
with it. (Or stiffen the craven against the threat implied to those
who disdain it.)
</P>
<P>
   So, although the public overwhelmingly, though inchoately,
supports gun control and has for decades, the nation remains
hostage to the National Rifle Association's permanent hysteria _
any control is a step toward federal storm troopers kicking in your
door and snatching your guns! _ and hostage to the big money and
the power politics that support the hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the current stand-off. The House and Senate passed
mild-to-meaningless controls last year, but there were signal
differences over one feature that could really matter: provisions
to close a loophole that allows sales at gun shows without
background checks. The Senate version plugs the loophole. The House
version pretends to.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference is necessary to resolve the
differences, and the president recently called in leaders of both
chambers and urged action. Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the key
player, said no.
</P>
<P>
   (The NRA remains bee-busy in the state legislatures, too. It was
instrumental just days ago in killing a bill in Georgia that would
have held adults liable for negligently leaving firearms where kids
could get to them easily.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, just like my wife, recently asked, ``How many more
people have to get killed before we do something?''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, when it is expected to, dutifully tsk-tsks over gun
victims, but in truth it doesn't really give a hoot about them. If
it did, it would be trying to prevent gun crime. Instead, its
response to every new gun outrage is only to call for putting
someone in prison, though that is self-evidently not a deterrent
and is cold comfort to the dead.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of fussing in the political atmosphere about
victims' rights. The most important right is the right to be given
a fair crack at not becoming a victim in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   On average, we're sacrificing 13 kids a day to keep the NRA
happy. It's political paganism.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
