<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OSCAR-BESTACTRESS-TEX     03-09 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-BESTACTRESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS' DARLING VS. `AMERICAN' INSIDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The safest bet to make in the Best Actress race at this year's
Academy Awards: Whoever wins will not have won before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, of the five nominees, only one _ Meryl Streep _ has
even been nominated for Best Actress before (Julianne Moore and
Annette Bening were previously nominated for supporting roles).
</P>
<P>
   Streep received her record-tying 12th nomination _ all but two
for lead roles _ for ``Music of the Heart,'' a sentimental,
fact-based drama that met with decidely mixed critical and audience
response. Actually, it met with little audience response; according
to the Internet Movie Database, the October 1999 release hadn't
even grossed $15 million by mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   It's often said that Streep is nominated just for being in a
movie, and many of the films she was nominated for _ ``One True
Thing,'' ``Postcards From the Edge,'' ``Ironweed'' _ are uneven
enough to give this credence. That she was nominated this year is
indicative of an ongoing problem in the motion-picture industry:
not enough strong lead roles for actresses.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing that can be said for this year's roles is that
nobody was nominated for playing a hooker, but aside from Streep's
music teacher, the characters weren't exactly what you'd call nice
people. The nominated roles include a woman who practiced deception
for deception's sake (Hilary Swank, ``Boys Don't Cry''); a single
mother whose solution to all her problems is to run away (Janet
McTeer, ``Tumbleweeds''); an insufferable homemaker/real-estate
agent (Annette Bening, ``American Beauty''); and an adulterer
(Julianne Moore, ``The End of the Affair'') _ although she
experiences a life-changing crisis that helps her find God.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moore is excellent in ``The End of the Affair'' as a
British aristocrat's wife who becomes involved in a torrid affair
with a novelist (Ralph Fiennes), you can scratch her off your list
of likely winners. Columbia Pictures, which released the movie,
never seemed to know what a good thing it had _ it was one of last
year's best films _ and botched the initial marketing, opening the
movie in limited release with little fanfare. When Columbia wised
up and widened the release, it was too little, too late, and even
Moore's nomination couldn't inspire the studio to give the movie a
bigger push.
</P>
<P>
   With Moore and Streep out of the running, the competition comes
down to a three-way race among Bening, McTeer and Swank. If you
were to go by previous awards, Swank would appear to have the edge
for her performance in ``Boys Don't Cry'' as Teena Brandon, a young
Nebraska woman who posed as a man named Brandon Teena and was
eventually murdered because of the deception. Swank won Best
Dramatic Actress at the Golden Globes, and was honored by the Los
Angeles Film Critics Association, the New York Film Critics Circle
and the Dallas-Fort Worth Critics Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Oscar voters don't think like critics, and ``Boys,'' though
much-admired, was little seen _ so far, it has grossed even less
than ``The End of the Affair'' or ``Music of the Heart.'' And
though Swank is amazing (her co-star Chloe Sevigny, a Best
Supporting Actress nominee, is even better), the movie may be too
brutally raw for voters' tastes, and that will work against Swank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tumbleweeds,'' on the other hand, is easy to take _ if you can
get past McTeer's character, whose flightiness is more annoying
than charming (she really makes you empathize with her
long-suffering daughter, well-played by Kimberly Brown).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the critical praise McTeer received hinged on the
knowledge of her range: She's a British stage actress who won a
Tony Award for her performance in Henrik Ibsen's deadly serious ``A
Doll's House,'' then made her movie breakthrough playing a
comically free-spirited Southern American mom. Judging from
``Tumbleweeds''' lackluster box office, audiences didn't much care;
don't expect the academy to care much either, even though McTeer
won a Golden Globe for Best Actress in a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves Bening, who has more on her side than her
appearance in one of last year's most-acclaimed movies. For one
thing, ``American Beauty'' was a hit (grossing more money than the
other four Best Actress movies combined) whereas Bening's
competition starred in movies that few people saw (and just because
the films were nominated doesn't mean that Oscar voters will
actually ``watch'' them). For another, DreamWorks has been smarter
than any other studio when it comes to Oscar marketing _ even
before ``Beauty'' received its seven nominations, the studio gave
it a huge, renewed Oscar-season re-release.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, is that Bening is much more of a
Hollywood insider than Swank and McTeer, and her marriage to Warren
Beatty should earn her a lot of votes just because of all the
friends they have in the community. She might not be at the March
26 ceremony because she's pregnant, and her baby is due right
around Oscar night. Academy Awards voters are a sentimental bunch,
and they're likely to give her an unusual baby-shower present.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Bening scores one of ``American Beauty's'' many
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Personal pick: Although ``Boys Don't Cry'' eventually
degenerates into tabloid sensationalism, Swank is never less than
compelling in her gender-twisting role.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
