r e BC-TV-MAMMOTH-REVIEW-SFC     03-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAMMOTH-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAMMOTH UNDERTAKING IN SIBERIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, they're not exhuming Orson Welles.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bona fide woolly mammoth in ``Raising the Mammoth,'' a
two-hour Discovery Channel special televised worldwide on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a woolly mammoth that died 20,000 years ago was
pulled from the Siberian permafrost and helicoptered 200 miles to
an ice cave, where its flesh is getting a slow thaw and its hair a
nice blow-dry.
</P>
<P>
   The thing was huge _ one mammoth could equal the weight of 130
men, or maybe 50 guests on ``Jerry Springer'' _ and might have
drowned after slipping into a pond. It was a 47-year-old male, not
many years away from a natural death.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think of it as Jocko. But its name, now if not then,
is Jarkov, for the Siberian nomad family that found its tusks
protruding from the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Jarkov isn't the only mammoth ever to be unearthed. Still, he's
an impressive specimen of a species that's been extinct for 10,000
years.
</P>
<P>
   So impressive that he might be cloned. Or possibly bred, in
absentia, with an Asian elephant to create a hybrid. An elemoth,
maybe?
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel helped to finance the mammoth expedition,
which was led by French explorer Bernard Buigues, so it could film
Sunday's special.
</P>
<P>
   It's always interesting how these programs find scientists who
specialize, passionately, in some particular creature. Here, a few
mammoth lovers have dreamed for decades about stroking the wiry
hairs of a mammoth. Their dreams are fulfilled, and they behave
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They even get, oh boy, a good whiff of Jarkov's dung and urine.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery Channel's job is to fire the public imagination.
It doesn't help that chipping away at permafrost doesn't exactly
make for riveting TV, or that the special ends with most of Jarkov
still encased in a block of ice.
</P>
<P>
   But really: 20,000 years, extinct species, big tusks, lousy
weather, Regis Philbin. All right, no Regis, but it's hard to
suppress a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The cable channel tries to help with occasional shots of
computer-generated mammoths, loping along like elephants, and with
a sometimes overwrought script.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tempest sweeps across the tundra like a legion of arctic
ghosts,'' the narrator says at one point, and you might wish they'd
put a tusk in it. The voice on my screening tape was a woman's,
though it's to be actor Jeff Bridges' voice in the final version.
</P>
<P>
   The program is due to be televised Sunday in 146 nations and 23
languages.
</P>
<P>
   About the cloning, many experts are pessimistic because DNA,
even frozen, deteriorates with the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   Still, who knows? We might eventually have woolly mammoths for
house pets. My bet is they'd make excellent guard animals, but you
might think hard about your china cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &QL; 
-0- &QC;
<P>
   When Kathie Lee Gifford announced her impending departure from
``Live with Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee,'' one reason she cited was that she
didn't want her son Cody, 10, exposed to any more public attention.
</P>
<P>
   That puzzled many observers, who tried to recall anyone but
Gifford herself exhibiting the slightest public interest in the
kid.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, along comes the movie ``Model Behavior'' on ABC's ``The
Wonderful World of Disney'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Kathie Lee Gifford and, in the cameo role of a
boy being groomed to be a photo model, a 10-year-old actor of,
shall we say, indeterminable origin. Sometimes you just shake your
head and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lucky you if you get the TV Land cable channel, because ``The
Honeymooners'' is returning for another round on television.
</P>
<P>
   After nightly specials at 7 and 10 p.m. each weeknight next week
_ a new documentary, a collection of sketches from Jackie Gleason's
``Cavalcade of Stars'' and two unusual ``Honeymooners''
installments _ the so-called ``classic 39'' episodes of the show
reach TV Land.
</P>
<P>
   First is a 48-hour marathon beginning at, gulp!, 3 a.m. on March
18. Then, starting March 20, the 39 filmed episodes will be shown
on TV Land's regular nightly lineup at 8 and 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It's seminal television comedy. And still funny after half a
century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a show that's new and worth a peek is ``Cover Me,''
which debuted last weekend on the USA Network. The second episode
is Sunday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Shaun Cassidy and purportedly based on a true story,
the series is an odd mix of drama and comedy as it traces the
adventures of an entire family that went undercover for the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as ``The Wonder Years'' meets ``The Sopranos.''
Weird stuff, but nicely cast and a handsome show.
</P>
<P>
   You might almost think that there was something out of the
ordinary in Cassidy's own childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
