<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PLANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDING AVIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Senate has come close to meeting an obligation to air
travelers by reaching a compromise with the House to increase funds
for aviation. The move comes at a late but appropriate time, just
after the Federal Aviation Administration released its forecast of
major growth in commercial, cargo, and general aviation over the
next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise increases outlays in the fiscal 2001 federal
budget to $12.7 billion from the current $10 billion for a wide
range of airport projects and improved safety systems essential to
support existing activity as well as projected growth.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and successive administrations have tended to underfund
aviation activity, spending only about 80 percent of funds raised
by passenger fees, with the balance used to reduce budget deficits.
This failure has contributed to the most nagging problems of
commercial aviation _ frequent delays and cancellations of flights.
</P>
<P>
   But the money should be linked to commitments by the airlines to
confer the benefits of competition in areas where de facto
monopolies currently allow both predatory fare schedules and the
abandonment of air service when traffic levels are deemed too low
to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective growth of traffic is impressive, and it should
be realized if fuel prices do not soar excessively. The FAA
predicts that commercial airline fleets will expand from their
current level of 4,300 planes to 6,400 in 2011, coupled with an
additional 630 cargo planes and 24,500 general aviation aircraft.
International traffic is expected to grow even faster than domestic
travel. Air fares are expected to decline on average and in
constant dollars by about 1.3 percent a year _ excluding the impact
of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Among the gains that the general public would most widely
welcome would be further improvements on aircraft noise _ the
source of persistent complaints and the root of controversies like
that afflicting Logan's plan for a relatively small runway. In the
interim, it is clear that aviation will continue to grow, placing
heavy responsibility on Congress to provide adequate support
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1453EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
