<HEADER>
A1850 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CALIF-DIVERSITY-HNS &LR;      03-09 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MORE HISPANICS, ASIANS TURN OUT FOR CALIFORNIA PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California voters are becoming more ethnically
diverse as more Hispanics and Asians exercise head to the ballot
boxes, according to surveys of voters as they left polling places
in Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that immigrants have become the new force in
electoral politics in the state,'' said David Lee, director of the
Chinese American Voter Education Committee. ``It's hard to imagine
the Democratic victories of the past few years without Latino
voters. And the Asian vote is just beginning to surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's electorate is notably more affluent than it was in
1992 and happy about it. Substantial numbers of voters said they
were doing better financially than they were eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly coincides with what we know is the general
direction of the California economy,'' said Stephen Levy, director
of the Palo Alto-based Center for the Continuing Study of the
California Economy.
</P>
<P>
   The exit poll by the Voter News Service and San Francisco
Examiner was conducted among 4,283 voters.
</P>
<P>
   It found that overall, more women than men voted and for the
first time, more Republican women than men voted in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican women now feel we have some viable candidates who
will take us on to the White House,'' said Shirley Foote, president
of the California Federation of Republican Women.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest shift has been ethnic, with Hispanics clearly
leading that change, according to Mark DiCamillo, an official of
California's Field Poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1980s, it was 80 percent whites and 20 percent
ethnic minorities,'' DiCamillo said. ``Now whites are at 72
percent. What's replacing them are generally Latinos, with some
Asians.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen percent of the voters on Tuesday identified themselves
as Hispanic; 6 percent as Asian; and 6 percent as black.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 primary, 8 percent of voters were Hispanic while in
1998, the Hispanic share of voters was 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DiCamillo credited the surge of Hispanic voters to activism
triggered by Proposition 187, a voter-approved, but court-rejected
1994 measure aimed at banning public services to illegal
immigrants. ``That was a wake-up call for Latinos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto said the fact that both the Republican and Democratic
presidential hopefuls courted the Hispanic vote made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing numbers of Hispanics and Asians who are voting
comes at a time when the number of black voters remains about the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known for some time that African-American political
participation has plateaued,'' Lee said. ``Every poll we've done,
including the latest one, show that increasingly, Asians and
Latinos are outnumbering African-Americans at the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Henry, professor of African-American Studies at the
University of California at Berkeley, said the fairly flat showing
of black voters at the polls Tuesday may have indicated lack of
interest in the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're talking about four years ago when Clinton ran, he
certainly had more appeal to black voters than either Gore or
Bradley,'' Henry said, referring the Vice President Al Gore and
former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, the two Democrats on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley announced Thursday that he was leaving the race after
failing to win any presidential primaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
