A1874 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WEST-`FIZZLE-FRIDAY'-     03-09 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-`FIZZLE-FRIDAY'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOUNTAIN WEST'S PRIMARY ANTICLIMAX  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Western-State Editors _ COLORADO, Utah, Wyoming)   (This 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A light snow fell Thursday morning outside the training
headquarters for the Denver Broncos football team and the crowd to
meet George W. Bush, the presumptive nominee for the Republican
nomination, was enthusiastic but small.
</P>
<P>
   The cold was not the problem here. Rather it was that single
word, ``presumptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush came here in spite of the news that John McCain was
withdrawing from the nomination derby after his poor showing in the
Super Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   For the Texas governor, though, the primary calendar keeps
rolling and today (Friday) is the turn of voters in Colorado, Utah
and Wyoming to have their say.
</P>
<P>
   But Little Friday _ as some have dubbed it _ might now be Fizzle
Friday. Turnouts in Colorado and Utah _ Wyoming has no voting as
such but a series of party meetings _ are expected to be dismally
low as the electorate realizes that both nominations have already
been locked up, by Bush and by Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it is a Friday hardly helps. In America, voting
traditionally happens on Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   This was not how it was meant to be. Indeed, this had been
heralded as the year when a region that is sometimes called the
Interior West or the Mountain West and is made up of eight enormous
states constituting almost one quarter of the landmass of the
United States, would at last make itself heard in the presidential
election process after years of being ignored by the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to give voice to the region began two years ago, with
a proposal by the governors of Utah and Colorado to have all eight
of the states _ their own plus Wyoming, Montana, New Mexico,
Arizona, Idaho and Nevada _ vote on a single day that would be
fairly far forward in the primaries schedule.
</P>
<P>
   They earmarked today (Friday), March 10. But in the end, the
plan proved too grandiose. Only the three states voting Friday
backed it.
</P>
<P>
   Even Little Friday seemed like a decent start, though. ``The
Mountain West is on the brink of a monumental breakthrough,'' Utah
Governor Michael Leavitt writes to voters on his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now...the Mountain West has been essentially irrelevant
in nominating candidates for the leadership of the free world. The
West has not been heard, it has been stereotyped.''
</P>
<P>
   The stereotyping, however, may not be reversed this year if
turnouts are as low as projected.
</P>
<P>
   And once more, issues that are important to this region _ public
land management, logging policies, water conservation and
protection against nuclear spillage _ may barely make the lips of
the candidates between now and election day in November.
</P>
<P>
   And the frustration among voters here will remain. ``It's kind
of anticlimactic,'' conceded Gina Seamans, a Republican from
Arvada, a Denver suburb, who will vote for McCain today (Friday)
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been better if we'd gotten together with more
Western states and made it more of a bigger deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Insult has been added to injury, meanwhile, by the commission
that selects venues for the presidential and vice presidential
debates that provide much of the drama in the final stretches of
the presidential race proper in the autumn.
</P>
<P>
   There will be four of these debates, but not one will be held in
the Interior West. There has not been a debate in the region for
more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just insane,'' Governor Leavitt raged recently,
complaining that to the rest of the country the Interior West
remains just an afterthought. That even though some of the fastest
growing regions in the land are in Utah and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Even this week, U.S. Census figures showed that five of the 10
fastest growing counties in the country are in Colorado, all
beneath the Rocky Mountains close to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Leavitt and the other governors wrote to the
Commission on Presidential Debates, imploring that an additional
debate be arranged and awarded to a city in the West. They were
rudely turned down.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been even worse. With McCain gone, Bush could have
taken Thursday off. Instead, he visited this state, Utah and
Wyoming. For that, the Republican faithful at least, will be
extremely grateful. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1517EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
