<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, BRADLEY THROW IN THE TOWEL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``p'' political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John McCain and Bill Bradley bade farewell to their
presidential ambitions Thursday, accepting with a tinge of
bitterness that they had taken on the political establishment and
lost.
</P>
<P>
   But both stood by their calls for reform and pledged to continue
their crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep fighting, keep fighting!'' McCain urged his backers at
the close of his brief valedictory speech. ``I have been defeated,
but the cause for which I ran has not,'' said Bradley at an
emotional last rally. ``It cannot be erased by one, or even 100,
defeats.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit of both challengers had become inevitable after their
losses in this week's Super Tuesday primaries. Bradley, who had
come within four points of beating Al Gore just five weeks before
in New Hampshire, won not a single state.
</P>
<P>
   McCain failed to make the national breakthrough he had hoped
for, winning only four New England states, albeit by big
majorities.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from his mountain retreat in Arizona after a day of
seclusion, McCain said that the voters had spoken, ``and I respect
their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking pale and tired, he told the hushed reporters: ``I am no
longer an active candidate for my party's nomination for
president.'' Technically, he has suspended rather than ended his
campaign, but few believe it will be revived.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that he respected the Republican victor and party
favorite, George W. Bush, and wished him well, but he declined to
endorse his candidacy and said he would take some time ``to reflect
our recent experiences and determine how we can best...bring about
the changes to the practices and institutions of our great
democracy that are the purpose of our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he appeared to scotch speculation that he would break
away from the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Wistfully, he said that he had hoped his campaign could be a
force for change in the Republican Party. Now, he said, ``I will
take our crusade back to the U.S. Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Colorado, congratulated his former rival
``for fighting the good fight'' and he said he appreciated McCain's
kind words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also agree with John McCain about the need to reform
Washington, D.C.,'' Bush said. ``In order to reform Washington,
D.C., it's important to get rid of Clinton-Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   By suspending, rather than winding up, his campaign, McCain does
not surrender the convention delegates he has won in the primaries
so far to Bush. These delegates could now become bargaining
counters in what is believed to be some hard bargaining between his
own camp and that of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, it is said, has set a price for his endorsement of Bush,
which includes acceptance of some provisions of his campaign
finance reforms.
</P>
<P>
   While making no bones about ending his campaign forthwith _ and
taking a well-earned vacation _ Bradley made clear that he was also
retaining his delegates, at least for the time being and he
repeated his insistence that he would not be a candidate for vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he will now support and campaign for the man
who beat him, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing reporters and campaign staff in West Orange, N.J.,
where he established his headquarters last year, Bradley said:
``The vice president and I had a stiff competition and he won. Now
it is time for unity. This country needs Democratic leadership and
I will work to ensure a Democratic White House and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   In saying that he would support Gore, however, Bradley declined
to use the word ``endorse,'' an omission seen as a deliberate
reflection of the ill-feeling left by some of Gore's campaign
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also gave the reporters allocated to the campaign two
poignant souvenirs: a tin of his favorite throat lozenges and a
silver key ring from Tiffany's, with a miniature athletic shoe
attached, a reminder of the basketball stardom that had launched
his public career. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 675-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
