<SLUG> BC-KOHL-CASH-COMEBACK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAMELESS KOHL RETURNS, WAVING BUNDLES OF MONEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The great fund-raiser is back. Helmut Kohl stormed into
the center of German politics Thursday, waving a large bundle of
money he hopes will buy back favor with the party he brought to the
verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Surreptitiously as in the old times, Kohl had again been
assembling a slush fund in recent weeks, but this time the donors
came with names attached.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public appearance for over a month, the
ex-chancellor revealed the names who were behind the DM6 million
war chest.
</P>
<P>
   The money was collected on behalf of the Christian Democrat
Party, to cover the debt Kohl left behind. He has admitted to
having accepted DM2.1 million in cash from unnamed donors while he
was chancellor. As a result the party is facing a fine three times
that sum.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Kohl, looking his ebullient old self, said he was
nearly there. He had to take out a mortgage of DM700,000 on the
family house in Ludwigshafen, and friends have chipped in with the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   The most generous of them was Leo Kirch, the conservative media
mogul, who is stumping up DM1 million. The other 29 donors are
academics, actors, a well-known singer and assorted celebrities,
who contributed upwards of DM5,000 each. The British publisher Lord
Weidenfeld threw DM30,000 into the hat.
</P>
<P>
   In his usual modesty, Kohl made clear that while his donors were
struck by the plight of the party, ``they wanted specifically to
support me.'' When he hands over the full DM6.3 million, his debts
will have been paid, he argues. ``I see no reason to seek
reconciliation with the party,'' Kohl declared.
</P>
<P>
   But the Christian Democrats are unlikely to be in such forgiving
mood. The party has already been fined DM41 million for
improprieties under his reign, so DM6 million will only keep the
bailiffs away for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Party colleagues are also concerned that their former boss is
once again up to his old tricks of buying influence. There are
rumors he plans to return to the Bundestag, and play a key role at
next month's party conference, where the CDU's new leader is to be
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kohl still refuses to make things easier for the
party by revealing the list of his secret donors. ``I've not named
names, and I will not name names,'' he said firmly Thursday. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
