<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-RACE-FIRSTPERSON-$ADV     03-09 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-FIRSTPERSON-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AN EYE-OPENING WALK IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF CIVIL RIGHTS PIONEERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was one of the worst days of my 15 years in
America.
</P>
<P>
   As I stood at an intersection in the central Illinois city of
Danville in April 1996, a white pickup truck zoomed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niggerrrrr!'' the white driver yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked, I could only stare at the white friend who was with me.
I wanted to run after the bigot who had called me a nigger and ask
him to repeat the word to my face. Then I'd beat him up for his
ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, I realized for the first time that my nationality
is irrelevant to racists. They only see my brown skin, which to
bigots is my sin. And to them, I am as much a nigger or a monkey as
any African American.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Liberia, West Africa, race was hardly an issue,
though tribal conflicts existed. I didn't even know what racism was
or meant.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Liberia was founded by freed slaves from the United
States, I don't recall the history of American slavery ever being
taught in school. I was also unaware of the civil rights movement
and the racism that still plagues America.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people in Third World countries, I believed America
was an utopia where everyone was rich. The thought that one was
judged there based on the color of one's skin never crossed my
mind.
</P>
<P>
   When I moved to the United States in 1984, my stepbrothers and
their cousins, who were African Americans, frequently warned me
about ``those damn white folks in this country who want to keep the
black man down.''
</P>
<P>
   At school, where blacks sat on one side of the cafeteria and
whites on the other side, I was once labeled a ``sellout'' for
sitting with a white friend on the white side of the room.
</P>
<P>
   At first I didn't understand what was going on and why the
tension existed. I didn't understand why there was a Black History
Month.
</P>
<P>
   When I began to study black history in school, I started to see
why African Americans were bitter toward whites. But none of the
history classes I took or books I read prepared me for a recent
trip to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   I was sent to cover the re-enactment of a march that led to the
passing of 1965 Voting Rights Act, which guaranteed all Americans,
regardless of race, the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to Selma where the actual march took place, I
visited Birmingham. I had seen film footage from the civil rights
movement on TV, but being in the places where they took place
raised powerful feelings.
</P>
<P>
   I felt angry as I walked in a downtown area, now the Kelly
Ingram Park, where blacks staging sit-ins, even young children, had
been attacked by police dogs. The protesters were also sprayed with
fire hoses powerful enough to rip the bark from a tree 80 feet
away.
</P>
<P>
   I felt bitter when I toured the Sixteenth Street Baptist Church,
where four little girls were killed when it was bombed by white
segregationists in the fall of 1963.
</P>
<P>
   A feeling that I can't describe came over me at the Civil Rights
Institute. There, I touched the gates from the Birmingham jail,
where the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. wrote his famous letter, and
viewed two water fountains labeled ``whites only'' and blacks
only.'' The white fountain was clean, but the black fountain was
rusty and filthy.
</P>
<P>
   The re-enactment of the march in Selma, on the Edmund Pettus
Bridge, brought tears to my eyes. It was on that very bridge that
young John Lewis, now a congressman from Georgia, led 600 peaceful
marchers to protest rules that prevented blacks from voting.
</P>
<P>
   However, before the marchers could make the 54-mile trek to
Montgomery, the state capital, they were attacked by Alabama state
troopers. The protesters were tear-gassed, whipped with billy clubs
and trampled by horses. Lewis suffered a skull fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Following that trip, I have a better understanding of the civil
rights movement, the struggles and the blood that was spilled.
</P>
<P>
   No, I still don't hate white people, nor do I condone racism.
But I certainly have a better understanding of why African
Americans are so angry.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
