<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1912 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-09 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MILLIONAIRE MIND' REHASHES OLD MATERIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as if many of us want to be millionaires, something
Thomas Stanley has bet on, to his benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, a Ph.D. who has studied the wealthy for more than 25
years, wrote ``The Millionaire Next Door,'' which has been on the
New York Times bestseller list more than 150 weeks and is No. 1 on
Business Week's paperback bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly every other business writer with a novel and popular
approach to personal finance, Stanley is exploiting his bestseller
by writing another book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Millionaire Mind'' (Andrews McMell, 406 pages, $26.95) is
already a hit, ranking No. 4 on the Times bestseller list last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But should you read 406 more pages devoted to millionaires'
habits, lifestyles and strategies _ much of the same material
covered so well in the first book?
</P>
<P>
   I would have to say, no.
</P>
<P>
   Like his first book, Stanley's second effort is based on about
1,000 responses to a questionnaire sent randomly to 5,000 U.S.
millionaires. Interviews and focus group sessions with millionaires
_ apparently some in this group really like to talk _ round out the
empirical evidence of what makes millionaires tick.
</P>
<P>
   The composite sketch looks something like this: male, 54 years
old, married 28 years, three children, average household net worth
of $9.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two percent are business owners or entrepreneurs; 16
percent are senior corporate executives; 10 percent are attorneys;
nine percent are physicians. Most made their own money rather than
inheriting it and live a comfortable but not luxurious life, with
little or no debt.
</P>
<P>
   But that just scratches the surface of Stanley's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stanley, the five factors that millionaires most
often mention as being crucial to their success are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Integrity: being honest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discipline: self-control.
</P>
<P>
   _ Social skills: getting along.
</P>
<P>
   _ A supportive spouse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hard work.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't earth-shattering enough, Stanley also provides
more minutiae about millionaires, such as their GPA (2.92) or SAT
scores (1190.) Of course, that would be relevant only if you
remember your own GPA or SAT scores, which I doubt that many people
retain past age 25, including the millionaires questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might want to know what millionaires think and do to
eliminate or reduce fears and worries. Stanley has concluded that
hard work, self-confidence, preparation and a focus on key issues
are the top ways millionaires overcome their problems. THAT insight
almost blinded me.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know the most important spousal qualities that
contribute to millionaires' successful marriages? Stanley has found
that out, too. Men value honesty, manners and physical attraction
in picking their spouses; women, in addition to those qualities,
focus slightly more on earning power and wealth when picking a
mate. This is something akin to my Irish grandmother's advice that
you can marry a rich man as easily as a poor one.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you seek insight, strategy or wealth-building clues, I
highly recommend Stanley's first book. It may not give you a road
map, but it does provide an eye-opening look at how rich people get
and spend their money.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's new book rehashes the same material, only with many
more pages of statistics and analysis to belabor the points.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shoestring Entrepreneur's Guide to The Best Home-Based
Businesses''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Spiegel
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   More than 23 million Americans work out of their homes, a figure
that has grown 35 percent in three years. Entrepreneur Robert
Spiegel writes about the top 50 professional home businesses, the
top 50 nonprofessional home businesses, 50 home business franchises
and more. He includes salary levels, start-up needs and customer
descriptions with each entry.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``100 Ways to Win The Profit Game: Battle-Tested Business
Strategies That Add Value to Your Business Now''
</P>
<P>
   By Barry R. Schimel and Gary R. Kravitz
</P>
<P>
   Capital Books, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Management consultants Barry Schimel and Gary Kravitz have
sifted through the profit ideas they've found in their business and
picked their Top 100. These ideas, they say, will add thousands and
sometimes millions of unrealized profit to most businesses.
Bundling products and services, using trickle marketing for
qualified leads, subletting unused space and rewarding employees
for bright ideas are some of their suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Give a Sucker An Even Break: W.C. Fields on Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Fields
</P>
<P>
   Prentice Hall Press, $22
</P>
<P>
   We've had Machiavelli, Genghis Kahn, Winnie the Pooh and even
Jesus Christ quoted about business. So why not W.C. Fields? This
book is written by Fields' grandson, who seems to be making a
business on his granddad, having written two other books and an
Emmy Award-winning video about the great comedian. If you're a W.C.
Fields fan, this is obviously for you. Otherwise, don't look for a
great deal of insight from an actor of 65 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
