<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-DOLPHINS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S FIGHTING DOLPHINS SOLD TO IRAN  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By PATRICK COCKBURN  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Fighting dolphins, once taught by the Soviet Navy to
blow up enemy ships with mines attached to their backs, have been
sold to Iran because their trainers could no longer afford to feed
them.
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins, which had been living in an oceanarium in
Sevastopol in the Crimea, were flown to Iran last month when they
failed to find a local buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a sadist I would stay in Sevastopol,'' said Boris
Zhurid, their chief trainer. ``But I cannot stand it when my
animals starve.''
</P>
<P>
   The three killing dolphins were part of a secret Soviet naval
project, originally started in 1966, under which they were taught
to sink hostile ships and attack enemy divers with harpoons fixed
to their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trained by a special military detachment,'' said
Col. Viktor Baranets, formerly an official in the Soviet Defense
Ministry. ``We called them fighting dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhurid, who accompanied his dolphins to Iran, had tried to
maintain them by teaching them circus tricks, but could not afford
the $120 a month it took to feed each dolphin.
</P>
<P>
   He told a Russian newspaper before leaving for Iran that the
dolphins _ along with seals and sea lions _ would be kept in
perfect conditions in a newly constructed oceanarium in their new
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iranian authorities have big plans to train the animals
and staff,'' said Zhurid. ``Of course Iran is not famous for its
humanity, but if my animals feel well I am ready to go to Allah or
to the devil himself.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the Iranians plan to put the dolphins
to military use.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Navy became interested in using marine animals to
carry weapons in the 1960s after learning that the U.S. Navy was
carrying out experiments with dolphins to investigate their
military potential.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1970s the Soviet Defense Ministry established
a special secret training base at Vityar Bay on the Soviet Union's
Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   With the break-up of the Soviet Union Zhurid, who was in charge
of the project along with his wife Svetlana, took the dolphins to
an oceanarium in Sevastopol on the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole group left on Feb. 15 and I'm happy for them,''
Valentina Inuza, deputy director of the oceanarium, told the
Independent. ``There was no money to feed them. They were really
hungry. In Iran they will be used for both scientific research and
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last winter Zhurid searched desperately for funds to
feed his dolphins and seals. Local authorities refused to donate
any funds. For several months the trainers received no salaries.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``Finally when the animals got so hungry that they
could not perform any more, we started to negotiate with anybody
who could buy the dolphinarium.'' Col. Baranets says that ``many
people wanted to buy the dolphins, but possibly the Iranians came
up with more money.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
