<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS &LR;      03-09 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AND THEY'RE OFF: BUSH, GORE BEGIN GENERAL ELECTION FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (EDS: Stands for CALIF-BATTLEGROUND)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Even though voters across the nation picked
two mainstream presidential candidates with traditional messages,
enough wounds were opened during the past few weeks to make the
battle between Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush
as nasty and suspenseful as the unexpectedly tough primaries.
</P>
<P>
   With former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey quitting the
Democratic race Thursday, and with Arizona Sen. John McCain
suspending his campaign for the Republican nomination, voters will
have more time to compare the parties' certain nominees _ Gore for
the Democrats, Bush for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush are already developing attack plans on education,
the environment, social issues, character, morality, campaign
finance abuses, the legacy of President Clinton and other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts believe Bush suffered the most during
the short-live primary season. Bradley's campaign fizzled as Gore
gained steam, but it was dog-eat-dog for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would clean up the `iron triangle'' of lobbyists,
legislation and money in Washington. McCain pushed Bush to the
right and opened up distracting problems for him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain appeared to have nearly committed a political
murder-suicide by attacking the religious conservatives as the
primary reached a critical point two weeks ago. His attacks
consolidated Bush's support from the right. That will shadow Bush
just when he needs a more moderate message for the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also refused to demand that South Carolina take down the
Confederate battle flag that flies over the state Capitol.
Democratic consultants in California already believe that issue
will damage Bush here, where the non-white population is nearly 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   `McCain was speaking to a constituency in the Republican Party
that is disaffected from the religious right and much of the
congressional Republican leadership,'' said veteran Democratic
consultant Bill Carrick. `I have trouble figuring out how Bush gets
them. ... Bush had to move further to the right than Gore had to
move to the left on his issues. There was some real damage done to
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has his vulnerabilities as well. Bush, in his victory
speech Tuesday night from Austin, Texas, got a huge cheer from the
audience when he said the country would reject a White House that
had `no controlling legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a slap at a phrase Gore used to explain fund-raising
calls the vice president made from the White House, which
Republicans blasted as an infraction of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Buddhist monks. Even before the votes were
counted, Bush was snipping at Gore for holding a 1996 re-election
fund-raiser at a Southern California Buddhist temple where monks
had taken a vow of poverty. A Gore associate was recently convicted
of violating campaign laws in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign does not believe that Gore will suffer because
of President Clinton's personal problems, but they will
nevertheless try to paint Gore as Clintonesque when he claimed to
have invented the Internet and was the subject of the book and
acclaimed movie `Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   `I don't think the election will be a look back at the personal
transgressions of President Clinton,'' said Karen Hughes, Bush's
national communications director. `People are sick of that. That
was an embarrassing chapter in our history, and people want to put
it behind us. But they do want a president they can trust, and so I
would point to some of candidate Gore's own statements.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also thinks it has an edge over Gore on
education and among Silicon Valley executives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Bradley raised far more money than Gore among the
high-tech crowd. Bush believes his plan to increase tax deductions
for charitable contributions _ to attract the wealthy technology
crowd _ and protect Silicon Valley businesses from securities
litigation will keep high-tech executives on his side, although
Democrats have traditionally wooed the high-tech crowd.
</P>
<P>
   `We're going to talk about the fact that on tort reform, Al Gore
stands with the trial lawyers, who are anathema to Silicon Valley
entrepreneurs,'' said Republican state Sen. Jim Brulte, a Bush
adviser in California.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are up for a few punches against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his victory speech Tuesday, started off the general
election campaign by telling his audience that Republican
administrations in the 1980s had increased the federal deficit and
sparked a recession in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton, the country since 1992 has seen crime rates drp,
abortion rates plummet and the economy take off, Gore will remind
voters.
</P>
<P>
   `We need to build on our record of prosperity,'' Gore said
Tuesday. `We don't need to go back to where we were eight years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also feel they need to rip into Bush's record in Texas
and statements he made on the campaign trail as he battled McCain.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh, there are plenty of things,'' said Democratic Party
strategist Bob Mulholland, mentioning Bush's opposition to abortion
and `irresponsible tax cut proposal''
</P>
<P>
   Carrick, the Democratic consultant, said the fights between
McCain and Bush over personality and campaign tactics meant Bush
remained untested on the national stage on many important policy
issues. Voters are going to be hearing for the first time his
positions on abortion and the environment, for example.
</P>
<P>
   `The most amazing things is we still haven't defined what this
election is about,'' said Henry Brady, a political scientist at the
University of California at Berkeley. `We still can't write a
one-sentence description about the 2000 election. In 1992, it was,
`It's the economy stupid.' It's hard to get real issues on people's
plates when the economy is doing so well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IRS-AUDITS10-COX     03-09 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-AUDITS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONSERVATIVES PRESS FOR ANSWERS ON IRS AUDITS
 &HT;    660&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than three years ago, federal tax auditors
began an audit of the Heritage Foundation that the research center
says has cost it $200,000 in legal fees and expenses so far and
generated a stack of documents 75 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens Against Government Waste received a similar visit from
Internal Revenue Service auditors that has cost the
Washington-based private watchdog group more than $50,000 without
reaching a final conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Across the continent a few months earlier, IRS inspectors probed
the records of a third group, the non-profit Western Journalism
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to these and about a dozen other examples,
conservatives say the IRS scrutiny amounts to retaliation against
some of the Clinton administration's toughest critics. An IRS
spokesman denied that politics influences audit decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation, evoking memories of President Nixon's attempts
to punish his political enemies with IRS audits, will get more
attention soon with the expected release of a report from Congress
and a ruling from a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the Joint Tax Committee of the House and
Senate was directed by congressional leaders from both parties to
review the issue ``as expeditiously as possible,'' aides say the
conclusions will be released in about about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was charged with examining whether the IRS was
pressured to audit certain non-profit groups because of their
political leanings. All the groups have tax exemptions that require
them to limit their political activity.
</P>
<P>
   The probe took so long because ``it's very labor-intensive,''
said Lindy Paull, chief of staff for the tax committee.
</P>
<P>
   Paull declined to say what the report of more than 100 pages
concludes, but she warned that it will not discuss specific tax
cases, since that is prohibited by federal privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Without those details, the report is unlikely to satisfy those
who believe they are victims of a vendetta by the Democratic
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is a systematic effort to intimidate these
organizations,'' said Mark R. Levin, whose Landmark Legal
Foundation sued to force the IRS to provide a list of politicians
who have sought tax audits of non-profit groups and the names of
their proposed targets.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the agency has handed over hundreds of letters sent by
the White House and members of Congress from both parties. But the
agency blacked out the identities of the groups they wanted
audited.
</P>
<P>
   Levin not only wants more details, but also alleges that an IRS
official discussed shredding key documents on this topic at an
October 1997 meeting. In a further touch of Watergate deja vu, the
IRS has conceded that a tape recording was made of that session and
said that it was later erased.
</P>
<P>
   Levin has been waiting since last November for a ruling from
U.S. District Court Judge Henry Kennedy in Washington on whether he
can depose four IRS officials and examine the tape.
</P>
<P>
   Delving into the IRS operations is difficult because of strict
secrecy laws. The agency says it examines 6,000 to 10,000
tax-exempt groups a year and that less than 1 percent of the cases
result from a request from Congress or the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a spokesman for the agency pointed out that the IRS is
largely operated by civil servants who are not appointed by the
president and insisted that audit decisions are based on law, not
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Hill, a University of Pennsylvania law professor who
specializes in tax-exempt organizations, said the number of
conservative groups being audited is not, by itself, evidence of
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how many of these groups would be audited for
other issues, like unrelated business income tax or excessive
compensation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she said that the tax agency is ``susceptible to
pressure'' from both parties in Congress and from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some details on the referrals to the IRS have already come to
light.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a Treasury Department internal investigation, made
public late last year in response to a Freedom of Information Act
request, traces the audit of the Western Journalism Center to a
citizen complaint that the White House faxed to the IRS. The letter
complained that the WJC, based in Fair Oaks, Calif., was seeking
donations to investigate the death of White House deputy counsel
Vincent Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials concluded that the IRS had acted
appropriately and had not been under undue pressure from the White
House. The audit ended without a finding of a violation.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Farah, executive director of WJC, said in an interview
that he has been surprised at the lack of interest in the
revelation of the White House role. ``You've got this clear paper
trail,'' he said, noting that the White House had prepared a secret
331-page ``conspiracy'' analysis that blamed his center for
generating reports on Clinton scandals that later became headlines
in major news outlets.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the White House has not been alone in asking the IRS
to check out private groups. House Ways and Means Committee
chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, asked for an investigation of the
California Buddhist temple that hosted a fund-raising event for
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers also called for a probe of the Public
Broadcasting System, which was found to be trading fund-raising
lists with political candidates, usually Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The roster of conservative groups who say they have been audited
by the IRS is much longer. Among them are the National Rifle
Association, Citizens for a Sound Economy, and Concerned Women for
America. Individual Clinton critics such as Paula Jones, the former
Arkansas state worker who accused Clinton of sexual harassment,
have also been audited.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Heritage Foundation was being penalized for its
critiques of the administration, Phil Truluck, executive vice
president of the Heritage Foundation, said, ``I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he cited the statements of former Rep. David Skaggs,
D-Colo., who asked the IRS to review the tax exemptions of both
Heritage and Citizens Against Government Waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed then and I believe now that these were serious
possible violations and the appropriate step was to ask the people
with the expertise,'' Skaggs told the Associated Press last year.
``But it would be incredible to suggest, and I won't, that there
was not a political dimension to these things. Of course there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Shelley L. Davis, the former IRS historian turned
whistle-blower on the agency: ``The IRS in the past has been used
politically to audit both conservative and liberal organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis found a file room at the agency that she said contains
evidence that the Kennedy administration used the IRS to punish
enemies. She was later forced out of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The facts will be difficult to uncover, she held, pointing to
agency's secrecy. ``I think there is much merit in the lawsuits,''
she said. ``But I also know how adept the IRS is at bouncing these
allegations off because they have the keys to all of this
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
