<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-WELLNESS10-C     03-09 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-WELLNESS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD EXPAND FREE PREVENTIVE SCREENINGS UNDER MEDICARE
 &HT;    With photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare beneficiaries would receive more
preventive screening tests without having to pay a portion of their
costs under a bipartisan bill introduced Thursday in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is sponsored by Reps. Mark Foley, R-Fla., and Sander
Levin, D-Mich., both of whom serve on the House Ways and Means
Committee, which has primary jurisdiction over Medicare. It is a
companion to legislation introduced last year by Sens. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., and James Jeffords, R-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more money you spend up front in preventive health care,
the better the return for the taxpayer,'' Foley said. He noted that
the Medicare system, which primarily covers the acute care needs of
elderly and disabled persons, will not pay for preventive care and
counseling for diabetes, ``but will amputate your leg or put you on
dialysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1997 law offering Medicare coverage for mammograms,
colorectal and prostate screenings, Levin said relatively few
seniors take advantage of the tests. He suggested that is because
seniors have to pay a 20 percent copayment. The bill would
eliminate those copayments.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would expand the list of Medicare-covered
screenings and counseling programs to include high blood pressure
tests; glaucoma, vision and hearing screenings; cholesterol and
osteoporosis screening; nutrition counseling; tobacco cessation
counseling, and hormone replacement therapy counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Future preventive care coverage would be recommended by the
National Institute of Medicine and added to Medicare benefits
unless specifically rejected by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Graham suggested that as lawmakers look for ways to reform
Medicare and add a prescription drug benefit, a major reform should
be to shift Medicare's focus from healing to prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
