<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' TV show, when a
contestant phones a friend for help with the answer, Regis Philbin
always says about the person being called, ``I know you can't see
us now.'' Why can't the person at home see the show as it's going
on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because ``Millionaire'' is taped in advance. So, obviously,
when the person at home sees the broadcast, the question already
had been asked at some earlier time. Since ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' is taped before a live audience at ABC's New York
studio, it can appear to viewers at home that the broadcast is
live.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' show recently featured a rerun of the
Osmond family reunion in December. I missed how many grandchildren
and great-grandchildren there are. Do you know? Also, two brothers
were doing sign language. Are they deaf?
</P>
<P>
   A: George and OIive have 9 children: Virl, Tom, Alan, Wayne,
Merrill, Jay, Donny, Marie and Jimmy. Virl has 7 children and 6
grandchildren. Tom has 9 children and 1 granddaughter. Alan has 8
children (all sons) and 2 granddaughters. Wayne has 5 children and
1 grandson. Merrill has 6 children. Jay has 3 children (all sons).
Donny has 5 children (all sons). Marie has 7 children. Jimmy has 3
children.
</P>
<P>
   So the total is 2 parents, 9 children, 53 grandchildren and 10
great-grandchildren, said Jennifer Wallace of Osmond.com.
</P>
<P>
   The two oldest Osmond sons, Virl and Tom, are hearing impaired.
They were the first deaf missionaries sent out by the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, serving the deaf population in
Canada. They aren't part of the Omond Brothers singing group.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you print the exact wording of the Second Amendment to
the U.S. Constitution, and the generally held interpretation as to
who may possess firearms?
</P>
<P>
   A: Capitalization and placement of commas is subject to
variation, but this is the text (as found in World Book
Encyclopedia, World Almanac and other common resources): A
well-regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a free
State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be
infringed.
</P>
<P>
   This amendment _ one of 10 known collectively as the Bill of
Rights, which was ratified on Dec. 15, 1791 _ has been interpreted
in two ways. Some people believe it gives ordinary citizens the
right to possess firearms; others believe it only gives each state
the right to maintain its own militia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What health benefits do members of Congress have, and how
much do they pay for this?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're entitled to participate in the health benefits
program available to all federal employees, said Pete Sepp of the
National Taxpayers Union. A number of insurance options are
negotiated with insurance companies by the federal government at a
discount, with no special subsidies involved for members of
Congress. The amount paid varies according to the options.
</P>
<P>
   Outside that program, there are some ``important benefits''
members of Congress get that aren't available to other federal
employees, Sepp said. First, they can avail themselves of the
Attending Physician's Office, which Sepp described as a
``reasonably comprehensive care clinic in the Capitol.'' That
service was free to members until 1992, when they began paying a
nominal fee of $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   And second, they're entitled to receive medical care of an acute
nature, such as surgery, at the Walter Reed Army Hospital and the
Bethesda Naval Hospital. This is ``privileged care,'' Sepp said,
meaning the members are admitted on a priority basis and get
upgraded rooms and greater privacy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book ``Washington: City of Scandals,'' members
of Congress are charged the minimum flat daily rate for stays at
either hospital, even if they require intensive care treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What states have the Powerball lottery?
</P>
<P>
   A: Arizona, Connecticut, Idaho, Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky,
Louisiana, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, New Hampshire, Oregon,
Rhode Island, Wisconsin and West Virginia, plus the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is the ``kudzu line,'' the farthest north that kudzu
can live over the winter?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kudzu might be seen in places are far north as Long Island,
but it doesn't thrive there season after season. It's basically
found in the South. Horticulturist Wayne McLaurin of the University
of Georgia says the clinging vine won't thrive year after year much
farther north Kentucky, Virginia and Maryland because it needs a
long growing season. In colder areas there's not enough time for
nutrients to be put back into the kudzu tubers for future growth,
McLaurin said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Pope John Paul would make an apology for Catholic
treatment in the past regarding persecution, and anti-Semitism in
particular. I haven't seen anything more about it since. Can you
give me an update?
</P>
<P>
   A: The apology will be in the form of a document, titled ``The
Church and the Faults of the Past: Memory in the Service of
Reconciliation,'' which is expected to be read March 12 by the pope
at a ceremony in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The paper, produced by a 28-member Vatican theological
commission, is viewed as an attempt to apologize for 2,000 years of
violence, persecution and ``blunders,'' such as the Inquisition,
the Crusades, and the Roman Catholic Church's treatment of Jewish
people.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of the paper is seen as a centerpiece of the
Vatican's holy year, or jubilee, celebrations, which occur every 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian newspaper La Repubblica has suggested that Pope John
Paul II will go so far as to apologize for the church's failure to
resist the Nazis, but without implicating Pope Pius XII, who has
been accused of ignoring the Holocaust during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives in the Curia, the Vatican's bureaucracy,
meanwhile, have argued that an apology would erode the foundations
of church authority. But they were rebuffed and told that the
jubilee could be celebrated only with ``purification of the
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is a Kalashnikov? It was mentioned, without explanation,
in a newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   A: The term refers to a family of automatic assault rifles and
light machine guns, most notably the AK-47. The AK-47 was designed
in 1947 by Mikhail Kalashnikov in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   It fires a rifle-type cartridge at up to 600 rounds per minute
and is one of the most widely distributed automatic rifles in
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Golfer Darren Clarke of Northern Ireland won $1 million at
the Match Play Championship in California. Does he have to pay
taxes to the Internal Revenue Service, since he is not a U.S.
citizen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Without knowing all the details, because exceptions and
extenuating circumstances are always possible, the IRS declined to
address Clarke's case specifically.
</P>
<P>
   But, in general, income earned in the United States by a
resident or non-resident alien is subject to taxation in the same
manner as for a U.S. citizen, said IRS spokesman Mark Green.
Information on the general topic can be found in IRS publication
519, U.S. Tax Guide for Aliens, Green added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I got my first driver's license and registered to vote as a
new 18-year-old bride in 1960. But I read recently that the voting
age wasn't lowered to 18 until 1972. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: You must have lived in Georgia, Kentucky or Alaska. Those
three states permitted 18-year-olds to vote before the 26th
Amendment was ratified in 1971. Three other states (Minnesota,
Montana and Massachusetts) permitted voting at 19, and three more
(Maine, Nebraska and Hawaii) allowed 20-year-olds to vote.
</P>
<P>
   On June 20, 1971, Ohio became the 38th state to ratify the 26th
Amendment, which lowered the minimum voting age to 18 for all
state, national and federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   The new amendment was certified officially in a White House
ceremony conducted by President Nixon on July 5, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the origin of the expression ``the whole nine yards''?
My wife believes it refers to a machine gunner's ammo belt, but I
insist it refers to sail.
</P>
<P>
   A: When Q&AMP;A printed an explanation several years ago, it created
a deluge of theories from readers. Among them: It came from ancient
burial practices in Egypt in which bodies of poor people were
wrapped only in short pieces of silk, but bodies of wealthy people
were fully wrapped, thus taking ``the whole nine yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Another version: The term came from fighter pilots in World War
II whose machine guns used ammo belts in nine-yard lengths, so if
they shot all their rounds of ammunition in a fight, they used
``the whole nine yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, a Scotsman's kilt needs a lot of material, hence, ``the
whole nine yards.''
</P>
<P>
   And still another: It refers to the nine yardarms on a clipper
ship, and when all the sails were being used, it was . . . well,
you know.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these is correct, if you accept the Facts on File
Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins as a resource. It traces
the expression to construction workers, who use the expression when
referring to the maximum capacity of a cement-mixer truck: nine
cubic yards of cement.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
