<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' TV show, when a
contestant phones a friend for help with the answer, Regis Philbin
always says about the person being called, ``I know you can't see
us now.'' Why can't the person at home see the show as it's going
on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because ``Millionaire'' is taped in advance. So, obviously,
when the person at home sees the broadcast, the question already
had been asked at some earlier time. Since ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' is taped before a live audience at ABC's New York
studio, it can appear to viewers at home that the broadcast is
live.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' show recently featured a rerun of the
Osmond family reunion in December. I missed how many grandchildren
and great-grandchildren there are. Do you know? Also, two brothers
were doing sign language. Are they deaf?
</P>
<P>
   A: George and OIive have 9 children: Virl, Tom, Alan, Wayne,
Merrill, Jay, Donny, Marie and Jimmy. Virl has 7 children and 6
grandchildren. Tom has 9 children and 1 granddaughter. Alan has 8
children (all sons) and 2 granddaughters. Wayne has 5 children and
1 grandson. Merrill has 6 children. Jay has 3 children (all sons).
Donny has 5 children (all sons). Marie has 7 children. Jimmy has 3
children.
</P>
<P>
   So the total is 2 parents, 9 children, 53 grandchildren and 10
great-grandchildren, said Jennifer Wallace of Osmond.com.
</P>
<P>
   The two oldest Osmond sons, Virl and Tom, are hearing impaired.
They were the first deaf missionaries sent out by the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, serving the deaf population in
Canada. They aren't part of the Omond Brothers singing group.
</P>
