<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SPACE-WEATHER-$ADV12-     03-09 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-WEATHER-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS MAY SOON FORECAST INVISIBLE 'SPACE WEATHER'
 &HT;    For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Space weathermen believe they are on the verge of
being able to forecast storms in the Earth's magnetic field, where
mysterious turbulence increasingly plagues a technology-dependent
world.
</P>
<P>
   Miles above the familiar dark clouds that have wrecked ships and
caused river valleys to flood throughout history, storms in the
planet's magnetosphere can disrupt activities that most of us now
take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   When these storms blow in, television reception is scrambled.
Pocket pagers go deaf. Cards won't swipe properly at ATM machines
or gasoline pumps. Even electric power grids can fail, subjecting
tens of thousands of of homes and businesses to black-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known for decades that the storms are stirred by
solar flares, super-hot areas caused by enormous explosions on the
face of the sun, but they have not known how to predict when the
flares would occur.
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in Arizona and Colorado announced last week (March
11) in Science magazine that they had successfully ``looked'' all
the way through the sun and were able to detect flares on its far
side.
</P>
<P>
   That ability was based on earthquake-like disturbances created
by developing solar storms on the far side of the sun. The
disturbances sent seismic waves all the way _ about 8 million miles
_ through the sun so they could be detected on the near side.
</P>
<P>
   Since it takes the sun 27 days to make one rotation on its axis,
the discovery should give researchers up to two weeks' notice,
rather than a few hours, before the super-hot blotches make their
way around to face the earth.
</P>
<P>
   And if all goes as planned, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration will launch IMAGE, the world's first ``space
weather'' satellite, this week. Scheduled for launch Saturday
(March 18) from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California, IMAGE is
to monitor the turbulent weather systems in the near-space region
occupied by the Earth's magnetosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Green, director of space science and data at NASA's Goddard
Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., predicts that the satellite
will be so successful that before long similar spacecraft will be
deployed to monitor conditions in the magnetosphere the way weather
satellites keep track of conditions in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the point where we need to know how to understand
space weather,'' he said. ``It is going to be fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no shortage of examples to support that view.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, solar storms sent a flood of charged particles racing
toward the Earth at over a million miles per hour. The storm these
particles generated in the magnetosphere knocked out electric
transformers belonging to Hydro-Quebec, the Montreal-based power
company, and left 6 million people in eastern Canada and the
northeastern United States without electricity for nine hours.
</P>
<P>
   The storms disrupted short-wave radio transmissions, crippled
Coast
</P>
<P>
   Guard navigation systems and spooked automatic garage doors into
opening and closing on their own. Over 80 percent of North
America's pocket pagers went deaf as a post because of another
solar storm two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Risk Insurance Management Society warned its members last
fall that ``storms in space _ originating on the sun, 93 million
miles away _ can have the same financial impact as a hurricane or
an earthquake, resulting in losses of tens of billions of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The flares and another phenomenon known as solar wind happen
because of the sun's own magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what happens there and in the Earth's
magnetosphere, it is useful to recall the common grade school
experiment in which the teacher sprinkles a pinch of iron filings
onto a sheet of paper, then passes a magnet beneath the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The filings immediately arrange themselves in a series of
curving and more or less concentric lines between the two ends of
the magnet, guided by the lines of force that emanate from the
magnet.
</P>
<P>
   As it spins, the core of the sun generates a similar field of
force. However, since the equatorial region of the core spins at a
different speed than the polar regions, the magnet ``lines'' are
not orderly like those of a classroom magnet. Instead, they bend
and overlap and tangle. Where they intersect, they generate
enormous energy, which heats the sun's atmosphere to temperatures
millions of degrees hotter than its surface.
</P>
<P>
   At those temperatures, atoms are ripped apart and plasma
composed of disassociated electrons and protons are sent flooding
through the solar system. This flood of electrically charged
particles is known as the solar wind. The flares cause ``gusts'' in
the solar wind.
</P>
<P>
   Green explained in an interview that on the sun's surface, the
tangle of solar magnetism becomes increasingly wound up, so that
once about every 11 years the sun goes into a ``solar maximum''
phase in which the number and intensity of flares increases. It is
now entering such a phase.
</P>
<P>
   When the solar wind reaches the Earth, it is deflected by this
planet's own magnetic field, which is generated by the rotation of
molten iron and nickel in the planet's core. It surrounds the Earth
like a protective cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   While it is much more orderly than the tangle of solar magnetic
lines, the Earth's magnetic field is also distorted _ by the solar
wind, which flattens the part of the field facing the sun and drags
out the part on the Earth's night side, somewhat like the tail of a
comet.
</P>
<P>
   The magnetosphere refers to charged particles trapped inside the
Earth's magnetic field. They are much like the teacher's iron
filings, but at densities of fewer than a dozen electrons per cubic
inch.
</P>
<P>
   The particles are electrically charged, and even at those
densities, they affect radio waves passing through them. When the
solar wind gusts strike the magnetosphere, turbulence occurs among
the particles, causing magnetosphere ``storms'' that disturb radio
transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   A gasoline pump depends on such transmissions to and from
communications satellites when it makes sure your credit card is
not maxed out before allowing you to fill your tank. If performance
of the satellites is disrupted by the storms, the swipe-and-pump
authorization can break down.
</P>
<P>
   Although the particles that make up the solar wind are deflected
away from the Earth's surface, they can send enormous jolts of
electricity flooding through the magnetosphere, and from there down
into the atmosphere and to the Earth's surface. Such a jolt is what
knocked out Hydro-Quebec's transformers 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The IMAGE satellite, Green explained, will view the patterns
formed by the charged particles trapped in it and sketch the
magnetic field from those patterns.
</P>
<P>
   It will loop through an elliptical polar orbit that takes it
28,000 miles above the North Pole and then swings it down for a
pass 600 miles over the South Pole. Powered by solar cells, it will
use a variety of technologies to map the particles.
</P>
<P>
   One, a Doppler radar not too different from speed detectors used
by police, will measure movements of the particles within the
magnetic field. Four thin antennae will each extend hundreds of
yards from the slowly turning satellite. From end-to-end, the
antennae will be longer than the height of New York's Empire State
Building, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Other, newly created technologies that will sense and image
previously invisible molecular processes. About a month after it is
launched, IMAGE is to start sketching the first picture of the
magnetosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Although around 30 satellites and other space craft have
collected samples of the magnetosphere, scientists have only a
crude understanding of its makeup, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine yourself as a scientist in this field for 30 years,
and all you've been able to do as you go into space is launch your
little probe and look at the temperature here and the temperature
there, particles here and there _ just various pieces of this
enormous cloud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 30 years, the best you can do is draw cartoons of it.
Now, imagine, all of a sudden, I will be able to show you an
honest-to-goodness picture of what it looks like. It's what we've
been working 30 or 40 years to do. That's where we are right now,
with this spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the pinnacle of your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
