<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-COURSE-BREADTH-ART-BO     03-09 2167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURSE-BREADTH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THREE CLASS ACTS ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos were sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Repeating for Springfield Union-News; originally moved 3/2)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  What do Duke Ellington, Alan Greenspan, and Aristotle have in
common?
</P>
<P>
   Genius, yes. (We'll grant Al some leeway here.) Beyond that,
each is a featured player in a popular course being offered on a
local campus this semester.
</P>
<P>
   One course is 30 years old and imaginatively combines community
service with classroom study. Another is a year old and like its
subject, the stock market, could scarcely be trendier. A third is
brand new and stylishly untrendy: a course on early American jazz,
taught by a Mozart scholar.
</P>
<P>
   The courses, chosen not entirely at random, sample the variety
and popularity of what's being taught at area colleges at any given
time.
</P>
<P>
   Literature and Arts B-80: The Swing Era Examines American jazz
from the early 1930s to bebop. Considers sociological issues and
the relationship of swing-era jazz to classical music and popular
song, to place swing's achievements into a broader historical and
musical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I call a mean tune!'' Robert Levin shouts out over
the closing bars of ``Hocus Pocus,'' a 1934 Fletcher Henderson cut,
featuring the incomparable Coleman Hawkins on tenor sax. Levin then
fires up a CD dub of a Louis Armstrong recording he inherited from
his father, a jazz buff.
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour, the perpetual-motion Harvard prof cannot seem
to stand _ or sit _ still. Bouncing over to the piano, Levin bangs
outs a Bach prelude followed by some Jelly Roll Morton licks.
Strutting around the Sanders Theatre stage in front of 560
students, he dips his shoulders and wags his fingers in classic
hepcat style to a peppery clarinet solo by Buster Bailey. Close
your eyes and you can almost smell the Cotton Club circa 1937.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're figuring out what makes this music tick as well as
connecting to it emotionally,'' Levin tells his audience, a mixed
bag of Harvard students and AARP types who are auditing.
</P>
<P>
   For Levin, a classically trained keyboardist who studied with
Nadia Boulanger, ``The Swing Era'' represents a chance not only to
branch out into more of a pop-music idiom but to expose a younger
generation, in a serious and scholarly way, to the recordings he
grooved on as a kid in Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple reason I'm doing this is that I'm crazy about the
music,'' says Levin, whose piano-thumping lecture style has been
packing them in all semester. ``But that's not reason enough. The
fact is, this is the first truly mass popular music in US history.
I want students to get a real insight into the aesthetics of swing,
the way they'd view a painting in a fine arts course or read a poem
in a literature class.''
</P>
<P>
   The course benefited from an early buzz around campus, in part
because Levin also teaches a popular course on chamber music and is
famous for his energy and showmanship. For most of the students in
L&AMP;A B-80, Bix Beiderbecke and Benny Goodman belong as much to
ancient musical history as Beethoven and Liszt do. But as they're
learning, American music didn't start with Jimi Hendrix and Miles
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah Trierweiler, a freshman from Denver, was initially drawn
to Levin's course because it fills a core requirement. ``I listen
to mostly KISS-108 stuff,'' says Trierweiler, ``but not a lot of
jazz. This looked like fun, though. Levin is pretty quirky, too. He
dances around a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Bolton, a junior from Alabama, grew up near New
Orleans listening to '60s and '70s rock. Now, she digs
jazz-influenced groups like Phish. ``I wanted to understand the
background more,'' says Bolton, who concedes that Levin's use of
terminology is ``tough to follow at times.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart and soul of Levin's lectures are close audio analyses
of classic swing tracks. Lectures on Goodman and Ellington
incorporated repeated playings of ``King Porter Stomp'' and ``Mood
Indigo,'' performed by different bands with different arrangements.
Like any good jazzman, though, Levin is an inveterate improviser. A
discourse on Ellington's recording of ``Take the A Train,'' for
instance, segued into a brief history of the Manhattan subway
system.
</P>
<P>
   Says Levin, ``My secret goal is to build students' listening
libraries, the way others bought `Rubber Soul' or `Born in the
USA.' Because once you've got these recordings, you'll listen to
them. I'm on a cultural crusade here.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Bruce PL 088-089: Person and Social Responsibility
(PULSE) Course requirements include 10 to 12 hours per week of
community service. In light of classic philosophical and
theological texts, students address the relationship of self and
society, the nature of community, the mystery of suffering, and the
practical difficulties of developing a just society.
</P>
<P>
   All things being equal, there is almost no chance Kristin
Kusmierz would have crossed paths with Michael Brady during her
college years. Or wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Kusmierz is a BC junior from North Kingstown, R.I. Brady is a
44-year-old, HIV-positive substance abuser from Scituate who never
went to college and who is ``pretty much on my last chance right
now,'' Brady says.
</P>
<P>
   BC's PULSE course is nothing if not a great equalizer, though.
And so one day last week, Kusmierz and Brady took a stroll together
around Shattuck Hospital in Jamaica Plain, where Brady is a patient
in the Living and Recovering Community program (LARC) and Kusmierz
works as a student volunteer through the Victory Programs agency.
The two found more in common than either might have dreamed of four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not like a conversation between a college student and a
dope fiend,'' Brady recalled afterward. ``We talked about the
virus, about substance abuse and her maybe going into human
services after she graduates.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to hear what a student has to say to someone who's
been on the street for 30 years.'' Kusmierz nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually see people living with the virus teaches you more
than any book can,'' she said, seated in a cramped hospital
conference room with two fellow PULSE students and half a dozen
LARC patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In class, we focus on how to live your life, how to develop a
system of meaning that builds a community. It's much easier to
internalize something when you read it and see it.'' Kusmierz is
one of 300 BC students enrolled in the program this year,
continuing a tradition established in 1970. In weekly section
meetings, students discuss writings by Aristotle, Rousseau, and
Locke along with contemporary authors like Charles Taylor and
Jonathan Kozol. They also keep detailed journals, diaries that
often provoke soul-searching examinations of what personal and
social responsibility truly mean.
</P>
<P>
   The course has seldom been more popular. About 150 students were
turned away this year for space reasons, despite the heavy reading
load and community-service requirement. Program director Donald
McMenamin says word of mouth is his best recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids hear from other students who say it's the most
important course they've taken at BC,'' says McMenamin. ``They
start out thinking they're going to change the world, and they
leave realizing how much they've been changed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   In class, McMenamin and his colleagues push students to relate
what they're reading to issues they've encountered in the field.
Thus a recent discussion of Taylor's ``The Ethics of Authenticity''
prompted McMenamin to ponder the relationship between the
individual and society, asking students if there were anything like
a shared definition of the American Dream. ``Does your concept of
the dream correspond to that of the people in the placement
agencies where you work?'' he inquired. ``If the good life is going
to be achieved,'' he argued, ``all the voices must be at the table.
If we exclude some of those voices, we risk impoverishing our
notion of what is authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kusmierz noted that as people focus more on individual freedoms
and less on how their actions affect others, the dividing line
between haves and have-nots sharpens.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as large segments of society can't realize their
definitions of the good life,'' she said, ``programs like LARC will
exist.'' The voices heard around a hospital conference table last
week were authentic, all right, painfully so. Amid the sobering
talk of viral loads and T-cell counts, though, there was also
laughter. And that constituted a learning experience in itself.
</P>
<P>
   John Miller, a LARC patient from Dorchester, glanced at Richie
Moriarity, a sophomore from Maryland, and said that if he could
give these BC kids one gift, it would be ``an awareness of drug
addiction. Because there's always a line to cross, and I crossed
it. Once you cross it, you can't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Moriarity smiled back. ``Being at BC gives you a warped sense of
reality,'' he said softly. ``Everyone there is fortunate. Everyone
has plenty of money. It knocks me off my feet every day I come over
here. It's like _ `` Moriarity glanced around the table _ ``hel-lo,
Richie. Welcome to the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   EXP 88S: Understanding the Stock Market Students will begin to
develop an understanding of and an appreciation for the
fundamentals of stock market investing, doing so within the realm
of larger social, demographic, political, and economic
contexts.``Who knows what a margin is?'' asks Timothy Stratford in
a basement classroom of Braker Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one?'' Twenty-nine students sit on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' says Stratford, writing ``THE MAGIC OF MARGIN'' on a
blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the whole premise of what I'm about to tell you is that
you should never do it, but it's crucial to know about.'' A hand
goes up. ``Yes?'' ``Alan Greenspan said today he was unconcerned
about margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratford laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he say why?'' he asks, tapping the board. ``OK, here's my
concern,'' continues Stratford. ``It's buying stock with money you
don't have. It's the biggest disaster you can do. Mutual funds do
it because they can get in and out of stocks quickly. You can't.
Any questions?'' Thus began week six of an unusual course offered
by Tufts University's Experimental College. Call it Greenspan 101.
From calculating interest rates to shorting tech stocks, the course
aims to demystify the Dow while equipping students with the basics
of portfolio building. Chaucer? Organic Chem? Forget about it. The
cheer you hear is tuition-strapped parents yelling, ``Finally, a
course with a return on investment!'' Stratford, an ex-bartender
who logged 17 years as a broker, was likewise cheered when 200
students showed up for the course last spring, six times the number
he could accommodate.``The ones who don't get in beg me for a
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   says Stratford, now teaching the course for the third time. ``If
I were a broker and 180 prospective clients showed up, I'd be
thrilled. But I'm not trying to sell them anything here.''
</P>
<P>
   The students, most of whom admit they don't know NASDAQ from
NASCAR, must write brief application essays. ``Like learning to fix
my car and cook a turkey,'' wrote one, ``learning about the stock
market is one of those goals that I've had for a while but haven't
gotten around to addressing.'' Gushed another, ``I only know that
those mysterious numbers that flash by right before the commercials
on the national news excite me more than any other possibility in
my life.'' Ah, youth.
</P>
<P>
   Two students have brought parents to class. Drew Carlton, a
senior from Shaker Heights, Ohio, took the course last fall. An
experienced day trader, Carlton knew as much about Internet trading
as Stratford did, maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says Carlton, ``I liked it because it's a lot more
relevant than most college classes. This is something everyone
should know about.'' Jennie Robin, a senior psychology major from
Long Island, knew nothing about investing before this semester.
``I'm about to graduate, and I thought I'd better take one course
in something relevant,'' says Robin. Her midterm assessment? ``It's
given me a basis for reading the business page every day,'' she
says. ``Some things are still unclear, though, like inflation and
interest rates or _ `` join the club, Jennie `` _ what actually
moves the stock market up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   If Stratford preaches anything, it's the value of patience and
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Strategies like dollar cost averaging _ investing small amounts
consistently to capitalize on market fluctuations _ are emphasized
over picking the next hot dot-com stock or go-go mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Says Stratford, ``Some of these kids want to make money, some
have parents who think this is good stuff to know, and some want to
walk into job interviews and not sound like idiots.'' He smiles.
``I'm here to help them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
