<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     03-09 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCIONS OF POLITICAL DYNASTIES BATTLE FOR PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 12)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON 
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If ruthless old King George III were still around,
he probably would chortle over the irony of George W. Bush and Al
Gore, sons of prominent political dynasties, battling for the
presidency of a republic that long ago rejected leadership by royal
succession.
</P>
<P>
   The English king might also smile at the fact that when Gore
journeys to Los Angeles in August to be anointed officially as the
Democratic Party's presidential nominee, he will share the
spotlight with America's most exalted political dynasty, the
Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   It is inevitable that the convention in Los Angeles will be
steeped in nostalgia because it was there that John F. Kennedy was
nominated 40 years ago. For a few fleeting hours in August,
sentimental Democrats may seek to transform the City of Angels into
a reincarnation of Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy connection is important to Gore. In various public
opinion polls, Americans list Kennedy among the outstanding
presidents in American history. The rating is probably more a
tribute to the Kennedy elegance, eloquence and premature death than
to his performance in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it could help Gore in his race with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles also is the city where Robert F. Kennedy was fatally
wounded 32 years ago after winning the 1968 Democratic presidential
primary. In addition, California is a state in which Edward M.
Kennedy defeated Jimmy Carter in the 1980 Democratic primary, but
to no avail. Carter was renominated and then defeated by Republican
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore might ponder a valuable lesson from the Kennedy campaign.
Against the advice of angry liberals, John Kennedy selected his
chief opponent for the presidential nomination, Senate Majority
Leader Lyndon Johnson of Texas, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberals threatened to bolt the party. Robert Kennedy
didn't like Johnson and strongly opposed the choice. But John
Kennedy stuck by his decision despite the fact that his
relationship with Johnson was nothing like Gore's warm relationship
with Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After President Kennedy was assassinated in Dallas, Johnson, a
master legislative tactician, took over the presidency and passed
into law every major item that had been on the liberals' agenda
since Harry Truman's presidency and, in some cases, since Franklin
Roosevelt's.
</P>
<P>
   That agenda included monumental civil rights legislation,
Medicare, Medicaid, federal aid to education, a war on poverty and
protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, after that record of achievement, Johnson led
America into the quagmire of Vietnam, and tragedy stalked our land.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Kennedy-Johnson ticket in 1960, however,
provides a second lesson for Gore: A candidate's chief political
opponent can be a helpful running mate and vice president if he
knows his way around Washington and has ideas about ways to improve
the lot of the American people. That fact of political life could
lead Gore to seek former Sen. Bill Bradley as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many other possible vice presidential nominees:
California Gov. Gray Davis, Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Sen.
Dianne Feinstein of California and even Sen. Bob Kerrey, who
actively supported Bradley in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Political dynasties are not new to America. In the earliest days
of the republic, voters elected John Adams as president and later
chose his son, John Quincy Adams for the same office.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been occupied by two Harrisons _ William
Henry and his grandson Benjamin. Neither left much of a mark on the
presidency or the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the presidential giants of the 20th century were distant
cousins Theodore and Franklin D. Roosevelt. Both had sons who
aspired to political glory, but never quite made it.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1960 has either political party chosen Los Angeles as
the site of its national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Although Los Angeles is 3,000 miles across the country from
Kennedy family base in Boston, it has become something of a second
home for the peripatetic Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy frequently visited the city where he mingled with
the flamboyant Hollywood ``Rat Pack'' headed by Frank Sinatra. It
presumably was there that he first met Marilyn Monroe, who became
an important hidden factor in his life.
</P>
<P>
   One of Kennedy's sisters, Pat, lived in a Santa Monica
beachfront home with her husband, actor Peter Lawford, who was an
intimate fixture in the Rat Pack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Kennedy and Tennessee Senator Albert Gore Sr. both
sought the Democratic vice presidential nomination on a ticket
headed by Adlai Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   Having been nominated for president a second time, Stevenson
decided that the way to breathe excitement into the Chicago
convention was to let the delegates pick his running mate. So, he
opened the race up to all who wished to take part.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees included Kennedy, Gore Sr., Sen. Hubert Humphrey of
Minnesota, New York Mayor Robert Wagner, and Gore's fellow senator
from Tennessee, Estes Kefauver.
</P>
<P>
   By the end if the first ballot, it was apparent that support for
Gore Sr., Humphrey and Wagner was fading. That meant a second
ballot showdown between Kennedy and Kefauver.
</P>
<P>
   The result was riveting as votes switched from one candidate to
another and the Kennedy and Kefauver tallies grew. Finally, Senator
Gore shifted Tennessee's vote to Kefauver and Oklahoma changed its
votes from Gore to Kefauver. Enough states followed Gore's lead to
put Kefauver over the top.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy won millions of friends and admirers by striding to
the stage to make a gracious speech urging that Kefauver's
nomination for vice president be made unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   If Speaker Sam Rayburn, the convention chairman, had not
recognized Gore and the Oklahoma delegation, Kennedy said later,
``I might have won that race with Senator Kefauver _ and my
political career would now be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Like European royalty, American dynasties are linked to one
another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
