<HEADLINE>
RIDE EASY, KNOWING YOUR CAR'S STREET-LEGAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What makes a car ``street-legal''?
</P>
<P>
   _ W.D., Del Mar, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``It means that the car complies with all federal, state and
local mandates,'' said Greg Rager, editor of High Performance Mopar
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Car regulations involve tires, lighting, emissions, ``ride
height'' and many other things that a car enthusiast can modify.
These laws vary from state to state and sometimes even county to
county, Rager said. ``What's legal in Florida is not necessarily
legal in California.''
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, you should familiarize yourself with local
ordinances and state laws before buying a car that's described as
street-legal. ``Caveat emptor,'' Rager said. ``If you're buying a
modified car in any state, you really ought to make it your
business to know what the laws of that state are.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Cindy Crawford?
</P>
<P>
   _ T., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Crawford in care of the William Morris Agency, 151
El Camino Drive, Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who turned 34 on Feb. 20, married nightclub owner
Rande Gerber in 1998, and they have a 7-month-old son, Presley
Walker Gerber.
</P>
<P>
   On her official Web site, www.cindy.com, Crawford posts monthly
updates on her activities and answers reader e-mail. ``We're in
Hawaii sneaking in a few days vacation,'' she wrote this month.
``Rande and I went golfing and even sporting-clay shooting, but
mostly just hanging out with Presley in the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many years ago, I had a small policy with the Conger Life
Insurance Co. in Florida. Is the company still in business?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.B., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The Conger Life Insurance Co., also known as Florida Life
Insurance, was placed into liquidation by Florida insurance
regulators in 1997. Conger policies were purchased by Life and
Health of America, so you should still be covered by the policy.
</P>
<P>
   To inquire about your insurance, send the policy number to Life
and Health of America, 6363 Taft St., Suite 202, Hollywood, FL
33024, or call (954) 920-7090.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
