<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD WE AID MOZAMBIQUE? SUCH A QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month ago, a studio audience probably could not have helped a
quiz show contestant win any part of a million dollars if the
following question had been asked:
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the capital of the African country that President
Clinton recently described as having the world's fastest growing
economy? Is it (a) Lagos; (b) Kinshasa; (c) Maputo; or (d)
Johannesburg?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not altogether certain that much help from that lifeline
would be forthcoming even today. That question was popped the other
day to a well-read, much-informed, policy-wonk journalist, and his
final answer was Lagos, the largest city in Nigeria, although he
wondered if it might not be Johannesburg, the industrial capital of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer, of course, is Maputo, the capital of
Mozambique. Presumably a goodly number of the audience for a ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' broadcast might have gotten wind of the
economic progress that has been happening in Mozambique because of
the tragedy of almost biblical proportions that has engulfed that
country.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks of drenching rain and a cyclone have transformed
Mozambique into a waterlogged nightmare of death, danger,
dehydration, devastation, hunger and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, more than 400 bodies had been recovered. As the
waters recede, that dreadful count is expected to exceed 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the country's farmland is inundated. Roads and bridges
have been washed away by the surging waters of the worst floods to
descend upon southern Africa in half a century. Between 800,000 and
900,000 people are said to have been victimized to some degree by
the enormous natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Although the devastation is not confined to Mozambique, that
country has been hit hardest. And the tragic irony of it is that it
struck just when Mozambique was doing so well, when it was being
hailed far and wide as a great African success story.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mozambique gained its independence from Portugal in
1975, it was embroiled in civil war until the early 1990s _ a
fierce struggle between the Marxist-oriented Frelimo government and
the Renamo insurgents backed by the apartheid government of South
Africa. Although the Frelimo government allowed a multiparty
electoral system in 1990, the war didn't end until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the multiparty system was put in place. And in
1994, Frelimo outpolled Renamo in free elections. Last year,
Frelimo repeated that feat.
</P>
<P>
   Democratization and a switch to a free-market economy opened the
way for forging strong economic links to South Africa and made
Mozambique more attractive for foreign investment generally.
</P>
<P>
   During each of the past three years, Mozambique has posted an
economic growth rate of 10 percent. Such has been the pace of
economic improvement in Mozambique that last year it opened a stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The country's prospects brightened even more when Mozambique's
primary governmental creditors agreed to reschedule most of its
international debt. A sizable percentage of its most burdensome
debt _ i.e., export credit debt on which interest is charged at
market rates _ was forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Now the floods have come and the skies have darkened for
Mozambique. The country's infrastructure is in shambles. Hundreds
of millions of dollars will be needed to put it back together
again.
</P>
<P>
   International aid is now flooding in, although some have
criticized the tardiness of its arrival from the United States and
some other developed nations. It will be some time before things
there can be restored to a semblance of normality.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that immediate assistance, the developed nations
should feel an obligation to make the necessary investment in
Mozambique to put it back on the progressive track on which it had
embarked before Mother Nature unleashed her fury upon the region.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States in particular, Mozambique's catastrophe
offers an opportunity to demonstrate the strength of its professed
commitment to paying more attention to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has made a good start by dispatching
U.S. military personnel to help with the rescue and rebuilding
efforts and in joining with Britain in agreeing to forgive more of
Mozambique's debt, now estimated at about $88 million.
</P>
<P>
   This country must also do its utmost to persuade other foreign
powers, the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund to take
similar action. Mozambique cannot possibly get back on its feet
while trying to service that debt obligation.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't need the intellectual wattage of a ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' contestant to figure out that it's in our national
interests to support free enterprise and democracy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
