</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-COURT (Miami) _ A federal judge hears arguments on whether
Elian Gonzalez should stay in the United States or be returned to
Cuba. Judge K. Michael Moore, who will now weigh arguments in the
case, gives no indication of when he will decide the fate of the
6-year-old boy. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   WOUNDED-EAGLE (San Francisco) _ Six years after a young bald
eagle left the care of the San Francisco Zoo for the wilds, Bobbie
is back. The bird lost part of a wing after being wounded by a
gunshot in January and will become a permanent resident of the
zoo's Eagle Island. By JUSTINO AGUILA. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NINTENDO-GLOVES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nintendo of America Inc. has
agreed to ship protective gloves to any of the estimated 1.2
million households that bought the game. The deal is part of an
out-of-court settlement with the state of New York in which
prosecutors argued that the hands of children using the game have
suffered blistering and bleeding. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In any war, political or military, a
good general has an exit strategy. For Bill Bradley, that was easy.
With no primary victories, he had to pull out of the presidential
race. But for Sen. John McCain, there are more options. He
suspended his campaign, but he can still be a force in the
Republican Party. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
