<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINTENDO-GLOVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NINTENDO TO PROVIDE PROTECTIVE GLOVES TO GAME PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nintendo boasts that its video game controller
will ``take a licking and keep on ticking,'' but the hands of the
children using it have been left blistered and bleeding, according
to the New York attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In a case surrounding ``Mario Party,'' Nintendo of America Inc.
agreed to ship protective gloves to any of the estimated 1.15
million households in the United States that bought the game,
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said in announcing an out-of-court
settlement with the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   With the company offering up to four pairs of the gloves to each
buyer and the gloves retailing for about $20, the settlement could
cost Nintendo upwards of $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer announced the settlement on Wednesday, calling it ``good
news for parents throughout the nation. Nintendo has agreed to take
responsibility for the effect of its games on young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Pritchard, a spokeswoman for Spitzer, said the company
had received about 100 complaints on injuries from the game, and an
undetermined number of people had called the attorney general's
office as well.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is partly in the hand-held controller _ which
Nintendo's Web site describes as ``ergonomically designed'' _ and
partly in the Mario Party game itself. To play Mario Party, which
is targeted at children ages 7 to 13, users must navigate through
certain ``mini-games,'' allowing them to collect coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for Mario to work off some of that pasta,'' one
demonstration page on the Web site reads. ``A big Boo threatens you
from behind, so unless you can generate enough light by turning
those pedals ultrafast, Boo will get you and your coins, too!''
</P>
<P>
   But to move quickly, some children press their palm onto the
controller's joystick, which has grooves etched into a circular
tip. The friction and pressure on the grooves have caused burns,
cuts, punctures, blistering and tearing of the skin, according to
the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo did not return a call for comment, but on its Web site
it is now posting a warning, ``To avoid irritation to your skin
and/or damage to the Control Stick, do not rotate it with the palm
of your hand. Rotate the Control Stick with your thumb or by
holding it between your thumb and forefinger.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the mini-games within Mario Party appear to encourage
the use of the palm. Spitzer singled out six: Paddle Battle, Tog O'
War, Pedal Power, Cast Aways, Deep Sea Divers, and Mecha Fly Guy.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain the gloves, people will have to submit an outline of
their hand on paper, along with some kind of proof of ownership,
which can include a receipt, credit card statement, serial number,
or even a photo of the user with the game, Pritchard said. The
company has a consumer hot line, 800-521-0900.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering the gloves, the company paid the state
$75,000 to cover the cost of the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
