<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALORIES-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: WITH CALORIES-ANSWERS and FOOD-CALORIES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defuse caloric bombs by measuring portions
</P>
<P>
   In her new book Portion Savvy (Pocket Books, $24), nutritionist
Carrie Latt Wiatt shows how portions add up to calorie overload.
</P>
<P>
   A simple meal of cereal, milk and juice can become a caloric
bomb if the portions are assumed and not measured. For her recipes
to work, you must measure the serving portions. Here are recipes
from her book and others.
</P>
<P>
   Greek feta chicken
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless, skinless chicken breast halves (weighing between 4
and 6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fat-free Italian salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces feta cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped, drained artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   5 sun-dried tomato halves, blanched in boiling water until
softened (chop to make 1/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped, pitted black olives (nicoise or kalamata)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the chicken breasts in a nonreactive dish and pour the
Italian dressing over them. Cover, refrigerate and marinate at
least 1 hour or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350(degrees). Coat a baking pan with cooking
spray and arrange the drained chicken in the pan. Bake for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, mix together all the remaining ingredients in a
medium bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Top each chicken breast with 2 tablespoons of the feta cheese
mixture and return to the oven for 10 minutes or until cheese is
softened. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 pieces of chicken and 1 cup topping.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional information for 4-ounce chicken breast and 2
tablespoons topping: 138 calories, 3.4 g. fat, 22.7 g. protein,
31.1 g. carbohydrates, 59 mg. cholesterol, 342 mg. sodium.)
</P>
<P>
   Ginger-crusted salmon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup low-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 4 teaspoons mirin (sweet rice wine), divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 salmon fillets (each weighing 5 to 8 ounces) Preheat oven to
350(degrees) and coat a baking sheet with cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together soy sauce, 1/4 cup of the mirin, the water and
sugar until sugar is dissolved. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bread crumbs, horseradish, ginger, 4 teaspoons mirin,
salt and pepper in the bowl of a food processor and process until
moistened and well combined.
</P>
<P>
   Press 1 tablespoon of the mixture onto each side of each salmon
fillet and place on prepared baking sheet. Bake without turning
until the crust is golden brown, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve salmon drizzled with reserved sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes salmon for 4, 1/2 cup breading mixture and 3/4 cup sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional information for 5-ounce salmon with 2 tablespoons
breading and 2 tablespoons sauce: 228 calories, 5.4 g. fat, 29.9 g.
protein, 9.2 g. carbohydrates, 74 mg. cholesterol, 874 mg. sodium.)
</P>
<P>
   Barbecued beef sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef chuck, trimmed of all visible fat
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fat-free, reduced sodium beef broth
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 to 1/4 teaspoon hot-pepper sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced 2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   For serving: 8 whole-wheat hamburger buns. Warm a large pot or
Dutch oven over medium heat until hot enough for drops of water to
dance on surface. Add the beef. Cook for 15 minutes, turning as
needed, until browned on all sides. Add the broth, onions and
pepper. Cover and cook over low heat for 2 to 3 hours, or until the
meat is very tender when pierced with a sharp knife.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large saucepan, combine the remaining
ingredients and bring to a boil. Reduce the heat to low. Simmer for
10 minutes to blend the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Remove beef from the pot onto a cutting board and slice it.
Transfer the beef slices to the saucepan and heat briefly in the
sauce. Taste and add more hot-pepper sauce if desired. Toast the
buns, if desired. Divide beef equally over the buns; spoon sauce
over each and cover with bun tops.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 294 calories, 8 g. fat, 30 g. protein, 24 g.
carbohydrates, 66 mg. cholesterol, 566 mg. sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Lower-fat peanut butter cookies
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup natural peanut butter (available in most supermarkets)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups unbleached or all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375(degrees).
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine 2/3 cup of the sugar, the butter or
margarine and buttermilk. With electric mixer, beat on medium speed
until creamy. Add the peanut butter, egg and vanilla. Beat on low
speed to mix well. In a medium bowl, combine dry ingredients and
stir into peanut butter mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the dough by teaspoonfuls onto an ungreased baking sheet.
Flatten with a fork dipped in the remaining tablespoon of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10 to 12 minutes, or until lightly browned. Cool on a rack
for 10 minutes before removing from pan. Allow to cool completely
before storing in airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 40 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 65 calories, 3.5 g. fat, 2 g. protein, 7.5 g.
carbohydrates, 6 mg. cholesterol, 86 mg. sodium.
</P>
<P>
   (Above recipes from Homestyle Cooking Made Healthy by Jeanne
Jones, Rodale Press, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
