<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SHOW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concept cars take spotlight at auto show
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some concept cars at The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
International Auto Show that stand a pretty good chance of making
it to the showroom not much different than the way they look today:
Ford's Thunderbird retro roadster and the Mercury Mountaineer
sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   There are others that are platforms for technology or design
ideas, like the Chrysler Chronos and the Oldsmobile Profile.
</P>
<P>
   But some former concepts have become reality and either are in
dealer showrooms or will be soon. Among them are the Chrysler PT
Cruiser, a retro minivan that is attracting attention and creating
waiting lists around the country; the edgy Pontiac Aztek
sport-utility; and the new little brother in the Ford SUV family,
the Escape.
</P>
<P>
   Besides concepts, the car show, sponsored by the Metro Atlanta
Automobile Dealers Association, features more than 500 new 2000 and
2001 model-year vehicles from more than 30 automakers. Here are
some highlights of the show, which continues through Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler
</P>
<P>
   One of this year's show stoppers is the Chrysler PT Cruiser, a
small, retro-looking minivan based on the Dodge Neon.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Dodge division of Chrysler group re-enters NASCAR
racing next year with its Intrepid. An early version of the red
racing machine that could be piloted by Georgia's Bill Elliott is
on display. For more conventional drivers, the company is showing
its redesigned Dodge and Chrysler minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its stable of sport-utility vehicles, Jeep is featuring
the Commander concept vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The German side of the family is showing the CL500 sedan and the
Alabama-built M-Class sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford
</P>
<P>
   From the mammoth Excursion and the hybrid Sport Trac to the
smaller Escape and the Mountaineer concept vehicle, light trucks
take the spotlight for the Ford and Mercury divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The newest entries include the 2000 Sport Trac, which already is
arriving in showrooms. The hybrid sport-utility/pickup truck
combines the seating from the Explorer SUV and adds a small pickup
bed behind it.
</P>
<P>
   While the Excursion, the largest SUV on the planet, has been on
sale for months, Ford also is showing the new addition at the small
end of the line, the Escape. It's smaller than the Ranger-based
Explorer but larger than its competition, the Honda CR-V and Toyota
RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury Mountaineer sport-utility concept is nearing its
final form before production. It will replace the current Explorer
clone.
</P>
<P>
   Besides SUVs being marketed under the Ford Outfitters theme,
Ford also is showing its 2001 F-Series SuperCrew full-size,
four-door pickup truck. The vehicle joins a number of similar-size
and smaller competitors in going beyond the usual extended cab. The
full-size rear doors open to a full-size back seat where full-size
adults can sit comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight also is on two cars, the Ford Thunderbird concept
and the Lincoln LS luxury sport sedan, which won Motor Trend's Car
of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   The new T-Bird joins the retro craze, going back to its 1950s
roots as a two-seater with a removable hardtop sporting porthole
windows and just a hint of turquoise in the Thunderbird logo. The
car is expected to go on sale in fall 2001 as either a 2001 or 2002
model.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display are the redesigned 2000 Ford Taurus and Mercury
Sable, both built at Hapeville and loaded with new safety features,
and the company's new small car, the Focus.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors
</P>
<P>
   GM divisions are wheeling out three concepts, two of which are
nearly ready to go on sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Pontiac Aztek is a sport-utility based on the company's
minivan platform, but it sure doesn't look like the Montanas and
Ventures rolling out of Doraville. Its sharp angles and aggressive
appearance are designed to appeal to younger buyers with active
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   To help them do that, it has an array of standard and optional
features, including a pull-out cargo tray. The tailgate is designed
for _ well _ tailgating, with sculpted seats and rear-facing
radio/CD speakers for the party.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztek will be in showrooms this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For grown-ups, the vehicle gets a different treatment from Buick
as the Rendezvous. The more traditional-looking SUV incorporates a
number of refinements for comfort, style and safety that Buick
hopes will help it hold on to buyers who have been moving from the
division's sedans. The Rendezvous is Buick's first truck and should
go on sale next year.
</P>
<P>
   The third concept, the Oldsmobile Profile, holds gee-whiz
technology such as voice-activated controls, Internet access and a
sliding rear door for a sedan. Olds also is showing the 2001 Aurora
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all from the General.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet displays two of its new, redesigned cars, the Monte
Carlo and Impala. Joining the Corvettes on the floor is a pace car
for the Le Mans-style race at Sebring, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturn division shows off its new, larger line, the LS, and
GMC is displaying its renamed Suburban, now known as the Yukon XL.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac shows its technological muscle in the DeVille. It
features Night Vision technology, which uses infrared signals
transmitted from the center of the grille to ``see'' in the dark.
The car also has back-up warning signals that beep when the car
gets too close to an obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   There's even some fun and games in the Buick display. A trailer
houses golf displays featuring Buick spokesman Tiger Woods and
automaker-sponsored tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Honda
</P>
<P>
   It's not a concept car, but it's a concept _ the 70 miles per
gallon gasoline-electric engine Honda Insight hybrid. The bright
green car would have attracted plenty of visitors anyhow, but with
gasoline prices at record levels and likely to go higher, interest
should be especially keen in two-seat coupe that can laugh as its
drives past a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a sportier turn of mind, Honda also is showing
its S2000 roadster. Look closely at dashboard just to the left of
the steering wheel. That red starter button is one of the car's
cooler features.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese automaker is going both big and little. In the
former category, it's showing the new Sequoia sport-utility
vehicle, which is even bigger than its current Land Cruiser. The
2001-model vehicle is comparable in size to the Ford Expedition.
Also on display is Toyota's full-size pickup, the Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   On the small side is the 2000 MR2 Spyder roadster, a snub-nosed
little sportster that will be on sale soon. In between, Toyota is
showing its hot compact, the Echo, which is being marketed to
children of baby boomers who sometimes are known as echo boomers.
</P>
<P>
   And not to be outdone in the mileage department, Toyota also is
displaying its high-mileage hybrid Prius with a gasoline-electric
engine.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean carmaker is bounding into the crossover vehicle
market with its own, the CrossTour, a coupe with a liftgate and the
back-seat utility of an SUV. It's also keeping touch with reality
by showing its new sport-utility, the 2001 Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
