<HEADER>
A1988 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FOOD-CALORIES-COX     03-09 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CALORIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dieter's dilemma: Calories really do count
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For dieters today, it's hooray for protein and hold the
carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, it was up with carbs and down with fat.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since calories were mentioned in any of
the diets.
</P>
<P>
   But they do count _ some more than others, according to
nutrition experts.
</P>
<P>
   Swinging from one diet craze to the other, following one
nutrition controversy after another, we've lost the focus on the
role calories play in nutrition, says Ellen Haas, former
undersecretary of the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed for years to reduce fat in the diet and after many
years, the manufacturers started listening. As a result, they gave
us thousands of products lower in fats, but still high in sugars
and calories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's missing is balance _ in our foods, and in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange dichotomy that more people than ever say they're
dieting and watching their weight, yet the numbers for overweight
Americans are notably high.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
reported that the number of obese Americans _ those at least 30
percent over ideal body
</P>
<P>
   weight _ rose from 12 percent in 1991 to 17.9 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The number of obese Floridians increased almost 72 percent, from
10.1
</P>
<P>
   percent in 1991 to 17.4 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate study, Tufts University researchers found that 63
percent of
</P>
<P>
   men and 55 percent of women over the age of 25 are obese or
overweight, the highest rate ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for weight gain is simple: We're taking in more
calories than we use; we're eating more and moving less.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem simple to eat less and exercise more. For most of
us, it's one of the most difficult things to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to weight control, Americans will try
anything,'' said Jackie Berning, professor at the University of
Colorado and spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association.
``But they don't want calories to count. What they want is to be
able to eat the foods they like, not count calories, and still lose
weight.''
</P>
<P>
   They also don't want to think about portion control. ``We
supersize everything, and wonder why we gain 10 pounds. It's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheah Rarback, a Miami dietitian who is also a spokeswoman for
the ADA, said Americans as a society are bombarded with food _ from
television commercials to fast-food outlets to convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet we have to seek out opportunities for physical exercise.
We're not walking, we're driving to the gym. We've become more and
more sedentary, yet we're being served bigger portions that our
bodies don't need. Our caloric intake is out of balance. And our
lifestyle equation is out of balance,'' Rarback said.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh, unprocessed foods are in short supply at restaurants. The
more processed the food, the higher in calories it's likely to be,
and more empty of nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fruits and vegetables are nutrient-dense, not calorie-dense,''
she said. ``They're also low in fat. They're high in flavor and you
get a lot of bang for your buck, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   That's before processing.
</P>
<P>
   A cup of broccoli has 46 calories; a cup of frozen broccoli from
Pillsbury is 120 calories. An almost imperceptible sauce on the
broccoli creates the added calories.
</P>
<P>
   Simple homemade mashed potatoes with margarine, whole milk and
salt have 111 calories per half cup. But those same potatoes made
from French's mashed potato mix jump to 140 calories, and they gain
31 mg. of sodium _ it's all in the processing. And who's going to
stop at just a half-cup?
</P>
<P>
   A whole fresh tomato (about 1 1/2 cups of fruit) has only 24
calories. But once it's pureed and canned, one cup contains 102
calories, 39 mg. more sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans talk about nutrition but don't practice it,
Berning said. Instead, dieters are lured by diets that eliminate
one food group or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what's mind-boggling. They throw out the carbohydrates
on these protein diets, for instance, and by cutting out one food
group, they're automatically eliminating calories,'' she said. ``Of
course they're going to lose weight _ for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bodies need protein, we can't live without it, so sure,
protein is great, but not at the expense of other nutrients,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, calories become an issue again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're overeating protein, you're going to gain weight. The
same with carbohydrates, fat, whatever food: If you're taking in
more than you burn, you're going to gain the weight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rarback agrees. She cautions that not everyone has the same
caloric intake level, so saying a 2,000 calorie diet is good for an
average gets a lot of people in trouble. ``You have to know
yourself and what you need. You have to decide how active you are,
and age and weight have a lot to do with it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing teens and athletic young adults require extra calories.
The more active you are, the more calories you need. ``If an adult
woman can maintain her weight at 1,200 calories, she's not active
enough,'' Rarback said. ``I'd tell her to add some activity. On the
other hand, 2,000 calories may be too many for an average small
woman who is active. ``
</P>
<P>
   The main thing, however, is to make the calories that you take
in count, she said. ``If you're eating nutrient-dense foods, you'll
have calories left over for those splurges.''
</P>
<P>
   And there should be indulgences built in to any diet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think eating should be pleasurable,'' Rarback said. ``Life's
to be enjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
