<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-ERIN-BROCKOVICH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING JULIA: JULIA ROBERTS ON FAME, FORTUNE AND `ERIN BROCKOVICH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Julia Roberts
in a scene from ``Erin Brockovich.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I'm not a bitch,'' Julia Roberts says. ``That's probably the
biggest misconception there is of me.''
 &HT;    Roberts knows that the label is frequently attached to her, but
she insists that it's unjustified.
 &HT;    ``I think I get it because I'm tall and really very smart and
have lots of ideas and am willing to share them,'' she says. ``When
you're energetic about things and opinionated, it often intimidates
people who aren't very smart themselves.''
 &HT;    If that sounds like Roberts has an axe to grind, dismiss the
idea. Actually, the 32-year-old actress seems calmer and more
comfortable with her own stardom than ever before.
 &HT;    ``I find the press less aggressive than before,'' she admits.
``I don't respond to stupidity and disrespectfulness. I notice
reporters seem to have increased intelligence and respect these
days.''
 &HT;    Her willingness to tell it the way she sees it may be left over
from her latest film, the based-on-fact ``Erin Brockovich,'' which
will open on March 17. It casts her as the title character, a
twice-divorced, working-class mother of three who finds a job in a
law office and stumbles onto a scandal involving polluted water and
a billion-dollar coverup.
 &HT;    Those who are used to the gorgeous, elegantly costumed and
charmingly adorable Roberts of her last three movies _ the hit
romantic comedies ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' (1998), ``Notting
Hill'' (l999) and ``Runaway Bride'' (l999) _ are in for a shock.
Roberts' Erin Brockovich is loud and vulgar, and doesn't suffer
fools gladly. She swears like a truck driver, and her wardrobe runs
to skintight tops and thigh-high skirts.
 &HT;    Which took a little help from the costume department, because
the real Brockovich _ who has a walk-on role as a waitress named
Julia _ fills out those tops considerably more than Roberts.
 &HT;    ``It's a great part in a really great story,'' the actress says,
laughing, ``and it allows me to reveal more cleavage than God ever
thought to give me. It was all Barbie theater _ all fabulous.''
 &HT;    The role is quite a departure from her two 1999 films: ``Notting
Hill'' cast her as a glamorous movie star _ hardly a stretch _
opposite Hugh Grant's nerdy bookseller, while ``Runaway Bride''
reunited her with Richard Gere, her co-star in ``Pretty Woman''
(l990), for the saga of a woman who just can't quite say ``I do.''
 &HT;    It must have been tempting to keep on in that lighthearted vein
_ after all, it was the success of those films that enabled Roberts
to become the highest-paid actress in Hollywood history, pocketing
$20 million for ``Erin Brockovich.''
 &HT;    ``I look at my salary as the bonus winning round in a TV quiz
show,'' she says. ``It doesn't change what I'm doing or how I
approach my work, and it doesn't make me a better actor or work any
harder. It's just a reward.''
 &HT;    It does, however, mark a peak in her up-and-down career since
``Pretty Woman,'' which this year will be released in a
10th-anniversary edition.
 &HT;    ``It's terrifying, isn't it?'' she says. ``It makes me feel old
_ but, then again, think about how much older that makes everyone
else.''
 &HT;    Roberts thinks the woman she is today bears little resemblance
to the youngster who first made Hollywood sit up and take notice.
 &HT;    ``I'm not the same girl,'' she says. ``That was a little while
ago _ I weighed 20 pounds more, and I knew about 50 things less.''
 &HT;    One of the things she knows now is that, even before this year's
Oscars are awarded, there's already Hollywood buzz that ``Erin
Brockovich'' could bring Roberts her third Oscar nomination next
year, her first since consecutive nods for ``Steel Magnolias''
(1989) and ``Pretty Woman.''
 &HT;    For her own part, Roberts declines to speculate on her chances.
 &HT;    ``I think all my movies are great,'' she says, shrugging. ``It's
just the press who choose to dump on me or not. But I'm not saying
that all the best elements of filmmaking didn't come together in
`Erin Brockovich.'''
 &HT;    And, yes, if she gets the opportunity, she'd vote for herself.
 &HT;    ``Yeaaah, honey,'' she says, laughing. ``You'd vote for
yourself. See your name on the ballot, and it's a real easy
check.''
 &HT;    As for the future, Roberts' name has been rumored to be attached
to any number of films. Most recently she's been said to be about
to star opposite Brad Pitt in David Fincher's ``The Mexican.''
 &HT;    The actress snorts in dismissal.
 &HT;    ``According to the Hollywood trade papers, I'm in every movie
they're making these days,'' she says. ``The truth is, I don't have
a next film. I've had eight months of break.
 &HT;    ``I'm taking some time off and enjoying it,'' she says. ``I like
hanging around the house with my mom and family, going to bed early
and waking up when I want to wake up and cooking and doing all that
kind of stuff.
 &HT;    ``When something good comes along, I'll take it,'' Roberts
concludes. ``If that's two years from now, that's how long my break
will be. If it's tomorrow, then there you go.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Erin Brockovich,'' consult the
official Website at www.erinbrockovich.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
