<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-COMPOSER-JOHN-WILLIAMS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEDI MAESTRO: `STAR WARS' COMPOSER JOHN WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of composer
John Williams with George Lucas during the making of ``Star Wars:
The Phantom Menace.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    John Williams knows the score.
 &HT;    Creating music for sci-fi megamovies is never an easy task, the
Oscar-winning composer says. Harder still, in the case of ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace,'' was living up to the expectations
created by his earlier trio of ``Star Wars'' scores.
 &HT;    ``I'm always daunted by these movies,'' Williams says on the eve
of the April 4 video release of ``The Phantom Menace.'' ``The music
has a lot of competition from sound effects, and the music has to
carry the sound of the film all the time.
 &HT;    ``The `Star Wars' movies don't have pages and pages of actors
doing dialogue,'' he explains, ``and the dialogue that's there is
very fragmented, so the orchestra has to sweep the film along.
 &HT;    ``There's also always a nagging doubt that you may not be able
to produce something as effective as the last time out,'' he adds.
``And when you're facing the prospect of writing two hours of music
in a couple of months _ that's hundreds of thousands of notes _
it's a challenge.
 &HT;    ``I was aided to a degree at the outset of `The Phantom Menace'
by the fact that we could use 10 percent of the earlier music, the
signature music, on the outer ends of the film,'' the composer
says. ``But 90 percent of the music is new. The energy of the film,
the battles, the pacing, the balancing of themes and keys and
tempos and variations of orchestration in order to maintain one's
interest in a score that long ... that's a technical challenge.''
 &HT;    Williams began by screening a rough assembly of ``The Phantom
Menace'' and discussing ``the musical kinetic'' with
writer/director George Lucas.
 &HT;    Then he strolled into a ``dimly lit'' room, yellow notepad in
hand, and hand-composed the score.
 &HT;    The music completed, Williams reunited with the London Symphony
Orchestra, with which he had teamed years earlier on the previous
``Star Wars'' adventures, to conduct and record the music.
 &HT;    As always, each major character has his or her own musical
motif, as do major worlds, certain battles and several varieties of
creature.
 &HT;    ``My task was to make the music of `The Phantom Menace' feel
that it belonged to the other three films, but was new to this
piece,'' Williams says by telephone from his Los Angeles home.
 &HT;    ``One of the nice elements was that Anakin (Jake Lloyd) _ who,
as we know, is to metamorphose into Darth Vader _ needed a theme,''
he says. ``If you listen to Anakin's theme, people say, `Ah, it
must be Darth Vader.' I decomposed Darth Vader's `Imperial March,'
and tried very subtly to introduce a slight hint of what he's to
become in the context of a very sweet, innocent and lyrical piece
suitable for Anakin.''
 &HT;    Williams admits to being ``very pleased'' with the ``Phantom
Menace'' score, and particularly likes the 65 minutes of material
culled together on the soundtrack.
 &HT;    He won't, however, win an Oscar for it. Instead, he received the
38th nomination of his career for the evocative Irish strains heard
in ``Angela's Ashes.''
 &HT;    Always busy, Williams is currently living at an even more
frenetic pace, devoting the spring and summer to a spate of
projects that include introducing a new piece, ``Tree Song,'' at
the Tanglewood Music Festival, scoring Mel Gibson's upcoming
Revolutionary War drama ``The Patriot'' and conducting several
Boston Pops concerts in Massachusetts.
 &HT;    At some point, probably in late 2001, he's expecting a call from
George Lucas. The composer _ whose other genre credits include
``The Time Tunnel'' and ``Lost in Space'' for television, as well
as ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' and ``E.T.: The
Extraterrestrial'' _ will then sharpen his pencils, dim the lights
and prepare to journey once again to a place far, far away.
 &HT;    Lucas is almost certain to call, because Williams' music is as
integral to the ``Star Wars'' mythos as the Force, Han Solo, R2-D2,
Tatooine or glowing lightsabers.
 &HT;    ``My sense of inseparability is probably a little less than
other people's,'' Williams says modestly. ``But if I look at it
objectively, they are inseparable.
 &HT;    ``It's one of those things that has always characterized
sequels,'' he adds. ``The strong musical signatures carry over.
It's very much a part of the genre as well.
 &HT;    ``I'm very gratified by the longevity of the `Star Wars' music
and the aural imagination that it engenders in people, that they
think of these characters when they hear the music.
 &HT;    ``I'm glad the next two prequels are going to happen,'' Williams
says. ``I'm very interested in seeing what George does and what
kind of opportunity the movies will give me to continue to add to
the body of what's become a weighty tome that so many people seem
to enjoy.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace,'' consult the official Website at www.starwars.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL;
