<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, March 10. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Josephine Schmidt; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
joschm(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRADE (Washington) _ As the Clinton administration
conceded Thursday that it does not have the votes for a giant China
trade accord, a titanic lobbying battle was shaping up for the 110
uncommitted House members who will decide the fate of the
President's most important remaining foreign policy goal. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KOHL (Berlin) _ Helmut Kohl, the former German
chancellor, emerged from weeks of seclusion Thursday to announce
that generous friends and a mortgage on his own house had enabled
him to raise enough money to cover the financial damage suffered by
the Christian Democratic party as a result of his ``mistakes.''
Appearing alternately jocular and irascible, Kohl broke his silence
at a news conference where he brandished a list of 30 friends and
admirers - including actresses, film producers and businessmen -
who he said had contributed to the raising of $2.95 million. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MINIMUM-WAGE (Washington) _ The House votes on raising federal
minimum wage to $6.15 an hour from $5.15 an hour, and on a
Republican $122-billion tax break bill for businesses and the
wealthy, which President Clinton has said would force him to veto
the entire package. The vote is expected to be late. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-JUDGES (Washington) _ The Senate approves two more
federal judges as Vice President Al Gore cancels a campaign trip to
be in Washington in case his vote is needed to break a tie. By Neil
A. Lewis. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Lawyers for the Miami relatives of Elian
Gonzalez told a judge Thursday that the 6-year-old boy has the
right to seek political asylum in the United States and the family
has the legal standing to try to block the U.S. government from
returning the shipwreck survivor to Cuba. In a hearing that could
go a long way toward resolving a bitter custody battle waged across
the Florida Straits, lawyers for the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service (INS) told U.S. District Judge Michael Moore
that only Elian's father in Cuba could speak for the boy. (Summary
from wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Sedona, Ariz.) _ Sen. John McCain, the Republican whose
insurgency became the surprise of the primary season, ended his
maverick candidacy on Thursday with the hope that he would
eventually prevail in ``making our party as big as the country we
serve.'' Two days after being soundly defeated in coast-to-coast
primaries, McCain had gracious words for Gov. George W. Bush but
stopped noticeably short of endorsing him, saying only, ``I
congratulate Governor Bush and wish him and his family well. He may
very well become the next president of the United States.'' He also
ended speculation that he might make a third-party run by repeating
once again, ``I love my party, it is my home.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,8.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY (West Orange, N.J.) _ After an often bitter 14-month,
$30-million campaign in which he failed to win a single Democratic
primary, former Sen. Bill Bradley ended his quest for the
presidency Thursday, saying the time had come to unite the party
behind Vice President Al Gore. But while Bradley pledged to work
for Gore's victory in the general election, he refused to use the
word ``endorse'' to describe his support for Mr. Gore and declined
to release his delegates to the vice president _ presumably to give
him more influence at the Democratic National Convention this
summer. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bradley, NYT5,7, and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Seldom has an index risen as rapidly
as the Nasdaq composite has done in leaping above the 5,000 mark, a
hurdle it surmounted yesterday little more than four months after
it first pushed past 3,000. Virtually never has an index done so
with such huge volatility. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRANSPLANT-FRAUD (Undated) _ Talking to the doctors who
uncovered the fraud of the South African researcher who claimed to
have the only data that showed bone marrow transplants worked for
women with breast cancer. The researcher will go on trial Friday.
By Denise Grady.
</P>
</TEXT>
