<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-DEPALMA-TEX     03-09 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEPALMA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEJA VU AND BRIAN DE PALMA, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't get us wrong _ we usually like Brian De Palma. Although he
has delivered some schlock through the years _ remember, he
directed ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' _ the snazzy filmmaker has
given us such winners as ``Carrie,'' ``Dressed to Kill,'' ``Blow
Out,'' ``The Untouchables'' and the underrated ``Casualties of
War.'' Even his latest, ``Mission to Mars,'' is entertaining enough
to look past its many flaws.
</P>
<P>
   But when we saw the ``Mission'' trailer _ which seemed to appear
before every movie during the past few months _ we couldn't help
but think, ``There goes De Palma again, ripping off another
director.'' Only this time, it's Stanley Kubrick instead of Alfred
Hitchcock. De Palma, it seems to us, has a penchant for borrowing
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Which gave us an idea for a chart, which follows. But let's play
nice, and say that De Palma is just paying homage to famous
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Obsession''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: After Cliff Robertson's wife is kidnapped, he
encounters a woman who looks just like her.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Alfred Hitchcock's ``Vertigo.''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: After James Stewart's girlfriend disappears, he
encounters a woman who looks just like her.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Phantom of the Paradise''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Shower slaying _ with a plunger.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Shower slaying _ with a kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Dressed to Kill''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Unexpected stabbing by a mysterious ``woman'' _ in
an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Unexpected stabbing by a mysterious ``woman'' _
in a shower.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Blow Out''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Sound-effects expert believes he's heard a murder
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Michelangelo Antonioni's ``Blowup''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Photographer believes he's seen a murder taking
place.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Body Double''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Voyeuristic chap gets in trouble when he witnesses
a murder.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Alfred Hitchcock's ``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Voyeuristic chap gets in trouble when he
witnesses a murder.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``The Untouchables''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: During a gunfight, an unattended baby carriage
takes a precarious journey down Chicago's Union Station steps.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Sergei Eisenstein's ``Potemkin''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: As soldiers gun down peasants, an unattended baby
carriage takes a precarious journey down Russia's Odessa Steps.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Snake Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Long, seemingly unbroken opening shot following
lead character as he interacts with other cast members.
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Orson Welles' ``Touch of Evil''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Long, seemingly unbroken opening shot following
lead characters as they interact with other cast members.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   De Palma movie: ``Mission to Mars''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen idea: Space-station astronauts defy gravity to the
strains of classic rock (Van Halen's ``Dance the Night Away'')
</P>
<P>
   Original movie: Stanley Kubrick's ``2001: A Space Odyssey''
</P>
<P>
   Original idea: Space-station astronauts defy gravity to the
strains of classical music (Johann Strauss' ``The Blue Danube
Waltz)''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
