<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS10-COX     03-09 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PANEL APPROVES BILL TO DOUBLE NUMBER OF HIGH-TECH VISAS
 &HT;    340&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill that would allow more high-skilled
foreigners to work in the United States was approved Thursday by
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that U.S. high-tech companies are
struggling to fill cubicles with capable and educated workers,''
said Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's American Competitiveness in the 21st Century Act would
increase the number of H-1B temporary visas, which allow highly
skilled workers to work in the United States three years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would increase the limit on the number of visas to
195,000 this fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, and in the next two
fiscal years. It would exempt from the limit those who come to the
United States to work at universities and those who have recently
received advanced degrees at a U.S. college.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, the visa limit is 115,000 this year, 107,500
next year, and 65,000 in fiscal 2002. Hatch's bill would more than
double the three-year total to 585,000 visas, compared to 287,500
under current law.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the increase is only a temporary solution to the
shortage of high-tech workers, and that more training and education
for American workers in areas of math, science, and technology were
needed. The bill would earmark $150 million for scholarships and
grants to train and educate more American workers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also retains a $500 fee for each visa, paid by the
companies that employ foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's bill was co-sponsored by Sens. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
Connie Mack, R-Fla., Mike DeWine, R-Ohio. The bill passed the
committee on a vote of 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bill was voted on, the panel rejected a substitute
offered by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., that would raise the limit
by a smaller amount and increase the visa fees paid by businesses.
A bill similar to Kennedy's is pending in the House.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's proposal would increase the number of visas this year
to 145,000, an additional 30,000 visas, and would exempt all
foreign workers with educations above a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's proposal would also establish a tiered fee system that
would collect $30 million per year. Companies with fewer than 150
employees would pay $1,000 per visa, companies with between 151 to
500 employees would pay $2,000 per visa, and those with more than
500 employees would pay $3,000 per visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech companies are experiencing record profits, and they
can well afford to pay a higher application fee,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested allocating money for training initiatives,
scholarships for low-income students, and improving the H-1B visa
applications process and enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any credible legislative proposal to increase the number of
high-tech workers available to American businesses must begin with
the expansion of state-of-the-art high-tech career training
opportunities for large numbers of American workers,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee rejected Kennedy's proposal, 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said that Kennedy's proposed increase in visas was
inadequate to address the shortage of high-tech labor. He added
that an increase in fees paid by companies was unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to Hatch and Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont, the ranking Democratic member of the Judiciary Committee,
a group of labor, immigration and civil rights organizations urged
Congress to consider more than just temporary immigration issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very troubled that the only immigration legislation
given adequate attention this year so far is related to
highly-skilled temporary workers,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees International Union, the Service Employees International
Union, the United Neddletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees,
the National Council of La Raza, and the National Immigration
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
