<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLYWOOD-MARS-COX     03-09 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-MARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IT'S DEAD!
 &HT;    IT'S RED!!
 &HT;    IT'S MARS!!!
 &HT;    By Michael Alicea
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give it up, Hollywood: Mars is dead.
</P>
<P>
   No canals. No mysterious face. No life of any kind. Nope, not
even one stinking bacterium. Nothing but red, dead, rusty dust.
</P>
<P>
   But when did the facts ever get in a movie's way? Mission to
Mars, which opens today, features not just Martian life but
super-intelligent Martian life that supposedly started life on
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is set in 2020. Humanity has launched its first manned
mission to the Red Planet. But yikes! When they get there, three of
four crew members are wiped out by a huge whirlwind worm. In come
the rescuers, who waste no time getting themselves in big trouble.
Good thing, for while saving themselves they uncork the secret of
life and then, of course, live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Fun, but what a crock. If there was ever any life on Mars, there
was no happy end to it. Mars _ named for the Roman god of war _ is
a dead, cold, inhospitable world whose air is poison and whose
climate would kill us in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, our Martian fascination has persisted for years.
We don't get excited about ``Jovians'' or ``Saturnians,'' but Mars
has always kept us wondering and waiting for a visitor or two.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Mars was thought to be the most likely of all the
planets to harbor life. Its modern appeal began with a
mistranslation of the Italian astronomer Giovanni Sciaparelli's
1877 observations of what he termed ``canali'' on Mars. What he
meant as ``channels,'' a natural occurrence, was taken as
``canals,'' man-made structures. Soon after, Martians became tragic
figures in our imaginations, scraping at the bone-dry dirt, which
is red because it's full of iron oxide (rust), and digging canals
in an attempt to save their race by drawing water from the frozen
poles.
</P>
<P>
   By 1897, H.G. Wells' The War of the Worlds had Martians looking
toward Earth to solve their own global concerns over the dying
Martian environment. In 1910, Percival Lowell penned Abode of Life,
a serious look into the possibility of advanced life-forms on the
Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Martians have been pictured as the enemy (Invaders
From Mars, Mars Attacks!), the misguided, (The Martian Chronicles),
the silly (Marvin the Martian, Spaced Invaders) _ and now, with
Mission to Mars, benevolent progenitors.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the movies, more serious arguments over the existence
of Martians have recently taken place. They began with the Viking
spacecraft images of a region named the Cydonia Mensae. These
pictures showed the now-infamous ``Face'' _ a mount that looks like
a human face when the light hits it just right _ and pyramid-like
mountains that look like remnants of a ``city.'' This area is the
centerpiece of Mission to Mars _ the last vestige of a race who
escaped a planetary catastrophe _ and the ``Face'' is their
monument to whichever creature from Earth had evolved enough to
travel ``home'' and prove his intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that these structures alone prove Mars either was
once inhabited and we are the descendants of that race, or was once
inhabited but all the Martians died, leaving behind their ruined
cities and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   But to scientists, this is simply nonsense. The city? A few
hills of ruddy dirt blown into rare shapes by the forces of Mars'
unrelenting winds. The Face? Shadows and rocks. Nothing more. Mars,
they say, is dead.
</P>
<P>
   But when did science ever sell movie tickets?
</P>
<P>
   michaelalicea(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MARS-MOVIES-COX     03-09 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-MOVIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: WITH MARS PROBES, HOLLYWOOD-MARS
 &HT;    Mars in the movies
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mission to Mars not enough for you? Check out these other Mars
movie classics:
</P>
<P>
   Total Recall (1990) _ Arnold Schwarzenegger takes to Mars to
flex his muscles and mush the schemes of a greedy Martian governor
in this thrill-a-minute futuristic tale.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Attacks! (1996) _ What begins as a hopeful meeting between
Martians and Earthlings on the plains of Pahrump, Nev., turns into
an all-star mad dash to save the planet from the plans of an evil
Martian horde. Look for the many incarnations of Jack Nicholson, as
the Prez and a sleazy developer.
</P>
<P>
   Invaders From Mars (1986) _ A remake of the 1953 classic.
Martians begin a silent invasion of Earth from an insomniac
preteen's backyard. Stars Karen Black of B-movie fame.
</P>
<P>
   War of the Worlds (1953) _ The H.G. Wells classic of
Martians-are-coming-to-get-us paranoia. The movie centers on the
invasion and subsequent destruction of most of Earth by Martians in
need of a flu shot.
</P>
<P>
   Spaced Invaders (1990) _ A silly romp about a group of Martians
who mistake the replay of the H.G. Wells/Orson Welles radio classic
as a verbatim account of an actual invasion of our Big Blue World.
Comedy ensues.
</P>
<P>
   The Martian Chronicles (1979) A group of short stories centered
on the last days of the last Martians on Mars. Rock Hudson stars as
the Martians use various means to deceive the humans into madness
and death in order to save their planet from invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Needs Women _ (1966) Tommy Kirk leads his fellow Martians
to Earth on an interplanetary quest for females. Kirk proves that
Martians have impeccable taste when one of his first conquests
turns out to be sexy scientist Yvonne Craig.
</P>
<P>
   The Angry Red Planet (1959) _ Just when you think it's safe to
explore other worlds, man-eating plants, giant rat-bat-crabs and a
cyclops that dissolves anything it touches ruin the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Flight to Mars (1951) _ Martians look like us. Really _ they do.
They even act like us when they run out of natural resources _ they
plot to plunder. Thank goodness for that Martian Underground _ they
save the day.
</P>
<P>
   Duck Dodgers in the 24th and a half Century (1953)_ Space hero
Duck Dodgers, along with Space Cadet Porky, travel to Planet X for
Illudium Phosdex. Unfortunately, Commander X-2, (Marvin the
Martian), arrives to claim Planet X in the name of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
