r e BC-MARS-PROBES-COX     03-09 0161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-PROBES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS. MARS-TEXAS, MARS-MOVIES, HOLLYWOOD-MARS
 &HT;    Missions to Mars
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A slew of Russian, American and Japanese probes and spacecraft
have orbited or landed on Mars and its moons Phobos and Deimos.
Some had little success in unlocking the secrets of the Red Planet.
Some exceeded our expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner (1964-1971): The 10 Mariner missions were flybys
designed to visit nearby planets. Mariner 4 gave us the first
up-close views of Mars in 1965. Mariners 6, 7 and 9 returned
information on its surface and atmospheric composition. Mariner 9
mapped 100 percent of the surface and photographed its moons.
</P>
<P>
   Viking I &AMP; II (1975): These missions were designed to orbit
Mars, land and make observations. Scientists still had hope of
finding life _ even if only bacterial. But the landers confirmed
Mariner's findings about the ``lunar-like'' Martian landscape. No
signs of life were detected.
</P>
<P>
   Phobos (198
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-VISAS-1STLD-$ADV     03-09 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS-1STLD-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS LIKELY TO GIVE HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY MORE FOREIGN WORKERS
 &HT;    Eds: Adds Senate committee action in graf 13 and White House
stance in graf 18.
 &HT;    840&AMP;adds. With TECH-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a labor drought this summer, technology
executives are asking Congress for relief this spring.
</P>
<P>
   They claim their businesses can grow only if sprinkled with
talent drawn from deep pools of labor found in India, China and
elsewhere. Congress must increase the ceiling on visas for
foreigners with high-tech skills to keep U.S. companies from
shriveling, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the effort believe today's worker shortages
will actually strengthen the economy in the long run. They argue
that if companies can't get a quick fix from overseas, they will
retrain older U.S. workers and work more closely with schools to
produce better students.
</P>
<P>
   With elections coming up, most members of Congress are eager to
please wealthy technology executives. And no lawmaker wants to be
accused of slowing the engine that has been driving the U.S.
economy's longest expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, these lawmakers fear a backlash from workers
concerned about competition from low-wage foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there is a national labor shortage of such
dimensions that we need more visas,'' said Vin O'Neill, a lobbyist
for the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, a
professional association based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The visas, known as H-1B visas, allow highly skilled workers
such as engineers and computer programmers to come into the United
States for three years. Usually, a visa can be renewed once for an
additional three-year stay. Often, temporary workers use the visas
as a step toward gaining permanent resident status.
</P>
<P>
   This debate over foreign workers may sound familiar. Just two
years ago, spurred on primarily by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
Congress raised the annual limit on high-tech visas from 65,000 to
115,000 for both fiscal 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But under current law, the limit will fall to 107,500 when
fiscal 2001 begins Oct. 1, and the following year, the cap will
return to 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies, which have been hiring frantically in the
past year, will hit this year's limit even before spring is over.
Unless the law is changed, they will have to cool their heels until
new visas become available Oct. 1 and will face even a greater
squeeze under next year's smaller visa cap. Some executives even
suggest U.S. businesses will have to move operations overseas to
find workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Computing Technology Industry Association, a trade group,
says nearly 269,000 high-tech jobs are going unfilled already,
costing U.S. businesses $4.5 billion in lost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   To help companies, Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., introduced a bill last month to increase H-1B
visas to 195,000 for this year, and to stay at that level through
fiscal 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Their legislation, sent to the Senate floor Thursday by a 15-3
vote of the Judiciary Committee, also would exempt from the cap
foreigners who work for U.S. colleges and universities or research
institutions, as well as foreigners who received a master's degree
or doctorate from a U.S. college within six months of their
employment.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would retain a provision of the 1998 bill requiring a
$500-per-visa fee to go toward scholarships and worker training
programs in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said labor shortages are so severe that he believes
lawmakers will move his bill quickly. ``I don't think we're going
to have tremendous opposition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some in Congress favor a different approach. Rep. Lamar
Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the House immigration subcommittee, has
submitted a bill that would boost the H-1B visa cap from 115,000 to
160,000, but just for this year. In 2001, the ceiling would fall to
107,500, and then to 65,000 the following year. ``Our bill seeks to
solve an immediate problem,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith bill also would boost the visa fee to $1,000 per
foreigner, with the revenues going to college scholarships for
students in high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration supports raising the visa ceiling.
``We are ready to support a reasonable increase in the number of
H-1B visas as long as it reflects a balanced approach that protects
and prepares the U.S. work force,'' White House spokesman Jake
Siewert said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has rounded up some key co-sponsors: Rep. Bob Goodlatte,
R-Va., who co-chairs the Congressional Internet Caucus; Rep. Tom
Campbell, R-Calif., whose district includes Silicon Valley, and
Rep. Chris Cannon, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Goodlatte's support is especially important because he is widely
regarded as the high-tech world's best friend in Washington. If
Goodlatte says this is the best deal industry is going to get from
Congress and the White House, tech lobbyists may well take his word
for it. Tech companies would then renew their fight for more visas
when a new Congress convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   How well next year's lobbying effort goes may depend heavily on
a study being conducted by the National Science Foundation, which
was directed by Congress in 1998 to verify high-tech job needs. The
foundation is expected to complete its work by October.
</P>
<P>
   The study may at last add facts to a debate that has been argued
with largely anecdotal evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of visas point to news stories about some foreign
workers who say they were lured to this country with promises of
good pay, only to earn a paltry $500 a month. But reliable research
has not determined exactly how often pay abuses occur.
</P>
<P>
   Visa opponents also say many older workers want high-tech jobs,
but young executives at high-tech companies won't offer them
training. Are there really enough older tech workers to supply
fast-growing companies with the labor they need? That question has
never been answered conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, visa opponents insist the job market is changing enough
to relieve labor shortages without more foreign help. O'Neill, of
the electrical engineers group, admits hiring has been difficult
for some companies in the past year, but attributes much of the
employment surge to the effort to repair Y2K computer bugs. Now
that those problems have been fixed, computer-related job openings
are declining and ``salaries are leveling off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Hatch-sponsored legislation, Dan Stein, a
lobbyist for the anti-immigration movement, says: ``There isn't a
single study that shows that kind of bill is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Tech employers vigorously disagree. They note that the Bureau of
Labor Statistics' employment projections through 2008 show the No.
1 industry for job growth will be computer and data processing
services, which will need 3.47 million workers in 2008, compared to
1.6 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000 and 2001, the Labor Department says the five
fastest-growing occupations are computer engineers; computer
support specialists, systems analysts, database administrators and
desktop publishing specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Department of Education reports that college
degrees granted in engineering are declining, while computer
science degrees are down sharply from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Stohler, a spokesman for the American Electronics
Association, a Washington-based trade group representing high-tech
companies, says U.S. colleges can't possibly produce enough
engineers to fill the labor market in coming years because very few
students are taking the math courses needed to get those degrees.
``The pipeline from K through 12 is not looking good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But given that the National Science Foundation's study on the
job market won't be completed for months, Smith and Goodlatte say
the most appropriate thing for Congress to do now is boost the visa
cap only for this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that the expansion is of a temporary
nature, so that our long-term goal is to make sure these
opportunities exist for American citizens,'' Goodlatte said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
