<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TENN-AQUARIUM12-COX     03-09 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-AQUARIUM12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stare death in the eye _ and live to tell about it
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dreaded Acanthophis antarcticus _ better, and more aptly,
known as the death adder _ is stirring things up at the Tennessee
Aquarium in downtown Chattanooga these days.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Australian native, whose deadly fangs inject
highly toxic venom into its hapless prey, is safely locked behind
glass, along with some equally fearsome friends.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened ``Venom: Striking Beauties,'' which will remain
in the aquarium's 1,500-square-foot changing exhibits gallery
through Jan. 2, 2002, brings visitors eyeball-to-eyeball with some
of the world's loveliest and most lethal animals.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought the black widow was trouble, get a load of cow
killer wasps, black mamba, bullet ant, the Goliath bird-eating
tarantula and the stinging catfish.
</P>
<P>
   These exotic creatures are among the nearly 50 species of
venomous spiders, insects, fish, scorpions, snakes and poisonous
dart frogs now residing in settings that mirror those in the wild.
Among the 22 habitats are a dense South American rain forest where
the yellow eyelash viper and terciopelo reside, an African rain
forest featuring several species of mambas and vipers, and a
Southwestern desert with rattlesnakes, Gila monsters and scorpions.
Oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its shock value, ``Venom'' aims to help visitors develop
an appreciation for these often misunderstood animals by offering a
glimpse into their secret worlds.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, venom is simply part of the feeding strategy _ a
way to immobilize the unfortunate victim destined to become supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these creatures use venom as means to capture prey,
not as a weapon,'' says Jackson Andrews, director of operations and
husbandry at the aquarium. ``Instead of relying on venom as a
defense, many of these animals have developed strategies that help
them remain hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   Austere design elements _ harsh angles, metal, vaulted chambers,
industrial locks _ give the exhibit a futuristic look.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive touch screens and graphic panels show cultural
connections to venom, describe its medical benefits and explain the
difference between venom and poison.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tennessee Aquarium, 423-265-0695 or
www.tnaqua.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
