<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-WINDOWS10-COX     03-09 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WINDOWS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Restored `Window' clearly a thrill
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too many trees have given their lives to provide pages for
essays about the cinema-as-voyeurism subtext and Freudian imagery
in ``Rear Window.'' Go to the library if you want that stuff. Here,
let's forget academic analysis and enjoy the restored, 1954
rerelease for what it is, bottom line: a sexy (if sometimes sexist)
chamber drama that gradually, expertly ups the suspense to
excruciating levels, all without breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a finessed variant on ``Rope,'' Alfred
Hitchcock's 1948 experiment that also tried to build tension while
confined to one interior set. Only this time _ without the single,
long takes that kept ``Rope'' mired in staginess _ Hitch got it
right.
</P>
<P>
   In case you don't know, James Stewart plays news photographer
L.G. ``Jeff'' Jeffries, stuck in a wheelchair with a broken leg.
When he's not getting massages from home nurse Thelma Ritter
(obviously in pre-HMO days), or fending off the charms of society
girlfriend Lisa (Grace Kelly), he whiles away his hours casually
spying on his neighbors through their windows overlooking his New
York courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   These folks are comic relief at first: the aging Miss
Lonelyhearts, the frustrated composer, the insatiable newlyweds and
the lithe, blond dancer who bends over and shows off her tush so
often that you figure she's wise to Jeff's peeping ways. Then
there's stocky salesman Lars Thorwald (Raymond Burr), who draws
Jeff's main focus when his nagging wife suddenly disappears. Has
she gone away, or been done away with?
</P>
<P>
   As Jeff grows convinced that he has (almost) seen a murder, the
movie builds suspense so gradually that it can surprise you with
its cumulative force. In particular, the sequence when Jeff watches
helplessly as Lisa, across the courtyard, finds herself in peril is
one of Hitchcock's more grueling scenes _ not because of what
happens, but what could. As usual, what we fear is much worse than
what we see.
</P>
<P>
   Thrills aren't the only thing ``Rear Window'' provides. It's
Hitchcock's second valentine to Kelly (they worked together three
times). Who can forget the amazing entrance he gives her, shooting
Lisa as an ambiguous force of both light (her dazzling blondness
and skin) and dark (the shadows she casts on commitment-shy Stewart
as she looms close for that way-sexy slo-mo kiss).
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also keeps the movie from becoming too claustrophobic: Her
inexhaustible, breathttaking wardrobe provides the equivalent of
ever-changing scenery.
</P>
<P>
   I know some people who call ``Rear Window'' their favorite
Hitchcock flick. It's not mine; it's too tidy, lacking the
unsettling, unsparing wide-screen landscapes of his later movies
(especially ``North by Northwest'' and ``Vertigo'') or the jolts
of, say, ``The Birds'' and especially ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Like one of Jeff's neighbors, the composer, Hitchcock is playing
a deceptively simple tune here, showing how much he can get away
with within a tight rhyme scheme. In fact, the movie is scored like
music. Pay attention to the way it alternates scenes thick with
dialogue with long, tense patches of silence.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the cacophony of street sounds and radio ditties
that constitute the movie's soundtrack gives way to the composer's
completed tune. In its final moments, ``Rear Window'' offers a view
of the world that I doubt Hitchcock believed for a second. It gives
us the reassurance (or perhaps illusion) that even in this backyard
microcosm tainted by loneliness, mistrust and murder, strangers and
the random events of their lives can come together, at least for a
moment, in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring James Stewart, Grace Kelly and Thelma Ritter. Rated
PG.1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   54 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A classic. See it.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
