<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-EXILE12-COX     03-09 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EXILE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Journey of discovery leads to the heart
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By Valerie Boyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service In his latest book of essays, James
<TEXT>
Alan McPherson's voice is not so much a voice of exile as it is the
voice of a masterful writer who has found his way home.
<P>
   For McPherson, home is Iowa City, Iowa, where he teaches at the
Iowa Writer's Workshop. Home has also been Grant Hall at Atlanta's
Morris Brown College, where, as a student, he learned priceless
lessons about pride and power. And it has also been, among other
places, Disneyland, where for years he took his daughter on
periodic pilgrimages to teach her to believe in magic. Ultimately,
though, the short story writer (who won a Pulitzer Prize in 1978
for his collection ``Elbow Room'') and memoirist (``Crabcakes'')
has found that home is a state of mind, a place of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Disneyland,'' one of the most affecting of the dozen essays
in ``A Region Not Home,'' McPherson tells how, after a bitter
divorce, he found an unlikely ally in hiking the emotional terrain
of long-distance fatherhood: his imagination. In what was surely
one of the most unusual uses of money awarded from a MacArthur
Foundation ``genius'' grant, McPherson and his daughter, Rachel,
began to fly _ literally. ``I began, then, in my imagination, to
view the country as one big house. My bedroom was in Iowa City.
Rachel's bedroom was in Charlottesville. Friends had guest rooms,
for Rachel and for me, in Richmond, in Washington, D.C., in
Stamford and in New Haven, in New York, in Boston, in Cambridge, in
Chicago, in Oakland, and in Los Angeles. All Rachel and I had to
do, with the MacArthur money, and with my own earnings after that
largesse had run out, was to move from room to room in this huge
house, bonding as we went with each other and with our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   On one of these treks, 10-year-old Rachel is grounded in
Chicago's O'Hare Airport by a massive snowstorm. You can almost
hear McPherson's voice shaking, as if it just happened yesterday,
when he writes: ``She had no money and was being obliged to sleep
in a chair or else on the floor of the airport with the other
children of divorce, tagged like Christmas gifts, who were serving
out their obligations to distant parents. ... During that hard
December night, I sat at my table and made telephone calls, like
thousands of other anonymous parents, to every possible source of
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel sleeps in the guest room of a family friend in Chicago.
But her father does not go to bed that night. Instead, he waits for
dawn: ``When the flight from O'Hare arrived and when Rachel came
down the jetway,'' he recalls, ``I thought my heart would break.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of intimate geography McPherson continually
traverses in ``A Region Not Home,'' whether he's writing about his
beloved daughter; about his mentor, the late Ralph Ellison; or
about a fascinating stranger _ a beggar in Palo Alto, Calif., for
instance, whose cardboard sign reads simply: ``I am a Christian
man.''
</P>
<P>
   McPherson's essays are at once eloquent and earthy, astute and
imaginative, philosophical and practical. And in each one, he
weaves together divergent strains of thought that eventually add up
to that one magic moment when it all becomes clear _ for the reader
and for McPherson himself, it seems. This, perhaps, is the signal
achievement of this remarkable collection: The author manages to
make you feel as if you're going with him on a journey of
discovery. Yet McPherson is thoroughly in control, writing with an
unrelenting intelligence that fully engages the intellect, even
while making the heart pound.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Region Not Home: Reflections From Exile. By James Alan
McPherson. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $24. 315 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The verdict: Powerful essays from a writer of formidable
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Boyd, a part-time editor at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is writing a biography of Zora Neale Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
