<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS12-COX     03-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The complexities of good and evil, faith and flesh
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serious novelists like to say that fiction is a moral concern,
and perhaps it is. But right and wrong exist on one plane, and good
and evil on another. It is easier to take measure of the forgivable
than of the ineradicable. Evil, if you believe it exists, is
somehow beyond human reach and yet it is all around us, resistant
to all purgatives.
</P>
<P>
   For Graham Greene, it was in the nature of things that there be
no grace without evil, the renewal of the one reinforcing the
presence of the other. Try as we might, we can never rid ourselves
of ourselves. Those who have seen the artistically exquisite movie
version of Greene's novel ``The End of the Affair'' understand this
better than they could have before _ understand, in particular, how
deeply he penetrated the psychology of desire and obligation,
betrayal and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 40-odd books that Greene wrote _ not only novels but
also travel narratives, essays and criticism, autobiography and
children's stories _ ``The End of the Affair'' and ``The Power and
the Glory'' stand in an odd relation to each other. Edmund Wilson
was not the only critic who counted ``The End of the Affair''
(along with, if I'm not mistaken, ``A Burnt-Out Case'') Greene's
finest work, but reacquaintance with it today makes clear how
different its theme is from that of ``The Power and the Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   At its most superficial level, as moviegoers know, ``The End of
the Affair'' involves an adulterous love affair, although Greene's
narrator, novelist Maurice Bendrix, tells us early on, ``... this
is a record of hate more than of love.'' It is a novel whose
complexities are the familiar ones: desire and betrayal, jealousy
and distrust. What is less familiar, perhaps, is the way in which
those emotions are shown to reveal not merely the necessary
circumstances of the story but the lineaments of human character.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond theological conundrums
</P>
<P>
   It is too easy for American readers to think of Greene as an
``English'' novelist, whatever that might imply. The truth is that,
apart from certain mannerisms of style, he was never as English as
Americans imagined. ``The End of the Affair'' is set in postwar
London, but what is more universal than love betrayed? And ``The
Power and the Glory'' is distinctly un-English _ in the Roman
Catholicism that broods over it, in the slightly exotic setting
(Mexico), in the dialectic of good and evil on which the novel is
built. The story is set in the sun-bleached southern provinces of
Tabasco and Chiapas, and the landscape itself becomes the
metaphorical canvas on which hunter and hunted play out their roles
in a drama that has its protagonist but no real heroes. The one
character who ought to have been, Padre Jose, goes to his death
praying that his own sins be forgiven along with those of his
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Greene was never above playing God with his characters. But in
``The Power and the Glory'' you have the sense of something deeper
than theological conundrums. Greene's whisky priest travels about
on his mule saying Mass and giving the sacraments in a country of
simple believers and a militantly atheistic government. The
government is prohibitionist as well, so Greene's fallible priest
has neither wine for himself nor wine that can be turned into the
blood of Christ for the faithful. (In one powerful scene, he comes
upon a bottle only to see it guzzled before his eyes by a
contemptuous government official.)
</P>
<P>
   Greene's padre takes the gospel to pueblos and tropical villages
where the rot and torpor are enough to drain a soul of all faith,
hope and charity. The air in a Greene novel always hangs heavy with
foreboding, an air in which only a Graham Greene character could
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   A failure of mind and heart
</P>
<P>
   But the atmosphere was never more than that _ the air and not
the ground on which the novel was planted. Greene's real subject
was human failure, and in a Greene novel neither faith nor flesh
has an easy time of it. It is no different in ``The End of the
Affair.'' When a priest urges on Bendrix the palliative of
confession, Bendrix tells him contemptuously, ``I've got nothing to
repent except failure. Go back to your own people, father, back to
your bloody little box and your beads.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure, in ``The End of the Affair,'' was one of the mind
and heart, not one that penance and prayer could undo. Neil Jordan,
the director of the movie version, understood this. John Ford, who
directed the 1947 movie version of ``The Power and the Glory''
(titled ``The Fugitive''), got things backward, giving the police
lieutenant in pursuit of Greene's padre an integrity that might
have been his salvation and the padre an indomitable goodness he
never possessed. The whole point of that novel is that good and
evil exist in us all, and that we come to grace only from guilt.
The padre, waiting in his cell for his executioner, says his rosary
consoled him only in the knowledge that another priest would come
for the faithful. And if they were lucky, he would be a better one.
In prayer, he knew he had failed both himself and those whose faith
was entrusted to him. The wrong he understood, but it was evil he
could not change.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
