<P>
   COKE-DAFT _ Doug Daft is putting his money where his mouth is.
Coke's new chairman is expected to tell employees today that he
will tie part of his compensation to meeting diversity goals. Daft
is also expected to create a new position of diversity officer for
the company. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SHOW _ ATLANTA _ A look at what's new at the AJC
International Auto Show. (Ritzler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
25. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-LATAM _ Home Depot could make an announcement in the
next week about its international growth plans, according to a new
analyst's report. The news could be that it is acquiring at least 3
Sam's Club stores from Wal-Mart for about $50 million in Buenos
Aires, Argentina. Analysts view that as positive because Home Depot
needs to leverage down the up-front costs incurred to enter Latin
America. Analysts estimate that Home Depot lost about $10-$11
million in the region in 1999 primarily due to startup costs. Also,
there has been speculation that HD is looking at European and
German acquisitions. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   PAPER _ As the paper industry's movers and shakers gather this
weekend for their annual business meeting, there's sure to be more
back-slapping than in years past. The pulp and paper industry is in
the midst of a major recovery. Demand and prices are soaring. And
the recent round of consolidation should increase profitability in
the sector. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   OT-ABUSE _ The nation's factories and offices are running
full-tilt. So, too are workers. And many aren't taking the extra
work load lightly. Instead, they're taking their employer to court
for overtime abuse. On the other side of the argument: the
workplace is changing thus creating a grey area: who should get
paid overtime? And who's exempt? A look at this issue. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
