<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2046 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     03-09 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST CALL FOR SHOWS LIKE `FREAKS AND GEEKS,' `FELICITY' AND `SPORTS
NIGHT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My guess is that Paul Feig wrote the pilot for ``Freaks and
Geeks'' both out of frustration and personal salvation, knowing
full well that any network programmer taking a chance on it had to
be either brilliant or batty.
</P>
<P>
   At age 37 and having had roles on promising-but-unnoticed
sitcoms like ``The Jackie Thomas Show,'' Feig had become
disillusioned by the medium's limitations. Apparently, it was
impossible to blend honesty, poignancy and humor on TV,
particularly when portraying adolescents, who were always presented
as precocious kids quick to upstage their slow-on-the-take parents.
</P>
<P>
   As written, and as executed by a fine cast of young actors,
``Freaks and Geeks'' gloriously rebels against the traditional TV
blueprint. It not only sets up shop in 1980, but it has the nerve
to zero in on the adolescent confusion of teen-agers drowning at
the bottom of the popularity gene pool without so much as a helping
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Judd Apatow, who, with Feig, co-created the series and serves as
executive producer, mentioned recently that NBC initially found
``Freaks'' clever and often downright hilarious, but over a number
of episodes, somewhat depressing. The network has become leery
about how long audiences would watch losers always being losers.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, its last airing registered at No. 77 on the prime-time
chart, just a few slots ahead of UPN's ``The Parkers,'' which means
it could be in serious trouble once networks start handing out pink
slips in mid-May to make room for the fall's new entries.
</P>
<P>
   With a little over two months left in the TV season, it's that
time of year when networks start fingering weak performers for
execution, and ``Freaks'' is clearly on NBC's radar. The dramedy
returns to the schedule Monday still well-liked by critics, but it
is on the proverbial ``bubble'' _ that is, so fragile that its
survival depends on the performance of this upcoming string of
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks'' is not alone, of course. ABC could give the boot to
the still underachieving ``Sports Night,'' CBS is rethinking the
future of ``Early Edition'' and ``Martial Law,'' Fox may have had
enough of ``Time of Your Life'' and ``Family Guy,'' and on NBC,
``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Suddenly Susan'' may have worn out
their welcomes. (''Stark Raving Mad'' might also be in trouble
considering that the Top 10 sitcom manages to lose 21 percent of
its ``Frasier'' lead-in.)
</P>
<P>
   The loss of ``Freaks'' would be painful. It's as adventurous and
risky as they come, as funny and touching, and, if I can debate TV
Guide here _ it's the Best Show You're Not Watching. (Sorry,
``Sports Night.'')
</P>
<P>
   Based on the premise that teen-age life can be hell, the show
has routinely found ways to both celebrate and ridicule the
protagonists, beginning with the Weir family, which includes
Lindsay (Linda Cardellini), a book-smart girl who camouflages her
good looks by wearing oversized army jackets and hanging out with
the less academically oriented ``freaks'' who smoke pot on the
school patio.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger brother, Sam (John Francis Daley), is even more of a
basket case. He's scrawny and whiny and insecure, and his fear of
showering after gym class (remember those days?) only egged on his
tormentors, who found a way of forcing him to streak through the
halls naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks'' is filled with an assortment of other
down-on-their-luck characters who defy the usual TV caricatures,
namely the pouty pretty people who inhabit shows on similar
subjects, like the WB's interesting but far less effective
``Popular.'' (Which will probably be renewed.)
</P>
<P>
   To the producers, both stand-up comedians with pain at the heart
of their laughter, the main focus of ``Freaks'' isn't about getting
the girl or winning the big game, but surviving obstacles with a
sense of humor intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about sending people home happy,'' is how Apatow
explains it.
</P>
<P>
   Armchair Internet critics and the influential viewers who make
up Viewers for Quality Television (it ranked No. 14 on VQT's latest
quality survey, ahead of ``Friends,'' ``The Simpsons'' and ``Ally
McBeal'') have found much to like with the series' edgy
sensibility. But I don't see the kind of
cancel-it-and-we'll-kill-you backing afforded ``Sports Night'' last
season when ABC even hinted at axing the half-hour series.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if ``Sports Night'' has that same die-for-you backing
this season, I haven't seen it. That's because ``Sports Night,''
though still a better half-hour than most, has been wildly uneven
this season, due in part to its erratic writing (what a boob
they've made of Felicity Huffman's once-strong Dana) and
squandering golden opportunities, like William Macy's recurring
character, who appeared like a flash of greatness and, then,
nothing. (Is writer/producer Aaron Sorkin spending too much time
with his new beau, ``The West Wing?'')
</P>
<P>
   Joining ``Freaks'' and ``Sports Night'' on the bubble is
Jennifer Love Hewitt's drama ``Time of Your Life'' and ``Get
Real,'' which have been mired in the bottom tenth of shows since
their first batch of episodes. Maybe Hewitt's fans have given up on
her as a lead character, or perhaps they've simply found nothing to
like about a series where character development was an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that ``Time of Your Life'' suffered tremendously
the day Fox asked creators Amy Lippman and Christopher Keyser to
shift the show's creative focus to better fit the quirkiness of
``Ally McBeal,'' which it precedes. There's nothing like packaging
to kill creativity. Suddenly, Hewitt became an annoying neurotic,
except without Calista Flockhart's strong cast support and David E.
Kelley's quaint writing.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Get Real,'' the family series where everyone spews pop
culture references while talking to the camera, it wouldn't have
returned if so many Fox shows hadn't failed to attract audiences.
With ``Party of Five'' ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and, maybe, ``The
X-Files,'' signing off this season, Fox will have to fill holes
left by shows with solid brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to ``Felicity'' and the WB. Fighting a
season-long ratings slump, the network is undergoing a major
schedule shakeup; the college drama moves to Wednesdays, into the
post-''Dawson's Creek'' slot, beginning April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting ``Felicity'' to Sunday proved a bigger disaster than
Keri Russell's haircut. This season the show is ranked 130th and
seen in an average of 2.4 million homes, down nearly a million from
last season when it aired on Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the alien romantic thriller ``Roswell'' is headed for
Monday nights. But be warned: The WB plans to revamp this charming
little series by playing up the sci-fi angle and slowing down what
I liked best about the series: the complications of alien
socialization among us.
</P>
<P>
   But the WB figures it's got to do something. ``Roswell''
currently ranks 125th for the season, with an average viewership of
3.8 million. (The WB midseason reinforcements include the new drama
``D.C.,'' about young people working in the nation's capital, and
``Movie Stars,'' the resurrected comedy about a family headed by
actors.)
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, the WB is in negotiations to air the foamation
comedy ``The PJs,'' the Eddie Murphy-backed series about the
tenants of a black housing project that Fox left off the fall
schedule and now seems willing to relinquish altogether. (It makes
perfect sense, now that the WB has a half-hour hole to fill on its
Segregated Friday night slate of black-cast comedies. Would it kill
them to actually ``develop'' a project with people of color?)
</P>
<P>
   For ``Freaks,'' let's hope it's not three strikes and out. This
is the third ``launch'' of the series, jokes Apatow. ``Freaks'' was
off the air for three weeks after its second episode. It was then
on for three weeks and off for four. It was MIA during all of
February sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning Monday, ``Freaks'' will have an uninterrupted
eight-episode run. The episodes ``are hilarious and sweet and
brutal all at the same time,'' Apatow promises. There's even an
upside. ``We know that if we're canceled, these episodes will air
on Nickelodeon for the rest of our lives,'' Apatow says.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we might as well make them special.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
