<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARNOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News and notes from around NASCAR
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK: NASCAR too quick to call Vegas race: NASCAR did
the East Coast media and race winner a favor by calling the
CarsDirect.com 400 after 148 of 267 scheduled laps because of rainy
weather. The decision was made 3:15 p.m. local time at a track that
has lights for night racing. The premature ending disappointed many
track fans, who had spent a pile of casino chips for tickets.
Granted, the forecast wasn't encouraging, but weather changes
quickly in the desert. NASCAR hung around for 12 hours to get in
last March's Atlanta race under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Chevy drivers means happy fans: NASCAR knows it is always
in trouble when the Chevys aren't running among the leaders, which
led to this week's rule change for the Monte Carlos. The sport
flourished in the 1990s because of seven words: ``Jeff Gordon's
domination and Dale Earnhardt's reputation.'' Both drive Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD: Rainbow Warriors may finally see pot of gold: The
Atlanta race could not come at a better time for Jeff Gordon, who
has suffered a tough start to the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has enjoyed good luck at Atlanta, winning the Cracker
Barrel 500 in 1999. Another series of bad breaks by Gordon at
Atlanta Motor Speedway could cause panic for the No. 24 team.
</P>
<P>
   How 'bout a sunny afternoon? NASCAR's luck with weather
continues to take a free-fall. Daytona was windy and cool,
Rockingham dealt with threatening clouds and Las Vegas fans dealt
with a rain-shortened event. Weather for Sunday's race depends on
the timing of a front, forecast to move through the area Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS OF THE PACK
</P>
<P>
   Rating some of the best Winston Cup crew chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Todd Parrott: Robert Yates made a brilliant move teaming
Parrott with Dale Jarrett. The two have won two Daytona 500s and a
Winston Cup title. Parrott has followed in the footsteps of his
father, Buddy, as a proven crew chief who can direct race teams to
victories. Parrott was instrumental in building the original
``Rainbow Warriors'' pit crew. He's an obvious pick for the top
spot.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jimmy Makar: He doesn't grab headlines and operates with a
low-key demeanor like his driver, Bobby Labonte. Makar has been
with the Joe Gibbs team from the beginning, giving the 18 car a
legitimate chance to win this year's Winston Cup championship. He
is the best at understanding the driver's needs and making
adjustments. After starting at the back of the pack in Atlanta last
November, Makar made adjustments and Labonte eventually won the
race.
</P>
<P>
   3. Jimmy Fennig: Much of Mark Martin's success can be attributed
to Fennig. The two communicate well when they set up the No. 6
Taurus. The radio communication between them on race day shows that
they are on the same page while deciding how to keep the team in
front.
</P>
<P>
   4. Greg Zippadelli: Many are pointing to the Zippadelli-Tony
Stewart tandem as the next Ray Evernham-Jeff Gordon duo. That is
lofty company, but the Pontiac team enjoyed the best rookie season
of any driver in NASCAR history. A year ago, NASCAR car fans were
wondering who Zippadelli was. Now they know.
</P>
<P>
   5. Tommy Baldwin, Jr.: When rumors began to swirl about the
departure of Ray Evernham from Hendrick Motorsports, Baldwin's name
kept surfacing as the man to lead Jeff Gordon into the new century.
He was offered the job but declined, saying that he was seeing
progress with Bill Davis Racing and Ward Burton and wanted to be
part of their success. Burton had made it to third in the points
standings before struggling last week at Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Some strong performances from those who are making a move toward
the front of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Johnny Benson: He bought his way out of his contract with the
No. 26 Roush team and it looks like he made a wise decision. His
No. 10 Pontiac led late in the Daytona 500 only to be worked over
by five Fords at the end. He backed up a good SpeedWeek with a
solid sixth place finish at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dale Earnhardt, Jr.: Most thought he would be good, but
Earnhardt Jr. ran up front most of the day at Las Vegas. He led 43
laps and was a legitimate threat to win.
</P>
<P>
   FREE FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Some weak performances from those who appear headed to the back
of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hendrick Motorsports: The leader of the bow-tie brigade has
fallen on hard times early in 2000. Jeff Gordon has gone eight
consecutive races without a top-five finish. Terry Labonte is
waiting for the emergence of the 1996 magic between he and recently
reunited crew chief Gary DeHart. Jerry Nadeau's season has been
dismal. The road-racing ace is praying for Sears Point and Watkins
Glen to get here soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gary Nelson: Nelson, NASCAR's series director, continues to
defend the belief in some corners that NASCAR racing has become
boring. While discussing the subject on Tuesday's ``NASCAR Live''
radio show, Nelson read endless statistics supporting the claim
that that the 2000 season is one of NASCAR's most competitive ever.
The fans aren't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who drives the No. 6 Ford Taurus in Winston Cup and
the No. 60 car in the Busch Series, is coming on strong after back
surgery during the off season. He has said that this year will be
his last in the Busch series, where he is the all-time leader with
41 victories. Here Martin talks with Cox News Service reporter Rick
Minter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After three weekends of driving in two divisions, how is your
back?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's real good. The pain is gone. It is still going to be
sort of a rebuilding process for probably the next year. It feels
great right now, and I'm able to do everything I could do and more,
than before I had the back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Considering all your success in the Busch Grand National
Series, why are you giving it up?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm getting old, getting tired. They ask too much of you
nowadays. There are too many interviews, too much media, too many
fans, too many races, too many sponsor appearances. I can't do
everything. It used to be I could just drive one car and then drive
the other. Now, I have to do all these other things.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have been instrumental in getting Matt Kenseth a ride in
a Roush Racing Ford. What impressed you about Matt?
</P>
<P>
   A: I knew where he came from and where he was racing. I knew he
was winning races in a lot of different cars, driving for a lot of
different people. That meant he knew how to make cars go, and he
wasn't relying on the teams. They didn't have enough depth to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the next Matt Kenseth?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I had the wherewithal, I'd have Casey Atwood under
contract. I forced Matt on Roush Racing, and if I was in charge I'd
have Casey, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people have said the Daytona 500 was a boring race. Do
you think it was, and what do you think of the new shock rules for
Talladega and Daytona?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just because nobody flipped doesn't mean it was boring. I
think the new shock rule is great. The reason I had a chance in
that race is because handling mattered. Handling has to matter for
it to be racing. I've been racing for 25 years, and handling has
always mattered everywhere, except Daytona and Talladega since we
started running restrictor plates.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the pressures that led to your retirement from the Busch
series making you think about how long you want to stay in Winston
Cup?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not worried about it. I'm going to be competitive for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   QUEST FOR VICTORY:
</P>
<P>
   Drivers with more than 100 NASCAR Winston Cup starts still
trying for that elusive first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Waltrip, 431
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mast, 311
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave, 282
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach, 198
</P>
<P>
   Chad Little, 192
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Wallace, 188
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pressley, 137
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Benson, 131
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Craven, 129
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner, 113
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fast fact: Michael Waltrip has shown strength at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. Waltrip scored a top-10 finish at the 1999 Cracker Barrel
500 and had a good showing at last year's fall race before an
unfortunate accident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
