<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-ELLIOTT10-COX     03-09 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ELLIOTT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill Elliott remains full of drive in year 25
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Feb. 29, 1976, Bill Elliott, his family and a few friends
from Dawsonville, Ga., showed up at Rockingham, N.C., with a
second-hand Ford Torino and a desire to become Winston Cup racers.
</P>
<P>
   Few people would have imagined that the skinny kid with the
bushy red hair and the syrupy Southern drawl one day would rule
Winston Cup racing. Or that he would still be a top competitor in
his 25th season.
</P>
<P>
   Even Elliott concedes that his success _ 40 victories, 49 poles,
the 1988 championship, a speed record and more than $21 million in
career earnings _ seemed unlikely on that first trip to ``the
Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a clue what we were doing,'' Elliott said. ``I
enjoyed working on the cars probably more than driving. Driving
became part of what I was doing, but I thoroughly enjoyed working
on the car. That was the biggest challenge _ working on the car and
making it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Elliott's latest challenges: Handling the flood of
speculation in recent weeks that he'll be switching to Dodge from
Ford next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll all come out in the wash on Friday,'' Elliott said
Wednesday when asked to comment on the rumors of the move to a new
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Everham, who left Jeff Gordon's garage last year to strike
out on his own with Dodge, plans a news conference Friday morning
to announce one of the two drivers for his Dodges next year.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that Elliott will be the driver named to the
Evernham team.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Elliott's 25th season has been marked by early success.
He finished third at the Daytona 500 and chalked up a fourth-place
finish at the CarsDirect.com 400 at Las Vegas. Elliott ranks sixth
in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's career began to blossom in 1977 after Roger Penske
decided to sell his Ford race cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy bought all that stuff off Roger,'' Elliott said. ``That
was the turning point of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Equipped to compete, Elliott began to crack the top 10 on a
regular basis, and fellow driver Benny Parsons, now a TV analyst,
took an interest in his career. Together, they persuaded Michigan
businessman Harry Melling to back Elliott's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the experience, and when Harry started putting money
into it, we were able to put it all together,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   He finished second seven times in Melling's car before he got
his first victory, in the season-ending race of 1983 at Riverside,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Allison clinched the series title in that race. ``Bill had
worked so hard and done such a good job driving that him getting
his first win added an extra piece of pleasure to my winning the
championship that day,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Bill Elliot ruled Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He won the Daytona 500 and 10 other races, including the Winston
500 at Talladega and Southern 500 at Darlington Raceway. In winning
three of the circuits four biggest races, he became the circuit's
first Winston Million winner.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 9 Ford stayed on a roll, winning the 1987 Daytona 500
and the 1988 championship and setting a qualifying mark of 212.809
mph at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   Success brought with it some difficult moments for Elliott, who
was content with being rather anonymous while growing up in the
remote Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can give me a shovel and I can dig a ditch and be just as
happy as I can be,'' he said. ``I tell people that when I retire,
I'm going to get me a pulpwooder's truck and a old chain saw and
hit the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   As the media pressure intensified, Elliott had to spend more
time in front of the microphone. He still avoids those moments as
much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not a high-profile kind of guy,'' Elliott said.
``It's not that I don't want to talk. I'm just uncomfortable doing
it, so I just shy away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he does speak, fans respond. For 14 of the past 16
years, he has been voted the circuit's most-popular driver. Elliott
said he plans to give those fans more to cheer about than they've
had the last few years. His last victory in a points event came in
the 1994 Southern 500 at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in racing _ and in his race teams _ have hampered his
career in recent years, he said. But Elliott now believes he has
the right combination to win races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a great career, if it ends tomorrow,'' Elliott said.
``But I still love driving a race car and I plan to do it for
several _ make that numerous _ more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
