<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NY     03-09 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SUSPENDS CAMPAIGN, BUT DEFERS BUSH ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT6, NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ Sen. John McCain said Thursday that he was
``suspending'' his campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination. But he stopped short of endorsing his rival, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, and vowed to continue his fight for party
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we began this campaign that we faced a difficult
challenge,'' McCain said at an outdoor news conference where the
desert wind whipped through the air. ``Last Tuesday, that challenge
became considerably more difficult as a majority of Republican
voters made clear their preference for president is Governor
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's noon announcement came two days after his staggering
losses in the major primaries on Super Tuesday. McCain took most of
the New England states at stake, but he lost the important
battlegrounds of California and New York to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain simply congratulated Bush Thursday, saying ``he deserves
the best wishes of every American.'' But he did not say that he
planned to release his delegates _ 224, to date _ and he even
stopped short of offering the outright declaration that Bush would
definitely become the next president: ``He may very well become the
next president of the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a Colorado rally following McCain's announcement, Bush
acknowledged the strong run that his rival had given him. ``I know
the competition has made me a better candidate,'' Bush said as his
supporters cheered. ``I know the competition will help us win the
White House come November.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush quickly turned his attention to the issues of military
spending and tax cuts, firing shot after shot at Vice President Al
Gore, the expected Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, Gore's major rival, announced an hour before
McCain's news conference that he had halted his campaign for the
Democratic Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Neither McCain nor Bradley signaled a willingness to make a
presidential bid on an independent ticket, as some supporters of
each of the underdogs hoped they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my party,'' McCain said. ``It is my home. Ours is the
party of Lincoln, Roosevelt and Reagan. That's good company for any
American to keep, and it is a distinct privilege to serve the same
cause that those great Americans dedicated their lives to.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, McCain had said that his party loyalty
was manifested in his quest to reform its workings. It was this
very image of an establishment outsider that propelled the senator
to unexpected popularity. He used Thursday's news conference to
emphasize his reform message, vowing that he would ``never walk
away from a fight'' and drawing wild whoops and thunderous applause
from his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped that our campaign would be a force for change in the
Republican Party,'' he said, ``and I indeed feel we've set a course
that will ultimately prevail in making our party as big as the
country we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, McCain lashed out at Bush for appealing
to the most conservative factions of the Republican Party. Bush
drew much of his primary votes from the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   By not releasing his delegates, McCain is trying to ensure that
he will have a prominent voice at this summer's Republican
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Anticipating McCain's concession, a few of Bush's supporters in
the Senate reached out to the senator's allies on Wednesday in the
hope of healing any rift between the two Republicans and uniting
the party.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of McCain said that Kenneth Duberstein, a former
White House chief of staff under President Ronald Reagan, and Sen.
Charles Hagel of Nebraska were relaying word to Bush's allies that
the governor had to take the initial step to heal the breach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that Governor Bush is going to need Senator
McCain, not just for John McCain, but for who and what John McCain
represents,'' Hagel said. ``He represents reform as much as any one
dynamic of who McCain is. John McCain is going to want to have a
voice in helping shape a reform agenda in the Republican Party as
we go into the election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of them will have to have a conversation about this
and about campaign finance's priority on a Bush agenda. What I'm
saying is that a reform agenda will have to be there for McCain to
get enthusiastically engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel emphasized that while he and McCain had talked several
times a day for the past several days, they had not discussed
whether McCain's support for Bush would be conditioned on his
stance toward an overhaul of the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush triumphed over McCain on Tuesday from coast to coast
except in New England, he will go into the general election in a
less commanding position than Gore because he had to turn to the
Republican Party's most conservative elements to defeat his rival.
That has carried a political cost.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's victory in the critical general election state of
California, for example, exit polls showed that Bush's victory
depended on Republicans. He ran far behind both Gore and McCain
among such critical swing groups as independents and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   A joint front with McCain could help him repair some of the
damage and draw to his side the legions of new voters that McCain
drew into the primaries. But several aides or advisers to Bush said
that the Texas governor was not offering specific changes in his
position on overhauling campaign finance regulations simply to
placate McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the conservative allies that used direct mail and
telephone banks to help Bush defeat McCain did so in large part
because they oppose McCain's campaign finance proposals, which they
believe would cut their own abilities to influence elections and
the public debate.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, Bush balked when Gore pledged to swear off
unlimited donations to political parties so long as Bush did.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN, Bush noted Gore's widely criticized
actions in raising money for the Democratic Party in 1996 and said
that Gore should enter into a debate over such campaign funds with
President Clinton, a reference to recent news reports that Clinton
has been busily raising such cash for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such partisan finger-pointing did not deter McCain from
passionately railing on the overall issue of campaign reform
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With your help, my fellow Americans,'' he said, ``we will keep
trying to force open doors where there are walls to your full
participation in the great enterprises of our democracy, be they
walls of cynicism or intolerance or walls raised by self-interested
elite who would exclude your voice from the highest councils of our
government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
