<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably cooler air will surge across the Northeastern states
Friday in the wake of a cold front, bringing the unseasonable
warmth of the past several days to an abrupt end. Readings in many
locations across the East will be as much as 30 degrees colder than
they were during the afternoon Thursday. To the south, showers will
develop in the Carolinas along the trailing end of the same front.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern Mississippi Valley, an area of low pressure will
strengthen as the day progresses, leading to patches of rain. With
breezes out of the Gulf of Mexico increasing, some locations in the
northern Gulf Coast states will receive as much as two inches of
rain with locally heavier amounts possible. Some localized flooding
will occur, especially in poor drainage locations. Meanwhile,
showers will also extend into the south-central Plains on the
northern edge of this system.
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers are likely on the high plains of western Kansas and
eastern Colorado Friday as winds veer and rise up the sloping
terrain. Low clouds will also be found in this region as
temperatures struggle to rise out of the 30s. Scattered snow
showers are also likely farther to the north in the mountains of
Colorado and southern Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   An area of high pressure will move across southern Nevada
Friday, bringing abundant sunshine to much of southern California
and the deserts of the Southwest. Meanwhile, rain will spread
toward the Pacific Northwest coast as a cold front moves ashore.
Snow will develop in the Cascades later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dust In The Wind
</P>
<P>
   The sky often clears following the passage of a cold front, but,
for several hours on Wednesday, the sky turned a pale brown in
parts of Iowa in the wake of a front. The darkened skies were the
result of suspended dust several thousand feet above the ground.
The dust particles originated in the southern plains, where, on
Tuesday, strong winds from the west picked up dirt over the
region's parched soil. Not infrequently, dust from the Sahara
desert in Africa travels several thousand miles across the
Atlantic, dimming the cerulean skies over the Caribbean islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
