<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER10-COX     03-09 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: McCain, Bradley bow out
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHALLENGERS SHEATHE THEIR SWORDS
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley and John McCain formally announced today they're no
longer presidential candidates. Bradley's comments, in West Orange,
N.J., retained traces of his campaign fight, but he said he'll
support Al Gore. McCain, in Sedona, Ariz., stopped short of a
complete surrender, saying he'll reflect on what he can do to best
serve the country. He wished George Bush well, but did not endorse
him.
</P>
<P>
   FULL BORE ON GORE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, in Colorado today, thanked his vanquished GOP
rival and immediately turned his fire on Al Gore, accusing him of
inconsistencies in his approach to campaign finance reform. Bush
criticized Gore for talking about eliminating unregulated ``soft
money'' in election campaigns while at the same time planning to
headline party efforts to raise millions in soft money for his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK WEB SITE UPDATES
</P>
<P>
   As they ended their campaigns, Bill Bradley and John McCain were
quick to send the news out over cyberspace. Bradley's Web page gave
the news straight, telling visitors in big, bold letters that he
had withdrawn from the presidential race. And Bradley quickly
e-mailed supporters to thank them for their hard work. McCain's Web
page was a little more subtle. The letters were smaller, but the
message was the same. And gone was the pop-up window asking
visitors to donate money.
</P>
<P>
   MRS. BUSH GRACIOUS TO ALL
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush congratulated her husband's opponents _ on both sides
of the isle. ``Of course I want to say congratulations (to the
McCains) on a hard-fought campaign,'' she told ABC. ``I think
</P>
<P>
   Senator McCain brought a lot of ideas to the table that will
continue to be discussed. And I think that's important.'' Laura
Bush also congratulated the Gores. ``I think they ran a great race.
Looks like they won everything ... and I think that's terrific for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TEMPLE OF DOOM?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is hoping to ride the nation's prosperity to the White
House, but he faces eight months of questions about impoverished
Buddhist monks and nuns who contributed more than $100,000 to his
1996 campaign. And laying out what is likely to become a campaign
theme, George W. Bush said America is ready to end the Clinton-Gore
administration. ``Americans want someone who will restore honor and
dignity to the White House,'' he told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   OR, MAYBE, ALAN GREENSPAN SHOULD BE RUNNING?
</P>
<P>
   By 46 percent to 44 percent, Americans say George W. Bush is
``more likely to continue the nation's economic expansion'' than Al
Gore, according to a new USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll. The poll had a
3 percentage point margin of error, which means the candidates are
in a statistical tie on that question.
</P>
<P>
   KISS AND MAKE UP, THEN TIE THE KNOT?
</P>
<P>
   Some of John McCain's closest advisers have begun pushing him as
George W. Bush's running mate, a political alliance that would
require delicate fence-mending in the aftermath of their bitter
primary fight. McCain has said he would not consider the vice
presidency, but Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford, two South
Carolina Republicans who counseled McCain through his primary
contests, said they would urge McCain to consider taking the No. 2
spot.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE GROUND ON THE BATTLEGROUND
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore, party nominations assured, are
reaching out to John McCain's independent-minded primary voters,
each determined to capture the middle ground. In California, where
candidates were ranked by all voters on a single ballot, McCain
finished third overall to Gore and Bush, but was the top
vote-getter among independents. Gore is moving quickly to stake out
the high ground on campaign finance reform, saying he would make it
a campaign priority. That's a major McCain position, and a subject
on which Gore himself is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   AND THE BATTLE GROUND MEANS MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Once the most cash-flush presidential candidate in history,
George W. Bush is embarking on a campaign to replenish his coffers
with another $10 million after taking in just $2.8 million in
February _ less than one-third of the $10 million John McCain
raised during the month. Bush now has raised more than $73 million,
a record. And Al Gore, who unlike Bush is subject to federal
spending limits, plans to raise an additional $4 million to
supplement some $7 million in unspent taxpayer funds for his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T FORGET KEYES _ HE'S STILL IN IT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes has been quiet about it, but some aides say they
expect him to remain in the GOP presidential race. But his schedule
will be pared back dramatically. He's spending today at home in
Maryland before going to Utah and Oklahoma for the rest of the
week. That trip is followed by eight days off, and then,
presumably, a light, sporadic schedule for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   AND THEN, THERE'S ALWAYS ROSS PEROT
</P>
<P>
   Now that the dust has settled in the major party fights, Reform
Party activists are stepping up their calls to persuade Ross Perot
to make a third try for the White House. The Dallas Morning News
reports that while discussion about recruiting John McCain is
``mostly talk, a push to recruit Perot for a third run will
intensify.'' Supporters are said to be sending postcards to Larry
King, urging him to invite Perot on his show, where he launched his
1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   FCC LOOKING AT THOSE WILY ADS
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission is investigating
Republicans for Clean Air, a group backed by Texas entrepreneurs
that began running ads last week touting George W. Bush's
environmental record and slamming John McCain's. It initially was
unclear who was behind the group or who paid for the ads until Sam
Wyly, a Dallas software magnate and longtime Bush supporter,
stepped forward last Friday to take the credit. McCain's campaign
complained to the FCC _ and the Federal Election Commission as well
_ arguing that the ads should have indicated they actually were
funded by Wyly and his brother, Charles. At least one commissioner,
Gloria Tristani, suggested she might agree.
</P>
<P>
   NOT A SEXUAL ISSUE, JUST MARCHING FOR PEACE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton was confronted at a meeting of a homosexual
Democratic group in Greenwich Village by two hecklers who demanded
to know why she plans to march in the St. Patrick's Day parade,
which excludes gay marchers. She asked the pair, a man and a woman,
to please allow her to finish her remarks first. The hecklers
allowed her to proceed. So why will she march in the parade? She
said because of her interest in supporting the Irish peace process,
a cause she and President Clinton have been involved in for the
last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE AND ON TRACK
</P>
<P>
   More than 17,000 Democrats in Arizona cast ballots through the
Internet in the first two days of a primary billed as the first
binding online election. By the end of Tuesday, more than 13,000
Democrats had voted online, officials said, but the rate fell
Wednesday, after news that Bill Bradley would drop out of the race.
Arizona Democrats with Internet access can cast ballots through
Friday, at any time of day, and those without access can vote at
polling places Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   NICE AND RELAXED IN THE ISLANDS
</P>
<P>
   The final results of Tuesday's Hawaii Democratic caucuses won't
be ready until early next week. Some districts on islands beyond
Oahu are having trouble compiling their numbers and sending them to
party headquarters in Honolulu, a party official said. The numbers
should arrive by Friday and be compiled by Monday. According to
preliminary figures compiled at midnight Wednesday, Al Gore won
nearly all of Hawaii's 14 delegates to the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   EMBATTLED D.A. IN ANOTHER RUNOFF
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles District Attorney Gil Garcetti, under fire for his
handling of the city's unfolding police corruption scandal, has
been forced into a November runoff election against one of his top
deputies. With about half of the vote counted, Garcetti led two
challengers with 39 percent, far short of the majority needed to
win a third term outright. Steve Cooley, a veteran deputy D.A. who
heads Garcetti's welfare fraud unit, had 37 percent. Garcetti was
forced into a runoff four years ago, too, after failing to win a
conviction against O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   RESHAPING A STATE
</P>
<P>
   A Republican candidate for governor of West Virginia wants to
help shape his state, but Joseph Oliverio wants to do it by lopping
off the Eastern Panhandle. He thinks a sale to Virginia or Maryland
could bring the state $20 billion for much-needed infrastructure
projects _ and do those three counties a favor at the same time.
``We just abuse these three counties. ... We take their tax money
and then show up every four years saying, `Vote for me!' They
deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
