<HEADER>
A2054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPACEMAN-BOOK-REVIEW-     03-09 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEMAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. SPACEMAN': HANG AROUND WITH EARTHLINGS AT YOUR OWN RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hero of Robert Olen Butler's new novel is nicer than Garry
Shandling's womanizer from outer space, calmer than Robin Williams'
Mork, and more conflicted than Steven Spielberg's E.T. As aliens
go, he's a pretty regular guy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plot of ``Mr. Spaceman,'' it sounds as if it came
straight from the pages of The National Enquirer: An alien, charged
by his superiors with learning the ways of earthlings, marries a
woman from a small town in Alabama, abducts a busload of tourists
and debriefs them aboard his spaceship in an effort to prepare
himself for a millennial appearance on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   It is a testament to Butler's gifts as a writer that he has
fashioned from such cartoonish materials a novel of surprising
poignance. Although the story is marred by silly, forced
comparisons between the spaceman and the Messiah, it gains in
resonance as it moves along, to emerge as one of Butler's most
convincing performances yet: a work as amusingly quirky as his 1996
collection ``Tabloid Dreams'' and as affecting, in its quixotic
fashion, as his award-winning 1992 book ``A Good Scent From a
Strange Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Spaceman'' begins pretty much where a story in ``Tabloid
Dreams'' titled ``Help Me Find My Spaceman Lover'' left off. Desi,
a ``wiggly hairless shy courteous smart-as-a-whip'' alien, has
returned to Earth to fetch his humanoid beloved, a hairdresser
named Edna Bradshaw, and the two have blissfully set up
housekeeping aboard his spaceship. He loves her for being a
blabbermouth, for blurting out her every whim and thought. She
loves him for his sweetness, his earnest desire to understand the
human species and his fumbling, Ricky Ricardo way with American
words.
</P>
<P>
   Desi and Edna are playing host to 12 humans who were on their
way to a casino when Desi beamed their tour bus up to his ship.
Having watched plenty of television over the years, Desi does his
best to fashion a greeting that will welcome his guests and put
them at ease. ``Hi,'' he says. ``My name is Desi. I am a friendly
guy. There is a Kind of Hush All Over the World Tonight. I Would
Like to Teach the World to Sing. I Would Like to Buy the World a
Coke.'' Despite his best efforts to charm his visitors, Desi is
secretly troubled. For decades he has been observing and
interviewing earthlings, trying to make sense of their species'
peculiar ways, but he knows now that the research phase of his work
is ending. It is already Dec. 30, 2000, and in a matter of hours he
must descend to Earth and make himself known _ he is under orders
from his superiors to inform earthlings that they are not alone in
the cosmos _ no matter what the personal consequences of such an
announcement might be.
</P>
<P>
   Edna, understandably, fears for his safety, and Desi, despite
his species' serene rationality, finds himself becoming
increasingly anxious, too. In fact in recent days he has found
himself developing strangely human traits: for the first time in
his life, he has begun having dreams _ nightmares, really _ when he
goes to sleep, and he has begun to suffer, as all humans do, from
inchoate feelings of yearning and loss.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, whose earlier books have often demonstrated a taste for
portentous philosophizing, tends to harp, annoyingly, on the
abstract qualities that make human beings human, and he also tends
to dwell, annoyingly, on the qualities that make Desi seem
Christlike. He suggests that the 12 tour bus visitors will become
Desi's disciples and describes the home-cooked meal Edna serves the
guests as Desi's ``last supper.''
</P>
<P>
   When these matters are allowed to recede into the background,
and Butler simply focuses on the sad-funny exchanges between his
characters, the results are more persuasive. Desi undergoes a kind
of mind meld with each of his visitors, which gives them all a
chance to tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   There's Judith Marie Nash, daughter of a born-again minister,
who believes _ or wants to believe _ that Desi is ``Jesus come
again.'' There's Hudson Smith, a black lawyer who mocks his
father's belief in the American dream, even as he realizes that his
own success stems from his father's faith. There's a Vietnamese
refugee named Lucky who loves to gamble, figuring that if you lose
as big a thing as your country, ``the great cosmic odds'' are that
you're due to win something equally large. There's Arthur
Stackhouse, a World War II veteran, who remains haunted by the
atomic test he once witnessed in the Nevada desert.
</P>
<P>
   In telling these people's stories Butler draws upon the same
gifts of empathy and insight, the same ability to limn an entire
life in a couple of pages, that he used to give his portraits of
Vietnamese immigrants in ``A Good Scent From a Strange Mountain''
such tenderness and power.
</P>
<P>
   As for Desi, Butler has managed to make him odd enough to seem
genuinely ... uh, alien while at the same time endowing him with
the melancholy sense of dislocation that afflicts so many of his
earlier heroes. In relating Desi's encounters with a human world
that's both in thrall to a tabloid culture of quick money and in
search of some kind of spiritual redemption, he has written a
pseudo-sci-fi novel that is at once funny and humane, entertaining
and touching.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MR. SPACEMAN'
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Olen Butler
</P>
<P>
   223 pages. Grove Press. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MIDNIGHT-FILM-REVIEW-     03-09 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDNIGHT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIDNIGHT': AFTER PERSONAL DARKNESS A MILLENNIAL DAWN IN RIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Midnight'' takes place in Rio de Janeiro in the recent past _
about 10 weeks ago, to be precise. Its story begins on the morning
of Dec. 30, 1999, and concludes two days later, in the bright dawn
of a new millennium, with the world looking pretty much the same as
it did before, which, given that the final scene takes place on one
of Rio's spectacular white sand beaches, is not too shabby.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers, Walter Salles and Daniela Thomas, capture some
of Rio's less lovely realities as well. In tracing the crossing
paths of characters drawn from Brazil's middle class and from its
criminal underworld, their camera captures the homelessness,
poverty and corruption that plague Brazilian society.
</P>
<P>
   But like ``Central Station,'' Salles' previous film,
``Midnight'' finds occasions for hope in the midst of general
unhappiness. Its mood, at once mournful and exuberant, owes
something to the spirit of samba, Rio's great contribution to world
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnight'' is a modest, somewhat sentimental film whose appeal
may lie as much in its evocative location as in the story it tells.
Its best sequence is a long, slow chase through the winding
alleyways of a favela, one of the crowded shantytowns that cling to
the hillsides above the bay.
</P>
<P>
   There are also spectacular rooftop shots that are like gritty
postcards of the blue ocean and metastasizing slums spread out
under the beneficent arms of a giant white statue of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Central Station,'' ``Midnight'` is about an unlikely
encounter between two incongruous characters _ in this case a
relatively affluent woman who makes her living helping others and a
representative of the urban demimonde. Maria (Fernanda Torres), a
speech tutor for the deaf, lives in a comfortable high-rise
apartment with her lover, Pedro (Carlos Vereza), a saturnine
intellectual who, on the last day of the century, abruptly abandons
her.
</P>
<P>
   Thrown into despair, she decides to hurl herself from the roof
of her building, which is where she meets Joao (Luiz Carlos
Vasconcelos), a convict who has been clandestinely released from
prison to kill his old friend Chico (Mateus Nachtergaele), a petty
hoodlum and police snitch.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vasconcelos and Torres are as unstintingly lugubrious as
they are beautiful to look at, and the film's pulse is supplied by
Nachtergaele, whose jittery, streetwise energy recalls a young
James Cagney. He is assisted by some deft hand-held-camera work and
beautiful color cinematography as well as by the natural vibrancy
of Rio.
</P>
<P>
   The climactic meeting of Joao and Maria _ she's virtually naked,
he's just out of prison and fireworks are going off all around
them, so you kind of know what's coming _ feels more like the
playing out of a narrative conceit than a plausible event in the
lives of two people.
</P>
<P>
   It's as trumped-up and artificial as the idea that a
happenstance of the calendar is a major event in history. In
attempting to debunk the notion that the passing of the millennium
is an event of apocalyptic significance, ``Midnight'' gives the
notion more credence than it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   But when it forgoes this kind of grandiosity in favor of close
attention to its characters and setting, ``Midnight'' is an
interesting, occasionally touching film. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MIDNIGHT' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Daniela Thomas and Walter Salles; written (in
Portuguese, with English subtitles) by Thomas, Salles and Joao
Carneiro; director of photography, Walter Carvalho; edited by
Felipe Lacerda; music by Antonio Pinto, Eduardo Bid and Nana
Vasconcellos; art director, Carla Caffe; produced by Pierre
Chevalier and Carole Scotta; released by Winstar Cinema. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Fernanda Torres (Maria), Luis Carlos Vasconcellos (Joao),
Mateus Nachtergaele (Chico), Nelson Sargento (Vovo) and Carlos
Vereza (Pedro).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 64 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
