<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRENCH-CINEMA-2TAKES-     03-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-CINEMA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RENDEZ-VOUS WITH FRENCH CINEMA': A TASTING MENU OF GALLIC CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This replaces NUIT-FILM-REVIEW)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No actress in the world is able to project more
emotion through a mask of immobility than Catherine Deneuve, the
enduring French star who gives one of her deepest screen
performances in Philippe Garrel's film ``Le Vent de la Nuit''
(``Night Wind'').
</P>
<P>
   This beautiful but sad-hearted movie, a high point of the Film
Society of Lincoln Center's annual ``Rendez-Vous With French
Cinema'' series, is a meditation on the relentless passage of time
and the suicidal impulses of two diehard romantics who refuse to
accept life's inevitable changes.
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve is Helene, a wealthy married woman from old money who is
desperately in love with Paul (Xavier Beauvois), a feckless young
sculptor of no particular charm. As Paul's commitment to Helene
wavers, she becomes increasingly agitated and possessive.
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve registers Helene's panic and frustration in minute but
telling changes of expression and vocal tone: a mouth that almost
imperceptibly tightens, eyes that brim with squeezed-back tears and
a voice that involuntarily clenches. Even when Helene finally
cracks and commits a desperate act, she maintains her formidable
reserve. Yet somehow Deneuve subtly registers every emotion
seething behind Helene's impenetrable surface.
</P>
<P>
   An irony at the heart of the movie is that Deneuve's towering
stature in French cinema is owed in part to her ageless beauty.
Time has not passed her by, the way it has passed her character by.
Helene eventually meets her doomed male counterpart, Serge (Daniel
Duval), a gaunt, taciturn architect and onetime political
revolutionary who is Paul's artistic mentor.
</P>
<P>
   As Paul and Serge drive from Positano to Paris to Berlin, we
glimpse an immaculate, economically robust Europe. Yet Serge, like
Helene, is unable to accept the present and remains obsessed with
self-destruction for reasons that are never totally specified.
</P>
<P>
   One of the remarkable things about the movie is the way it
withholds evaluation. Instead of casting a psychoanalytically
knowing gaze on these unhappy middle-aged people, it prefers to
paint them as romantic heroes. Yes, they may be fools, but they are
also the ravaged survivors of a nobler, more authentic era.
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve's neurotic, despairing Helene is only one of many
powerful female performances in this season's ``Rendez-Vous,''
which opens Friday at the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center
and runs through March 19.
</P>
<P>
   If this year's series were to be summed up in one phrase, it
might be the Year of the Woman. Although women have always been
held in much higher regard by the French cinema than by Hollywood,
a majority of the strongest entries in the 16-film series are by
and about women.
</P>
<P>
   The subjects range from children to teen-agers to the
middle-aged. ``Le Vent de la Nuit,'' incidentally, is not the only
movie to feature Deneuve, who also stars in Gabriel Aghion's much
more conventional screwball comedy, ``Belle Maman''(``Beautiful
Mother'').
</P>
<P>
   Another high point of the series is Daniele Thompson's
warm-hearted ensemble film, ``La Buche,'' (``Yule Log'') which was
a big hit in France. Making her directorial debut, Thompson, a
screenwriter who collaborated with Patrice Chereau on his films
``Queen Margot'' and ``Those Who Love Me Can Take the Train,'' has
created a rich, tasty plum pudding of a movie about the members of
an extended Parisian family uneasily gathering together at
Christmas after the death of their mother's second husband.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this Gallic answer to ``Home for the Holidays''
are three sisters: Louba (Sabine Azema), a nightclub singer of
Russian folk songs whose long affair with a married man has reached
a critical turning point; Sonia (Emmanuelle Beart), a beautiful,
affluent superwoman whose picture-perfect marriage is on the rocks;
and Milla (Charlotte Gainsbourg), their sullen, rebellious younger
sister.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond capturing the mixture of melancholy, anxiety and
exhilaration that the holiday season brings to most of us, this
tour de force of ensemble acting offers incisive but compassionate
portraits of more than half a dozen complex characters whose lives
are all in rapid flux.
</P>
<P>
   A riskier, more volatile group portrait, Noemie Lvovsky's film
``La Vie Ne Me Fait Pas Peur'' (``I'm Not Afraid of Life''),
examines the frenetic childhood and adolescence of a clique of four
girls growing up in the 1970s and early '80s. The movie dives
headlong into the spirit of childhood, capturing as few movies have
done the raw, untamed energy of girls passing through the tomboy
stage of pre-pubescence into a turbulent, boy-crazy adolescence of
fly-by-night fads and crazy, momentary obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   The movie plunges us into the rough-and-tumble physical and
emotional chaos of youth with all its embarrassingly uncontrollable
emotions amped up high. While the movie doesn't sort out its
characters' histories as carefully as it might, it takes huge
risks, including staging its characters' fantasies in
candy-colored, costumed musical sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Solveig Anspach's ``Haut les Coeurs!'' (``Chin Up!'') and Pascal
Thomas' ``Dilettante,'' by contrast, are carefully drawn,
compelling portraits of individual women. ``Haut les Coeurs!'' is a
finely acted, clinically detailed portrait of Emma, a pregnant
30-year-old musician (beautifully played by Karin Viard) who is
found to have breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Advised by one doctor to abort her four-month-old fetus lest it
be deformed by chemotherapy, she resists and arranges with another,
more caring doctor to bear the child prematurely (by Caesarean
section) at the same time she undergoes a mastectomy. The movie is
acutely attuned to the doctor-patient relationship and the
wrenching medical choices a cancer patient must make.
</P>
<P>
   Viard's compelling performance takes us on an emotional roller
coaster whose moods run from a wild and scary defiance to abject
terror and self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``La Dilettante,'' Catherine Frot gives a masterly,
sympathetic portrait of a perplexing character, a 40-something
woman with two grown children who impulsively returns to Paris from
Switzerland, where she has been living, to start a new life. Her
character, Pierrette, is a sophisticated charmer who has never
taken life all that seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Even when she lands in prison after helping an unscrupulous
antiques dealer buy a valuable heirloom at bargain prices, she
maintains a blithe detachment. While some might describe Pierrette
as having psychopathic tendencies, others would laud her as a free
spirit. The movie withholds any judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Puce'' and ``Les Vacances'' (``Holidays''), two short films
by Emmanuelle Bercot playing together, both feature remarkable
performances by Isild Le Besco, a young actress who captures the
impish brashness of early adolescent sexuality with an astonishing
naturalness.
</P>
<P>
   In ``La Puce,'' by far the more substantial of the two, she is a
virginal but curious 14-year-old girl who allows herself to be
seduced by a man more than twice her age. Every slippery nuance of
a power game that ends in what would be called statutory rape in
the United States rings nastily true.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every film in the series is so directly concerned
with female experience. ``Ma Petite Entreprise'' (``My Little
Business''), which opens the 10-day festival Friday, is a
skillfully plotted caper about a law-abiding woodworker forced to
concoct an elaborate insurance scam after his workshop is destroyed
by fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Enfants du Marais'' (``The Children of the Marshland'') is
similarly lighthearted. A nostalgic valentine to life in rural
France between the two world wars, it is peopled with lovable
eccentrics.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Klapisch's millennial science-fiction comedy
``Peut-Etre'' (``Perhaps'') stars a wizened but still charming
Jean-Paul Belmondo as a futuristic patriarch who encounters his
father as a young man during a New Year's Eve time warp and begs
him to impregnate his girlfriend so that he can be born. The
imaginatively designed right-to-life fable portrays Paris in the
not-too-distant future as half-buried in desert sand.
</P>
<P>
   In Benoit Jacquot's ``Pas de Scandale'' (``Keep It Quiet''),
Fabrice Luchini plays a corrupt corporate buccaneer recently
discharged from prison whose mysterious conversion from crook to
childlike truth-teller upsets his family and associates upon his
return. The movie, which features Isabelle Huppert as his grimly
proper wife, takes a heavy-handed swipe at upper-middle-class
social hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peau d'Homme, Coeur de Bete'' (``Skin of Man, Heart of
Beast''), the feature film debut of Helene Angel, portrays another
return. A man who left home 15 years ago under mysterious
circumstances comes back to the fold and disturbs the family's
psychological chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like misty-eyed love stories, there's Francois
Dupeyron's ``C'est Quoi la Vie?'' (``What's Life?''), a kind of
back-to-nature answer to Claude Lelouche's make-out classic, ``A
Man and a Woman.'' In this variation, a handsome young farmer (Eric
Caravaca) and a reclusive opera singer (Isabelle Renauld) find
happiness in a small farm in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Createur'' (``The Creator''), an outrageous satire of the
self-centered artist, stars Albert Dupontel, an actor, writer and
director who at times suggests a Gallic Peter Sellers, as a
playwright whose monumental writer's block can be breached only by
acts of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Claude Berri's ``Debandade,'' France's first
Viagra comedy. In casting himself as a dilapidated over-60 art
dealer who discovers the joys of the sexual wonder drug, Berri
certainly displays courage in portraying late-middle-aged sexual
activity. That doesn't make the spectacle of Berri pawing and
kissing a woman less than half his age especially appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   If this year's ``Rendez-Vous'' series isn't quite as strong or
as sensational as last year's (which introduced Catherine
Breillat's ``Romance,'' with its hard-core erotic sequences), it
still displays a level-headed humanity that one doesn't find in
American films, with their mixture of gadgetry and market-tested
emotional string-pulling. One of the keys to that humanity is the
assumption that women's lives are as important as men's. That sense
of sexual balance makes all the difference. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1748EST &QL; 
