<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-09 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE EXIT STRATEGY  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In any war, political or military, a good general
has an exit strategy to save face in case his grand vision of
victory doesn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill Bradley, that was easy; with no primary victories, he
had no choice but to pull out of the Democratic presidential
contest. He made brave noises about continuing to talk up issues
that are important to him but he has lost his public megaphone and
will have trouble being heard from now on.
</P>
<P>
   For Sen. John McCain, there are more options. He suspended his
campaign, but he is in a strong position to remain a force for
reform in the Republican Party. He did not detail his full exit
strategy, which is bound to be complicated _ balancing partisan
loyalty with a continuing crusade to change the GOP and the
campaign process. He said he would not take the third-party route.
</P>
<P>
   Both men insisted they would never, ever accept the vice
presidential nomination, recoiling from the notion in horror. To
hear them tell it, being second banana to Vice President Al Gore or
Gov. George W. Bush has about as much appeal as a pit full of
alligators.
</P>
<P>
   They could in the end change their minds, as other losers have
done once their own presidential hopes are thoroughly dashed.
Lyndon Johnson, for instance, swore he would never take the second
spot right up to the moment John F. Kennedy asked him to do so. In
any case, there is no sign that Gore and Bush plan to tap their
defeated rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley brings no additional political strength to a Gore
ticket, and McCain doesn't fit Bush's oft-repeated ideal of a
running mate as ``someone who likes me.''
</P>
<P>
   While McCain's speech was conciliatory in tone, he was
noticeably unenthusiastic about the future Republican nominee. He
wished Bush well but did not endorse him or even suggest that he
meant to support his candidacy in more than a superficial way.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's potential for stirring up trouble gives him
considerable political leverage to demand things of Bush in the
name of party unity. The question is how much he wants, and what
Bush is prepared to give. If I were Bush, I'd give a lot, short of
selling my soul.
</P>
<P>
   Defeated candidates with a following who are not brought
promptly back into the fold can greatly undermine the winner's
future _ and help their own political standing. After losing the
GOP primaries to President Ford in 1976, Ronald Reagan pretty much
sat on his hands during the campaign and contributed to Ford's
defeat by Jimmy Carter. Then Reagan picked up the mantle four years
later.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot win the White House unless he can attract a large
chunk of the moderate and independent voters who preferred McCain.
Nearly 20 percent of McCain voters polled during Tuesday's election
said that if the senator were not the nominee, they would support
Gore over Bush and only 10 percent said they would jump to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At this early stage, McCain is apparently thinking only in terms
of somehow pursing his campaign reform agenda in the Senate and at
this summer's GOP convention. His power as Senate Commerce
Committee chairman will be helpful there.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush and the Republican establishment oppose the central
legislative changes he wants to make, it is difficult to see how
they can successfully co-opt McCain. But the GOP will have to try.
He may have lost the election but he now belongs in the pantheon of
800- pound political gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee for the Study of the American Electorate (CSAE), a
nonpartisan research organization, reports that McCain was solely
responsible for a surge in GOP turnout on Super Tuesday. He
galvanized both supporters outside his party who crossed over to
help him and opponents within who wanted to stop him. Many of his
voters were independents more liberal on social issues than
traditional Republicans. Roughly one third of the electorate is
firmly Democratic, one third Republican and the rest independent _
the urgent target of both general election candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, CSAE director, notes that Republican Party turnout
was the highest since Sen. Barry Goldwater ran in 1964,
inaugurating the party's lurch to the right. It rose 4.3 percentage
points to a level of 13.6 percent of the eligible electorate.
Democratic turnout, by contrast, was low, at 10.1 percent. ``McCain
stole any semblance of interest and contest from the Democratic
race,'' Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gans doesn't predict what might happen in the general
election without McCain. Sustaining voter excitement is now up to
the two philosophically opposed candidates, the issues they develop
and the tightness of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Will Gore and Bush sharpen their differences or move
simultaneously to the mushy middle? Gore is stuck with the Clinton
administration (Bush constantly refers to the Clinton-Gore years),
but if Gore can keep the focus on the economy rather than the
scandals, he may transcend that guilt by association. Bush is stuck
with Pat Robertson, who has his shoes on backward marching
resolutely into the past, but Bush's own record is milder and more
acceptable to the mainstream, and he may overcome that association
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The mushy middle may be boring, but it is safe. It doesn't scare
folks. Tilting too far one way or the other can create a backlash,
as McCain discovered.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy was a surprise blockbuster. What will he do
for an encore? You can bet there will be one.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
