<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      03-09 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWMAKERS STRESS NEED TO IDENTIFY, TREAT POTENTIALLY VIOLENT
YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tackling the issue of youth violence in the wake of
several fatal school shootings across the country, a bipartisan
group of lawmakers issued a report Thursday calling for more
programs aimed at identifying troubled children early and
addressing their mental health needs.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 lawmakers, who included representatives as ideologically
diverse as conservative Bob Barr, R-Ga., and liberal Sheila
Jackson-Lee, D-Texas, agreed that state and local jurisdictions
need to focus attention on boosting the ability of individual
schools to intervene in the lives of troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, the panel co-chair, said the panel
members steered clear of discussing gun control, a divisive issue
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting weekly since last fall, the lawmakers made three
broad conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Congress should ensure that early intervention programs are
adequately funded in schools and communities across the country.
One example is where a uniformed police officer is placed full time
in a school to counsel students and defuse potentially violent
situations.
</P>
<P>
   &Cx1f; _ Congress should ensure that schools have the resources to
identify ``at-risk'' children and to provide them with health
programs and mental health counseling, especially if they are being
abused at home. Numerous studies have shown a link between abuse
and criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   _ The juvenile justice system should not apply a one-size-fits
all approach to children who break the law. Instead, the focus
should be on rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   The report also stressed the need for parents to provide a
``strong moral foundation'' and positive role models.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference, Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., who
co-chaired the panel, said ``early intervention efforts that
require the close participation of parents and communities are
essential to reducing youth violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost added that ``we must deal with this from a very early
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent schoolyard shootings have heightened concerns about
violence amount children and adolescents. On Feb. 29, a 6-year-old
Michigan boy shot and killed a 6-year-old girl in front of a
teacher and classmates. Last April, two teen-agers killed 12 fellow
students, a teacher and then took their own lives at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo. In 1998, two boys, 11-years-old and
13-years-old, opened fire at a middle school in Jonesboro, Ark.,
killing a teacher and four girls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
