<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0310-COX     03-09 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0310-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE HEARS ARGUMENTS IN ELIAN CASE, FATHER HIRES ATTORNEY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The fate of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez
inched toward a resolution Thursday, as a federal judge took
arguments in a long-awaited hearing on whether the boy should go
home to Cuba or stay with relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Michael Moore issued no decision and
gave no indication when he might do so.
</P>
<P>
   The judge instead listened to three hours of intense and often
arcane legal argument, then dismissed the teams of attorneys
without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Miami's Federal Courthouse, a small group of protesters
_ mostly Cuba exiles _ waved Cuban flags and chanted for Elian to
be allowed to stay in the United States. The boy did not attend the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The court date was the latest chapter in Elian's saga, which
began three months ago when he was found floating in an inner tube
off Fort Lauderdale after his mother and 10 other people perished
on an ill-fated attempt to flee Cuba by boat.
</P>
<P>
   The boy has lived with relatives in Miami since then, but his
case has become an international tug-of-war, prompting angry
rhetoric and dueling protests between Miami's Cuban exiles and
Cuban President Fidel Castro's communist government.
</P>
<P>
   In January, federal immigration officials ruled that Elian
should go back to Cuba to live with his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, saying that both U.S. and international law support the
notion that parents are best equipped to speak for their children
in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision triggered angry protests in Miami, and federal
officials backed away from forcibly taking Elian back to Cuba.
Instead, they invited the Miami relatives to file a federal lawsuit
to resolve the case.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's hearing, government lawyers argued that the
lawsuit should be tossed out, saying that federal immigration
decisions are not subject to review in the courts. They also said
Elian was too young to speak for himself, and that federal
officials properly identified the boy's father as the one who
should make decisions on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recognition of the rights and responsibilities of parents
is a fundamental part of our law and constitution,'' said the
government's lead attorney, Deputy Solicitor-General Edwin
Kneedler. ``The question is, 'Who best speaks for the child?'''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the Miami relatives said federal statutes also
grant any alien present in the United States the right to apply for
asylum regardless of their age, and that Elian was wrongly denied
that right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute clearly states that any alien physically present
in the U.S. has the right to apply for asylum,'' argued Barbara
Lopoa, one of the attorneys for Elian's Miami relatives. ``Nowhere
in the statute does it say that this right is limited solely to
adult aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's attorneys have filed an asylum application for the
boy, and argued that federal officials wrongly refused to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Moore questioned Kneedler closely on the point, asking
whether the government had or had not officially accepted the
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have it both ways,'' Moore said. ``The problem is
that the record doesn't support your argument. If an application
was accepted, then you have to hold a hearing and have due
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore also seemed troubled that the federal law governing such
cases doesn't spell out how old an alien must be in order to file
an asylum application on his own, or which federal officials have
the authority to decide who should speak for a child in such a
case.
</P>
<P>
   Kneedler admitted the statute is silent on those matters, but
again emphasized that U.S. and international law support the
child-parent bond.
</P>
<P>
   Government attorneys also argued that the federal court has no
authority in the case, and that the Miami relatives have no legal
standing to file court actions on Elian's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Moore could toss out the case for those reasons, or grant the
family's request and order an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In either event, the losing party could appeal, and the legal
battle could stretch on for weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Thursday, Juan Miguel Gonzalez
disclosed that he has hired a high-powered Washington attorney,
Gregory Craig, who represented President Clinton in his impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In an about-face from previous statements, Gonzalez said he is
prepared to come to the U.S. to take his son home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But when that day might come seemed no clearer after Thursday's
court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   One legal expert predicted the case could drag on for months,
especially if Judge Moore orders an asylum hearing for Elian. The
longer the boy stays with his Miami family, the less likely a court
would be to uproot him, said Ira Kurzban, a noted South Florida
immigration attorney who attended the hearing as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delaying tactic,'' he said ``That's been the family's
strategy from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
