<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DETERRENCE-FILM-REVIE     03-09 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETERRENCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DETERRENCE': PREPOSTEROUS, BUT A TINGLE OR TWO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The threat of nuclear war may have receded in the last two
decades, but it certainly hasn't disappeared. That's why a movie
like ``Deterrence,'' Rod Lurie's clunky political thriller about
nuclear brinksmanship in the near future, probably serves some
useful purpose, despite its ham-fisted preachiness and mediocre
acting.
</P>
<P>
   A shrill warning to the complacent, the movie extrapolates from
the present to eight years in the future with barely enough
credibility to make you shudder at the possibility of a nuclear
confrontation between the United States and Iraq. Almost despite
itself, it does produce a mild tingle or two.
</P>
<P>
   In Lurie's ominous vision of global politics in 2008, a large
Iraqi army marches into Kuwait unexpectedly while the United States
is preoccupied with potentially explosive tensions in Asia. The
sudden, large invasion is initiated while the incumbent president,
Walter Emerson (Kevin Pollak), is campaigning for his party's
nomination in Colorado. When a surprise blizzard traps him and
important members of his staff at a diner in the tiny town of
Aztec, they are forced to deal with the crisis equipped with only
four telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deterrence'' has the look, attitude and touch-all-bases
casting philosophy of a budget-conscious television movie from the
1970s. With its blunt admonitory tone and single-set location
(reminiscent of ``Twelve Angry Men''), it often has the feel of a
high school civics lesson packaged as melodrama. Its editorial
pretensions are underscored by an opening black-and-white montage
of actual presidents from Franklin D. Roosevelt through Bill
Clinton lambasting war.
</P>
<P>
   The diner's employees and patrons are a predictable variety-pack
assortment of types. They include its black cook (Bajda Djola) and
French-Canadian waitress (Clotilde Courau), an invective-spewing,
equal-opportunity bigot (Sean Astin) and a white middle-class
couple (Michael Mantell and Kathryn Morris) who happen to be
playing chess when the president's party pops in. Each wooden
character has his own designated speech pinning down a different
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The only character to depart from formula is the president, who
as played by Pollak is one of the least statesmanlike U.S. chief
executives to appear in a Hollywood film. Even though the character
wasn't elected president (he ascended from the vice presidency
after the death of his predecessor), Pollak's president, when
discussing world affairs, exhibits all the charm and stature of a
shifty-eyed accountant outlining tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Without appearing to think twice, he issues a preposterous
ultimatum to the Iraqis: If they don't immediately halt their
invasion and disarm their biological weapons, the United States
will launch a nuclear attack on Baghdad. He gives the residents
exactly one hour and 20 minutes to vacate the city. The
inappropriately sarcastic tone that creeps into his voice
occasionally suggests Dennis Miller delivering one of his
misanthropic rants.
</P>
<P>
   While the movie shows some nerve in depicting the president as a
hawkish cold fish, Pollak's Emerson is so devoid of appealing human
qualities that the notion of anyone having chosen this pompous
nebbish for a running mate is inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   The president's chief advisers aren't much more credible. Sheryl
Lee Ralph as his national security adviser, Gayle Redford, exhibits
a cool, glossy huffiness more appropriate to a pop diva than a
government official. Timothy Hutton, as his chief of staff, is
saddled with the movie's most bombastic speech, about how the
Garden of Eden was originally in Iraq and how dropping a nuclear
bomb in the area would be the equivalent of destroying the cradle
of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Having ``Deterrence'' unfold on a single set only adds to the
film's artificiality. Had the characters been given any depth or
complexity, the diner might have turned into a microcosm of the
larger world. But the little dramas that erupt among these
cardboard mouthpieces cooped up together are strictly the stuff of
amateur theater.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's strongest element is its reasonably sophisticated
projection of global politics based on present-day realities. But
even here, ``Deterrence'' falls apart when it pulls a final trick
out of its sleeve. Although it would be unfair to give that trick
away, suffice it to say it is not a whammy of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DETERRENCE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Rod Lurie; director of photography,
Frank Perl; edited by Alan Roberts; music by Lawrence Nash Groupe;
production designer, W. Brook Wheeler; produced by Marc Frydman and
James Spies; released by Paramount Classics.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kevin Pollak (Walter Emerson), Timothy Hutton (Marshall
Thompson), Sheryl Lee Ralph (Gayle Redford), Sean Astin (Ralph),
Bajda Djola (Harvey), Clotilde Courau (Katie), Michael Mantell
(Taylor Woods), Kathryn Morris (Lizzie Woods) and Mark Thompson
(Gerald Irving).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 101 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deterrence'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian); it has some strong language and one scene of
violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-09 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSION TO MARS': SMALL STEP FOR MAN, BUT A BIG WHOOP FOR
MARTIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As in ``Apollo 13,'' Gary Sinise gets to watch all his pals go
off into space without him. In ``Mission to Mars,'' he's Jim, a
morose astronaut pining for his dead wife, and his depression makes
him an unlikely candidate for the Mars mission. ``He's good,''
explains Cmdr. Woody Blake (Tim Robbins), ``but not for this.''
</P>
<P>
   All the characters _ the cast includes Don Cheadle, Connie
Nielsen and an uncredited Armin Mueller-Stahl _ are nice-guyish and
cooperative, so much so that they're nondescript. The director,
Brian De Palma, catches them in noble profile so often that you
wonder when the commemorative coins are going to be issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' takes off with a splash of wit, with the
ominous rumbles of a rocket launched toward the heavens. That
rocket explodes into a spray of confetti as the camera pulls back
to show a backyard barbecue and the happy NASA crew discussing the
coming Mars flight.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma loves to dance with the medium to show that any move,
from a quick twirl to an athletic arabesque, can be immediately
achieved. But what's not at his disposal this time is his ability
to mix tones. ``Mission to Mars'' is a plea for understanding, a
call for brotherhood. It's as much of a New Age paperweight as
``Contact,'' Robert Zemeckis' film about finding an otherworldly
intelligence, but De Palma is emotionally lost in the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' could be called De Palma's ``Abyss.'' And in
turn, that James Cameron opus was a brine-soaked attempt to work
through the themes of Stanley Kubrick's ``2001: A Space Odyssey''
with a benevolent perspective as an alien intelligence extended a
tendril of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma soars off into space toward the same end, with a group
of writers including Graham Yost of ``Speed'' and writers with
producers' credits like Ted Tally (``Silence of the Lambs'') and
David Goyer (``Blade''), although much of the picture feels as if
it came from the director. It can't take too many people to come up
with lines like ``Those stresses have never been tested in space!''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since such a grandiloquent souffle of
majesty and silliness refused to rise on the big screen: probably
not since ``The Abyss,'' in which Cameron's deepest desire was to
have audiences discover he was not just a genre filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma's gift is an ability to bend the generally rigid
constraints of genre to suit his needs by inflating the emotional
content of thrillers and film noir so that you choke on your
laughter or are simultaneously touched and frightened.
</P>
<P>
   He has been accused of being inexpressive, but his problem here
is that he is too enraptured by his subject. There's a
follow-your-bliss dreaminess here that wouldn't be out of place at
a Deepak Chopra seminar or on a Mannheim Steamroller album.
</P>
<P>
   The visual design is spectacular, and the scenes on the Martian
surface look so real that the picture could have been made on
location. A holographic sequence detailing the evolutionary link
between Earth and Mars is staggeringly well staged. Even in those
instances, the movie is undermined by De Palma's uncharacteristic
wet-eyed awe.
</P>
<P>
   He introduces a standard-issue alien with an elongated frame and
then goes that cliche one better. A single tear rolls down its _
well, I guess you'd call it its cheek _ and there it stands, as if
it were a Martian Iron Eyes Cody.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be an original moment in the entire movie,
and the score is so repetitive that it could have been downloaded
directly from -EnnioMorricone.com. All this addled sincerity comes
from trying to create wonderment for adults, growing out of Jim's
rediscovery of his humanity after he is later recruited for a
rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   Sinise's thoughtful patience in this situation makes him appear
to be a little sluggish, though not as sluggish as the movie, which
narratively seems to be taking place in zero gravity, where each
minute seems to last an additional 30 seconds. In space no one can
hear you snore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Mission to Mars' is rated PG (parental guidance suggested). It
includes grown-up astronaut language and potentially upsetting
violence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MISSION TO MARS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian De Palma; written by Jim Thomas, John Thomas
and Graham Yost, based on a story by Lowell Cannon and the Thomas
brothers; director of photography, Stephen H. Burum; edited by Paul
Hirsch; music by Ennio Morricone; production designer, Ed Verreaux;
produced by Tom Jacobson; David Goyer, Justis Greene, Jim Wedaa and
Ted Tally, co-producers; released by Touchstone Pictures. Running
time: 113 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Gary Sinise (Jim McConnell), Tim Robbins (Woody Blake),
Don Cheadle (Luke Graham), Connie Nielsen (Terri Fisher), Jerry
O'Connell (Phil Ohlmyer), Peter Outerbridge (Sergei Kirov), Kavan
Smith (Nicholas Willis), Kim Delaney (Maggie McConnell) and Armin
Mueller-Stahl (NASA chief). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
