<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     03-09 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LUXE SPLENDOR OF ROME IN THE 1700S 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City considers itself the art capital of the world, but
it will probably never be the equal of Rome in the 18th century.
Rome was a mecca for cultivated citizens from all over the world.
``Rome in the 18th century was like New York today,'' said Peter
Marino, a New York architect. ``You had to go and be seen there. It
was the center of energy, where everything was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Rishel, the senior curator for European paintings at
the Philadelphia Museum of Art, agreed. ``Rome was the pre-eminent
international school of art in 18th-century Europe,'' he said,
``the place where new ideas were most often hatched, nurtured,
developed and launched into international circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   For painters and architects especially, all roads led to Rome.
The French painters Jacques Louis David and Ingres went to paint
and see masterpieces. The English architects William Kent, Robert
Adam and John Soane measured ancient ruins. The Americans Benjamin
West and John Singleton Copley copied pictures by the masters.
</P>
<P>
   This influence is explored in ``The Splendor of 18th-Century
Rome,'' an ambitious exhibition that opens at the Philadelphia
Museum of Art on Thursday and runs through May 28. Some 400 works,
mostly paintings but also prints, drawings, sculpture, textiles,
furniture and objets d'art represent Rome's wealth in art during
that century.
</P>
<P>
   Rishel said the show, which has been in the works since 1991,
came from a realization that ``for the average museum visitor,
18th-century Rome remains terra incognita, and the work of even its
finest painters, sculptors and architects is unfamiliar.''
</P>
<P>
   The show reminds visitors that before Rome became the capital of
a united Italy in 1871, it was an independent Papal State. The
popes were generous patrons of all the arts. There are ravishing
examples of ecclesiastical pieces and vestments embroidered in gold
and silver. ``These are the luxe of the luxe,'' Rishel said. ``They
are as luxe as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition opens with a dazzling, two-foot-tall silver,
silver gilt and lapis lazuli inkstand showing the monument in the
middle of the piazza of the Quirinal Palace in Rome. The miniature
is a tour de force, complete with the Quirinal's famous Egyptian
obelisk and the two ancient sculptural groups on either side of it,
which depict Castor and Pollux and their horses. On the model the
horses are lids for the inkwells. The water in the Quirinal
fountain is represented by the blue lapis lazuli.
</P>
<P>
   The model was made in 1792 as a presentation piece for Pope Pius
VI, who could see the monument from the window of his summer
palace, by a Roman silversmith, Vincenzo Coaci (1756-94). Coaci was
the student of Luigi Valadier (1726-85), a Roman silversmith who
was the subject of an exhibition at the Louvre in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This artist was not only a gold and silversmith, but also a
designer and maker of both bronze and stone objects,'' Alvar
Gonzalez-Palacios writes of Valadier in the show's catalog.
Gonzalez-Palacios is the editor of a journal of decorative arts in
Rome and has just written a best-selling autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valadier was one of the first to perfect small-scale
reproductions in bronze of classical masterpieces,'' he writes,
``which in his hands became precious objects, embellished by
decoration and settings made of ancient colored marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition has three Valadier carta glorias, which are
religious crib sheets. These have elaborate gilt bronze frames with
stands. Inside the frame, where you might expect a picture,
Valadier has chiseled the Latin words of the Mass in silver _ just
in case a priest lost his place during Mass. They are dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   Valadier antiques are in great demand, and there are a few on
the market now. Aveline, a top Paris dealer, has two pairs of
signed Valadier candelabra that were made as centerpieces for the
tables of the nobility. Each has four gilt bronze arms coming out
of an alabaster vase that is supported by three caryatids. The
caryatids stand on a base decorated with multicolored marbles.
Jean-Marie Rossi, the proprietor, said they were very rare and
``have a very rare price.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariane Dandois, another Paris dealer, has a ``term'' attributed
to Valadier. As Dandois explained, ``According to Roman mythology,
a term was the god who marked and protected the boundaries of a
person's fields. He is always represented as a bust on a
pedestal.'' Her term, from about 1775, may have been made for the
gallery of the Palazzo Borghese in Rome, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The most stunning piece of furniture in the exhibition is
probably the console table designed by Vincenzo Pacetti. Its top is
one solid piece of black and white marble that looks like black
paint splattered over white snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romans were stone snobs,'' said Dean Walker, the senior
curator of decorative arts and sculpture at the museum. ``They got
green stone from Egypt and black and white from Aquitaine in
France.''
</P>
<P>
   An 18th-century stone sample book, also in the exhibition,
identifies the Pacetti marble as bianco and nero antico. It rests
on four caryatids, beautifully modeled male and female figures that
morph at the waist into normal table legs inset with the same
marble.
</P>
<P>
   Italian antiques at this elevated level seem to be coming back
into fashion, though they are very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big revival of interest in Italian furniture,'' said
Marino, the architect. ``I have two clients who don't want French
or Georgian antiques, only Italian, perhaps because they go well
with modern slick interiors. But this furniture needs volume; you
have to show it in big spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers also think it's in vogue. Lou Marotta, an antiques
dealer on East 60th Street in Manhattan, said, ``There is a demand
for top-of-the-line Italian pieces, but not as strong as in the
1980s.'' He has a pair of 18th-century gilded Roman consoles, with
veneered marble tops and cabriole legs ending in horse hooves,
priced at $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roman things are more edited,'' Marotta said. ``They are
incredibly powerful but they are not over the top, as Venetian
pieces often are. The days of an entire Roman room are over. A good
Italian antique has to be juxtaposed against something contemporary
to bring it down and make it more humorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Regal, another dealer on East 60th Street, said, ``Italian
furniture is not as fussy as French furniture, and it has more
movement than English furniture.'' He is selling a real souvenir of
the Grand Tour, a set of three buttermilk yellow marble miniature
Roman temples, for $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dandois best summed up the appeal. ``Roman things have more
fantasy and imagination than French pieces of the same period,''
she said. ``They have guts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
