<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CONDO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-09 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONDO PAINTING': LETTING AN ARTIST EXPLAIN, WHETHER IT HELPS OR
NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Condo Painting'' is not, as the title might seem to suggest,
an instructional film for apartment owners, but rather a 87-minute
documentary on the life, work and thought of George Condo, a
garrulous painter with a mischievous sense of humor and an
eccentric, quasi-mystical view of art and the world it inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   To call the film a documentary may be a bit misleading. Directed
by the Chicago filmmaker John McNaughton (whose earlier work
includes the cult classic pseudo-documentary ``Henry: Portrait of a
Serial Killer'' and the feverish sex thriller ``Wild Things'') in
close collaboration with its subject, ``Condo Painting'' tries not
only to record the artist's aesthetic theories but also to apply
them.
</P>
<P>
   What results is a free-form excursion, studded with abstract
music-video effects (and accompanied by a soundtrack featuring
music by people like DJ Spooky, Tom Waits and the Residents),
through the sensibility of a man who is sometimes enlightening,
sometimes amusing and sometimes annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Like many artists, Condo has built an elaborate intellectual
apparatus to explain what he does, and like most artists, what he
does is more interesting than his explanations. One of his central
conceits, borrowed from Aldous Huxley's mescaline bible ``Heaven
and Hell,'' involves contact with what Huxley calls the antipodes,
the distant regions of human consciousness that constitute a kind
of collective dream world.
</P>
<P>
   In Condo's words, these regions are inhabited by interpodal or
antipodal beings who look, in his portraits of them, like the
zombie kin of Yosemite Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Condo, a draftsman of considerable skill and a painter committed
to classical standards of discipline and decorum, declares
affinities to both the world of modern American pop culture and the
traditions of the old masters.
</P>
<P>
   One of his side projects is a handmade book called ``Granny's
Guide to Art History'' _ Granny as in Granny Clampitt of ``The
Beverly Hillbillies,'' whose head, along with those of other Nick
at Nite icons like Gomer Pyle and Barney Fife, Condo superimposes
on reproductions from Leonardo, Hals and Velazquez.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest debt seems to be not to any other visual artists,
but to the literary heroes of the Beat Generation. Allen Ginsberg
and William S. Burroughs appear in the movie, which also follows
Condo on a pilgrimage to Lowell, Mass., the hometown of Jack
Kerouac.
</P>
<P>
   Condo, a native of nearby Chelmsford, was born in 1957 and so
could not have known the Beats in their heyday. And while there is
something wishful and secondhand about his devotion to them, there
is also something earnest and touching. The most affecting part of
the movie, its last half-hour or so, observes Condo at work on a
painting he conceives as a tribute to Burroughs and Ginsberg, each
of whom died midway through the making of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Condo seems to be one of those peculiar souls who regard
Ginsberg, Burroughs and Kerouac not just as colorful characters or
interesting writers but also as major thinkers. Your tolerance for
``Condo Painting,'' which began as a 15-minute promotional film for
the PaceWildenstein Gallery before swelling to feature length, is
likely to depend on how much Beat idolatry you can stand.
</P>
<P>
   You may wish that Condo would expand further on the space-time
continuum, the status of conscious reality, the geography of the
antipodes and other vital matters. On the other hand, you may wish
that he would just shut up and paint and that McNaughton's restless
camera would just sit still and watch him.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CONDO PAINTING' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John McNaughton; written by George Condo and
McNaughton; director of photography, McNaughton; edited by Elena
Maganini and Tom Keefe; music by Jim Sampas; produced by Dana
Giacchetto; released by USA Films/October Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: George Condo, William S. Burroughs, Allen Ginsberg, John
Sampas, Anna Condo, Bernard Picasso and Patrick Achdjian.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
