<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COOPER-DESIGN-ART-2TA     03-09 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOPER-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEAZAPOPPIN': IMAGES FLY AT COOPER-HEWITT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2 and 3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is it too much to expect the National Design Museum
to show a little design now and then? Finally Cooper-Hewitt has
taken the plunge. With the first edition of its National Design
Triennial the museum brings us real, living design. Not the history
of design; not the sociology, anthropology, psychology, theory,
politics or economics of design. Not Good Design, Green Design or
Universal Design. Just Design, the whole field of American Design
and nothing but Design.
</P>
<P>
   The first in a series of survey exhibitions to be held every
three years, it offers a bracing dunk in the present. Encompassing
graphics, fashion, industrial products, architecture, interiors,
furniture, toys, stage and movie sets, and computer animation, the
show is not a Best of the Best contest. Projects by 83 designers
and firms, all produced in the last three years, are not grouped by
disciplines. Viewers may pick their own winners and losers. We
expect survey shows to be irritating, and this one does not
disappoint. Too often the ideas lose focus. There are vexing
omissions and far-fetched connections. Still, this show makes
design look like the most protean, fertile field this side of the
Tigris and Euphrates.
</P>
<P>
   It has been organized by Donald Albrecht and Ellen Lupton, two
curators on Cooper-Hewitt's staff, along with Steven Skov Holt, a
seasoned Silicon Valley denizen. Their synergy is infectious. They
have taken what might be called the Josephine Baker approach to the
bountiful subject. In concert performances Baker would toss
peaches, apples, papayas and other fruits into the audience. At
Cooper-Hewitt the curators pelt us with ideas. Color, light, form,
image, movement, materials and technologies land in seemingly
random arrangements of contemporary American style.
</P>
<P>
   The Triennial is organized around eight themes, from Fluid to
Unbelievable, with stops at Physical, Minimal, Reclaimed, Local,
Branded and Narrative along the way. The logic behind these motifs
is more intuitive than analytic. This is not to say that the
curators lack discrimination. Their approach reflects the mercurial
state of design today.
</P>
<P>
   Fluid, the introductory theme, states the show's overarching
message: dead or alive, natural or cultural, all things must morph.
The section also documents a particular current circulating through
architecture and design today. Greg Lynn's ``Hydrogen House,''
created in 1996 for the Austrian Mineral Oil Co., exemplifies the
movement toward ``blob'' architecture created with animation
software. Frank O. Gehry's unbuilt project for 1 Times Square
deploys folding fabric as an innovative building skin. The impact
of both projects is rooted in the shifting, mutable nature of
contemporary visual culture.
</P>
<P>
   A second-floor gallery devoted to Branded design embraces
without condescension Martha Stewart's antiseptically earthy
gardening products. Seed packets and a remarkable poison-free bug
killer are used to symbolize the power exercised by labels, logos
and slogans in the world of mass consumption. But why include
Stewart and not Ralph Lauren? Why ask why? We love Martha and we
don't like Ralph. Go figure. Just do it. Whoosh.
</P>
<P>
   The eight themes are themselves brands, meta-labels for objects
whose existence hangs on their reception in the consumer
marketplace. Although handbags by Kate Spade and a dress by
Geoffrey Beene are displayed in a Minimal gallery, Spade and Beene
are also outstanding brand names. So are Apple and, at this point,
even Frank O. Gehry. Less established designers, like Stefan
Sagmeister, shown in a photograph with his name carved into his
naked torso, are labels in the making. Doesn't everyone want to be
a trademark? Isn't that what's driving the explosion of all those
FillInYourName.coms?
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors will be impressed by the commercial aspect of this
show. Some of the objects can actually be purchased at the
Cooper-Hewitt gift shop. Others are available at fine stores
everywhere, or online. Many of the objects have graced the covers
and articles of that excellent trade magazine ID. An architect
whose work is represented in the show told me that his first
response on seeing it was to look around for a shopping cart. In
short, it offers a field day for those who can't wait for another
chance to whine about the breakdown of the cordon sanitaire between
museum and marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of museum design departments, however, such a
boundary never existed. Since the 1930s the explicit purpose of
design departments like that at the Museum of Modern Art was to
encourage a rapprochement between art and industry. This had been
the Bauhaus ideal. The Modern extended the ideal from production to
consumption. The museum didn't design products. Instead it rewarded
manufacturers for producing objects that Philip Johnson and
subsequent curators found aesthetically pleasing. They Branded
stuff with the Good Design label.
</P>
<P>
   In the Good Design period, Branded and Minimal shared a similar,
machine-based aesthetic. Today the two are complementary opposites.
The Brand catapults more stuff into the world. Minimal design
creates the illusion that stuff can be kept at bay. Michael
Gambelli, who designed the Triennial, is an excellent illusionist.
Using a Minimal palette of gray homisote panels, clear plexiglass
containers, white fabric and empty space, he has kept the show from
turning into Times Square. Gambelli has also achieved the
remarkable feat of keeping the ornate interiors of Andrew
Carnegie's mansion from undermining the entire idea of design.
</P>
<P>
   Reclaimed, another Triennial theme, is the offspring of Branded
and Minimal. Since stuff never really goes away, it might as well
be made use of. Reclaimed is design's trash compactor. It shows
what to do when Branded objects lose their value or aura. Don't
throw away those webbed plastic straps that came wrapped around
that shipment of clingy Diane von Furstenberg traveling pants
suits. Make your own version of Constantin and Lorene Leon Boym's
version of Breuer's Wassily chair! Breuer's aesthetic was based on
industrial production. The Boym sensibility derives from the
landfill end of the consumer system.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Images and ideas can be reclaimed along with physical castoffs.
Peter Girardi, a retired graffiti writer based in Manhattan,
collects old typefaces, printer's marks, candy wrappers and other
signifiers cut loose from their signifieds. Then he posts them on a
Web site: www.funnygarbage.com, a semiotic town dump. In contrast
to the crisp, clean look of most computer graphics, Girardi and his
associate, Chris Capuozzo, want Web pages to look like old
newspapers blowing around the alley. Funny Garbage is working on
``Pink Donkey and the Fly,'' a cartoon show on cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bargmann's ``Testing the Waters'' is the most ambitious
project in the Reclaimed section, and one of the best in the
Triennial. A 45-acre park now under construction in Vintondale,
Pa., it is reclaiming land polluted by the drainage from a former
coal mine. To produce the design Bargmann, a landscape architect,
recruited a historian, a hydrogeologist and a visual artist. They
have produced what the curators call ``a giant ecological washing
machine'' that invites visitors to witness basins, spillways and
other stages in the water-cleansing process.
</P>
<P>
   The themes slither through one another like a series of spinoffs
and mergers. ``Testing the Waters'' would fit just as well or
better in the section called Local, dedicated to our archaic
attachment to place. The Local highlight is a remarkable house
designed by Marwan Al-Sayed for a couple in Phoenix. Formerly
employed by the New York architects Tod Williams and Billie Tsien
(who are handsomely represented in the Physical part of the show),
Al-Sayed uses thick masonry walls, metal trusses, tent fabric and
the desert surroundings in a design that recalls Frank Lloyd
Wright's Taliesin West.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture in general is sketchily handled. The selections are
choice but misleadingly labeled. Given the earnestness with which
Steven Holl pursues architecture's metaphysical dimension, it is
painfully obtuse to classify his MIT dormitory under Physical. Nor
is Neil Denari's work all that Fluid. Scary is more like it. With a
vocabulary derived from space age technology, his designs tend
toward the hard-edged. Beautifully conceived, Denari's projects are
beginning to look like Cold War antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gluckman and Robert Wilson's project for the Pittsburgh
Cultural Trust is filed under Minimal but is also a good example of
Reclaimed, or even Branded. The design drapes backlighted,
translucent theatrical scrims over the side walls of old industrial
buildings that are being recycled into Pittsburgh's new arts
district. A form of subliminal advertising, devoid of words or
images, the design is a refreshing antidote to the cloying,
scenographic buildings of Michael Graves and Charles Moore.
</P>
<P>
   If Walter Pater were alive today, he might well conclude that
all art aspires to the condition of movie titles. Examples of the
genre, created by the Hollywood company Imaginary Forces, are found
in the Physical galleries, and it is true that these haunting,
hilarious and brilliant montages provoke a visceral response.
Created for ``Seven,'' ``Mimic'' and ``Dead Man on Campus,'' these
short films should come with a warning attached: please don't
reveal the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The show's final two segments are utterly misnamed. Most of the
work displayed under the Narrative rubric is actually
illustrational. Projects by David Rockwell, Julie Taymor, Gary
Lloyd and David Gallo are fine examples of scenographic art, but
there is nothing narrative about them. Narration, in architecture
and design, refers to a spatial or visual sequence that duplicates
the formal structure of storytelling. That structure, analyzed by
Russian linguists in the early 20th century, proceeds from an
initial state of equilibrium through a series of unbalancing
episodes to a final, heightened state of equipoise. (Think of
rising, by stages, to the top of the Eiffel Tower.)
</P>
<P>
   Lebbeus Woods' project is the only one in the section that
follows a true narrative structure. Titled ``Civilization,'' it is
part of an exhibition that is to open in Berlin in May.
Intentionally or not, the design recreates in architectural form
the world according to Richard Rorty, author of the influential
1989 book ``Contingency, Irony and Solidarity.'' Rorty, our most
enlightened contemporary philosopher, has reflected on ways of
adapting to rapid cultural change. Woods, whose previous work
includes visionary studies of war-torn Sarajevo, has created a
dystopic environment of sharp, fragmented shapes that will serve as
an installation for a show on fantasies of 21st-century life.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable, the show's final section, would be more accurately
titled Next. Given the objects already seen, it is all too easy to
believe that the projects gathered here, or variants of them, will
soon be on the market. David Small's ``Talmud Project'' is a work
of genius. A prototype for an interactive book, produced at the MIT
Media Lab, the project may be the Triennial's most powerful piece
of architecture. Combining passages from the Torah and the Talmud,
in English and French translations, the software enables viewers to
manipulate blocks of text into the walls, streets and windows in an
imaginary city of words.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that is truly Unbelievable at Cooper-Hewitt
(apart from Martha Stewart's poison-free bug killer) is the entire
exhibition. In recent years New Yorkers have come to depend on
Moss, the SoHo store, for close-up inspections of new design. This
routine reversed the standard protocol in Good Design days, when a
museum display of well-designed objects preceded by some years the
establishment of retail outlets where consumers could buy them. It
is refreshing to see commercial and curatorial intelligence brought
into closer alignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Triennial was conceived a few years ago by Dianne H.
Pilgrim, who stepped down as the director of Cooper-Hewitt in
January. What a great parting gift.
</P>
<P>
   The National Design Triennial remains at the Cooper-Hewitt
Museum, 2 East 91st Street, Manhattan, (212) 849-8400, through Aug.
6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-CLOTHES-COX     03-09 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-CLOTHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a short time after two men were stabbed to
death in a brawl and Ray Lewis was composing himself in his room at
a posh hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and his companions saw an early morning TV broadcast
saying that two men were dead near a Buckhead nightclub. The
initial report was that it was a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were relieved _ it wasn't them,'' said Atlanta attorney
Akil Secret, recounting what his client, Jessica Robertson, has
told prosecutors. But then the broadcast mentioned a stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robertson, who was in the room, Lewis turned to one
of the co-defendants and asked, ``You didn't stab anyone, did
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, a Lewis acquaintance who last week was given immunity
from prosecution, on Saturday turned over to investigators nine
garment bags, a carry-on bag, a plaque and a sweatshirt belonging
to Lewis. Two of the garment bags contained fur coats, including
the dark-colored mink and dark gray suit Lewis wore that night.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are expected to test the clothing for any blood
stains.
</P>
<P>
   Secret said he did not see any blood on the clothing during a
cursory look before turning the garments over to authorities. But
he said he would not be surprised if the blood tests were positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the evidence is going to be that the coat fell off
onto the floor'' of the limousine Lewis and his party were riding
in, Secret said. ``If there was as much blood in the limo (as
authorities have said) then it would be odd if there was no blood
on the coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's blood on the coat, I don't think that implicates
anybody; that is a fact that could have many interpretations,''
Secret added. ``You have people scurrying into the vehicle after a
melee. There's bound to be contact, person to person, person to
car, clothes to clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and two friends, Joseph Sweeting, and Reginald Oakley,
have been charged with the murder of Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard
Lollar, 24, both of Decatur, Ga. The men died after they and others
were involved in a brawl with members of Lewis' party on a Buckhead
street near the Cobalt lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and about 10 others fled the Buckhead scene in a
37-foot-long Lincoln Navigator that was hit by five shots as it
sped away, authorities had said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure pandemonium'' inside the limo, Secret said,
describing the scene. ``They were screaming at (driver) Duane
Fassett to `Drive! Drive!' It seemed like he froze.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis met Robertson, a Houston woman in her 20s, the Wednesday
before the Super Bowl and accompanied him to parties thrown by
Magic Johnson and Atlanta music producer Jermaine Dupri, Secret
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since she has come forward, authorities now have the names of
several more passengers in the limousine. Robertson has told
prosecutors that Lewis and his companions were encountered by the
victims and overhead statements that led them to believe they were
about to be robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Secret said Robertson was not hiding the clothes from
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not take that to hide them,'' he said. ``She thought
there was nothing sinister involved. There was nothing like that
said.''
</P>
<P>
   Secret said Lewis's original plan was to have his limo driver
bring his cache of clothes back to his Maryland home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never intended to take them to Hawaii'' where Lewis was to
play the following week in the Pro Bowl, Secret said. ``He was
going to travel light to Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   But the limo was incapacitated because of the gunshots and Lewis
called Robertson on her cell phone as she was driving away from the
hotel. ``She got a call, it was Ray asking her if she didn't mind
taking his clothes until he got back,'' said Secret.
</P>
<P>
   Secret said that Robertson placed the clothes in a storage
locker here in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a very good reason why she chose, on her own, to put
those clothes in the storage bin,'' Secret said, declining to
elaborate. ``Ray Lewis had nothing to do with her decision to do
that. Nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the next few days, Robertson became aware that
Atlanta Police considered the clothes Lewis wore that night to be
evidence. ``The D.A.'s office began to infect the atmosphere that
the clothes were hidden because of some sinister purpose,'' Secret
said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned, Robertson went back and took a look at the clothes,
the lawyer said. ``She noticed no blood stains at all.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard would not comment on Robertson's
statements or anything regarding the case, citing the court-imposed
gag order.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
