<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ORPHANS-FILM-REVIEW-N     03-09 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORPHANS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ORPHANS': MOM'S DEAD, BUT HER BROOD ISN'T A WHOLE LOT BETTER OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Orphans'' was shown as part of last year's New Directors/New
Films series. Following are excerpts from Stephen Holden's review,
which appeared in The New York Times on April 2. The film opens
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The milk of human kindness hasn't merely soured in Peter
Mullan's transcendently nasty but very funny comedy, ``Orphans.''
It has so poisoned the air of Glasgow that its clammy atmosphere
seems charged with petty malice.
</P>
<P>
   The story of three brothers and a sister, each of whom goes
grotesquely haywire after the death of their beloved mother, the
film gleefully rubs our noses in comic misanthropy that makes
American movies like ``The Ref'' and ``Very Bad Things'' seem
almost like rays of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   The directorial debut of Mullan, who won acclaim for his
portrayal of a recovering alcoholic in Ken Loach's film ``My Name
Is Joe,'' ``Orphans'' takes especially wicked delight in
contrasting the survivors' mawkish displays of grief over the death
of their dear old mum with their mean, spiteful attitudes toward
everyone outside the family.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins innocently enough as the four Flynn siblings _
Thomas (Gary Lewis), Michael (Douglas Henshall), Sheila (Rosemarie
Stevenson) and John (Stephen McCole) _ mourn at the coffin of their
recently deceased mother, who in flashback is shown comforting her
wee ones during a scary thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner have they kissed her goodbye and deposited keepsakes
beside her body than they repair to a local pub where Thomas
lurches onto the stage to sing his mother's favorite song, ``The
Air That I Breathe.'' To the vast amusement of the onlookers,
Thomas collapses midsong into a blubbering heap.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Michael promptly gets into a brawl with Duncan
(Malcolm Shields), one of the jeering patrons, and finds himself
stabbed in the abdomen. Bleeding profusely, he rushes outside the
bar, where he runs into John and tells him what happened. John goes
ballistic, vowing to kill Duncan. He recruits his embittered cousin
Tanga (who delivers Chinese food) as an ally, and the pair spend
the rest of the movie cruising around Glasgow in Tanga's truck with
a sawed-off shotgun looking for Duncan and along the way nearly
raping and killing two of Tanga's takeout customers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Michael decides not to seek treatment for his wound.
Instead he plans to go to work early the next morning and pretend
he was injured in an industrial accident and sue for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The Flynns' sister is no day at the beach either. Impatient to
leave the church where Thomas insists on remaining overnight with
their mother's coffin, Sheila, who is mentally and physically
disabled and confined to a wheelchair, leaves the premises and has
a series of misadventures after her vehicle gets stuck in a rut.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila is the kind of person who is so wound up with rage that
she often doesn't deign to reply when other people address her. In
Stevenson's portrayal, she emerges a grumpy little beast dispensing
hostility and malice at every turn. As if the atmosphere weren't
already tempestuous enough, a violent storm erupts, causing power
failures around the city.
</P>
<P>
   As the Flynn siblings survive one mishap after another, the
movie settles into being an uproarious knockabout farce larded with
the kind of gross-out jokes you would expect to find in a Farrelly
Brothers comedy. But instead of having a prankish adolescent joie
de vivre, these bits have a meaner Swiftian edge.
</P>
<P>
   The awful things people say and do to one another don't emanate
from an impulse to make mischief so much as from a deep-seated
anger and frustration. When the characters lash out, they hope to
inflict permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   Like most satires whose point is to remind us that beneath our
civilized surfaces we're no better than beasts, ``Orphans'' doesn't
really know where to carry its misanthropy. After ridiculing the
Flynn siblings' sentimentality, the movie ends up feeling sorry for
them as they finally gather, much the worse for wear, for their
mother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The only way a movie like this can finally shoot the moon is
have the world come to an end in one final self-destructive spasm.
But that was already done in ``Dr. Strangelove.'' At the end of
``Orphans,'' life creeps on. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
