<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      03-09 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MODEL BEHAVIOR': TIRED PLOT, LOTS OF GUEST-STARS  
 `CAITLIN'S WAY': NEW SERIES ABOUT AN UNHAPPY TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of reviews. Time and station are
for New York area; check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alex Burrows has a terrible life. She's 16, shy, insecure and
dateless. At a party, when she tries to talk to the boy she has a
crush on, she just humiliates herself. And home is no better. Her
little brother is a tattletale, and her father forces her to put on
a chef's hat and coat and work on weekends for his catering
company. Honestly, she might as well be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in her bedroom, flipping through a magazine, she sees
pictures of Janine Adams, a teen-age supermodel, and wonders why
she can't have a glamorous life like Janine's. Fashion shoots!
Trips to Paris! Partying with the stars! Well, she's going to get
her chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Model Behavior,'' Sunday night's ``Wonderful World of Disney''
movie, is the story of how Alex and Janine _ who happen to look
exactly alike when Alex takes off her glasses and lets her
tied-back hair loose _ decide to trade places for a week. It's a
grass-is-greener ``Prince and the Pauper'' plot, played as teen-age
tragicomedy, with guest stars of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   For young viewers there's Justin Timberlake, a member of the pop
group 'N Sync, as another famous model. For the grownups there's
Kathie Lee Gifford, already practicing for life after Regis Philbin
(she announced recently that she was leaving their morning talk
show this year), as Janine's pushy stage mother. Gifford's
9-year-old son, Cody, has a small role in the film, too, as
Janine's ambitious little brother, off to Aruba for his first
modeling job. Vendela, the model, also has a cameo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Model Behavior'' has its small charms (it's great fun when
Janine talks back to Alex's teacher) and is sure to be watched by
its young target audience, but it's riddled with unimaginative,
trite elements that smell suspiciously of an ``oh, heck, it's good
enough for kids, they won't know any better'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   When Janine and Alex (both played by Maggie Lawson) meet,
bumping into each other at a book-signing party for Janine's new
memoir, naturally Alex is carrying a tray full of canapes. And
although the tray hits Janine directly in the face, her hair,
makeup and valuable facial features emerge miraculously undamaged.
There should at least have been traces of a cheese ball sticking to
her nose. When Alex, pretending to be Janine, takes her nervous
personal assistant, Monique, skating, the scene naturally ends with
Monique falling down.
</P>
<P>
   The film even does the old person-mistaking-lookalike-for-mirror
act (which was done much better by Lucille Ball and Harpo Marx and,
in a recent variation, by David Duchovny in an episode of ``The
X-Files''). Mark Rosman, the director, calls this version ``a very
fun scene.'' But the premise doesn't even make sense in this
instance, since one of the two people has to be intentionally
mimicking the other's movements and expressions. Not the case here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Model Behavior'' ignores that, just as it has neither Alex nor
Janine make any real effort to pretend to know her lookalike's
friends and family. Once in a while, luckily, that works, as when
Janine takes one look at Alex's little brother, Josh, and says,
``Are we related?'' Josh takes the comment as sarcasm and replies,
``Only genetically.''
</P>
<P>
   The film does make Janine's desire to trade places with Alex
believable, too. She's absolutely ready to give up 5 a.m. workouts
and business parties with people 20 years her senior, and she's
dying to order out for pizza and Chinese food, even if it means she
gains a pound or two.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Clark, who plays Josh, is a standout. So is Karen Hines,
who plays the eager-to-please Monique. Gifford's work is uneven,
but she doesn't have much depth of character to work with. As
Janine's mother, she has lines like ``When I was a model, we did
everything our handlers told us to,'' and ``Have you been pigging
out on peanut butter cups again?''
</P>
<P>
   The truth comes out at the Greenfield High Fall Ball, with
appropriate statements by characters who have learned lessons from
the experience. Gifford's character, for instance, is going to
respect Janine's need to be just a regular teen-ager now and then.
And everyone finds true love or at least a dancing partner, even
Cody.
</P>
<P>
   WONDERFUL WORLD OF DISNEY
</P>
<P>
   `Model Behavior'
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at 7 p.m. on ABC (Channel 7 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by David Kukoff and Matt Roshkow; based on the book
``Janine and Alex, Alex and Janine,'' by Michael Levin. Mark
Rosman, director; Ronald E. Frazier, producer; Alistair MacRae,
production designer; Laszlo George, director of photography; music
by Eric Colvin; edited by Bonnie Koehler. A Karz Entertainment Inc.
production in association with Walt Disney Television. Mike Karz,
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Maggie Lawson (Alex and Janine), Kathie Lee Gifford
(Deirdre), Justin Timberlake (Jason Sharp), Cody Gifford (Max), Jim
Abele (Ted), Daniel Clark (Josh), Karen Hines (Monique), Jesse
Nilsson (Eric) and Vendela (herself).
</P>
<P>
   Go West, Young Woman
</P>
<P>
   Yet another unhappy teen-age girl, Caitlin (Lindsay Felton), is
the heroine of Nickelodeon's new series ``Caitlin's Way.'' She's a
tough New York orphan who has run through six foster families in
two years. In Saturday night's hourlong preview episode, she learns
that her dead mother does have a living relative after all, a
cousin, and lucky Caitlin is going to live with her and her family.
In Montana. Oh no, says the worldly, obviously sensitive Caitlin,
``those people are weird out in the sticks.'' The show, which seems
false and awkward in the city, seems more at home out West.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin, whose defense mechanism is taking photographs of
anything that disturbs her, soon learns that out in ``the sticks''
there are killer wolves and rustlers. And that this new family
(``the cop, the vet and the geek _ I guess things could be worse'')
may stick with her. In the show's first regular half-hour on
Sunday, the vet-cousin (Cynthia Belliveau) decides it's time to
tame Bandit, who is beautiful as a wild horse but has to learn the
rules with his new family. Nice metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `CAITLIN'S WAY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at 9 p.m. ET on Nickelodeon
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1813EST &QL; 
