<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT &LR;      03-09 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAILLEBOTTE AT   CHRISTIE'S; SOTHEBY'S DECIDES AGAINST   TWO
EVENING SALES; A MUSEUM OF CONTEMPORARY ART   IN TOKYO ; WHITNEY
ESTABLISHES AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: France, Britain, Calif., Iowa, Ill.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All the negative news about Sotheby's and Christie's
since the federal antitrust investigation heated up last month has
left the art world wondering what these auction house giants will
have to sell at their important spring sales in New York in May. So
Christie's was eager to send out the word that one of the stars of
its sale of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist works on May 8 _
and the cover art for the sale catalog _ will be what it calls the
most important Caillebotte ever to come on the auction market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Balcony, Boulevard Haussmann,'' painted in 1880,
depicts the back of a man who experts think was the the artist's
lawyer, Albert Courtier, looking out at the boulevard from the
balcony of Caillebotte's Paris apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Impressionist painters, much of the work has to
do with light and shadow. A sun-dappled cityscape is angled in the
distance, while the intricately painted ironwork in the foreground
separates inside from out. The work centers on the figure of the
man, who is shaded by a red-and-white awning.
</P>
<P>
   Caillebotte had moved into his sixth-floor apartment just a year
before he painted ``Man on the Balcony'' and was fascinated with
the architectural views of Paris, especially the new buildings he
could see from his vantage. ``The perspective and the composition
are particularly modern,'' said Franck Giraud, who heads Christie's
19th- and 20th-century art department. ``The way the view is set at
a diagonal looking west over Paris was quite radical for its
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Caillebotte gave the painting to Courtier. After the lawyer's
death in the early years of the century his estate sold it to a
Jean Metthey, a Paris dealer, then put it up at auction in Paris in
1946. It was bought by George Courturat, another Parisian
collector, and has been in the Courturat family ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``My colleague in Geneva Thomas Seydoux knew the owners and had
been talking with them about selling the painting for years,'' said
Giraud, who added that their decision to sell this spring had to do
with both the strength of the market and a desire to begin some
estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, expected to sell for $6 million to $8 million, has
been exhibited in several major shows, most recently ``Gustave
Caillebotte: Urban Impressionist,'' which opened at the Grand
Palais in Paris in 1994 and then traveled to the Art Institute of
Chicago and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ART NOW? NOT NOW
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has abandoned its plans to hold a second evening sale
of contemporary art in May. After the November sales it announced
it was initiating ``Contemporary Art Now,'' an auction devoted to
art from the last 20 years, purposely to keep up with with
Christie's, whose contemporary-art auctions cover 1970 to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``When talking to clients, I could feel the resistance to having
a third evening contemporary-art sale,'' said Tobias Meyer,
director of contemporary art for Sotheby's worldwide. ``We had the
material and could have pulled it off. But at this moment I'd
prefer to have one really energetic sale.'' Meyer said, however,
that he still wanted ``to keep the door open'' such an auction in
the future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IN A TOKYO TOWER
</P>
<P>
   Minoru Mori, president and chief executive of the Mori Building
Co., the largest developer in Japan, is planning a museum devoted
to 20th- and 21st-century art, architecture and design. The Mori
Art Center will be a Kunsthalle, a museum without its own
collection. It will be part of a $2.5 billion complex, the largest
private urban redevelopment in Japan, with residential towers,
movie complexes, restaurants and shops. It is to open in early 2003
in the Roppongi district of central Tokyo, on the 51st to 54th
floors of an office building with an observation deck providing
panoramic views of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese public still loves Impressionist rather than
contemporary art,'' Mori said. ``I wanted to help make the public
more aware of newer art.''
</P>
<P>
   Mori, a member of the Museum of Modern Art's International
Council, has asked the Modern to serve as the museum's cultural
partner and artistic adviser. ``We have an arrangement to give the
museum guidance, to help them build a first-class institution,''
said Glenn D. Lowry, director of the Modern. ``We will also
periodically make available to them exhibitions.'' The new museum
will pay the same fees the Modern charges as for any traveling
exhibition, Lowery said, and is paying it a consulting fee.
</P>
<P>
   The Mori Art Center has also established a collaborative
arrangement with the Royal Academy of Art in London.
</P>
<P>
   A WHITNEY AWARD
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough that the Tate Gallery in London, the Solomon R.
Guggenheim Museum and the Cooper-Hewitt in New York, and the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art all have their own awards programs;
now the Whitney Museum of Art is getting into the act. It plans to
give a $100,000 prize every two years to an emerging artist living
and working in the United States. The winner will be chosen from
the artists included in the Whitney's Biennial exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Named the Bucksbaum Award, it has been established by the
Bucksbaum Family Foundation of Des Moines, Iowa, run by Melva
Bucksbaum, a Whitney trustee since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some months now we had been thinking of launching an
artist-in-residence program as a way of championing emerging
artists,'' said Maxwell L. Anderson, director of the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Each winner will spend two years participating in the museum's
graduate and independent study programs as well as public events,
like lectures and symposiums. At some point during the residency
the artist's work will be on view as part of the museum's
continuing contemporary-art series.
</P>
<P>
   The first winner is to be chosen in April by a jury of five arts
professionals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
