<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-RARE-RADIOS-2TAKES-HN     03-09 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RARE-RADIOS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUND COLLECTION: TEXAN'S MACHINES REVEAL THE REVOLUTION OF
ELECTRONICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: N.J., N.Y.) 
(Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By MARTY RACINE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYTOWN, Texas _ Bob Botto shows off a remarkable piece of
technology in his dining room. It's encased in rich wood grain, and
the ``top works,'' or hardware, are exquisitely crafted.
</P>
<P>
   This item is so revolutionary it reproduces sound without
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   It is an 1892 Edison Class M business phonograph.
</P>
<P>
   We tend to attribute the Information Age to computer technology.
But, as Botto's Houston-area home reveals, the electronic continuum
dates to the 1800s, when inventors, many of them immigrants,
advanced the means of communication and defined the American
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Botto, an analytical chemist for Exxon, and his wife, Kathy, who
runs the couple's antique radio and record player shop, own more
than quaint, fanciful machines. These are artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Edison invented the Class M phonograph in 1888 as a
recording and playback device for office dictations; phonographs
for home entertainment weren't produced until a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The machine was battery-powered, with sound imprinted on a wax
cylinder that fit onto a spindle, or mandrel. It's a classic, Botto
says. ``One of these comes along in a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought it from a Dallas collector who called one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is one you really want, it's missing
(parts),'' the collector told him. ``But, oh, let's see, I'm paying
$1,200 for it, I'll let you have it for $2,400.''
</P>
<P>
   Botto went up immediately and claimed it. Moments later another
collector called, offering $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   He rebuilt the motor and top works, and found an original
bichromate battery _ ``so rare, it's the only one I've ever seen''
_ for $700. A wood expert restored the housing.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase included a box of cylinders that rank among the
first commercial recordings. Produced by the Chicago Talking
Machine Co., one was a march conducted by John Phillip Souza,
recorded in 1892.
</P>
<P>
   Botto regards the cylinder with awe: ``It's very, very
precious.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`HERE IT IS, AN EDISON PHONOGRAPH' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Botto, 50, grew up in Buffalo, N.Y., as a curious sort. He was
fascinated with electricity and magnetism, loved museums, and
collected rocks and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   While in college, he met Kathy, a high school junior, on a bus
transporting their respective church youth groups to Syracuse. Bob
happened to have one of his inventions, ``light solution.'' Add
water and it emits light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carried it around in a little bottle. You never know when
you might need it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a chemist. He lived in the basement. He didn't think
about women. But he mustered the courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you like to see my light solution?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Kathy enrolled at the State University of New
York-Buffalo in history, Bob was at Cornell in Ithaca working on
his Ph.D. in geochemistry. But the long-distance relationship
blossomed. They married during their respective final years in
school, and in 1975 Bob was hired at Exxon's chemical plant in
Baytown, a city of 68,000 people about 15 miles east of downtown
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Bob had no apparent interest in vintage communications
equipment. But in 1983 he was driving home from a chemical
conference in Waco when he stopped to rest in Hiedenhiemer. There
was a junk shop across the street.
</P>
<P>
   As he perused old telephones and such, the white-haired
shopkeeper spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come here, I've got just what you need.''
</P>
<P>
   From beneath the counter he produced a wooden box filled with
rusted parts and spiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it is, an Edison phonograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Botto saw only rusty parts and spiders. But he was intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   The man wanted $25; Botto had $19.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, you take it and send me a check.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A STORE IS BORN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was an 1899 Edison. Botto began assembling it. The
trial-and-error process, he figured, was not dissimilar to that of
inventing.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later he had it playing. Botto was enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I'd play this machine for everybody who
walked in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he wanted more. He hunted specimens that today are
``virtually nonexistent,'' or ``so historic you would never see
one.''
</P>
<P>
   To Kathy they were contraptions cluttering the house. But she
grew fond of antique radios. She began collecting and restoring,
and joined the Houston Vintage Radio Club.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1985, Bob and Kathy recognized the inevitable: All
our stuff will keep increasing, then we'll need to get rid of some
because we'll find better stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: a store. Kathy runs Vintage Sounds in northwest
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider her a technological historian,'' Bob says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
A LITTLE HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Edison, born in 1849, is The Man. Fascinated with science
and nature, he devised things that helped people, Botto says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had knowledge of what people wanted. And he had a powerful
ability to get people working on something and make it improved.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest invention was neither the phonograph nor the light
bulb. It was the research laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were scientific laboratories in universities, but none
produced inventions except by accident. Edison was the first to put
together an industrial research laboratory and say we're going to
invent, manufacture and market things all out of this laboratory.''
</P>
<P>
   Edison invented the tinfoil phonograph in 1878. By the 1890s his
Standard, more portable than the Class M, was a home fixture.
Spring-powered for uniformity of speed, it was equipped with
octopuslike listening tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Others copied the Edison model. Columbia boasted of its 1895
graphophone, ``It talks, laughs, plays and sings. Strictly
high-class entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   The graphophone and Edison's phonograph reproduced sound waves
incised vertically onto the cylinder. Simultaneously, German
immigrant Emile Berliner in Philadelphia invented the gramophone,
with sound incised laterally onto a disc, or ``plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The hand-cranked gramophone didn't compete with the Edison until
1896 when Eldridge R. Johnson of nearby Camden, N.J., produced
Berliner's first spring-powered unit. The phonograph became popular
when Johnson in 1900 produced a plate from a wax master (rather
than a crude zinc disc). And when the Victor Talking Machine Co.
developed superior electric-process plates, Edison's cylinder
phonograph was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   By whatever format, talking machines disseminated popular
culture at the dawn of mass marketing. A recording comedian known
as Uncle Josh cut an episode in 1910 titled ``Uncle Josh Buys an
Automobile.'' It begins:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I've done it, yes sir, Nancy nagged at me until I bought
an automobile. Nancy said the Willets had one and the Weavers had
one and here we were riding around in a buckboard behind a
bone-rattling horse that was blind on the offside. I hadn't been
a-hankerin' for that gasoline wagon, but in order to keep peace in
the family I sold four head of cattle, some hogs, 10 ton of hay and
put a mortgage on the farm and bought an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all Pumpkin Center turned out to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1917 Victor released a radical new music called the Jass One
Step by the Dixieland Jass Band. Botto owns this, the very first
jazz recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody heard anything but ballads, marches, sacred music and
classical,'' Botto says. ``Columbia first recorded the song, then
passed on releasing it. So (the band) went to Victor, which had a
little more snap. They said, hey, maybe some people might like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
A PAIR OF MUSEUMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Bottos' two daughters left home, their upstairs
bedrooms morphed into museums, one for Kathy's radios, the other
for Bob's newest passion, communications.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Wireless Room. Illuminated by an 1890s Edison
bulb, it features oddities like the magneto electric machine.
Invented in 1854, it produced a magnetic current for therapeutic
purposes. But by harnessing the relationship between magnetism and
electricity, it presaged the concept of radio.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the first telegraph, or sounder, invented by Samuel Morse
in 1860 and manufactured by Charles L. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In 1875 Williams leased his Boston workshop to a fellow named
Alexander Graham Bell, who with Williams' technician, Thomas
Watson, invented the telephone. It became practical when Edison
invented the carbon button transmitter in 1877.
</P>
<P>
   The country would soon be strung with telephone and telegraph
lines. Cities would choke on them. What if, some mused, we could
communicate without wires?
</P>
<P>
   In 1890, Edouard Branley formed a circuit, or coherence, between
two electrodes hooked to a battery and relay. He called his device
the coherer.
</P>
<P>
   Botto's 1897 coherer looks like a primitive bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the very, very first device to receive radio
transmission. Believe me, there's not many of these around.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian-born Guglielmo Marconi applied the coherer to
communications. He was more visionary than inventor, Botto says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put the idea in front of people so they could understand
what you can do with (an invention). Before him, it was just a
laboratory curiosity.``
</P>
<P>
   Marconi developed ship-to-shore communication, and in 1901 he
transmitted Morse code across the Atlantic. After the sinking of
the Titanic, all ships at sea were required to have a wireless
operator aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The first wireless voice transmission was in 1906, but voice
wasn't feasible until Lee DeForest, the ``father of modern radio,''
invented an electron tube that amplified signals.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural radio broadcast was in 1920 over Pittsburgh
station KDKA. A year later Westinghouse produced a crystal receiver
that required no headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Now technology followed you anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
