<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-KOHL-(TRIMS)-     03-09 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOHL-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL SAYS HE HAS RAISED FUNDS TO COVER FINES ON CDU 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Helmut Kohl, the former German chancellor, emerged from
weeks of seclusion Thursday to announce that generous friends and a
mortgage on his house had enabled him to raise enough money to
cover the financial damage suffered by the Christian Democratic
party as a result of his ``mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing alternately jocular and irascible, Kohl broke his
silence at a news conference where he brandished a list of 30
friends and admirers _ including actresses, film producers and
businessmen _ who he said had contributed to the raising of $2.95
million.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, who unified Germany a decade ago, has admitted accepting
just over $1 million in secret _ and thus illegal _ payments
between 1993 and 1998. His actions have exposed the party to fines
of $3.15 million and set off a crisis of the dominant political
force in postwar Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the $3.15 million, Kohl said, ``I will soon be in a
position to transfer the entire sum to the treasurer of the
Christian Democratic Union.'' He added, ``I made a mistake and I
want to try to repair the financial damage.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not financial damage that has principally hurt the
Christian Democrats. Rather, it has been the prolonged sight of the
once venerated Kohl defying the law by refusing to name the people
who secretly gave him money while he was in power.
</P>
<P>
   To see Europe's preeminent statesman of the last decade reduced
Thursday to revealing the amount of money raised by the mortgaging
of his house _ $250,000 _ was to appreciate the extraordinary
downward turn in Kohl's life over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   On the central issue of legality and trust, where Kohl has
maintained that his ``word of honor'' prevents him from revealing
the identities of donors to whom he guaranteed anonymity, there was
no sign of any shift Thursday. ``I have no intention of changing my
position,'' Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   While the Christian Democrats will certainly be relieved to
receive the promised financial assistance, they would be much
happier with a list of the donors between 1993 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Democratic Union welcomes every contribution
that will help us in our difficult financial situation,'' said
Wolfgang Schauble, Kohl's successor as party leader who himself
announced his resignation in February. ``But loss of trust requires
explanations that cannot be replaced with money alone.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although apparently schooled by his aides to appear humble and
contrite Thursday, Kohl, 69, bristled visibly when a journalist
asked if he was trying to buy an ``indulgence'' _ a remission for
past sins _ through his fund-raising drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with indulgences, nothing whatever,''
Kohl shot back. ``That is an absurd suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats, in opposition now after 16 years in
government under Kohl that ended in 1998, have forced the former
chancellor to resign as honorary chairman and canceled a lavish
70th-birthday celebration that had been planned for April. But they
have been unable to persuade him to talk openly.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kohl did produce one list Thursday _ that of the donors who he
said have helped him raise money in recent weeks. The single
largest contribution, he said, was made by Leo Kirch, a close
friend and the head of the Kirch media group, who gave $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other contributions were made by the British publisher, Lord
Weidenfeld, the president of Nestle, Helmut Maucher; the German
newspaper publisher, Erich Schumann; and the actress Uschi Glass.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kohl said the contributions, which cannot be claimed as tax
write-offs, were being collected in account number 1216175 of a
Commerzbank branch in Essen. He appealed to citizens of Germany and
the European Union to give freely.
</P>
<P>
   Among the donors were Kohl himself and his wife, Hannelore,
weighing in with $350,000, raised partly through the mortgaging of
their house in Ludwigshafen-Oggersheim and partly from the former
chancellor's savings.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl said he intended to restore his financial situation by
writing his memoirs and publishing them next year. It seemed
unlikely, however, that this promised book would shed any further
light on the identity of the donors because the former chancellor
appears to be convinced that he is morally bound to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks that everything he did was for the good of Germany
and so he does not have to bother with small details like the
law,'' said Christian von Westinghausen, a Berlin lawyer. ``This
was the performance of a king, a monarch late in his life who has
lost touch with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Christian Democrats have been fined $21 million for
the acceptance of various illegal contributions during Kohl's
chancellorship. Imposing the fine in February, Wolfgang Thierse,
the Social Democratic speaker of Parliament, said pointedly,
``There are no provisions in the law for words of honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats, who enjoyed a string of successes in
state and local elections last year as the government of Social
Democratic Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder floundered, have seen their
support plunge in recent months. The party lost in the state of
Schleswig-Holstein in February, but performed well enough to
suggest that it would not disintegrate as Italy's Christian
Democrats did in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party has every chance now to come out of its current
malaise,'' Kohl said, without spelling out his reasons for this
opinion. It is currently leaderless and will choose a replacement
for Schauble later in March.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hahne, a commentator on German television, suggested that
Kohl was mistaken. ``He portrayed this as a coup, a demonstration
of the wide support he has from people in the country,'' Hahne
said. ``But the fact is this drama may well prove unending for the
Christian Democrats as long as the names have not been revealed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OT-ABUSE10-COX     03-09 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OT-ABUSE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Increasing number of employees face more work but no overtime
pay
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Worley is seeing firsthand the pangs of a
hard-charging economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 2 1/2 years, the Atlanta attorney said he has filed
two dozen lawsuits _ twice his usual number _ from workers who say
they're not being adequately paid for working overtime. His list of
clients includes accountants, construction workers, parking lot
attendants, television industry technicians, office clerks,
security guards and health care workers.
</P>
<P>
   Working overtime has become the norm in the booming economy as
more companies pile more work on existing employees because they
can't find new ones to hire. Many workers aren't taking the extra
workload lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their employers are forcing them to work longer and longer
hours but failing to pay them the required overtime,'' said Worley,
whose own workload has increased as he works on behalf of
overworked workers.
</P>
<P>
   His latest case involves five CVS pharmacists in Georgia, four
of whom are in metro Atlanta, and whether they are exempt from
overtime provisions. The pharmacists allege they routinely worked
60 to 70 hours a week but weren't getting overtime. CVS disputes
the claim but declined to discuss the case in detail. Says CVS
spokesman Todd Andrews: ``We have examined the plaintiffs' case and
believe it has no merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such disputes likely will become more common as the economic
good times, tight labor market and low unemployment stretch on _
and continue to stretch workers thin.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the overtime issue arose as Congress is considering
a bill to raise the minimum wage. The provisions, tucked inside the
voluminous bill, ask that certain inside sales employees and
computer professionals be exempt from overtime requirements. Who is
entitled to overtime and who isn't is at the heart of legislation
dating from the 1930s. Today, roughly six in 10 American workers
are entitled to overtime under the law.
</P>
<P>
   It continues to be a source of frustration for workers and their
employers. A check of recent overtime violations shows the numbers
are on the rise. In fiscal year 1999, which ran from October 1998
through September 1999, the U.S. Department of Labor's Wage and
Hour division determined that some 100,000 U.S. workers were owed
about $62.3 million in overtime pay. So far in fiscal year 2000 _
just over five months _ about 75,000 workers are due $46.4 million
in overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violation rates seem to be climbing,'' says John McKeon,
Atlanta-based deputy regional administrator for the U.S. Department
of Labor's Wage and Hour division. ``The tight labor market makes
it harder for companies to attract workers and as a consequence
they may work their existing employees more hours and don't pay the
proper overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Wage and Hour Administrator Michael Kerr recently testified
before Congress that production and nonsupervisory workers were
logging more overtime than a decade ago: The average weekly
overtime hours in 1999 were 4.6 hours, compared with 3.8 hours in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Personnel Decision International found that
more than half the 600 full-time workers surveyed said their work
week has increased in the last five years, with the average work
week totalling close to 50 hours. Of those who were working more
hours, 44 percent said they were putting in more than 50 hours.
They attributed the increased time on the job to increased demands
from their company.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the overtime dispute is a set of federal laws
fashioned under President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal, which
among other things ushered in the 40-hour work week and promised to
make life easier for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Labor Standards Act, established in 1938, governs
record-keeping, wage and hour, child labor and overtime. It
essentially says exempt workers _ those who aren't managers or
professionals performing certain highly skilled tasks _ should be
paid overtime (usually time and a half) for working beyond 40 hours
a week. The law has been amended and grown more complicated over
time.
</P>
<P>
   The debate illustrates how much the nature of work has changed
since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated updates, observers say, the law has become
outdated because of technological and sociological changes. Also,
new categories of jobs such as computer programmers and help-desk
workers have created gray areas in the law, making it hard for
employers to figure out who is entitled to overtime and who isn't.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of computer jobs, some workers are exempt under
provisions written into the federal law in 1996, yet whether
overtime pay applies to scores of others is unclear, says Tim
Bartl, assistant general counsel for LPA, a trade group
representing senior human resource executives of major
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the gray area. It's a different type of work and
different type of compensation,'' such as stock options, that
exists now, Bartl added. ``It's a new dynamic and creative work
environment. The government needs to figure out a way to make it
easier for employers to determine who gets overtime and who
doesn't. Right now as the law stands, it's very complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta attorney Ann Hale-Smith agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the economy we have now, there are so many more different
kinds of jobs than there used to be,'' said the attorney with the
Atlanta law firm of Irvin, Stanford &AMP; Kessler, which represents
management in labor and employment law disputes. ``You have jobs in
high tech that didn't exist five years ago. We've gone to more of a
service economy vs. manufacturing, and they don't fit into the neat
categories that jobs fit into 30 or 15 years ago when you could
clearly say somebody was blue, white or pink collar. That's not
true anymore, and the law is struggling to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Worley doesn't buy Hale-Smith's argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an excuse a lot of employers use to violate the law,''
he said. ``They say the workplace is changing and the laws were
passed in 1938. Fact is, the law was passed so that people would
not be overworked, and the way that's enforced is that the law
requires you be paid time and a half. That's not something
employers and workers can negotiate around.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more prevalent is the growing use of independent
contractors, part-time and temporary help workers, most of whom
aren't getting overtime pay or traditional benefits, legal experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Some) companies are hiring contractors and working them far
more than 40 hours, but not paying them overtime either,'' Worley
noted. While the debate over overtime rages on, the booming economy
has provided overworked workers with another option.
</P>
<P>
   ``If excessive amounts of overtime are required, employees will
vote with their feet by leaving,'' says Les Hough, executive
director of the Usery Center for The Workplace at Georgia State
University. ``That only exacerbates the problem. Turnover has
become a chief irritant in retaining employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
