<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-DISASTER-AID10-COX     03-09 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-AID10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PANEL RESTORES MONEY FOR PRINCEVILLE STUDY
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Appropriations Committee reinstated
funding Thursday for a $1.5 million federal study on raising the
dike that protects the historic town of Princeville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The money had been dropped earlier this week from a Republican
plan to provide more than $347 million in flood aid for victims of
last year's Hurricane Floyd. The action angered many people,
including Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., who called the omission
``unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Thursday that dropping the $1.5 million was ``a
mix-up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't intend to take this one out,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla., chairman of the Appropriations Committee. The money
was mistakenly grouped with another project that was rejected, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their story and they're sticking to it,'' said Clayton,
whose district includes Princeville. But she added that the
explanation ``could be true,'' and she was grateful to the GOP
leadership for their help in putting together a good emergency aid
package.
</P>
<P>
   The money for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers study and the
overall flood aid is part of an $8.8 billion supplemental spending
bill for the current fiscal year. The bill includes nearly $5
billion for peacekeeping operations in Kosovo and $1.7 billion for
drug intervention in Colombia. The Appropriations Committee was
expected to vote on it late Thursday after several hours of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Walter Jones, R-N.C., an outspoken critic of foreign aid,
said he would vote in favor of the measure, despite his
reservations about the money included for foreign operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to vote for any legislation that will help the
people of eastern North Carolina,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton attended part of the committee hearing with Delia
Perkins, the mayor of Princeville, who was in Washington lobbying
for aid. Rep. David Price, D-N.C., introduced both Clayton and
Perkins in the hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great coincidence,'' said Clayton, that Perkins was
in the capital. ``She was our ace in the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeville, the oldest town in the country incorporated by
freed slaves, gained widespread attention last year in the
aftermath of Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Edgecombe County town was submerged in 23 feet of water for
10 days after heavy rains sent the Tar River over the dike. Almost
all of the town's 650 homes, 30 businesses and three churches were
damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased,'' Perkins said about the emergency aid.
``It's very good _ not only for Princeville but for the surrounding
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
