<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CRASH-NYT &LR;      03-09 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN JOURNALIST AND OIL EXECUTIVE DIE IN PLANE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A top Russian investigative journalist and a leading
petroleum executive were among nine people killed early Thursday
when a chartered jet crashed on takeoff from Moscow's main domestic
airport, Sheremetyevo One.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, Artyom Borovik, and the head of the oil-trading
company Alliance Group, Ziya Bazhayev, had taken off for Kiev when
the three-engine Yak-40 passenger jet apparently tipped sideways
and slammed into the runway. Two other oil-company employees and
five crew members also died in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   There was immediate speculation that the two men had been slain
in one of the violent feuds that periodically rock the top echelons
of Russian industry and politics. Moscow transportation
investigators opened a criminal inquiry into whether the flight
violated air-safety rules, and one official told the Interfax news
service that a terrorist act had not been ruled out as a cause of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the Federal Security Service, the domestic
successor to the Soviet KGB, said Thursday night that Bashayev, who
is of Chechen descent, had received threats because he had refused
to supply weapons to rebels in the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no way to document that accusation. Nor was there
any evidence of foul play. Witnesses said that one wing of the jet
struck the runway during takeoff, causing the aircraft to cartwheel
and break up just after it left the ground. The plane's flight-data
recorder was recovered and will be analyzed for evidence of the
cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Borovik, reported to be 38 or 39, was something of a legend in
Russian journalism. The son of a famous Soviet-era foreign
correspondent, he himself became famous for his highly critical
dispatches on the war in Afghanistan. His articles, published just
as Mikhail Gorbachev had begun loosening controls over freedom of
expression, caused a sensation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, he built a small media conglomerate called
Sovershenno Sekretno Holding _ the words mean ``top secret'' _
which produced newspapers and television programs with an
investigative bent. His television program bearing that name was
bounced off Russia's state-controlled RTR network last June after
delving into political corruption. It had an eight-year run.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives said then that the program was smearing major
political figures to maintain its huge popularity. But Borovik
contended that the move signaled the Kremlin's intention to subdue
the press before the winter's parliamentary elections and the 2000
presidential campaign _ a prediction which has largely come true.
</P>
<P>
   Bazhayev's Alliance Group was well known in petroleum-industry
circles. But unlike some Russian tycoons who have won both wealth
and notoriety in the oil business, his was not a household name.
Industry analysts said the Bazhayev company was an oil broker,
buying and reselling petroleum shipments, and an adviser to other
oil companies undergoing restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Bazhayev, who would have been 40 in July, served in the
mid-1990s as the president of Yunko, a government-controlled
enterprise created to manage Chechnya's petroleum business. He
later became head of a huge but financially troubled oil producer,
Sidanko. The company has since gone bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Russian business press, Bazhayev's company was
struggling this month with Sidanko executives over the disposition
of a Sidanko subsidiary deeply in debt to Alliance Group.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the two men were flying to Kiev. An
Alliance Group executive was quoted on Moscow television as saying
that Borovik and Bashayev were old friends and were discussing a
joint business venture. Other reports, none of them confirmed,
stated that Borovik was planning to expand distribution of his
publications in Ukraine, or that he was investigating Russian
involvement in the Ukrainian aluminum industry.
</P>
<P>
   The two men's private Yak-40 jet, which was 24 years old, was
due to be retired in July 2001, but the plane's owners said it was
in excellent mechanical condition. The pilot was said to have
logged more than 7,000 hours in the air.
</P>
</TEXT>
