<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2121 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-MCCAIN-ANALYSIS-COX     03-09 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Straight Talk Express didn't keep up with Bush campaign
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, ARIZ. _ John McCain had never lost an election before
the South Carolina primary and his unfamiliarity with giving a
concession speech showed on election night last month.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than congratulate George W. Bush and let it go at that,
McCain gave an angry speech that attacked Bush as, in effect, an
empty suit.
</P>
<P>
   His jaw tight and his speech clipped, McCain looked nothing like
the happy warrior who caravaned through New Hampshire on the way to
a stunning victory.
</P>
<P>
   McCain the man had been on the receiving end of so much negative
advertising and campaigning, including allegations that he fathered
children out of wedlock and approved of abortion, that he might
have been excused for a little anger.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain the politician should have known that the campaign
was going to get rough after Bush lost New Hampshire and found
himself under siege by supporters who were wondering what was going
on.
</P>
<P>
   McCain took it personally and he let it show, and the moment may
have marked a turning point in his campaign. ``The reaction of the
McCain camp to the South Carolina loss started the downward spiral
because it got them fundamentally away from the message that had
elevated them and provided the excitement to that point,'' said
Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster who is not affiliated with either
campaign. ``It's almost as though their anger at the Bush campaign
tactics clouded their political judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reform, McCain's main line of attack was to criticize
Bush for negative campaigning. After Pat Robertson weighed in in
Michigan with anti-McCain telephone calls, the Arizona Republican
unleashed a memorable speech that branded Robertson and the Rev.
Jerry Falwell ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   He did himself no favors when the next day he used the word evil
to describe the two men, even if he was joking, as he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The speech played well in some circles, but among Republicans,
particularly conservative Republicans, McCain's comments were a
call to battle.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ran poorly among Republicans in most primaries, but his
comments appeared to galvanize social conservative voters behind
Bush's campaign. ``We may not like Bush, but we have to stop
McCain,'' said Steve Frank, a leader of California conservatives,
describing the tenor of a flood of e-mail messages in the days
before Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a true-blue Republican with a 17-year voting record
that left little doubt about his conservatism, but he was finding
it very difficult to come by Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   Independents and Democrats, attracted by his story and his call
for reform, showed no reluctance to vote for him. And their
support, which McCain contends is crucial if Republicans are to win
the White House, may be his campaign's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats and independents do not a Republican nominee make.
</P>
<P>
   A telltale sign of McCain's problems in this regard came in the
form of a placard at Ohio State University last month that read,
``Republicans for McCain.'' It was a revealing and damaging
statement that a Republican would have to advertise there are other
Republicans behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, said McCain's speech, delivered in Robertson's hometown
of Virginia Beach, solidified McCain's place in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech is one more piece of the giant mosaic that McCain
has constructed that says, 'I am the Democratic, independent, media
candidate for the Republican nomination,'' Sabato said. ``The
problem is that in the end, to get the nomination, you have to be a
Republican candidate for the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of McCain's exit from the race and
some costly errors that have hurt in recent weeks, it is easy to
underestimate what McCain accomplished in his 14-month campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, they've done a remarkable job given the
resources at their disposal,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain always knew that it would take the political equivalent
of a perfect game to win the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed to have too much of everything _ money,
endorsements, organization and a huge lead in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to knock Bush off stride by winning four early
primaries _ New Hampshire, South Carolina, Arizona and Michigan _
then hope that Bush would look like a weak candidate once his aura
of invincibility had been stripped away.
</P>
<P>
   What McCain had to do was introduce himself to voters by means
of his personal history, then provide a platform of reform,
principally of campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear early on that crowds warmed to his optimism and
enthusiasm, all the more remarkable in view of his long struggle as
a prisoner of war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared on the presidential scene at a moment when Americans
were looking for someone to believe in, someone not tainted by the
sex and campaign finance scandals that engulfed Washington for the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was, in the words of Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.), ``the
antidote to Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the reaction to McCain as he went to one town hall
meeting after another in New Hampshire. It helped propel his win in
New Hampshire and sent him to South Carolina with polls showing he
had erased Bush's once sizable lead there and in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment in South Carolina when anything looked
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Having just fled the cold of New Hampshire for sunny South
Carolina, McCain spoke at a breakfast at an antebellum, waterfront
mansion in Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   Shaded by an enormous water oak heavy with Spanish moss, McCain
stood on the front steps. But many in the overflow crowd urged him
up one step and then another because they could not see.
</P>
<P>
   A delighted McCain complied and hit on a metaphor for his
campaign. ``One step at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he stumbled a few times and watched Bush roll inexorably
toward the nomination. Tuesday's round of voting was the clincher,
as McCain lost nine of 13 contests in what amounted to a nationwide
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by reporters, McCain looked back on his campaign in the
days before Tuesday's primaries. He acknowledged many mistakes,
blaming himself for the many ``idiotic things I've said.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused to dwell on any one error. McCain and his aides knew
all along that attacking Falwell and Roberston carried enormous
risks.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the campaign, they all insisted it had been the
right thing to do a statement of principle, even if it backfired as
a political tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to say that and you had to say it before the
(Virginia) primary because if we had said it after the primary then
you're not...legitimately giving your criticism and your vision for
the party,'' McCain said the day before the California primary.
</P>
<P>
   This comment was made aboard the Straight Talk Express, the
campaign bus that became a rolling news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the campaign, however, McCain got in trouble on
at least two occasions for remarks he made on the bus. One was the
``evil'' comment, which became front-page news in the New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, McCain and reporters engaged in a tense
back-and-forth over whether he had misled them about his
participation in a debate.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion was of no lasting importance, but it showed an
evolution of sorts in a campaign that started off carefree in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that McCain lost either his perspective or
sense of humor. He never blamed a reporter for a piece of bad news,
and he insisted right to the end that the experience of running for
president was the most rewarding of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not enjoy it? Good God, how many people in the world have
this opportunity?'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   And there were events, even in the last days, when he appeared
uplifted by the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people waited in the dark for McCain at the Vietnam
memorial in Rochester, N.Y., on a cold, windy night. The candidate
described his initial dislike of the Vietnam memorial in
Washington, D.C.. But he said his view was forever changed when he
saw two grizzled veterans at the wall, touching the names of dead
comrades and crying openly.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished, the campaign fired off streamers that, aided
by the wind, looked like fireworks in the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
