<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -ASSETS10-COX &HT;    SENATE BILL PASSES LAW ON COMPENSATING TERROR VICTIMS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill that would allow American victims of
state-sponsored terrorism to be compensated by the offending
countries unanimously passed the Senate Judiciary Committee on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will give the United States one more weapon
in the fight against terrorism,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., who sponsored the bill with Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The bill wouyld prevent victims of terrorism from being blocked
from recovering court-awarded damages the frozen assets of
terrorist countries. Countries such as Iran and Cuba have assets in
the United States frozen by the Treasury Department. The bill
excludes diplomatic properties from eligible assets.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 anti-terrorism law gave American victims the right to sue
foreign sponsors of terrorism in U.S. courts. Two years ago,
Congress passed another law that allowed victims to tap the frozen
assets of terrorist states as compensation for their injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent cases, President Clinton has waived the right of
American families to obtain damages from frozen assets in the
United States. The administration has taken the position the assets
could be used in negotiations with the terrorist nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the Senate will stand with American victims of
terrorism and act to bring them the justice they deserve,'' Mack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg and Mack were joined by 23 other co-sponsors of the
bill, including Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
