<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-RETURN-$ADV12-     03-09 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-RETURN-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 12)  
 &HT;     McCAIN WILL HAVE NEW RESPECT FROM SENATE COLLEAGUES  
 &HT;     EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When John McCain returns to the Senate after his
blistering campaign for the Republican presidential nomination, he
will be greeted _ begrudgingly _ as a hero by his fellow
Republicans who will need his help to keep control of Congress in
the November election.
</P>
<P>
   The maverick Arizona Republican, who said he was on a ``great
crusade'' to reform the GOP, gained astonishing celebrity during
his 14 months of campaigning on the theme that big campaign
contributions unduly influence politicians.
</P>
<P>
   His calls for campaign finance reform infuriated many fellow
Republicans who claim their party would be disproportionately hurt
because the GOP tends to pull in more contributions in the
unregulated soft money donations that McCain would ban. Soft money
contributions are given to political parties _ not candidates _ and
can come from corporations and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also alienated the Republican establishment by attacking
leaders of the religious right _ including television evangelist
Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell _ and by his personal
criticism of Republican front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's tremendous crossover appeal to Democrats and
independents, which won him victories in five New England states
and Michigan, will make him an indispensable asset for Bush and for
Republican congressional candidates desperate to corral independent
swing voters, the same ones Ross Perot appealed to in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News-Wall Street Journal poll last week showed that 23
percent of voters would vote for McCain as a third-party candidate
in a general election, compared with 34 percent for Vice President
Al Gore and 32 percent for Bush. Those numbers explain why Bush's
supporters are hoping McCain will eventually endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush can't win without McCain,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb., national co-chairman of McCain's campaign and one of just
four Republican senators to back him. ``He has an appeal we haven't
seen since Bobby Kennedy. He'll come back to the Senate with a much
enhanced reputation and status.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain will be hugely popular with Republican congressional
candidates, especially senators in tight races. That list includes
Sens. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, Rod Grams of Minnesota,
Spencer Abraham of Michigan and John Ashcroft of Missouri,
according to Republican analyst Marshall Wittmann.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans command a 55-45 majority in the Senate and a 222-211
majority in the House, where two members are independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his Republican colleagues are smart, they will treat him
like a conquering hero,'' Wittmann said. ``These politicians
understand when there is a new dynamic, a new force in the
electorate, and he was able to reach it. What politicians are most
attracted to is success because they want the success themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll find a lot of senators who'll have a picture of
them with John McCain in the front lobby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before McCain launched his anti-establishment bid, he had
strained relationships with his GOP Senate colleagues, with many
dissenting from his efforts to overhaul the campaign finance
system. While 51 Republican senators endorsed Bush, only four _
Hagel, Sens. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, Mike DeWine of Ohio and
John L. Kyl of Arizona _ backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Trent Lott, R-Miss., said last week that McCain
has given him ``heartburn at times'' and alienated many senators by
saying they've been corrupted by special interest money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go into a senator's state and box his ears,'' Lott
said. ``John sometimes has stepped on people's linenow that doesn't
sit too well with your 99 colleagues in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lott also seems awed by McCain's success on the campaign
trail. ``He ran a whale of a campaign,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Pitney, a political scientist at Claremont McKenna College,
said McCain is now ``probably the most famous senator and that
drives them nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitney quoted a line from a detective novel by Raymond Chandler,
saying McCain will ``encounter the plastic smiles people wear when
they're trying not to scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Whit Ayres said McCain will get ``a lot of
grudging respect for the voters he's energized and brought into the
Republican primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly captured the imagination of a number of voters
who have heretofore not been energized by previous Republican
candidates for president,'' Ayres said. ``So much of his reception
is going to be determined by whether he looks like he's going to
put his shoulder to the wheel and help to elect a Republican
president or whether he's going to continue to send signals that
the Republican party remains divided.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., McCain's long-standing opponent in
the continuing debate over campaign finance reform, said the
Arizona senator ``is going to get a very warm reception'' when he
returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves respect for running such a successful campaign,''
McConnell said. But McConnell insisted that doesn't mean he will
give an inch in his campaign finance reform battle against McCain.
``That's an issue we debate every year,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the aisle will also roll out the red carpet
when McCain comes back to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators will ``embrace Sen. McCain when he comes
back,'' because he has supported many of their causes such as
campaign finance reform, said Senate Minority Leader Thomas A.
Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle added that if McCain had succeeded in becoming the
Republican presidential nominee, ``I don't think we'd be as
enthusiastic about his return.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy &LR; hearstdc.com.
</P>
