<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
FRIDAY, March 10 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Josephine Schmidt (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Sedona, Ariz.) _ Sen. John McCain, the Republican whose
insurgency became the surprise of the primary season, ended his
maverick candidacy on Thursday with the hope that he would
eventually prevail in ``making our party as big as the country we
serve.'' Two days after being soundly defeated in coast-to-coast
primaries, McCain had gracious words for Gov. George W. Bush but
stopped noticeably short of endorsing him, saying only, ``I
congratulate Governor Bush and wish him and his family well. He may
very well become the next president of the United States.'' He also
ended speculation that he might make a third-party run by repeating
once again, ``I love my party, it is my home.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,8.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-KIDS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Every day after school, 13
year-old Jeffrey Mendelman has a peanut butter and jelly sandwich
with milk, finishes his homework _ and checks his stocks. ``My
dad's stock was going up,'' he explains of his decision to plunge
into the market, following stocks the way he once collected
baseball cards. ``Most kids here are interested in the market.
Because a lot of their dads have become pretty rich and that's why
they get to live in a gigantic house.'' A new sort of American
childhood is being forged in the land where each day brings the
dawn of an estimated 64 new millionaires. It's one in which CEOs
are the new superheroes, family dinner table conversations are
often likely to include talk of multiples and the latest IPO and
where a recent collision between two students in a high school
parking lot here, to no one's surprise, involved a brand-new Toyota
SUV Forerunner and a Mercedes 500 SL. But along with a new openness
about money and the obvious good things it can bring, have come
concerns about the effect of the Valley's unprecedented wealth on
children. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-SAFETY (Washington) _ A new NASA report on the safety of
the space shuttle is highly critical of the privatization of launch
and service operations that has been going on in recent years. The
report of the Independent Safety Assessment Team calls for more
inspections and the hiring of more NASA people to be more deeply
involved in operations at Cape Canaveral. It listed 37 things that
should be done before the next four shuttle flights are completed.
By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRADE (Washington) _ As the Clinton administration
conceded Thursday that it does not have the votes for a giant China
trade accord, a titanic lobbying battle was shaping up for the 110
uncommitted House members who will decide the fate of the
president's most important remaining foreign policy goal. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-URBAN-ENCLAVE (Newark, N.J.) _ Soaring home prices. Sclerotic
traffic. The maddening roar of new construction. Too many people,
not enough open space. Ah, the woes of a booming economy. But, in
an unlikely tale for flush times, this scenario is playing out not
in Manhattan, but in one corner of a city more often associated
with urban decay than runaway development. Newark's Ironbound
section, long a bastion of Portuguese immigrants and more recently
a magnet for Brazilians and other Latin Americans, has become one
of the hottest swaths of real estate in the region. By Andrew
Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT21,22,23.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-BOAT-PEOPLE (Hong Kong) _ Ask Nguyen Kim Lien about
life inside the barbed-wire fence of the Pillar Point Vietnamese
Refugee Camp here, and she is remarkably stoic. Her family lives in
squalor. Her husband is out of work and addicted to heroin. Yet
Mrs. Lien, 36, has found dignity amid the debris. She runs a shop
that sells Vietnamese noodles to the camp's 1,070 refugees. Her two
children, who were born in Hong Kong and have never lived outside
the camp, go to a nearby school. If Mrs. Lien has a reason to
despair, it is because after 10 years, she and her family must
leave Pillar Point by the end of May. Last month, Hong Kong
announced it was shutting down its last refugee camp for Vietnamese
boat people, ending a drama that began in May 1975. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
