<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-DROPOUT-HNS &LR;      03-09 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DROPOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN SUSPENDS CAMPAIGN, YIELDS GOP NOMINATION TO BUSH 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ John McCain, whose insurgent battle against
George W. Bush had its ups and downs before finally crashing on
Super Tuesday, retreated to a northern Arizona mountaintop Thursday
to end his race for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outdoors with his wife, Cindy, at his side and a
panorama of snow-dusted, red mountains in the background, the
Arizona senator yielded to the obvious fact that his maverick,
reform-oriented campaign _ despite its appeal for independent
voters _ had never caught on with most members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his task became ``considerably more difficult''
after coast-to-coast primaries Tuesday, when ``a majority of
Republican voters made clear their preference for president is
Governor Bush.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect their decision, and ... I am no longer an active
candidate for my party's nomination for president,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, McCain, 63, chose to suspend his candidacy, rather
than formally withdraw from the presidential race. By so doing, he
will remain eligible for federal matching campaign funds and will
keep the 231 delegates he has earned to this summer's Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said he may use the power of those delegates to persuade
the party to put campaign-finance reform into the platform and high
on Bush's agenda as the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that he was yielding the GOP nomination to the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on a bus traveling to his rally with Colorado
supporters before the primaries Friday there and in Utah and
Wyoming, when he listened to McCain's announcement over the radio.
He spoke with McCain and said he wanted to encourage him to
continue working in the Senate on campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the warm tone and his best wishes for me
and my family,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with him on a reform agenda. I'm
confident we can get a major reform package through on paycheck
protection ... to make sure the ban on corporate soft money and the
ban on labor union soft money is complete,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can find great areas of agreement,'' Bush said, insisting
they already have an important common ground: ``Making sure Al Gore
is not elected president.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who defied Republican leaders by making campaign-finance
reform the centerpiece of his campaign, also seemed to rule out an
independent race for the White House, although he may have left
that door slightly open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my party. It is my home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I am also dedicated to the necessary cause of
reform, and I will never walk away from a fight for what I know is
right and just for our country. As I said throughout the campaign,
what is good for my country is good for my party.``
</P>
<P>
   But the senator warned Republicans that their party ``will
surely slip into the mists of history, deserving the allegiance of
none'' if the GOP does not continue his efforts to reform the
political system and broaden the party's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The fight between McCain and Bush had grown increasingly bitter
and negative as the two traded primary wins in key states during
the past two months. Religious fundamentalist supporters of Bush
had attacked McCain, and McCain, in some states, had sponsored
phone calls suggesting Bush was supported by anti-Catholic bigots.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's tone Thursday was conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate Governor Bush and wish him and his family
well,'' he said, without endorsing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may very well become the next president of the United
States. That is an honor accorded very few, and it is such a great
responsibility that he deserves the best wishes of every American.
He certainly has mine.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain, his wife and top aides drove up to his announcement
site, on the side of a mountain road overlooking Sedona, in his
campaign bus, the ``Straight Talk Express,'' on which the senator
had held virtually non-stop, on-the-record discussions with
reporters while campaigning across the country.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, he delivered his remarks from a prepared
text, took no questions and quickly departed, returning to his
vacation home in nearby Cottonwood, where he planned to host an
off-the-record barbecue for staffers and reporters later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Howard Opinsky said McCain declined to answer
questions because he was facing an ``emotional time. He made a
statement, and I think that's all he wants to say today.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign caught fire with many independent and
Democratic voters, who were crucial to his victories over Bush in
early, open primaries in New Hampshire and Michigan, spoiling the
GOP ``coronation'' that many Republicans had anticipated for the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the better-funded Bush eventually wore McCain down. The
governor scored a decisive victory over the senator in South
Carolina with a strongly conservative campaign and drew on the
support of Republican leaders and conservative GOP voters to
deliver a fatal blow in California, Ohio, New York and other states
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And, next week, McCain would have faced an intimidating lineup
of primaries in Texas, Florida and other southern states that
heavily favor Bush.
</P>
<P>
   According to exit polls, Bush trounced McCain among conservative
Republican voters in New York, Ohio, California and other Super
Tuesday states. McCain not only lost all 162 of California's
Republican delegates to the Texas governor, he also came in third
in that state's open primary, which the senator had hoped to
capture as a symbol of his potential ``electability'' in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Navy pilot who spent five and one-half years as
a prisoner of war in North Vietnam, said he will take his
``crusade'' back to the Senate, where he lost a battle over
campaign-finance reform last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will keep fighting to give the government back to the
people; to keep our promises to young and old alike by paying our
debts, saving Social Security and Medicare, and reforming a tax
code that benefits the powerful few at the expense of many,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter John W. Gonzalez in Denver contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
