<HEADLINE>
MIT SAYS SPREADSHEET ERROR CAUSED GRADE CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A teaching assistant's mistaken mouse click, not a
computer hacker bent on tampering with test scores, altered the
grades of 22 students in an MIT biology class, institute officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Apologizing before the 120 undergraduates in his cell biology
course Thursday morning, Professor Harvey Lodish said one of the
class's six teaching assistants accidentally assigned students the
wrong grades after incorrectly sorting them on a computer
spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   Lodish, who last Thursday announced to the class that a cheating
scandal had been uncovered, would not answer questions about why it
took a week to realize the clerical error, which lowered the grades
of 20 students and raised the marks of two students.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Sauer, chairman of the biology department, said he
didn't believe there was anything strange about the lag time, and
that Lodish was sorry for unsettling the class by accusing students
of cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson that I hope was learned here is that you have to
move slow and be cautious in these kinds of cases,'' Sauer said.
``The initial interpretation was the wrong one. And that
interpretation was shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent headlines about hackers breaking into high-profile
commercial Web sites such as Yahoo.com or breaching the Pentagon's
vaunted electronic firewalls, he said, likely predisposed Lodish
and institute administrators into assuming the altered grades was
just another case of hacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this happens, as a teacher, it immediately
sends a chill down your spine,'' Sauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Institute officials said they discovered it was human error only
after ruling out that anyone had infiltrated the biology class's
computer system, MIT spokesman Ken Campbell said. Adding to the
delay, the teaching assistant who make the mistake did realize the
error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more complicated to figure out a mistake than a
violation,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``simple slip-up,'' he explained that the teaching
assistant using the spreadsheet highlighted only a column of names,
instead of clicking on and sorting both a column of names and
grades. Officials would not identify the teaching assistant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-DROPOUT-HNS &LR;      03-09 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-DROPOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DROPS OUT OF RACE, CONGRATULATES GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley, whose ``big idea''
presidential candidacy once threatened to thwart Vice President Al
Gore's political future, officially dropped out of the race
Thursday, offering only tepid support to his former rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president and I had a stiff competition, and he won.
I congratulate him,'' Bradley said at a press conference near his
campaign headquarters. ``He will be the nominee of the Democratic
Party and I will support him in his bid to win the White House.``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a 56-year-old former pro basketball star and former
senator from New Jersey, said he plans to take a vacation with his
wife, Ernestine, before returning to campaign for his fellow
Democrats. He did not rule out a future run for president, but he
did say, as he has all along, that he would not consider becoming
Gore's running mate if he were to be asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I will not be a candidate for vice president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton praised Bradley and the tenor
of the Democratic nominating contest in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked at the issues he raised and the way in which he
raised them, it recalled again how very much more substantive in my
judgment the debate was on the Democratic side, on the issues, and
how much more agreement there was,'' Clinton said during a
question-and-answer session with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Republican side there was far more disagreement, I
think, and it was far less rooted in issues that will really affect
the American people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that while he is bowing out of the race, he will
not release the 415 delegates he has won. He did not say what role
he plans for himself at this summer's Democratic convention, but
said he would follow the tradition of his party to close ranks
behind the nominee once the people have spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is time for unity,'' he said. ``Democrats know that the
offerings of the likely Republican nominee are opposite of where
our country should be headed.``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he telephoned Gore on Thursday morning to tell him
he would support him, but he declined to detail their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to deviate on the last day of his campaign from his usual
practice of keeping his personal feelings to himself, Bradley
paused briefly before responding:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something I believe I gave my full heart, mind, soul
and energy to, and it didn't turn out,'' he said. ``As I said the
other night, you win and you lose. This is a loss, and I move on.``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has characterized Gore as being untruthful, said he
spoke his mind during the campaign when he felt his opponent had
engaged in distortions and negativity, and he said he would not
hesitate to speak up again during the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his call for Gore to come clean on the 1996
fund-raising scandals to remove what he considers a major
Democratic weakness in the fight against Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he'll run a better campaign in the general
election,'' Bradley said of Gore. ``I was calling it as I saw it,
but I believe that a Democratic president is better for our country
than a Republican president. He has my full support.``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also spoke of his pride in bringing a ``new politics''
to America, a politics not dominated by money, but one of core
convictions, such as his platform of improving health care,
reforming campaign-finance laws, and ending child poverty, racial
discrimination and gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are my convictions,'' he said, ``convictions I do not
change because elections are won or lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abraham Lincoln once wrote that the cause of liberty must not
be surrendered at the end of one or even a hundred defeats,'' he
added to lengthy applause from his campaign workers. ``We have been
defeated, but the cause for which I ran has not been ... that
cannot be defeated by one or a hundred defeats.``
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley repeated his campaign refrain that in this time of
economic prosperity, America should be ``fixing our roof while the
sun is shining.``
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't seize this moment,'' he warned, ``future
generations will judge us harshly and say, `They knew what was
wrong. They had the means to make it better and they did not
act.'``
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's announcement came as no surprise as the presidential
hopeful had essentially conceded defeat after Gore swept the Super
Tuesday primaries this week, collecting enough delegates to ensure
his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who once led Gore in polls in Northeastern states, came
within 4 percentage points of winning the New Hampshire primary
Feb. 1, but after that, his campaign fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gore completely shut him out, winning even in
Bradley's home state of Missouri and in New York, where he played
for the Knicks. Despite Bradley's pounding on the theme of racial
unity, blacks preferred Gore by a margin of 6-to-1, and Hispanics
by 8-to-1. Union members also backed Gore as did established
abortion rights groups who rallied behind the vice president when
Bradley tried to question his commitment to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday what he thought went wrong with his campaign,
Bradley was philosophical. He said he failed to get across the
message that his campaign was not about self-interest, but was
about something much bigger than any individual involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ended his campaign, which he called ``a joyous
journey,'' by joking with reporters and conducting a mock
graduation ceremony. As his staff quietly hummed ``Pomp and
Circumstance,'' Bradley shook hands with the traveling press corps
and handed out gifts _ Tiffany key chains dangling silver high-top
tennis shoes and tins of his favorite throat lozenges, his
trademark from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
