u p BC-FRONT-RUNNERS-HNS &LR;      03-09 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-RUNNERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH APPEALS TO McCAIN'S SUPPORTERS IN ATTACKING GORE 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ George W. Bush praised his erstwhile opponent John
McCain on Thursday, but showered caustic remarks on his new
opponent, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly outdoor at the Denver Broncos training facility
in suburban Englewood, Bush said he, not Gore, has the most appeal
for McCain's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to win his supporters over is when they realize
that Al Gore is no reformer, Al Gore is no John McCain,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Heaping criticism on Gore, Bush said the same day the vice
president was condemning ``soft-money'' donations in political
campaigns, he was mobilizing to raise $35 million worth of the
donations from corporate, labor union and other supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed ... Here's a man who stood up in front of America
yesterday and talked about ridding the system of soft money, while
evidently they're planning to raise soft money, $35 million,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who went to a Buddhist temple to raise money. My
only point is, Mr. Gore, I'm not going to let you get away with
that. I'm going to remind people of how you've conducted your
business in the past and how you're conducting it today,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed incensed by news accounts that Gore was seeking new
sums of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what he's thinking. He must be thinking we're
not paying attention. He must believe that words don't matter in
life. It's a perplexing way to lead,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While Democratic officials acknowledged that Gore will help the
party raise unregulated ``soft money, the vice president said that
the party would not halt such activities if Bush and the
Republicans refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he thinks the Democratic Party is going to unilaterally
disarm and and jump off a cliff he has another thing coming,'' Gore
said..
</P>
<P>
   The vice president had canceled an event in Minneapolis and
rushed back to Washington to be on hand for Senate votes on two
judicial nominees. In the end Gore's tie-breaking vote was not
needed as the Senate approved the two nominees to the Ninth Circuit
Court of Appeals by a comfortable margin.
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech Tuesday night Gore called on Bush to
eliminate soft-money contributions. He also challenged the
Republican nominee to forgo 30- and 60-second ads and debate twice
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee spokesman Jenny Backus said the
upcoming fund-raisers that Gore is expected to participate in are
part of a general election strategy that has been in the works
since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure our state parties and our national
parties are in a strong position for the 2000 elections and
beyond,'' she said. ``We assumed once we had a (presidential)
nominee we would like the nominee and other Democratic party
leaders to help us raise funds and work on grass-roots support for
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic party officials said they hoped to raise about $35
million in these unregulated funds by the time of the August
convention. The party has planned a tribute to President Clinton,
which is expected to bring in $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, asked to elaborate on how he would woo McCain's loyalists,
said, ``McCain voters will be looking for someone to bring honor
and integrity to the White House. McCain voters want to hear
somebody who's got a positive vision to make sure the American
dream touches everyone's heart. McCain voters want somebody who
knows what they're talking about when it comes to education. And
McCain voters hopefully want somebody who will fight for tax
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Austin, Texas, late Thursday, Bush
campaigned in the other two Western states that have GOP primaries
Friday, Utah and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my 24 hours (rest). Now I'm out campaigning again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
