<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TJX-ENGLISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TJX NAMES NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edmond ``Ted'' English, who began his retail career as a stock
boy at Filene's Basement, will assume day-to-day command of TJX
Cos., the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As successor to Bernard Cammarata, English will become chief
executive of TJX _ a nearly $9 billion retail empire _ in mid
April, according to a statement released by the Framingham, Mass.
operator of the T.J. Maxx and Marshalls chains.
</P>
<P>
   Cammarata, 60, remains as chairman and will focus on the
company's long-term strategic objectives, TJX said.
</P>
<P>
   English's promotion was expected, and English, 46, said he will
continue to pursue Cammarata's vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay the course,'' said English, who played a
major role in integrating Marshalls into the TJX empire a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cammarata said he spent two years grooming English as his
successor. Last summer, TJX signaled to Wall Street that English
was the heir apparent when he was promoted to president, a title
previously held by Cammarata.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement, Cammarata said, ``concludes a
thoughtful and deliberative senior succession plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a very smooth and seamless transition,'' said
Sally H. Wallick, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Since acquiring Marshalls in 1995, TJX has often enjoyed
explosive growth. It continued to boom in fiscal 1999, though its
fourth-quarter suffered a bit from tough comparisons with the
fourth-quarter of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, TJX said it exceeded its goals for 1999's fourth quarter,
and overall results for the year were ``excellent,'' the company
said. For 1999, net income rose from $423.9 million to $521.7
million, and sales rose 11 percent to $8.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from 1976 when T.J. Maxx was a one-man
operation. For 24 years, Cammarata has focused on a single idea
known as off-price retail: selling brand-name clothing at bargain
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Others have pursued this concept and sometimes run into trouble
as they strayed from their off-price roots. Such may be the case
with Filene's Basement Corp. and Loehmann's Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But by staying focused on brand names for less, Cammarata has
built TJX into an off-price powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben has a pretty terrific formula,'' English said of
Cammarata. ``What we do works. We know this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Given TJX's momentum, Cammarata said the timing was right to
announce the succession plan.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that Cammarata and English plan to address together is
what to do with all the cash TJX is generating. One option is a
possible acquisition; another is a bigger stock buyback program.
</P>
<P>
   TJX's strong performance is reflected in its stock price,
analysts said. Like many retailers, TJX has seen its stock dip
sharply as Wall Street has grown disenchanted with old-economy
companies. Thursday TJX shares dropped 1/8 to close at 15 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 1915EST &QL; 
