<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      03-09 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY VALUES: MOM AND DAD ARE BATTLING OVER THE BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE NEXT BEST THING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madonna, Rupert Everett, Benjamin Bratt, Malcolm Stumpf, Michael
Vartan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Schlesinger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 107 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think ``Kramer vs. Kramer,'' but with major twists in
relationships and living arrangements. When Abbie (Madonna), a yoga
instructor, is dumped by her boyfriend (Vartan), she clings to her
best friend, Robert (Everett), who is gay. After getting drunk on
the Fourth of July, they make love and voila: a pregnancy that
grows markedly by the scene until we have little Sam (Malcolm
Stumpf).
</P>
<P>
   Assured that he is the father, Robert takes his parenting duties
to heart, and the three make up a comfy household until six years
later, when different sexual orientations finally exert their pull.
Abbie becomes involved with Ben ( Bratt), a generic investment
banker who's on the banal side but not too bad a person. Robert is
the problem, turning aggressively possessive of Sam and threatened
by what increasingly becomes a drift toward a new family alignment.
</P>
<P>
   With Abbie and Ben planning to move away and take Sam with them,
a custody struggle takes shape. Robert fights bitterly in court,
raising some thought-provoking issues of parental rights. But then
there is a major surprise and, later, a burst of common sense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Abbie and Robert's coupling is not shown in detail, but
there is some partial nudity and much sexual discussion, gay and
straight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: A fair amount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 12: Obviously the film is inappropriate for the very
young. As for older children, the family troubles could be
disturbing. Parents should realize that sexual issues are
continually front and center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: Neither the situation nor the characters are of
much interest to most teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HANGING UP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meg Ryan, Diane Keaton, Lisa Kudrow, Walter Matthau &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Keaton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 92 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chirping cell phones link three fizzed-up sisters and their
difficult old dad, who in contrast to his daughters' jittery
hyperactivity is slowly sinking toward his demise. Scribbling
``It's too late'' in his hospital room, Lou (Matthau), a
79-year-old who once wrote movies for John Wayne and now can't seem
to get anything straight, relies on the middle daughter, Eve
(Ryan), for aid and comfort. That's not to say his other two girls
don't care, but it's hard focusing on Dad when you're quite this
frantic.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia (Keaton), the eldest, is madly preparing the
fifth-anniversary edition of Georgia, the glossy New York magazine
she founded in honor of herself. Maddy (Kudrow), the youngest,
frets over her huge sloppy dog and a soap opera acting career that
will last exactly as long as her next relationship on ``Loving
Dangerously.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Lou understandably apprehensive and constantly
demanding. Working a cell phone with the best of them, he leans on
Eve. A professional party planner, she is the most frenzied of them
all, flitting here and there in her Land Rover, shaggy hairdo
artfully askew, crashing into a nice Iranian doctor's Mercedes, and
being as perky and addled as Ryan can be when she's on full
adorable.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the sisters collide at an event Eve has planned at the
Nixon Library. Together they thrash out some tensions between them
and rally at Lou's bedside in time to wet a hankie over the last
farewell. Cut to Thanksgiving for a reunion, some good laughs and a
food fight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: The alcoholic Lou is a nasty drunk and when ambulatory
terrorizes a birthday party for little children with crude remarks
and violent gestures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Hailed as a wizened but still semi-potent ladies man, Lou
is a fount of salacious and often painfully tasteless
observations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Obscenities and off-color remarks sneak in here and
there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10: This isn't a film for small children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-12: Girls might buy the package, which comes with a
frothy script by Delia and Nora Ephron. That's fine as far as it
goes, but lost in the dazzle is any kind of realistic sense of
coming to terms with a dying parent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP: No harm, but teen-agers generally won't relate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOILER ROOM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Ribisi, Vin Diesel, Nia Long, Nicky Katt, Ron Rifkin,
Scott Caan, Ben Affleck, Jamie Kennedy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ben Younger &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 110 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pigeon: 45-year-old male, makes $150,000 a year, has $1 million
in assets, typically lives in the Midwest but wants to do business
with a New York broker. For such clients, sweaty-palmed but up for
a plunge, the firm J.T. Marlin, off Exit 53 on the Long Island
Expressway (that's New York, right?), has a trading (boiler) room
full of brokers barely out of high school with all kinds of risks
to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Young (Affleck), J.T. Marlin's drill sergeant, instructs the
firm's recruits on the fine art of the phone spiel. As for broker
remuneration, it's not a question that the adept among them will be
making at least $1 million a year. The question is how many
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 27, describes himself as too old for the game he's
teaching. The recruits, several years younger, are crass,
beer-swilling Long Island boys. The best is Seth (Ribisi), who
dropped out of college and began running an illegal casino. That
displeases his father (Rifkin), a federal judge, so Seth considers
an overture from J.T. Marlin. ``Nobody wants to work for it
anymore, so I became a stockbroker,'' he says in a voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he is landing clients and selling stocks (``the white boy
way of slinging crack rock''). But when he overhears his boss' plan
to vacate the office in minutes if need be, his suspicions are
aroused. J.T. Marlin is selling stock in companies that don't
exist. With the feds closing in, Seth discovers his conscience. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: A loud, boorish crew, J.T. Marlin recruits beat up a
barroom antagonist and threaten brawls with up-market counterparts
who work for Wall Street firms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: The talk gets bawdy, and Seth discreetly has sex with a
very nice $80,000-a-year J.T. Marlin secretary (Long). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: These are pretty obscene people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER 14: No, no, no, but Ribisi is a very appealing young
actor, as are Diesel (as Chris, another broker) and, of course,
Affleck. They and the get-rich-quick phenomenon could attract
children at younger ages than one might expect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17: This is certainly a movie for the times and, R-rated
features notwithstanding, it is quite a good one with plenty of
ratty characters but also some strong ones who stand up and do the
right thing when they have to. Parents will land on both sides of
the attendance issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
