<HEADLINE>
VOTERS-REBELS) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Updates AM-BUDGET, adding REPUBS-ASSESS, GORE, VOTER-TURNOUT and
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories and photos on the
presidential race, with the withdrawals of both McCain and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Sedona, Ariz.) _ Sen. John McCain ``suspended'' his
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination on Thursday and
wished his rival, Gov. George W. Bush, well, but stopped short of
endorsing him. And in an effort to make sure that his reform
message would continue to have resonance in the party, McCain said
he would hold on to his delegates until this summer's convention.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis: Dealing with McCain
as a non-candidate may be as hard for Bush as campaigning against
him. By Richard L. Berke. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Denver) _ Gov. George W. Bush continues campaigning in the
mountain states ahead of Friday's primaries. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY (West Orange, N.J.) _ Bill Bradley withdrew from the
race for the Democratic presidential nomination on Thursday,
leaving the field to Vice President Al Gore. ``Following the
results of Tuesday's primaries, I have decided to withdraw from the
Democratic race for president,'' Bradley said. Bradley pledged his
support for Gore, saying, ``Now is the time for unity.'' But he
said he would not yet release the delegates that he had won. By
James Dao and Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bradley and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ Once again, Al Gore, as vice president, is
summoned to an ``important'' vote in the Senate. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-TURNOUT (Washington) _ An analysis of primaries through
Super Tuesday shows turnout hit record highs for Republican
presidential primaries in 12 of the 18 completed contests. But this
was clearly a McCain phenomenon; Democratic turnout was the second
lowest in 40 years, with Clinton's uncontested renomination in 1996
the only lower. By Robin Toner. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS-REBELS (Undated) _ It was a tidy television package, the
sight of these vanquished politicians, McCain and Bradley, their
wives at their sides, offering their clipped exit lines to the
applause of their staffs. But something more than the
multi-million-dollar apparatus of two national campaigns was now to
be dismantled. What was disappearing from the stage with them was
something less tangible: the romance of the 2000 campaign. Not too
long ago, it looked as if this might be the year of the maverick.
Ultimately, though, these were rebels who lost their causes, beaten
back by standard-bearers of the establishment, a pair of political
heirs with proud old inside-the-beltway pedigrees and famous family
names. A political memo by Peter Marks. (925 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
