<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-DRUGWAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL OK'S $2 BILLION TO INTENSIFY DRUG WAR IN COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Backing President Clinton, House Republicans on a
powerful committee Thursday gave their prescription for the war on
drugs: yes for $2 billion to fight drugs at their source in
Colombia, no for $1.3 billion to treat addicts at home.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside amendments by leading Democrats to delete funds
for the Colombian military and pour money into treatment of
addicts, the votes by the House Appropriations Committee boosted
the White House's ambitious plan to battle drug cultivation in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The panel planned to vote on the entire $9 billion emergency
supplemental request late Thursday, after which the measure goes to
the full House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a military solution. We want a humanitarian solution
to the war on drugs,'' said Representative Nancy Pelosi, the
California Democrat who introduced the $1.3 billion treatment
amendment, after the vote. ``The discussion is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendments by Pelosi, the ranking Democrat on the
subcommitte on foreign oporations, and Wisconsin Democrat David R.
Obey underscored the deep unease among Democrats and some
Republicans of a foray into Colombia that the administration
estimates would last a minimum of five years. The $2 billion
funding, which the Republicans increased by $428 million over
Clinton's proposal, was for two years, but administration officials
say the final cost could easily include a few billion dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan debate Thursday at times grew heated, with
Republicans finding themselves oddly in the same corner with a
Democratic president. Some GOP members, who had pushed for
intervention in Colombia for years, chided Democrats for not
standing with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you must have confidence in your president,'' said
Representative Sonny Callahan, an Alabama Republican, speaking to
Obey. ``Your lack of confidence in your president is stunning to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Obey replied: ``I elect my president every four years to be my
leader, but I do not elect my president to do my thinking for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged the committee to at least temporarily remove $552
million from funds for the Colombian military, which has been tied
to the notorious paramilitary forces in three recent reports by
human rights organizations. Obey said more time was needed to study
the military's role in the counter-narcotics fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually none of us have the facts we need to know about this
issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chairman C.W. Bill Young, a Florida Republican, said there
was no time to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential to eliminate the product where it is grown,''
Young said. ``Every day we delay eliminating these drugs, another
hundred or a thousands kids could be addicted. . . . We're not
satisfied this is the best program, but are we ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan also expressed doubt about the package, calling it ``a
mile wide and an inch deep,'' but added: ``If anyone thinks drug
use in the United States is not an emergency, they better think
again.'' The committee defeated Obey's amendment 36-20.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Pelosi cited a Rand Corp. study in 1994 that found money
spent on treatment was 23 times more cost-effective than
eradication of crops and 11 times more cost-effective than
interdiction. She also noted that only 37 percent of America's 5.7
million hard-core addicts received treatment in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we neglect the obvious need in our country when
sending all that money to Colombia that is 23 times less
effective?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Edward Porter, an Illinois Republican,
answered that the Clinton administration didn't view treatment of
drug addicts as an emergency priority and didn't include it in
their package. ``We will take care of this problem'' later in
committee, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Young had said earlier on the military package, Michigan
Democrat Carolyn C. Kilpatrick of Michigan said action was needed
urgently for helping addicts, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emergency is before our eyes,'' she said. ``How can we
pass a bill for Colombia that we're not sure will work and not
spend money for the people in our districts that we know will
help?''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi's amendment lost 30-23 in a mostly party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   The $9 billion emergency bill also includes money for US troops
in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
