<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HOME VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DVD Format Gains a Foothold &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As DVD proliferates, so do the questions. Will DVD ever replace
VHS? Will we rent or buy the discs? Where are prices headed? As the
format becomes more mainstream, the answers refine themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among studios and distributors holds that DVD will
replace VHS within about five to seven years. But with VCRs in more
than 90 percent of households in the United States, the
videocassette may never disappear entirely, and video industry
people note that no single technology completely replaces another.
</P>
<P>
   With 5 million DVD players in use, VHS overwhelmingly
predominates, but retailers say they are noticing the beginnings of
a shift. ``The DVD player is going into the parents' room or family
room, the VCR into the kids' room,'' said Lon Weingart, a senior
vice president of Hollywood Video, the country's second largest
chain.
</P>
<P>
   The discs' cost of $25 to $39 encourages sales, but many
newcomers to DVD want to rent discs the way they do cassettes.
Meeting a big rental demand requires big inventories, which in turn
introduces all of video's legendary pricing complications.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the trick is to keep retail prices low enough to
promote sales and wholesale prices high enough to allow studios and
dealers to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood Video the DVD demand is primarily rental. Weingart
said that there had been no major customer complaints about a
shortage of hit titles, but this could change as the numbers of DVD
players and renters increase.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem the chain has with DVD is the occasional lag
between the release dates of the videocassette and the DVD, he
said. Studios generally try to get the disc out the same day as the
tape, but movies on DVD don't always appear on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most do, some don't,'' he said. One that won't is ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' due on videocassette next month.
For his own reasons, George Lucas, creator of the ``Star Wars''
films, has withheld them from DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Not producing such a big title on DVD hurts a format reaching
for the masses. ``To have to explain why a movie is available on
VHS and not DVD is a very difficult position to put our stores
in,'' Weingart said. ``It's a real customer service issue.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's to Bogart at 100 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It took Warner a while to recognize Humphrey Bogart's 100th
birthday (he was born on Jan. 23, 1899), but the studio is playing
catch-up with a collection of 18 Bogart films on videocassette. The
group, released on Tuesday, includes three first-timers on tape.
The best is ``The Amazing Dr. Clitterhouse'' (1938), with Bogart as
a hood called Rocks and Edward G. Robinson as a prominent doctor
who furthers his research into criminals by becoming one (and a
good one, too).
</P>
<P>
   The others are ``Black Legion'' (1936), with Bogart getting
involved with the Ku Klux Klan, and ``The Wagons Roll at Midnight''
(1941), with Bogart as a circus master. But for an amusing sendup
of the criminal justice system along with a lesson on how to wear a
double-breasted suit, try ``The Amazing Dr. Clitterhouse.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Bone Collector &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One wonders how the recorded seat-belt appeal in New York City
taxis might be amended to inform passengers about a driver who
locks them in and speeds off to underground caverns, where he
steams them to death or bloodies them some to attract swarms of
rats.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a case for the super forensic detective Lincoln Rhyme
(Denzel Washington), an imperious quadriplegic who oversees the
investigation second by second via a computer system that
instantaneously links him to anything. Left to retrieve the
corpses, his gorgeous protegee, Amelia Donaghy (Angelina Jolie),
gets the creepy end of an adventure in which, Stephen Holden wrote
in The New York Times, ``there is nothing remotely believable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37; DVD, $29.98. 118 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: March 14. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drive Me Crazy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chase (Adrian Grenier) and Nicole (Melissa Joan Hart) live next
door to each other but haven't been buddies since he turned
politically radical and personally scuzzy and she became little
miss well-scrubbed high-school achiever.
</P>
<P>
   But to help her land a basketball star, she enlists Chase, first
getting him decked out at the Gap to look at least semi-normal. A
bright, charismatic boy, Chase gets popular, which helps attract
Nicole in a film that as teen-age romantic comedies go, ``ranks
among the easy to take'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. 91 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guinevere &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An impressionable 21-year-old, Harper Sloane (Sarah Polley),
grows up under the sexual and intellectual tutelage of an older
man, a photographer named Connie (Stephen Rea). Latest in a long
string of Guineveres (the handle Connie assigns all his women),
Harper is flattered by his encouragement of her artistic ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up her end, she fulfills his need for a disciple and
lover. Such a situation can't go on for long of course, and as
Harper develops, Connie loses his control of her. While it lasts,
though, ``Rea and Polley show a lovely rapport, and a bantering
kinship that makes the relationship credible'' (Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 104 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside Providence &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worried about his son's drinking and drugging in Pawtucket,
R.I., Old Man Dunphy (Alec Baldwin) ships young Dunph (Shawn
Hatosy) off to a snooty prep school in Connecticut. Stuck with the
tweedy set, Dunph gets to class but sticks to his old Pawtucket
values. That kind of individuality attracts a classmate named Jane
(Amy Smart) and riles the school's administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunph does it his way and goes back home on his own terms in
a film that ``doesn't have the time or piety for the usual
coming-of-age hallmarks'' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: March 14. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'M STILL HERE ... DAMN IT! Courtney Love, Gianni Versace and
Rosie O'Donnell mightily irritate the dagger-tongued comedian
Sandra Bernhard in her 1999 HBO special, filmed in San Francisco.
Mother Teresa doesn't come out well either, or Diana, Princess of
Wales, or Tom Cruise. Designer water is out and so are
anti-bacterial soap and The New Yorker. 1999. Palm Pictures.
$19.95; DVD, $24.95. 60 minutes, with 30 minutes of extra
material. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DESIGNATED MOURNER. In David Hare's film, written by Wallace
Shawn, a genially sarcastic journalist (Mike Nichols in his
feature-film acting debut), the lone survivor of a cultural
revolution in an unnamed country, decides that he and his highbrow
intellectual friends didn't have the answers after all. 1997. First
Look Pictures. $79.95. 95 minutes. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WINDHORSE. Set in the Himalayas and the streets of Lhasa, the
capital of Tibet, Paul Wagner's film dramatizes the struggles of a
Tibetan brother and sister and their cousin under Chinese rule.
Clearly a tale with a cause, Lawrence Van Gelder wrote in The New
York Times, ``it tells its story in a straightforward manner.''
1999. New Yorker. $89.95. 97 minutes. English, Chinese and Tibetan
with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
