<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVER-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE LIVER USED TO HELP TWO PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two patients who had been on the brink of death a
little over a month ago _ a 45-year-old-man and an infant _ were
smiling Thursday at the successful outcome of a still-rare type of
transplant operation in which two people split a donor liver from
one cadaver. The procedure was done at Massachusetts General
Hospital last month.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, donor livers are in short supply. Nearly 15,000
people with varying stages of liver disease are on a waiting list,
according to the United Network for Organ Sharing, the nonprofit
organization that maintains the US organ transplant waiting list
and helps set transplant policy. Fewer than 5,000 get an organ in
any given year.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted doctors at a few medical centers across the
country to perform ``split-liver'' transplants in which one donor
liver is divided into a small portion, typically given to a child,
and a larger portion, given to an adult. In 1998, the last year for
which figures are available, there were only 138 split-liver
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   At MGH, one such operation was done successfully in November,
but the families declined to make their cases public. Thursday, the
families of Larry Hause, 45, and Jazmyn Thomson Bordoy, 19 months
old, decided to share their good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The saga began at 8 p.m on January 31. Hause, a 45-year-old
Scituate man who used to install carpets and flooring for a living,
was in the hospital, with just days to live.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Hause had been so severely burned that he needed
blood transfusions. Though no one knew it at the time, those
transfusions infected him with hepatitis C, a virus that attacks
the liver. For more than 20 years he did well, but in recent months
his liver had been failing, Hause said Thursday from his room at
MGH.
</P>
<P>
   That January night, Hause was losing ground rapidly. He needed a
liver transplant and had been at the top of the transplant list for
weeks _ but no donor organs had been found. Then he got a call from
one of his specialists, Dr. Sandy Feng: MGH finally had a cadaver
liver, but there was a catch.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby room at MGH, an infant, 18-month old Jazmyn Thompson
Bordoy of Boston, was also in desperate need of a new liver. She
had been born with biliary atresia, a condition in which the bile
ducts in the liver are missing or don't function. Like Hause's,
Jazymn's blood type matched that of the donor liver.
</P>
<P>
   Feng told Hause and his family, who had just made the drive from
Scituate, of her proposal: If Hause was willing, she wanted to
split the cadaver liver so that Hause got 80 percent, enough to
save his life, and Jazmyn, the other 20 percent, enough to save
hers. Hause doesn't remember the moment. ``I was so sick. Was I
given a choice? I made the choice?''
</P>
<P>
   But his mother, Mary Hause, remembers it vividly: ``No one
opened their mouth. He decided to do this on his own. . .He was
terribly nervous and afraid, but he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor assured Hause that once they opened him up, if he
needed the whole liver he would get it, and that Jazmyn could use
her other option, a piece of her father's liver. Her father, Isaac
Bordoy, had been tested and was at MGH, ready for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The father ``was an appropriate donor,'' said Dr. Ben Cosimi,
chief of the MGH transplant unit. ``We were about to do a living
donor transplant for her almost as an emergent procedure, when this
other opportunity'' came along.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to share the donor liver with Jazymn, Hause was
taking a risk with his own chances, noted Cosimi. ``The reason this
(split liver transplants) hasn't caught on more is that there is a
slightly increased risk'' of complications.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, recipients who get partial liver transplants in general
have a 5 percent less chance of success'' than those who get a full
liver, said Cosimi. ``We presented this honestly and he said,
`That's fine, if this can help the child'. . .it was almost like he
donated the organ to someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazmyn has already gone home. Hause hopes to go home soon. His
mother says simply, ``It makes us all feel good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
