u w BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS &LR;      03-09 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATE CONFIRMS TWO CALIFORNIA NOMINEES TO 9TH CIRCUIT COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a bitter debate, the Senate on Thursday
confirmed two controversial California nominees to the U.S. 9th
Circuit Court of Appeals, ending years of political wrangling over
their appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berzon, 54, a San Francisco lawyer, was approved by a
64-34 vote. Less than an hour later, the Senate confirmed U.S.
District Court Judge Richard A. Paez by a 59-39 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Paez's nomination had been stalled for four years, longer than
any other federal judicial nominee in modern history. Berzon was
nominated more than two years ago. The 9th circuit court covers
California and eight other Western states.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the long delays, Democrats had charged that the
Republicans were resisting nominations of women and minorities.
Paez is Mexican American.
</P>
<P>
   During the floor debate, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., called the votes on the two ``long overdue.'' He added, ``I
can't imagine how anybody could rationalize, could explain why we
would put any nominee through the anguish that these two have had
to endure.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the drama behind the final votes was played out behind
the scenes. Vice President Al Gore flew to Washington, cutting
short a Midwest campaign swing, after Daschle called him Wednesday
night saying that he, as president of the Senate, might be needed
to break a tie on Paez.
</P>
<P>
   The call came after Paez and Berzon supporters in the Senate
succeeded in halting a filibuster mounted by conservative
Republicans. At that point, Berzon was seen as easily winning
confirmation, but Paez, who had gained support from several GOP
senators, was still not a shoo-in. Chris Lehane, press secretary
for Gore's presidential campaign, quoted Daschle as saying he
``anticipated a very, very close vote'' on Paez.
</P>
<P>
   After the Thursday confirmations, Gore declared in Spanish,
``Friends, today we've finally achieved justice.'' He added, ``It
is inexcusable that the Republican Senate played politics with
these crucial nominations.
</P>
<P>
   `We've seen a troubling pattern of the Republican Party standing
against qualified judicial nominees who happen to be women and
minorities,'' he said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Paez, who was strongly supported by Hispanic groups, is a former
legal aid attorney and served as a Los Angeles Municipal Court
judge for 14 years before being named to the lower federal court in
1994. Berzon, an expert in labor law, has specialized in federal
appeals cases. She is a member of the board of the American Civil
Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also referred to the nominees' diverse
backgrounds in hailing the votes at the end of a White House
meeting with religious leaders: ``I think maybe we're, by fits and
starts, moving toward our one America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore urged the Senate to confirm more federal court
nominees. Gore said that an ``alarming'' number of vacancies are
causing problems in the nation's justice system. ``When it comes to
our judiciary, justice delayed is still justice denied,'' he
said.Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., hailed the confirmation votes as
a ``wonderful day for justice, even though we had a long, tortuous
path to this vote.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the two nominations were flashpoints of
controversy. Conservative Republicans argued that Paez and Berzon
were too liberal and would only add to an already liberal 9th
circuit court. Democrats countered that the two were mainstream
legal scholars and accused the GOP leadership of stalling the
nominations because of a bias against Hispanics and women.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's debate, both sides revisited those arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something wrong with this circuit,'' Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said. ``It's extremely liberal and it
will get worse with these two nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority leader also rejected the accusations that he and
other Senate Republicans were reluctant to confirm women and
minority nominees. ``This is politics at its most crass, and I hate
to see anybody inside or outside of Washington lower themselves to
that level,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Paez of being a judicial activist, Sen. Robert Smith,
R-N.H., said the judge ``feels free to say which laws he likes and
which laws he doesn't.'' Smith added: ``Judges are supposed to be
impartial. He goes over the line.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats noted that Paez has publicly stated he is against
any form of judicial activism. The Democrats also insisted that the
liberal tag has been unfairly applied to Paez, former head of the
Legal Aid Foundation, and Berzon, who has won major cases at the
Supreme Court. ``Both of these candidates have been endorsed by
numerous law enforcement groups,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif. ``How is that liberal?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the confirmation of Paez and Berzon, there are still 73
vacancies on federal courts. Republicans defended their attempt to
block the confirmations of Paez and Berzon, saying that,
historically, few judges are confirmed in the final year of a
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the People for the American Way, a liberal
advocacy group, the Senate has in fact confirmed substantial
numbers of judges at the end of previous administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four judges were confirmed in 1980, 44 in 1984, 42 in 1988
and 66 in 1992. So far, the Senate has confirmed seven judicial
nominees including Paez and Berzon this year. With their addition
to the 9th circuit court, that bench still has four vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
