<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      03-09 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Capturing Insanity
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Commuters on the FDR Drive on a recent weeknight may
have been startled to see a bright celestial apparition in place of
the narrow footbridge that connects Manhattan to Wards Island.
Magnificently lighted by the cinematographer Amy Vincent and her
crew, the bridge was being transformed into part of the dream world
of Romulus Ledbetter, a homeless schizophrenic known to his
acquaintances as the Caveman.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Caveman's Valentine,'' which is being produced by Danny
DeVito's Jersey Films for release next fall by Universal, the title
character is portrayed by Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Once a promising Juilliard-trained pianist, Romulus has suffered
a mental breakdown and abandoned his family to live in a cave in
Inwood Hill Park. Now a raving paranoid, he believes the world is
controlled by a mysterious being named Stuyvesant who lives at the
top of the Chrysler Building and enforces his will through an army
of faceless foot soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight,'' said the producer Stacey Sher, ``will be the big
No-Face shootout,'' the climactic confrontation that will pit
Romulus against the monsters who inhabit his hallucinations.
Shooting was scheduled to begin at sunset, and a crew was busily
covering a nearby playground with artificial snow, the unusually
warm New York weather having failed to provide the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of chicks around here,'' observed Sher, as she
watched Vincent set up her lighting in close consultation with the
film's director, Kasi Lemmons. This is the second collaboration
between Lemmons and Vincent, who worked together on Lemmons' first
film as a director, the acclaimed 1997 ``Eve's Bayou.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy and I are big believers in storyboards,'' Lemmons said.
``We draw the whole movie out, and it helps us to get things
organized in our heads. Then we tend to extrapolate from the
storyboards as we go along in the process. They give us a map that
we can deviate from.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons, 39, began her career as an actor, appearing most
notably as Jodie Foster's fellow FBI trainee in ``The Silence of
the Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were plenty of less satisfying work experiences. ``I
was fed up with the triviality of my acting career,'' she said.
``So I went and studied cinematography, and that kind of added to
my way of looking at things. Definitely the combination of acting
and writing and wanting to be a director of cinematography have
added to my approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmons shares credit for the screenplay of ``Caveman's
Valentine'' with George Dawes Green, author of the 1995 novel on
which the movie is based, and Scott Frank, whose work includes
``Get Shorty'' and ``Out of Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someplace between my reading George's draft and adding my
little input to it I began to visualize the film completely,'' said
Lemmons, who was then led off by an assistant to complete the
process. The camera turned, and words became images.
</P>
<P>
   Director's Jet Lag
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Nossiter is just back from the 50th Berlin
International Film Festival, and he isn't feeling so good. His new
film, ``Signs and Wonders,'' was drafted as the token independent
American film in the festival's competition section, where the
other contenders included ``The Beach,'' ``The Talented Mr.
Ripley'' and ``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two American critics bothered to see ``Signs and Wonders,''
and both hated it, calling it pretentious and anti-American. Their
reviews appeared in the trade publications Variety and The
Hollywood Reporter, and that won't help the film's chances of
receiving major theatrical distribution. ``They weren't just
negative,'' Nossiter said. ``They were apocalyptic.''
</P>
<P>
   But others have found ``Signs and Wonders'' to be a work of
great skill and resonance. Like Nossiter's previous feature, the
1997 Sundance winner ``Sunday,'' it is an intimate psychological
portrait of a middle-aged man in crisis. (Here, Stellan Skarsgard
plays an American businessman in Athens, Greece, who leaves his
loving wife, Charlotte Rampling, for a disastrous affair with a
co-worker, Deborah Kara Unger, and then clumsily attempts to
return.)
</P>
<P>
   And like ``Sunday,'' this film is an anomaly among indie
productions in that its characters are not instantly likable,
something that seems to have deeply offended the American
reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the film is going to divide people,'' said Nossiter
over coffee near his walk-up apartment in the Little Italy section
of New York. ``I'm surprised by that. You don't set out to make a
film to divide people, but to engage as many people as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stellan is one of the few actors willing to embrace a
peculiarly male monstrousness. I find him immensely sympathetic
precisely because of the vulnerability and the nakedness with which
he expresses a very male mania.''
</P>
<P>
   Nossiter, 38, spent his childhood in France, England, Italy,
Greece and India, and cultural displacement remains one of the
central themes of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signs and Wonders'' takes place in an Athens unrecognizable
from the tourist brochures _ a city of concrete, sharp angles and
looming billboards for American franchises. ``I knew I was in
trouble,'' Nossiter said, ``when the first question at the press
conference was `How much did McDonald's pay you for the product
placement?'''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he decided to shoot on video rather than film because
of ``the immediacy of the relationship between physical space and
human beings that video seems to provide,'' he said. He was also
able to take advantage of new digital techniques that allowed him
to alter the color and lighting of scenes already shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, the technology was available only to big-budget
special-effects films, but in the past few months these things have
become more accessible and infinitely cheaper,'' Nossiter said.
``It's an amazing freedom for the director that is completely new.
You can go back and readjust the look of the film to fit the
emotions. These are brand new tools, and I found them incredibly
exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Vive la Streep
</P>
<P>
   Last week Meryl Streep joined Beverly Sills, the photographer
Duane Michaels and the trumpeter Clark Terry in being inducted as
an ``officier'' of the French Order of Arts and Letters in a
ceremony with French officials in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I take a film to France,'' Streep said, ``I am
struck because the journalists that I speak to engage in the most
penetrating and infuriating and passionate and interesting
conversations about film, about acting, about the state of the
world as reflected in film culture. It's such a thrill, and it
reminds me of how we just don't look at it that way back home, in
the hurly-burly of marketing movies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
