<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-QUITS10-COX     03-09 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-QUITS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley acknowledges `closing of this chapter'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Having officially withdrawn from the
Democratic race and thrown his support to Vice President Al Gore,
Bill Bradley concluded his valedictory news conference Thursday
with a presentation to the national media.
</P>
<P>
   As his staff hummed an off-key rendition of ``Pomp and
Circumstance,'' the graduation march, Bradley called reporters,
producers and photographers to the podium to give each some parting
gifts _ ``two tokens of my respect,'' Bradley called them.
</P>
<P>
   The first gift was a silver Tiffany key chain with a small
basketball shoe, symbolic of Bradley's basketball playing days and
the long road he traveled to attempt the Democratic nomination. The
second was a small tin of Bradley's favorite throat lozenges, which
continually rattled in his mouth whenever he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley apologized that he didn't have gifts for everyone in the
room. ``But I wanted to make sure that we at least give a momento
for those who were here most often,'' he said, with wife Ernestine
at his side.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation was typical of Bradley, part ironic, part
genuine. It was a side to his personality that he displayed little
during his 14-month bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But as he saw the nomination slipping away in the campaign's
closing two weeks, Bradley allowed himself more of such moments. On
Thursday, the final day of what may be his only presidential
campaign, Bradley appeared very much at peace with himself, opening
his news conference with a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to begin this morning with a discussion of my favorite
books,'' he deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wasn't angry. He sounded at once philosophical and
realistic about his overwhelming defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, personally, today means the closing of this chapter,''
Bradley said. ``It is something I believe that I gave my full
heart, mind, soul and energy to. And it didn't turn out. As I said
the other night, you win and lose. This is a loss, and you move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley declined to engage in too much Monday morning
quarterbacking about how his once promising campaign came up so
short, but offered two explanations for his failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really get across the extent to which this wasn't
really a campaign of self-interest,'' Bradley said. People ``came
to support me ... because they truly believed in what we were
trying to do, in terms of the goodness of the American people, in
terms of the need for a new politics and in terms of the issues
that we thought illustrated the values I espoused. ... Maybe we
could have done a better job of getting across that aspect of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Sen. John McCain's withdrawal from the Republican
primary, Bradley said his loss also demonstrated the long odds
challengers face against incum- bents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how difficult it is to run against entrenched power
in this country,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley pledged to work for Gore, although it is unclear how
much the vice president will use Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning, Bradley stood by his contention that Gore had
misrepresented his record and said he hoped Gore would ``run a
better campaign in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also said that he would continue to speak candidly about
Gore's involvement in the 1996 fund-raising scandals. He repeated
his assertion that Gore needs to explain more about his role in a
controversial fund-raising luncheon at a Buddhist temple in
California. But he softened his rhetoric somewhat, saying Gore's
recent acknowledgement that he made a mistake was promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to do that more,'' Bradley said. ``And I do think
that he needs to remove that issue by opening up on what happened
in 1996. I haven't changed my view on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gore said, Bradley is ``a good man whom I
respect greatly'' and commended him ``for running a good campaign
based on the highest ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his good-byes at a catering hall a short distance
from his campaign headquarters. A hundred or so of his staff
attended, cheering Bradley after his opening remarks, and jeering
when a member of the press asked if Bradley would consider being
Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be a candidate for vice president,'' Bradley said,
as his staff erupted in applause.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he planned to take a vacation with his wife before
returning to ``work hard'' for Gore and other Democratic candidates
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, no one, not even his closest advisers, could say
for sure what is ahead for the 56-year-old former New Jersey
senator. ``He obviously is going to continue to be active on the
issues he cares about,'' said Anita Dunn, his communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
