<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rust shows, but Avery's debut `pretty good'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Steve Avery was a little preoccupied Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it might have been weird to be back on the mound in a
Braves uniform for the first time since 1996, but for him it was
weird to be back on the mound, period. Coming off the first arm
surgery of his life in August when he had an arthroscopic procedure
on his shoulder, Avery said he felt bizarre but good.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched a scoreless fourth inning in the Braves' 8-7
exhibition win over the Los Angeles Dodgers and reported no pain
afterward. It was a positive first step in Avery's bid to return to
the Braves' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's news that John Smoltz is out for the season
with a torn elbow ligament, Terry Mulholland and Bruce Chen are
slated to be the fourth and fifth starters, but Avery's lurking as
a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky to be here. I guess they're going to give me every
opportunity to try to get healthy and help this team,'' Avery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see myself in there somewhere down the road, I'm just
not sure when. ...When I can get out there and start throwing four,
five, six innings and not get tired, not feel the pain, then I know
I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery's only complaint Thursday was feeling out-of-kilter
mechanically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty good,'' he said. ``I felt like I hadn't been
there in about seven and a half months. Little rusty. It was
pain-free. I got three outs so it was good. But then again, it's a
long way from where I want to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a leadoff walk to Kevin Elster, Avery cruised through
his inning by getting a pop-up from Gary Sheffield, a flyout to
center by Shawn Green and a groundout by Kevin Orie. He threw 20
pitches, 11 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good for his first time out,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox said. ``(His mechanics may be off) until he gets out there
more, but I was satisfied with what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery threw predominantly change-ups and fastballs with one
curveball mixed in. He would have preferred to throw nothing but
fastballs to work out his kinks but needed to mix it up to get
outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do a couple things different to try to throw harder,''
Avery said. ``You're not supposed to, but that's the way sometimes
you do it when you haven't been out there very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
