<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-MARS10-COX     03-09 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MARS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visually stunning `Mission' a space odyssey fit for 2001
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It is almost 2001, so perhaps it is time
for a new ``Space Odyssey.'' Director Brian De Palma, who built a
career on homages to Alfred Hitchcock, has shifted toborrowing from
Stanley Kubrick. But just because his foray into science fiction,
``Mission to Mars,'' lacks originality does not mean it is without
merit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, see if this sounds familiar: A team of astronauts embarks
on a lengthy space voyage, runs into mechanical difficulties that
require exterior repairs, aided by the voice of the ship's
omniscient computer.
</P>
<P>
   The space jockeys reach their destination and make discoveries
that imply the existence of a higher intelligence that inspired
life on Earth. They solve a puzzle posed by the otherworldly
beings, and then one of the astronauts opts for a rebirth that will
presumably begin the life cycle again. Details vary, but in its
overall story arc, the resemblance of ``Mission to Mars to 2001: A
Space Odyssey'' is unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, ``Mission'' is stunning. The depiction of
weightlessness, whether dancing bodies, floating blood pellets or
helixes of M&AMP;Ms, is as convincing as ever captured on film. The
rocky terrain of Mars _ as played by the outskirts of Vancouver,
British Columbia _ is both beautiful and forbidding. And when the
land suddenly becomes animate and transforms itself into a
mysterious facial totem, the effect is truly awesome.
</P>
<P>
   If only there weren't so much cliched dialogue and so many
bone-headed actions by these highly trained, best-and-brightest
astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Jim Thomas, John Thomas and Graham Yost leans
to fevered exchanges like: ``Jim, are you sure you want to do
this?'' ``I'm not sure about anything anymore.'' When the
Mars-bound, rescue-mission spaceship springs a couple of air leaks
and begins losing cabin pressure, heroic, brooding Jim McConnell
(Gary Sinise) doesn't bother to put on his helmet. This presumably
is for dramatic effect, so that he can almost expire from lack of
oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   When Woody Blake (Tim Robbins) becomes adrift in space _ as
someone always does in these movies _ and his crew member wife,
Terri (Connie Nielsen), goes to save him, you can bet that common
sense will give way to emotions. And just in case you do not know
how to react, there is Ennio Morricone's heavy-handed and celestial
music score to guide the way.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite these wince points, there is an intelligence at work
in ``Mission to Mars,'' and not just from the Martians. Like
``2001,'' the time spent aboard ship is steeped in the mission
minutia and hardware of science fact, all the better to persuade us
of what the team finds on Mars. And who would not want to believe
that there is intelligent life out there, willing to make contact,
to connect with mere humans and share the secrets of the universe?
</P>
<P>
   As in most space flicks, the muted acting takes a backseat to
the special effects. This is the inevitable consequence of
performing while encased in a thermal suit and space helmet. The
``Mars'' cast does well enough in a low-key way, even when they
have an extraterrestrial encounter.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the first of this year's interplanetary movies to
land, with ``Red Planet,'' ``Titan A.E.'' and ``Battlefield Earth''
still to come. Those with no interest in what could be lurking
beyond our world may be excused from attendance. Those who are
drawn to the ride, and do not mind an experience more geared to
wonder than terror, will find it in ``Mission to Mars.'' Plus, the
movie should do great things for M&AMP;M sales.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
