<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-RECORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH STOCKS PROPEL NASDAQ INDEX TO 5000-PLUS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq stock index closed above 5000 Thursday for the first
time as speculators chasing profits in technology stocks drove the
index to a summit two times higher than it was seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The high-flying Nasdaq added 154.20 points, a 3 percent gain, to
close at 5046.86. The Blue Chips of the technology industry drove
the Nasdaq to its new high, causing a 4000-point record, achieved
just 10 weeks ago, to recede in the market's rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's remarkable performance, looked at another way, has
caused a doubling in its value since Aug. 10, a phenomenon that
seasoned investment professionals said they had never before
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is the individual is leading this
market,'' said Chris Bertelsen, portfolio manager for Phoenix
Investment Partners. ``Speculation is certainly part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, hammered Tuesday as investors
fled old-line companies for tech stocks, was lifted out of an
early-day decline Thursday by strong performance in companies such
as Hewlett-Packard Co. The computer hardware maker, which traded
below $70 a share four months ago, closed Thursday at $151.875, up
$11 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Thursday closed at 10,010.73, up 154.20 points, or 1.5
percent, though the major market index is still down 13 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But attention was riveted to the Nasdaq, which has gained 24
percent this year. The Nasdaq has seen a flood of new money into
technology stocks from individual investors, both day traders and
mutual fund investors, and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisers, a division of State Street Corp., said that $97 billion
went into aggressive growth and technology-oriented stock funds
during 1999. This year alone $65 billion has already flowed into
those funds.
</P>
<P>
   By another estimate, $700 million was funneled into eight
technology and computer funds in the first five days of March,
according to California-based TrimTabs.com Investment Research Inc.
That amounted to half of the inflows into those same funds for the
entire month of February.
</P>
<P>
   A building wave of money into technology has caused the index's
performance to accelerate. It took 24 years for the once-novel
Nasdaq to top 1000 and three years more to get to 2000. Climbing to
3000 took 15 months, and 4000 only two additional months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly being driven by the Internet phenomenon,'' said
Riley. ``Whether it's PCs or semiconducutors or software companies,
their growth rates (are) projected in the future to be far suprior
to growth rates the Old Economy stocks might be offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley and others said institutional investors, under pressure to
turn in a good performance, are beginning to take note and put more
money into the technology sector, too. ``People are really caught
in the lemming syndrome right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, a note of defensiveness could be detected even in the
Nasdaq's rise. Some of the biggest gains posted by technology
stocks Thursday were large companies: Cisco Systems Inc., up
$6.9375 to $139.3125.; American Online Inc., up $6.125 to 61;
Microsoft Corp., up $4.4375 to $100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are viewed as a safer bet than, say, a start-up
that recently went public. However, some smaller companies also
soared. Network Solutions Inc. and I2 Technologies Inc. were among
10 members of the Nasdaq 100 Index to rise more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investor has been used to very high returns, and they want
to continue getting those high returns _ and they're certainly not
getting them in the traditional funds,'' said Robert Freedman,
executive vice president of John Hancock Funds, explaining the
stampede to technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bubbly enthusiasm, investment experts said there is no
evidence the momentum of the Nasdaq index is losing steam. Two
separate warnings this week by Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan did little to dampen investors' enthusiasm for tech
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Four stocks rose for every three that fell on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The technology index trades for 56 times estimated earnings,
compared with 23 times profit for the consumer staples index and 24
times for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. The S&AMP;P index gained 34.99
points Thursday, closing at 1401.69.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it's probably going to go higher,'' said Marshall
Acuff, equity strategist for Salomon Smith Barney. ``I'm not one to
argue with momentum at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dow was dragged down in early trading Thursday by
its line-up of industrial and financial stocks, which have been
hurt by rising interest rates and the prospect they would go
higher. Fed policymakers next meet on March 21. Some Dow average
stocks fell, including International Paper Co., and Minnesota
Mining &AMP; Manufacturing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are fearful that rate increases will hurt''
industrial, consumer and financial companies, said Jim Awad,
chairman of Awad Asset Management Inc., which oversees $1 billion
in investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
