<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NASDAQ-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      03-09 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE VOLATILE NASDAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also VALUATION-NORRIS-COLUMN, MARKET) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seldom has an index risen as rapidly as the Nasdaq
composite has in leaping above the 5,000 mark, a hurdle it
surmounted Thursday little more than four months after it first
pushed past 3,000. Virtually never has an index done so with such
huge volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index gained 146.69 points, or 3.1 percent,
to 5,046.86 Thursday after having first traded over the mark on
Tuesday, only to fall below 4,750 during trading Wednesday before
it again began climbing.
</P>
<P>
   The move has been largely concentrated in only a handful of
sectors within the market _ biotechnology, computer technology and
telecommunications. Other sectors have generally lost value during
the period, as the decision of the Federal Reserve Board to push up
interest rates has taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Indexes of stocks that are not so concentrated in technology
have done much worse. While the Nasdaq composite is up 67 percent
since Nov. 3, 1999, the day it first closed over 3,000, the Dow
Jones industrial average is down 6 percent over the same period,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks has risen just 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While most stocks were falling, the enthusiasm for the ``new
economy,'' dominated by the Internet, has only increased among
investors in recent months. And the performance of those stocks has
not matched that of biotechnology issues, which have nothing to do
with the Internet but which have suddenly come alive in their
strongest performance since 1992, when biotechnology stocks
dominated market speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has made it clear that he
expects to keep raising interest rates until the economy slows, and
he has forecast that the stock market's surge will slow or reverse,
thus dampening the wealth effect that has spurred consumer
spending.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Boston on Monday, Greenspan said the market was
``groping for the appropriate valuation of these companies'' and
noted that ``many analysts are now projecting that the rate of
increase in stock market wealth may soon begin to slow.'' In fact,
that has happened for most stocks, but the speculative fervor in
favored stocks has continued unabated, and margin debt _ the money
borrowed to buy stocks _ has begun to rise sharply.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of shares that are rising has narrowed, pressure
has grown on money managers to buy the stocks that are working and
to shun the stocks that are not. That pressure has been intensified
by mutual fund investors, who have pulled money out of many funds
that have been poor performers while pouring cash into funds that
have been rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, valuation measures are being thrown out the
window,'' said Phillip Coburn, a strategist at Warburg Dillon Read.
He said that the average price of technology stocks, using a
measure that compares price-earnings multiples with earnings growth
rates, is now twice what investors deemed reasonable only a couple
of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said, money managers are only being prudent when
they load up on technology stocks. ``Given the fact that I don't
see the end in sight, I don't think they are being foolish,'' he
said. ``They are being practical, and they are making money for
their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   As the market has narrowed, even some of the large technology
stocks that had been market leaders have begun to falter. Qualcomm,
Dell Computer and Microsoft, all stars last year, are down in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses have been made up for by many other stocks,
however. ``We've had this change to lower-quality growth,'' said
Robert Farrell, a senior investment adviser at Merrill Lynch. ``We
do have a hierarchy of big tech stocks,'' he added, ``but big tech
is giving way to smaller tech, to anything that has a good story.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners, the Nasdaq computer index is up 26 percent
and the Nasdaq telecommunications index has risen 19 percent since
the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But those gains have paled next to those of the Nasdaq biotech
index, which has risen 63 percent this year and has leaped 144
percent since last Nov. 3, the day the Nasdaq composite first
topped 3,000. That is more than double the impressive move of the
overall Nasdaq index.
</P>
<P>
   But this week the Nasdaq biotech index has fallen 10 percent,
without much in the way of news to explain the action. But then,
there was not that much news to explain the increase, other than
growing investor enthusiasm for the potential profits from new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That volatility has beset the overall Nasdaq market as well. One
way to measure such volatility is to look at the number of days
when the Nasdaq index has closed with a gain or loss of at least 3
percent from the prior day, as it did Thursday. So far this year
there have been 12 such days _ six up and six down, an average of
more than one a week.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, during the eight years from 1988 through 1995,
there were 10 such days, an average of slightly more than one a
year. Even last year, when Nasdaq's volatility was greater than at
any time in the past, there were just 20 such days, an average of
fewer than two a month.
</P>
<P>
   That volatility has reflected the different forces competing for
investor attention. Some days the hopes for exciting new
technologies drive prices up. But on other days most Nasdaq stocks
succumb to the same concerns, often about higher interest rates,
that have bedeviled many other stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The real losers have been stocks that are vulnerable to higher
interest rates but have no competing technological allure. So far
this year, the Nasdaq bank index is down 19 percent and the Nasdaq
insurance index has lost 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Data from AMG Data Services, which tracks mutual fund cash
flows, shows that through March 8 funds specializing in the hot
areas _ aggressive growth, technology, small cap and biotech _ had
garnered 76 percent of the $93 billion investors have put into
stock funds. At that rate, said Robert Adler, the president of AMG,
the annual record for stock fund inflows will be broken by the end
of this month. In 1999, those hot sectors took in 41 percent of the
money invested in stock funds, up from 10 percent in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The massive inflows into the mutual funds are going into a
narrow group of funds,'' said L. Keith Mullins, who specializes in
small stocks as an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``Clearly,
money is chasing performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
