<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VALUATION-NORRIS-COLU     03-09 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUATION-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE NEWS TURNS BAD, VALUATION SUDDENLY MATTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Value is scorned and ignored. Money managers who pay attention
to the traditional measures of valuation post horrible results and
see customers flee.
</P>
<P>
   But even as value is disdained by the multitude, the seeds of
its revival are being sown. This week's debacle in Procter &AMP;
Gamble, in which a moderate profit shortfall caused the maker of
Tide and Crest to shed $40 billion in market value, may be a
precursor of what will happen as other beloved stocks fall by the
wayside.
</P>
<P>
   That is not, it must be acknowledged, how a lot of people see
it. James J. Cramer, the money manager and market commentator who
is in the majority of investors who now treasure high-flying
technology stocks, sounded gleeful: ``If there is more risk in P&AMP;G
than Broadcom or Brocade but much less reward, which are you going
to be in?'' he asked rhetorically in his column on TheStreet.com.
``All of that price-to-earnings flotsam and
discount-to-normalized-earnings jetsam didn't save you today.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom and Brocade, both in the computer business, are among
the stars of the two-year boom in new offerings. They trade at more
than 300 times projected profits and at more than 30 times their
original offering prices. Anyone who worried about valuation missed
that phenomenal performance.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson that many people have taken from such stock moves is
that the old valuation measures are irrelevant. Until a few years
ago, measuring stock prices as multiples of such factors as
earnings, revenue and book value was generally accepted. Even
growth-stock investors used measures that related growth rates to
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But as share prices rose and went through traditional limits,
those who ignored the old rules profited. No new valuation concepts
arose, so what matters now is whether people are disappointed.
Stocks soar on good news, no matter how expensive they already are.
``We no longer have touchstones, because we no longer think we know
how to value companies,'' said Robert Barbera, the chief economist
of Hoenig &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the process has accelerated. Money managers
who care about value have done badly and lost customers to managers
that buy the Broadcoms and Brocades of the world, whatever their
price.
</P>
<P>
   But even as less money has been invested by those relying on the
old notions of value, the potential importance of those concepts
may be rising. P&AMP;G had until recently been one of the favored
stocks, a big company that benefited from strong brands and the
flood of money that went into index funds tracking the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, its price-to-earnings multiple gradually expanded
until it stood at 37 at the end of 1999. Contrary to what Cramer
seems to think, it was not believers in ``price-to-earnings
flotsam'' who paid such prices.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bad news. The company disclosed that profits would
be down about 10 percent this quarter. It had not prepared analysts
for that, and suddenly a lot of shareholders wanted out. They
yelled ``sell'' all at once.
</P>
<P>
   But who would buy? The answer was that some who cared about
value were willing to step in _ once P&AMP;G fell to a multiple that
seemed reasonable under the old rules. It now trades for about 19
times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G may be prologue for many companies. Those that disappoint
will fall until they look cheap _ based on old-fashioned valuation
measures _ to the dwindling band of investors not playing the
momentum game. Then value will matter, even to those who now
disdain such ``jetsam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
