<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN10-COX     03-09 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain suspends his campaign bid
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ John McCain ended his presidential campaign
Thursday, conceding that rival George W. Bush has effectively
locked up the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Red rock mountains tinged with snow provided a spectacular
backdrop as the Arizona senator announced he is suspending his
campaign for the White House, but not formally withdrawing from the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of Republican voters made clear that their
preference for president is Governor Bush. I respect their
decision,'' McCain said. ``Therefore, I announce today ... that I
am no longer an active candidate for my party's nomination for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain pointedly offered Bush his ``best wishes'' but not his
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before McCain bowed out, Bill Bradley quit the race for
the Democratic nomination and said he will support Vice President
Al Gore because ``it is time for unity'' to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator telephoned Gore to pledge support.
But at a news conference in West Orange, N.J., Bradley said he will
not release his delegates, saying they had earned a voice at the
Democratic National Convention. He had 412 _ more than 1,000 behind
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's decision to suspend his campaign rather than withdraw
may allow him to collect his full allotment of federal campaign
funds, including convention expenses. It also gives himleverage in
his battle to ensure that the GOP heeds his twin campaign themes of
campaign finance reform and inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also retained control of his 231 delegates, a fraction of
the 1,034 needed for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides did not read much into the distinction between
withdrawing and suspending the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got out of the race today by any stretch of the
explanation,'' said Howard Opinsky, McCain's campaign press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, with his wife Cindy beside him, had few warm words for
Bush. The Republican primary fight bruised feelings in both camps
and left McCain unable to say that Bush had run an honorable
campaign when he was asked about it last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Colorado, congratulated his former rival
``for fighting the good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor said he had ``a very short'' telephone
conversation with McCain, but didn't ask for his endorsement. ``I
intend to talk with him at his convenience,'' Bush told reporters.
``There needs to be some time to settle out. John needed some time
to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to McCain said they are waiting to see how far Bush is
willing to go to adopt some of their candidate's views and to heal
any wounds.
</P>
<P>
   McCain referred to himself as a loyal Republican, seemingly
closing the door on a third-party run for the presidency. ``I love
my party. It is my home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he told supporters to continue the fight for reform, and
said he would join them. ``I will never walk away from a fight for
what I know is right and just for our country,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator wore the same ``lucky'' thick-soled shoes that he
first put on in New Hampshire, then continued to wear after he won
the primary there.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke for seven minutes and did not take questions, a rare
one-sided encounter with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sparked more enthusiasm and won more votes than anyone
could have imagined when he started his campaign 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a startlingly large victory in New Hampshire, he
captured seven primaries and posed a serious obstacle to Bush's
march to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain never connected with Republican voters in the same
way he drew Democrats and independents. Bush began to pile up
primary victories by attracting enough votes from Republicans to
withstand crossover votes for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   After winning nine of 13 state contests Tuesday, Bush had
amassed enough convention delegates to show that he could not be
stopped. He may clinch the nomination by Tuesday, when Texas and
five other Southern states hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain met Wednesday with family members, senior aides and major
financial backers at his vacation home here in northern Arizona.
They quickly concluded that continuing the campaign would be futile
and might damage the public's perception of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knew precisely what he wanted to do,'' said John
Raidt, a longtime aide to the senator.
</P>
<P>
   McCain scrapped his campaign schedule that was to have taken him
to Colorado and Illinois on Thursday and today.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the discussion focused on how best to make sure his
message continues to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for McCain's supporters has already begun. Both Bush
and Gore have made appeals to independent voters who flocked to
McCain in state after state.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain voters could well determine the outcome of this
election,'' Raidt said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
