u i BC-CHILE-TENSIONS-BOS &LR;      03-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-TENSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RETURN OF PINOCHET, TENSIONS GROW IN CHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Twenty-seven years ago, it was an unusual mix
of characters that led to this country's darkest and most violent
moment: A newly elected socialist president, an omnipotent general
and a powerful, disciplined army in a conservative but divided
South American nation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Chile is nervously facing a similar set of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Lagos will be sworn in Saturday as the country's first
socialist president since 1973. General Augusto Pinochet, the
iron-fisted leader who overthrew the last socialist leader,
Salvador Allende, came home last week to a hero's welcome after 16
months of house arrest in London for human rights violations. And
the military, still loyal to its beloved general, has defiantly
backed away from attempts to find the remains of victims killed
during Pinochet's dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, almost no one in Chile expects another coup d'etat,
largely because of the catastrophic effects it would have on the
economy and international relations, and because of the confidence
Chileans have in their young democracy. But there is an uncertainty
hanging over this arid and mountainous land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Hollywood sequel in a way,'' said Nicolas Lozano,
a 26-year-old poet. ``Only this time the ending would be different.
I think there will be some nervousness, but mostly peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the unease felt here is not so much about the
84-year-old Pinochet, who doctors have portrayed as physically and
mentally weak and who still faces 65 lawsuits at home from the
deaths and disappearances of foes during his dictatorship. Nor is
it about Lagos, who despite his socialist label has offered mostly
centrist economic and social policy ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The questions largely surround the army, which controlled nearly
every major office during Pinochet's rule, including the ``death
caravans'' that hunted down his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions arose last week, when the retired general returned
home. When Pinochet's plane _ a military jet that had been
especially equipped for him _ touched down, a contingent of
decorated officers, an army band and a group of close friends and
family offered him a brief welcoming reception on the tarmac. The
first person to embrace Pinochet as he rose from his wheelchair was
Army Chief General Ricardo Izurieta.
</P>
<P>
   The reception and heavy security given the former dictator was
immediately denounced by the government as an act of defiance
because of Pinochet's legal troubles. An appellate judge earlier
this week recommended that Pinochet's parliamentary immunity be
revoked so that he could stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials, however, saw the homecoming as ``a modest
act'' for a historic figure unjustly held in a foreign land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an official ceremony and it was never meant to be
one,'' said army spokesman Hermez Lopez. ``(Pinochet) has been
threatened many times so the security was necessary for his own
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, much of the anger expressed by anti-Pinochet
protesters this week has been also aimed at the armed forces. When
3,000 demonstrators marched along a downtown Santiago avenue on
Saturday demanding Pinochet be brought to trial, the throng stopped
outside the army's headquarters and pelted bottles, rocks and
stones at the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinochet should be held responsible for what he did,'' said
one marcher, community activist Edmundo Borrego. ``But we shouldn't
ignore the role of the entire military, because they were the ones
who carried out his orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists have also blamed military leaders for
stalling the work of a government-sponsored committee that has
asked military cooperation in investigating the disappearances of
hundreds of people during the dicatatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials were implicated Thursday in a story published
in the Argentine newspaper Clarin, which reported that the officers
had secretly masterminded a legal defense strategy for Pinochet
that was based on pressuring judges not to remove the former
strongman's immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy, officers in all three armed forces
branches have insisted that today's military is different from the
one nearly three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Recognized by analysts as the most disciplined force in Latin
America, Chile's 51,000-member army has been under a modernization
plan during the last several years, upgrading everything from its
management and training to its hardware, including the possible
purchase of US-made F-16 fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a force that has tried to change as Chile has become
more modern,'' said Tom Cardamone, editor of the Washington-based
Arms Trade News. ``It has less domestic political influence since
the Pinochet era, but clear-cut civilian control is not there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Pinochet, whose 17-year dictatorship was known mostly for
its brutality and firm imposition of a free-market economy, the
military flourished with funds and power. Military rule ended in
1990, when Chile returned to civilian government.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some military experts say, the main issue for Chile's
armed forces is money. The army, navy and air force depend on
government allocations to pay its payroll, which has remained
relatively stable, but use a portion of revenues from Chile's state
copper mining company for equipment purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main issues that will most influence the
relationship between the new president and the military will be
money, for higher wages and better housing,'' said Armen
Kouyoumdjian, a Chilean military analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers and even some military officials predicted
Pinochet's legal fortunes may affect the relationship between
Chile's armed forces and the new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, (Pinochet) is still our hero and symbol,'' one army
soldier in Santiago, who refused to give his name, said earlier
this week. ``If he goes down, then others will follow, and no one
here wants to see that happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
