<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LONDON-MAYOR-875(2TAK     03-09 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-MAYOR-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR BARRED THE DOOR; RED KEN STORMS THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ken Livingstone is the ghost of Labor past, an
unsettling reminder to Prime Minister Tony Blair of the antic
politics, overheated oratory and excessive promises that the
British leader believes made the party he pointedly now calls New
Labor unelectable for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   With Livingstone's declaration this week that he will be an
independent candidate opposing the official Labor choice for the
first elected mayor for London, the disruptive specter once known
as ``Red Ken'' has returned, posing nightmarish problems for a
government with a horror of reliving its party's quarrelsome
history, little tolerance for defiance from within, and no talent
at admitting mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an energetic effort by the Blair government to discredit
him _ or more likely because of it _ Livingstone, 54, already looks
to be a winner in the May 4 election. A poll published in The
Guardian shows him with 68 percent support to only 13 percent for
the Labor candidate, Blair's former health secretary, Frank Dobson,
59. Steven Norris, 54, the Conservative, was at 11 percent and
Susan Kramer, 49, the Liberal Democrat, at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the London mayor's powers are limited, the office will
have a larger popular mandate than any other in British public life
and comes with Livingstone's favored piece of furniture: a soapbox.
Armed with a tart tongue, a passion for power and a gleeful
eagerness to stick his finger in the eye of authority, he looms as
the first opposition to Labor of any concern since the party turned
the Conservatives out of power in the electoral rout of May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His appeal to a majority of London's 5 million voters seems at
the moment to be entirely a personal one. Issues have not come up.
His initial success is evidence that ideology and party political
control, while they may matter in national contests, do not count
for much in local elections like this, the first of its kind in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   London had a limited form of local government until 1986, when
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher abolished the Greater London
Council, then headed by Livingstone, and turned the running of the
city over to the national government. The unrelated position of
lord mayor, dating from 1215, is an appointive office filled by a a
business leader to oversee the City of London financial center for
a year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The raffish Livingstone mixture of cheek and brash
self-confidence that has alienated the Blair people has proved to
be the principal attraction to Londoners. Blair's overall
leadership is not threatened; he still has his sizable majority in
Parliament, the Conservative opposition is feckless, and there is
little doubt that he will get a second term in the next national
election, expected in the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Though Blair remains the most popular prime minister in British
history, polling has shown that even his supporters fault him for
his iron command of his party. Standing up to that authority has
been what has enhanced Livingstone with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The savvy political operatives around Blair lost their touch
when it came to trying to halt Livingstone. Efforts by 10 Downing
St. to demonize him backfired. Blair from the outset has called the
prospect of Livingstone in office a ``disaster,'' and the party
devised a serpentine electoral college selection process to keep
him off the ballot. It allowed Dobson to emerge as the approved
candidate even though Livingstone got more votes, a result that was
greeted with ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's attempts to manipulate the rules of the political game
were so obvious that even the House of Lords was able to posture as
a champion of unfettered elections, forcing the government this
week to agree to finance the cost of mailing campaign literature
from all candidates to every voter.
</P>
<P>
   The perception of being bullied by Labor headquarters gave
Livingstone his chance to explain away his decision to break with
the party despite repeated pledges in recent months that he would
not. ``I offer no weasel words of equivocation, and I apologize,''
he said. ``But what I do not intend to do is take any lectures from
those who have set new standards in ballot rigging.''
</P>
<P>
   Stealing Blair's favorite possessive, he proclaimed his effort a
``people's campaign'' and appealed for donations to increase his
war chest from its current $32,000 to the $800,000 total he said
other parties would be spending.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his bent for opportunism, he staged the
announcement of his rebellion on Monday just hours before the
campaign of Dobson was being officially launched.
</P>
<P>
   It was Blair's proposal, made early in his administration, for
creating an elected mayor for London that gave Livingstone his
opportunity for political resurrection. Livingstone had had such a
big impact on British politics in the early 1980s that he was
almost as well known as Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Ousted by her action of shutting down the Greater London
Council, he became a member of Parliament in 1987 and sank from
view. ``It's the GLC everyone remembers,'' he said ruefully in
1988. ``You had a billion a year to spend and you made a lot of
news. Now I am just one of 650-odd MPs, with no power. All I can do
is talk.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not only did no one listen but his Labor colleagues shunned him
as the party shed its radical socialist and union past and moved to
the political center to win over the voters of middle England who
had kept the Conservatives in office for 18 straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone's arrival on the scene in 1981 was a
characteristically blustery one. Within hours of being elected to
the council, he staged a spectacular and ruthless coup, ousting the
longtime leader and taking over the post himself in the name of
populist politics.
</P>
<P>
   He attracted public attention by cutting fares on buses and
subways by a third, supporting minority rights, embracing the Irish
republican movement, supporting a ``Babies Against the Bomb''
program to build day-care centers for the children of peace
protesters, and calling for the party to resist Thatcher by
proclaiming its dedication to socialism.
</P>
<P>
   He hung out a huge banner listing unemployment figures across
the facade of the grand Edwardian county building that sits across
the Thames from Parliament, and he flew red flags from its roof. As
Britain moved to the right under Thatcher, the Labor militants
became known as the ``Loony Left,'' with Livingstone at once their
court jester and their king.
</P>
<P>
   His flamboyantly insurgent posture cost him his job then, and a
repetition could cause him problems if he gets into office now.
Though the new mayor will manage a budget of $5 billion, almost all
of it comes from the national treasury, now in the tight fists of a
sworn enemy, Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone can also expect little support among the 25 members
of the new Greater London Assembly, who have the power to
substitute their own budget for his and will be following the lead
of party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, the problem is perceived to be Blair's.
A front-page cartoon in The Times of London showed the four
candidates taking their marks for the beginning of the race. The
starter's pistol was in the prime minister's hand. He was aiming it
at his own foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
