<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina setting for Roberts' latest romance
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Romance novels have changed since Nora Roberts began writing two
decades ago, but love hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rush you have when you fall in love, and all the emotions,
are universal and a constant,'' says Roberts, 49, who has published
134 novels and sold more than 106 million books.
</P>
<P>
   It's the romance genre that's different. Half-naked pirates
still rip the bodices of their beautiful captives, but not as
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started writing in 1979,'' Roberts says, ``the heroine
was 18 and a virgin, and the hero was a great deal older and the
richest man in the free world. These days, they're more likely to
be closer in age and partners. The man doesn't have to ride in on a
white charger and rescue her.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' latest best seller, ``Carolina Moon'' (Putnam, $24.95),
mixes romance with mystery as a woman returns to her hometown in
South Carolina to solve the murder of a childhood friend. In the
midst of searching for the killer, she falls in love with a wealthy
cotton farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts says she chose South Carolina because she was looking
for a place with marshes and cotton farms. ``South Carolina fit the
bill. I've been there a few times, but I did most of my research on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything Roberts writes becomes a best seller, but that
wasn't the case when she began. Stuck at her Maryland home during a
blizzard in 1979, Roberts wrote her first romance out of boredom.
That novel and her next six efforts were rejected before ``Irish
Thoroughbred'' was published in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The prolific Roberts writes _ and sells _ as many as six novels
a year. ``I'm driven to tell stories,'' she says. ``And it's
something I love. I wouldn't do it if it weren't fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts will sign books at 7 tonight at Waldenbooks at North
Point Mall in Alpharetta. 770-740-
</P>
<P>
   8341.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Short-listed: Four American authors are among the seven
finalists for the world's richest literary prize. Toni Morrison
(``Paradise''), Michael Cunningham (``The Hours''), Alice McDermott
(``Charming Billy'') and Philip Roth (``I Married a Communist'')
all made the cut from an original list of 101 nominees for the
$130,000 International IMPAC Dublin Literary Award. Other finalists
are English writer Nicola Barker (``Wide Open''), Scottish author
Jackie Kay (``The Trumpet'') and Irish writer Colum McCann (``This
Side of Brightness''). The winner will be announced May 9 in Dublin
Castle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Prose that pays: Some authors' books are not only
page-turners, but also dollar-earners. The richest writers and
their annual earnings, according to Forbes magazine, are Tom Clancy
($66 million), Stephen King ($65 million), John Grisham ($36
million), Dean Koontz ($34 million) and Michael Crichton ($33.5
million). Crichton's earnings have dropped, Forbes notes, because
he has made a deal to take lower film advances in favor of bigger
back-end deals. Universal recently bought the movie rights to
``Timeline'' for $1, but agreed to pay Crichton 15 percent of the
gross.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary portraits: The Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum has
gathered most of the major Southern writers under one roof. Well,
their portraits anyway. Images of Pat Conroy, Patricia Cornwell,
Anne Rivers Siddons, James Dickey, Anne Rice, William Styron,
Shelby Foote and others from David Spielman's book, ``Southern
Writers,'' are spotlighted in an exhibit through the end of June.
To see and hear one of the writers in the flesh, however, stop by
the Margaret Mitchell House, 999 Peachtree St., at 8 tonight for a
reading by Atlanta playwright and novelist Jim Grimsley.
Information: 404-249-7015.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
