<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-ART10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American art gets second look
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winslow Homer is one of America's most revered
artists, but his work is as scarce as trolley cars in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   For the next month, however, viewers have the opportunity to see
the scope of his achievement in ``Winslow Homer: Facing Nature,''
his first major Georgia one-man show, brought to town by the
Marietta/Cobb Museum of Art in Georgia. Organized by the Portland
Museum of Art in Maine, the exhibition spans Homer's long,
productive career, from his Harper's Weekly illustrations of the
Civil War to his idyllic watercolors of the Adirondack Mountains
and the paintings inspired by observations of life in Prouts Neck,
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not the only first. Brenau University in Gainesville
is bringing the sculpture of Marisol to Georgia for her first solo
show in the state. The only woman commonly associated with the pop
art movement, the Venezuela-born artist traveled her own path, with
her singular portraits carved into and out of chunky blocks of
wood. The sweep of Marisol's subject matter is apparent in this
show, whose subjects, all from the 1990s, range from a famous
Indian chief to President Kennedy's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Add the John Henry Twachtman exhibition at the High Museum of
Art to the list of uncommon displays. The High, which owns two
works by the late-19th-century artist, has organized the touring
show ``John Henry Twachtman: An American Impressionist.'' The first
such retrospective in this generation, it reveals an artist who,
though influenced by French impressionism, followed his own,
American course. The High provides a context for his explorations
in ``American Art Circa 1900,'' a group show drawn largely from its
permanent collection. Some 42 artists display the range of American
production at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   From another continent entirely, but just as unusual,
hallucinogenic paintings by contemporary Australian Aboriginal
artists are part of a yearlong celebration of culture Down Under at
Kennesaw State University.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
