<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WRAP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall's golden with a wealth of rich fabrics and luxurious
details
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We return to you _ after a month roaming the runways of New
York, Milan and Paris _ with good and bad news from the fashion
capitals regarding womenswear for next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Good news first: You trendsetters out there have a good six
months before you really have to worry whether you're dressed
right.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news next: That leaves less than 200 days until a) you've
decided which of the many new styles look right on you; and b)
you've squirreled away enough time, money, nerve and motivation to
wear them.
</P>
<P>
   Even the niftiest new styles are diamonds in the rough. They've
got all the wardrobe-enhancing potential in the world. But
potential's hardly ever fully realized. N'est-ce pas?
</P>
<P>
   Next fall's forecast calls for new colors, cuts, costs and
attitudes to get used to. Nowhere is the word ``comfort''
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Six months out, the new requirements for appearing best-dressed
seem unreasonable. But, about 200 days from now, this city's
trendsetters will thank heaven for foresight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TWEED SURRENDER: Donegals, herringbones and other woolly
plaids dominated a great many collections. Though they often showed
up in somber shades of black, gray and brown, the way designers
played with the dimensions of tweed (i.e. herringbones the size of
whale bones) and the materials they could be made from (think mink)
added novelty to the classic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SHORT SHIFT: Tongues will wag around the office if women take
designers up on this fall proposition: hemlines hiked high up on
the thigh. The majority of skirts shown still hovered around the
knee. But short, slit or asymmetrically slashed skirts will signal
how attuned you are to new styles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  KNIT PICKING: Take extra care when adding sweaters to your
wardrobe: Blouses are the new ``in'' thing. A sweater will have to
be extra-special to score style points with it. Blouses shown were
breezy, rather sheer and featured scarfed necklines. Sweaters were
extra-bulky and had cowl necklines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HEAD GAMES: For once in a long while, designers topped
ensembles with hip-looking hats and caps. Styles ranged from cowboy
hats to fedoras to berets. The emphasis on headwear's just another
indication of how ``finished'' women will be expected to appear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SLACKING UP: Pants will play an important role in the fall.
Generally, pants will ride a bit higher on the hip but still fit
tight on the thigh. Something to get accustomed to _ as European
women already have _ is wearing pants cropped at midcalf. Denim _
trimmed with fur or embroidery _ will maintain its prominence.
Other features that'll distinguish the new from the old:
razor-sharp creases, gold belts and buckles, logo pocket stitching
and patchwork leathers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SUIT YOURSELF: Tailored suits were a hallmark of the
collections' emphasis on formality. Pinstripes and tweeds made them
look that much dressier. In most cases, jackets were trim-fitting
and cropped high on the waist.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MATERIAL, GIRL: Fall styles will be judged as much by what
they're made of as what they look like. Suddenly, cashmere's no
longer the most luxurious material to wear. Exotic skins (i.e.,
snake and crocodile), furs and precious silks will be prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  VOLUME CONTROL: Fall's styles will look curvier and more
voluminous as angular silhouettes go by the wayside. Pants will
tend to flare from the knee down, and skirts will widen out from
the waist down. Coats look fluffier by virtue of all the fur
involved, and they sweep toward the floor for more dramatic effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COLOR CODING: Black's coming back (no surprise there). But
there's also an abundance of clothes in turquoise, purple and rosy
or winey shades of red. Mossy green and cream shades will be
factors. Gold, however, will stand out as the key accent color for
fall, both in apparel and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DETAIL-ORIENTED: Accessories will be key components of the
dressed-up look. Handbags will be smaller but showier, in fur,
animal prints, skins or richly embellished versions. Coats will be
belted robe style, or closed with gold buckles or zippers. Footwear
will be high-heeled or knee-booted. Skirts will be ruffled. And
both dresses and blouses will feature scarves dangling from the
neck, shoulder or waist.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton is fashion editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
