 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Dawsonville, Ga. _ Amicalola State Park presents a two-day
Backpacking Clinic with demonstrations and workshop led by outdoor
enthusiasts, trip leaders and REI staff members on Saturday and a
history of the Appalachian Trail and experiences on the trail on
Sunday. 706-265-4703.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Savannah, Ga. _ The 11th annual Savannah Onstage International
Arts Festival, through Sunday, features concerts in historic
venues, plus a lineup of offstage events including a festival,
exhibits, lectures, theater and dance. The American Traditions
competition showcases 38 vocalists competing for $27,500 in prizes.
Also, weekend jazz and free outdoor concerts in the City Market
courtyard and along the Savannah River. 912-236-5745 or
www.savannahonstage
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Savannah, Ga. _ The annual St. Patrick's Day parade, the
second-largest in the country, winds through the historic district
from Forsyth Park to Bay Street and back on March 17. The
procession includes more than 265 units, including 30 floats, 30
family groups and 25 bands. Also, the Budweiser Clydesdales, the
Mummers of Philadelphia, the Summerall Guards from the Citadel in
Charleston and those wacky Shriners. 1-877-728-2662 or
www.savannah-visit.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Macon, Ga. _ The International Cherry Blossom Festival March
17-27 encompasses 500 events _ including a performance by the Tommy
Dorsey Orchestra and historic tours _ celebrating the blossoming of
nearly a quarter-million Yoshino cherry trees. 912-751-7429 or www
</P>
<P>
   .cherryblossom.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Ga. _ ``Digging History: The Archaeology of
Columbus'' is on view through May 7. The exhibit tells the story of
the city's archaeological heritage and centers on recent
excavations in the Second Avenue Revitalization Project.
706-649-0713.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ The sixth annual ``A Mountain
Quiltfest'' is March 15-19 at the Smoky Mountain Convention Center.
Event features quiltmaking classes and an exhibition of
one-of-a-kind quilts. 1-800-251-9100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birmingham _ The Birmingham Museum of Art presents ``Art in
Bloom,'' March 17-19. The event features 61 flower arrangements by
70 local and regional floral designers, who interpret, through
flowers, selected artworks. Also, workshop, lecture and
demonstration by South African floral designer Charles Kinnear.
205-254-2565 or www.artsBMA.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 53rd Festival of Houses and Gardens is
March 16-April 15, featuring daily afternoon and candlelight
walking tours and Lowcountry oyster roasts at Drayton Hall
plantation. To order tickets ($40) by phone, call 843-722-3405.
Also visit www.historiccharleston.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando _ The Orlando Museum of Art presents ``Twentieth
Century Still-Life Paintings From the Phillips Collection,''
Saturday through May 21. The nationally touring exhibition of 70
paintings by 47 artists, including Picasso and Man Ray, brings
together modern American and European still-lifes. 407-896-4231 or
www
</P>
<P>
   .OMArt.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ The play ``Conquest &AMP; Colonization,''
opening Thursday at the St. Augustine Amphitheater, portrays the
settlement of the city in 1565 by Don Pedro Menendez de Aviles.
10:30 a.m. Thursdays and Fridays through April 14. 904-824-9449.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plant City, Fla. _ The Florida Strawberry Festival, continuing
through Sunday, features arts and crafts, country singers,
entertainment, food, vendors, exhibits and everything strawberry.
813-752-9194 or www.flstrawberryfestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando _ Mardi Gras at Universal Studios Florida continues
through April 1. Universal's backlot streets become a moving street
party with entertainment, float-filled parades and food.
407-363-8000 or www.uescape.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daytona Beach, Fla. _ Bike Week, continuing through Sunday, is
one of the oldest and largest international motorcycle festivals in
the world, with races, expos and concerts held throughout the city.
1-800-854-1234 or www.officialbikeweek.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miami _ Carnaval Miami, through Sunday, brings the city's
Latin flavor center stage with top Latin performers. 305-644-8888
or www.carnaval-miami.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miami Beach _ Artist Carlos Betancourt and poets Richard
Blanco, Fred D'Aguiar and Campbell McGrath will present ``The
Sounds, Symbols Project,'' a 300-foot-long-by-90-foot-wide art
installation and performance on the sand at 21st Street on March
19. Inspired by Caribbean and African tribal symbols, the 24-hour
environmental art installation will consist of thousands of
individually sculpted wood shapes anchored to the beach to outline
a large-scale form over the sand. 305-573-9955.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natchez, Miss. _ Natchez Spring Pilgrimage today through April
8 includes tours of 31 antebellum mansions, music and the fancy
Confederate Pageant. 1-800-647-6742 or www.natchezpilgrimage.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
