<SLUG> BC-STEPHEN-KING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horror meister turns a page
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen King, who bypassed the traditional paper-and-ink format
with his recent audio-only book ``Smoke and Blood,'' is turning to
the Internet for his next work.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Tuesday, King's 16,000-word ghost story, ``Riding the
Bullet,'' will be available only on the Web as an e-book for $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will be able to download the 66-page novella from computers
at www.netlibrary.com or onto Palm organizers and other handheld
computing devices through peanutpress.com, a division of the
Boulder, Colo.-based netLibrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm curious to see what sort of response there is and whether
or not this is the future,'' said King, who described ``Riding the
Bullet'' as ``a ghost story in the grand manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is a co-publication between Scribner and Philtgrum
Press and electronically published through Simon &AMP; Schuster online.
King wrote the novella shortly after his near-fatal accident when
he was hit by a van in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that e-books will replace books,'' said King's
agent, Ralph Vicinanza. ``It's a new format that will exist side by
side with the traditional outlets for bookselling.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster favors the method because it cuts costs and
time. Normally, it takes a year to bring a book from manuscript to
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can get more information and read a three-page excerpt at
www.SimonSays.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
