<SLUG> BC-FLA-PRIMARY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adviser urges Floridians to vote for McCain, despite `suspended'
campaign
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ John McCain may have been captured by the
forces of George W. Bush, but the former Marine general leading his
Florida campaign is urging his troops to storm the polls Tuesday
and vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have something to say,'' said Bob Milligan, state
comptroller and McCain's Florida campaign director. ``Our votes
still count and we want to make sure that John McCain's voice is
still heard.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain all but ended his campaign Thursday when the Arizona
senator said he was ``suspending'' it. Handily defeated in most of
this week's primaries, McCain refused to formally end his campaign,
giving small hope to his supporters that a miracle could still
happen.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's name remains on next Tuesday's Florida primary ballot.
So does the name of former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley who was
soundly defeated this week by Vice President Al Gore. Bradley
formerly dropped out of the race Thursday and gave his support to
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Texas Gov. George W. Bush nor Gore are taking anything
for granted next Tuesday, even though their party rivals have
faded. Bush will campaign Sunday in the Little Havana section of
Miami. He will spend most of the day in Florida, according to his
campaign staff, with details of his visit rapidly changing. Gore
will be in Orlando and Miami on Monday, according to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore expect Florida to be a key state in the
November election. Bush, who likely will be nominated by the
Republican Party at its Philadelphia convention this summer, could
face opposition from McCain loyalists in forming the party's
convention theme. Party rules say that any candidate who has won
six states will have a voice in the convention proceedings. McCain
has won seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what election turnout is going to be because of
what happened this week,'' said Milligan,'' but if enough people
feel strongly about John McCain and his message, then I still think
we can have an impact on the Republican campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, however, Milligan said he will be
loyal to the party nominee. ``I'm a conservative and I'm a
Republican and I'll support George W.,'' Milligan said. ``But I
still want his campaign to reflect the philosophy of John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
