<SLUG> BC-AETNA-SLAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA APOLOGIZES FOR 1850S POLICIES ON SLAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc. expressed regret for its apparent role as an insurer
for slaveowners in the 1850s, joining a string of major
institutions that have recently apologized for their past conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the big Hartford, Conn. insurer, had previously disclosed
papers in its archives showing it wrote at least four policies
related to individual slaves, in effect providing
property-insurance for their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in response to a critic in New York, the company went
a step further and issued a statement saying that it feels ``deep
regret over any participation at all in this deplorable practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement is the latest in a series of official acts of
contrition by institutions for past misdeeds. This weekend, Pope
John Paul II is expected to apologize for the Catholic Church's
``faults of the past,'' including aspects of the Crusades and the
Inquisition. Swiss banks and German automakers have also apologized
in recent years for their treatment of Jews and other minorities
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized these statements as cheap posturing, while
others say they are important for a full understanding of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very welcome when a company has the moral courage to
admit a serious transgression against a group,'' said Harvard Law
School professor Charles Ogletree Jr. He is part of a group of
black intellectuals who may seek reparation payments for decendants
of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint against Aetna was brought by another activist,
Deadria Farmer-Paellmann, an African-American woman who graduated
from the New England College of Law in Boston last year and now
lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer-Paellmann wrote to Aetna last month seeking both an
apology and some financial compensation. ``These companies have
inherited wealth that doesn't belong to them,'' she said in an
interview Thursday. ``They have a moral obligation to the heirs''
of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna disagreed and said it was unclear whether it had ever
collected any premiums for the policies, which typically had a face
value of $600, or paid any off. It said further that any
obligations it might have were offset by ``our strong, consistent
commitment to diversity over many years'' and its philanthropic
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The company cited grants to the NAACP and many African-American
colleges, and noted its directors included the late Arthur Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer-Paellmann said she hopes to change Aetna's mind. She also
has asked FleetBoston Financial Corp. to explain its relationship
to The Providence Bank, which she said earned profits from the the
traffic in slaves to the New World.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal shows the complexity of the issue, however, since the
bank's officials seem to have included abolitionists. Fleet
spokesman James Mahoney said the Providence Bank was only one of a
dozen or so predecessor companies to Fleet. While the matter is
still under review, payments aren't being discussed with
Farmer-Paellmann, he said. ``The connection between our current
company and the banking entity founded in 1791 is very distant,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
