u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-610&AMP;ADD     03-09 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI AND PALESTINIAN OFFICIALS MEET IN EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARM EL SHEIK, Egypt _ After over a month of sniping at each
other, Israeli and Palestinian officials met Thursday for an
informal lunch and pep talk from President Hosni Mubarak as they
prepared to resume peace talks in Washington this month.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, acting as host and coach, gave the only public
statement of the day after emerging from brief discussions with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met here in a very friendly atmosphere, overcoming so many
obstacles,'' Mubarak said after he had escorted the two men into a
hotel conference room in this Red Sea resort. ``The good relations
between the two leaders give great hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene bore a strong resemblance to one on Wednesday in the
West Bank town of Ramallah, where the U.S. envoy, Dennis Ross, also
spoke on behalf of the Israeli and Palestinian sides in announcing
a resumption of the stalled negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The strong American and Egyptian intervention reassured some
Palestinian leaders who have wanted higher-profile mediation in
their dealings with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of Mubarak and Ross was not just symbolic,'' said
Yasser Abed Rabbo, chief negotiator for the Palestinian side and
the information minister of the Palestinian Authority. ``It was
meant to provide guarantees that the Israelis would be committed to
implement the understandings already reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials on both sides said Thursday that Israel was prepared
to make a few conciliatory gestures, including the release of some
Palestinian prisoners from its jails and a reconsideration of how a
``safe passage'' route between the West Bank and the Gaza Strip
would operate.
</P>
<P>
   There were no clear answers on the core issue of land _ where,
when and how it will be transferred to the Palestinians _ that is
at the heart of the 7-year-old peace process. But there were hints.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Yatom, Barak's senior diplomatic and security adviser,
told Israel radio on Thursday that he could not rule out the
possibility that some or all of the Arab towns near the edge of
Jerusalem could be given over to the Palestinians before a final
peace treaty is negotiated. The two sides have announced Sept. 13
as a deadline for the final accord.
</P>
<P>
   The towns mentioned by Yatom for possible transfer were Abu-Dis,
el-Azariya and A-Ram, all Jerusalem suburbs that have been on a
Palestinian wish list. The towns would be the closest geographic
link to Arab East Jerusalem, which they want as the capital of a
new state but which has been nearly surrounded by Jewish
neighborhoods for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has refused to include any land in the Jerusalem area in
the next scheduled transfer of territory, which is supposed to
amount to an additional 6.1 percent of the occupied West Bank. With
that land, the Palestinian Authority would control civil life or
security or both in 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Another dispute has been over what will happen after that
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have pushed to have all the occupied land, with
the exception of Jewish settlements and military outposts, turned
over to them before the talks on the final status. The final
negotiations are supposed to deal with especially sensitive topics
like the settlements, Jerusalem, borders between Israel and a
Palestinian entity, and the rights of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary peace deal struck by Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization in 1993 envisioned that most of the
occupied territory would be in Palestinian hands by the time a
final treaty was on the table. But Barak has been vague about
whether he would go so far.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last two days, Israeli and Palestinian officials have
hinted that as a result of Egyptian and U.S. mediation Barak might
be willing to cede a substantial section of the Israeli-occupied
West Bank in advance of a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the outlines of what Israel might or might not be willing
to do in the next round of talks are not clear. Israeli officials
publicly denied that any deals had been struck about how much land
would be handed over in the course of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not yet decided, prior to any progress having been
made, whether it will be a single percent, less than 1 percent or a
little more than 1 percent,'' the foreign minister of Israel, David
Levy, said after returning from Egypt. ``All that depends on
progress, Israel's interests and what we achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, Abed Rabbo said he would also reserve
his opinion. ``We will try now to observe and see if the Israelis
really desire to deal seriously with the issues or if they are just
maneuvering to calm the situation on Palestinian track so they can
deal with crisis on other tracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That same chilliness was in the air at the meeting here of the
Palestinian and Israeli leaders. There was a clasping of hands, as
well as a few public pats on the back and brief bear hugs. But
Barak and Arafat had the air of exhausted football players being
sent back onto the field for another bruising quarter of play.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mubarak's attempt to be inspirational _ he cheerily
predicted that ``soon the problem of the Middle East will be
finished'' _ the two leaders showed little warmth toward each
other. Their aides were even less jolly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
