<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenseth rolls to Busch pole
 &HT;    Michael Carvell and Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Matt Kenseth is focusing this year on his rookie
season in Winston Cup, but he's also having quite a year as a
part-time campaigner on the Busch Grand National Series.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday at Atlanta Motor Speedway, Kenseth won the pole for
Saturday's Aaron's 312 with a lap at 185.704 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth won the Busch race at Daytona and, after strong runs at
Rockingham and Las Vegas, leads the series point standings. That
soon will end because he plans to run only those Busch races that
are held in conjunction with Winston Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   The car he drove at Atlanta is the same car that Tim Bender put
on the pole in the Busch race at AMS in the spring of 1997. It also
has been wrecked and repaired numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real heavy and real old, but it's a good driving car,''
Kenseth said.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Chaffin took the outside pole in a car prepared by former
Winston Cup driver Jimmy Means.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was almost perfect,'' said Chaffin, a short-track
veteran who started his racing career at Nashville Speedway. ``I
ran wide open all the way around the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Anthony Lazzaro from Acworth, Ga., will start fifth in
his first race at his home track. His season is off to a slow start
since injuries forced him to skip the season opener at Daytona, and
he failed to qualify last week at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come here for the first time and put it fifth on the grid
says a lot for this team,'' Lazzaro said. ``After we missed the
race last week, this certainly shows that our team knows how to
rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Georgians had miserable qualifying efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones of Tucker was one of the fastest cars in
practice, but the adjustments his crew made in an effort to get the
pole backfired. He was 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing pushed like a dump truck,'' Jones said. ``Sometimes
when you go for the pole it can bite you, and it bit us hard
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Young from Conyers was 52nd of the 53 drivers who are trying
to start the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to be here, but we've got a lot of work to do,''
Young said. ``It's hard when you show up here without much
experience or know-how.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he plans to ask Jones to try his car this morning.
``I want to see if the car's that bad off or if it's me,'' Young
said.
</P>
<P>
   HELTON SEES EXCITEMENT
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's chief operating officer Mike Helton said this week that
he disagrees with recent news articles saying the early season
Winston Cup races have been boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our records show that we've had 44 lead changes among 20
drivers in the first three races,'' Helton said. ``We have more
cars than ever finishing on the lead lap, and people in the garage
tell us that the competition is so close today that it's not as
easy to blow by people as it once was.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the increased level of competition has forced drivers to
rethink race strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the guy in front of them is running almost as good
as they are so they have to think a little bit about how to get
around him,'' Helton said. ``We still think it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
