<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-NY-PICKUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK WILL ALLOW PICKUP TRUCKS ON PARKWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARCIA BIEDERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Beware the Ides of March? For commuters in and around
New York City, that might be an overreaction, but a new era will
begin next Wednesday as pickup trucks become eligible to join the
traffic crush on parkways.
</P>
<P>
   New state rules will allow all but the heaviest personal-use
pickups to be registered as passenger vehicles. For the first time,
they will be allowed to use roads, like the parkways, that bar
commercial traffic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Current regulations, requiring commercial plates on virtually
all pickups with open beds, ``penalize some drivers simply because
of the vehicles they drive, and make no sense,'' said Gov. George
Pataki in a statement announcing the change. The effort began last
July and included a period of public comment, which ran 3-to-1 in
favor of the change, which was made through administrative
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, open-bed pickups with an unloaded weight of
5,000 pounds or less and no advertising are eligible for
passenger-vehicle plates. Previously, pickups could not have
passenger plates unless they were permanently modified with camper
tops over their cargo beds, plus seats or other camping equipment,
like a stove. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But before a jacked-up F-150 with chrome air horns can roll onto
the FDR Drive or the Sprain Parkway, its owner must exchange its
commercial plates for passenger tags. Ken Brown, a spokesman for
the Department of Motor Vehicles, said the switch could be made at
any motor vehicle office for $6.50. The owner must present the
vehicle's title to make the change.
</P>
<P>
   More than 485,000 vehicles could qualify for the change, Brown
said, though current registrations do not indicate how many of
these trucks are used commercially.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule will bring New York in line with states like
Connecticut and New Jersey, where pickup owners can choose between
commercial and other plates. Trucks with noncommercial plates from
other states will also gain access to New York parkways, though
drivers could be ticketed if the trucks exceed the weight
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers lobbied for the change in hopes of spurring pickup
sales. Last year, pickups accounted for less than 3 percent of
new-vehicle registrations in New York City and the counties of
Putnam, Rockland and Westchester, compared with about 19 percent
nationally, according to the Polk Co., which tracks registration
data.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect personal-use trucks to catch on in the city, where
open beds pose security problems. But in Westchester, which is
laced with parkways, ``if it doesn't help, it won't harm,'' said
Leon Geller, president of Beck Chevrolet in Yonkers. He said he had
been selling more trucks recently, ``but it's not like out West.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
