<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ BREAKS 5000; OTHER GAUGES ALSO SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NASDAQ-ASSESS, VALUATION-NORRIS-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology issues paced a strong stock-market rally
Thursday as the Nasdaq composite index soared through the 5,000
mark for the first time while the broadest market gauge of all, the
Wilshire total market index, surged above 14,000, also a record.
</P>
<P>
   After some early losses, prices climbed steadily without benefit
of any obvious trigger as investors piling again into
computer-related and other technology stocks were joined by those
seeking bargains in other sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech had a great day and drugs had a great day,'' said Matthew
W. Johnson, chief Nasdaq trader at Lehman Brothers. ``There's money
that wants to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market gained 149.60 points, or 3.05 percent, to
finish at 5,046.86, surpassing the previous high, set last Friday,
of 4,914.79, and solidly above the 5,000 benchmark it had briefly
reached on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other major gauges also surged, with the Dow Jones industrial
average pulling out of an early 118-point hole to end with a gain
of 154.20, or 1.56 percent, to finish back above the 10,000 mark.
At 10,010.73, the blue-chip average is now less than twice the
Nasdaq composite compared with five times as much in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 advanced 34.99 points, or 2.56
percent, to end at 1,401.69. Of its components, 340 posted gains
while 141 declined and 19 were unchanged. Leading the way, Cisco
gained 6 15/16 to 139 5/16, Microsoft 4 7/16 to 100 and America
Online 6 3/8 to 61 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the winners chasing the winners,'' said Ned Riley Jr.,
chief investment strategist at State Street Global Advisors in
Boston. He predicted that investors would continue to favor
highflying technology issues for another three or four months until
it became clear that the Federal Reserve was succeeding, as he said
it inevitably would, in slowing down a white-hot economy.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term investors, however, might want to start looking
elsewhere to pick up bargains, Riley suggested.
</P>
<P>
   For a second straight day, it was the beaten-down drug sector
that captured much of this attention. Bristol-Myers jumped 6 to 53
3/4 and Warner-Lambert 5 11/16 to 91 1/2, with Lilly, Merck and
American Home Products advancing more than four points each. Some
analysts said the threat of government intervention to restrict
price increases seems to have receded with the winnowing of the
presidential field, while others said that drug stocks had simply
gotten too cheap to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perfect example of a group that was oversold,''
Johnson said of drug stocks, several of which have double-digit
percentage losses this year. ``People began to realize these things
are valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, whose stock reached 99 7/8 last spring and which an
institutional holder wants to see auctioned off piecemeal, advanced
2 7/8 to 57.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Lehman Brothers recommended several producers
of depressed specialty chemicals but those stocks showed little
response.
</P>
<P>
   And PaineWebber found little enthusiasm despite a spurt in
quarterly profits for H.J. Heinz, which traded as high as 54 last
May but closed Thursday at 34 1/2, up 1/4. The firm cut its target
price to 36 from 44.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, clobbered earlier in the week, was little
changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilshire 5000 index, which covers nearly every American
stock, climbed into positive territory for the year, advancing
338.45 points, or 2.48 percent, to 14,006.37.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 1,682 issues gained while 1,299
lost ground, but 52-week lows still far exceeded new highs, this
time by 175 to 65. Volume edged down to 1.12 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, major indexes rose about 2 percent in Sao Paulo,
Brazil, and London but fell about .05 percent in Tokyo and
Frankfurt. Hong Kong stocks fell 1.75 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
