<SLUG> BC-NC-HURRICANE-CARS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD-HIT CARS SOAK PURCHASERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY E. TURNBULL   
 Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ AAA Carolinas estimates that 75,000 cars were
flooded by Hurricane Floyd, and of that, one third, or 25,000, are
in circulation across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The latest estimate represents five times more than the original
15,000 cars thought damaged by flood water last September. It
includes vehicles that weren't necessarily submerged, but had water
up to their floorboards or weren't left in water very long,
explained Tom Crosby, an AAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 25,000 cars in circulation ``could end up anywhere''
for resale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a couple of complaints,'' Crosby said, generally
``from people who were fortunate enough to avoid them.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina attorney general's office has investigated
several complaints from people who suspect that unscrupulous
sellers soaked them by not disclosing the car's history.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, it is a misdemeanor not to tell a buyer a
vehicle was involved in an accident in which the cost exceeded 25
percent of the vehicle's value, or that a vehicle was flooded,
reconstructed or salvaged. That information must also be listed on
title and registration cards unless it meets certain criteria for
repair. Removing the title or supporting documents from a vehicle
with the intent to conceal damage is also a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina Automobile Dealers Association, which has a
policy of full disclosure for its members, estimates that nearly a
third of auto sales are made outside a dealership _ person to
person _ making it important that people investigate any car they
want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Callers who can provide a Vehicle Identification Number can have
the North Carolina Department of Motor Vehicles in Raleigh check
its records to see if a car was salvaged or flooded. The DMV
customer service line is (919) 715-7000
</P>
<P>
   Also, the state attorney general's office has set up a Web site
_ www.jus.state.nc.us/cpframe.htm _ where people can find if a car
was titled as ``flood'' or ``water damaged'' in North Carolina. The
site includes a VIN list of flooded vehicles that were properly
titled in the state. The site also provides a link where people can
request a complete title history on a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office cautions that when cars are
retitled out of state, the flood designation can be lost; so a
visit to the Web site or a gathering a title history is a good idea
for prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, the dealers association has designed and
distributed to its members supplemental damage reports for car
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about the consumer impact down the chain of
flood vehicles,'' said executive vice president Robert Glaser.
``The form is a level of assurance,'' he said, so buyers will
``know the history of a vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more immediate ways to tell if a car might have been
in a flood.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first tip-offs is a strong, musty odor of mildew.
Rust around the dashboard area and electrical problems _
particularly with automatic door locks and windows that have wiring
and switches in the doors _ are also sometimes evidence that a car
was underwater.
</P>
<P>
   The AAA warns that flooded cars can be dangerous to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some could run OK, but on the other hand, the water that got
into the engine could cause corrosion,'' Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser said a person could be driving down the road and have a
car die without warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the old days where you could just jump-start the
car,'' he said. ``Today's cars are all circuitry.''
</P>
<P>
   Another danger with flooded cars is unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just never know when the impact of the flood is going to
take place,'' Glaser said. It could be two weeks after a car is
purchased, or six months later.
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
