<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2234 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-09 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE WATER'S EDGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I was starting to envy the political reporters, because there
seemed to be no foreign policy in this year's presidential primary
campaign. But then I realized that there was no policy in this
campaign, let alone foreign policy, so there was really nothing to
envy. So far, this has been a campaign about campaigning _ who has
the best ad strategy for distorting the other guy's position and
re-inventing his own in order to mislead voters.
</P>
<P>
   We had a primary in New York in which people actually discussed
whether John McCain was for or against breast cancer, and George W.
Bush, who presides over one of the most polluted states in the
nation, ran as the candidate from Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that distortion is part of campaigning, but when did
it become campaigning? I guess the true measure of how little
foreign policy figured in the primaries was the fact that none of
the candidates felt impelled to even distort the other's
foreign-policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of foreign policy is due in part to the relative
peace and prosperity America now enjoys, but there are other
factors at play. To begin with, the substantive differences between
the center of the Democratic and Republican parties on many key
foreign-policy questions has narrowed. Face it, President Clinton
has done to the Republicans on foreign policy exactly what he did
to them on domestic policy: He took all their favorite issues and
left them with the garbage. The Republicans wanted NATO expansion,
so Clinton expanded NATO. The Republicans initiated NAFTA, and
Clinton got it ratified. The Republicans were in favor of
ballistic-missile defense, so Clinton made it part of the
Democratic plank too. There aren't a lot of global wedge issues
left.
</P>
<P>
   The differences have also narrowed because some of the key
issues have become too complicated to distort. They are so complex
they don't fit on a bumper sticker at all. You'd need the whole
bumper to describe them.
</P>
<P>
   America's obvious national interest today is sustainable
globalization. Just that term is a mouthful. But the fact is, it's
America's products, technologies, ideas, values, culture and style
of capitalism that are being most globalized today. So surely our
overriding interest is to keep that going _ by both stabilizing the
world system militarily and democratizing it economically and
politically, so that more people in more places benefit from this
globalization.
</P>
<P>
   That's the theory. The practice is even more complicated,
particularly in an age when Americans are held responsible for
everything in the world but don't want to die for anything. As
such, the practice of sustainable globalization is a quirky
combination of cruise missiles and Web servers. It means deploying
classic deterrence against Iraq; pursuing arms control, IMF aid and
containment vis-a-vis Russia; combining gunboats, trade and
Internet investment to move China along; and deterrence and
potatoes to induce North Korea not to go nuclear. It is not heroic
stuff, but so far it's kept the peace and globalization alive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the differences have narrowed because for a lot of
citizens the biggest foreign-policy issue is now the biggest
domestic issue: education. Just as the Soviet launch of Sputnik
elevated the importance of science education in the early Cold War,
the onset of globalization and intensified economic competition is
elevating the importance of technology education today. In the Cold
War we thought we had to get smarter to survive in a world of
walls, and in this era of globalization we think we need to get
smarter to survive in a world without walls.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the center of both parties, argues Robert Pastor,
an Emory University political scientist, what's left that really
differentiates them is attitude _ ``how they define American
leadership'' _ with the Democrats tending to believe that the best
way to pursue our interests is by working with coalitions of
allies, the U.N. and through international treaties, and the
Republicans at least talking about more unilateral approaches and
rejecting treaties, such as the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. But
how much even those differences are real and how much they grow out
of who's in office and who's not is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Both George W. Bush and Al Gore would drive with
roughly the same foreign-policy map. It's really a question of who
you'd trust with the car keys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
