<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-09 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE MORNING AFTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore-Bush. Deep down, we all knew it would come to this.
</P>
<P>
   Bush-Gore. Maybe it will be good for our character. It's really
superficial, you know, this desire for a chief executive with
charisma.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be fine, in time. Our citizenship has been tested with
much worse match-ups _ remember Reagan-Mondale? Dukakis-Bush?
Clinton-Dole? But it's going to take a while to accept the fact
that we've been left alone with these two guys for the next eight
months.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months. How many times can Al Gore casually drop the fact
that he was in the Army in Vietnam over that long a stretch? How
many times will George W. Bush announce that he doesn't just want
to lower the toll on the road to the middle class, he wants to tear
down the tollbooth? How many times will he screw it up? The man has
an MBA from Harvard, but he cannot get this tollbooth thing down
right. Some days he wants to tear down the toll, sometimes he wants
to lower the booth.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, they're stronger than we are. Never before have we
had a presidential contest involving people in such good physical
shape. In the prime of life, by our new flexible baby-boom
standards, they're fitness fiends. Put George W. down for a rest
stop, and he's off on a three-mile run like an unleashed beagle.
Leave the vice president alone behind closed doors and he'll start
doing sit-ups. Both camps now assure us they are going to use this
energy to leap directly into a 34-week non-stop conflict in which
punches will be thrown and mutilation inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strap on your seat belts, we're in for a roller coaster
ride,'' said Gore's spokesman, Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Politics as an Iron Man Triathlon _ did anybody ask the public
about this? Could be a blessing, though. It may lead to revisionist
thinking about William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedal to the metal!'' said Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, truth to tell, is better at these endurance
tests than Bush, who whined his way through several states yearning
for his family, his dog and his own no-steam shaving mirror back
home. Gore just seems to be real, real good at enduring discomfort.
In the age of indulgence, we've got a stoic running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the days grow longer, we become stronger!'' said Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Gore celebrated his victory Tuesday night by morphing into
McCain. Admitting past sins, he embraced campaign finance reform _
for real this time, cross my heart _ and embarked on a series of
town hall meetings. Bush had already had his turn to become McCain
during his ``reformer with results'' reincarnation after New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Enoughenough. By all rights, today should be reserved for
bidding farewell to the original John McCain and to Bill Bradley,
who made the last few months a whole lot more interesting than we'd
anticipated. They both withdrew from combat Thursday, expressing
controlled disdain for their former opponents. McCain was by far
the frostier, offering Bush the political equivalent of ``Good
luck, you'll need it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator from Arizona will never have to wonder whether he
could have gone further if he had tried harder. All the McCain team
worked like maniacs. (``Throw up on your own time,'' one of his
supporters gibed at another when flu struck the Straight Talk
Express in South Carolina.) Win or lose, he's had a political
adventure on a level nobody but Bill Clinton has experienced,
without the impeachment downside.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's candidacy, on the other hand, just sort of faded away.
It was one of those campaigns where the high points are the
announcement and the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a certain amount of showmanship is required,''
sighed Kathy Boland, a nurse who stood through a Bradley rally in
the Seattle rain. His audiences were full of the helping
professions, and people with great insurance coverage worrying
about universal health care. Bill Bradley had the nicest supporters
of any candidate. There just weren't very many of them.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated candidates are now off to vacation with their
wives, leaving us in what currently feels like a battle to the
death between More of the Same and Less of the Same. We miss them
already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
