<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     03-09 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON FOR OLD PSAL NAMES TO REMINISCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Mass., N.Y.)   By   DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``This time of year,'' Dolph Schayes was saying.
``This is when I really start to think basketball: the NCAA and the
NIT, then the NBA playoffs. This is the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the time to remember basketball in other eras, as
Schayes, Nate (Tiny) Archibald, Andrew (Fuzzy) Levane, Floyd Layne,
Zeke Sinicola and Alex Isaacs did Thursday _ New York names that
many of today's pro, college and high school players should know
but probably never heard of because they're too busy dunking.
</P>
<P>
   These old names had gathered among the Carnegie Deli's
corned-beef sandwiches to reminisce about another alphabetic
tournament, the 98th PSAL (alias the Public Schools Athletic
League) championships Sunday at the Garden: Lincoln vs. Kennedy
(Boys A), Roosevelt vs. Hale (Boys B) and Sheepshead Bay-Bergtraum
(Girls B).
</P>
<P>
   Schayes and Archibald are enshrined in the Naismith Memorial
Basketball Hall of Fame in Springfield, Mass., but their roots were
planted two decades apart at DeWitt Clinton High School in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Now 72, Schayes, who was an all-American at New York University
when college basketball ruled the Garden half a century ago, should
have been a Knick instead of the Syracuse Nationals' six-time
first-team All-Star forward. If he had been a Knick, maybe the
Knicks would have won a National Basketball Association title
before 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the Knicks' first-round choice, but that year their
boss, Ned Irish, had the NBA institute what amounted to a salary
cap _ $100,000 for the team, $5,000 for a rookie,'' Schayes
recalled. ``That's all the Knicks could offer me, but Syracuse,
which then was in the rival National Basketball League before the
merger, offered me $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish couldn't give me more than $5,000 because he would be
busting the salary cap that had been his idea, but since I had an
engineering degree at NYU, the Knicks told me they'd get me a job
with the Port Authority in the off-season as an extra salary. But
nobody told me what the job was. For all I knew, I'd be taking
tolls at a bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget that at the time, $5,000 was pretty good money,''
he added. ``That came out to $100 a week and I remember telling my
mother when I graduated, `If I can make $100 a week the rest of my
life, I'll be happy.' And when I took the Nats' $7,500, I told her,
`I'll just play one year.' But that one year turned into 16
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1955 Syracuse Nats, with Schayes averaging 18.5 points and
12.3 rebounds, won the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Archibald, the point guard on the 1981 champion Boston Celtics,
was on Clinton's 1963 PSAL title team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year before, we lost to Boys High in the final at the
Garden,'' Archibald recalled. ``What a great atmosphere that was
for high school kids to be in, but that was when they had the riot.
After the game ended, people were coming out of the stands, guys
were breaking things, just going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years after that riot, the PSAL championships were
banned from the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next year, we won the title,'' Archibald said, ``but we
played the final in Queens. Just two teams, two referees, no
spectators.''
</P>
<P>
   After having been in the Garden, playing for the title at a high
school gym, Archibald recalled, ``was like a punishment.'' Levane,
a longtime Knicks scout and briefly the Knicks' coach four decades
ago, was on James Madison's 1938 champions before starring at St.
John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were undefeated, 23 and 0,'' he said. ``We had what I don't
think any other high school team ever had _ six guys who went on to
play pro. I was with the Rochester Royals; the Rader twins, Lenny
and Howie, and Stan Waxman were with Buffalo; Fred Lewis was with
Sheboygan, all in the old NBL, and Larry Baxter was with Paterson
of the old American Basketball League.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs, whose father, John, had played for the legendary
Renaissance Ballroom team, was on Taft's 1975 champions, three
decades after Sinicola and Layne were teammates at Benjamin
Franklin High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat Erasmus for the 1946 title,'' said Sinicola, who went
on to Niagara University and the Fort Wayne Pistons. ``We had one
of the legends of high school basketball in those years, Rabbit
Walthour.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that name, Layne, who was later the point guard on City
College's unprecedented and unmatched 1950 sweep of both the
National Collegiate Athletic Association and National Invitation
Tournament titles, held up his long fingers and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``See all the knobs on these fingers,'' said Layne, now the
coach at Prospect Heights High in Brooklyn. ``I was fortunate to be
at the end of the passes that Rabbit and Zeke threw, but I had I
don't know how many sprained fingers I got from catching those
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Layne, who later coached at CCNY, was among the Beaver players
convicted of shaving points in the 1951 scandal that tarnished his
chances of joining an NBA team as an assistant coach. He was
interviewed twice, once with the Knicks and once with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the scandal hurt me, I wouldn't say that,'' he said
without any bitterness in his voice. ``That's for others to say.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
