<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-COURT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE OF CUBAN BOY STILL UP IN THE AIR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After three months of a political tug-of-war, the fate
of 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor Elian Gonzalez remains
uncertain after a federal judge Thursday raised questions about the
government's handling of the boy's petition for political asylum,
but issued no ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Though U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore could reach a
decision as early as next week on a petition filed on behalf of the
boy's Miami family, the issue may take months, if not years, to
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The judge was considering a lawsuit brought by Elian's
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, who is trying to keep the child with
Miami relatives in the United States _ rather than have the boy
sent back to his father in communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   If Moore rules in favor of the U.S. Justice Department, which
has said the boy should be returned, attorneys for the family have
said they may file appeals all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court,
if necessary. And if Moore allows the boy to file for political
asylum, that process could take at least 60 days before reaching an
immigration hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our hope that the court's resolution will make it
possible for this little boy to go back to his father and put an
end to this extraordinary stress on the family,'' said Patricia
Maher, deputy assistant U.S. Attorney General.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was rescued off the coast of Fort Lauderdale last
Thanksgiving by a pair of fishermen who found him floating adrift
strapped to an inner tube. He was one of three survivors on an
ill-fated boat trip to the United States from Cuba. His mother, who
had taken him on the journey without informing family members in
Cuba, was among 11 people who drowned on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since his rescue, Elian has been at the center of a
political maelstrom pitting Miami's Cuban exile community, which
wants him to remain in the United States, and Cuban dictator Fidel
Castro, who has rallied support around Elian's father.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides accuse the other of using Elian as a political pawn.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-hour hearing Thursday morning, a Justice Department
attorney argued that no court had the jurisdiction to remove the
authority from the U.S. Attorney General's office in an immigration
issue. However, attorneys for Elian's Miami's family claimed the
boy was unjustly denied his right to seek asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin S. Kneedler, deputy solicitor general of the United
States, said the INS twice rejected political asylum applications
filed on behalf of the boy _ decisions upheld by Attorney General
Janet Reno. The agency determined that Elian's father, as the boy's
sole legal guardian, was the only person who could seek asylum on
behalf of the boy. Reno withdrew the applications at the request of
the father, Juan Gonzalez, who asked that his son be returned to
him in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Kneedler argued that a federal court did not have the
jurisdiction to review a decision by the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Elian's Miami family, however, said the boy's
political asylum applications should have never been withdrawn
because he had the same rights as any illegal immigrant to petition
for protection under the Refugee Act of 1980. They filed affidavits
supporting their claims that a dismal, if not perilous, future
awaits the boy if he is returned to Cuba. Attorneys declined to
comment about the affidavits, which were sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is that a child, Elian Gonzalez, regardless of
the fact that he is 6 years old has the right to file a petition
for asylum. That's it. That's the question. And the government is
trying to distort the law and not follow the law,'' said Barbara
Lagoa, one of the Gonzalez family attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Moore asked Kneedler why the INS had not
resolved the issue in an immigration court rather than denying the
application without a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   If that course had been taken, Moore said the issue probably
would have been resolved by now.
</P>
<P>
   Kneedler said the INS was not compelled to consider the
application after the boy's father asked to have it removed. Also,
he said a 6-year-old, because of juvenile status, cannot seek
asylum on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does it say in the statute if you're under six (years
old you cannot apply?) Where does it say who is authorized to
speak? When I look at the law it states any alien is eligible to
apply,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the INS has the prerogative to accept the application
and then let an immigration court decide whether it should be
denied, but that the agency ``can't have it both ways.``
</P>
<P>
   Kneedler said the boy had not been admitted into the United
States, and that he had been paroled into the care of his great
uncle Lazaro Gonzalez only until the INS could determine the boy's
status.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials in early January spoke to the boy's father in Cuba
and determined he had maintained an ongoing relationship with his
son and was a fit father.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, about 60 demonstrators _ most of them
supporters of Elian's staying in the United States _ waved huge
Cuban flags, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Ira Kurzban, an adjunct law professor
specializing in immigration law at the University of Miami, said
Kneedler concentrated too much on defending Reno and her decision
rather than arguing the father's parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense of the father was secondary and that may make a
difference,'' he said. Thus far, events have favored efforts to
keep the boy in Miami, which he described as a ``long stall.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
