<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BURNS, IT'S HOCKEY AS USUAL, DESPITE THE PRESSURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Untying his skates as a pizza arrived in the
coaches room at the Entertainment and Sports Arena Thursday
following practice, Bruins coach Pat Burns made it clear. ``You can
talk to me, but I don't want to talk about Ray Bourque, Marty
McSorley, Harry Sinden, or Jeremy Jacobs.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs spoke on a wide variety of topics in both Boston
newspapers Thursday, and he softened _ if not backpedaled from _
his previous criticism of the Bruins' coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   So that couldn't be ignored, and Burns eventually chose to speak
on the topic one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Jacobs...,'' Burns said, then paused. ``I've said
things that have been taken out of context and written all kinds of
ways, and the way I see it, he's not a bad person and I never felt
that he was. I think what he was trying to get was an explanation
of why these things were happening. It's normal. And of course
you're trying to do that, you own the team. Of course you're
scratching your head trying to figure it out. But he's far from
being a bad person. I've got to know him a little bit from the
certain amount of times I've met him. He's been very cordial to me.
Very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs told the Globe's Kevin Paul Dupont, ``I don't know if
changing Burns is the right thing, I really don't . . .'' After
being critical of the Bruins' penalty-killing unit _ which dropped
from first to last in a year _ in a Will McDonough column a few
weeks ago, Jacobs said, ``I was critical, but it wasn't of Burns,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Thursday that when he first read Jacobs's criticism,
``I was shocked. I was shocked like everybody else was shocked.
What the hell was this?'' Yet he understood the owner saying what
he had to say and he didn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dislike anybody in this organization,'' said Burns.
``I've said it before and I'll say it again, I like Harry. I love
going fishing with Harry. We have fun. We disagree on certain
things. I'm doing the best I can with what I've got. That's all I
can give. It's not where I want to be with this team. I agree it's
not where this team should be. We should be better. But changes and
things have happened and it's been very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets frustrated and things are said and then there's
a counter to that. It becomes, like I said, a mudslinging affair
and it gets ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even heard I was responsible for Ray's departure. That's so
stupid. Ray had an opportunity to go somewhere. He has a chance to
win a Cup and Harry being the great hockey man he is, acknowledged
that and he put him on a pretty good team. I don't know if he'll
play next year but he's a great individual, a great person, and a
great hockey player. This is not the first time this has come up
with Ray Bourque. If the team would have been doing better maybe he
wouldn't have asked for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he's not going to take anything to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think until Mr. Jacobs talks to me personally and tells me
exactly what he said, I'm not going to believe anything,'' said
Burns. ``If he wants to talk to me personally I'd definitely
entertain an occasion to talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Jacobs's long-distance ownership is no different than
some of the owners he's played for in the past. Though he might
have seen his bosses in Montreal and Toronto more, he didn't speak
to them that much, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is normal for me,'' said Burns. ``I know the trend now is
for owners to be more hands on, and if that's the case, fine. We're
employees and they're the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has his teaching cap on, and said a few days ago he wanted
to enjoy his team the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players need to go out and have fun and play together and
work,'' said Burns. ``Management wants to see these young players,
so we're going to see them. So now you're trying to pull for them
to do their best. I think it's more than wins right now. There's a
lot of pressure on them, so I don't want to be sitting behind them
and over their shoulder, but I do want to correct things and try to
make them better players for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had fun in (the Buffalo game Wednesday) except for one
mental mistake at the end, and then it was back to square one, so
today you've got to bring them back up again and say, `Hey, we
played 60 hard minutes and we had fun doing it and we tried
something new, and the guys liked it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Burns may have the reputation of being a tough coach, but he
won't be a screamer now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put them out there and when they come back and we see
something we tell them, but they have to find their own way,'' he
said. ``This is a different league. It's gone beyond taking a guy
aside for the rest of the year and say you have to do this and do
that. We're asking players to do what they do best and we have to
see whether it's good enough or not to play for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs expressed disappointment with Sergei Samsonov because his
play has tailed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (Jason) Allison, Samsonov never had the centerman who
he had all those points with,'' said Burns. ``He ends up playing
with Joe (Thornton) and things haven't clicked. They're young.
They're two 20-year-olds. (Actually Samsonov is 21). They're out
there every night, and asking them to win games for us all the time
is tough. I know they're going to struggle in areas, but when they
have the opportunities to score they have to finish them. Sergei's
a hard worker. He's one of the hardest workers on the team. He's
not a big guy and other teams know that . . . they're banging him
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said on several occasions he's had to refocus the team,
especially lately in light of Bourque's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told everybody to shut up (about the Bourque
situation),'' Burns said. ``Forget talking about it and the
mudslinging. Everybody's just got to be quiet and do their job and
get through this thing. We have five weeks to go and that's a long
time to bury your head. I think it's getting through. You see the
players aren't really involved in this mess. They're not the cause
of what happened and shouldn't be implicated.''
</P>
<P>
   For so much of Burns's career, he's been battling for and in the
playoffs. Not now. While he has a plan for the players, what's the
plan for himself? How does he keep from getting discouraged?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job, simple as that,'' said Burns. ``I could go in
there and yell and scream at them, but am I going to get anywhere?
I don't think so. They do have some experience. At this time of the
year, you don't yell and scream and punish, punish, punish. We do a
lot of correcting and that's what keeps us upbeat. We're a very
young and inexperienced team right now. We have three guys with 300
games or more, that's not a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The players knew Bourque's days were numbered, and some now feel
Burns may be next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's another coach then the players will like that
coach,'' Burns said. ``That doesn't change. If Pat Burns had to
leave tomorrow or at the end of the season or midway through the
season next year, that's not gonna change. The players just feel .
. . is it wrong when players want to play for a coach? The game has
changed. This is not your kick-in-the-pants-all-the-time anymore or
stick-over-the-head stuff, or bench 'em stuff. Players know what to
expect from you. But there's been so many changes with this club
all year, players up and down, up and down. It's very difficult to
have any kind of system.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he's trying to find new leaders. He chatted Thursday
with Kyle McLaren and told him, ``If you want to be a leader on the
club, you have to lead by example. You have to bring the level of
your game up to be able to say, `Hey, let's go.' If you're not
doing it, it's very difficult to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would say it's difficult for Burns to lead under the
circumstances, that his situation is now becoming a death watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be an evaluation at the end of the year,'' Burns
said. ``That's fine. I just have to go about my business and do the
best job I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
