<HEADLINE>
GROUP CITES RISE IN ANTI-GAY HARASSMENT IN MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reports of anti-gay harassment in the military more
than doubled last year, despite renewed Pentagon efforts to curb
such abuse after the killing of a gay soldier in his barracks, a
legal aid group for gay service members said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Servicemembers Legal Defense Network received reports of 968
cases of verbal abuse and physical assaults last year, according to
the group's annual report. It was the worst year for harassment
since the group began monitoring the military's ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing from service members that harassment is very bad
and in some commands it is getting worse,'' said Michelle M.
Benecke, co-executive director of the group. ``People are getting
fed up at being put in situations where they have to choose between
safety and staying in the service.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday that he would read the report
and ``take appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this report is accurate, I would expect to see a
substantial improvement this year. Substantial,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has called for the elimination of the
policy, saying that ``gays and lesbians should be allowed to serve
their country without discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican candidate
for president, supports the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, which
allows gay men and lesbians to serve in the military as long as
they keep their sexual orientation to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said Thursday that while they had no figures
to support the claim of an increase in abuse of gays, they would
study the new report by the private group and investigate the
incidents it cited.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are specifics in this report that talk about
harassment, we will follow up,'' said Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a
spokesman for the Pentagon. ``I don't want to belittle it, but we
just need to take a look.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder of Army Pfc. Barry Winchell at Fort Campbell, Ky.,
marked a turning point in the debate over the Pentagon's policy.
</P>
<P>
   After a much publicized conviction of Pvt. Calvin Glover in that
killing, the president said in a radio interview that the ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy was ``out of whack.'' Soon afterward,
Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen ordered the Pentagon's
inspector general to investigate the extent of anti-gay harassment.
He also ordered all service members, from privates to generals, to
receive training this year on the policy.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report will be issued later this month.
So far, the military has largely judged how well the policy was
working by keeping track of the number of service members
discharged for being gay. In 1999, 10 percent fewer were discharged
for being gay: 1,034 compared with 1,145 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's report, entitled ``Conduct Unbecoming,'' argued
that the policy was ``a tortured law'' that was difficult to
understand and apply. ``This details the dramatic and horrifying
results of a bad policy made worse by failed leadership,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the policy had resulted in the discharges of
three people a day on grounds of being gay. Several Pentagon
officials say there is evidence that some service members declare
they are gay solely to leave the military with honorable
discharges. Benecke disputed that contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are overwhelmingly coming out because of harassment,
which is not an easy way to get out of the service'' Benecke said.
</P>
<P>
   The legal aid group said that its methods of reporting these
incidents had improved and that more service members knew about the
group. But the group said that this did not account for the 142
percent increase in harassment reports over last year.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted an increase in anti-gay graffiti, verbal abuse
and harassment of lesbians. Women were being discharged at the
highest rate in two decades, according to the report, which singled
out the Defense Language Institute at Monterey, Calif., for
discharging 12 Air Force women.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the group said there had been some
improvements, in particular ``physical abuse by investigators and
criminal prosecutions of lesbian, gay and bisexual service members
have all subsided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
