<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-VOTERS-REBELS-NYT &LR;      03-09 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: BOWING OUT, MCCAIN AND BRADLEY FIND COMMON GROUND
ANEW
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they did so vividly three months ago in Claremont, N.H., the
campaigns of John McCain and Bill Bradley again found common ground
Thursday. In mirror-image speeches barely an hour apart, the
conservative Republican and the liberal Democrat abandoned the
presidential race, leaving the country to puzzle over the demise of
a pair of candidacies that had once so captured the fancy of the
American press and public.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tidy television package, the sight of these vanquished
politicians, their wives at their sides, offering their clipped
exit lines to the applause of their staffs. But something more than
the multimillion-dollar apparatus of two national campaigns was now
to be dismantled. What was disappearing from the stage with them
was something less tangible: the romance of the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, it looked as if this might be the year of the
maverick. In the months before the caucuses and primaries began,
the insurgent candidacies of Bradley and McCain seemed to click
with voters in an elemental way. It was as if a fairly prosperous
electorate, content for the most part with how the machinery of
government was functioning, wanted something spiritually deeper in
its next commander-in-chief. The sentiment was sensed by reporters:
``Authenticity'' was the first buzzword of the season, another way
of saying that in the race for a successor to President Clinton, it
appeared that character was going to count for a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Though insiders by virtue of their Washington credentials,
McCain, the senator from Arizona, and Bradley, the former senator
from New Jersey. were the embodiments of outsider-ness on the
stump. McCain's instantly legendary campaign bus, the Straight Talk
Express, became a rolling metaphor for this ethos of unfiltered
politics: it was ``The Real World'' on wheels. And Bradley's
stoop-shouldered naturalness _ a man ``comfortable in his own
skin,'' was how the scribes put it _ sent the Hydralike campaign of
Vice President Al Gore into a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Gore was closing down shop in Washington and _ mimicking
Bradley's decision to place his headquarters in a nondescript
medical-office building in West Orange, N.J. _ relocated his
operation back home, in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The news media were dazzled, especially by McCain, a Republican
from a wing of the party not known for harboring a deep affection
for the national press. And unlike some mavericks of the past,
including Pat Buchanan or Ross Perot, the McCain and Bradley
candidacies, as the conservative commentator William Kristol has
noted, were optimistic in tone. Each had a highly media-genic story
and an apparent zeal to shake things up: one, a swashbuckling war
hero crusading for campaign finance reform, the other, an
introspective former basketball star asking the nation to embrace
the politics of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Their idealistic appeals had their moments; it even looked for a
time _ more recently for McCain than Bradley _ that they would pull
off something close to impossible in modern presidential politics,
melt the heart of a major party with the heat of insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, these were rebels who lost their causes,
beaten back by standard-bearers of the establishment, a pair of
political heirs with proud old inside-the-beltway pedigrees and
famous family names.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's fate, complicated by a monthlong dormancy in the
Democratic primary-election schedule and the more intense media
focus on the Republican contest, had seemed sealed in the weeks
after his crushing defeats in Iowa and New Hampshire, where he
invested millions of dollars. But the end of McCain's joy ride came
on Super Tuesday with astonishing swiftness, after a seesaw battle
with Gov. George W. Bush that kept the nation entertained and
talking politics for much of the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Party primaries are essentially family feuds. And as countless
commentators noted, it was always going to be hugely difficult for
Bradley or McCain to appropriate the seat at the head of the table
from a sitting vice president or a big-state governor who could
count on the blessings of virtually all the party elders.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the decks were stacked against them, the two
insurgents saw their auras dissipate as the race progressed.
Bradley's lethargic demeanor and laid-back campaigning style looked
increasingly like indifference, and the vigor of McCain turned ever
more vinegary under the relentless pressure, in the form of attack
ads, applied by forces allied with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, their opponents' campaigns began to understand that
Bradley and McCain had tapped into an unease in the population
about the two front-runners: it seemed that a scripted candidate,
in an age of casual Fridays and blockbuster movies made with
hand-held cameras, was something of a throwback. So they tried to
draw on the outsider aura. Gore now showed up at events in his
shirt sleeves; Bush tried to co-opt his rival's mantle of reform:
he was not only a compassionate conservative, but also a reformer
with results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the missteps he might have made in recent weeks,
McCain had supplied much of the primary season's adrenalin, and one
could almost sense it draining out of the race Thursday as he stood
disconsolately at the podium, promising to continue his crusade in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As Jonathan Alter, the commentator for NBC News and Newsweek,
put it, ``It's just the end of the fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2043EST &QL; 
