<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ART-NYT &LR;      03-09 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY ENDS CAMPAIGN FOR PRESIDENCY AND OFFERS `SUPPORT' TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT5 and NYT7, have been sent to New York Times
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ After an often bitter 14-month, $30-million
campaign in which he failed to win a single primary, former Sen.
Bill Bradley ended his quest for the presidency Thursday, saying
the time had come to unite the Democratic Party behind Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bradley pledged to work for Gore's victory in the
general election in November, he did not release his roughly 400
delegates, presumably to give him more influence at the Democratic
National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bradley said he would not hesitate to criticize the
vice president if he engaged in the same kind of negative
campaigning against Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive
Republican nominee, that Bradley had accused Gore of using during
the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he'll run a better campaign in the general
election,'' Bradley said of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before teary-eyed aides in a hall near his national
headquarters here, Bradley, whose party loyalty was questioned by
Gore during the campaign, called it a Democratic tradition ``to
fight hard during primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And now it is time for unity,'' said Bradley, his wife,
Ernestine, at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats know that the offerings of the likely Republican
nominee and his party are the opposite of where our country should
be headed,'' he said. ``This country needs Democratic leadership,
and I will work to ensure a Democratic White House and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he called Gore earlier Thursday to offer his
support and congratulations, though he declined to discuss details
of their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore released a statement in which he praised Bradley as ``a
good man'' and then made an appeal to his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend Bill, Ernestine, and all their staff and supporters
for running a good campaign based on the highest ideals,'' Gore
said. ``They showed real courage, conviction and commitment in
taking their message to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were ample signs Thursday that it would not be easy
for Gore to win over Bradley's core supporters. There was, for
example, talk among some of Bradley's aides of ``guerrilla action''
against the Gore campaign. His staff groaned when Bradley was asked
whether he would run as Gore's vice president, and cheered when he
said no.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed in a news conference to explain why he had not used the
word ``endorse,'' Bradley showed a flash of irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had this a number of times in the campaign,'' he said.
``I'm not parsing words today, I'm saying very clearly, I have
called him, I said I would support him, I intend to support him,
and I intend to work for the Democratic ticket and for Democrats to
regain control of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Anita Dunn, Bradley's communications director,
asserted that Bradley was using ``endorse'' and ``support''
interchangeably. ``He likes to say he supports candidates and
endorses checks,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While his aides blinked back tears, Bradley looked relaxed and
cheerful. He even opened his speech with a joke for reporters,
saying, ``I want to begin this morning with a discussion of my
favorite books.'' (During the campaign, Bradley would routinely
brush aside questions about his favorite books, films, philosophers
or foods.)
</P>
<P>
   When the news conference was over, he tried to show that he had
no hard feelings toward the press corps that has followed him since
last fall by giving each member two gifts: a box of the same kinds
of lozenges he rolled in his mouth during events and a key chain
with a silver basketball shoe from Tiffany &AMP; Co. (The New York
Times' policy prohibits staff members from accepting gifts of more
than trivial value. The key chain will be returned with thanks.)
</P>
<P>
   But the gifts could not hide the fact that many of Bradley's
advisers feel that he was unfairly written off by the news media
after he lost the New Hampshire on Feb. 1, five weeks before
Tuesday's climactic primaries and caucuses in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech was uncharacteristically short, lasting about
five minutes. His news conference, on the other hand, was one of
the longest he has given in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In it, he refused to expand on what his campaign did wrong,
drawing an almost mystical analogy to Marcel Proust's seven-volume
novel, ``Remembrance of Things Past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that the seven volumes are written, and by the
end of the seventh volume, he says `Well, now I think I really know
what it is to write,''' Bradley said. ``And that might apply to
this campaign, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not say whether he would run again for president,
saying that his only plan was to take a vacation. Asked to explain
what the defeat meant, he said: ``For me personally, today means,
you know, the closing of this chapter. It is something that I
believe I gave my full heart, mind, soul and energy to. And it
didn't turn out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
