<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAUNDER-LEGISLATION-N     03-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUNDER-LEGISLATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFSHORE BANKING BILL ATTACKED AS SCHUMER VOWS TO TOUGHEN
PROPOSAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa)    By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Promising a ``fight on the floor of the Senate,''
Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said Thursday that he planned to
``toughen up'' legislation proposed by the Clinton administration
to combat money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's main criticism of a White House proposal announced on
Wednesday was that penalties against offshore banks or countries
would be left to the discretion of U.S. authorities rather than
being set off automatically when money-laundering abuses are
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a hearing on money laundering convened by Rep. Jim
Leach, the Iowa Republican who is chairman of the House Banking
Committee, Schumer said that an effective policy against money
laundering required that suspect offshore banks be automatically
forbidden access to the U.S. banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my years as a legislator, I've observed time and again that
in the international arena, discretion is usually a code word for
delay and avoid,'' Schumer said. ``There is no reason to allow any
of these banks to exist because we know their sole _ and only _
purpose is money laundering. What discretion do we need?''
</P>
<P>
   Money laundering refers to the practice of filtering profits
from illegal activities through banks to disguise their origin. The
White House initiative is a response to heightened awareness of
money laundering that emerged after the disclosure last year that
$7 billion in suspect Russian funds had moved through the Bank of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department has proposed an array of legislative and
regulatory initiatives aimed at money laundering, including the
designation of metropolitan areas deemed high-risk zones for such
activities. The department is also asking Congress for broad new
powers to combat money laundering, including the authority to ban
financial transactions between United States banks or brokerage
houses and offshore financial centers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal has been criticized by some in
Washington as too little, too late. The House and Senate Banking
committees have already submitted anti-money-laundering
legislation, and members of both committees have been working
closely together to devise a compromise bill. That legislation
would place a greater burden on financial institutions to determine
the actual beneficiaries of bank and brokerage accounts and to
police money-laundering problems themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Leach and Rep. John J. LaFalce, D-N.Y., have been more
supportive of the administration's proposal. They introduced the
administration's anti-money-laundering bill into the House
Thursday, saying that it ``builds in a constructive, although more
limited, basis'' on their own legislation. Leach said he hoped
Congress and the White House could ``pass meaningful
anti-money-laundering legislation this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Eizenstat, deputy secretary of the Treasury, testified
Thursday that penalties against offshore banks and jurisdictions
should be discretionary ``so that the response we make is
proportionate to the problem.'' He said he saw a ``potential for
real problems'' if penalties were imposed on ``automatic pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said the administration would push to add political
corruption to the list of crimes that would fall under the legal
umbrella of money laundering. Investigators examining the suspect
transactions at the Bank of New York think that some of the funds
may represent the proceeds of political graft in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Leach had planned to subpoena Peter Berlin and Lucy Edwards, two
main suspects in the Bank of New York investigation, to testify
before his committee Thursday but decided not to do so at the
request of the Justice Department. Berlin and Edwards recently
pleaded guilty to money laundering and are cooperating with federal
investigators. Leach said, however, that his ``patience in this
regard has its limits'' and that he would seek the couple's
testimony at the earliest possible date. A member of Leach's staff
said the couple would be asked to testify no later than this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan M. Winer, a former deputy assistant secretary of state,
testified that a Bank of New York affiliate based in Geneva _ Bank
of New York-Inter Maritime _ was a leading provider of banking
services to Internet gambling companies based in the Caribbean.
Winer said such activities were troubling because ``Internet casino
gambling, among other innovative financial solutions, has the
potential to provide an open invitation to money launderers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York declined to comment. Officials at the Bank
of New York-Inter Maritime could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHR     03-09 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN SUSPENDS CAMPAIGN, BUT DEFERS BUSH ENDORSEMENT  
 (SUBS throughout for rewriting)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6, NYT8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ Sen. John McCain, whose insurgency became the
surprise of the presidential primary season, on Wednesday ended his
maverick bid for the Republican nomination with the hope that he
would eventually prevail in ``making our party as big as the
country we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after being defeated by Texas Gov. George W. Bush in
primaries from coast to coast, the Arizona senator, standing with
striated mountains and the glorious Verde Valley as his backdrop,
acknowledged that no matter how many crossover voters he had
attracted, he was not the preference of the majority in his own
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore I announce today, on this fine Arizona morning and
in this beautiful place, that I am not longer an active candidate
for my party's nomination for president,'' McCain said, his wife,
Cindy, at his side.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had gracious words for Bush, congratulating him but
stopping short of endorsing him. The senator also said he would not
``walk away from'' his fight for reform, adding: ``What is good for
my country is good for my party. Should our party ever abandon this
principle, the American people will rightly abandon us, and we will
surely slip into the mists of history, deserving the allegiance of
none.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain made his announcement only an hour after former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey withdrew from the Democratic race. Their
decisions brought an abrupt end to the primary season and set the
stage for what promises to be a costly and bitter battle between
Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Colorado, congratulated McCain ``for
fighting the good fight'' and called the senator's concession
``gracious.'' The governor also said he had a short telephone
conversation with McCain. He said there was no timetable for longer
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us have just come off a tough campaign,'' Bush said,
``John needs some time to think. I need some time. But I believe
that when it's all said and done that we can have a good
dialogue,'' Bush said. ``I intend to talk with him at his
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone call followed a series of back-door conversations
between supporters of Bush and Washington-based supporters of
McCain. It began what many Republicans hope will be a process of
reconciliation that could lead to McCain's eventual endorsement of
Bush and allow the Republican nominee to hold on to many of the
independents and new voters that had flocked to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But the hurdles for the party go beyond the personal
rapprochement needed after such a bitter campaign. With McCain
insisting that he would continue his fight for reform, he and Bush
will have to bridge fundamental differences between their agendas,
in particular McCain's advocacy of overhauling the campaign finance
system and his support of a tax cut plan that is at odds with
Republican orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they thought avenues of compromise could
emerge.``There's no way you're going to be able to meld everything
Bush said and McCain said and get a broth that's eatable,'' said
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who is close to McCain and who has been
working to smooth the way for a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question you'll have to sand off the edges to fit
it,'' Hagel said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also seemed to leave open the option of using his 231
delegates, from seven state delegations as a force to press for
changes in the party platform at the Republican National Convention
this summer. Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, said the
senator was keeping an organization together to ``maintain contact
with our delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will press for measures that are germane for reform,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis downplayed any idea that platform fight would be
necessary and and spoke like a loyal Republican of the necessity of
defeating Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2051EST &QL; 
