<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOULDER-DA-NYT &LR;      03-09 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOULDER-DA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRICT ATTORNEY IN RAMSEY CASE DECLINES TO SEEK RE-ELECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Alex Hunter, the Boulder County district attorney
leading the investigation of the killing of JonBenet Ramsey,
announced Thursday that he would leave his office at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The decision not to seek an eighth four-year term was
influenced, he said, more by family considerations than by the
Ramsey case, despite widespread criticism over his handling of it.
</P>
<P>
   Since the body of the 6-year-old girl was found in her parents'
home more than three years ago, no one has been arrested. Hunter
adjourned a grand jury last fall after his prosecutors failed to
produce enough evidence to indict anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hunter, 63, defended his work and said he would
remain active in the case through the end of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is the American public would like to hang
somebody for this case,'' he said in an interview. ``So would Alex
Hunter and 10 other prosecutors who have said there is not enough
evidence. But by not filing a case, it means we've done the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no apologies to make,'' he added, ``even if the public
has a different take on things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter burst into public view after Dec. 29, 1996, the day
JonBenet's body was found, bound and strangled.
</P>
<P>
   The case drew instant worldwide attention because of the age of
the victim and videotapes released by the Ramsey family that showed
her dressed like a little cowgirl, singing and dancing in child
beauty contests.
</P>
<P>
   But sloppy police work on the morning the body was discovered
compromised evidence, leading to quick public denunciations of
Hunter and Boulder investigators. Criticism continued over the next
several years as investigators failed to develop enough evidence to
charge anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said in October after dismissing the grand jury that the
investigation would continue with the girl's parents, John and
Patsy Ramsey, ``under the umbrella of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   But little has changed since then, and investigators seem no
closer now to an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, the son of a former mayor of Briarcliff Manor, N.Y.,
said that after he leaves office he plans to spend more time with
his five children, two of whom are lawyers in private practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TRADE-925(2TA     03-09 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRADE-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE STILL LACKS VOTES TO PASS CHINA TRADE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Miss., Calif., Ore., N.Y., S.D., Minn., Texas, Mich.,
Ariz.)   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in `i' news file)  
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration conceded Thursday that
