<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-HONGKONG-BOAT-PEOPLE-     03-09 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-BOAT-PEOPLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE REFUGEES IN HONG KONG TO FACE LIFE OUTSIDE THE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Ask Nguyen Kim Lien about life inside the
barbed-wire fence of the Pillar Point Vietnamese Refugee Camp here
and she is remarkably stoic. Her family lives in squalor _ a couple
of rooms in a dilapidated housing block, where rats prowl brazenly
outside the door. Her husband, who is out of work and addicted to
heroin, spends his days wandering the camp in a haze.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nguyen Kim Lien, 36, has found dignity amid the debris. She
runs a shop that sells Vietnamese noodles to the camp's 1,070
refugees. Her two children, who were born in Hong Kong and have
never lived outside the camp, go to a nearby school, where they are
learning to read and write Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   If she has a reason to despair, it is because in two months she
and her family must leave Pillar Point and find a way to support
themselves elsewhere in Hong Kong. Last month, this former British
colony announced it was shutting down its only remaining refugee
camp, ending a drama that began in May 1975, a month after the fall
of Saigon, when the first boat laden with refugees came ashore
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' said Lien, who fled Vietnam in 1988 and has been
in Pillar Point since 1991. ``Inside the camp, I can support
myself. But outside, I don't know. I'm scared that I won't get used
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   People like Nguyen Kim Lien are the ebb tide of a vast diaspora.
Of the more than 800,000 Vietnamese who passed through camps in
Southeast Asian countries between 1975 and the late-1980s, about
224,000 came to Hong Kong. Most of these went on to settle in the
United States, Canada and other countries. At its peak in 1979,
there were 68,695 refugees crowded into camps throughout the
colony.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong says it treated the boat people better than other
Asian countries, welcoming them sooner and taking care of them
longer. But it granted residency to only a small number of ethnic
Chinese refugees and by the mid-1990s it had put 94,700 people on
planes back to Vietnam _ often dragging them up the ramp.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,900 boat people left in Hong Kong have fallen between all
the cracks. After more than a decade of filing applications, they
cannot gain asylum anywhere else. And they either cannot or will
not return to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Hong Kong has closed its doors to immigrants from
mainland China, it is no longer willing to take care of these
holdouts. In February, it agreed to give them legal status here,
but also imposed a deadline: move into society by May 31. They can
choose to remain refugees, but Hong Kong will no longer try to find
them homes overseas. It will also stop paying for their housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to close this chapter of history,'' said
Regina Ip, Hong Kong's secretary of security, who handles
immigration policy. ``It's been a problem for Hong Kong for a
quarter of a century.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong's ultimatum sounds abrupt, few people fault
the government for imposing it. Even critics say the continued
existence of Pillar Point has become an intractable hurdle to the
efforts of the Vietnamese to get on with their lives. A grim,
isolated compound, it is a breeding ground for drug abuse, petty
crime and sporadic violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the camps were virtual prisons, but now Pillar
Point is open, and residents are encouraged to find jobs outside.
But the housing blocks were meant to be temporary structures, and
they now look like abandoned army barracks. Even after more than a
decade, life for the refugees still feels tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, police broke up a riot between Vietnamese and ethnic
Chinese refugees, also from Vietnam, who live uneasily next to each
other. Sixteen people were injured in the melee. A chain-link fence
topped with barbed wire now slices through the camp to separate the
two groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The condition of the camp is appalling,'' said Pam Baker, a
British lawyer who has represented boat people in cases against the
government. ``It really is a purpose-built den of iniquity.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has prodded the refugees to move into
their own apartments, it refused to grant them legal status, and
the accompanying identification cards. That makes it hard for them
to find decent work. With rents in Hong Kong among the highest in
Asia, the lure of free housing pulls many back into the camp. Along
with residency, the refugees would get ID cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a logical conclusion, but it's not a complete
conclusion,'' Baker said. ``What's going to happen to those people
who are not accepted for residency? What's going to happen to those
who are not allowed to apply?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 130 people would seem to fall into one of those
categories. Most have been classified as illegal immigrants or
economic migrants rather than refugees. The Vietnamese government
has refused to take many back because they have criminal records or
health problems. Hong Kong insists it will continue trying to
repatriate them, though it is vague about what it will do if that
fails.
</P>
<P>
   For those who gain residency, the biggest challenge may be
shedding the habits and attitudes developed in years of camp life.
Diep Long Anh, an ethnic Chinese who fled Ho Chi Minh City in 1990,
said she thought about moving out several times. But the free
housing allows Diep, 42, to stay home with her son while her
husband works as a laborer on a construction site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't want to work,'' Diep said. ``We're not
lazy. It's just that we worry about getting jobs. It's so expensive
to live outside.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees still nourish dreams of moving to California or
Canada. This is despite the fact that Hong Kong resettled only 71
people in 1999, and a single person so far this year. The U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, which had helped process applications,
is so beset with refugee problems in Africa and the Balkans that it
no longer finances its program here. In a few months, it will
reassign its local officer and oversee Hong Kong from its Beijing
office. Officials here note that the United Nations owes $149
million for the upkeep of the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hong Kong's financial outlays, the sense of futility
among many refugees has mutated into bitterness toward their
adopted home. Some blame their predicament on Hong Kong's return to
China in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here because we wanted freedom, but now Hong Kong is a
Communist country,'' said Nguyen Van Thang, a wiry man with hollow
eyes who looks older than his 28 years. Thang said he still hoped
to move to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the refugees regard their future with dread. Pham Thi
Binh, a 33-year-old woman who arrived in Hong Kong in 1988, has
bounced in and out of Pillar Point a few times as she and her
husband have tried to make it outside. They both work on a
construction site; she as a welder and concrete pourer. Binh is
determined to succeed, not least because she wants her 11-year-old
son to mix with local children.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years in Hong Kong, we know we just have to
work hard,'' she said. ``If I save enough, I'll go back and invest
in Vietnam,'' she added, with a smile so broad that it briefly
lifted the camp's gloom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
