<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SHUTTLE-SAFETY-ART-NY     03-09 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUDY RAISES SAFETY ISSUES FOR THE SPACE SHUTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Efforts to cut the costs of operating the space
shuttle are eroding safety, and NASA needs to immediately take a
more active role in shuttle operations by private contractors to
reduce risks, an independent study group said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, one of the most significant of shuttle safety since
the Challenger disaster in 1986, was organized by NASA in September
to review maintenance practices for the four-shuttle fleet. Turning
shuttle operations over to private contractors four years ago has
streamlined operations and greatly reduced costs, the panel said in
a report. However, it said, these changes may have gone too far,
resulting in systemic problems that threaten safety.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of key staff members through personnel reductions,
increased workloads and stress on remaining workers, and
simplifying operational procedures raises major concerns that
safety in the shuttle program is being eroded, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report has identified significant problems that must be
addressed to maintain an effective program,'' the committee wrote.
The panel said the problems it found ``appear to be systemic in
nature and not confined to any one shuttle sub-system or element.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended an immediate increase in the workforce
servicing and monitoring the shuttles. Implying that NASA may have
stepped back too far in allowing contractors to run shuttle
operations, the panel said the new workers should be NASA
employees, not contract workers. NASA needs more hands-on
involvement in maintenance and safety, the report said, and not
just serve as a ``safety auditor'' of contractor activities.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-member group, headed by Dr. Henry McDonald, director of
NASA's Ames Research Center in California, and including experts in
civilian and military aviation, made 81 recommendations for
improving shuttle maintenance and operations. Some called for
immediate action, which NASA said it had carried out, while others
called for changes to be put into place over the next six months
and later.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph H. Rothenberg, NASA's associate administrator for space
flight, told a news conference that safety continues to be the
agency's main priority for the shuttle program and that NASA would
study the recommendations and act upon them as soon as possible.
However, he said the panel listed some practices and changes in its
recommendations that are valid for aircraft and airline operations,
but that may not apply to the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, ``We're not going to dismiss any of these
recommendations out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg noted that the panel supported the continued flight
of shuttles while its recommendations were being considered and
acted upon. ``They endorsed the shuttle as safe to fly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NASA put together the study group because of maintenance
questions that arose after a flight last July by the shuttle
Columbia. On that flight, a short circuit in a wire where
insulation had been worn away knocked out a computerized controller
for one of the three main engines, and a backup had to take over.
In addition, a small pin came loose in one engine and damaged
liquid hydrogen lines in an engine nozzle, resulting in the shuttle
going into a slightly lower than expected orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Resulting inspections found damage caused by maintenance workers
in all four shuttles, resulting in the fleet being grounded for
months for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The panel made four recommendations concerning safety
inspections _ including one to have shuttle managers re-examine 76
critical electrical areas for which there are no backups _ that
NASA acted upon before shuttles began flying again in December,
Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, another study group, NASA's Aerospace Safety
Advisory Panel, expressed similar concerns about the shortages of
skilled engineers and technicians brought about by past staff
reductions. The panel said cutbacks and reorganizations within NASA
and contractors had created problems that could affect safety.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Goldin, the NASA administrator, said the agency was
aware of these staffing problems and had asked for money in next
year's budget to start hiring 1,850 new employees to make up for
past attrition by retirements and buyouts. He said new employees
were needed to add people with certain skills and experience, with
an emphasis on safety engineers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-COURTS-NYT &LR;      03-09 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-COURTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S CHIEF JUSTICE STRIVES TO OIL A CREAKING SYSTEM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Seated at his desk, Chief Justice Genaro Gongora
Pimentel was partly hidden behind an 18-inch stack of judicial
papers. With assembly line rhythm, a clerk was pulling writs and
rulings from atop the pile, sliding scores of them, one after the
other, under the chief justice's hand for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   This clerical drudgery took much of an hour. It is not
uncharacteristic of routines at the Mexican Supreme Court, where
the caseload is overwhelming. Last year Gongora and his 10
colleagues issued 6,573 rulings. The U.S. Supreme Court issued 75.
</P>
<P>
   The workload is one sign of the archaic state of the Mexican
judiciary, the weak sister in the country's out-of-kilter system of
checks and balances. The opposition-led Congress, though still
dominated by an overwhelmingly powerful executive branch, is
flexing new muscles. But the court system remains feeble.
</P>
<P>
   That is what the chief justice says he is determined to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to modernize our federal judiciary,'' he said during a
recent 90-minute interview in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Since he began a four-year term as chief justice last year,
Gongora has lobbied publicly for measures to reduce the court's
workload and to strengthen its role as a referee between the
executive and legislative powers. He has endorsed Mexico's
evolution toward democracy more forcefully than any previous chief
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to be upset,'' he told reporters as he left
a tumultuous session of Congress last fall in which President
Ernesto Zedillo had been heckled and raucous booing had drowned out
the speech of an opposition member. ``This was a display of
pluralism. We Mexicans need to get used to new times.''
</P>
<P>
   His public candor has won him many admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court was silent before,'' said Hector Fix Zamudio, a
prominent Mexican constitutional scholar. ``Justice Gongora has
given it an active voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his initiatives have drawn criticism, too. The court's
appointment of about 50 new federal judges last fall under an
expedited process that sidestepped requirements for a competitive
examination aroused a furor in legal circles here. Many of the new
judges have close professional ties to Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to confront the judiciary's problems, which is
praiseworthy,'' said Jose Ramon Cossio Diaz, the law dean at Mexico
City's Autonomous Technological Institute, whom Gongora invited to
serve on a judicial reform commission. ``But the way he's gone
about trying to strengthen the court is dangerous and could bring
the judiciary into general discredit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican judiciary has never enjoyed the prestige of the
executive branch. A prominent lawyer returned from studies at
Harvard University in 1972 convinced of the need to strengthen the
Supreme Court, and urged a leader of the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party to seek appointment as its chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to be Mexico's John Marshall,'' the lawyer said,
referring to 19th-century America's pioneering chief justice. The
party leader just laughed. ``He said I didn't know how things
worked, that to be on the Supreme Court was just to be in limbo,''
the lawyer recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Three presidents in this century have simply dismissed Mexico's
entire Supreme Court. One was Zedillo, who in his first month in
office removed all 26 justices, installing a new 11-member court.
</P>
<P>
   Gongora, who is 62, was one of Zedillo's new appointments.
Before his nomination, he served as a judge, appellate magistrate
and law professor. His colleagues voted him chief justice in
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, in a speech before Zedillo and hundreds of
other senior officials, Gongora urged constitutional amendments to
increase the Supreme Court's power. Approved last June, they
relieved the court of the obligation to rule on hundreds of arcane
jurisdictional disputes that had clogged its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But its caseload remains extraordinary, and Gongora's most
ambitious initiative to date is in part aimed at reducing it
further. He has invited judges, lawyers and law professors to draft
a new, simpler law governing the fundamental procedure by which
Mexicans appeal sentences, file habeas corpus petitions, seek
injunctions and contest the constitutionality of laws.
</P>
<P>
   A curious feature of the system is that Supreme Court rulings
declaring laws unconstitutional apply only to the victorious
plaintiff. All other Mexicans must continue to obey the flawed law
or file their own constitutional challenges, forcing the court to
review the same law over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Gongora's sense of the urgency of judicial reform stems in part
from his belief that Mexico must modernize its institutions to
compete economically in a changing world.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he visited Washington and came away intrigued by
the American Supreme Court's power to reject cases considered
constitutionally irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfasting with other justices, he described how the American
court received about 7,000 appeals last year, but refused to
consider most of them. He also recalled reading that Justice
William O. Douglas had enjoyed white-water kayaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't that be great?'' Gongora added slyly to his
colleagues. ``If we had that much time, we'd be out there kayaking
too!''
</P>
<P>
   He said later he had meant no criticism of the American system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its crowded agenda, Mexico's Supreme Court has issued
several recent rulings that scholars say have moved it somewhat
from the president's shadow. In one, the court sided with a
defector from the governing party who challenged a law written
specifically to bar him from running for mayor of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often rule against the government,'' Gongora said.
</P>
<P>
   But legal scholars could recall no court ruling that had
circumscribed presidential power significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't dare,'' said Elisur Arteaga Nava, the author of
a standard four-volume text on Mexican constitutional law. ``Our
presidents are still far too powerful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
