<HEADLINE>
PEREZ AND HIS CONTRACT BEING WATCHED CLOSELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. - When it comes to the opening-day
roster, Dodgers left-hander Carlos Perez's contract might have
something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Daly, managing general partner and CEO of the Dodgers, said
all issues will be considered when it's time to fill the 25-man
roster that opens the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take into account everything,'' Daly said of
evaluating a player.
</P>
<P>
   Daly stressed the decisions will be left to general manager
Kevin Malone and manager Davey Johnson. But certain instances might
exist in which the front office gets more involved. One such case
could be Perez, who is owed $12.6 million over the next two
seasons. Though Perez could be sent to Triple-A Albuquerque, the
club might not be willing to send such a high-priced player to the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's an issue the Dodgers don't want to deal with
now, especially since he's pitched only once this spring. His next
outing is Saturday against St. Louis, but the whirlwind surrounding
him intensified when he allowed five runs in two innings in his
first appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that the next time out there, he'll have a little
better outing, show some signs,'' Johnson said. ``I'm looking for
him to have a better breaking ball, locate better. I don't want any
guy thinking they have to go out there, first time out, and start
tricking people with a changeup, split, curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is there's some competition going on in that
area. It's not one of those where you can kind of gear it up and
just peak at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   While other pitchers are cut slack, Perez is scrutinized for two
reasons: He's owed money and he was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if Carlos Perez doesn't have a much
better year than he did last year,'' Daly said. ``What role he
plays is a question. That's up to Davey to decide who starts. We
have a commitment to him. I have to assume the glass is half
full.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing helping Perez right now is the pitching of
rookie right-hander Eric Gagne. Though Gagne is expected to make
the rotation, he's competing with Perez and Orel Hershiser for one
of two spots. And for the second time in as many outings, he was
hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne allowed five runs, including a 420-foot, three-run blast
by Andruw Jones, in three innings Thursday against Atlanta. He's
allowed 12 runs in 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's spring training and I'm not here to throw no-hitters
every day,'' Gagne said. ``I'm here to get ready for a season. I'm
seeing the hitter, the catcher, the stands. Usually, in the season,
all I see is the glove. The last couple innings, my focus was a lot
better. The offseason, you lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Lefty Onan Masaoka was sharp in one scoreless
inning against Kansas City. It was his first action of the spring
after spraining his left ankle two weeks ago.... An MRI on the
shoulder of Kevin Gibbs, a minor-league outfielder with speed whom
Johnson likes, was negative. He's day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS vs. HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   When/Where: 10:05 a.m., Osceola County Stadium, Kissimmee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: XTRA 1150 AM (tape delay begins at 5:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: Manager Davey Johnson sees an old friend today as
Astros RH Doc Gooden faces the Dodgers. Going for the Dodgers is RH
Darren Dreifort, who is relishing not having to prove his worth as
a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's results: The losing continued as the Dodgers lost a
pair of games to fall to 1-8. Alan Mills allowed four runs in the
eighth inning of a 5-2 loss to Kansas City at Dodgertown.
Meanwhile, the Dodgers scored seven times in the ninth to tie it
but lost 8-7 to Atlanta on Tim Unroe's homer in the bottom of the
inning at Disney's Wide World of Sports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
