<SLUG> BC-COKE-DIVERSITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE CEO TIES MANAGEMENT COMPENSATION TO ACHIEVEMENTS IN 
 DIVERSITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a striking move intended to counter accusations that the
Coca-Cola Co. has not cared enough about building a diverse work
force, Coke's chairman and chief executive said Thursday that
management compensation at the company, including his own, will be
closely tied to still-unannounced diversity goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What gets measured gets done,'' said the executive, Douglas N.
Daft, who was elevated to Coke's top job last month. ``Diversity,
in its broadest sense, is a clear business imperative for our
company and its future, and it is a top priority for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The definition is broad, to be sure. A company spokesman, Ben
Deutsch, said diversity would ``include, but not be limited to
race, gender, lifestyle, national origin, age and religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been criticized for failing to promote black
employees, which resulted in a Federal lawsuit filed 11 months ago
by a group of current and former Coke workers. It has no women
among its senior and executive vice presidents, and except for Carl
Ware, a black executive vice president who was persuaded to call
off his retirement in January, white men control most of the power
in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Daft plans shortly to appoint a vice president for diversity
strategies, who will monitor efforts toward diversifying the work
force and report directly to him. ``My own success and compensation
will be tied to these diversity goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A possible candidate is Ingrid S. Jones, a vice president, who
is black and who has served on committees trying to improve Coke's
diversity. Deutsch, the spokesman, would not comment on candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement, made in a memo sent to all employees,
is a major shift for Coca-Cola, which is being sued by eight
current and former black employees who say they were unfairly
treated because of their race. The recommendation to name an
executive to supervise the diversity efforts came from the
company's diversity council, formed by the then-chairman and chief
executive, M. Douglas Ivester, after the lawsuit was filed in
April.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is one of several developments over the last year that
have stained the company's public image. It may have contributed to
Ivester's decision to retire last month at the age of 52.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the plaintiffs called the announcement ``a
spectacular victory'' and said it would improve conditions at the
company. ``This is the first step toward moving Coca-Cola from a
laggard to a leader on diversity,'' the lawyer, Cyrus Mehri, said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 consultant's report recommended ``developing a direct
link between diversity and other business objectives,'' although no
policy was outlined at that time.
</P>
<P>
   A report the same year from Ware made observations about life
for blacks within Coke like: ``Some African Americans are viewed
inappropriately as lacking the skills and intelligence to succeed
in certain areas.'' Ware's report also said that several black
executives who met to discuss diversity ``had been humiliated,
ignored, overlooked or unacknowledged,'' and relied on each other
``to provide sanity checks,'' which ``allowed many of them to
retain their psychological health.''
</P>
<P>
   His report, now more than four years old, called at the time for
specific diversity goals to be set.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst with Salomon Smith Barney,
said: ``The most important thing Coke needs to do is mend its
global public image. And if this helps in that respect, the
shareholders are going to benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft has signaled his intention to resolve the lawsuit as
quickly as possible. In January, the federal judge overseeing the
case ordered the contesting parties to try to reach a settlement.
To date, no talks have been held.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 people, many of them Coke employees, held a rally in
Atlanta on Saturday in which they said they might boycott the
company over its diversity record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
