</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-POLICE-SHOOTING-845&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTING BY POLICE LEAVES LOUISVILLE UNSETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In an episode with incendiary aspects of
racial divide, the aftermath of a deadly shooting by two officers
has plunged this proud, resilient city into open doubts about the
loyalty of its police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I fail, everything breaks down,'' Mayor David L. Armstrong
said as he worked to calm a citywide furor over a march on City
Hall last Friday by a large and angry part of the force.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of officers deserted their beats, startling residents, to
protest the mayor's firing of the police chief, Eugene Sherrard,
who without the mayor's knowledge had approved valor awards for two
officers at the heart of the simmering racial controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The awards for the two officers, both white, resulted from an
alleyway encounter last May in which they killed an unarmed black
car-theft suspect with a fusillade of 22 shots, an incident widely
denounced by blacks as an abuse of police power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, when the police marched down here, it left the
average citizen in a quandary, wondering one thing: Who's watching
over us?'' said the mayor, grim-faced from the protest, where, with
Sherrard in attendance, shouting officers cut off downtown traffic
and left the lights on their cruisers flashing ominously outside
the seat of government as they called for the mayor's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   To underline the resistance, the top nine commanders of the
720-member force also attended the rally and, in a dramatic
gesture, threw their badges down in sympathy with Sherrard.
</P>
<P>
   While the city is boiling with doubts about police fidelity,
majority support has quickly grown on the Board of Aldermen,
Louisville's legislative body, for a law that would increase
civilian oversight of the department through an appointed review
board.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, a 58-year-old Democrat with deep criminal-justice
roots as a past prosecutor and state attorney general often
endorsed by organizations of police officers, opposes the measure
for the same reason he felt obliged to fire Sherrard:
Accountability to the people, he stresses, must reside with
elected, not appointed, officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that complicated,'' the mayor said in his office,
which is a tense, busy place as he reaches out to church, business
and civic leaders to treat what he sadly terms a traumatic wound.
``There's one person the chief has to make happy, and that's the
elected representative of the people. And that did not happen, so I
removed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's standoff with the police continues. The rate of
misdemeanor arrests has begun dropping as the police union, though
denying ``blue flu'' resentment, accuses the mayor of ruining
morale. The union, Chapter 6 of the Fraternal Order of Police, is
planning another street protest on March 17, this time with the
city permit it lacked last Friday. It is distributing hundreds of
``Armstrong's Wrong'' T-shirts to citizens, contending that the
will of the majority is being overridden by the mayor, not the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor fell to a whole lot of political pressure from part
of the black community,'' Rick McCubbin, Chapter 6 president,
contended in defending the valor awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reacted in a threatening situation and unfortunately took
a life,'' McCubbin said of the two officers. ``But they won, if you
will,'' he added, alluding to a grand jury inquiry that cleared
them of criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual initiative, however, the grand jurors
ordered the city to conduct a special investigation of police
procedures to answer a series of troubling questions, among them
why detectives waited more than a week before questioning residents
near the scene of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The alleyway incident, in which the officers said they fired as
the suspect prepared to run them over with a vehicle, followed the
beating and jailhouse death of a black suspect that heightened
complaints about the state of criminal justice here. The trial of a
jail guard on homicide charges is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of that case and continuing investigations
into the alleyway shooting, Armstrong felt blindsided by Sherrard's
decision on the valor awards, part of an annual list for 63
officers deemed to have been put at risk in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   The chief let a month go by before telling City Hall, on the eve
of the awards dinner, causing chagrin in Armstrong, who had proudly
selected Sherrard for the top spot from the ranks of the department
14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible; it was a breach of trust,'' Armstrong said
of the award decision, emphasizing the highly delicate state of
affairs in this city of 269,000 people, of whom 70 percent are
white and 30 percent black. (The police force is 16 percent black.)
</P>
<P>
   As the furor grew, Sherrard apologized, saying, ``Unfortunately
I failed to anticipate some of the sentiment of the community.''
But the mayor, who, like Sherrard is white, decided the chief had
already demonstrated that he was more invested in the morale of his
rank and file than in the city's larger sensitivities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After he was fired, Sherrard was photographed proudly accepting
support at the headquarters of the union, which demanded his
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' the mayor said, ``is maybe a symptom of a small group
of folks on the force who have a culture. And this culture only
adds to the hostility of minorities who feel they are treated by
the police as second-class citizens, without respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Any doubter should drive in blackface in Louisville and ``find
out how often you're stopped,'' he advised, vowing to reform police
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sat on the sidelines and seen a lot of this stuff where
I couldn't make a decision,'' said Armstrong, referring to past
national criminal justice studies he took part in that focused on
race, police enforcement and accountability. Now that he is
directly responsible to the people, he said, his decision is firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't work in our city,'' he said of the valor awards.
``It's fundamentally wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
