u a BC-SCI-TRANSPLANT-FRAUD-     03-09 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRANSPLANT-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS OF MORE SERIOUS FRAUD   SEEN IN BREAST CANCER STUDY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., Mass., South Africa)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New details emerging from an investigation into research fraud
in a South African breast cancer study suggest that the deception
and violations of ethics were even more serious than initially
recognized, and may have included patients being given experimental
treatment without their knowledge or consent.
</P>
<P>
   The study, revealed last month to be fraudulent, had claimed
that bone-marrow transplantation and high-dose chemotherapy could
prolong the lives of women with advanced breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The research was conducted by Dr. Werner Bezwoda of the
University of Witwatersrand in Johannesburg, who presented it last
May in Atlanta at a major meeting of the American Society of
Clinical Oncology. Of five bone-marrow transplant studies presented
at that conference, Bezwoda's was the only one to show a benefit
for the grueling procedure. It was widely publicized and seen as a
ray of hope by many patients.
</P>
<P>
   But when American researchers visited Bezwoda's laboratory, in
preparation for trying his techniques here, they found that he had
falsified some of his data. Bezwoda admitted the deception, and the
study was discredited.
</P>
<P>
   Bezwoda, who had been highly respected and had trained many
other cancer specialists in his country, is to face a tribunal
Friday at the University of Witwatersrand, which will decide
whether he will be dismissed. Several American researchers who
audited his study are to testify at the tribunal, and a report of
their findings will be posted Friday on the Web site of a medical
journal, The Lancet, at www.thelancet.com.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the researchers said they could find no consent
forms for any patient, leaving open the question of whether the
women, who were mostly blacks, had given consent, known what drugs
they were receiving or even known that they were part of an
experiment. In addition, Bezwoda admitted that patients in the
study who were said to have been given a standard form of
chemotherapy for breast cancer were actually given a different,
less effective treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all based on a myth,'' said Dr. Raymond Weiss, an
oncologist and clinical professor of medicine at Georgetown
University, and one of the investigators. ``There are so many
problems with this research. We don't know whether the patients
exist, we don't know whether there was truly a study and, if there
was, we don't know that the patients knew it or that there was a
consent. It's a likelihood that no consents were signed and they
didn't know they were in a study.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said they were shocked by what they found. One
of them, Dr. F. Marc Stewart, chief of hematology and oncology at
the University of Massachusetts Memorial Medical Center in
Worcester, said: ``A number of us were transplant physicians. This
was not a group biased against transplantation. We were initially
excited to confirm the results, which we hoped would be verified.''
</P>
<P>
   But even before they left for Johannesburg, Weiss said, there
were warning signs. Bezwoda would permit the group only two days to
conduct their review, and allow only four researchers to visit. At
one point, he changed his mind and said they could not come at all.
He later relented. He took several months to provide the team a
copy of his research protocol, the plan for the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the protocol was written for our benefit, but who
knows,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Problems continued when the investigators arrived in
Johannesburg. Stewart said, ``The first concern was that we were
not permitted to see the charts of patients treated on the control
arm of the study.''
</P>
<P>
   Those women accounted for about half the patients. Some records
from the experimental group were also withheld, he said; Bezwoda
showed investigators charts for only 58 of 75 women in that group.
One of the charts, Weiss said, consisted of only a single page.
</P>
<P>
   Bezwoda repeatedly refused to provide the missing charts. Even
the charts they were allowed to see revealed problems, Stewart
said. For a study to be valid, the patients have to be clearly
defined in terms of age and diagnosis; otherwise, researchers will
be comparing apples and oranges, and the results will be
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Bezwoda's patients did not meet the criteria that he
had established for the study. ``In some cases, patients were older
than the protocol specified,'' Stewart said. ``In some cases the
disease stage did not correspond to the protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Cleaton-Jones, chairman of the university's committee
for research on human subjects, said Bezwoda had never cleared his
study with the committee. Cleaton-Jones, who graduated from medical
school with Bezwoda in 1967, said he could not imagine why his
classmate would falsify his work. ``I'm quite fascinated to try to
understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the university said that Bezwoda declined to
be interviewed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
