<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-VOTER-TURNOUT-NYT &LR;      03-09 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER-TURNOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN BY MCCAIN SWELLED GOP PRIMARY TURNOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turnout for Republican presidential primaries hit
record highs in 12 of the 18 states that have held them so far, and
it was clearly a result of John McCain's candidacy, now suspended,
according to a new nonpartisan analysis of voting.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Democratic turnout was the second-lowest in 40
years. Only President Clinton's uncontested run for the nomination
in 1996 drew fewer voters to the polls, according to the analysis,
by the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's analysis found that 13.6 percent of the
voting-age population had gone to the polls in Republican primaries
so far this year, up 4.3 percentage points from Republican
primaries in those states four years ago and the highest level of
Republican turnout since Sen. Barry Goldwater's primary campaign in
1964. The influence of McCain, who ran well among independents, was
apparent in the open and semiopen Republican primaries, the
committee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of this primary season,'' said Curtis Gans, the
committee's director, ``was McCain: McCain mobilizing alienated
independents and disaffected Democrats into Republican primaries;
McCain spawning an organizational counterrevolution'' by Christian
conservatives and Republican regulars ``who had vested their future
in Gov. George Bush.'' Moreover, Gans said, the five-week lull in
Democratic primaries between New Hampshire and Super Tuesday helped
McCain dominate the political news.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, turnout was 10.1 percent of the
voting-age population in the states that held primaries through
Super Tuesday, slightly higher than in 1996 but substantially below
previous levels _ for example, 25 percent lower than in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Gans added that nothing in the primary season so far was
predictive of turnout this November. ``There was too much, and too
ill-founded, euphoria about the McCain-driven turnout increases,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
