<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SENATE-JUDGES-ART-(TR     03-09 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUDGES-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LONG DELAYS, SENATE CONFIRMS 2 JUDICIAL NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 27 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three weeks ago, Polly Paez, a Mexican-American
woman with immense pride in her son, who is a federal judge in Los
Angeles, decided she had to do something to save his long-stalled
nomination to a higher court.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Paez, 76, called Sen. Harry Reid of Nevada, the Senate's
second-ranking Democratic leader and a fellow member of the Mormon
Church, and asked him to reach out to the other Mormons in the
Senate and tell them her son was a good person and worthy of
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's what I did,'' Reid said on Thursday after the Senate
confirmed Judge Richard A. Paez by a vote of 59-39 to a seat on the
9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers California and
several western states. Four of the votes in favor of Paez were
cast by Mormons, three of them Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the votes of the Mormon Republicans were only one of
several factors behind the confirmation of Paez, which came after a
four-year delay.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over Paez grew well beyond an ordinary dispute on
nominations. By the time the vote was taken late on Thursday, the
debate touched on a range of issues including presidential
politics, the political fund-raising scandals of 1996, whether
Senate Republicans were tougher on Hispanic and female nominees and
the ideology of the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Senate opponents of the nomination had criticized Paez as too
liberal, based on several of his rulings on the lower court. Many
of them had hoped to avoid a vote, fearing that colleagues who were
privately opposed to the nomination would vote to confirm Paez for
fear of offending Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore interrupted his campaign to fly back to
Washington from Detroit late Wednesday night in case his vote was
needed to break a tie on the Paez nomination. Gore's presence was
almost certainly not needed but it provided a flourish to the day
and his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists said that they had the votes without Gore
but that his presence had the effect of assuring that enough
Republicans would support the nomination to avoid giving him the
opportunity to make a heroic appearance. ``We sure weren't going to
let him come riding in on a horse to save the day,'' said one
senior Republican staff aide.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Senate also confirmed Marsha L. Berzon, a San
Francisco lawyer, to the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals. Berzon had
waited more than two years for a vote. She was confirmed by a vote
of 64-34.
</P>
<P>
   After complaints last year from groups that presented statistics
showing that female and Hispanic candidates waited longer than
white male candidates, Sen. Trent Lott, the Senate Republican
leader, promised a vote on the Paez and Berzon nominations by
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' strategy was to collect at least six Republican
votes to add to the 45 from their own party. One of the ways to get
those votes, Reid said, was to ``play the Mormon card but also the
Hispanic card, the fairness card and any other card I could think
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he had urged Mrs. Paez to come to Washington to lobby
on behalf of her son. ``But she's kind of ailing,'' Reid said. ``So
she asked me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He lobbied fellow Mormons and several Republican senators: Orrin
G. Hatch and Robert F. Bennett of Utah, Gordon H. Smith of Oregon,
and Michael D. Crapo of Idaho. Hatch, the chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, had long supported the Paez nomination. Of that group,
only Crapo voted against the Paez nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said that when he telephoned Judge Paez on Thursday to
congratulate him, he told him, ``Your mother really helped do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Paez declined to be interviewed but said in a statement
that he was grateful to his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against Judge Paez was led by Sens. Robert C. Smith
of New Hampshire and Jeff Sessions of Alabama, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Smith argued that the 9th Circuit was far too liberal and that
adding Judge Paez would increase its ideological tilt. Sessions
argued that Judge Paez should be denied a seat on the court because
he had accepted a plea agreement that allowed John Huang, a central
figure in the Democratic fund-raising scandals, to avoid going to
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Sessions asserted that Judge Paez had also flouted federal
sentencing guidelines in the case, suggesting that he had been
lenient with Huang in order to help promote his candidacy for the
appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, the Vermont Democrat who is the ranking
member of the Judiciary Committee, ridiculed the charge. Leahy said
that the case had been randomly assigned to Judge Paez and that all
he did was accept a plea bargain approved by the prosecution and
the probation service.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, President Clinton celebrated the confirmations
but lamented how long it had taken for both candidates to be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to repeat that dozens of other qualified judicial
nominees still await confirmation,'' he said. ``Meanwhile, case
loads rise and backlogs mount.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton said many nominees were being held up because of
election-year politics. Democrats like Leahy complain that the
traditional slowdown in confirmations before a presidential
election has been started far too early by the Republicans.
Republicans dispute suggestions that they have slowed the process
in hope of preserving as many vacancies as possible in case they
retake the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
