<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRUDENTIAL-NASDAQ-ART     03-09 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUDENTIAL-NASDAQ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO CASE LEADS TO FINE FOR PRUDENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stock market regulators censured and fined Prudential Securities
Inc. $100,000 on Thursday over allegations that the company tried
to avoid competing on price to manage a 1996 initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities
Dealers had contended that Prudential had asked a regional
investment bank, Friedman Billings Ramsey, to step aside as lead
manager of the $60 million public offering and instead accept a
secondary role to Prudential. Because Prudential planned to charge
more than Friedman Billings, Prudential's plan would have cost the
issuer, a California mortgage lender, about $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman Billings, which is based in Arlington, Va., refused to
do so, kept its fee at 6 percent rather than the 7 percent
Prudential would have charged, and won the deal, according to the
NASD.
</P>
<P>
   In paying the fine, Prudential, one of Wall Street's largest
securities firms, neither admitted nor denied wrongdoing on the
NASD's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been firmly committed to closely following all
rules and regulations of the NASD,'' Prudential said in a
statement. ``We are pleased to have put this matter behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement between Prudential and the NASD highlights one of
Wall Street's great ironies. The securities firms that form the
nerve center of American capitalism hate to cut their prices, and
nowhere is that fact more apparent than in the lucrative business
of underwriting initial offerings.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Wall Street has charged companies a standard fee of
7 percent to sell their shares to the public. Only one in five
companies pays an underwriting fee of less than 7 percent, and the
percentage of issuers that pays less has decreased in recent years,
even as the average size of new offerings has tripled.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies are paying more money than ever in
underwriting fees. In 1999, initial public offering fees totaled
almost $5 billion, up from $1.3 billion in 1991, according to
Thomson Financial Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very strongly that firms ought to compete in this area
on all terms _ price and quality of service,'' said Barry
Goldsmith, executive vice president of enforcement for NASD
Regulation. ``The conduct here certainly has the potential to
thwart that free and open competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman Billings declined to comment on the case, which
involved the June 1996 underwriting of First Alliance Corp., a
company in Irvine, Calif., that specializes in making mortgage
loans to people with bad credit. According to the NASD, First
Alliance decided to sell shares to the public in late 1995 and
began to interview securities firms to pick a lead underwriter, a
process known as a beauty contest.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street firms typically underwrite offerings in teams,
the lead underwriter, or manager, of the offering has primary
responsibility for selling the offering and reaps much of the fees
and profit. Traditionally, firms in a beauty contest compete on
their ability to find buyers for the offering and the skills of
their research analysts, who will cover the company after it is
public. They do not compete on price.
</P>
<P>
   But First Alliance, which felt it was a strong company in a hot
market sector, did not want to pay the usual 7 percent fee,
according to the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real easy IPO, and the market was responsive at that
point too,'' said Brian Chisick, chairman and chief executive of
First Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   So, in February 1996, First Alliance appointed Friedman
Billings, which had agreed to charge a 6 percent fee, and
Prudential, which had stuck with the traditional rate, as
co-managers of the offering. Then First Alliance told Prudential
that Prudential could be lead manager if it cut its fee to 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Prudential would not cut its fee, the NASD contended.
Instead, Prudential repeatedly tried to get Friedman Billings to
defer to it and accept a co-manager position, with Prudential
leading the deal and charging 7 percent. If Friedman Billings ``had
agreed to Prudential's requests, it would have effectively taken
itself out of consideration for the lead,'' the NASD said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman Billings refused to back down and eventually managed
the First Alliance offering as sole underwriter for a 6 percent
fee.
</P>
<P>
   The offering was completed in July 1996, raising $59.5 million
for First Alliance. Of that, $3.57 million went to the
underwriters, $595,000 less than would have been charged if
Prudential had led the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to Friedman Billings, and they said they would do it
for 6 percent, and we were delighted,'' Chisick said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, First Alliance's stock nearly doubled. Since
then, it has fallen more than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of underwriting fees has caught the attention of the
Justice Department, which disclosed last year that it had opened an
investigation into ``the possibility of anticompetitive practices''
at leading Wall Street firms, including Merrill Lynch, Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, and Goldman, Sachs. The investigation is under
way, a Justice Department spokeswoman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts said the 7 percent fee is fair, given the costs
of managing an initial public offering and the difficulty of
pricing a stock and finding the right buyers for a company.
</P>
<P>
   Investment firms compete on the basis of ``how much time are you
going to commit to due diligence and drafting the documents and
helping to articulate a growth story,'' said Scott Sipprelle, the
former head of U.S. equity capital markets for Morgan Stanley and
the founder of Midtown Research, a New York firm that specializes
in investing in newly public companies. ``I would argue strongly
that 7 percent is not excessive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
