u a BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      03-09 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROPER MEDICARE PAYMENTS ROSE SLIGHTLY IN '99 TO $13.5 BILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Ill.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Improper Medicare payments to doctors, hospitals
and other health care providers increased slightly last year, after
falling sharply in 1997 and 1998, federal investigators said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs Brown, inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services, said the improper payments cost the government
$13.5 billion last year, up slightly from $12.6 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In previous reports, Brown estimated that improper payments cost
Medicare $23.2 billion in 1996 and $20.3 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing of the Senate Appropriations Committee, Brown said
the government had resolved ``a lot of the easier problems'' in its
campaign against Medicare waste, fraud and abuse. ``It will take
some intensive work'' to reduce errors further, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Brown said, about 8 percent of all payments in the
traditional fee-for-service Medicare program were improper. The
error rate appears to have leveled off, after dropping to 7.1
percent in 1998, from 14 percent in 1996 and 11 percent in 1997,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare provides care for 39 million people who are elderly or
disabled. Every dollar saved is another dollar that can be used for
new benefits like prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that 75 percent of the improper Medicare payments
last year went to four kinds of providers: hospitals, which
accounted for $3.6 billion, doctors at $3 billion, suppliers of
medical equipment accounting for $1.8 billion and home health care
agencies, also responsible for $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing homes, hospices, kidney dialysis centers and medical
laboratories received a total of $2.2 billion in improper payments
last year, the inspector general said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she suspected that fraud accounted for ``a small
proportion'' of the improper payments. But she emphasized that the
audit focused only on billing mistakes. ``If a doctor's signature
has been forged or if a roomful of medical records was
fabricated,'' she said, ``we would not necessarily detect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Health care providers need to improve the documentation of
claims, Brown said, and Medicare officials should make more
aggressive efforts to collect debts owed to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Payments were classified as improper if, for example, there was
no medical record to justify a treatment, if the service was not
performed or if the treatment was not covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not scrutinize payments to health maintenance
organizations. Brown and other officials have repeatedly said that
Medicare is overpaying HMOs. The managed care industry disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said Medicare payments were often
excessive but not illegal. He held up a syringe and said Medicare
buys it for $2.93 while the Department of Veterans Affairs pays
$1.89. For a bag of saline solution, he said, the disparity is even
greater, $7.90 as against $2.38.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore often says the Clinton administration has
reduced fraud and improved service to the public with a seven-year
effort to ``reinvent government.''
</P>
<P>
   But in response to a question at Thursday's hearing, Brown said
the White House Office of Management and Budget had rejected her
request for $15 million to have federal auditors work year-round at
the insurance companies that review and pay Medicare claims for the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was inspector general of the Defense Department from
1987 to 1989, said the Pentagon regularly assigned auditors to work
in the offices of large military contractors. But, she said,
``there has been virtually no audit oversight'' of Medicare
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recently told Medicare officials to improve supervision
of the contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy W. Dickey, former president of the American Medical
Association, criticized the inspector general's testimony as
``irresponsible grandstanding.'' Dickey said doctors wanted to
comply with Medicare rules, but had difficulty because the rules
were as complex as the tax code. Moreover, Dickey said, the
propriety of Medicare payments often involves subtle questions
about whether a test or a procedure is medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Health Care
Financing Administration, the federal agency that runs Medicare,
said the improper payments to doctors often involved simple
questions: ``Did you see a patient, or did you not? Did you perform
the service, or did you not?''
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said she would soon establish a toll-free telephone
service to answer doctors' questions about billing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said more ``criminal prosecutions may
be the appropriate therapy'' for providers who intentionally
overcharge Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association also raised questions about the
statistical methods used by the inspector general to estimate
improper payments. Brown said the latest estimate was based on a
review of 5,223 claims for $5.4 million worth of services provided
to 600 beneficiaries, and she insisted that the sample was
``statistically valid.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said officials did not have adequate control over the huge
amounts of cash that flowed through Medicare every day. For
example, she said, a bank in Chicago has routinely withdrawn more
money from the Federal Reserve system than it needs to pay Medicare
contractors. In a recent 11-day period, she said, the excessive
withdrawals ranged from $100 million to $420 million a day, and the
bank earned more than $700,000 in interest by investing the money
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials told the bank to stop the practice, but bank
officials believed that they were entitled to this ``perquisite,''
Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
