<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, MARCH 10
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT (moved on Monday, March 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 6,
about computer software that makes it easy to find and copy music
on the Internet without payment misidentified the performer of
``Play That Funky Music,'' an example of a song that could be
downloaded. It was the band Wild Cherry, not James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INDIA-MOVIES-EXTORTION-NYT (moved on Saturday, Feb. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Feb. 26,
about gangs that prey on filmmakers in Bombay, India's movie
capital, misstated the given names of a prominent producer and his
son, who is a director. The producer is Yash Chopra, not S. Chopra.
His son is Aditya Chopra, not Yash Chopra.
</P>
<P>
   BC-STEEL-TRADE-NYT (moved on Friday, March 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 3,
about duties on imported steel referred incorrectly to actions
taken last month by the United States International Trade
Commission. The commission split, 3 to 3, on whether relief should
be provided to makers of wire rod and voted 5 to 1 in favor of
relief for pipe makers. Both recommendations were sent to President
Clinton, as required by law, and he decided to impose duties. The
commission was not unable to reach a decision.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-LONGEVITY-ETHICS-NYT (moved on Monday, March 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, March 6,
about ethical implications of trying to extend human life by
decades misstated the affiliation of Rabbi Neil Gilman, who backed
the idea of such research. He is a professor of philosophy at
Jewish Theological Seminary, not Center.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT (moved on Monday, Jan. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Jan. 24,
about the risks of overdosing on acetaminophen, commercially known
as Tylenol, referred imprecisely to the amount that becomes toxic.
Treating a child five times a day or more for several days, at the
recommended dosage, could result in a build-up to half or more of
the toxic quantity. A single dose given once is about 11 percent of
the toxic quantity. The drug's maker reported the error in a letter
on Feb. 14, but the writer was away from the office and did not see
her mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
