A2297 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     03-09 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREW: NO RESPECT FROM ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Former Angels hitting coach Rod Carew walked
onto the field at Tempe Diablo Stadium Thursday morning and
immediately was greeted by Angels staff members and players. Now
the hitting coach for the Milwaukee Brewers, Carew smiled and
hugged his way to the visiting dugout.
</P>
<P>
   But Carew hasn't completely gotten over being let go by the
Angels after last season, his eighth with the club. It wasn't so
much that new manager Mike Scioscia decided to bring in his own
staff, including Mickey Hatcher as the hitting coach, but how he
was let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that bothered me the most was the way
(general manager Bill) Stoneman went about it,'' Carew said. ``It
was like it was no big deal, like when they retired me in '85. I
walked away bitter in '85 but this time I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Carew said he has never spoken with Stoneman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to call to find out what was going on,'' Carew said.
``They didn't give me a courtesy call, I had to call them. At least
they could have given me some respect. That's all anybody wants.
But that's water under the bridge. It's a business, it's something
I have to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a call from Baseball Operations,'' said Angels
spokesman Tim Mead. ``(Assistant GM) Ken Forsch called him. We all
appreciate everything Rodney did. It was a difficult off-season to
say the least. We've all moved on. He's in a good situation now.
Our staff feels the same way about our current staff. Change is not
an indictment of individuals. It's just change.''
</P>
<P>
   Carew said he likes his new situation with the Brewers, but it
wasn't easy to end his tenure with the Angels after last year's
debacle when the offense was last in the league in runs and batting
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I would have liked to stay was because of
what we went through last year,'' Carew said. ``Nobody wants to
leave on a sour note after what happened to the offense. Nobody
wants to walk away from an opportunity to correct it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn returned to camp Thursday and was back in the starting
lineup after missing Wednesday's game because of a corneal abrasion
to his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something fell in the room,'' Vaughn said. ``I woke up in the
morning and I had particles in my eye. I'm all right. I'm at full
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has been staying at his aunt's house in the area, which
got manager Mike Scioscia to suggest Vaughn buy his aunt a new
house. Responded Vaughn: ``She's got a new house! She's waiting for
me to leave so she can sell this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn not only went 1 for 2 with an RBI in the game, but he
stole second base with a head-first slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo Vaughn thinks he can steal bases, he takes it as a personal
affront when they play behind him,'' manager Mike Scioscia said.
``He says 'You guys don't know I'm an athlete.' He wants guys to at
least play him honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he likes Vaughn's passion for the game, but he
said he told Vaughn he doesn't want Vaughn to risk an injury by
diving into the bag. And since Vaughn hasn't stolen a base in a
regular season game since 1997, Scioscia said he got the base and
presented it to Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said this is your first and last stolen base this season,''
Scioscia said. ``He didn't like that part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrod Washburn has a strained muscle in his right side, just
below the rib cage, and is the same injury he had last year that
cause him to miss seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He said he won't be out as long this time, but a timetable for
his return hasn't been determined. And it certainly won't help his
case in trying to win a spot in the starting rotation, which is why
he didn't tell anyone when he first felt pain in his first start
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew exactly what it was but I didn't say anything because I
knew they wouldn't let me pitch,'' Washburn said. ``I wanted to see
if I could pitch with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't. In his second start, Washburn walked four in 2 2/3
innings, giving up three runs and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it (his side) on every pitch,'' Washburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Brian Cooper gave up six runs and four hits in
two innings in the Angels' 7-6 win over the Brewers at Tempe Diablo
Stadium. He didn't get help from second baseman Justin Baughman,
whose two errors led to two unearned runs. Outfielder Mike
Colangelo drove in the game-winner in the bottom of the ninth,
scoring Orlando Palmeiro from second with a single to right field.
Tim Salmon hit a three-run homer in the third inning for the Angels
(3-3). ... Pitcher Tim Belcher threw off the mound Thursday for the
first time this spring. Coming off surgery to repair a torn muscle
in his right elbow, Belcher threw to a catcher who was standing up
in front of the plate. ... Outfielder Jeff DaVanon, who has a torn
labrum in his left shoulder, will have surgery next Friday and will
will miss most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   WHEN/WHERE: 12:05 p.m., Tempe Diablo Stadium; 12:05 p.m. Peoria
Sports Complex
</P>
<P>
   RADIO/TV: KLAC-570, XPRS-1090 (at Tempe)
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S GAMES (split squad): Troy Percival starts for Anaheim
against San Diego's Buddy Carlyle at Tempe. Percival, coming off
shoulder surgery, is making his first appearance this spring and
will be limited to 15-20 pitches today. He'll be followed by Kent
Mercker. Seth Etherton starts for Anaheim against San Diego's Brian
Boehringer at Peoria. Etherton, who pitched for USC, is expected to
pitch for triple-A Edmonton this season.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S RESULTS: Mike Colangelo's RBI single in the ninth
inning drove in Orlando Palmeiro with the winning run in the
Angels' 7-6 win over the Brewers. The Angels (3-3) got a three-run
homer by Tim Salmon.
</P>
