<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-2NDLD-WRITETHR     03-09 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN SUSPENDS CAMPAIGN, BUT DEFERS BUSH ENDORSEMENT  
 (SUBS lede to CORRECT day to Thursday and add `powerful';   adds
about 500 words   to end ) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT6, NYT8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ Sen. John McCain, whose powerful insurgency
became the surprise of the presidential primary season, on Thursday
ended his maverick bid for the Republican nomination with the hope
that he would eventually prevail in ``making our party as big as
the country we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after being defeated by Texas Gov. George W. Bush in
primaries from coast to coast, the Arizona senator, standing with
striated mountains and the glorious Verde Valley as his backdrop,
acknowledged that no matter how many crossover voters he had
attracted, he was not the preference of the majority in his own
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore I announce today, on this fine Arizona morning and
in this beautiful place, that I am not longer an active candidate
for my party's nomination for president,'' McCain said, his wife,
Cindy, at his side.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had gracious words for Bush, congratulating him but
stopping short of endorsing him. The senator also said he would not
``walk away from'' his fight for reform, adding: ``What is good for
my country is good for my party. Should our party ever abandon this
principle, the American people will rightly abandon us, and we will
surely slip into the mists of history, deserving the allegiance of
none.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain made his announcement only an hour after former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey withdrew from the Democratic race. Their
decisions brought an abrupt end to the primary season and set the
stage for what promises to be a costly and bitter battle between
Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning in Colorado, congratulated McCain ``for
fighting the good fight'' and called the senator's concession
``gracious.'' The governor also said he had a short telephone
conversation with McCain. He said there was no timetable for longer
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us have just come off a tough campaign,'' Bush said,
``John needs some time to think. I need some time. But I believe
that when it's all said and done that we can have a good
dialogue,'' Bush said. ``I intend to talk with him at his
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone call followed a series of back-door conversations
between supporters of Bush and Washington-based supporters of
McCain. It began what many Republicans hope will be a process of
reconciliation that could lead to McCain's eventual endorsement of
Bush and allow the Republican nominee to hold on to many of the
independents and new voters that had flocked to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But the hurdles for the party go beyond the personal
rapprochement needed after such a bitter campaign. With McCain
insisting that he would continue his fight for reform, he and Bush
will have to bridge fundamental differences between their agendas,
in particular McCain's advocacy of overhauling the campaign finance
system and his support of a tax cut plan that is at odds with
Republican orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they thought avenues of compromise could
emerge.``There's no way you're going to be able to meld everything
Bush said and McCain said and get a broth that's eatable,'' said
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who is close to McCain and who has been
working to smooth the way for a reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question you'll have to sand off the edges to fit
it,'' Hagel said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also seemed to leave open the option of using his 231
delegates, from seven state delegations as a force to press for
changes in the party platform at the Republican National Convention
this summer. Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, said the
senator was keeping an organization together to ``maintain contact
with our delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will press for measures that are germane for reform,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis downplayed any idea that platform fight would be
necessary and and spoke like a loyal Republican of the necessity of
defeating Gore.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy turned out to be the surprise of the primary
season as he went from obscurity to political phenomenon, drawing
Democrats and independents and winning the New Hampshire primary by
a landslide. He appealed to voters hungry for change with his
compelling biography as a former prisoner of war in Vietnam and his
promises that ``I will never lie to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while he looked like he might defeat Bush despite the
governor's advantage in resources and establishment support. But as
the campaign became more brutal, McCain began to lose his appeal to
members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   His hopes of carrying California and New York disappeared
Tuesday when he was only able to prevail in New England.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made his speech stepping out of the race and had his
first contact with Bush on Thursday only after two days of talks
between the Bush and McCain camps, conversations that bypassed
McCain's immediate campaign staff, who have been more combative
than some of the senator's Washington allies.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans close to the two sides said Sen. Paul Coverdell of
Georgia, who is a prominent Bush backer, conferred with Hagel while
Karl Rove, Bush's senior strategist, consulted with Kenneth
Duberstein, a former chief of staff to President Ronald Reagan and
a member of McCain's kitchen cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning before McCain delivered his statement in
Arizona, Rove was told by Duberstein ``you'll like what you hear,''
according to Republican who supported Bush. But he was also told
that it was too early to suggest or broker a visit. McCain was
leaving immediately for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCain did not rule out a future endorsement but
said that Bush would have to take steps towards some of McCain's
agenda, such as campaign finance overhaul and a dedication to
shoring up Social Security to win the senator's support.
</P>
<P>
   Davis on Thursday characterized the reconciliation as a
step-by-step process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first step was to take ourselves of the nominating
process,'' he said. ``That way it was clear to the Bush campaign
that they can save their resources and their efforts toward winning
the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Thursday several times publicly sent signals that he
understood McCain's significance by linking the senator to reform.
Of McCain's supporters, he said, ``What's going to win his
supporters over is when they realize Al Gore is no reformer and Al
Gore is no John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain put a damper on speculation that he would mount a
third-party candidacy, saying ``I love my party. It is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   He also implored all the new and untraditional voters who had
come to his side, ``Promise me that you will never give up that you
will continue your service in the worthy cause of revitalizing our
democracy, Our crusade will never accomplish all its goals if your
voices fall silent in the national debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in the surest sign that McCain's wild ride was over, the
ever accessible candidate ended his speech and departed without
taking any questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
