<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIRLINE-CONGESTION-NY     03-09 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-CONGESTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA TO CONSULT AIRLINES ON AVOIDING TRAFFIC DELAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After huge numbers of air traffic delays last
summer, the Clinton administration has decided to take a markedly
different approach this year: asking the airlines what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than deciding on its own how to handle thunderstorms and
other problems, the Federal Aviation Administration will consult
with the airlines every two hours, with conference calls and
computer hookups. The federal government will also open military
airspace off the East Coast, try to route more planes over Canada
and use a new computer system to get hourly updates on how many
planes the airlines want to fly, rather than the semimonthly
updates it gets now.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Jane F. Garvey, the FAA administrator, and
representatives of airlines, the air traffic controllers' union,
and the pilots' union are to announce the changes on Friday at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines are going to be much more involved in the
decision making,'' said John Hotard, a spokesman for American
Airlines. ``That can only improve the situation we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlines and the agency say that in addition to fewer
delays, this ``collaborative decision making'' will give airlines a
clear idea of delays hours in advance, so they can tell passengers
well before boarding time how late a flight will probably be. With
more realistic expectations, people involved in announcing the
changes say, the airlines may also choose to cancel flights early,
rather than load passengers, push back from the gate and wait for
hours, then and finally cancel anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Participants said that the agency and the airlines were showing
unaccustomed signs of flexibility. The airlines fear that extensive
delays will prompt expensive ``passenger rights'' legislation, one
participant said, and the agency is eager to avoid further
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Last July the FAA recorded 45,162 air traffic delays, up 76
percent from the level the year before. The agency blamed weather
and new equipment. April, May and August 1999 were also far worse
than those months in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Garvey, speaking at a conference here on Wednesday, warned
that the changes planned for this summer were ``not the silver
bullet.'' What the system really needs is more modernization, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, the agency predicted continued strong growth
in air traffic. About 4,300 large passenger jets are registered in
this country, plus 1,000 big planes carrying freight, express
packages and mail. Other experts say, however, that air traffic
could be reduced if the price of oil stays high.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials would not comment on details of the plan Thursday,
in advance of the scheduled announcement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But an important part of the plan, according to airline managers
and others involved in the planning, is to have the major airlines
negotiate with the agency in six or eight daily sessions of
conference calls and Web links to deal with detours and delays
required by bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it runs now, they just dictate to us,'' said one
airline manager who has been involved in the planning for the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to officials at the agency and the airlines, they
will develop a consensus about detour routes and delays. If a long
north-south line of thunderstorms developed, under the current
system, the FAA would probably shift all traffic around it in one
direction, say, to the north, creating a traffic jam in the sky,
according to air traffic experts. Under the new method, some
airlines might propose diverting south, or, using better weather
information that they would share with the agency, finding a hole
to fly through.
</P>
<P>
   Another change involves centralizing authority in the FAA so
that its System Command Center in Herndon, Va., has more power to
direct each of the 20 main traffic control centers to accept more
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the changes will take effect on Sunday, though
others are still under development. Many changes are related to
thunderstorms or the threat of such storms, which last summer
disrupted air traffic as the FAA held planes on the ground in
anticipation of bad weather en route. In some cases, the bad
weather did not develop, air traffic control experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the points to be announced, participants said, are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency and the airlines will develop forecasts based on
weather reports available to the airlines as well as those
available to the agency, and both parties will follow up through
the day to ensure that they are not reacting to forecast storms
that fail to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   _ If disruptive thunderstorms develop, the Defense Department,
principally the Navy, will promptly relinquish control of a slice
of its airspace off the East Coast, for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
   _ When thunderstorms restrict air routes, some jetliners will be
offered routes at 18,000 feet and below for extended periods, even
though this burns more fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines and the FAA will have to plan ahead to use low-altitude
routes, because in many cases it will require loading extra fuel
before takeoff or removing some cargo or passengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
