<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Utah, Wyo.)  
 WITH McCAIN GONE, BUSH JUST PLOWS AHEAD  
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEYENNE, Wyo. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas briskly returned
to the campaign trail Thursday as if his competition had not
withered away, seeking to sustain the momentum from his climactic
victories on Tuesday and hone his attacks on Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, mindful that a languid start in the general election was
the undoing of some past presidential nominees, courted voters in
three states that hold primaries on Friday _ Colorado, Utah and
Wyoming _ even though victories are assured in this conservative
region.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also made a brief call to Sen. John McCain after McCain
announced Thursday that he was suspending his campaign. Bush
thanked him for making what the governor termed a gracious exit
from the race, but the two men did not discuss holding some sort of
peace parley, Bush aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain did not indicate whether he would campaign for
Bush _ or even endorse him _ Bush had only kind words for McCain on
Thursday, hoping to heal the wounds from an unexpectedly fractious
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate so very much the competition and the hard work he
put into the campaign,'' Bush said of McCain at a rally before
several hundred people at the airport in Provo, Utah. ``I
appreciate his commitment to reform.'' He paused, and then
continued, ``The best reform for America, the best reform for this
country, is to end the Clinton-Gore era in Washington D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters Thursday how he would win over McCain
supporters who might harbor resentment from the primary, Bush spoke
of his own credentials as a reformer, while ridiculing Gore's
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush chose an issue that McCain found had strong appeal with
independents: campaign-finance reform. And as he had with McCain,
Bush tried to turn the issue against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and McCain favor a ban on the largely unregulated
political contributions known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that even as Gore was calling for such a ban, the
vice president and his aides were planning an aggressive effort to
collect such donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's not going to be fooled by the difference between
rhetoric and reality,'' Bush said at a rally at the Denver Broncos'
training facility in Englewood, Colo. ``We are not going to be
fooled by somebody who says one thing and goes out and absolutely
does something else. He must think that we have amnesia. He must
think that we have forgotten Buddhist temples and fund-raising
scams.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was using a strategy popular among politicians who oppose a
broad overhaul of the campaign-finance laws: questioning why
proponents of the measures do not voluntarily live by the proposals
they are espousing. The Democratic response to such attacks has
also been typical: that it would be political suicide to
unilaterally reject such fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a less far-reaching plan that would ban soft-money
donations from corporations and unions, but not from individuals.
At a news conference Thursday, he brushed aside a question about
why he did not voluntarily refrain from raising corporate and labor
soft money, given his backing for such a ban. Instead, he repeated
his criticism of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said in a statement that Bush was trying to
shift attention from his tactics in the Republican primary.
Christopher Lehane, a Gore campaign spokesman, renewed Gore's call
for a soft-money ban and for debates between the two candidates
twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's attack is a wily attempt to avoid fallout from John
McCain's complaint about possible illegal campaign spending,''
Lehane said. ``George Bush opposes real campaign-finance reform. He
is flouting all the campaign spending limits currently on the
books. And his millionaire friends spent big bucks on negative TV
ads to bash John McCain.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his comments Thursday, Bush also promoted a measure, long
popular with Republicans, that would bar unions from making
political contributions without their members' consent. The measure
is anathema to Democrats, who receive the lion's share of labor
donations. Republicans have often cited the Democrats' opposition
as evidence of hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have true reform, we must say to the union bosses,
you can't spend union people's money without their permission,''
Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
