<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MS-VIDEOGAME-700&AMP;ADD-     03-09 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MS-VIDEOGAME-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SEEKS SHARE OF VIDEOGAME MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an ambitious step beyond its stronghold in personal
computing, Microsoft Corp. is announcing plans Friday to challenge
Sony, Nintendo and Sega with a videogame machine called the X-Box.
</P>
<P>
   At an industry conference in San Jose, Calif., Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman, will sketch out his company's plans to
capture a sizable share of the $20 billion-a-year worldwide
videogame market.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Microsoft, a name synonymous with software, has
pretty much limited its forays into hardware to keyboards and mice.
The X-Box is more ambitious _ basically a powerful personal
computer customized to function as a very powerful videogame
console with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   A latecomer to the videogame market, Microsoft is hoping it can
persuade game developers, most of whom already design games for PCs
and video consoles, to add designs for the X-Box. It will argue
that they will be working with familiar technology _ Pentium or
Pentium clone hardware and an operating system based on its
industry-standard Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic message to developers is that the basic systems in
this machine will be personal computer technology,'' said Robbie
Bach, who will be vice president of a new games division at
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But the videogame business is very different from the personal
computer industry. And Microsoft's move is the start of what
promises to be a multibillion-dollar effort over the next few years
to become a leader in digital home entertainment _ a fast-growing
field in which the computer, the television and the Internet are
converging.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been increasingly positioning itself to address
that market, as it has earmarked markets beyond the personal
computer for future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Box fits squarely with how we've redefined this company
in the last year or so,'' said Steven Ballmer, Microsoft's
president and chief executive. ``We want to have the hot device
that people use in their family room on their TV that is linked to
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The X-Box will not go on sale until the fall of 2001. But
industry consultants who have been briefed by Microsoft are
impressed by the company's plans and technical specifications for
the machine. Running at 600 megahertz, its microprocessor will be
faster than all but the most powerful personal computers today.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would not say Thursday who would supply the chip, and
there have been reports that Advanced Micro Devices Inc., the
second-largest microprocessor maker for PCs, was the front-runner.
But one industry consultant said Thursday that Intel Corp., the
largest chip maker and the maker of Pentium processors, won the
design contest for the X-Box.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics chip for the X-Box, made by Nvidia Corp., is
extremely fast, able to process more than 300 million polygons a
second, which analysts said is well ahead of the Sony Playstation
2, which went on sale in Japan just last week. And the X-Box uses
Microsoft's game-development software technology, called DirectX.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Box has a DVD player that can play movies and
high-performance games, and a standard Ethernet network card for
high-speed Internet connections. Unlike the Sony Playstation 2, the
Microsoft X-Box also has a hard drive _ of eight gigabytes _ for
storing games or adding more audio to the sports, action and arcade
games popular with players.
</P>
<P>
   But whether a few technical advantages will give Microsoft any
edge over Sony, in particular, is uncertain. In the first four days
in Japanese stores, Sony sold more than 1 million Playstation 2
machines. The Playstation 2 is expected to go on sale in the United
States this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In videogame machines, a product generation comes every five
years or so. Microsoft has an opening as this generation of
products comes to market. Nintendo's new game player, Dolphin, is
expected to premier sometime next year. But Microsoft is arriving
late, and Sony holds a commanding position with nearly 60 percent
of the console market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big-time gamble for Microsoft,'' said Richard
Doherty, president of Envisioneering, a research firm in Seaford,
N.Y. ``But there are huge changes going on in the consumer market.
Microsoft can't afford to be left out of that, and it does not want
to depend just on the PC.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Microsoft has fielded people from around the company to work on
its consumer games effort. Starting last July, Rick Thompson, who
had led the company's hardware unit, split off a team of 20 people
to work on the X-Box initiative. J. Allard, one of the early
Internet advocates within Microsoft, has led the work on the
stripped-down operating system embedded in the X-Box. For graphics
work, Microsoft even tapped its research division, including Jim
Blinn, a leading computer graphics researcher who came from NASA's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's PC games, like Age of Empires 2 and Flight
Simulator, will be included in the new games division. Ed Fries
will be the division's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the X-Box program is new terrain for Microsoft. ``The
technology is familiar, but the business model is not the PC model
at all,'' Bach said. ``This is a consumer product. Our view is that
technologies converge, but devices don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
