<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-IKEABIZ-IKEABIZ_SFCHR     03-09 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IKEABIZ-IKEABIZ </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Ikea Experience Coming to the Bay Area  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It is rare that a single store opening is significant enough to
noticeably alter the way people shop.
<P>
   But it is also rare that a single store is as big as a Home
Depot, a Wal-Mart, a Safeway and an Old Navy combined.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Swedish home goods retailer Ikea opens a
274,000-square-foot megastore in Emeryville.
</P>
<P>
   The store, decked out in the blue and yellow of the Swedish
flag, is the size of five football fields and surrounded by 9 acres
of parking. Starting April 12, shoppers will be able to buy
virtually everything for the home and office there, from armoires
to vases to flooring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ikea has three really big advantages,'' said Marc Friedman, a
retail consultant with McMillan/Doolittle. ``The stores are easy to
shop, they have the widest assortment you'll find and they're a
very good value. For much of what they carry, you can't find the
same things at a comparable price anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitors, including HomeLife, J.C. Penney and Cost Plus, will
be looking over their shoulders as Ikea enters the $2.2 billion
local home-goods market.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea's prices are low because its furniture tends to be made
from low-cost materials and is sold ready-to-assemble, meaning that
shoppers buy a boxed set of pieces they put together at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea can also buy merchandise from its suppliers more cheaply
than smaller competitors and pass the savings along to shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden, where Ikea was founded in 1943, these advantages have
translated into an astonishing 30 percent share of spending on
furniture and home goods.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects Ikea to attain a comparable share in the United
States, a much larger and more diverse market than Sweden
(population 9 million).
</P>
<P>
   But if other U.S. cities are any example, Ikea will take a
sizable chunk of sales here _ and bring a distinctly Scandinavian
aesthetic to many Bay Area homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, after just five years, Ikea has already become the
most popular furniture seller.
</P>
<P>
   Some 19.3 percent of local furniture shoppers made a purchase at
Seattle's lone Ikea store between September 1998 and August 1999,
according to a survey conducted for Ikea by Scarborough Research.
</P>
<P>
   The Bon Marche department store chain came in second with 18.5
percent; J.C. Penney, 16.5 percent; HomeLife, 13.4 percent; Pier 1,
11.8 percent; and Levitz, 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea's ascent has been rapid; one year earlier, it was third in
the line-up, according to Bjorn Bayley, the Seattle store's
co-owner and a past president of Ikea North America.
</P>
<P>
   The Emeryville store is expected to generate $55 million in
sales its first year and $100 million the second.
</P>
<P>
   But Ikea tends to make conservative forecasts. Sales at a
Chicago store that opened in November 1998 came in more than 50
percent above the projected $60 million in first-year sales. That
prompted the addition of 50,000 square feet to the existing
450,000-square-foot structure.
</P>
<P>
   In Emeryville, an extra 30,000 square feet are available for
future growth. Ikea is also negotiating for a site in East Palo
Alto and, if all goes well, it may open more Bay Area outlets down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kjellman, Ikea North America's chief executive, expects a
Bay Area market share of 5 to 6 percent in about three years. In
the future, probably after more stores have opened, the goal is as
high as 20 percent in the Bay Area and other major markets.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Ikea, which runs about 160 stores in 28
countries, is like the slow-and-steady tortoise in a race against
fast-growing, publicly traded retail hares.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Ikea opens just 10 to 12 stores around the world,
compared with the 200 stores Home Depot hopes to open worldwide
this year, financing its growth through cash flow, rather than
debt. It chooses sites carefully and rarely closes a store.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea even buys most of its sites rather than leasing, a
commitment that few retailers are willing to make. In Emeryville,
Ikea invested $46 million in its 15-acre property and building.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea's growth strategy is dictated by founder Ingvar Kamprad,
whose initials make up the first two letters of the acronym Ikea.
(The rest comes from Elmtyard, the farm where Kamprad grew up, and
Agunnaryd, his hometown.)
</P>
<P>
   Kamprad is determined to run Ikea his way, employing egalitarian
Swedish values and keeping an eye on the long term.
</P>
<P>
   To keep Ikea safe from potential acquirers who might feel
otherwise, Kamprad created a foundation that functions as a holding
company for Ikea and based the organization in the Netherlands,
where laws make takeovers nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ikea doesn't have public shareholders to answer to, it
can go into a new market, such as Russia, which it will enter this
month, and lose money for years. But it's all part of the strategy:
In the long run, such markets make tremendous contributions to both
sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Ikea operates just 13 stores and plans to
open no more than three new ones a year for the foreseeable future.
At this pace, the United States could exceed Germany as Ikea's
biggest market in five years. Eventually, the U.S. business, which
racked up $881 million in sales last year, could be 10 times that
size, said Kjellman.
</P>
<P>
   Retail experts downplay the impact of the Emeryville store on
local furniture merchants, at least in the near term. They say Ikea
tends to increase the amount spent on home furnishings in new
markets, so not every dollar spent there is a dollar taken from
another retailer.
</P>
<P>
   For example, retail consultant Steen Kantor, a past president of
Ikea North America, gives Ikea credit for popularizing duvets,
fluffy feather- or foam-filled comforters that have replaced
blankets on many American beds.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers have made money from duvets, not just Ikea,
Kantor said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman agrees that Ikea's high-profile grand opening and
continued advertising will generate more interest in home goods
generally. He estimates the Emeryville store will ring up around 3
percent of Bay Area furniture sales in its first year or two. ``But
if they create 2 to 3 percent growth, no one loses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that sales are diverted from other merchants, the
impact will be spread among many stores including Cost Plus,
HomeLife, J.C. Penney and small specialty stores, retail experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Petaluma's Scandinavian Designs, which sells ready-to-assemble
furniture in styles similar to Ikea's, appears to have the most to
lose. But Van Scotto, general manager, said his company has
successfully competed against Ikea in both Seattle and Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually more happy than not that they're here because
they expand awareness of RTA  &LR; (ready-to-assemble) furniture and
help people become more accepting of it,'' Scotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Scandinavian Designs, which operates eight stores in the Bay
Area, also offers more hands-on service and slightly more upscale
furniture than Ikea, Scotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea prides itself on its egalitarian Swedish values. Sales
associates, who the company insists on calling ``co-workers,'' make
a competitive hourly wage of $7.75 to $18 in the Bay Area, plus
medical, dental and vision coverage for both full-time and
part-time staff, said Michael O'Rourke, general manager of the
store.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Ikea generated headlines by donating a full day's
sales to its employees. Tens of thousands of workers around the
world, from truck drivers to corporate presidents, received
identical payouts of close to $2,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea has stumbled more than once since opening its first U.S.
store in Philadelphia in 1985. In 1992, Ikea bought three Southern
California stores from a competitor called Stor cq &LR;   &LR; (after first
winning a copyright suit against Stor for knocking off Ikea's
concept).
</P>
<P>
   Those locations lost money for several years and, eventually,
one location was closed. The early '90s recession didn't help. ``If
Ikea had been public, we probably would have had to leave the
U.S.,'' Kjellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Kamprad also came under fire five years ago after a newspaper
revealed that he was actively involved in the Nazi Party in his
youth. Kamprad has publicly apologized and Ikea is now planning to
open a store in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carol Emert at cemert &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
