<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Schumer Vows Fight for Money Laundering Bill
</P>
<P>
   Promising a ``fight on the floor of the Senate,'' Sen. Charles
E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said that he planned to ``toughen up''
legislation proposed by the Clinton administration to combat money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's main criticism of the proposal is that penalties
against offshore banks or countries would be left to the discretion
of the U.S. authorities rather than being set off automatically
when money-laundering abuses are uncovered. He said that an
effective policy required that suspect offshore banks be
automatically forbidden access to the U.S. banking system.
</P>
<P>
   German Banks Detail Merger Plan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that the era of ``Germany Inc.'' is over, the chief
executive of Deutsche Bank, Rolf-Ernst Breuer, outlined a radical
plan to merge his bank with Dresdner Bank in a stock swap worth $30
billion. With $1.2 trillion in assets, the new Deutsche Bank would
be second only to the forthcoming union between three of Japan's
biggest banks. The planned combination would also unravel the
labyrinthine cross-holdings that have for decades bound together
German banks and insurance companies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Man Who Would Lead the IMF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, Horst Koehler, the German head of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, issued a one-line
statement that he was not in the running to be managing director of
the International Monetary Fund. But a call from Germany's
chancellor changed that, and Koehler's candidacy has become mired
in a trans-Atlantic debate over his credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Votes Still Needed for China Accord &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration acknowledged that it does not have
the votes to pass an accord granting permanent normal trading
privileges to China, and a lobbying battle was shaping up for the
130 or so uncommitted House members who will decide the fate of the
president's most important remaining foreign policy goal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARKETS &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technology Stocks Lead a Rebound &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares paced a strong stock-market rally as the
Nasdaq composite index soared through the 5,000 mark for the first
time, climbing 149.60 points, or 3.05 percent, to 5,046.86. Other
major gauges also surged, with the Dow Jones industrial average
gaining 154.20 points, or 1.56 percent, to 10,010.73. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index advanced 34.99 points, or 2.56 percent, to
1,401.69.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPANIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Earning Edge Up 3.5 Percent
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Heinz posted a 3.5 percent increase in third-quarter
profit, the smallest gain in three and a half years, on falling
sales of baby foods, canned tuna and pet products. In the quarter
that ended on Jan. 26, profit from operations at Heinz rose to
$227.2 million, or 63 cents a diluted share. Analysts had expected
Heinz to earn 62 cents a share. Shares of Heinz rose 25 cents, to
$34.50. The stock has fallen a third over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Direct Marketer in Deal
</P>
<P>
   With Draft Worldwide, a direct marketing agency owned by
Interpublic Group, is acquiring a majority stake in AG Worldwide,
the brand strategy and advertising agency owned by Peter Arnell,
the iconoclastic creative executive. Terms of the deal were not
disclosed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coke Plans to Tie Pay to Diversity &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a move designed to counter charges that Coca-Cola has not
cared enough about building a diverse work force, Douglas N. Daft,
Coke's chairman and chief executive, said that compensation at the
company, including his own, would be closely tied to
still-unannounced diversity goals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Head of AT&AMP;T Wireless Unit Resigns &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the nation's biggest long-distance telephone company, said
that Daniel Hesse, the president and chief executive of its
wireless services unit, would leave just weeks before a planned
initial public offering of a portion of the company's wireless
business. Mohan Gyani, the chief financial officer of the AT&AMP;T
Wireless Group, will succeed him.
</P>
