<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      03-09 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews  &UR; (RETRANSMITTING
THIS
 &UR; EXCELLENT FEATURE IN CASE YOU MISSED IT./  &UR; ALSO MOVIING IN THE
``E'' CATEGORY):
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``AS NATURE MADE HIM'' &QL; 
By John Colapinto (HarperCollins, $26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've probably heard about this book on television magazine and
talk shows, but until you read what happened to Bruce Reimer on
April 7, 1966, you won't understand the staggering trauma he
endured. On that day, Bruce and his twin brother, Brian, were set
to undergo routine circumcisions in the Canadian hospital where
they had been born eight months earlier. Bruce went first. Doctors
never got to Brian. Instead, their young parents were told that
there had been an ``accident'' during Bruce's procedure _ the
circumcision had been botched, his genitals were all but destroyed
and the family was left to make wrenching decisions in an era of
little knowledge and few options. In desperation, they consulted a
sex researcher at Johns Hopkins Hospital, who advised them to
``reassign'' their son as a girl, mentally and physically. So,
Bruce was castrated and raised as a girl _ Brenda _ until she was
14 and, in the book's most moving scene, finally told what had
happened to her. This is a chilling story about the power of
nature. If you have a baby boy in your house, you will want to grab
him and run for the hills. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WORKSHOP: SEVEN DECADES OF THE IOWA WRITERS' WORKSHOP'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Edited by Tom Grimes (Hyperion, $30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's some great fiction here, but we fell for the
introductions, the brief lead-in to each story written by the
writer or, in the case of Flannery O'Connor, Wallace Stegner, Andre
Dubus, Raymond Carver or others no longer living, by a
contemporary. Michael Cunningham, for example, tells the publishing
history of his story ``White Angel'' (an early chapter in his
novel, ``A Home at the End of the World''). He had sent many
stories to ``The New Yorker'' to no avail, but a friend insisted
that he try again with ``White Angel.'' To his astonishment, the
magazine said yes, and the story's appearance in 1988 made, he
says, ``more difference than I'd ever imagined,'' with a dozen
editors calling to ask whether they could have a chance at his
first novel. The stories are arranged chronologically, with Stegner
in the 1930s; writers such as Elizabeth McCracken and Buddy Udall
in the 1990s; and Ethan Canin, T. Coraghessan Boyle, Jayne Anne
Phillips, Stuart Dybek, Thom Jones, John Casey and others in
between. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``SHRUB'' &QL; 
By Molly Ivins and Lou Dubose (Random House, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We'd buy this one just for the title. In the introduction, Ivins
shifts to her other nickname for George W. Bush _ ``Dubya'' _ which
is good, too. Her book, subtitled ``The Short but Happy Political
Life of George W. Bush,'' is written from a Texan's point of view,
which is helpful because Dubya promises to do for the country what
he did for the state. Ivins and Dubose (editor of ``The Texas
Observer'') try to portray the candidate as he really is:
privileged, personable, unintellectual and most of all, LUCKY. For
one thing, he inherited a healthy Texas from Ann Richards, his
predecessor in the Governor's Office. Then there is his father.
``The political career of W. Bush is a fairly funny yarn,'' the
authors write, ``on account of being the son of a former president
is not . . . actually sufficient job training for the governance of
a large state. Fortunately, in Texas, this makes no difference.''
If you think that Bush's record is different from his rhetoric, and
that his resume is, as Ivins puts it, ``a little light,'' don't
blame her. ``There's really not much there,'' she says. ``We've
been looking for six years.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``DISH'' &QL; 
By Jeannette Walls (Spike, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walls looks at our fascination with gossip, beginning with the
columns of Walter Winchell in the 1920s and the gossip reporters
who subsequently became some of the most influential journalists of
the midcentury, and ending with the notorious events of recent
years _ the O.J. Simpson trial; the death of Diana, Princess of
Wales; Matt Drudge's theft of ``Newsweek'' information to scoop the
world on the Clinton/Lewinsky affair. Also here are miniprofiles of
former ``Vanity Fair'' and ``New Yorker'' Editor Tina Brown;
powerful Hollywood publicist Pat Kingsley (who redefined the term
``star access'' with her belligerence toward reporters seeking
interviews with client Tom Cruise); and Mike Wallace, who jumped
into the gossip cauldron with his 1956 program, ``Night Beat.'' In
the process of reporting all of this, Walls herself panders to the
gossip mill with mention of rumors of Cruise's homosexuality and
John and Robert Kennedy's simultaneous affairs with Marilyn Monroe.
Best of all, she provides an index. You can choose your own gossip,
and leave the rest to the tabloids. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER-NYT     03-09 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE BANK ANNOUNCES MERGER PLANS WITH RIVAL
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Declaring the era of ``Germany Inc.'' had
ended, the chief executive of Deutsche Bank AG outlined a radical
plan Thursday to merge with its main rival and spin off their
retail businesses serving 10 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Though its main elements were already known, Deutsche Bank's
planned combination with Dresdner Bank is one of the most
far-reaching overhauls for Germany's huge banks since the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It would also unravel the labyrinthine cross-holdings that have
bound together German banks and insurance companies, a move that
could accelerate the pace of corporate change in Europe's biggest
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The headline for this is disentanglement and thus another
facet in the farewell from Germany Inc.,'' said Rolf-Ernst Breuer,
Deutsche Bank's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could have an impact on Germany's other big private
banks _ Commerzbank AG in Frankfurt and Hypovereinsbank AG in
Munich. Both would be far overshadowed by the Deutsche-Dresdner
colossus, and German newspapers were already carrying unconfirmed
reports that Commerzbank had become a takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Deutsche will essentially acquire Dresdner in a
stock exchange worth about $30 billion. With $1.2 trillion in
assets and operations around the globe, the new Deutsche Bank would
be second only to the forthcoming union between three of Japan's
biggest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Under a complex deal with the German insurance conglomerate
Allianz AG, which holds stakes in both banks, Deutsche will spin
off both banks' retail branch networks in a new entity that will be
called Bank 24. Allianz will then reduce its stake in the two banks
but acquire 49 percent of Bank 24. Allianz will also acquire
Deutsche's big mutual fund business, called DWS, as well as
Deutsche's own insurance subsidiary, Deutsche Herold.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Breuer told reporters and analysts Thursday, the bank
merger would make it possible to eliminate 16,000 jobs around the
world. About 5,900 jobs would be cut by reducing the number of
local branch offices in Germany, while most of the rest would come
from combining investment banking businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the bank merger would have little impact
on American banks, in part because Dresdner has little presence in
the United States. But the merger goes a long way toward solving
Deutsche's biggest problem, which is its huge and costly network of
retail branch offices across Germany.
</P>
<P>
   That network barely makes a profit, and analysts believe that
Dresdner's local branch operations are running substantial losses.
Both banks are suffering the same problem: a huge oversupply of
branches and cutthroat price competition from Germany's savings
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise is Deutsche Bank's decision to jettison the
entire retail business, only keeping enough control to be able to
still sell its own financial products through them.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives have speculated at length on this kind of
outcome, and Breuer himself has hinted strongly in recent weeks
that the rise of electronic banking over the Internet makes it far
less important now to serve customers through physical branch
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many analysts have been skeptical that Deutsche
would give up such a big stake, because it means losing control
over a distribution channel to millions of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's merger is the latest in a wave of bank consolidations
across Europe, from the merger of Banque National de Paris and
Paribas in France to deals in Spain, Belgium, Italy and
Scandinavia. Until Thursday, Germany had been behind most other
countries even though the banking market here is extremely crowded.
Though experts and industry executives have agreed that mergers are
the only possible source of relief, the four big private banks have
spent years wrestling over who would cede control.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the deal Thursday was a ``merger of equals.'' But
Deutsche Bank is clearly in charge. Though the exact exchange ratio
was not set, Deutsche shareholders will own between 60 percent and
64 percent of the company and Dresdner shareholders will own the
rest. The new bank will be called Deutsche Bank but will use
Dresdner's green logo. Dresdner's chief executive, Bernhard Walter,
will share the top post with Breuer.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both banks soared when news of the merger surfaced
Tuesday. But Dresdner shares fell 11 percent Thursday and Deutsche
shares fell almost 13 percent as investors assessed the
cost-cutting plans.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer predicted that the combined bank would be able to save
about $2.9 billion a year, though that figure was considerably more
optimistic than some investment analysts had calculated.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
