A2324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-NYT &LR;      03-09 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SCENTS A STARRING ROLE AND SEIZES IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was clear Thursday that the Senate would vote
for President Clinton's judicial nominees, but so what? Vice
President Al Gore had a chance _ his third in five weeks _ to cast
his shadow over Senate Republicans. So he took it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore diverted his campaign plane to Washington from Detroit late
Wednesday after Senate Democrats told him he might be needed to
break a tie vote on the nomination of Judge Richard A. Paez to the
federal bench. Paez is a Mexican-American whose appointment has
been advocated by Hispanic groups and blocked by Republicans for
four years, longer than that of any other federal judicial nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say he is too liberal. Nonetheless, several,
including Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the Judiciary
Committee, signaled over the last several days that they would vote
for Paez, and they did. Thursday's final tally: 59 in favor,
including 14 Republicans, and 39 against.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Gore rush off the campaign trail to Capitol Hill?
</P>
<P>
   This was better than the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Gore a chance to show that just the threat of his vote
could change Republican minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew that I had such influence in the Republican
Party,'' Gore told reporters. ``I used to joke that every time I
vote, we win. I think it's getting better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But his opening remarks also gave a powerful hint of his
motivation. ``Amigos, hoy finalmente hemos logrado justicia,'' Gore
said. ``Friends, today finally we have seen justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The nomination has been a cause celebre among the nation's
increasingly influential Hispanic voters, and Gore will face a
tough fight with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the likely
Republican nominee, for their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his appearance to position himself against
congressional Republicans, with whom Bush has often been allied.
Gore said there was ``a troubling pattern'' of Senate Republicans'
opposing ``qualified judicial nominees who happen to be women and
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of threatening to break close votes and claim credit
was not lost on Gore, who suggested that this might be an
increasingly common strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I can come back soon to get the Republicans to
change their minds and pass a real patients' bill of rights and
pass a prescription-drug benefit,'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0404 </DOCNO>
