<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2327 &Cx1f; tad-z
s s BC-BKC-CREMINS10-COX     03-09 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CREMINS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss a microcosm of season for Cremins
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Going into his final ACC Tournament as Georgia
Tech's coach, Bobby Cremins said he wasn't worried about winning
and losing. He just wanted his team to play well. If it had to end,
he wanted it to end with his team playing good basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Cremins did not get his wish Thursday night as
the problems which made Georgia Tech an inconsistent team all
season were painfully on display as the Yellow Jackets lost to
Florida State 63-62. It was the fourth consecutive year that the
Yellow Jackets had been eliminated in their first ACC Tournament
game.
</P>
<P>
   After it was over, Cremins received a standing ovation from the
sold-out crowd at the Charlotte Coliseum. But those warm moments
hardly soothed the disappointment of what had transpired in the
previous two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech faithful turned out in force to support their
coach of the past 19 years. Both of Cremins' brothers, Johnny and
Frank, were in the Georgia Tech section, as was wife Carolyn, who
received her fair share of hugs before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Several writers and broadcasters along press row, including
Woody Durham, the voice of the North Carolina Tar Heels, wore
yellow ties and blue shirts to honor the man whose association with
the ACC dated back to 1966, when he was a player for South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   During the pregame announcement of the starting lineup, the
spotlight lingered on Cremins for a few seconds as he recieved the
polite applause of the crowd. He acknowledged it, but seemed
embarrassed by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   They all came here Thursday night hoping to see Cremins win at
least one game and advance to today's second round against
Maryland. Losing to Maryland, one of the hottest teams in the
nation, would not have seemed such a bad way for Cremins to go out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what they got was a reminder of why Cremins believes
``the program needs new leadership.'' Tech played one one of its
worst halves of basketball this season, hitting only 7 of 23 shots
from the field and an inexplicable 5 of 16 from the free throw
line. The Yellow Jackets turned it over nine times.
</P>
<P>
   Only an equally wretched half by Florida State made it a close
game at halftime, as Georgia Tech trailed 25-23.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech trailed by as many as nine in the second half and
finally made its run, closing the margin to 53-52 with 3:24 left.
By then the Coliseum was full and, except for the 2,000 Florida
State fans, they were all pulling for Cremins. But Georgia Tech
could not make the plays down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Cremins went through his postgame rituals for
the final time. He spoke to his team. He spoke to the media. He did
his radio and TV show. There will be some other loose ends to tie
up. He'll fly out to the West Coast Monday to do Gary Miller's Up
Close show on ESPN. Wednesday, he and Carolyn are headed to an
Alabama resort for a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Cremins had allowed himself to dream. There was part of
him that believed his guys could get hot, make a little run in the
tournament, and give these folks in Charlotte something to remember
him by.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of this night was the same as 30 years ago, when
his career as a player was suddenly cut short in this very town in
this very tournament. The basketball has no feelings. You make your
shots, you win. You miss your shots, you lose. It knows or cares
nothing about proper goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
