<HEADLINE>
UNION POLLS WORKING WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey released Thursday found that one-fourth of working
women hold a job that requires them to work at night or on
weekends, while nearly half of working women work shifts different
from those of their spouses or partners.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, sponsored by the AFL-CIO, found that many working
women felt stressed and overstretched, with many complaining that
their employers did not offer flexible hours, paid sick leave or
child-care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 765 working women over 18 years of age found that
60 percent of working women toiled 40 or more hours a week and that
women with minor children were more likely than other women to work
different shifts from their husbands. Fifty-one percent of women
with children under 18 work different hours from their spouses or
partners, while 46 percent of all working women do.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted to articulate what issues are important
to women with an eye to pressuring politicians to heed their
concerns. Many priorities expressed by the women surveyed
dovetailed with the AFL-CIO's legislative program, which calls for
making quality health care more affordable and strengthening laws
to provide benefits and better pay for part-time and temporary
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by Lake Snell Perry &AMP; Associates, found
that the No. 1 legislative priority for women was stronger
equal-pay laws, because many women were unhappy that women earn on
average 73 cents for every dollar that men earn. Eighty-seven
percent of women surveyed said such laws were a priority, while 84
percent said that quality, affordable health care was a priority,
and 83 percent stressed expanding the Family and Medical Leave Act
to provide paid leave.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which had a margin of sampling error of plus or
minus 3.5 percentage points, also found that 34 percent of women
said their employers did not provide them with flexible hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
