<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL-FAULTYCHIP10-COX     03-09 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-FAULTYCHIP10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell recalls notebook computers because of flawed memory chips
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Up to one-third of the notebook computers Dell
Computer Corp. produced last year may have defective memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   Dell began alerting customers during the past few weeks that
some of its Latitude corporate laptops and Inspiron consumer
machines may encounter an unexpected glitch when coming out of
suspension mode, a power-saving function when computers aren't in
use. Because of a memory-chip problem, some notebooks will freeze
or crash, Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affects between 200,000 and 400,000 of the notebooks
made between February and November 1999. Dell produced about 1.2
million notebooks last year, including 540,000 units in the fourth
quarter, according to industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said it will replace the memory modules at no cost to
customers, whom it began informing by letter in recent weeks. Those
customers also are receiving diagnostic tools that will determine
whether their machines are affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue screens and system hangs happen for numerous reasons,''
said Dell spokesman Rob Crawley. ``That doesn't necessarily mean
it's bad memory. That's one of the reasons it took awhile to nail
down the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said the majority of the laptops in question are
Latitudes, which are generally purchased by corporate customers.
Because Dell uses multiple memory-chip suppliers, not all laptops
have the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The affected computers came with either 32 megabytes or 64
megabytes of memory in modules made by Micron Technology Inc. of
Boise, Idaho. Micron spokeswoman Julie Nash said Micron's chips met
Dell's initial specifications, but there was a problem when Dell
added an auto-refresh feature.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said it will either send customers new chips, which
customers can install themselves, or they'll send a tech-support
person to replace the memory modules.
</P>
<P>
   Dell and Micron say they are working out the financial details.
</P>
<P>
   But both companies say the cost of replacing the chips will not
have a financial impact. Analysts agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those chips don't cost much,'' said Jimmy Johnson, an analyst
at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. ``I don't think that's going
to be any big deal. These things happen all the time, but most of
them aren't published. It's no different than when Microsoft has a
problem with its (operating system) and they make a patch
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Micron's retail prices for those modules currently range from
$58.50 to $90. Under a worst-case scenario, the cost is $23.4
million to $36 million, which is less than Dell's daily sales over
the Internet of about $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody like Dell could absorb that quite easily,'' said
Brian Matas, a chip-industry analyst with IC Insights in
Scottsdale, Ariz. ``You'd see it, but it wouldn't impact the bottom
line too much. You want to jump on it right away and take care of
that problem. The bad P.R. would be far more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although word of the problem spread throughout the day Thursday,
Dell's stock enjoyed one of its biggest gains in a long time,
rising $3.50 to close at $50.44. It was Dell's first venture above
$50 since late December. Micron rose $9 to $110 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
