<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOODOO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE CONVICTS VOODOO PRIEST ON 2 MINOR CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tangled trial of a voodoo priest accused of trying to burn a
Haitian pop singer to death in a religious ritual ended Thursday in
Newark, N.J., with the priest convicted only of two minor charges.
</P>
<P>
   During the monthlong trial, Judge Paul J. Vichness threw out
charges that the 43-year-old priest, Pierrot Charles of Irvington,
N.J., had conspired to murder the singer, Sheila DeGraff, 29, and
had intentionally set her on fire in a voodoo ceremony in October
1997. On Thursday, Vichness, who conducted the trial without a
jury, threw out another charge, aggravated assault, and found
Charles guilty of simple assault, based on negligence, and criminal
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally in New Jersey courts, convictions on such charges
carry a sentence of probation. The original charges against Charles
carried a sentence of up to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Charles' lawyer, James M. Weinberg, said that he and his client
had mixed emotions about the outcome. ``We're happy the worst
didn't happen and the main charges were thrown out,'' he said.
``But we're not happy because an innocent man was convicted.''
Weinberg contended during trial that the second- and third-degree
burns DeGraff suffered to her face and neck during the ritual had
occurred accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Jean Valme, DeGraff's former boyfriend, were
originally indicted on charges of conspiracy to murder and
attempted murder, and went on trial together on Feb. 8. But the
prosecution's case was troubled by too few witnesses and by weak,
contradictory testimony that did not support the theory that the
two men wanted to kill DeGraff to spare Valme from repaying a
$25,000 loan.
</P>
<P>
   DeGraff testified that the hood of her robe caught fire during
the ritual after Charles poured an alcohol-based, flammable liquid
known as Florida Water on it.
</P>
<P>
   In midtrial, the prosecutor dropped all charges against Valme in
exchange for his testimony against Charles. Valme denied the
existence of a murder plot and said the hood started burning as
Charles held a candle near it as he sprinkled it with Florida
Water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
