<HEADER>
A2347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-GIULIANI-AR     03-09 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-GIULIANI-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DECIDES TO KEEP HIS HANDS OFF ART SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT42 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that he
considered an artwork that alludes to him and the Nazis offensive,
but that he would not ask the Whitney Museum of American Art to
remove it from a forthcoming exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League, however, harshly criticized the
museum for including the piece in its Biennial exhibition, charging
that the work trivializes the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for the German-born artist, Hans Haacke, who created
the work, it was just another workday in Westbeth, the Greenwich
Village artists' community where he lives, except that his
telephone rang constantly. Labeling the contretemps ``a bit
amusing,'' he said he would not speak in detail about the work,
which is called ``Sanitation,'' until after its installation next
week, in part because he was still working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfortunate that before a work is completed, it is
being talked about,'' Haacke said. ``It's all hypothetical. It
probably won't change, but who knows? I may discover that something
may not work and I may have to adjust it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unadjusted, ``Sanitation'' consists of a wall displaying a
gold-framed reproduction of the First Amendment and six quotations,
printed in the Fraktur Gothic typeface favored by Hitler and the
Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Three quotes are from the mayor and refer to his opposition to
``Sensation,'' the exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art last
fall that included works Giuliani considered offensive. The three
other passages are from conservative politicians who have taken
stands against the National Endowment for the Arts and much
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the quotations, Haacke plans to place a row of eight to
12 garbage cans, each with a speaker playing the sounds of marching
troops.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Giuliani said that the city would take no
action on the piece, which the Whitney commissioned without knowing
its precise contents. ``The real concern of the city has to be when
public money is being used,'' he said. ``If this is privately
funded, and I believe that it is, then the governmental objection
to it passes away. The government has no right to intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added, however, that he did find the piece offensive.
``There is an issue here about demeaning the whole historical and
contemporary importance of the Holocaust,'' he said. ``When people
misuse descriptions like that, in essence they do a grave injustice
to the people who suffered in the Holocaust and to the reality of
what the Holocaust was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the same objection, the Anti-Defamation League's national
director, Abraham H. Foxman, took issue with the Whitney's decision
to show the work in the Biennial, which opens on March 23.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Maxwell L. Anderson, the museum's director,
Foxman berated the Whitney for denigrating the memory of those who
were killed by the Nazis. ``We do not deny Haacke the artistic
freedom to create what he chooses,'' the letter said. ``We would,
however, have expected that the leadership of the Whitney would
have chosen not to contribute to his trivialization of the
Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Foxman added that he found the work to
be ``a very harsh political statement, inappropriate in an election
period.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Anderson said that ``the museum would never
deliberately do anything to offend those affected by the Holocaust,
and we do not believe that this was the artist's intent. We
continue to support artists' right to free expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Haacke, as those familiar with his work know, was simply doing
what he always does. Over the years, Ronald Reagan, George Bush,
Margaret Thatcher, Sen. Jesse Helms, Daimler-Benz, Mobil Oil,
Philip Morris, Benetton and dozens of other individuals,
corporations, governments and institutions have felt Haacke's
sting.
</P>
<P>
   He has even taken on one of Giuliani's targets: Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, the advertising agency founded by Charles Saatchi, who
owns the works in ``Sensation'' and helped sponsor the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   As John Weber, who has been Haacke's dealer for 30 years, said,
``He is the grandfather of this contemporary political art that
everyone is now doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Haacke, 67, began making political statements in the 1960s,
around the time he moved here from Germany. He has never become an
American citizen and has said that his politics are eclectic and
cannot be labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Sol Lewitt, a well-known conceptual artist and a longtime friend
of Haacke, said: ``He has had a vast amount of influence, and
anyone who does anything with political content owes a great debt
to him. He is the first and the best.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of Haacke's best-known pieces was the most talked-about work
at the 1993 Venice Biennale. Visitors to the German pavilion, which
was built in the 1930s, came upon a huge gold Deutsche mark coin
above the door and a blown-up picture of Hitler inspecting the 1934
Venice Biennale. As they passed the photo to enter the grand hall,
they found nothing except ``Germania'' emblazoned on the wall:
Haacke had taken a jackhammer to the marble floor, leaving it in
ruins. ``People were in tears,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years earlier, Haacke had created a giant pack of
cigarettes using the Marlboro colors and logo type, and labeled it
``Helmsboro.'' A picture of Helms, R-N.C., was placed inside the
cameo insignia and ``Philip Morris funds Jesse Helms'' was printed
on each cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Haacke had to teach to make a living, and he became a
tenured professor at Cooper Union. Now his works sell for $25,000
to $200,000, but he still teaches. ``I like to retain my
independence from the art market,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
