<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-BIGEAST-I-NYT &LR;      03-09 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGEAST-I-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOYAS PUSH THE ORANGEMEN AROUND AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT43 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early in the second half of a major upset Thursday
afternoon, Lee Scruggs of Georgetown defended against Etan Thomas
of Syracuse by throwing a high, hard elbow. ``Cut it out!'' shouted
an official, who called a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs smiled, shrugged and gestured with his hands as if to
say, ``Knock off what?'' This, after all, is the way the Hoyas
played all day against Thomas and have played against almost
everyone. Scruggs and his teammates did not exactly knock Thomas'
block off, but they used a rugged defense among other weapons to
knock off the top-seeded Orangemen by 76-72 in the quarterfinals of
the Big East conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown (18-13), which is seeded ninth and won only 6-of-16
league games in the regular season, will meet Connecticut (23-8)
Friday night in the first of two semifinal games at Madison Square
Garden. The Huskies, defending a national championship as well as
this tournament's title, advanced by beating Seton Hall, 79-64, in
the second quarterfinal Thursday afternoon behind 30 points from
Khalid El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown played its best game of the season, just about
everyone agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy right now,'' said Kevin Braswell, the point
guard, who scored 20 points and added eight assists, ``because we
just knocked the No. 1-seeded team off.''
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs, a center, also scored 20 points and had nine rebounds.
``We kind of held Etan in check, and that was the outcome of the
game,'' the 6-foot-10-inch Scruggs said, referring to the best
Syracuse player. ``Coach emphasized that and said every time a shot
went up somebody's got to get a piece of him. I think we kept him
off the boards pretty much.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a 6-9 senior center, managed 17 points and 13 rebounds,
above his season averages, but the Hoyas wore him down, ganging up
on him, substituting frequently with a rotation of big men, forcing
him to commit four fouls while defending his own basket.
Georgetown's Ruben Boumtje Boumtje, who missed Tuesday's
first-round game with a sprained ankle, was part of the rotation,
playing 27 minutes, scoring 12 points and grabbing four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs hit short jumpers from the lane on turnaround moves and
layups from beneath the basket and follow shots after misses by
teammates. He showed emotion with facial expressions and body
language.
</P>
<P>
   After he fouled Thomas, he pounded his fist into the padded
pillar that holds up the basket. But he had better things to do
with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started putting him at the free-throw line against their
zone rather than on the baseline and wing,'' said Craig Esherick,
the Georgetown coach. ``Lee did a great job. He's capable of
hitting that jump shot. He's a two-guard in a 6-11 body. I thought
Lee did a good job in the middle of that zone, both hitting the
shot and getting the ball inside to Ruben.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Boeheim, the Syracuse coach, was not giving the victors
too much praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problem with this game was Syracuse,'' Boeheim said. ``It has
nothing to do with Georgetown. This is the worst we've played the
whole year. I didn't see any leadership. I didn't see any effort
until about 10 minutes to go in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked how his team would rally from this, Boeheim
said, ``I'm sure they're back there having a party.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse, which fell to 24-5, lost its regular-season finale at
Connecticut and is 5-5 in its last 10 games. Boeheim criticized the
play of Damone Brown, who scored 15 points, and Jason Hart, who
scored 11. When asked about DeShaun Williams, who scored 11 points,
Boeheim said: ``We're going to have put up with his defensive
shortcomings. He can't guard anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas seemed more composed than his coach and chose not to find
fault. ``When you lose, everyone wants to point the finger,''
Thomas said. ``All isn't lost. Everyone has to stay positive. We
can't listen to the wrong people too much and get our heads down.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his teammates tried hard and that they are not
``shattered'' as they look forward to the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament next week.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown would be a long shot for an at-large selection in the
64-team field, but would go automatically if it wins the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Esherick said, ``I don't know what the tournament committee
would do if we lost our next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall fell to 20-9 and still hopes for a bid. The Pirates
cut Connecticut's 16-point lead to three points early in the second
half, but fell beneath the weight of El-Amin's entertaining show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a player starts feeling good, he thinks he can hit
anything,'' El-Amin said. ``I was just going at the defense and
attacking the defense like I should.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have won their last five games. For those who
doubted the defending champions during an 8-7 slump before that,
El-Amin said: ``People were counting us out. We can compete with
anyone. We can play with anyone. We can beat anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly beat Seton Hall, which got 21 points from Shaheen
Holloway and 11 each from Samuel Dalembert and Rimas Kaukenas.
Coach Tommy Amaker got a technical foul, a rarity for him.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there should have been a foul called and I said
so,'' Amaker said. He also said El-Amin played a great ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any answers for him in the first half,'' Amaker
said, referring to El-Amin's 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   Darius Lane scored only four points for Seton Hall, which was
outrebounded by 41-25.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Saunders, working back into the good graces of Huskies
Coach Jim Calhoun, scored 14 points and added nine rebounds.
Calhoun praised Kevin Freeman for covering Lane and many others for
all the rebounding. ``We dominated the boards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward the semifinals, Calhoun said to his players:
``Friday night, New York City, the best teams in the neighborhood
playing. A lot of fun for basketball competitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
