<HEADLINE>
FIRE THAT LED TO 3 KILLINGS WAS ARSON, INVESTIGATORS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ Investigators established Thursday that arson was the
cause of the blaze that drew firefighters to a suburban home on
Wednesday afternoon where two firefighters and a sheriff's deputy
were shot to death, as well as the wife of the prime suspect in the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   But no motive was evident yet, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Across this city Thursday, outrage at the seemingly senseless
shootings mixed with sympathy for the families of the victims, who
spent their day making funeral arrangements. Flags flew at half
staff and people left mementos at the shooting site.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they expected to charge Frederick Williams, a
41-year-old firefighter, with multiple counts of first-degree
murder and arson. They said the fire was started by igniting
clothes and bed sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings began when firefighters responded to a call at the
brick house in a middle-class subdivision on the city's southeast
edge. As they were preparing to fight the fire, a man who witnesses
identified as Williams shot at them, killing Lt. Javier Lerma, 41,
and Pvt. William Blakemore, 48, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Peete, 45, a sheriff's deputy, who had been flagged down
by a passer-by, arrived at the house and was also fired upon and
killed. The passer-by, who had gotten out of her car to stop Peete,
was hit in the face by a bullet, but her injuries were not
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers who arrived later shot and wounded Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' wife, Stacey Williams, 32, a postal worker, was found
shot to death inside the burning house. The couple had married been
three weeks ago on Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis police director Walter Crews said, ``It appears this all
might have begun with some sort of domestic disagreement between
the suspect and his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews said Stacey Williams had filed a domestic violence
complaint against Williams in October, and he was scheduled to
appear in court on the charge next week. Crews also indicated that
Williams might have made an emergency call before the ambush to
report the fire at his home.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was being questioned Thursday at a local hospital. He
suffered a broken leg when he was hit by police gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of comments and messages of condolence from all over
the country were posted on the Web site www.Firehouse.com. The
comments included a message from a Memphis firefighter and
paramedic: ``I am deeply saddened, hurt, angry and embarrassed that
'one of our own could do this. My thoughts go out to each and every
one of these families who have suffered a very tragic, senseless
loss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
