<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-HNS &LR;      03-09 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETO LIKELY AS HOUSE TIES TAX CUT TO $1 BOOST IN MINIMUM WAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House easily approved a $1 raise in the minimum
wage Thursday, a move that could boost the average pay for a
full-time worker by $2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure appears headed for a presidential veto because
Republican leaders insisted on attaching it to a $123 billion tax
cut that President Clinton said could jeopardize the nation's
economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again the Republican leadership has derailed what should
be a simple vote on the minimum wage with a maximum of political
maneuvering,'' Clinton said, complaining about the linkage of the
wage issue with a tax-cut measure he insisted would hurt the
government's ability to preserve Social Security and pay down the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should send me a bill I can sign, not one that I have
to veto.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 boost in the minimum wage from $5.15 an hour to $6.15
over two years was approved 246-179. The tax cut, which reduces
estate or so-called ``death'' taxes by more than $78 billion over
10 years, passed 257-169. The bill would also help businesses
cushion the cost of implementing the wage increase through various
tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have long been opposed to any increase in the
minimum wage, preferring to let market forces determine pay levels.
But with the November elections approaching, moderate Republicans,
especially in the Northeast, threw their support behind it out of
concern that labor unions and Democrats might use the issue against
them.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, however, insisted that the minimum wage
measure be tied to a tax relief bill containing provisions from the
$792 billion tax-cut package they failed to get signed into law
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the linkage between the two is designed
to ``kill the minimum wage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they think the American people are stupid?'' asked Rep. Mel
Watt, D-N.C., during the debate. ``It's obvious that the Republican
leadership does not want to pass a minimum wage increase ... That's
why they've attached it to a tax-cut bill that they know is going
to get vetoed.''
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver of linking the wage measure to a tax bill is part
of a election-year strategy by Republican leaders designed to make
it look like they are addressing controversial matters, such as the
minimum wage and health care reform, that could become issues in
the fall campaign. But GOP aides acknowledge that the primary goal
of the strategy is to force the Democrats to deal with the tax-cut
proposals that Clinton rejected last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Republican tax bill is a poison pill designed to defeat
the increase in the minimum wage,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats called on Republican leaders to separate the two
issues, but they refused. They also refused to allow a separate
vote on a smaller $38 billion substitute tax bill offered by Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y,. that was paid for by closing other tax
loopholes. The Rangel bill also contained a targeted tax break for
small businesses that might be affected by the wage increase and a
cut in estate taxes aimed primarily at farmers.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
accused the Democrats of trying to cast the debate over the minimum
wage and tax cuts as ``class warfare'' by charging that the GOP
bill would benefit the rich.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the bill also contains provisions to help the
self-employed buy health insurance and to encourage investment in
poor communities. The tax package would also increase the amount
allowed for business meal deductions and gradually expand
retirement contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats still can't stop the `tax cut for the rich' broken
record,'' Archer said, complaining about the argument Democrats
have long used against GOP-sponsored tax relief legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again Democrats are fighting any tax relief and all tax
relief,'' Archer added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fighting against any tax relief, we're fighting for
fair tax relief,'' Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich, shot back,
challenging his Republican colleagues to bring the minimum wage
measure and the Democratic tax relief substitute up for separate
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a White House appearance earlier this week promoting
the minimum wage increase, served notice that Democrats would
remind voters in November if Republicans failed to back the $1
raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to stop nickel-and-diming the American working
people out of the money that they need and deserve,'' he said.
''This is just wrong ... We have destroyed every single argument
against raising the minimum wage. They're gone. All you've got now
is legislative game-playing, and it's wrong.``
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed its own version of the minimum wage measure
last month, but it would phase in a $1.05 increase over three years
instead of two, a delay that Democrats say will cost hourly workers
$1,000 in annual earnings. The Senate measure would increase the
wage by 35 cents this year, 35 cents next March and 35 cents in
2002. The House bill would increase the hourly rate by 50 cents
this year and 50 cents next year.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate versions will now have to be melded into a
compromise package and sent to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that he still wants a ``clean'' minimum
wage bill free of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have not ruled out the possibility of compromise
with Clinton. But Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, said GOP members will
insist that the wage hike be tied to a tax break of some kind for
businesses that may be forced to pay a higher salary to their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to cushion the impact on the economy, particularly
small business,'' Portman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
