<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CALIF-CASINOS-1STLD-A     03-09 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CASINOS-1STLD-ART-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MAY HAVE HIT ITS JACKPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 6th graf to add an alternative estimate of the market's
value; subs 15th graf to change $50 million to $80 million and to
make some wording changes)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COACHELLA, Calif. _ The modest Indian gambling hall near a truck
stop here in the desert has little of the flamboyance of Donald
Trump's Taj Mahal in Atlantic City, N.J., or of numerous Las Vegas
resorts. About the only glitz is provided by illuminated
star-shaped wall plaques autographed by Tom Jones, Crystal Gale,
Shirley Bassey and other entertainers who have performed at the
casino's combination theater-bingo hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taj has incredible crystal chandeliers that will
absolutely knock your eyes out,'' said Charles J. Irwin, general
manager of the Spotlight 29 Casino here and a former vice chairman
of the New Jersey Casino Control Commission. ``The Vegas places
have water effects and pirate ships and that kind of thing. This is
just a small Indian casino.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not for long. Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts announced
Wednesday that it had signed a letter of intent with the
Twenty-Nine Palms Band of Mission Indians to take over the
Spotlight's management. The tribe and Trump Hotels will raise up to
$60 million to turn the betting parlor into more of a resort, which
is expected to take on the Trump brand name and a dash of Trump's
trademark extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after California voters approved a
measure to legalize Las Vegas-style casinos on Indian lands
throughout the state, setting off a scramble by tribes to expand
existing casinos or open new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Casino companies from Nevada, New Jersey and elsewhere are
angling to get in on what could become a huge gambling market.
Three Las Vegas companies _ Harrah's Entertainment, Anchor Gaming
and Station Casinos _ have already announced deals to build and
manage tribal casinos, each costing roughly $100 million. Lakes
Gaming, a Minnesota company that specializes in managing Indian
casinos, says it has signed up two tribes. Other deals are expected
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal gaming, of course, is already widespread. But the
expansion of tribal casinos in California is noteworthy because the
large population could allow the state to grow quickly into one of
the largest gambling markets, perhaps rivaling New Jersey. Bear,
Stearns has estimated that casino revenue in California will grow
to $4.7 billion in 2004 from about $1 billion a year now. But
Robertson Stephens estimates the California market will reach only
$2.6 billion by then. By contrast, Nevada has about $9 billion in
casino revenue and New Jersey $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It is also noteworthy because California, next door to Nevada,
supplies about a third of the visitors to Las Vegas and an even
higher percentage to Laughlin, Reno and Lake Tahoe. California
could thus pose a bigger threat than other states to Nevada's
gambling-based economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a positive for Las Vegas, I can tell you that,'' said
Trump, whose company runs three casinos in Atlantic City and one in
Indiana but none in Las Vegas. One of the most attractive markets,
he and others said, is this area around Palm Springs, already a
sizable tourist spot. People from Los Angeles can drive here in
about two hours, less than half the time needed to get to Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada casinos spent more than $20 million to try to defeat a
ballot measure in 1998 to legalize California tribal gambling. The
measure was approved overwhelmingly, though it was later overturned
in court. So this year the casinos did not oppose the measure,
which got 65 percent of the vote, and instead are trying for a
slice of the tribal revenues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even the master casino builder Stephen A. Wynn has been
scouting, although the planned acquisition of his company Mirage
Resorts by MGM Grand will take any decision out of his hands. The
Cabazon Band of Mission Indians, which runs a casino a few minutes'
drive from the Spotlight, has held talks with Mirage and other
casino companies, said Brenda Soulliere, first vice chairman, who
said no decision had been made yet.
</P>
<P>
   There are already about 40 tribal casinos in California with
about 19,000 slot machines. But the state constitution bans
Nevada-style gambling, so officials had threatened to shut the
casinos down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, casinos will be able to put in full-fledged slot machines,
not the so-called video lottery terminals they have now, which do
not have arms to pull and print out winnings on a piece of paper.
The tribes will also be able to have card games like blackjack in
which players play against the house. (Now players pay 50 cents or
a dollar a hand into a pool that is used to pay winners.) But craps
and roulette will not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   All this could make gambling more attractive in California. But
more important, with the threat of shutdown eliminated, the tribes
will find it easier to get financing to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so relieved,'' said Richard M. Milanovich, chairman
of the Tribal Council of the Agua Caliente Band of Cahuilla
Indians, which spent millions of dollars to win approval of
Indian-run gambling. The tribe's five-year-old Spa Casino is housed
mainly in a huge canvas tent that stands somewhat incongruously in
the middle of upscale Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tribe is wasting little time. On Monday, the tribe is
expected to announce plans to invest more than $100 million to
build a permanent casino with an entertainment center and
restaurants, and to replace the adjacent Spa hotel with a larger
one. The tribe, one of California's wealthiest, is also expected to
announce an investment of $80 million or more to build a second
casino nearby. The total number of slot machines is expected to
grow to 2,000 from 1,150.
</P>
<P>
   Some tribal officials dispute predictions of an explosion of
gambling in California or a huge influx of Nevada companies. Some
deals now being announced or proposed will not get financing or
prove economically feasible. Some still require tribes to obtain
land and could face local opposition. Many reservations in remote
locations could not support a casino of any size.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to have a lot of significant operations,''
said Howard L. Dickstein, a Sacramento lawyer who represents
several tribes. He said more than half the existing casinos had
fewer than 350 slot machines each.
</P>
<P>
   For casino companies as well, the opportunity is somewhat
limited. Under federal law, outside companies cannot own tribal
casinos and management contracts last no more than seven years, and
usually five.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world I would rather own 100 percent,'' said
Glenn C. Christenson, chief financial officer of Station Casinos.
Still, he said, such deals can be profitable. Station will get 22.5
percent of the net revenue of the casino it will build with the
United Auburn Indian Community near Sacramento, a few miles from
the highway that links San Francisco and Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some casino executives say it makes little sense to set
up a competitor only to be kicked out after five or seven years.
Some tribes, having already run their own casinos, do not need
outside help and do not want to split the profits. Some tribes also
have lingering resentment against the casinos that tried to defeat
the 1998 ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   For slot machine makers the opportunity is less ambiguous.
``It's probably one of the biggest markets that ever opened up all
at one time,'' said Ed Rogich, vice president for marketing at
International Game Technology, the largest manufacturer of slot
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement between tribes and the state, the number of
slot machines could more than double, to about 45,000 _ more than
New Jersey's 36,000 but far behind Nevada's 200,000. And some
analysts say the agreement could be interpreted to allow even more.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Each tribe will be allowed up to 2,000 machines; most big Las
Vegas resorts, Rogich said, have 2,000 to 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the shaky legal ground of the California casinos, the
leading slot machine makers would not sell to them before for fear
of losing their own licenses. The machines in use at the tribal
casinos here, with names like Native American Gold or Native
Nickels, are crude compared with the machines now available
elsewhere, which have themes like Wheel of Fortune or Monopoly, and
bonus rounds. And without clanging coins, these are no doubt some
of the quietest casinos around.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas itself is not expected to suffer much because its
billion-dollar resorts offer entertainment beyond gambling. The
city has continued to grow despite the advent of gambling in
numerous other states. Indeed, there is some evidence that gambling
elsewhere only whets people's appetite for Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Las Vegas is going to be reproduced in Palm
Springs,'' said Ellis Landau, chief financial officer of Boyd
Gaming, which runs four hotels in Las Vegas. While there are four
casinos in the Palm Springs area, they are spread apart.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno and Laughlin, which have fewer nongambling amenities
and are more dependent than Las Vegas on people driving from
California, could be hit harder. Harry C. Curtis, an analyst at
Robertson Stephens, estimates that casino earnings in those cities
could drop 15 to 20 percent in 2001, but recover later.
</P>
<P>
   Harry York, chief executive of the Reno-Sparks Chamber of
Commerce, said the expansion of California gaming was ``definitely
something we have to reckon with and deal with, but it's not going
to kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the city was renovating its downtown and advertising
itself as a place for more than just gambling. And while 30 percent
of the economy is directly dependent on gambling, that number has
dropped as the city has diversified. For example, it has attracted
a big Amazon.com distribution center.
</P>
<P>
   But some people gambling here say they already visit Nevada
less. ``It's better than having to drive to Vegas,'' said Rita
Recio, from near Los Angeles, who was playing a slot machine in the
Palm Springs casino. The lack of clanging coins and the makeshift
environment did not bother her. ``I didn't even notice it was a
tent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people interviewed said they supported the casinos, which
they said had helped the economy and provided entertainment for the
many retirees here. But there was some concern about casinos
growing too rapidly or the area becoming too much like Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see the smallness of it change,'' said Marjorie
Young, who has lived in Palm Springs for 24 years and gambles at
the Spa Casino twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Palms Springs casino has attracted some local opposition,
especially because of its garish electric sign, which some see as
clashing with the city's more subdued ambience. But Milanovich, the
tribal chairman, said the new casino would blend in.
</P>
<P>
   As for Trump, some gamblers were puzzled about what a big
developer could want with a little casino like this. ``Compared to
Mirage and MGM Grand it seems a rather small type of thing,'' said
Joe Preece, a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some said the money could help. Elaine Pandl, visiting
from Wisconsin, said she found the casino a bit ``tacky,'' but when
she heard of Trump's involvement added, ``Maybe he'll put in a new
carpet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
