<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ABANDONED-BABIES-7     03-09 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABANDONED-BABIES-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK PLAN ADDRESSES ABANDONMENT OF NEWBORNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Desperate parents who do not want their newborn
babies would be able to abandon them at hospitals or other safe
places without fear of criminal prosecution, under legislation
endorsed Thursday by the Republican leaders of the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators said the proposal was intended to address the
growing problem of infants who are left to die every year in trash
containers, bathrooms and other dangerous hiding places. Under
state law, a mother who leaves a baby at a hospital without
identifying herself or taking other legal steps for adoption faces
arrest for child abandonment, a felony with a maximum penalty of 16
months to four years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Most hospitals routinely notify law-enforcement officials about
babies left at their doors, but many of the parents are never
prosecuted. The number of arrests for child abandonment has
declined statewide, from 78 in 1997 to 57 last year, according to
statistics provided by the Division of Criminal Justice Services.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's main sponsor, Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann,
R-Syracuse, said a young unwed mother can be so afraid, or ashamed
to tell her parents about her pregnancy, that she will hide it at
any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost impossible to anybody who hasn't been there to
understand how any woman or young girl can go all the way through a
full-term pregnancy without getting help for herself and her unborn
child,'' she said. ``But that is a fact of life. We're not going to
be able to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal seemingly unites a diverse group of family
advocates and lawmakers, although the Democratic leaders of the
Assembly have not yet taken a position.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two dozen states, including New Jersey and California,
have introduced legislation that would allow parents to avoid
prosecution for abandonment, provided that the infant is left in a
safe place or with a responsible person, like an emergency-room
worker. In September, Texas became the first state to enact such a
law, but children's advocates said it was still too early to tell
whether the law had made an impact.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the change in the law would essentially legalize a
practice that has been in place for years in Syracuse and western
parts of the state, several lawmakers and prosecutors said.
Although no statistics are available, Hoffmann said she had worked
with prosecutors and hospitals to ensure that desperate parents
could leave their babies at certain hospitals without being charged
with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers on Thursday also endorsed a pilot program
for the Albany region that would offer amnesty to parents who
abandon infants within 72 hours of their birth at hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth R. Bruno, the Rensselaer County district attorney, said
he was contacting district attorneys and hospitals to participate
in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be criticism of this program,'' Bruno said,
``but we all believe it is much more important to try to prevent a
homicide from happening than it is to deal with someone who
abandons their child.'' His father, Joseph Bruno, the Senate
majority leader, endorsed the pilot project and the bill on
Thursday at a Capitol news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Cases in which babies are found dead in trash bins or other
hiding places tend to get a lot of attention, like the one
involving a New Jersey teen-ager who gave birth in the bathroom at
her senior prom and left the newborn wrapped in plastic. But there
are only sketchy national statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were 105 abandonments in public places, and 33 of
the babies were found dead, according to a review of news reports
by the Department of Health and Human Services that suggested such
incidents were on the rise. That same year, officials said, 31,000
babies were left at hospitals, many by drug addicted or
HIV-positive mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann's bill, which was submitted last month, calls for an
``affirmative defense'' that would allow parents to avoid criminal
prosecution for abandonment if their intention was to safeguard
their babies' lives by leaving them in a safe place. Joseph Bruno
said the bill would be amended in the next few weeks as lawmakers
studied the legislation in Texas and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill would most likely outline a comprehensive
approach to addressing the problem of abandoned babies, Hoffmann
said. In Syracuse, for instance, local officials not only contacted
hospitals but also tried to inform young parents about their
options by broadcasting radio and television commercials, passing
out fliers in schools and establishing a crisis hot line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Joan Christensen, D-Syracuse, who has worked with
Hoffmann on this issue, is sponsoring a version of the legislation
in the Democratic-controlled Assembly. But Assembly leaders,
including Speaker Sheldon Silver, have not yet taken a position.
Patricia Lynch, Silver's spokeswoman, said it was under review.
</P>
<P>
   Several advocacy groups for children and families expressed
their support Thursday. ``Women in these desperate circumstances
need a safe place to turn to,'' said Patricia McGeown, executive
director of the Upper Hudson Planned Parenthood in Albany. But she
also stressed that more sex education and counseling programs were
needed to prevent the unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
