u s BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-NYT &LR;      03-09 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TALK, BUT NO WORD ON JETS DEALING JOHNSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson's future with the New York Jets remained in
limbo Thursday, even as a high-ranking team official said that the
trade talk surrounding Johnson this week has been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Clark, the Cleveland Browns' vice president and director
of football operations, acknowledged Thursday that Bill Parcells
had spoken with the Browns' coach, Chris Palmer, but Clark said no
trade had been offered and that Parcells had just been testing the
waters.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Buccaneers, who hold the 13th and 27th overall
picks in the draft, have also spoken with Parcells, the Jets'
director of football operations. Parcells may be trying to
accumulate picks in an effort to offer an enticing package to a
team that holds one of the top few choices.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has talked with at least six teams about Johnson, a
National Football League executive said, including the teams that
hold the top five picks: Cleveland, Washington (which has the
second and third selections), Cincinnati and Baltimore. Ultimately,
though, the Jets' new head coach, Al Groh, has the final say on
personnel matters, a power that Parcells himself ceded to Groh when
he named Groh as his successor. The Jets declined comment Thursday
through a team spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, with the top pick in the April draft, had once
seemed unlikely to trade away the chance to select the Florida
State wide receiver Peter Warrick. But after seeing the Penn State
defensive lineman Courtney Brown _ whom Parcells is thought to
covet _ and his college teammate, linebacker LaVar Arrington, Clark
said the Browns' plans may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   That could affect the Jets. After a woeful expansion season, the
Browns might be hard-pressed to ignore a deal for several draft
picks. The Jets already have the 16th and 18th picks in the first
round, and if a deal is completed for Johnson, the Jets would
likely package whatever picks are gained from the trade to try to
move up into the top four slots of a draft that is thought to have
just four superstar players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we'll keep the pick,'' Clark said. ``But if
there's an unbelievable deal that comes across, then we'll have to
take a look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark added: ``Coach Parcells is very sly. And he plays this
cat-and-mouse game better than anybody. So if he's saying Courtney
Brown, you really have no idea. He could be saying Courtney Brown
to throw everybody off or it could be true. Who knows? I personally
think he wants LaVar Arrington, because LaVar Arrington is Lawrence
Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals, a team with a well-known desire to keep costs down,
are not opposed to moving down in the draft, the team's director of
pro personnel, Jim Lippincott, said. The Ravens, too, seem
interested in trying to make a deal with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   But the window of opportunity may be rapidly closing. Ravens
Coach Brian Billick, who has been remarkably candid about his
team's interest in Johnson, said Thursday that the Ravens would
probably call the Jets last night or Friday morning to ask them
what is going on. Ever since the Ravens told the Jets the
parameters in which they would work to try to make a deal _ the
Ravens want to talk to Johnson and his agent, Jerome Stanley _ they
have not heard back from the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the gamesmanship you play,'' Billick said. ``We've
set some parameters as far as how far we can go time-wise. There is
coming a point very quickly where this is prohibiting us from doing
other things. There comes a point where our timetable is going to
force us to say, `You need to respond or we'll move on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Billick said he would not like to see the Ravens' involvement
drag on past the weekend if the Jets do not indicate interest in
working toward a deal. Still, Billick remains optimistic that if
the Jets are interested, a deal could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the right place and we have the resources available
to us, because we've been cap conservative,'' Billick said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
