</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DREW DONATIONS FROM 49 STATES LAST YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's Senate campaign received
contributions last year from donors in every state except North
Dakota, attracting an even broader geographic spectrum of financial
support than his rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton, according to a
report Thursday by a nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, by the Center for Responsive Politics,
criticized the Giuliani campaign sharply for failing to provide
full disclosure of its largest donors, saying that 21 percent of
those contributing $200 or more had not specified their occupations
or employers in filings with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that data, it is impossible to identify the donors'
economic interests,'' said the report, which followed a separate
report in late February by the same group on Clinton's
contributors. It found that the Clinton campaign had identified the
occupations and employers of more than 90 percent of its donors who
gave $200 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism provoked a sharp exchange between campaign
advisers, with Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, charging in a
news release that the Giuliani camp was ``evading campaign laws by
refusing to tell the people of New York what his donors do for a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   Although federal election guidelines require candidates to seek
and disclose information on their donors' employment, there is a
gray area in that donors are under no obligation to disclose what
they do or where they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton's press secretary either doesn't know what he is
talking about or doesn't care,'' said John H. Gross, the Giuliani
campaign treasurer. He said the mayor's campaign staff had ``fully
complied'' with federal rules by asking for employment information
in its direct mailings to potential donors and in follow-up letters
to people who sent contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that Giuliani's campaign raised $11.8 million
last year from donors in 49 states, compared with Clinton's
campaign contributions of $8.1 million from donors in 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   It said that the largest source of financial support for the
mayor came from people in the financial industry, based in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier report on the Clinton campaign found its biggest
source of support was among lawyers and people in the entertainment
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
