u f BC-IMF-KOHLER-NYT &LR;      03-09 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-KOHLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CANDIDATE FOR IMF POST IS WELL VERSED IN POST-SOVIET TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Just four months ago, as rumors swirled about likely
candidates for the top job at the International Monetary Fund,
Horst Koehler, the German head of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, decided to issue a one-line
statement that he was not in the running. How things change.
</P>
<P>
   This week, after a telephone call from Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, Koehler told his staff that if the majority of the IMF's
shareholders wanted him as managing director, ``then I would not
decline that request.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a cautious and noncommittal way of accepting an offer
that Schroeder clearly did not want him to refuse after the
withdrawal of an earlier German candidate, Caio Koch-Weser.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with Koch-Weser's contentious candidacy, Koehler _ a
57-year-old former Finance Ministry official with an impressive
record in gluing the financial underpinnings of both German
reunification and the European single currency _ has become mired
in a trans-Atlantic debate over his credentials to head the IMF,
one of the world's most influential financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler was not available for comment, his aides said Thursday.
But they insisted that he did not invite the present situation.
``He was approached,'' one aide said. ``He didn't pursue this.''
What made the difference between his statement last November and
his attitude this week, the aide said, was simple: ``He got a call
from the chancellor.''
</P>
<P>
   Wishing to avoid a second embarrassment over an unpopular
candidate, Schroeder has been making quite a few calls to win an
endorsement of Koehler, and he has insisted that that support is
building.
</P>
<P>
   Even Thursday, the chancellor said he received a pledge of
backing from Britain. But the British government declined to state
its position, adding to the uncertainty surrounding Koehler's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In money terms, the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development that Koehler heads is not in the same league as the
IMF. Last year, it made a modest profit of $42 million.
Significantly, though, the year before, its exposure in Russia
contributed to a $260 million loss.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler joined the organization just two weeks after Russia
defaulted on some of its debt and has overseen the bank's recovery.
``The bank didn't lose its way'' after the Russia crisis, said Mark
Milner, a British financial journalist who covers the bank. ``It
didn't lose its nerve, which it might easily have done.''
</P>
<P>
   But its scope is also narrower than the IMF's. Established in
1991 to help build market economies and democracy in the old Soviet
bloc, the bank operates in 26 countries from Russia to Albania. It
primarily invests in business-sector projects, drawing capital into
enterprises it supports. So far, it has sunk $13 billion into
projects it values in total around $47 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The European bank's image, however, is tarnished with the
excesses of its early years when its director, Jacques Attali of
France, was accused of running an institution that financed itself
more than the fledgling businesses of Eastern Europe. In excess of
$1 million was reportedly spent on replacing the marble in its
London entrance lobby, prompting some to ask if the bank was needed
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler has tried to move the bank away from those perceptions,
even though it remains a top-heavy institution with 23 directors
and an array of governors. ``He wants to get out and see what the
money is doing,'' said Barbara Clay, the bank's spokeswoman. ``He's
a very hands-on guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is the bank the only measure of his portfolio. As a
senior German official, Koehler was involved in the negotiations
leading to his country's reunification and European monetary union
in the early 1990s. In Germany, he played a central role in
privatizing the ruined economic institutions of East Germany. And
as the German ``sherpa'' to the Group of Seven industrial nations
_the nickname given the officials who prepare top-level meetings _
he has traveled widely.
</P>
<P>
   During the Asian economic crisis, he was dispatched to Indonesia
to discuss a German role in recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler's association with the European bank has strengthened an
appearance of close ties with Eastern and Central Europe that go
back to his birth in Poland in 1943 and his childhood in eastern
Germany before his family fled to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a good background,'' he said in a published
interview last year. ``I have a certain understanding of the
emotions, of the psychology of the people who live in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The question raised in European capitals is whether he is
focused too narrowly on the former East bloc and on the minutiae of
the region's transition from Communism to market economics.
</P>
<P>
   Aides have sought to portray Koehler as an investment-oriented
businessman running a for-profit bank. Moreover, they say, Koehler
spent time in private business from 1993 to 1998 as president of
the German Savings Bank Association. And, his backers say, he has a
wide range of government and business contacts.
</P>
<P>
   People who work with him depict him as intense and impatient.
``He's got a passionate but logical view of the way the world ought
to work,'' a co-worker said. ``Once he has got a strategy, he likes
to see it put in place real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who have met him argue that his experience may be
perceived in Washington and elsewhere as limited. ``It's a question
of whether he could become a global player,'' a British banker
said. ``He's running an international financial institute, that's
true. But it's not the biggest one in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
