<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-REPUBS-BALLOT-ART-     03-09 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBS-BALLOT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATE LEADER ATTACKS PRIMARY SYSTEM AND CALLS FOR CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT39 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Calling New York's Republican presidential
primary system ``absolute nonsense,'' the Republican leader of the
state Senate called Thursday for top-to-bottom reform, making
ballots easier to understand, and making it simpler for candidates
to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal by Joseph L. Bruno, the Senate majority leader,
reflected his impatience with Gov. George Pataki, a fellow
Republican who had signaled that he was in no hurry to revise the
rules, and it widened the growing rift between them.
</P>
<P>
   It also appeared that Bruno had forced the governor's hand.
Michael McKeon, Pataki's press secretary, at first said there was
no urgency to changing the rules, but Thursday evening he said that
the governor would make his own proposal. ``I would expect
something sooner rather than later,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Pataki and Bruno have skirmished over Bruno's
efforts to strike out independently on issues while the governor's
aides have insisted that Bruno defer to Pataki. Last month, Bruno
said that on ballot reform, he would do just that, waiting for the
governor to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last two months, New York's Republicans have taken a
steady drubbing from Sen. John McCain and his supporters, from
newspaper editorials and from election reform groups _ first for
the complicated rules that the party establishment used in an
unsuccessful effort to keep McCain off the ballot and then for the
equally convoluted structure of the ballot itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats in the Senate, hoping to embarrass Republicans and
pick up a few seats in November, have called for changes in the
primary system, as has the Republican minority in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was clearly concerned that the whole affair had tainted
Republican legislators, 21 of whom were on Tuesday's ballot as
delegates for George W. Bush. Bruno, who himself was elected a Bush
delegate, Thursday took the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the Senate are going to move diligently to correct a
system that we believe to be faulty,'' he said at a news conference
in the Senate majority's oak-paneled conference room in the
Capitol. ``It was absolute nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial response from the governor's office was tepid, as
McKeon declined to comment directly on Bruno's statements, noting
that the issue need not be decided soon because it ``won't be
relevant again until 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``We fully expect to continue to embrace reform ideas
that make the process even more user-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, advisers to the governor were irritated that once
again, Bruno had taken the lead.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Republicans and Democrats have long had an
understanding that the lawmakers in each party can devise their own
primary rules. In other words, if the Senate and the governor
agreed on a new set of rules, then the Democrats who control the
Assembly would not stand in the way. Thus, the only obstacle to
Bruno's aims is Pataki, who will come under pressure to follow the
Senate's lead or risk being tagged an opponent of reform.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear what the Democrats would do if the Senate
passes a bill that Pataki opposes. Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
declined to comment on Bruno's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters complained that they had difficulty understanding
the Republican primary ballot, which showed delegates' names in
large type, with the names of the presidential candidates whom
those delegates supported listed below, in much smaller print. Some
voters said they had trouble reading the candidates' names, or did
not understand that they could vote for up to three delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there was too much confusion,'' Bruno said. ``What
we want is a system where people can be confident and comfortable
that they voted the way they intended to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno declined to make his proposals specific, saying that no
bill had been drafted yet, but he said he wanted to remove
obstacles to having the names of well-known candidates placed on
the ballot. ``We're taking a look at something that will be rather
comprehensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, well-known candidates are automatically placed
on the ballot, and in others, only a filing fee is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Republican Party's rules are widely considered the
most difficult in the nation. They require the collection of
thousands of registered Republicans' signatures, with a certain
number needed in each congressional district, including districts
in New York City where Republicans are exceedingly rare. New York's
election law also gives candidates ample room to knock one another
off the ballot by challenging their opponents' signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a federal judge ordered all candidates placed on all
ballots, but the effort to prevent McCain from competing left a
sour taste for some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who bowed out of the presidential race Thursday, ran
strong in New York but lost. He won just four of contests in 13
states on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' presidential rules in New York are strikingly
different from the Republicans', with less onerous signature
requirements, and voters vote directly for the candidates as well
as for the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, meeting Thursday with reporters at state party
headquarters here, said, ``I'm not opposed to change,'' but
declined to take a stand on what Bruno had said.
</P>
<P>
   For politicians who ran as Bush delegates, the last month has
been harrowing. Many were recruited as delegates last year by
Pataki, with assurances that there would be no real contest, then
suddenly found themselves in a race. Some lost, a serious blow to
their prestige; others had close calls; and many said they would
welcome rules changes that would avoid a reprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
