<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR SULLIES STARS' FORMERLY CLEAN IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amply polished and deftly marketed, the Dallas Stars heretofore
have been the choir boys of the local sports scene.
</P>
<P>
   From the star of Stars, Mike Modano, every local mother's
wannabe son, to the head coach, the engaging Ken Hitchcock, the
Stars' image in the area community has been Zambonied clean.
</P>
<P>
   They are not about nose rings or feather boas. Their star
receiver didn't wear a fur coat and designer shades to testify
before the grand jury. Their right fielder never pulled out of a
game because his pants were too large.
</P>
<P>
   Until the wee hours of Wednesday morning, the Stars had almost
basked in antiseptic charm. Lord Stanley himself, fans here smugly
assumed, would have been proud.
</P>
<P>
   Except that somewhere on the wrong side of midnight that night,
the star goaltender got Maced. That was before Dallas police
slapped handcuffs and leg-irons on him, but after he had caught the
hotel guy in a 15-minute headlock.
</P>
<P>
   Boys will be boys. But judging by the police report, this was an
acute case of drunken stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   We only know what the report says. Yet Ed Belfour's behavior
Wednesday morning was loutish, even for a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   The police report reads like a scene from Slapshot, Hollywood's
cult salute to goon hockey. Wall-slams and headlocks are part of
hockey's ancient mating ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a woman involved. She told police that Belfour
scared her.
</P>
<P>
   We know. Belfour has eyes that glaze with mischief.
</P>
<P>
   The woman appears to have been only a catalyst in the early
morning saga. The more troubling scenes are the alleged ones
involving Belfour's attack on the hotel employee, his resistance
when police arrived, and his misbehavior inside the jailhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, was it the alcohol, or was it Eddie?
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars organization stepped aside Thursday, NHL
substance-abuse investigators began to dig deep. If Belfour has a
problem, whether it be alcohol or his behavior, the NHL people are
expected to identify it and deal accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour could be back playing next week. On the other hand,
Belfour could be back next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know when or how long this is going to take,''
Hitchcock said Thursday. ``The way the NHL handles it, it pretty
much takes us out of the picture right now.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are ready to welcome him back. Concern and support
for Belfour has been unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest part is going to be coming back into our group,''
Hitchcock said. ``The easiest part will be the playing of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a well-respected person who means a lot to our team and
has gone through a lot with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Stars lineup, therefore, won't be difficult for
Belfour. In a season beset with injuries, the Stars can do without
another of their top players for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the abuse that will be showered upon Belfour on the
road is something the team can deal with. As a rule, Belfour
provokes enemy ticket-buyers and sets them to chanting.
</P>
<P>
   No, that won't be the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's biggest hurdle will be the NHL's diagnosis. There
could be an after-care program. Weekly _ or even more frequent _
testing. Even if the Stars add nothing to Belfour's ``punishment,''
the NHL substance-abuse people could place him on a figurative,
well-confined leash.
</P>
<P>
   The public? Belfour figures to get more get-well cards than
tsk-tsks. Next to golden boy Modano, he could well be the most
popular member of the Stanley Cup champions. He has been an avid
supporter of the Make-A-Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Stars have earned considerable slack. It's
going to drive the arrogant Cowboys front office crazy. Where are
the three-inch headlines, they'll want to know? Where's the public
outcry, the Channel 5 reports?
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any. The Stars' reputation, unlike the Jones-era
Cowboys, is almost Disneyesque.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans' greatest fear today isn't Belfour's likely future
court date _ it's when he will return to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   For his sake, hopefully that day is soon. Soberingly soon. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
