<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-ART-NYT &LR;      03-09 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMUM-WAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMUM WAGE RAISE OF $1 IS APPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is an added starter to The New York Times front page)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House agreed Thursday to raise the federal
minimum wage by $1 to $6.15 an hour but coupled the measure with a
$123 billion tax-cut package sponsored by the Republicans that
President Clinton had threatened to veto, imperiling the wage
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans staged separate votes on the two measures, seeking
to defuse a politically potent Democratic issue in the November
election by promoting one of their own, tax cuts, then merged the
two measures into one bill. The political effect, however, is that
the measures cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   The final vote on the wage increase was 282-143. Earlier,
lawmakers voted 246-179 to approve a Democratic amendment that
would spread the increase over two years instead of three, which
would provide low-income workers with more money, faster. On that
vote, 42 Republicans joined 203 Democrats and one independent.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the tax cuts said they would ease the impact of
the wage increase on employers and poor rural and urban
communities. But Democrats denounced the measure as a gift to the
rich.
</P>
<P>
   That measure passed, 257-169, with 41 Democrats joining 215
Republicans and one independent in favor, and 167 Democrats, one
Republican and one independent voting against.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Senate approved an overhaul of bankruptcy laws
that included a $1 increase in the minimum wage over three years
and $76 billion in tax breaks over 10 years. House and Senate
negotiators must now reconcile the competing versions before a
final bill can be sent to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But looming over those talks is Clinton's threat to veto the
overall bill because the Republican tax breaks would gobble up too
much of the projected budget surplus that could be used to shore up
Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the Republican leadership has derailed what should
be a simple vote on the minimum wage with a maximum of political
maneuvering,'' Clinton said before the vote. ``Congress should send
me a bill I can sign, not one I have to veto.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the tax bill's 10-year cost comes from a gradual
reduction in the estate tax, costing $78.6 billion over the decade,
with Democrats calling the measure tax breaks to people with
incomes over $319,000.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the House's passage last month of a bill to cut
taxes for married couples by $182 billion over the next decade,
Republicans have now approved two pillars of their $792 billion,
10-year tax plan that Clinton vetoed last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Republicans have adopted the strategy of breaking out
important parts of that bill and ramming them through the House,
knowing that the measure's prospects in the Senate are uncertain
and that it is doomed at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But in an election year, House Republicans are willing to pocket
the floor votes as legislative triumphs and portray the White House
as out of step with public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, Democrats are fighting tax relief, all tax
relief,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the House Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The tax package also gradually increases the 401(k) contribution
limit and makes some other pension changes, makes health insurance
premiums fully tax deductible for self-employed people sooner than
under current law, increases the amount of business meals that can
be deducted, and repeals accounting rules that require
small-business owners to pay capital gains immediately on the sale
of their businesses, even if they are paid by the buyer in
installments.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans staged the dual votes Thursday night on the minimum
wage and tax breaks to prevent Democrats from pushing through their
own minimum wage increase, which has support from moderate
Republicans from the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of waging a contentious battle as they did in 1996,
the last time Congress increased the minimum wage, Republican
leaders acknowledged that a minimum wage raise was an election-year
inevitability. The only questions centered on when the increases
would take effect and how large the corresponding tax cuts would
be.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 million full-time workers paid the minimum wage now
earn about $10,700 a year. Raising their wages to $6.15 an hour
would increase their annual earnings by $2,000, enough, supporters
say, for a low-income family of four to buy groceries for seven
months or pay rent for five months.
</P>
</TEXT>
