<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-WAC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU DUMPS SAN JOSE STATE; TULSA NEXT UP FOR FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 TOURNAMENT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ Hey, Horned Frogs, you've just beaten San Jose
State, 84-71, in the first round of the Western Athletic Conference
tournament, so here's Billy to tell you what you've won. Drum roll,
please.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tulsa,'' TCU coach Billy Tubbs said with his trademark dry
wit. ``That's a big prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, the Frogs also probably won an expenses-paid trip to
the National Invitation Tournament, but that parting gift is at
least a Selection Sunday away.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate goody is Friday's first WAC semifinal at 8 p.m. If
the fifth-seeded Frogs (18-13) are going to reach Saturday's WAC
title game, they've got to get past a team that has beaten them by
a combined 54 points in this season's two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 seed Tulsa, 28-3 and ranked 15th nationally, appeared to
waste little energy in handling eighth-seeded Rice, 71-51,
Thursday. And though the regular-season league champion Golden
Hurricane handed TCU its two worst beatings of the season _ 33 and
21 points _ Frogs guard Estell Laster believes the pressure is on
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the underdog,'' Laster said after scoring 22 points
Thursday. ``They might come in overconfident. The third time is
usually when you get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Laster, the only Frogs player to have two solid games against
Tulsa, is banking on the experience of those setbacks to reverse
his team's fortunes Friday, even though Tulsa swallowed up TCU
quickly in both contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what they like to run, know their sets and their
mind-set is that they're going to win,'' said Laster, who averaged
18 points in the losses. ``We're going to have to match their
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said his team matches up well athletically with the Golden
Hurricane, but offensive execution and defensive discipline have
been the problem in both games. Derrick Davenport, the Frogs'
6-foot-10 shot-blocking specialist, returns to the starting lineup
Friday in place of 6-6 guard Bingo Merriex.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's frontline may also receive a boost if Tubbs summons 6-7
power forward Myron Anthony from Fort Worth. Tubbs said Anthony,
suspended before the Frogs left for Fresno, Calif., has served his
punishment and it's possible he'll be on a plane this morning.
</P>
<P>
   If the Frogs are going to have a chance against Tulsa, Tubbs
said, they would need to duplicate Thursday's second-half
performance. TCU exploded past the Spartans over the final 20
minutes on the strength of a relentless press and deadeye shooting.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State (15-15) allowed only 58.9 points per game during
the season, but TCU nearly reached that total in the second stanza
alone, outscoring the Spartans 54-33. TCU erased a 38-30 halftime
deficit with a 15-2 run to open the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of the game was too fast in the second half and
didn't allow us to set up in our half-court offense,'' San Jose
State coach Steve Barnes said. ``We got caught up in TCU's style of
play and our game broke down. Fatigue was definitely a factor in
the outcome of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Frogs guard Ryan Carroll, who scored 19 points and hit three
3-pointers, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice the full-court press all the time,'' Carroll said.
``I don't think many people are used to playing it, so I think that
is where we were able to capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   The question Friday is whether the Hurricane, relatively rested
but not extremely deep, can be worn down with the Frogs' preferred
frenetic tempo. Tulsa played Thursday's first game and, because
they built a big early lead, coasted in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we play, there's an advantage for a team that's got a
little more rest,'' Tubbs said. ``But the good thing about young
bodies, they recover quickly.'' TULSA 71, RICE 51
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Golden Hurricane jumped out to a quick 10-0 lead
and never looked back in eliminating No. 8 Rice (5-22). Reserve
forward David Shelton scored 20 points in 22 minutes, and center
Brandon Kurtz added 14 points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 10 minutes, we were ready to play,'' Tulsa coach
Bill Self said. ``When you get a big lead, sometimes you lose
energy. We didn't play with passion in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   While today's semifinalists are hoping to improve their NCAA
Tournament chances with a strong showing, Self said his squad,
already a lock for the NCAAs, has a different motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team understands that our performance here will make the
difference in seeding for the (NCAA) Tournament,'' he said. ``We
know the difference between a 6-seed and a 3-seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice ended its season 5-22.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
