<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEWS ANALYSIS: McCAIN AS NONCANDIDATE IS STILL PROBLEM FOR BUSH  
(Eds: Adds ``without the workers' consent'' to end of 6th graf.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has not even been officially crowned the Republican
presidential nominee, but already Gov. George W. Bush finds himself
confronted with a classic predicament, one that poses a significant
test to his leadership skills: How does he win over Sen. John
McCain _ and his crucial block of independent and Democratic
loyalists _ without antagonizing the Republican establishment that
pulled Bush to victory?
</P>
<P>
   It is a ticklish spot: Bush cannot win the election in November
unless large numbers of McCain's supporters rally behind him. The
simplest way for that to happen is for the Arizona senator to rally
behind Bush first.
</P>
<P>
   Already top Bush lieutenants are quietly reaching out to
McCain's camp, sending signals that they respect him and want to
work with him.
</P>
<P>
   But many people close to McCain said he might not be inclined to
play along, at least not enthusiastically, unless Bush embraces the
centerpiece of his candidacy: his sweeping campaign-finance
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The quandary for Bush is that his advisers say it would be
inconceivable for the Texas governor to sign on to McCain's
prescription for campaign reform, because its ban on unregulated
soft money has been scorned by crucial elements of the Republican
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Bush demonstrated the sensitivity
of the matter by not ridiculing the McCain proposal as he usually
does. Instead, he dodged a question about whether he would embrace
a ban on soft money, saying, ``We'll just see at the time.'' He
went on to press for his own proposal that would ban union dues
from being used for political campaigns without the workers'
consent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Bush drew so much support so early from
governors, members of Congress and interest groups _ and that
McCain did so poorly with those same categories _ is that he vowed
never to do anything to jeopardize the Republicans' financial
advantages. The governor is not about to risk alienating those
groups now, especially when some are planning to run independent
advertising campaigns that would benefit his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate situation because Bush is no longer the
front-runner _ he is in effect the nominee _ and he therefore has a
responsibility to lead the party,'' said Ed Gillespie, a Republican
strategist who supports Bush. ``But at the same time, the key to
victory in November is an appeal to many of the voters McCain
appealed to in February and March.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush adopted McCain's campaign-finance plan, Gillespie said,
``he would be whipsawed from the left and from the right.''
</P>
<P>
   That's only part of the problem. Bush could risk looking like a
compliant pushover if he were to fold. After all, he derided
McCain's finance plan at one of their debates by saying: ``It is
bad for Republicans and it's going to hurt the conservative
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain is not about to settle for the far less sweeping
campaign-reform plan that Bush introduced just before the South
Carolina primary, in a move to trump the senator's reform
credentials. McCain called it a ``camouflage and a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush would get into a little consistency trap,'' said Don
Sipple, a media consultant for the governor's past campaigns.
``He's staked out his position pretty well. He would look
unprincipled and opportunistic and hypocritical if he was to lurch
over on that one issue for instant gratification. Whatever you get
at the end of that process is just not worth what you gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Bush does not somehow find a way to mollify McCain, even
more trouble could lie ahead. There is a rich history in the
Republican Party of struggles between the party's establishment and
wings on one side or another. Barry Goldwater, who was nominated on
a right-wing crusade in 1964, never succeeded in reaching out to
Nelson Rockefeller or his more moderate supporters. He lost in that
November.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1992, President George Bush reached out _ in hindsight
too eagerly _ to the insurgent who had tried to topple his campaign
from the right, Pat Buchanan. Buchanan's irate speech at the
nominating convention haunted the party for months, even years, to
come _ and played a part in dooming Bush's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans close to the Bush campaign said one possibility is
that the governor would put out an explicit or tacit signal to
McCain that he could take issue publicly with Bush on prized topics
like campaign finance and taxes but still be welcomed on good
terms. The important thing, they said, is that he support Bush as
the far preferable alternative to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It may be wishful thinking, but Bush advisers are also primed
with examples of other politicians who are close to McCain but take
issue with his position on campaign finance. For example, Sen.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, a top McCain adviser, did not vote for the
campaign-finance measure, and Bob Dole opposed it as well _ even
though he and McCain are close.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican official familiar with the talks between the two
camps said of McCain, ``He's going to be watching to see how Bush
talks about reform'' _ and to make sure that his ``reformer with
results'' self-description is more than a slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem for Bush is that he, of course, can only
play one side of the equation. It is not clear yet what McCain
expects _ or might demand _ from Bush or from the committee that
will draft the party platform for the convention in Philadelphia in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Few clues could be gleaned from the senator's enigmatic speech
in the mountains of Arizona on Thursday. After making clear that
the Republican Party ``is my home,'' McCain once again raised his
signature issue that so many Republicans despise. ``I'm also
dedicated to the necessary cause of reform,'' he said, ``and I will
never walk away from a fight for what I know is right and just for
our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
