<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: SIGNING MINE BAN Russia agreed to sign the 1996 Geneva
treaty banning anti-personnel land mines, a weapon its troops have
used widely _ and to sharp criticism _ in their war against Chechen
rebels. The Kremlin said it would sign, after being persuaded that
it could cheaply destroy its existing stocks of up to 60 million
mines and still protect key sites, like nuclear installations, with
other defenses. The United States has not adopted the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY: PREMIER QUITS Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik, 52,
quit after losing a key environmental vote in Parliament. Bondevik
said he would hand in his resignation to King Harald on Friday
after an opposition majority led by the Labor Party voted to build
Norway's first gas-fired power plants. Jens Stoltenberg, 40,
Labor's leader, is expected to try to form a new cabinet. Bondevik
had been in power since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: ENVOY RECALLED Britain recalled its ambassador from
Zimbabwe to protest the forced opening of a 7-ton diplomatic
consignment. Britain said such shipments are protected by
convention from customs searches. Zimbabwe, which argued that it
had a right to open unusually large diplomatic packages, said the
consignment contained ``sensitive communications gadgets.'' Britain
said it contained routine ``protective screening equipment for
communications as well as the tools for its installation.''
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: BOOK BANNED A court banned circulation of a best-selling
book containing a reference to Jesus' having sexual relations with
Mary Magdalene. The book, titled ``M to the Power of N,'' was
banned in northern Greece pending a final decision on May 16 about
the rest of the country. The Greek Orthodox Church has condemned
the book as ``unscientific, filthy, and the vilest book in
Christendom.'' Judge Maria Robbi said she acted after religious
militants threatened to take action against the author and
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: RIGHTIST'S THREAT TO QUIT As conservative Canadians seek
to unite the right, Preston Manning says he will resign as leader
of the Western-based Reform Party if party delegates vote March 25
to join a new national party, the Canadian Reform Conservative
Alliance. With a leadership race for the new party scheduled for
June 25, Manning, a veteran Alberta member of Parliament, is
expected to face stiff competition from Stockwell Day, Alberta's
49-year-old treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SCHOOL SIT-IN ENDS Several dozen students and parents
supporting them ended a three-day occupation of the offices of the
president of the National University. The protesters, who were
demanding the release of students jailed when the police broke up a
nine-month strike on Feb. 6, faced a barrage of public criticism.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: KEY AIDE A SUICIDE A top aide to Attorney General Jorge
Madrazo, Juan Manuel Izabal, shot himself to death as authorities
were beginning an investigation into $700,000 found in his name at
a Citibank branch. Izabal left a letter saying the money was from
``businesses.'' He denied accumulating the funds from drug
traffickers' bribes, but acknowledged that they were ``difficult to
explain.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: PRAISE BY KIM President Kim Dae-jung, on a
three-day visit to Germany, praised the way the Germans handled
unification in 1990 and said he hoped to achieve the same
reconciliation with North Korea through ``cooperation, coexistence
and co-prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: COMPLAINTS TO UNITED NATIONS Iraq complained to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan about a visit by U.S. and Turkish
officials to the Kurdish-controlled areas of northern Iraq without
approval. It was not the first time U.S. officials entered from
Turkey, an act that Iraq regards as illegal. The U.S. State
Department said such visits would continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
