</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DELIBERATING CASE OF OFFICER WHO KILLED FUGITIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. _ While intense attention has been focused on
the trials of police officers in the death of Amadou Diallo and the
assault on Abner Louima, a jury in State Superior Court here has
been hearing the case of the first Connecticut police officer ever
charged with murder in the shooting of a suspect while on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations in the trial of the officer, Scott Smith of the
New Milford, Conn., police department, began Thursday afternoon.
Smith is charged with killing a fugitive, Franklyn Reid, by
shooting him once in the back after chasing him along a local
highway on Dec. 29, 1998. Reid, an ex-convict, was being sought for
failing to appear in court on a harassment charge. Like the New
York cases, this one has racial overtones: Smith is white; Reid was
black.
</P>
<P>
   After the closing arguments Thursday, Judge Charles D. Gill
noted ``various citizen-police incidents'' in the news lately and
admonished the jurors not to ``let those other cases interfere'' as
they considered Smith's fate. Gill, at the prosecution's request,
also instructed jurors to consider lesser charges of manslaughter
should they reach a not-guilty verdict on the murder count.
</P>
<P>
   In summing up the prosecution's case Thursday morning, State's
Attorney John A. Connelly described a cold-blooded killing. He said
that Reid was lying on the ground with Smith's foot on his back
when he was shot. The officer's 9-millimeter service weapon was
pressed against Reid's spine when it was fired, Connelly said.
``This bullet severed Franklyn Reid's spine,'' he said. ``The hole
is perfectly round.''
</P>
<P>
   Recounting testimony from several witnesses who saw Smith
standing over Reid on the shoulder of Route 202 in New Milford,
Connelly described a scene in which a suspect who had raised his
arms in the air as a sign of surrender was suddenly shot dead by an
officer out of control. ``Officer Smith let his emotions take
over,'' Connelly said. ``And because of that, Franklyn Reid is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In closing for the defense, Smith's lawyer, John J. Kelly,
recounted Reid's criminal record _ including a conviction for a
stabbing _ and reminded the jurors that he had been fleeing an
arrest warrant. Reid ignored Smith's orders to show his hands,
Kelly said, and after the shooting was found with a knife in his
jacket and a Pennsylvania driver's license in a fake name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show me your hands, show me your hands,'' Kelly said,
describing his client's efforts to subdue Reid. ``Despite repeated
requests to stop, despite repeated requests to show your hands,
that didn't happen.'' Holding up the pocket knife to the jury, he
said, ``Did Scott Smith have to wait until Franklyn Reid got ahold
of this knife and used it on him before defending himself?''
</P>
<P>
   He said Smith had no motive. ``The state's theory in this case
comes down to this: that Scott Smith conducted a public execution
of Franklyn Reid for no reason,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the two-week trial's most dramatic day of
testimony, Smith took the stand in his own defense. ``I couldn't
see his hands,'' he said. ``I kept yelling, `Show me your hands'
like a broken record. It didn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not listening,'' Smith said. ``He was scaring me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith testified that he fired once after Reid made a sudden
movement to the left. ``He turned around and gave me a
confrontational stare, like he was preparing an attack,'' Smith
said. ``It wasn't until he made that sudden movement when I thought
my life was in danger, that's why I shot him.''
</P>
<P>
   But in cross-examination, Connelly scoffed at the account. ``You
want this jury to believe that Mr. Reid, on his knees, facing up an
embankment with your hand on this shoulder,'' he said, ``was
endangering your life?''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that Smith had fired without warning. ``You never
warned him verbally that you were going to shoot him, did you?''
Connelly asked. Smith replied, ``I didn't have the time, sir.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
