<SLUG> BC-BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KC, TWA reach tentative agreement on maintenance base lease  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
c. 2000 The Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas City and
Trans World Airlines tentatively have agreed to a 25-year lease
renewal of the airline's jet maintenance base, easing concern about
the future of TWA's presence in Kansas City.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiations continue on how to finance about $40 million in
improvements to the city-owned facility, but city officials are
confident a new lease would be completed before the current one
expires May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lease looks like it's well in hand,'' Russell Widmar,
director of the Kansas City Aviation Department, said Thursday.
``We're moving the process forward and hope to get it before the
City Council by the end of April.''
</P>
<P>
   A TWA spokeswoman said the airline doesn't discuss ongoing
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   However, several union and city officials confirmed an agreement
in principle has been reached to renew the lease on the 250-acre
complex at Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has about 3,500 employees in Kansas City, and the pending
lease renewal comes as a relief to the 2,300 workers at the base.
Eighteen months of negotiations and TWA's financial condition have
created doubts about the airline's commitment to the underutilized
maintenance facility.
</P>
<P>
   Although the contract TWA reached with the Machinists union last
year called for the company to seek a lease renewal, many area
employees nevertheless are worried about what TWA might do at the
Kansas City overhaul base if maintenance operations were cut back.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's top union official in Kansas City applauded the progress
the city and airline have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``All systems are go, and we're happy about that,'' said Butch
Sponaugle, president of Machinists Local 1650. ``Hopefully, they
can get that old, worn-out base upgraded for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The city and TWA are discussing about $40 million in general
improvements to the overhaul base, which opened more than 40 years
ago, Widmar said. That would include upgrading the electrical
system, heating and cooling, and possibly the roof, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A firm to be hired by both parties will conduct an engineering
study of the proposed improvements, Widmar said.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation would be financed through airport revenue bonds
issued by the aviation department. The bonds would be paid off by
TWA lease payments. The council approved such a resolution a month
ago, said Councilwoman Teresa Loar, who heads the committee that
oversees the aviation department.
</P>
<P>
   However, the aviation department will need voter approval to
issue the bonds. That item is expected to be on the city ballot in
August or November.
</P>
<P>
   City officials don't expect voter resistance because funding for
the bonds would come from user fees generated by the airport and
not through additional sales taxes or property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think it would be a slam dunk because it would come
from existing airport funds,'' Loar said.
</P>
<P>
   The time-lag between the lease's renewal in June and the bond
issue later this year also should not be a problem, Widmar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lease can be executed with enough controls in
place and with the best-faith efforts of both sides,'' he said.
``We think the bonds can be authorized and sold in the time frame
that TWA wants.''
</P>
<P>
   A second phase of renovations and upgrades for the overhaul base
could come later, Widmar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking at there is process-type improvements,
things that would make it easier and faster for TWA to do the work
at the facility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the company has shrunk through the years, TWA's maintenance
capacity has stayed relatively the same. In addition to Kansas
City, the airline has maintenance facilities in New York, St. Louis
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   TWA also has begun acquiring new, more efficient aircraft,
replacing its older planes that required more maintenance checks.
Widebody planes, such as the Boeing 747 that exclusively were
maintained in Kansas City, have been retired.
</P>
<P>
   Those trends have led to a need for less hangar space, TWA
officials have said. Area Machinists officers have lobbied
management to seek maintenance business from other carriers, but
TWA has maintained that contract work in Kansas City is not
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a consulting firm explored what changes could be
made at the Kansas City overhaul base.
</P>
<P>
   Among those options included consolidating operations into one
building and eliminating superhangars at the base that housed
widebody planes. A second building at the complex then could be
leased to another tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Such major reconstruction to the facility, however, was
estimated to cost at least $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the initial renovations are not that drastic, city
officials say they think the lease renewal and the proposed
improvements are steps in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've come up with some good ideas to make this a
partnership of sorts,'' Widmar said. ``We understand the importance
of the overhaul base to the community and to TWA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2321EST &QL; 
