r a BC-BC-BASEBALL-STADIUM-K     03-09 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-BASEBALL-STADIUM-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Kauffman Stadium improvements to help Royals' bottom line  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK and GLENN E. RICE  
c. 2000 The Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Drive along
Interstate 70 by the big Royals crown these days and you'll see
something that's becoming as much a rite of spring as a crack of
the bat: workers preparing new features for Kauffman Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last four years, these additions have included an arcade
tent, advertisements ringing the field and high-dollar seats behind
home plate. This year, navy blue seats are replacing orange ones
around the upper deck, and a ``party pavilion'' for groups is being
built behind the left-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might not be able to call balls and strikes from there,''
Royals marketing vice president Mike Levy said of the pavilion,
``but it'll be something unique, like having a picnic at a baseball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes are making the Royals a more profitable team, but
they're hardly keeping up with the rest of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an unprecedented building boom, 20 of Major League
Baseball's 30 franchises will play by 2003 in stadiums that are
much newer than Kauffman. Five of the remaining franchises operate
in the nation's largest metropolitan areas. That leaves five teams
_ including the Royals _ competing in smaller cities with vastly
smaller stadium revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Baseball's newest stadiums, with numerous luxury
suites, averaged $47 million in gate revenues for 1998, according
to Paul Kagan Associates Inc., a sports research firm. Kauffman
Stadium's gate revenues averaged $15.5 million through the 1990s,
and all its new features by themselves could add less than $6
million to the team's coffers this year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a recent study of baseball economics by Street &AMP;
Smith's SportsBusiness Journal ranked Kansas City second to last in
total projected revenues for 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap is continuing to widen,'' Levy said. ``We have to
continue to upgrade our facility just to stay behind less.''
</P>
<P>
   This means the annual rite of off-season construction probably
will go on. Next year, a second deck could be added to the new
pavilion. The year after that, a pavilion could be built behind
right field. And there are plans for more substantial improvements,
such as converting the entire middle club level into suites and
adding a restaurant beyond the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, this will translate into more victories on the field
and more fans in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this will generate revenue for the team,'' said John
Bondon, a member of the Jackson County Sports Complex Authority.
``That way, you can spend more money for better players. And when
you buy better players, you will have more fans.''  &LR; brk:More suites
</P>
<P>
   The Royals reportedly turned a profit in 1999 for the first time
in years, but that had more to do with cutting expenses than adding
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   A Paul Kagan Associates analysis of the team showed it pared
$14.3 million in salaries by replacing such higher-priced veterans
as Dean Palmer with rookies or lower-paid players such as Joe
Randa. Then the players scored the most runs in its history and
produced a Rookie of the Year, but still came close to the
franchise's record for losses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an $11 million stadium improvement project added
dugout suites on the field and four rows of Crown seats behind home
plate. These were expected to push the Royals' gate receipts beyond
1998's $16 million, which was about half the major-league average,
according to Paul Kagan Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking pretty minor revenue gains,'' said Hadrian Shaw,
a sports analyst for Paul Kagan. ``Kauffman doesn't have nearly as
much to offer as the new parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 28-year-old Kauffman Stadium contains 23 suites. That's
about one-third the major-league average and about one-fourth the
average of stadiums opened since 1989, according to the Association
of Luxury Suite Directors.
</P>
<P>
   And in the baseball marketplace, Kansas City's predicament is
only getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1998 season, a Forbes magazine study of professional
sports ranked Kansas City No. 20 among 28 baseball teams in terms
of stadium revenues. Since then, however, five of the eight teams
below Kansas City _ plus two expansion teams _ have either moved
into new ballparks or are building one.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, Kansas City will slip toward the bottom
of that ranking _ in line with where Street &AMP; Smith's
SportsBusiness Journal ranked Kauffman Stadium for 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the stadiums from the 1960s and '70s are now all
gone,'' said Bill Dorsey, executive director of the luxury suite
association. ``There's a reason for that. The older ones don't have
the local revenue dollars, so that makes it harder to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Although economists debate whether building new stadiums with
taxes is a reasonable public investment, there's no doubt the new
palaces help their teams financially.
</P>
<P>
   Look at what a new ballpark means: Nine under construction or
being designed will raise their teams' revenues by an average of
$39 million, according to projections from Paul Kagan Associates.
By contrast, the Royals estimate Kauffman Stadium's new suites,
seats, pavilion and even ad signs generate between $5 million and
$6 million combined. Ads facing the field behind home plate are
worth $1 million alone, the Royals' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be able to compete with these other teams,
we have to provide more revenues,'' Levy said. ``We're going to
continue trying to do things every year.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:`More intimate'
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon last week at Kauffman Stadium, construction
workers stood on a scaffold and stacked concrete blocks behind left
field. From the other side of the stadium, around the upper deck,
came the ``whooop'' of air drills tightening bolts on new navy blue
seat bottoms. The work is to be finished by opening day, April 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see, especially at night, the stadium will have a
different feel to it,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   That is, he said, a little more cozy and a little more festive.
</P>
<P>
   The upper-deck seats complete a conversion to entirely one color
for the first time. Gone are the bright oranges and yellows of the
past. Levy calls the darker look ``more intimate'' because empty
seats won't stand out as much.
</P>
<P>
   The new left-field pavilion, called the Royal Pavilion, will
contain two covered, open-air suites with picnic tables and stadium
seats, plus an adjoining patio and its own concrete-block rest
rooms. Levy dubs it the ``party pavilion,'' and reservations
already exceed the team's projections. It holds 100 and costs about
$45 per person, which pays for hot dogs, barbecue and beer,
compared to $100 per person for a dugout suite.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals intend to gauge how much the fans like the pavilion
before deciding whether to expand it or add another. And it remains
to be seen whether the franchise will be able to take on much more.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City-based HOK Sport, one of the nation's leading stadium
architectural firms, created a $75 million plan for Kauffman
Stadium called Vision 2000. It includes several features of newer
stadiums, namely more suites and a sit-down restaurant. Here are
some of the ideas:
</P>
<P>
   ---- Removing the midlevel Stadium Club and moving the press box
to open up the entire level for glassed-in suites.
</P>
<P>
   ---- Building glass cylinders in the empty cores of the
corkscrew ramps and filling them with shops.
</P>
<P>
   ---- Moving the lower-level concessions farther from the seats
and widening the main concourse for more novelty and food stands.
</P>
<P>
   ---- Adding a sit-down restaurant beyond right field and
connecting the left- and right-field sides so a walkway can circle
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day at Royals stadium is a very family-oriented venture, and
what we tried to do is to enhance those features,'' said Earl
Santee, a senior vice president of HOK Sport.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable for these improvements _ if they ever happen _
remains murky.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Prentice's ill-fated bid for the Royals in 1998 requested
these improvements within five years. But it's unclear whether a
similar provision will be part of the current ownership
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is or not, the Royals and local civic leaders are
counting on the area's bistate sales tax to pay for some stadium
improvements. Yet using Union Station's bistate tax for sports
requires new legislation, and such legislation has reached a
roadblock in the Kansas House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the chances for passage don't look good,'' said
Republican Rep. David Adkins of Leawood.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce is lobbying
more in Topeka than ever before to pass the plan, probably by
adding it to another bill at the end of the session. Or another
attempt could be made next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County can't afford stadium improvements by itself, said
County Executive Katheryn Shields. And Royals surveys repeatedly
show more fans come from Johnson County than Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fortunate we're only having a discussion on improvements
instead of a new stadium,'' Levy said. ``It's because we have a
stadium that was state-of-the-art when it was built, and we just
think with some improvements we can once again make it
state-of-the-art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
