<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BC-BABY-CARJAK-KAN &LR;      03-09 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-BABY-CARJAK-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Toddler found safe in stolen Jeep two weeks after similar
abduction  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
c. 2000 The Kansas City Star LEE'S SUMMIT, Mo. -- It would only
take a second.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher Schlegel thought he could pop into the gas station's
convenience store Thursday, buy a pack of gum and hop back into his
Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   So he pulled up to the Phillips 66 gas station convenience store
on Langsford Road in Lee's Summit. With the Jeep running and his
16-month-old son strapped into the back seat, he ran inside.
</P>
<P>
   But as Schlegel handed the clerk his money, he heard the Jeep's
engine churn. And it dawned on him what had just happened: A thief
had stolen his car with his son inside.
</P>
<P>
   The store clerk called 911, touching off a frantic manhunt that
would end an hour later after a Lee's Summit couple found the
abandoned Jeep and called police.
</P>
<P>
   Schlegel's son, Collin, was unharmed. And by 10:30 a.m., an
emotional Christopher and Robin Schlegel were reunited with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy that he's back with us,'' Robin Schlegel said.
``I was so shocked and stunned when this happened. He's the most
precious thing we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The car thief remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Police are looking for a white man in his mid-20s, with dark
hair and a mustache. He is about 5 feet 5 inches tall, weighs about
140 pounds and was wearing a blue jacket, blue pants and brown
boots.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Schlegel, of Garden City, had gone to Lee's Summit
for a dental appointment Thursday morning. Collin had come along
for the ride, while his mom went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Schlegel left the dentist's office at 9:05 a.m., stopped at a
nearby bank, then went to get a pack of gum.
</P>
<P>
   When he pulled into the gas station, he noticed a man loitering
in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew he was up to something,'' Schlegel said. ``I
watched him watch me.''
</P>
<P>
   But then the man disappeared around a corner. Schlegel pulled up
to the front door of the convenience store, put his flashers on and
ran inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could enter and exit within 45 seconds,'' he said.
``But it's a serious mistake that no one should make.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Schlegel saw the suspicious-looking man drive off
in his Jeep. Schlegel told police he last saw the Jeep disappear
down Ridgeview Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Within 20 minutes, Lee's Summit police issued an Amber Alert, a
emergency broadcast system adopted in October to notify the public
of a child abduction.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first Amber Alert issued in Missouri since the
practice started and the second alert in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   At the police station, the Schlegels waited nervously.
</P>
<P>
   They thought of Jake Robel, the 6-year-old Independence, Mo.,
boy who was dragged to his death two weeks ago. His mother had left
him strapped into her car's back seat while she ran into a
restaurant for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   A thief stole her car, and Jake became tangled in his seat belt
when his mother tried to rescue him. Kim L. Davis of Kansas City,
Mo., has been charged with the boy's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a horrible, horrible feeling,'' Christopher
Schlegel said. ``You just never know what someone is going to do
when they know they are being hunted.''
</P>
<P>
   Just five blocks from the gas station, a Lee's Summit couple was
leaving their home to go to the supermarket. Billie Adams said she
noticed a Jeep parked up the block, on Ridgeview near Tanner's Bar
&AMP; Grill. Its flashers were on.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, the Jeep was still there. Then they saw the
Amber Alert on television. The report gave a description of the
missing car and the license plate.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Adams rushed back outside, confirmed the license plate
number of the Jeep, then told her husband, Brent, to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   When the Adamses ran to the Jeep, they found a howling little
boy strapped into his car seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was screaming and as red as can be,'' Brent Adams said.
``But as soon as Billie took him out of the car, he calmed right
down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was just happy to see a person,'' Billie Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Schlegel said he cried when he learned his son was
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether parents who leave their children unattended in a
car should be punished, Robin Schlegel said: ``I think we've been
punished a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that a person who has gone through this feels
like someone has reached into their chest and just ripped their
heart out through their ribs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to now try to twist their actions into something
criminal would be a misuse of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Schlegel did nothing illegal, Beaird said. For a
parent to be charged with child endangerment, there has to be
evidence of criminal negligence.
</P>
<P>
   If the child were left in the car while a parent went shopping
in a mall or went drinking in a bar, that would be criminal
negligence, Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in cases like these, the people weren't far from their
cars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlegel said he's learned his lesson, and he urged others not
to make the same mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might think something terrible like this couldn't happen
to you,'' he said. ``But you just can't take that chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
