<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-TRADE-1STLD-W     03-09 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: spirited debate.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senate opponents concede they face an uphill struggle, but said
momentum has shifted in the past three months. ``I don't say we
have the votes to defeat this, but it's going to be a more intense
fight than people thought,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.
Wellstone is among those who oppose the bill because, he says,
allowing China into the trade organization would cause the U.S.
trade deficit with China to balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping the House right now is like herding cats. But
according to vote-counters on both sides, here is what the math
looks like:
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, about 150 Republicans and 110
Democrats have voted to grant China normal trading status as part
of the annual review. A bill needs 218 votes to pass the House if
all members vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republican vote-counters say they can probably produce at least
135 votes for granting permanent normal trade status, barring any
new provocations by China, although they are short of that now.
Democratic supporters say they can count on about 50 to 60 firm
``yes'' votes now, but insist that aggressive lobbying by business
groups, Clinton and his top aides will harvest dozens of
uncommitted Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   By the count of some pro-trade lobbyists, at least 60 House
Democrats are uncommitted. Some House critics say that number is
closer to 20 to 30, and that the remainder are leaning toward
``no.'' Republicans say perhaps 70 of their rank and file are also
uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said Thursday that the administration is focusing its
efforts on about 50 of those 130 uncommitted members.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in farm states and in high-tech districts in
California are under particular pressure from local interests to
approve the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, who fought Clinton over impeachment last
year, are well aware that they would be delivering the majority of
votes needed to cement a foreign policy triumph for the president.
</P>
<P>
   So they are trying to put pressure on the Democrats, aides say.
That way, if the measure fails, Republicans can blame the White
House for not turning out its party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president gets us 100 Democrats, we'll be fine,'' Rep.
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the House majority whip who supports the trade
bill, said in a brief interview. Other supporters say that figure
is unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking
Democrat, said that 128 of 211 House Democrats were opposing the
measure. He added that 30 of those opponents had supported China in
annual reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in an early stage but the momentum is with us,'' Bonior
said in an interview Thursday. ``People are moving toward our
position.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be true in some cases. Rep. John Conyers Jr., a senior
liberal Democrat from Michigan who has voted for giving China
normal trade status on a yearly basis, said in an interview that he
would oppose permanent status because it would be a mistake to
surrender the leverage of an annual vote.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews with about one-third of the 30 representatives
that Bonior said had switched to opposing permanent status, some
said they truly had not made up their minds. ``I'm undecided,''
said Rep. Martin T. Meehan, D-Mass. ``I'm willing to look at the
administration's arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., said he had heard from labor activists
who oppose the bill, as well as from orange growers, cotton farmers
and executives from technology companies like Motorola and
Honeywell in his district who support permanent trade status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the fence,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
