<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS CONSIDER SIGNING UNDERWOOD; MITCHELL CHOOSES CINCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ On the same day the Dallas Cowboys lost out on
one maligned prospective free-agent signee _ thanks to Scott
Mitchell choosing to back up Akili Smith in Cincinnati rather than
Troy Aikman _ the team turned its sights to another.
</P>
<P>
   A source said the Cowboys are seriously considering signing
troubled defensive end Dimitrius Underwood, whose rookie season in
1999 was highlighted by a string of bizarre incidents, including a
suicide attempt. He was released by both the Miami Dolphins and
Minnesota Vikings last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones was unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' interest in Underwood is not without some working
knowledge of the situation. Newly hired defensive line coach Andre
Patterson worked with Underwood during his brief stint in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood was picked in the first round by the Vikings last
season after playing in college at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could be in the market for a defensive end _
considering the free-agent loss of Kavika Pittman (Denver) and the
questionable status of Greg Ellis (fractured leg). However, the
interest in Underwood should be construed more as a chance to take
a free look at a talented player rather than solely trying to fill
a need, much like the Alonzo Spellman situation of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he chose the Bengals because he felt he had a
better chance of playing there as a backup to Smith. Mitchell
signed a one-year deal with a $200,000 signing bonus and a $600,000
base salary. The Cowboys' offer was similar.
</P>
<P>
   With Mitchell taken, few quarterbacks are left on the free-agent
market who fit the Cowboys' need for a moderately priced veteran.
One possibility is Paul Justin, who was with the St. Louis Rams
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have also expressed interest in former San Francisco
49ers linebacker Lee Woodall. Woodall, however, is leaning toward
signing with the Carolina Panthers. nn
</P>
