u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      03-09 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KEEPING THE CAUSE ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 10:
</P>
<P>
   In pulling out of the presidential race Thursday, John McCain
and Bill Bradley vowed to keep fighting for reform. That promise
was to be expected as part of the ritual of politics. But because
both candidates inspired new voters and brought new vision to the
campaign this year, their ability to continue influencing the
debate is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who ``suspended'' his candidacy but did not endorse Gov.
George W. Bush for the Republican nomination, is in an especially
crucial spot. He made overhauling the campaign finance system his
central theme, and now he can refocus his energy to stop a coming
orgy of corrupt fund raising by both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Republicans and even many Democrats in Washington
were dismissing the need to clean up the system. They said it was a
minor issue for voters. But now the presidential race has proved
them wrong. In fact, it has elevated reform to a new level of
prominence and urgency.
</P>
<P>
   In January the joint pledge by McCain and Bradley to forgo
unregulated soft-money donations was quickly endorsed by Gore, who
later went further and declared that a campaign finance cleanup
would be one of his top priorities as president. Bush has defeated
McCain for the GOP nomination, but only after trying to co-opt his
message by describing himself as a ``reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain could use several means to keep alive his reform campaign
even as a non-candidate, forcing Bush to back up his words with
action. It is not clear whether campaign legislation has much
chance for passage this year, but the senator can continue pressing
for change in Congress, around the country and at the Republican
Convention this summer. He needs to make clear that no one can
inherit the popular support that he won this year by simply
mouthing empty slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of reform is all the more urgent because, with Gore
and Bush having a clear path to their parties' nominations, fund
raising has now risen to the top of their agendas. The Bush
campaign's $70 million war chest is almost depleted, drained by the
costly fight against McCain. Amazingly, the vice president is said
actually to have more money on hand than the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush needs to raise at least some money under the regular
federal limitations of $1,000 per contributor. But both candidates
will be turning their attention to raising the unregulated ``soft
money'' donations for the Republican and Democratic parties that
were the focus of the scandals of 1996. As expected, Bush has
rejected Gore's offer to forgo soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the two parties are expected to haul in more than
$500 million from corporations, unions and rich donors. That is
twice the sum they collected four years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both parties consider themselves in an arms race and feel they
cannot unilaterally disarm. That is understandable given the
pressures of an all-out campaign. Thus it is imperative that Gore
keep pressing Bush to accept a joint ban on soft money, and that
McCain and Bradley, who are still in a position to command public
and political attention, keep up the pressure on the candidates and
the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Common Cause pointed out again how the soft money
raised last year came from unions, the securities and investments
sector, the telecommunications industry and other groups with a
stake in legislation before Congress. To be fair to many of the
donors, the soft-money scam may often be less a case of businesses
trying to buy influence than of politicians trying to shake the
businesses down. Either way, the process is corrupt. It insures
that the wealthy special interests of this country will prevail, no
matter who wins in November.
</P>
<P>
   After their thoughtful but ill-fated drives for the White House,
McCain and Bradley can best fulfill the promises they made to their
supporters by keeping national attention riveted on the need for
reform. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
