<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-FETAL-TISSUE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 House subcommittee looks into fetal tissue market  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
c. 2000 The Kansas City Star WASHINGTON -- Members of U.S. House
subcommittee called Thursday for a federal criminal investigation
into whether fetal tissue was illegally extracted and marketed out
of an Overland Park, Kan., clinic where abortions are performed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The request came during a packed and emotional hearing of the
Health and Environment Subcommittee, which wants to find out if
laws restricting the methods and fees allowed for fetal tissue work
are being violated in Kansas or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing focused mostly on Lee's Summit, Mo., pathologist
Miles Jones, a key witness who failed to appear despite a subpoena.
Committee members had wanted to ask him about a contract to do
tissue extraction at Comprehensive Health, the clinic of Planned
Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Another Lee's Summit man, medical technician Lawrence Dean
Alberty Jr., did testify, but admitted making false statements in
the past about profiteering.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood issued a statement Thursday denying any
wrongdoing and called for a full inquiry into Jones or others who
may have tried to improperly profit on fetal tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee voted unanimously to hold Jones in contempt. If
the full House agrees, Jones will be subject to arrest next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear he has chosen to ignore the mandate of this
committee,'' said Rep. Thomas Bliley Jr., a Virginia Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has not returned repeated phone calls from The Kansas City
Star. No one answered the door at his two-story home in a Lee's
Summit subdivision Thursday afternoon. A neighbor, who asked not to
be named, said Jones is rarely seen there and that both Jones and
his wife appear to travel frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the abortion issue denounced Jones
for statements he made during a hidden camera interview with the
ABC News show ``20//20,'' broadcast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones told a program producer who posed as a potential investor
in his business that he could make $50,000 a week selling tissue.
Hearts, brains, livers and other fetal parts can bring ``what you
can sell them for,'' he said, when demand is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for this type of gross violation of the law
and sickening disrespect for human life,'' said Rep. Fred Upton, a
Michigan Republican who wrote the 1993 bill that outlawed selling
tissue at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Upton wrote a letter to Attorney General Janet Reno calling for
an investigation. There was no indication of a federal or state
investigation in Kansas, but the Jackson County, Mo., prosecutor's
office said it has begun looking into the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the committee who support a woman's right to
abortion services also denounced profiteering, but voiced fears
that abortion opponents would try to exploit the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that the charges leveled today, while serious
and troubling, are also being used by pro-life groups to inflame
the abortion debate,'' said Rep. Lois Capps, a California Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not sensationalize this process,'' said Rep. Henry
Waxman, a California Democrat. The controversy should not detract
from evidence that fetal tissue has proved valuable in research to
fight diabetes, AIDS, hepatitis B, Parkinson's and other diseases,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they appreciate the value of fetal tissue
research but they said they are concerned there will be more
abortions if fetal tissue research become profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The committee did not get any clear answers Thursday on what is
considered a ``reasonable'' fee for extracting, packaging and
transporting fetal tissue. Jones had a price lists for his company,
Opening Lines, that included $999 for a brain, $150 for skin, and
$325 for a spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had a contract with Planned Parenthood for fetal removal
for about ten weeks in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Brownlie, president of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and
Mid-Missouri, said Thursday that contract was terminated after
officials learned of his price list and other business practices.
Planned Parenthood also had differences with Anatomic Gift and had
terminated that relationship earlier in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former Planned Parenthood employee testified of concerns about
fees Anatomic Gift paid to the clinic for space rental because of a
lack of documentation on how the fees were calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I saw how widely the amounts varied, I became
concerned,'' said Lynn Fredericks, who was terminated in 1997 as
director of physician services at the clinic of Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlie has said Planned Parenthood did not collect excessive
amounts. No one does that kind of work at the clinic anymore but
may in the future in compliance with the law and ethics, Brownlie
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support the right of women having an abortion to choose to
donate tissue,'' Brownlie said. ``We also strongly support laws
that prohibit the sale of fetal tissue and protect women form any
coercion, pressure or incentive to donate.''
</P>
<P>
   The most graphic and criticized testimony at the hearing came
from Alberty, who worked for Anatomic Gifts and then for Jones at
the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty testified of becoming distraught after witnessing
fetuses being born alive and then cut up to get body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty said he agreed to share his experiences with a pro-life
organization called Life Dynamics, based in Denton, Tex. Alberty
admitted accepting more than $10,000 from Life Dynamics to work
under cover gathering information.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty said he also accepted $400 to make a videotape for Life
Dynamics in which he told stories of seeing viable fetuses killed.
He said donned a woman's wig to hide his identity.
</P>
<P>
   Under sharp questioning by Republicans and Democrats, Alberty
said he exaggerated to Life Dynamics about what he witnessed and
acknowledged he had no personal knowledge of excessive fees.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty maintained that what he told the committee under oath on
Thursday was true. During a recess, Alberty cried beside the
witness table and said testifying was very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by one congressman why he would tell Life Dynamics false
stories, Alberty said ``It's what they wanted to hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
