<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-CELICA-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA CELICA: A LOOK SO VERY NOW. (IS IT OLD YET?)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)  
 (af)  
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any doubts I had about the design of the new Toyota Celica were
erased when I pulled into the lot of the local car wash. One look
at the red, serpent-headed sport coupe sent the rag-wielding
workers into a frenzy worthy of the early hominids in ``2001: A
Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. The Celica has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, cars with so much instant youth appeal _ call it a
high ``fly'' quotient _ don't have a long shelf life. The 2000
Celica, the seventh-generation car to wear that nameplate, revels
in the current edge-design idiom, with more bevels, corners,
creases and flares than a napkin folded like a bishop's hat.
</P>
<P>
   Its doorstop shape and menacing, trapezoidal headlights cater _
nay, pander _ to ``slammers,'' those West Coast youths who modify
imported coupes with cosmetic and performance add-ons.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Celica is the product of Toyota's intricate
demographic analysis of Generation Y; not surprisingly, the new
design plays to a young audience. The average age of the Celica
buyer has dropped to 33 years old, from 42.
</P>
<P>
   But does the look have legs? The downfall of computer design and
rapid prototyping is that as vehicle development times grow
shorter, the urge to shape a car to the moment grows stronger. With
all of its slammer-inspired surface excitement _ the wing, the hood
nostril, the plunging fenders, the glassy blisters on the
headlights _ the Celica seems somehow as ephemeral as a California
sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The Celica, like the Mercury Cougar before it, illustrates the
difference between good design and fashion. One makes a lasting
contribution to the visual world; the other shows off cool-looking
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And like trendy footwear, the Celica fails to inspire deep
attachment in those who drive it. I sampled the GT-S model powered
by a howling 1.8-liter, four-cylinder engine. Developed with
Yamaha, this all-aluminum motor, bristling with variable-valve
timing and exotic fuel and ignition controls, produces peak power
between 6,000 rpm and the redline of 7,800 rpm. Consequently, to
keep the car in the horsepower zone you must stir the six-speed
shifter like Emeril Lagasse concocting a roux. At lower rpm, the
car positively falls on its nose.
</P>
<P>
   Push the throttle past six grand and the engine, with a little
gasp as the valves open up, starts to chirr like an overtaxed yard
appliance, loudly enough to swamp the cabin with noise and antsy
vibration. The first time I heard it, I could hardly believe it.
Toyota leads the industry in vanquishing noise, vibration and
harshness _ what auto engineers commonly call NVH. This car seems a
perverse celebration of NVH.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, Toyota figured that its target buyers _ the
steel-nerved teenagers who listen to Korn at runway-decibel levels
_ might enjoy the car's mechanical bombast. But again, how long can
such appeal last? Seeing as the car weighs only 2,500 pounds, I
believe its performance would not suffer unduly from an additional
50 pounds of sound-muffling material.
</P>
<P>
   The GT-S model produces 180 horsepower and 133 foot-pounds of
torque. The GT model, powered by a similar 1.8-liter motor, turns
out 140 horses and 125 foot-pounds. A five-speed manual
transmission is standard with the GT; a six-speed manual comes in
the GT-S.
</P>
<P>
   Both cars are available with four-speed automatic transmissions,
and the GT-Ss can be shifted manually with buttons on the steering
wheel, as in the Lexus GS400.
</P>
<P>
   Its youth-inspired shortcomings notwithstanding, the Celica GT-S
is an awful lot of fun to drive hard, if only you are in the mood.
Typical for Toyota products, the ride compliance is excellent over
a variety of surfaces, yet the chassis maintains surprising poise
when pushed through quick corners. An orthodox suspension of
MacPherson struts up front and double wishbones in back benefits
from the low body weight (there is less mass to control) and
excellent wheels and tires: low-profile 16-inch radials wrapped
around five-spoke alloy wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth and stout braking is provided by large disc brakes at all
four wheels. But, surprisingly, four-wheel antilock brakes _
standard on such quotidian fare as the Chevy Cavalier _ are a $550
option on both Celicas. That seems unduly flinty for Toyota,
considering that this is its mainline sports model.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from the bonds of daily commuting, the Celica comes into
its own on country roads. With a deft use of the gossamer-light
clutch, the car can be launched to 60 miles an hour in less than 7
seconds. At speed, the car bends silkily into corners, answering to
the firm and accurate steering. A lightweight, powerful sports
coupe can be a beautiful thing, as the Celica so nearly is.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Celica is a fantasia of arcing lines and swooping
dash vinyl. Among the curiosities is a center console shaped like a
snowshoe; high on the dash, in the toe of the snowshoe is a large,
lidded storage bin _ it can handle 8 compact disk cases or 10
cassettes _ in what should be prime instrument real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The GT-S has a CD-equipped stereo with eight speakers, and the
sound system's performance is adequately raucous to drown out even
the engine at full shout. Obviously, high-quality audio is a big
part of the car's mission profile.
</P>
<P>
   Shiny aluminum pedals, drilled out like a racecar's for
lightness, gleam in the foot well. Under a deep binnacle, the
lettering on the orange-on-black dials recalls the italic script in
Porsche sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   The bucket seats in front are excellent, comfortable and
supportive leather-lined sockets. The seats in back are there
primarily to hold down insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Celica is a fast, frantic and stylistically fussy little
sports coupe tuned to a higher pitch than one is accustomed to
hearing from Toyota, even counting the tightly wound Supra, now
defunct. As a product of copious market analysis, the Celica aims
at its target audience with the precision of a political attack ad.
But presidential campaigns end, and to everything there is a
season. The Celica may not be forever, but it is definitely now.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Immediate gratification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
