<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUBWAY-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CENSORS IN THE SUBWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, March 10:
</P>
<P>
   Rush hour on New York City's subways has never been for the
faint of heart. Yet the Metropolitan Transportation Authority has
decided that its clientele would flee the subways if they were
allowed to see a new advertisement that compares a crowded subway
to an overloaded cattle car. The ad, part of a campaign for transit
improvements by the Straphangers Campaign and the Regional Plan
Association, features a picture of subway riders under the caption
``With livestock it's called animal cruelty. With people it's
called a morning commute.'' The authority rejected the advertising
last week as being ``directly adverse'' to the commercial interests
of the transit system. Or as one official explained, ``it might
drive riders away.'' The idea that New Yorkers might stampede if
subjected to the livestock comparison would be a joke if rejecting
this ad were not so clearly a serious challenge to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Straphangers Campaign and the Regional Plan Association have
filed suit in federal court charging a violation of the First
Amendment. The two advocacy groups had planned a $500,000
advertising campaign to run in more than 2,000 subway cars in April
to generate public support for a Second Avenue subway line and
other transit improvements. Their message deserves to be heard as
the state Legislature gears up to consider the MTA's
capital-spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA's rejection of the cattle ad seems clearly
unconstitutional. The Supreme Court has held that transportation
agencies, which function in part as a business, can exert some
limited control over the advertisements they run and can even ban
whole categories of advertising. But the MTA is still a public
agency that must not carry out its policies arbitrarily. The
authority has willingly sold advertising space to other advocates,
including both anti-abortion and pro-choice groups. The agency has
even taken earlier ads from the Straphangers Campaign and has
grudgingly accepted an ad for the April campaign that is tamer than
the one it rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional issues aside, common sense suggests that the MTA
as a public agency ought to allow for a broad range of civic
expression. The subways are one of the most appropriate forums to
argue transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago the MTA established sweeping and self-serving
guidelines for rejecting ads, but top officials insisted they would
not be used to ban political ads critical of the agency. This page
and others were skeptical. At one public meeting to discuss the
rules in 1997, a member of the Straphangers Campaign wore a gag and
stood before the microphone silently to protest the possibility
that speech would be illegally silenced by the authority. At the
time, MTA officials dismissed the gag as a publicity stunt. It
turned out to be an accurate prediction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
