<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-REALIGNMENT-NYT &LR;      03-09 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REALIGNMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RADICAL REALIGNMENT IS SENSIBLE BUT OWNERS AREN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball owners have this magnanimous outlook on realignment.
Realign? Absolutely, they say. Certainly we need to do that. It
will improve the game and our revenue, and heaven knows, we need
more revenue. But what's that? You want my team to change leagues,
change divisions? Oh no, we couldn't do that. Not us. No, let the
other guy move. We have the right to say no, and by golly, we're
saying no.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario, basically, was the one that a few years ago
undermined the effort to have significant realignment. The
Milwaukee Brewers, owned at the time by the acting commissioner,
Bud Selig, were the only team that was willing (eager, some
baseball people said) to change leagues. Radical realignment had to
wait for another day.
</P>
<P>
   That day still isn't here. Selig, now the commissioner, will
present to the owners either at a meeting next month or the
following one in June a realignment plan, but it can't be
considered radical. To Jerry Colangelo, if it's the plan that has
been most discussed, it would be radical, but not to any of the
other owners. They haven't lost their selfish view of what might
be, to coin a phrase, in the best interests of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo operates the Arizona Diamondbacks, one of the two most
recent expansion teams. Before the other owners allowed the
Diamondbacks and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays into their exclusive
club, they coerced from them a higher entrance fee, at the last
minute, and the agreement that they could be moved to the other
league after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise. Under the plan getting the most attention,
the Diamondbacks and the Devil Rays are the only teams that would
change leagues, the Diamondbacks moving to the American and the
Devil Rays to the National.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the commissioner Fay Vincent responded to a request
from half of the National League teams and ordered realignment of
the league's divisions to make them geographically correct. Atlanta
and Cincinnati would move to the East, the Cubs and St. Louis to
the West.
</P>
<P>
   The idea made eminent sense, to everyone but the Cubs, that is.
Their owners, Tribune Co., sued Vincent, even though owners sign an
agreement that prohibits them from suing the commissioner, and then
became co-conspirators in the move to oust Vincent. It was not,
Tribune Co. argued, in the best interests of baseball to move the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current plan, some teams would change divisions, but
none of those teams has complained, at least not publicly. Members
of the Cardinals expressed outrage earlier this week over the
prospect of being in a division without the Cubs, their archrivals,
but their protests were based on incorrect information. A published
report had reversed the Cardinals and the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   With the National League changing to a four-division format for
the 2001 season, North East and South East divisions would be
created. The Mets would be in the North East with Philadelphia,
Pittsburgh and Montreal. The Reds and Atlanta would be in the South
East with Florida and Tampa Bay, a refugee from the AL.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs and the Cardinals would form the Central division with
Milwaukee and Houston, and the West would have Los Angeles, San
Francisco and San Diego. Tribune Co. has not threatened a lawsuit.
Come to think of it, Tribune Co. didn't sue, either, after the Cubs
were switched from the East to the Central in 1993, when the NL
went to three divisions.
</P>
<P>
   One baseball official said the difference between Vincent's
attempted move of the Cubs and Selig's is that this realignment
will lead to an unbalanced schedule and the rotation of divisions
for interleague play. But the 1992 plan made the same geographical
sense that Selig's plan does.
</P>
<P>
   The unbalanced schedule is long overdue. For too many seasons, a
team played basically the same number of games against teams in
other divisions (12 each) as it did against teams in its own
division (13 each). Under the planned format for 2001, the Mets
would play the Phillies, the Pirates and the Expos 20 times each,
then play nine games against each team in a ``sister'' division,
six games each against teams in the other two divisions and 18
interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, with a slightly different breakdown because the AL
would maintain its three divisions, would play 18 games each
against Boston, Baltimore and Toronto, nine each against the other
10 teams and 18 interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-team AL would have four teams each in the East and West
and six in the Central. That even-numbered alignment would create a
better schedule, especially for division races in September, than
the 5-5-4 format that exists now.
</P>
<P>
   The new alignment would create another imbalance. The AL would
continue with a wild-card team in its playoffs, but the NL playoffs
would have four division champions and no wild card. Only in
major-league baseball can the leagues play under different rules
(see designated hitter) and formats.
</P>
<P>
   Under any realignment plan, the Texas Rangers will leave the AL
West and join their Central time zone brethren. It's the pledge to
the Rangers that is causing the problem for the Diamondbacks. The
departure of the Rangers would leave a vacancy in the AL West, and
that's where Arizona seems to be headed.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, Colangelo keeps saying, reluctant to relinquish the
Diamondbacks' home in the NL. Colangelo said he called Selig after
seeing a newspaper report this week about the realignment plan that
had Arizona changing leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reassured me that's old, rehashed speculation,'' Colangelo
said by telephone from Phoenix. ``I'm counting on Bud. Bud said he
is looking at other options. Why should we be the team just because
they have the right to move us?''
</P>
<P>
   If Colangelo's arguments sway Selig and the commissioner decides
to leave the Diamondbacks where they are, the team then most likely
to move would be the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
