<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BACKSLASH-INTERNET-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN COMPUTERS KNOW WHAT A STRANGER CAN'T  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To hear some Internet executives tell it, the
stranger eating a salad at the desk of her Manhattan retail shop
shouldn't have become so perturbed when I asked for her style
preference in lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   But she looked at me as if I had asked if I could rifle through
her purse for loose change. So I tried a different tack. ``Then can
I just have your Social Security number?'' I asked, polite as could
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me!?'' she said, now looking like she might pull a
rifle from her purse.
</P>
<P>
   My inquiry was precipitated by the recent debate about how much
personal information Internet companies like DoubleClick should be
allowed to gather on Web surfers. To its proponents, the concept is
that by tracking what sites people visit and what they buy online,
dot-com companies can direct advertising to people, based on their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Internet companies assert that consumers are eager
for this personalized service. But it isn't easy to accept that
perspective blindly, because one bit of data we know about the
executives is that they get more money from advertisers if they can
direct ads to people based on their tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I wondered, how willing are people to part with
personal information if they are asked in person _ truly confronted
with a choice about whether to confide _ rather than being tracked
invisibly and automatically over the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   The salad-eating woman, the proprietor of a lingerie shop, made
it clear that she preferred to disclose nothing except her strong
desire for me to leave the store.
</P>
<P>
   But for every person like her, I found at least five people as
loquacious as Milton C. Schlein. I wandered into . Schlein on a
sidewalk in Midtown Manhattan while he was standing outside his
office smoking a Marlboro and reading The Wall Street Journal.
Schlein, 67, a securities analyst who regularly uses the Internet,
appeared to be from the old school. Describing his taste in music,
Schlein said he liked ``both kinds: show music (italics)and(end
italics) classical.''
</P>
<P>
   Without hesitation (and after I'd disclosed myself to be a
reporter and shown him identification) Schlein easily shared the
above information and more: he drives but doesn't own a car, reads
history books, has smoked for 50 years and often visits Yahoo.com
and Amazon.com. He even seemed on the verge of confiding his Social
Security number and perhaps would have if I had been able to
produce, in exchange, a tape of the New York Philharmonic playing
``Annie Get Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't he worry about giving such information to me, or having
it tracked online? ``It's nothing someone couldn't find out in five
minutes,'' he said, explaining that he has succumbed to a world in
which personal information is widely accessible. That said, he
wasn't too keen on disclosing whether he had ever visited an adult
Web site. ``That I wouldn't answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the woman at the lingerie shop wasn't the only person
I approached and asked for personal information who looked at me as
if I was in serious need of a Thorazine drip. But perhaps many New
Yorkers, accustomed to living in tight spaces, are more willing to
share than their brethren nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Some people shared Schlein's sense that there was no point in
trying to keep most things private. One woman let me watch her shop
at a Duane Reade drugstore for Tums and nail polish, saying, while
perusing the suppository section, that she and her husband own
``dirty movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, within minutes of meeting me, confided that she
suffered severe depression, recently lost her mother to pneumonia
and was having financial trouble with her condominium. As I walked
off, the woman proudly showed me a picture of her with Maury
Povich, whose talk show she said she frequents.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in a roundabout way, gets to a point raised by Marc
Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center, an advocacy group. ``People go on `The Jerry Springer Show'
too,'' Rotenberg said. ``The larger question is whether they should
have the right (italicsnot(end italics) to go on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Rotenberg believes that Web sites should make clear
what information they are capturing and give users a clear option
to decline to participate. In other words, the Web sites should
have to ask for information as clearly as I asked the woman at the
lingerie shop _ perhaps not face to face, but in no uncertain
terms.
</P>
<P>
   When I pressed that woman about why she was so reluctant to
share information, I asked whether she might be more willing to
give information online, in an anonymous setting, rather than being
confronted in person, in such a relatively intimate setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone were on the Internet or on the phone,'' she said,
``I wouldn't have been so nice when I told them to go to hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
