<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-OCEAN-CONDOS-2TAK     03-09 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-OCEAN-CONDOS-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
198 NEW APTS. $2 MILLION AND UP. VIEWS OF ALL OCEANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday night, the owners of 47 luxury apartments in a new
$260 million complex are invited to a lavish cocktail party in
London to toast their future homes and to meet the interior
designers who will decorate them.
</P>
<P>
   Though they come from several different countries, including the
United States, Britain, Germany, Norway and France, the new
neighbors have much in common.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having a minimum net worth of at least $5
million, they have agreed to pay $2 million to $6.84 million in
cash for furnished apartments they have never seen in a structure
that will not be completed until December 2001. Their dwellings do
not even have a permanent address, but every apartment is
guaranteed an ocean view.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the World, the first cruise ship conceived as a
residential community. Under construction since September at the
Fosen Mekaniske Verksteder A/S shipyard in Rissa, Norway, the
644-foot-long, 40,000-ton vessel is about midsize for a cruise
ship. It will house 110 privately owned apartments and 88 guest
suites available for rent to the owners' friends or staff as well
as a limited number of outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Owners can sell or rent their apartments whenever they wish. But
with less than half the lodgings sold on a ship that is about half
the size of the one originally planned, the investment potential of
these apartments is at best unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they raise the question, we tell them they are buying a
lifestyle experience, not an investment,'' said Fredy Dellis, chief
executive officer of ResidenSea Ltd., the privately held company,
incorporated in the Bahamas, that owns the ship.
</P>
<P>
   A glossy, sea-blue promotional book, about the size and shape of
a coffee-table art book, boasts that the ship will have the
amenities of the world's most sybaritic resorts _ a full-size
tennis court, two swimming pools, a jogging track, putting greens,
driving ranges, boutiques, a health spa, a nightclub, a casino and
a theater offering movies and classical concerts by visiting
artists.
</P>
<P>
   A crew of 252 will care for residents as the ship follows the
warm weather to places like the Italian and French Rivieras, the
Greek islands, the Caribbean, the Baltic States, the Chilean fjords
and the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The ship will dock at length for events like Carnival in Rio de
Janeiro, the Cannes Film Festival in France and the Grand Prix in
Monaco. After the first two years, the ship's equivalent of a co-op
board will choose the itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has two- and three-bedroom apartments, ranging from
1,106 square feet, a typical two-bedroom apartment on land, to
3,252 square feet, the equivalent of a sprawling Park Avenue co-op.
All come with fully equipped kitchens, walk-in closets and
terraces; hot tubs are optional.
</P>
<P>
   ResidenSea's marketers take pains to distance their ship from
the big, glitzy andmore mass-market vessels associated with the
cruise industry. With plans to spend 250 days a year in port, and
small enough to enter some ports off the usual tourist path, the
ResidenSea ship is being marketed as an apartment complex that
travels rather than as a cruise ship with condos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship allows you to travel around the world without leaving
home,'' Dellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Beckwith, a property developer from London with homes in
France and Colorado, bought a space on the ship even though he has
never taken a cruise. One reason for buying, he said, was the
opportunity to stay in his own apartment, instead of hotels, while
he traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I will fly in and use the ship as a hotel home in
the cities or resorts we want to visit, but I don't plan to spend a
lot of time cruising,'' Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the buyers, who prefer to remain anonymous, have a
greater affinity for the sea. But as a first-generation
entrepreneur in his 50s, Beckwith fits the profile of his fellow
apartment owners, Dellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dellis said full-scale mock-ups of four apartments would be
shown starting in May in Baden, Austria. ResidenSea expects about
half the owners to be North Americans and 40 percent Europeans. And
the company hopes to build more residential ships. ``We've always
believed this ship was not a one-off,'' Dellis said.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the cruise and real estate industries is as
optimistic. ``It's a fascinating concept, absolutely unique, but
the question is whether there are enough people who want to sink
money into a cruise ship that goes around the world,'' said David
Seaman, a real estate analyst with Pricewaterhouse-Coopers.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining a shipboard apartment is not cheap; the annual fee
is about 5 percent of the purchase price, or $100,000 on a $2
million apartment. Industry experts say that figure is high, but
not out of line with similar luxury properties on land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're sort of a bargain in a way, depending on how
much you plan to use it,'' said Mike Thiel, president of Hideaways
International, an upmarket travel agency and club in Portsmouth,
N.H. He said expenses on high-end cruise ships were about $700 a
day per person.
</P>
<P>
   But Thiel expressed doubts about a long-term investment in a
ship. ``Ships deteriorate and require a lot of maintenance,'' he
said. ( Dellis said the ship would have what accountants, if not
seamen, call a sinking fund to cover all maintenance.)
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Corcoran, president of the Corcoran Group, a New York
real estate firm specializing in high-end properties, said the
purchase cost and annual fees were comparable to those of an
unfurnished suite at the Pierre Hotel in New York, which comes with
daily maid service and costs $84,000 a year to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you say you have a suite at the Pierre, the entire
world knows you've arrived,'' Corcoran said. ``I'm not sure you
have such an association with an apartment on a luxury cruise
ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the ship has not been easy. It is only half the
size of the 1,000-foot-long, 80,000-ton megaship with 260
apartments and 180 guest suites _ larger than the Queen Elizabeth
II _ envisioned in 1997 by Knut U. Kloster Jr., the former chairman
of Royal Viking Line and a member of the Norwegian family that
developed the modern cruise industry in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in oil prices, which hurt the Norwegian investors, and
the dip in the Asian financial markets made it impossible to raise
the $190 million needed to start building.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-down plan requires an initial investment only half as
large. In addition to Kloster, ResidenSea's backers include
Silversea Cruises, which will oversee the ship's day-to-day
management; CNA, the American insurer; and several Norwegians in
the cruise, shipping and hospitality industries.
</P>
<P>
   The apartments come furnished, and the cost includes the work of
a choice of four very different designers: Nina Campbell, the
London-based designer known for a traditional English look; Juan
Pablo Molyneux of New York, known for opulent, antique-filled
interiors; Luciano Di Pilla of Rome, who creates contemporary,
European-style designs; and Yran &AMP; Storbraaten, the ship's
architects, who devise fashionable yacht interiors. Owners can
provide original antiques to replace reproductions, or hang their
own art.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and Molyneux said their designs differed only in small
details from what they would devise for apartments in Mayfair or on
Park Avenue. Shelves will have raised edges to prevent objects from
falling when seas are choppy. ``And I didn't use metals or bronzes
that might corrode,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Molyneux said fabrics had to meet fire safety standards, but his
usual choices from Clarence House and Brunschwig &AMP; Fils fit the
bill. ``The experience should be like magic,'' he said. ``One
minute you're walking on an ocean liner. But when you turn your
key, you've come back home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
