<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S KATZ UNLEASHES HIS CLAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In ABC's version of ``March Madness,'' even those
without a straitjacket have trouble keeping the pairings straight.
</P>
<P>
   Network sports chief Howard Katz, who hasn't been in the big
chair a year, has detonated the foundation of ``Monday Night
Football'' louder and quicker than a Dick Vitale cliche. Katz'
scheme isn't to go in a new direction but to dig up an old one;
build it not with lightweight fiber but old mud and clay. He's
bringing out of retirement the legendary producer-director Don
Ohlmeyer to help a show he left more than 20 years ago, a man whose
most recent public decision - that Norm Macdonald wasn't funny at
NBC - ironically actually helped ABC's prime-time lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, by the way, Katz also dumped analyst Boomer Esiason, eating
a reported $1.3 million contract in a move needed since his hiring
two years ago but one that at least diverts attention from the
mayhem created by the Ohlmeyer decision.
</P>
<P>
   And thankfully - somehow - Al Michaels avoids the debris and
remains the play-by-play pillar of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Sifting through the rubble, what does this mean? Katz isn't all
bark, for what that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we have to make the show special again,'' he said
Wednesday night. ``It has to be a big event again. I'm looking for
a spark.''
</P>
<P>
   So fired were Ken Wolfe and Craig Janoff, who have produced and
directed ``MNF'' together the last 12 years and kept it a
consistent top 10-rated prime-time show. They created something
that Katz characterized as having too much ``sameness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sameness in that it was the third-ranked prime-time show last
fall and the network's top-rated show until the Philbin-phenomenon
``Millionaire'' lust caught on. And sameness like ... ESPN's
``Sunday Night Football''? Whose fault is that?
</P>
<P>
   A year after ABC bounced Dan Dierdorf and two after easing out
Frank Gifford, sacking Esiason and bringing in one or two people
with some personality would have solved 99 percent of that
``sameness'' problem two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not overly surprised (by Katz's decision), knowing the
tension that was growing within ABC Sports,'' Esiason decided to
say to the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   But in an equally bizarre move, Katz, who started his TV career
as an assistant on ``MNF'' back in 1971, has brought back mentor
Ohlmeyer, who produced the show from 1971 to '77 and has since been
golfing after a run as NBC's West Coast entertainment president.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Katz talked Keith Jackson out of retirement to
return to a reduced play-by-play workload on college football
games. That made sense. But with Ohlmeyer, you get the feeling that
if Howard Cosell were alive, Katz would have stopped his Social
Security payments, too, and shown Michaels the exit.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer says he wants to bring back the element of surprise and
danger to the ``MNF'' telecast. If so, start by bringing back your
old pal, O.J. Simpson. Or Frank (begin ital)and(end ital) Kathie
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Katz already has set off the nitro with these brash decisions,
for all the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fertile field to plow,'' Ohlmeyer said of his new
job, ``and to do it in an interesting, innovative way that will
keep people tuned in.''
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say Norm Macdonald?
</P>
<P>
   You rule: The idea behind ESPN's special ``NHL Rules!'' telecast
isn't so much to dumb things down as it is to ... well, maybe it
(begin ital)really is(end ital) to dumb things down.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's first instructional live telecast of the Jan. 9 Colorado-
Chicago contest - using no play-by-play guy, two analysts, having
an NHL referee sit in to interpret rules and taking e-mail from
viewers - drew positive reviews from those who matter most, the
folks at home. The second try will be with Tuesday's exclusive
Ducks-Avalanche game from Denver (ESPN, 5 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (that telecast) exceeded expectations,'' said Darren
Pang, one of two analysts (with Bill Clement) who worked that game
and will be there Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of respect for the viewers and don't want to
appear condescending. We try to explain it as if we're coaching a
kid's hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   That Jan. 9 show marked a few firsts for Internet-TV sports live
coverage: It was the first time visitors to a Web site interacted
with on-air analysts during a game telecast, and it was the first
time that athletes participated in an Internet chat during a game.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,300 questions were submitted to chat-room hosts
Steve Levy and Barry Melrose in the three-hour telecast, and 17,000
unique users popped into the ESPN.com chat room set up specifically
for the telecast. Levy and Melrose typed in some of the answers and
passed questions on to Pang and Clement, who responded on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Before the second and third periods, ESPN.com users participated
in audio format chats with players Tony Amonte and Joe Sakic, who
were picked in ESPN.com user polls before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Both elements are expected to be used Tuesday, with e-mail also
accepted from NHL.com. And for a game this late in the season, Pang
said there will be more explanation on what a team like Anaheim,
desperate to get into the playoffs, might do tactically at certain
situations to avoid taking a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Borgen, the Kings' game producer on Fox Sports Net, likes
the idea of the ``Rules!'' telecast but doesn't see doing that for
one of the local telecasts. With NHL expansion into so many new
cities lately, a national telecast like this works. In L.A., it
needs more balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jim Fox, I think we are always half educational with our
replays,'' said Borgen, ``but we're more subtle about it. You have
to know your audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's like opera - people who watch it, watch it; people
who don't, don't. It's too bad that 30 years later, we still need
to have offsides explained. But then, how many baseball fans really
know the infield-fly rule?''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Pang: ``It's no different with the Toronto Raptors and
Vince Carter I promise you they'll do a similar thing in Canada
with a basketball telecast. I just hope Americans don't say, `Those
dumb Canadians.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, we won't.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -Nike's inspired ``Bracketville'' TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   -ESPN Classic's 23-hours-long ``March Madness Marathon'' starts
Sunday at 4 p.m. with the 1983 Western Regional first-round game
between North Carolina State and Pepperdine, as the Waves, coached
by Jim Harrick, take the eventual national champions, coached by
Jim Valvano, into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   -The acceptance speech by NBC's Bob Costas after he was named
Favorite Sportscaster of the Year at the TV Guide Awards in L.A. on
Monday: ``I'd like to thank the viewers for being so kind and the
editors of TV Guide for apparently misplacing all the ballots that
were cast for Al Michaels.''
</P>
<P>
   -Sport magazine has a golfer on its cover - Tiger Woods, of
course - marking the first time a PGA Tour player has made its
cover since Johnny Miller 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -The NBA's bumbling attempt to make coaches wear mikes on the
bench during nationally televised games. Two league-wide memos have
reportedly been sent out, requiring coaches to comply if they are
approached by NBC or TNT. The latest memo threatens them with a
$100,000 fine if they balk, which is what the Lakers' Phil Jackson,
Miami's Pat Riley and Indiana's Larry Bird have already done. Now,
there's also talk of a memo reportedly informing teams that cameras
in the locker room (to see what?) are being considered on a
voluntary basis, which has already caused players to start
squirming and union boss Billy Hunter to threaten legal action.
Maybe NBA officials should focus on the positives that have come
out of this, such as a recent game when Philadelphia coach Larry
Brown wore a mike for NBC and it was used on tape, then remind the
players and union who (begin ital)really(end ital) pay the salaries
and that more people watch at home than in person because that's
all they can afford. At least then there might not be such a
resistance to a little bit of technological progress that's already
become a bigger deal than it needs to be.
</P>
<P>
   -TNT giving Charles Barkley a two-year deal to be a studio
analyst. (begin ital)This(end ital) is a reason to fret about
having someone miked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
