<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-PARIS-PAINTERS-AR     03-09 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-PARIS-PAINTERS-ART-1055(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ONE CITY WAS THE HEART OF ART'S YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1946 the Metropolitan Museum of Art acquired its
first painting by Picasso, his portrait of Gertrude Stein, painted
in 1906 when he was 24 and she was 32. (When told that Stein did
not resemble his image of her, Picasso famously predicted, ``She
will.'') Unexpectedly, Stein bequeathed the portrait to the Met;
she wanted it hung in a museum whose stature was equal to her own.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it the first Picasso to enter the Met, which was at
that time scarcely interested in pursuing 20th-century European
art, but it was also the museum's first acquisition by a living
artist of the School of Paris. And it provided a cornerstone on
which a modern collection could be built.
</P>
<P>
   The Met has added much to that foundation, particularly during
the last 20 years, and the additions are celebrated in a huge show
assembled by its department of 20th-century art, ``Painters in
Paris: 1895-1950.''
</P>
<P>
   On display are more than 100 works from the department's
collection by prominent artists of the School of Paris. (This
rather loose term refers not to any particular style, but to the
many innovative artists working in Paris from the turn of the
century to just after World War II.)
</P>
<P>
   The premises of the exhibition are a little complicated. For one
thing, it is the third in a series of acquisition shows mounted by
the Met's individual curatorial departments _ the two others were
by the medieval department and the American Wing (whose notable
acquisitions from 1980 to 1999 are on view through Nov. 12). But
this show is slightly different: It concentrates on a single aspect
_ the School of Paris _ of a much larger 20th-century collection.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the exhibition is not confined to recent
acquisitions but goes all the way back to 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Works acquired between 1979 and 1999 are marked by a small blue
symbol denoting recent acquisitions, and their presence is a
tribute to the grand acquisitorship of the department's chairman
and the show's organizer, William S. Lieberman. He joined the Met
in 1979 after a long curatorship at the Museum of Modern Art and
stepped up the department's acquisitions considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Lieberman's gift for collecting significant
collectors, the museum has snagged not only individual works but
also groups and entire holdings, like the 18 major objects
bequeathed by Florene M. Schoenborn in 1995 and the Jacques and
Natasha Gelman trove of 85 masterpieces bequeathed in 1998. (Only
10 paintings from the Gelman donation are on view here; the group
will soon be shown in its entirety.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 67 School of Paris acquisitions over the last 20 years
were gifts; the Met had to dip into the till for only four.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show fills eight galleries of the Lila Acheson
Wallace Wing with work by some of the 20th century's greatest _
Bonnard, Braque, Chagall, de Chirico, Derain, Gris, Leger, Matisse,
Miro, Modigliani, Monet and Picasso among them _ Lieberman points
out that what is on view is by no means a complete survey. There
are important gaps, including works by Giacometti, Duchamp and
Masson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the parade of treasures, while admittedly a distance from
the awesome trove held by the Museum of Modern Art, is enough to
bedazzle the most jaded Met-goer. Many of these works have been
shown individually or in various theme exhibitions. But to view
them laid out as a half-century of masterpieces _ a period that
spawned the vital movements of fauvism, cubism, futurism and
surrealism _ is something else again.
</P>
<P>
   Influences, correspondences, relationships of form and color
(Lieberman is good at installing works to point up these themes)
are apparent in ways they would not be were the objects not
gathered together. The roughly chronological arrangement sometimes
pauses to take account of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The show begins with early works by Bonnard, Maurice Denis and
Edouard Vuillard, at that time members of the Nabis, a small group
of painters and poets who took the name from the word ``prophet''
in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   They were influenced by Gauguin's expressive (as opposed to
realistic) use of bright color and flat decorative patterning. Six
of the nine Bonnards in the show are in this gallery, along with
four Vuillards and one painting by Denis, a stylized, brightly
lighted mythoreligious scene titled ``Springtime'' (circa 1897),
which is a study for a larger decoration.
</P>
<P>
   The two earliest Bonnards, from 1895 and 1899, are unexciting,
hardly predictive of the sensuous fusion of color and light in his
later works. Of those accompanying them, ``The Green Blouse''
(1919) stands out, a soft melange of figures and still life in rich
colors with a window view of a fine sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   The show's best Bonnard, the very large ``Terrace at Vernonnet''
(1939), hung in another gallery, is a masterpiece glowing with warm
peach-orange tones, in which the figures of women are deftly melded
with a dreamy, summery landscape.
</P>
<P>
   A surprise is the huge, tapestrylike painting by Vuillard,
``Place Vintimille, Paris'' (1916), a pleasant urban landscape that
is a far cry from the busy, patterned interiors with which the
artist is associated. His lovely summer mood piece ``Morning in the
Garden at Vaucresson'' (1923 and 1937), hung nearby, is a more
typical intimist view.
</P>
<P>
   A little out of sync here, but far more radical than the other
paintings, is one of Monet's numerous waterlily paintings. Titled
``Reflections, the Waterlily Pond at Giverny'' (circa 1920), it is
an intense, richly brushed almost abstract close-up of leaves,
blossoms and water that throws off scintillating light reflections
while drawing the eye into its dark, liquescent depths.
</P>
<P>
   From the fauve period, Matisse's well-known masterwork ``The
Young Sailor II'' (1906) stands out. More decorative than
realistic, it is a vividly colored study of a burly tough with
masklike features who stares boldly at the viewer, the curves of
his body played off against a straight-backed chair.
</P>
<P>
   The artist most heavily represented in the show is _ would you
believe _ Picasso, with no fewer than 22 works. An important group
of his pre-cubist paintings includes a wistful Blue Period
``Harlequin'' (1901) and ``The Actor'' (1904-05), a large,
mannerist-style painting of an emotive figure that is transitional
between his blue and rose periods.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the display of important cubist works, Picasso's ``Still
Life With a Bottle of Rum'' and Braque's ``Still Life With a Pair
of Banderillas'' (both 1911) are paired. The two, composed of
fractured planes, lines, invented shapes and shadings, inflected by
letters, were painted at the same time at Ceret, a Pyrenees town
where the artists, who together invented analytic cubism,
collaborated.
</P>
<P>
   In a surrealist mode, Picasso is well represented with ``Nude
Standing by the Sea'' (1929), a grotesque view of the female body
as quirky architecture, with a tiny ball for a head perched atop a
pyramidal tower.
</P>
<P>
   Other surrealist notables are Miro's ``Dutch Interior III''
(1928), the only Miro in the show; it is a playful canvas with a
freewheeling calligraphy of black and brightly colored biomorphic
forms, linear scratchings, a hint of a foot, and ebullient bird
shapes. Yves Tanguy's ``Hostages'' (1934), with its blobby
humanoids massed against a distant horizon, is a classic surrealist
dreamscape.
</P>
<P>
   Even though de Chirico's ``Jewish Angel'' (1916) precedes
surrealism by almost a decade, it is an important precursor, with
its odd assemblage of draftsman's tools topped by a left triangle
and presided over by an enormous eye, painted on a piece of paper
folded over in one corner. No angel, Jewish or otherwise, can be
discerned in it.
</P>
<P>
   Of three arresting Legers, the star is ``Woman With a Cat''
(1921). A monumental, highly stylized rendering of the seated
woman, all puffy curves set off by linearities with bold color
areas, it is vintage Leger, down to its four-fingered hand, a
notable Leger idiosyncrasy.
</P>
<P>
   The only still-living artist whose work is in the show is
Balthus, now 92, whose four paintings go back to the 1930s. The
biggest, and most remarkable, is ``The Mountain'' (1937), a
dreamlike, semi-surrealist tableau of figures in an Alpine summer
landscape, which owes a visible debt to the rocky terrains of
Courbet.
</P>
<P>
   World War II and the years immediately following are brilliantly
represented by Jean Dubuffet, whose three early paintings comment
on wartime Paris. ``Woman Grinding Coffee'' (1945), a highly
textured, playfully primitive rendering of a squat woman
manipulating a coffee grinder, was a Christmas gift to his wife
when real coffee was difficult to come by in Paris. His unusually
bright-colored ``View of Paris With Furtive Pedestrians'' (1944)
shows male and female walkers, the women wearing wooden clogs
because of the scarcity of leather.
</P>
<P>
   But there is much, much more here to show the growing strength
of the Met's once-limited School of Paris holdings. And not to
worry, the museum's hand will always be extended, palm up. As
Lieberman says in the catalog, ``A growing collection can never be
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Painters in Paris: 1895-1950'' is at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art, Fifth Avenue at 81st Street, New York, (212) 535-7710,
through Dec. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
