<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A GOOD TRADE DEAL WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, March 10:
</P>
<P>
   Congress should quickly approve legislation needed to smooth
China's admission to the World Trade Organization. By helping China
into the WTO, lawmakers would not be endorsing Beijing's policies
in other areas, like human rights and Taiwan. They would be
speeding the opening and reform of China's economy and
subordinating Beijing's arbitrary authority in trade matters to the
rule of international law.
</P>
<P>
   What President Clinton seeks from Congress is a change in
China's trade status under American law. Currently, China's access
to normal trading privileges in the American market is subject to
annual congressional review. Under the bill submitted this week,
China, as a prospective member of the WTO, would be granted normal
trading status on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, some members of Congress used the annual debates
over China's trade privileges to challenge Beijing's human rights
record and other offensive behavior. But linking these issues to
trade made no obvious sense and produced scant results.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the Clinton administration has wisely separated
its efforts to open Chinese markets from other aspects of
Washington's relations with Beijing. That has allowed the
administration to support trade policies that serve American
interests, while opposing Chinese actions that conflict with
American values or threaten regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   Last November the White House negotiated a highly favorable deal
with China on WTO admission terms. Beijing committed itself to end
export subsidies and open its markets more fully to American
farmers, telecommunications companies and financial institutions.
By joining the trade organization, China will invite international
scrutiny of its performance in keeping those pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Senate approval of the needed changes in trade law seems likely.
But the outlook in the House is less promising. At this point, only
50 to 60 House Democrats are willing to break ranks with organized
labor, which strongly opposes the legislation because it wants
continued annual review of China's harsh labor practices and denial
of political freedoms. These are legitimate concerns, but best
addressed outside the trade status legislation.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 more Democratic votes are needed, since many
Republicans who might otherwise have voted yes have been alienated
by Beijing's recent noisy threats against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress approves the China trade legislation by the end
of this spring, the issue is likely to get caught up in campaign
politics and delayed until next year. By then, China might back off
from some of the market-opening concessions it is now offering.
Neither the Taiwan issue nor labor's misplaced opposition should
hold up an early, positive vote. The China trade bill serves broad
American interests and deserves strong bipartisan support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-09-00 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000309.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-09 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JEWISH-PARIS-PAINTERS     03-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-PARIS-PAINTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH ARTISTS WHO MADE PARIS THEIR EXUBERANT GARRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT16 and 17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is by a remarkable coincidence that the Jewish
Museum should have just opened an exhibition whose subject is
largely identical to that of ``Painters in Paris: 1895-1950'' at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The subject is the same, the time
span is the same and quite a few of the artists are the same. But
the Jewish Museum show is ``Paris in New York: French Jewish
Artists in Private Collections.''
</P>
<P>
   This is somewhat misleading in that the show includes artists
who were no more French, by birth, than I am. But it was in France
that they found freedom and stimulation on a scale not to be found
elsewhere. They identified with Paris and Paris supported them, no
matter how precariously, in times of trouble. And New York
collectors have done well by them.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the exhibition, for instance, there is a
painting by Max Weber, who was born in Russia in 1881, came to the
United States in 1891 and went to France in 1905. Once in Paris he
made his mark with Gertrude Stein, Robert Delaunay, Henri Rousseau
and others. He also attended the school that Henri Matisse opened
in 1908. The first painting in the Jewish Museum is, in fact, a
Weber work that shows the interior of Matisse's Academy with the
cast of Apollo that students were encouraged to copy. As such it is
a historical document.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Jewish artists of the time, Elie Nadelman is not
included in the Met exhibition, but at the Jewish Museum he stands
out. His 10 years in Paris were invaluable to him, and his three
bronzes in the show have the dandified elegance that persuaded
Helena Rubinstein to act as his patron and sponsor when he returned
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Lipchitz, though not everyone's favorite sculptor, was a
solid, well-established figure in Paris. (The catalog for the
Jewish Museum show illustrates the house that Le Corbusier built
for him in 1924.) In midlife he did not have the lightest of hands,
but the Jewish Museum scores very well with his ``Detachable
Figure: Seated Musician'' (1915). This is a figure of a cellist in
painted wood. It manages to be exact, funny and debonair. Even the
stiff white collar of the cellist is straight from the laundry. The
image is not pedantic. Nor is it flippant. It is just right, and a
tiny masterwork.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing discreditable about the exclusion of these
artists from the Met exhibition. No show of this kind is a
dictionary answerable from A to Z. The spaces of the Jewish Museum
have a certain privacy that give luster to little paintings like
the ``Carpenters and Fish'' of 1912 by Marc Chagall. Chagall's
involvement in everyday life in his native Russia may well have
been all the more intense while he lived in Paris from 1910 to
1914.
</P>
<P>
   As to what these artists and many others found in Paris, the
catalog has much to say with archival photographs and a lively text
by Romy Golan. Paris was genuinely a second and often an uproarious
home to many artists from other countries. Whether or not they
succeeded in any lasting way, there was a camaraderie in
Montparnasse that was the stuff of genuine legend. Simply to be
there, and to hang around, was to be part of a multinational buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists who are also prominent in the Met show,
Modigliani comes out well here with his limestone head of 1911-12,
his portrait of Leon Lindenbaum and his portrait of the English
poet Beatrice Hastings, with whom he lived in 1914-15. If there is
such a thing as a specifically English face, Beatrice Hastings had
it in spades with her tall, narrow, slightly judgmental look, and
Modigliani got it down on canvas. The portrait is completely unlike
what people expect of Modigliani.
</P>
<P>
   Soutine comes out very well at the Met, and at the Jewish Museum
there are four very good examples of his work. ``Hanging Turkey''
(circa 1925) has the particular gash and bite of the brush that
only Soutine had.
</P>
<P>
   A notable absentee from the Met is Sonia Delaunay. Her ``Rythme
No. 5'' of 1939 at the Jewish Museum is only a little gouache on
paper, but it has the gaiety that she kept for the rest of her long
life (1885-1979).
</P>
<P>
   The relevant rooms in the Jewish Museum still have the character
of a rather grand private house. The paintings have room to
breathe, and the portrait sculptures by Chana Orloff, in
particular, look as if they were completely at home instead of
being on loan for a month or two.
</P>
<P>
   As for the catalog, it has almost the character of a family
album, thanks to the fullness of its biographical material and its
highly evocative group photographs. Golan's long text is a treasure
box of relevant quotations from publications that not all of us
have on hand. This show is, in its way, an understated triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paris in New York: French Jewish Artists in Private
Collections'' is at the Jewish Museum, Fifth Avenue at 92nd Street,
(212) 423-3200, through June 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
