</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: AFTER BEING DISMISSED, ESIASON FIRES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to all needing) (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boomer Esiason, fired from ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' on
Wednesday, Esiason vented his fury Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He fulminated about Al Michaels, his on-air partner, saying he
squelched Esiason's desire to be looser and funnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the happiest he's been for a long time because he's a
one-man booth,'' Esiason said during a phone interview. ``Al is
propped up as the star and wants to do things his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels was unavailable to comment on Esiason's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ABC did not return Esiason's fire. ``Boomer's contribution to
`Monday Night Football' is highly valued,'' said Mark Mandel, an
ABC Sports spokesman. ``He's got many close friends and admirers
here, so we understand his frustration after yesterday's
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels has worked well in previous three-man booths in
football (with Dan Dierdorf and Frank Gifford) and baseball (with
Jim Palmer and Tim McCarver). Any backstage tensions failed to play
out on the air or become public knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason also described himself as a victim of infighting at ABC
Sports, where a new president, Howard Katz, and a new executive
producer, John Filippelli, quarreled over the direction of the
program with Ken Wolfe, the producer, and Craig Janoff, the
director. Wolfe and Janoff were fired, after 14 and 12 years,
respectively, on the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny and Craig had their own way of doing things,'' Esiason
said. ``And they were phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's hard when a new coach comes in and wants his
own team, but I'm sorry I had to be part of the purge, or the
smokescreen in front of the purge.''
</P>
<P>
   With Esiason, Wolfe and Janoff gone, Katz brought in his mentor,
Don Ohlmeyer, to elevate the show above the ``sameness'' he felt it
suffered from. Ohlmeyer produced ``Monday Night'' from 1973 to
1976. Ohlmeyer wants to revive the show's fromer penchant for
unpredictability and danger. But Howard Cosell died in 1995 and Don
Meredith isn't coming back from his retreat in Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Before Ohlmeyer's arrival, ABC had begun talking to possible
analyst candidates like Bill Parcells, who will most likely stay as
the New York Jets' director of football operations through next
month's college draft; Steve Young, who did a fair job on ABC's
postseason studio show but has not decided to retire as a player,
and Jimmy Johnson, the former Miami Dolphins coach, who is
available.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has also interviewed for jobs at Fox and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason is caught between his natural candor and his frustration
at the serious pothole in his new career. He didn't sign a
three-year deal in 1998 for $1.75 million annually to wind up
looking for a job after two. He went in with high hopes and little
experience, replacing Gifford as Michaels' and Dierdorf's mate.
After Dierdorf's release, Esiason worked with Michaels last season.
</P>
<P>
   Had Esiason been a true breakthrough analyst _ like Phil Simms
was in his first year at NBC _ he might have survived. Had ratings
been better, he might have stayed, too. But one senses that he
feels Michaels prevented him from being his best.
</P>
<P>
   So, feeling his talent didn't fail him, he is firing away. Doing
so after only two years may be risky if he wants to rebound with
CBS, Fox or HBO. The more experienced Dierdorf and Gifford chose
not to fire excess verbal bullets when they were let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really ambivalent about Al,'' Esiason said. ``At times his
on-air genius is so apparent, but at times his uneven nature and
meanness, not just toward me, but toward other people, is
disappointing. He has such a great job that he shouldn't worry
about what other people say.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason said he worked well with Wolfe and Janoff, getting more
in sync as their second season together concluded with the Super
Bowl and the Pro Bowl. Even Michaels has said, ``We really hit our
stride this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Esiason never felt Michaels gave him a chance to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do your job when you're trying to offer humor and
be provocative and the guy next to you isn't trying to bring it out
in you,'' he said. ``Al could have been better for me, and I tried
with him, but it never clicked with me because he never wanted it
to click.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason is again in risky territory. While Michaels is a
demanding perfectionist, he is the best play-by-play announcer in
football. He is much more loquacious than Pat Summerall or Dick
Stockton or Greg Gumbel. But Esiason said Michaels overplayed his
role and stifled his analysis.
</P>
<P>
   He notes how Dierdorf is a more relaxed analyst at CBS, working
with Verne Lundquist. ``Dan has a guy in Lundquist who sets him,''
Esiason said. ``This is Al's show, man. This is what he lives for;
he gives a lot of good information, but he's not the normal TV
announcer.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason said it was odd that some observers thought he didn't
get along with Dierdorf in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got along tremendously,'' he said. ``Whoever said we didn't
get along had to be someone who didn't want us to get along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
